<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE MAKES STOPS FOR PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Ted Johnson again was able to take a close
look at the Patriots defense. The injured New England linebacker
had to sit out his second exhibition game in five days, but Johnson
likes what he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the defense has done well,'' Johnson said after Friday
night's 13-10 win over the Lions. ``The defense did a great job and
the mental errors were minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering how New England's starting offense brought out all
the horror pictures from the end of the 1999 season (in fact it was
close to being totally inept) the defense displayed how it will be
_ and must be _ the strength of the team this season. It is very
early, of course, but the question now is whether the Patriots'
defense will outscore the offense in 2000, as it did Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   As for individual defensive performances, free safety Tebucky
Jones again showed he is more comfortable at safety than at
cornerback. And Antonio Langham, given a chance to start at
cornerback, played decently in the 22 or so minutes the first unit
was on the field. The Lions, as expected, picked on Langham,
throwing four passes in his direction. The veteran, however, seemed
vastly improved from the lost cause he has been in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But for Johnson, a promising note was that the defense was able
to hold its own against a huge and physical Lions offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some trouble against the run (Friday) night and they
schemed us with things we hadn't really seen,'' said Johnson.
``They stretched (the running game) a bit and we really hadn't seen
behemoths like that. So I'm glad we experienced it so when
Thanksgiving comes around'' _ when the Patriots again meet the
Lions in the Silverdome _ ``they won't shock us with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Belichick again was careful not to hand out too much
praise, saying the defense ``had its moments. We, fortunately, made
a couple of plays where we had the right call that matched up
fairly well with the play they had on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots returned the favor, scheming the Lions when Detroit
tried its passing game with woeful quarterback Mike Tomczak.
Detroit fans are universally fervent in their belief that starter
Charlie Batch (broken leg) can return soon after the regular season
starts. A safety blitz by Lawyer Milloy in the first quarter was
typical of Belichick's chess moves as Milloy caused a fumble when
he came in on Tomczak untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were OK on defense,'' Belichick said. ``We still
had a couple of breakdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   But they also made plays that took the ball away from the Lions,
including Milloy's perfectly timed blitz and end Willie McGinest
causing another Tomczak first-quarter fumble. McGinest then read a
Lions screen pass, picked it off, and ran it back 49 yards for the
Patriots' lone touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of defense that anybody wants, a big-play
defense,'' said McGinest. ``And that's what we're trying to do,
cause those turnovers and make those big plays to give the offense
the ball deep in their territory. Nine times out of 10, the offense
will score when you give 'em the ball down there.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest was referring to the fumble Milloy caused that was
recovered by Chad Eaton at the Detroit 9-yard line. But 9 yards
proved to be too long a trek for the Patriots' anemic offense as
Drew Bledsoe threw a horrid interception in an attempt to find
triple-covered tight end Eric Bjornson in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Next time around, McGinest no longer trusted the odds of the
offense being able to score ``nine times out of 10'' that deep in
enemy territory. Instead, he took the turnover all the way to the
end zone himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ball disruption is what we're trying to do,'' said McGinest.
``That's our main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite that goal being achieved against the Lions, several
defenders noted there is still much work to do. Milloy called the
Patriots' effort ``a humbling game for us right now considering
what we came off last (Monday). We know there's room for a lot of
improvement. We definitely have to go out and clean up some
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell how good we are,'' said McGinest.
``It's just preseason and everybody is not healthy. Everybody is
not playing. The other teams aren't running their full offensive
packages. We look good, but it's still too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Early or not, half the Patriots team looks good. Perhaps good
enough to carry the other half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
