FORCE BEHIND GORE'S PLATFORM IS 25-YEAR-OLD VALLEY GUY &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Growing up in Southern California's San Fernando
Valley, Andrei Cherny had such a passion for politics he worked in
Michael Dukakis' 1988 presidential campaign when he was only in
eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Now 25, Cherny is a senior speech writer for Vice President Al
Gore, as well as being a law student, author and spokesman for the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   And he is the primary author of the massive party platform that
will stake out a wide array of Democratic positions at next week's
national convention in his home town.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard graduate grew up in a middle-class household in Los
Angeles with his Czechoslavakian immigrant parents _ his father is
an elementary schoolteacher and his mother is a psychotherapist _
and he now divides his time between Washington, D.C., Los Angeles
and Berkeley, where he is a second-year law student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting. In some ways I feel like I'm going to get a
chance to show off my city to all of the people I work with,'' he
said in an interview. ``I'm really proud that I'm going to be able
to show everybody the L.A. that I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances said Cherny converses with some of the nation's
most powerful politicos with ease and opines as if he were a
veteran politician. California's state Assembly Speaker Bob
Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, counts him among his tight circle of trusted
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   They call him bright, poised and witty, with a dry sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time of his bar mitzvah, he was 13 going on 35,'' said
Valley Village Temple Adat Ari El Rabbi Moshe Rothblum, who has
known Cherny since he was 5. ``He was an absolutely unusual human
being since I've known him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherny said it was his sixth-grade history teacher at Colfax
Avenue Elementary School in North Hollywood who sparked his
interest in politics.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, he arrived at the Dukakis campaign office and offered to
volunteer. After a brief stint vacuuming floors, he advanced by the
end of the summer to stuffing envelopes and calling voters.
</P>
<P>
   He was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was something I liked and something I wanted to keep
on doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed involved in Jewish youth groups and other activities
at North Hollywood High School. Then he attended Harvard
University, where he worked his way through college with the tips
he earned as a bartender, aided by loans and scholarships. He
confides that he may have been the ``world's worst bartender.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits he worked hard but hesitates to take all the credit
for his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pretty lucky along the way as well. A lot of people
work hard and never get the breaks and the chances that I've had,''
he said. ``It takes a combination of hard work and luck to
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest break, he said, came when a top adviser to Bill
Clinton showed the president a column Cherny wrote for the Harvard
Crimson student newspaper. Impressed, the president personally saw
to it that the White House employed Cherny as a senior speechwriter
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave the directive to hire me,'' Cherny said. ``It was a
very, very strange, surreal experience. I had no idea that any of
this was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to writing the platform, Cherny currently is an
editor for the Democratic policy journal Blueprint, is attending
law school and working part-time advising Hertzberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't feel like you're working with a kid,'' Hertzberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are working with somebody with a very clear mind who has a
broad understanding of policy and good writing skills. He's always
willing to step forth with ideas, and he's not intimidated by
people who are twice his age sitting around the same table.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cherny exhibits some telltale signs of a twentysomething.
A movie buff, he loves ``Star Wars'' and ``Ferris Bueller's Day
Off.'' He has close groups of friends in the nation's capital and
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treat me like Andrei, and, thankfully, politics rarely
comes up,'' he said. ``We have much more important things to
discuss when we're together _ the latest gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting together the platform _ which focuses on the themes of
progress, prosperity and peace _ was ``a massive undertaking,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After exhausting negotiations with citizen groups, labor unions
and business groups, he culled through 30,000 e-mails from
Americans with ideas for the platform. And he worked with top
Democrats to fuse an entire party's stance with the vision of Gore,
who will be nominated at the Aug. 14-17 convention at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a platform that Democrats can be really proud of and
will really help them as they run from now until November,'' Cherny
said. ``I was really honored to be asked because I think it is an
important job and a chance to have an impact on a historical
document.''
</P>
<P>
   Working for the White House was stressful but fulfilled his
dreams. Still, Cherny said, the Valley and Los Angeles stayed in
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make sure I never forgot where I came from and that
I really was, hopefully, able to help the people I grew up with,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley in many ways represents what a lot of communities
all over the country are dealing with _ everything from education
to crime to health care. The concern that we have as families in
the Valley are ones that people everywhere are facing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that growing up in that environment has given me the
drive to try to address a lot of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Cherny said he wants to be a prosecutor. But
Rabbi Rothblum suspects Cherny was born for politics.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg drew no lines around Cherny's future: ``His future is
limited by his imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
