<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RVS-POPULAR-KAN </SLUG>
  
 RVs offer comforts of home, freedom of the road  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES HART  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Jerry and Carolyn Holloway recently
invited friends and family to kick the tires on their new house.
</P>
<P>
   Guests gathered in the parking lot at Overland Park Regional
Medical Center, where the 45-foot motor coach was parked. After
signing the guest book outside, they marveled at the mirrored
ceilings, Ultrasuede walls and granite floors within.
</P>
<P>
   RV sales have boomed nationwide, thanks to a strong economy and
baby boomers who want to see the country while they're still young
enough to enjoy the ride. This year, sales are expected to reach
about 330,000 vehicles, up 91 percent from 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Holloways started traveling a few years ago, when workaholic
Jerry, then 55, retired. The Overland Park couple's new vehicle,
their third in nine years, cost as much as one /{very/} nice house
_ or several smaller, still-pretty-nice houses. ``I think it
surprises them that it's just like a home,'' Carolyn said of her
guests.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, RV sales are as strong as they've ever been,
according to the Recreation Vehicle Dealers Association. RV rentals
also are expected to rise by 21 percent this year, according to the
Recreation Vehicle Rental Association.
</P>
<P>
   Some leading manufacturers, though, are predicting hard times
ahead, blaming higher interest rates, higher gasoline prices and
surplus RVs on dealer lots. Stock prices have been dropping this
year for companies such as Fleetwood, down 39 percent, and National
RV, down 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of motor homes have dropped, but smaller truck campers,
certain trailers and other RVs are boosting the overall sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a pretty strong boom for the last three or four
years,'' said David Woodworth, a motor-camping historian and
collector who has made presentations at the Smithsonian
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The motor home goes back decades. The first was built around
1910, said Woodworth, who once traveled in Mae West's 1931 motor
home. (It had a back porch and slept four.)
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers are responsible for some of the gains. The average
RV owner is 48 years old with a spouse and an income of $47,000,
according to a study by the University of Michigan commissioned by
the RV industry. About one in four households led by 35- to
54-year-olds plans to buy an RV within three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it promotes good family togetherness,'' said Jim Frum,
the general manager of Olathe Ford's RV department.
</P>
<P>
   Frum has sold the vehicles since the mid-1970s. Even when the
economy was bad during the 1980s, RVs could still sell. And the
last few years have been better, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles on his lot range in cost from $5,000 to $257,000,
Frum said. (The Holloways asked that the price of their customized
vehicle not be included in this article, but it was substantially
more than the most expensive motor home on Frum's lot.)
</P>
<P>
   Because the Holloways travel about half the year, their motor
coach has all the comforts of home, including three televisions, a
satellite dish, a full stereo system and standard house appliances,
as well as a slide-out room.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle gets a mileage only slightly better than a real
house, about eight miles per gallon. The tank holds 200 gallons of
diesel, so a fill-up costs a few hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the expense hardly bothers buyers, said Ross Naylor, who
owns a dealership in Kansas City. According to industry sources,
most people put only 5,000 to 6,000 miles on their RVs annually, so
travel is not cost prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   The average motor home length is 34 to 36 feet, he said. Few are
longer than 40 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for a lifestyle, and they've got everything in
that trailer that they have at home,'' Naylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Younger families usually buy smaller trailers, which are
comfortable but still retain the atmosphere of a campsite. Other
people buy motor homes _ ``rolling condominiums,'' as Naylor put it
_ but that loses the feel of camping, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer, 57, lived in a travel trailer exclusively for five
years, starting when he was 45. He was based mostly in a Florida
park. If he felt like seeing the Florida Keys, away he went. The
following week he might get a yen for the mountains, so the trailer
would head north.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just adventure,'' Naylor said. ``Live on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Naylor recommends that people travel before they get too old.
The Holloways agree. ``We thought, we want to do it while we're
young enough to enjoy it,'' Carolyn Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   The Holloways spend most of their trips at a resort in Arizona,
where Jerry golfs and Carolyn models clothing. They also have
roamed around good portions of North America. ``We've hit it all,''
Carolyn said. ``We've gone all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry's advice? Retire as early as possible. After all, he said,
you can always go back to work.
</P>
<P>
   But then, you can go anywhere in a 45-foot, mirrored-ceiling,
granite-floored, globally positioned motor home.
</P>
</TEXT>
