r s BC-CAR-SONOMA-LADN-(SLAN     08-07 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SONOMA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KALITTA FINDS NICHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Don't be surprised if Doug Kalitta makes a
suggestion to run all the National Hot Rod Association national
events at Sears Point Raceway here.
</P>
<P>
   That was the feeling Sunday after the former USAC Silver Crown
champion defeated Larry Dixon to capture his third consecutive Top
Fuel final at the 13th annual Fram Autolite Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners were John Force in Funny Car and Kurt Johnson in
Pro Stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess this would be a good place to have them all,''
said Kalitta, who won a tire-smoking battle over Dixon in the final
round. ``I don't know what it is about this place. I wish we could
carry it around to all the races. We just seem to come along on a
combination that was working for us this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   That showed early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kalitta, who blistered the track with a stout 4.657-second pass
during qualifying Saturday, backed it up with a solid 4.661 in a
first-round victory over Craig Smith. He then followed with
back-to-back 4.70s before defeating Dixon in the final, which saw
both drivers overpower the track.
</P>
<P>
   Kalitta held a slight advantage off the starting line before
both he and Dixon smoked the tires near half-track. Kalitta
recovered first and was able to just drive past the Don Prudhomme
dragster at the finish line, finishing a mere 0.21 seconds ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the thing started losing traction, I was just hoping I
wouldn't see him,'' Kalitta said. ``About halfway, I pumped it once
and we were able to sneak by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there at the end, I saw him then. And my experience has
been that if you can see 'em at all, you've lost. So I was pretty
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Force, who earned his 88th career victory and his seventh of the
season when teammate Tony Pedregon jumped the start, was just
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me he red-lighted when I got to the other end,''
said Force, who covered the quarter-mile in a sub-par 9.055 after
smoking the tires just past 330 feet. ``Then I really went into a
coma. That's your worst nightmare in a two-car deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sponsor says, `What a great job; you won. I said, `No. Half
the career is winning, the other half is keeping people loving
you.' (The spectators) want to see a race. They paid to see a
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Which Force was unable to deliver when Pedregon rolled across
the starting line a mere 23-thousands of a second before the green
light. Still, the victory was profitable for the Bell Gardens
native. He took over first place in the point standings and moved
75 points ahead of Jerry Toliver, who failed to qualify for the
first time this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
