<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION MIDFIELD MAY NEED REVAMPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The evolution of the Revolution midfield
provides an indication of the team's future.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1-1 tie against the Columbus Crew Saturday night, John
Harkes was flanked by two energetic young markers _ Joe Franchino
and Carlos Parra. The combination was effective in discouraging the
Crew midfield. Roles were clearly defined. Harkes was the point of
reference, but he also contributed defensively.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not what coach Fernando Clavijo envisioned when he
was hired in December. Nor did it produce offensive inspiration or
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo and director of soccer Sunil Gulati conceived the
Revolution as a Latin-flavored team, with Bolivian Mauricio Ramos
choreographing the midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, though, has been relegated to the bench. Leonel Alvarez
will return from suspension for the Revolution's visit to the
MetroStars Saturday. But Alvarez's availability again raises the
question of redundancy in the supporting midfield positions.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws in the Revolution's 3-5-2 design are becoming more
apparent as they fight for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The team is experienced up the middle, with goalkeeper Juergen
Sommer, libero Mauricio Wright, either Alvarez or Harkes in
midfield, and Wolde Harris-Jose Luis Morales as the strike
combination.
</P>
<P>
   But for the team to progress, the midfield should be guided by
either Alvarez or Harkes, not both. Ramos should be the creative
midfielder, flanked by a younger player, either Parra or someone
like Paulo Dos Santos, who was cut in the preseason and is now
playing for Aalesund in Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos has not played a full game since the Revolution's 4-1 loss
at Columbus July 12. In that game, New England's weaknesses were
exploited by a more dynamic and versatile Crew attack. Clavijo has
since attempted to adjust, and the Revolution lineup, which
outplayed Columbus for most of the second half Saturday, included
seven players 24 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution lineup includes more speed and variety than a
year ago. Clavijo has been resourceful in utilizing those qualities
_ substitutes William Sunsing and Johnny Torres nearly salvaged a
victory against the Crew. But the concept of a cohesive, flowing
attack has been sacrificed. The Revolution have a 9-10-6 record and
are in playoff contention, but they have seldom made the game seem
easy.
</P>
<P>
   And as teams compete in the stretch run, matches will be tinged
with more desperation. As in previous Revolution seasons, players
who give the appearance of working hard will be favored. There will
be more fight than flair. And, whether the Revolution qualify for
the playoffs or not, the team's makeup will have to be reevaluated,
starting with the midfield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
