<SLUG> BC-RAC-SPICY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORDICAN INCH WINS SPICY LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
 LIVING SWEEPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ With Saratoga in full swing, it is difficult for
Rockingham to attract an outstanding field, even for the $100,000
purse offered in Sunday's Spicy Living Sweepstakes. However,
although only five horses contested the 1 1/8-mile turf event, it
turned into a memorable battle between two fillies with a future,
as Nordican Inch nipped Always Sure by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   From the powerful New York stable of Christophe Clement,
Nordican Inch, who began her career in France and races for Edouard
de Rothschild of the famous banking and wine making family, is the
real deal. She never has been out of the money (13-4-6-3), and she
justified her favorite's odds of 11-10 ($4.20 to win) by escaping a
trap in the upper stretch under Joe Hampshire and staging a
rippling run to the wire in 1:49 3/5.
</P>
<P>
   Always Sure, from the the up-and-coming barn of Tom Amoss, who
is a force in the Midwest and is currently stabled at The Spa, is
also a horse to watch. She ran a strong race with Eddie Martin Jr.
aboard, losing in the final jump as the 8-5 second choice. Final
Tango, the least accomplished of the three New York invaders,
finished third, a length and three-quarters behind with Filiberto
Leon, after leading turning for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nordican Inch is a pretty difficult filly to ride,'' said
Nicholas Balachard, assistant trainer for Clement. ``She gets very
rank. We told Joe to just take her back and follow Amoss's filly,
and that's what he did. Joe came up the rail. Sometimes a hole
opens and sometimes it doesn't. This time, it didn't. But Joe got
out, and she came running. She was very game. This was a very good
race; it was a thrilling finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampshire, who rode four winners on the day and is the leading
rider at the meet with 53 victories, was momentarily blocked when
Always Sure swept past Final Tango at the top of the lane, and both
horses dropped over in front of Nordican Inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``She settled pretty well, and I wasn't worried,'' said
Hampshire. ``I had a lot of horse, and I was sitting, sitting,
sitting. I let her run to try to get through, but we got in a
traffic jam. Martin did a great job. He came around, and tried to
box me in, then he drew off. I got Nordican Inch out, hit her
righthanded, and she just exploded. I must admit it probably wasn't
the smoothest trip I ever had, but we wound up in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Amoss, who has won six training titles at Fair Grounds and is
currently conditioning Heritage Of Gold, the top handicap mare in
the country, at Saratoga, felt his filly was compromised when she
got a bit nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She ran well off the pace, and had good position early,'' said
Amoss. ``She got a little overanxious down the backstretch, and I
knew she was beaten at the top of the stretch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
