<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUCIAL ISSUES REMAIN FOR OZ DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 DEVELOPMENT-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Johnson County, Kan., Commission prepares to vote on the
Oz Entertainment Co.'s plan to develop the Sunflower Army
Ammunition Plant site, significant questions remain and key
agreements have not been reached.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will begin its public review Wednesday with a 7
p.m. work session at which Oz officials will detail the complex
transaction. Three public comment meetings will follow this month.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings come almost two months after Oz and federal
officials announced they had ``substantially completed'' the deal _
and after federal officials pushed the county to start the approval
process.
</P>
<P>
   The County Commission must give its approval before the plan to
transfer Sunflower to Oz for development of an $861 million theme
park and resort can go forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finally starting,'' said Blaine Hastings, the federal
official overseeing the transfer. ``The longer (Sunflower) sits
there, the more it costs the taxpayers'' as the government
maintains the land and does some cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   But several issues have not been resolved, according to
interviews and county documents:
</P>
<P>
   Oz must rework an agreement that spells out the deal between Oz
and the state to transfer the land and possibly issue bonds. An Oz
attorney called the agreement the ``key document'' yet to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Oz has not announced a developer for a hotel and
entertainment//retail complex. Those developments would provide the
revenue to pay back some of the bonds Oz wants the Kansas
Development Finance Authority to issue.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/ Questions remain about how realistic the Oz company's
feasibility studies are. An Oz opponent with expertise in
government finance calls the company's attendance projections
faulty.
</P>
<P>
   The county has questions about the company's finance plan and
its request for public improvements to the site.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to county commissioners, county Chief Counsel Don
Jarrett listed 24 questions and issues that were not resolved in
the Oz company's redevelopment plan released in June.
</P>
<P>
   Oz officials say they will answer the questions during the work
session Wednesday and in subsequent discussions with the county and
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Jarrett's document addresses the right issues. We
respect those right issues, and we look forward to addressing
them,'' Oz spokesman David Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The project is complex: The federal government agrees to
transfer the land in phases to the state through the finance
authority. The state would immediately transfer the land to Oz. The
company will agree to take all 9,065 acres of Sunflower and clean
the land of contamination caused by years of propellant
manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   A redevelopment agreement spells out the authority's involvement
in the land transfer and its ability to issue bonds for the
project. Oz plans to finance almost a third of the project with
those bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Oz submitted its redevelopment agreement to the authority in
June. The authority, however, found it unacceptable and asked the
company to revise it, said Rebecca Floyd, the authority's executive
vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognized there was no point in spending anyone's time or
resources, knowing that this document contained issues significant
enough to cause significant problems for the transaction as a
whole,'' Floyd said. ``We did want to give them an opportunity to
rectify those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   One important issue is whether the agreement commits the
authority to issuing the bonds, said Oz attorney Larry Winn.
</P>
<P>
   He said the authority wants to ``maintain their absolute
discretion'' in deciding to issue bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as we approach our investors and investment bankers, they
need assurance that under certain circumstances there would be no
reason (the finance authority) would not issue the bonds,'' Winn
said. ``It's two sides of one coin.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is important because the finance authority may
proceed with the land transaction before the financing structure _
including the bonds _ is in place.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said Oz and the finance authority had planned to close on
the land and soon after complete the financing deal. But it appears
now that Oz may complete the financing at a later date, possibly a
few months after the closing, Floyd and Winn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business issue and decision for them,'' Floyd said.
``If they're comfortable closing on the land without the financing
structure in place, that's certainly their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Oz opponents worry that the company wants the land without
having to build the theme park. Although the opponents don't want a
theme park there, they are concerned that Oz is more interested in
getting cheap land than in its proposed development.
</P>
<P>
   But Floyd said the land would have to be used according to the
plan in the redevelopment agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Oz could sell the land, but any buyer who wanted to tap the
authority's ability to issue bonds for the site would have to go
through the process outlined in state law. Even if the buyer did
not want bonds, the land would be protected by deed restrictions
requiring that the land be cleaned up _ paid for by Oz and its
insurance _ before it is developed.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said ``myriad contractual considerations'' would prevent a
land grab.
</P>
<P>
   Winn said Oz has no interest in the land without a theme park.
The land would not be ready for development for decades without the
Oz project, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land and the project are inseparable,'' Winn said. ``We
don't want the land without a high possibility of a project to go
on the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle to completing the deal is a lawsuit brought by
Taxpayers Opposed to Oz against the federal government. The
authority won't close on the land until the lawsuit is resolved,
Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   The taxpayers group, known as TOTO, wants a federal judge to
stop the transfer until the government conducts more studies of the
land deal's impact.
</P>
<P>
   Oz opponents also continue to question the feasibility of the Oz
plan.
</P>
<P>
   TOTO will present an analysis of the company's feasibility study
at a public comment meeting this month.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Wilson, a certified public accountant who consults with
city governments on utility issues, concluded in his analysis that
the Oz study is faulty. Wilson owns 80 acres of land near
Sunflower.
</P>
<P>
   To project revenues, Oz estimates that 2.8 million to 3.2
million people will visit the theme park each year.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson said those figures are high. If 2.8 million people
visit, the theme park would capture 22 percent of Kansas City's
tourist market. Of 19 theme parks listed in the Oz study, only two
capture that much of their markets.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, Wilson said he doesn't think the attendance figure
is reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't get past that, the rest of the numbers fall
apart,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Oz officials have said the project will generate the necessary
attendance and revenue because it will be a ``destination'' resort
that will expand Kansas City's tourism market.
</P>
<P>
   To be a ``destination complex,'' the Oz studies state, the
project must include an entertainment//retail village and a resort
with a 350-room hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The studies assume that the entertainment//retail village would
generate $132 million a year and that the resort would generate $33
million a year in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But Oz has not announced that it has a developer for those
projects, which concerns Jarrett at the county. Without the
developments, Oz could not repay the sales tax bonds it wants the
finance authority to issue, Jarrett said. Sales tax generated at
the theme park and resort would be used to pay off those bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also does not say what would happen to property taxes
that the hotel and retail village would owe, Jarrett said. The plan
does not say those taxes would be used to pay off tax-increment
financing bonds that Oz wants, but it also doesn't say the tax
amount would go to the county, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not needed (for bonds) but it's not going to us, I
think that's a big issue,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the county needs more information on a road and dam
Oz wants it to build for the project. The company's financial plan
shows the road costing $6 million, but Jarrett noted that elsewhere
in the report the figure is listed at $6 million to $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Oz wants the state to build a $29 million interchange off Kansas
10, but the state did not include it among the $1 billion in
projects announced Friday. That leads to questions about the
company's contingency plan, Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of the interchange to handle Oz's visitors ``will
create some questions in the approval'' process, Jarrett said. The
commission could approve the redevelopment agreement without the
interchange. But it would not grant the company a conditional-use
permit, allowing it to start building the project, without a
commitment on the interchange, Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Also of concern to Jarrett: Oz says a private company would
provide sewers to the area but hasn't said which company; Oz says
its plan depends on $20 million in economic development grants, but
it is unclear whether the company will be able to get those grants;
and the county needs more information on how Oz would use
authority-issued bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Oz knew there would be more questions, and the company will
address them, Winn said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is looking forward to showing the commission and the
public the entire Oz project, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winn noted that he recently saw the project referred to as a
``carnival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone needs to get higher on the learning curve so
we can dispose of the stereotypical statements and focus on the
project itself,'' Winn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
