<SLUG> BC-BBN-HAMPTON </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hampton open to return to Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mike Hampton, just months away from becoming one of
the most sought-after pitchers on the free-agent market, isn't
ruling out the possibility of re-signing with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they make some moves to get better, of course,'' Hampton
told reporters this weekend in Phoenix, where the New York Mets
played the Arizona Diamondbacks. ``If they make a legitimate shot,
I'll consider it _ like any team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, 27, will return to Houston, where he played for six
seasons, and get his first glimpse of Enron Field when he starts
tonight's series opener against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who set an Astros record with 22 victories last season,
was traded to the Mets last December for righthander Octavio Dotel,
outfielder Roger Cedeno and a minor-league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said he expects an emotional homecoming when he starts
against his former teammates. The lefthander has kept in close
contact with several Astros, including Jeff Bagwell and Craig
Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be one of those things where I'll have to hold myself
back,'' he said. ``I'll just try to relax and not be too pumped
up.''
</P>
<P>
   After being part of three NL Central winners, Hampton is
surprised the Astros own the worst record in baseball (42-69).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that if I had stayed there we'd be in first
place right now,'' he said. ``I'm happy to be on this team,
especially with the way things have gone (in Houston). I guess
timing was on my side.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
