A4428 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-07 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hampton won't be swayed back easily
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If he could have pitched every other day as well as
played a little shortstop, second base and third base and served as
staff closer on his days off, then maybe Mike Hampton could have
made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   If he could have driven in 120 runs and stolen 70 bases, then
maybe the Astros truly would have been able to say ``what if''
today when the former staff ace takes the mound at Enron Field for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hampy's great, but Cy Young couldn't have turned it around for
us this year,'' incumbent Astros ace Scott Elarton said. ``It's
just been one of those years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not by any stretch is Hampton's absence the only reason the
Astros fell apart in 2000. His departure to the Mets was only the
start of the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was Hampton some kind of Superman, although he figures
to be paid like one when free-agent offers come falling into his
lap like mountains of gold this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to the intrigue and irony of Hampton's returning to
Houston today, as so many imaginations dance to the tune of somehow
luring him back.
</P>
<P>
   He won't come until things change. And maybe things won't really
look like they're changing until he comes back.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton returns today leading the kind of team that could win it
all if things fall right. After a sluggish start to the 2000
season, he is, at 11-7, showing the kind of stuff that could lead
to maybe $14 million a year from the Mets, Braves, Cardinals, Red
Sox or Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Astros' chances, you want to say Enron is the place
and Houston the city that Hampton should crave, and surely he
should have reasons to want to make a triumphant return.
</P>
<P>
   With his good looks and good stuff, his leadership, youth and
grit, you want to say Hampton is all the Astros need to get back to
winning titles instead of spiraling downward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen when you have a pitcher that you know will win
every time out,'' Astros slugger Jeff Bagwell said. ``A great
pitcher can help everyone and mess up the hitters on the other team
for the whole series.
</P>
<P>
   Look what Kevin Brown did to us in (the '98 Division Series).
You just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the Astros would have become a better team had Hampton
been on the hill for opening night in April. And feel free to side
with whomever you want on the failed Hampton negotiations of last
winter that led to the Mets trade _ ownership, which said Hampton
never seriously considered staying, or Hampton's representatives,
who said the Astros never talked serious dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Hampton, the Astros would not have been a
championship team. And they wouldn't have for the same reason
Hampton left and probably won't come back. It takes more than just
one man, even when that man is a ground-ball ace lefty who's
capable of 20-plus wins in any given year.
</P>
<P>
   No one realizes this more than Hampton. He all but wrote his own
trade papers last offseason, because when looking around the
organization, he saw hints of what was to come: A tightening
budget, an iffy relief staff, a manager in whom he had lost
confidence, and a commitment to winning that was dwindling as cash
cow Enron Field was going up.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Astros consider themselves legitimate contenders
to bring back the much-adored Hampton to his Houston fans, they
won't be until all those things that sent him away in the first
place begin to turn around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He enjoyed playing here,'' said Bagwell, who has kept in
contact with Hampton all year. ``But there's no way we can sign him
right now the way things are. It's not exactly the best atmosphere
in the world compared to other places, and he's the premier pitcher
on the free-agent market. But if things change, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   So take a long, hard look at Hampton working his sinking stuff
at Enron tonight. Sure, it's easy to imagine how significant it
would be for the club to get Hampton back, particularly because his
pitching style fits the stadium better than that of most any other
pitcher in the league.
</P>
<P>
   But just as it was last offseason, getting Hampton is not only
about Hampton. Before anyone in management thinks seriously about
making a run at their former ace, they have to make a run at a
shortstop, a third baseman and serious relief help.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hampton casts anything more than courtesy glances back at
Houston, Bagwell must sign an extension, and decisions will need to
be made regarding the futures here of Ken Caminiti, Moises Alou and
manager Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   For six seasons, Hampton was known as ``the Bulldog'' in
Houston. He didn't earn the nickname chasing only dollars, although
he is a rare breed.
</P>
<P>
   He cares about winning. And if the Astros want him back, they're
going to have to show how much they care, too.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
