<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     08-07 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES BATTERED IN L.A. RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the darker side of the pitching ledger, there
is bad, really bad _ and Ismael Valdes Sunday against the Milwaukee
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was so remarkably bad, he managed what no one in the Los
Angeles Dodgers organization has been able to pull off all season _
earn cheers for Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those came as Perez replaced Valdes, who left having
allowed seven runs on eight hits _ all currently being tracked by
NASA _ in 1 innings of what could loosely be described as work.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers never could fully recover, ultimately losing 9-6,
falling to 3 games back of the Giants and being left to plead that
this was some kind of otherworldly one-game aberration for Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as hard as I've ever seen him hit,'' said Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson, who wasn't alone. ``I really don't know what
the problem was.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was making his first start at Dodger Stadium since being
reacquired by the Dodgers last week in that unexpected trade with
the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight hits he allowed in his brief stint, four were
doubles and one a home run.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, no Dodgers fielders were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Valdes said. ``Everything was
right. I just got my (butt) kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, everything was right except for !ital!that.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the strange night was the relief work of Perez, who
took over in the second and proceeded to pitch 5 innings of shutout
ball. The struggling Perez was removed from the rotation last week
in favor of 30-year-old rookie Matt Herges, who is making his first
start tonight against the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos did a good job, we just didn't have enough to get
back,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes had been a disappointment with the Cubs this season (2-4,
5.32 ERA) and had been so-so in his one previous start for the
Dodgers in Pittsburgh (two earned runs, four hits in four innings).
But nothing that would have hinted at Sunday. Valdes got the first
two outs to open the game but then gave up consecutive singles
before a two-run Jeromy Burnitz double.
</P>
<P>
   He started the second with a walk to Jose Hernandez and then
gave up a double to that new Dodger killer, Henry Blanco.
Right-hander pitcher Jimmy Haynes, who had one RBI in his previous
42 at-bats, then doubled in two. And on it went. Ron Belliard
singled in Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   Marquis Grissom popped up for Valdes' only out of the inning,
but then former USC Trojan Geoff Jenkins _ who had homered twice on
Saturday _ homered again, and it was 7-zip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like it was just a line drive that kept going,''
Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   When Richie Sexson then doubled, Johnson got merciful and
removed Valdes. He left to a chorus of boos.
</P>
<P>
   And welcome home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the world,'' Valdes said. ``We have to
continue working, concentrate and do more the next start.''
</P>
<P>
   He did leave himself room for improvement. To his credit,
though, Valdes waited for over two hours after his exit to face the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's loss completed a disappointing weekend series against
the underwhelming Brewers (47-64), who took two of three games
after the Dodgers had won the series opener on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers couldn't do much with Haynes (10-10), who had not
won since July 7 and had a 7.40 ERA over his last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers finally scored two in the fifth on a Perez groundout
and Tom Goodwin single, then two more in the seventh on RBI singles
by Alex Cora and Mark Grudzielanek, who also singled in a pair in
the ninth. But there would be no coming back from that 7-0 hole
Valdes had left them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before when we faced him, he was hitting his spots,''
Hernandez said. ``Tonight he was leaving it out over the plate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
