 &HT;    DAVE WALKER'S WEB SITE &AMP; MAGAZINE REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Dave Walker's reviews of a Web site and current
magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   The peak months of the hurricane season begin with August, and
though we're more concerned here with blowing dust and palm fronds
than storms of mass destruction, the National Hurricane Center's
official site offers armchair meteorologists as much data as they
can handle. No, more. In addition to up-to-the-minute satellite
images, landlocked storm buffs will find tracking charts and
detailed accounts of aircraft reconnaissance missions as well as
long-term forecasts. (According to the center, conditions have
aligned to make this season a busy one, at least in the Atlantic.)
If the Weather Channel isn't interactive enough for you, this could
become a favorite bookmark.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES
</P>
<P>
   ``PSYCHOLOGY TODAY''
</P>
<P>
   In the cover story, Robert J. Sternberg asks readers to cast
themselves in their own love story. The idea: ``As much as
psychologists have attempted to explain the mysteries of love
through scientific laws and theories, it turns out that the best
mirrors of romantic experience may be (beginitalic)Wuthering
Heights, Casablanca (enditalic)and (beginitalic)General
Hospital(enditalic)(beginitalic),(enditalic)'' he writes. A reader
quiz helps decide your type - you know, cop or comedian, princess
or martyr. We took the quiz on our lunch hour and discovered that
our type is one of the lesser (beginitalic)Chicken Run
(enditalic)hedS &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
