<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      08-07 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S NEW &AMP; NOTABLE BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING in ``E'' and ``L'' categories 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of four new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``PURPLE CANE ROAD''
</P>
<P>
   by James Lee Burke
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Burke has been called the Faulkner of crime fiction, and while
we might quibble with the particulars, there's no denying that he's
very, very good. His characters inhabit his setting - the darker
corners of Louisiana - with consummate ease, and he makes few of
the missteps common to other writers, mistakes that disrupt a
reader's easy way through a violent and sometimes tawdry story. In
Burke's new novel, detective Dave Robicheaux learns from a New
Orleans pimp some sketchy details about the death of Robicheaux's
mother, an alleged prostitute whom he has not seen since he was in
high school. Robicheaux's obsessive search for more information
takes him through a maze of colorful characters, any one of whom
could carry a novel alone. The book's only flaw is its ending,
which has so many twists that it seems calculated. Otherwise,
there's no beating the rich, sweaty atmosphere of the bayou country
Burke portrays so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WEALTH OF CHOICES''
</P>
<P>
   by Alan Murray
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Murray, Washington Bureau chief for the(beginitalic) Wall Street
Journal(enditalic) and columnist at
(beginitalic)SmartMoney(enditalic) magazine, starts his book with a
quiz that's supposed to tell if you are prepared to succeed in the
New Economy. New &AMP; Notable took this quiz, and we are dazed to
report that we scored very high - a fact that probably says more
about Murray's questions than our financial savvy. Indeed, much of
his book is just a compendium of common sense, filtered through the
sensibilities of the Internet age. His advice: Use your computer to
get information on car prices, airfares, stocks, insurance rates,
long-distance phone service. Dicker over everything you buy -
sellers often lower their prices. And don't buy the fancy model
when the standard model will do. There's not a whole lot of new
information here, but it's an effective, entry-level pep talk for
people who are intimidated by money and by the decisions that will
determine their financial futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``WRITING ON DRUGS''
</P>
<P>
   by Sadie Plant
</P>
<P>
   (FSG, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Louis Stevenson wrote (beginitalic)The Strange Case of
Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde (enditalic)during six days and nights of a
cocaine high. Wilkie Collins dictated the last part of
(beginitalic)The Moonstone (enditalic)under the effects of opium.
``When it was finished,'' he said, ``I was not only pleased and
astonished at the finale but did not recognize it as my own.''
Anais Nin's diaries contain florid accounts of her LSD dreams, and
speed gave Philip K. Dick (beginitalic)Do Androids Dream of
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Electric Sleep(enditalic)?, the book that
became (beginitalic)Blade Runner(enditalic). Plant explores the
history of drugs and their use by writers of the last two
centuries. Her book is thought-provoking and packed with
information we're not sure we wanted to know. We learned, for
instance, that Frederic-Auguste Bartholdi, the architect of the
Statue of Liberty, was a coke enthusiast. ``It is very probable
that had I taken it 20 years ago,'' he said, ``the Statue of
Liberty would have attained the height of several hundred meters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``THE RICH AND HOW THEY GOT THAT WAY''
</P>
<P>
   by Cynthia Crossen
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I fight,'' Hetty Green once said, ``there is usually a
funeral, and it isn't mine.'' She was a driven, demented, stingy
and unpleasant woman at a time when Victorian ladies were expected
to be gracious and demure. But when she died in 1916, she was worth
$100 million - more than $1 billion in today's dollars. Crossen
profiles some of the wealthiest people of all time, from
11th-century plunderer Machmud of Ghazni (who accumulated wealth by
saying ``That's mine,'' and killing anyone who disagreed) to the
sleazy and corrupt Pope Alexander VI, who made his fortune during
the 15th century through shameless use of divine imperative, and to
Bill Gates, whose monopolistic methods look like church work by
comparison. Sadly, of the 10 people here, only one is a woman, but
we like Hetty best. ``I go my own way, take no partners, risk no
one else's fortune,'' she once said, ``therefore I am Madame
Ishmael, set against every man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
