<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 02:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-GOP-CIRCUS-ORWELL-IND     08-07 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CIRCUS-ORWELL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNUM AND BAILEY MEETS GEORGE ORWELL: THE GOP CONVENTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This 875-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As the balloons descended into the air at three
minutes before eleven on Thursday night, the music struck up and
the fireworks went off to acclaim George W. Bush, the party's
candidate, it was hard to think of the Republican Convention in
Philadelphia as anything but the Greatest Show On Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Music, dancing, videos, ceaseless parties, and a parade of
characters from grandmothers in New Jersey through to Bo Derek had
been brought here for our lavish entertainment, creating that great
fusion of show business and sport which is American politics.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another side to the week, the hidden face of the
Republican machine which designed and steered every second, every
minute, every smile and whoop. A convention is also about political
control: it is Barnum and Bailey meets George Orwell.
</P>
<P>
   The convention's last day was a time for pulling out all of the
stops. Country singing duo Brooks and Dunn was brought on, the
latest in a line of musical entertainment which had included a
Philadelphia gospel choir, the Delfonics, Harold Melvin and the
Blue Notes, Cuban-born singer Joe Secada, Hank Williams, Jr. and a
dozen more. The audience sang along, cheered, clapped, waved their
hats and danced.
</P>
<P>
   And if they did not, there were always people there to make sure
that they livened it up just a little bit harder. This was a show
made for television, even if most of the networks chose not to show
more than a few minutes each day, and nothing was left to chance.
</P>
<P>
   From high in the rafters of the First Union Center, a team of
Republican controllers watched the proceedings on television sets
and with the aid of binoculars, scanning the arena for signs of
trouble or a lacklustre response.
</P>
<P>
   They communicated instantly with the whips on the floor, most
wearing orange baseball caps and spread among the different
delegations.
</P>
<P>
   Only once was there trouble, when some delegates objected to the
presence of a gay speaker; the rest of the time the whips were more
involved in making sure that the fun was as ostentatious as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But it was emblematic of the very precise control exerted over
every aspect of life at the Republican convention. Every speech,
badge and T-shirt was vetted; every speaker carefully chosen to
make a point.
</P>
<P>
   You could have been forgiven for believing that this was a
predominantly black and Hispanic party; it is not.
</P>
<P>
   And the schedulers would never choose a white male politician to
make a point if they could find a minority spokesperson: the blind
mountaineer who opened the convention, the first deaf Miss America,
a Hispanic girl to represent the state of Texas or Bush's own black
preacher.
</P>
<P>
   That control was all-pervasive. Ask a delegate what they
thought, and the replies would be surprisingly similiar. The
reason: a set of speaking points which each had been issued with,
telling them that Bush was a uniter not a divider, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The message was hammered home, over and over again. By the end
of the week, you could repeat it in your sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But if this all gave the impression of vacuity, it was not true.
Pushing home the message was a disciplined, precise task. It has
been guided by a vast team of communications professionals,
literally hundreds of people. They designed the podium.
</P>
<P>
   (``Materials such as lumber, wood-grained laminates in mahogany
and maple finishes, jade-green slate tiles and fresh flowers were
used to give the podium a warm and natural look,'' said the press
release.) They designed the speeches. And in the end, they also
designed the people.
</P>
<P>
   If all this gave the impression of politics without politics,
however, that was deliberate. Bush has campaigned as a man who is
more concerned with the real world than with Washington. But it
certainly did not mean that the politicians were idle in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   It was elsewhere that the real business was taking place, the
conversations which make politics turn in America.
</P>
<P>
   Up at the level of the suites, far above the thronging crowds,
the odor of expensive cologne mingled with the whiff of hors
d'oeuvres as businessmen entertained their politician friends with
shrimp, lobster, scotch, champagne and a little cold, hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   At this rarefied altitude, it became clearer how things really
worked.
</P>
<P>
   For $15,000 you could gain access to the luxury box of
Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson, and a number of companies had
thrown in their cash to buy a little space for their favorite
congressman or official: United Distillers and Vintners, for
instance, was sponsoring a box for Dennis Hastert, the Speaker of
the House.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the stadium a discreet door led to the Victors'
Club, a haven for the really high rollers. And fenced off from the
rest of the convention, exclusive parties were staged for
contributors in a line of vintage railway cars hosted by House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   While the good times rolled in the stadium, the money kept on
flowing: reporters from the Philadelphia Inquirer found a $5,000
check made out to one congressman lying on the ground, apparently
forgotten amidst the merry exchange of cash for favors.
</P>
<P>
   It is too easy to say that the money men run the show; after
all, if the party cannot convince the people seated at the top of
the stadium, the ``nosebleed seats,'' to vote for them, then all
the shrimp in the world will not matter.
</P>
<P>
   For a convention to work, money, media and political control
must be brought together in a perfect fusion; from that point of
view, the Republicans will have been well pleased with their week
in the City of Brotherly Love. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 875-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
