<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 08:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-BUSH-EISENHOWER-     08-07 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-BUSH-EISENHOWER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES THE SON RUN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, Aug. 5, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JOHN EISENHOWER    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAPPE, Md. _ As a presidential son of 40 years ago, I naturally
take special interest in the careers of others who have been in
similar situations. On the whole, I find it hard to understand why
a member of a president's family, aware of the often unjustified
criticism presidents endure, would voluntarily seek to occupy the
presidency. But those who do should be considered on their own
merits, not as reflections or psychological extensions of their
fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Many pundits have theorized that George W. Bush is seeking to
justify his father's administration after the defeat in 1992, and
looking for a chance to restore his family's honor. This assumption
may be natural, but it is unfair. The son of a president is his own
person, with his own ambitions and talents and views, as he
demonstrated on Thursday night in his nomination speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the third presidential son in our history who has been
seriously considered by a major party for president. John Quincy
Adams, the son of John Adams, was elected president in 1824, and
Robert A. Taft, son of William Howard Taft, ran for the GOP
nomination in 1948 and 1952, though he never attained it. While
some other presidential offspring may have had some political
ambitions _ Robert Todd Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt Jr. come to
mind _ none got far down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps by coincidence, all three who did were sons of
single-term presidents: John Adams was ousted from office by Thomas
Jefferson in 1800, William Howard Taft was a victim of Theodore
Roosevelt's Bull Moose party in 1912 and George H.W. Bush was
defeated for a second term by Bill Clinton in 1992. Perhaps there
is a psychology in these sons of ``getting back,'' a compulsion to
right what they perceive as a wrong. Such a feeling is
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   I can attest to how difficult it is for a presidential family to
leave the grandeur and heady atmosphere of the White House. That
regret must be vastly magnified when the family perceives the term
as having been cut short. The challenge for George W. Bush is one
of timing. He is running only eight short years after his father's
defeat by the man whose designated heir is his rival, and he has
had little time to carve out a political identity of his own.
</P>
<P>
   For the Adamses, 24 years elapsed between the departure of the
father from the White House and the arrival of the son. In the
years between, John Quincy Adams was continuously in governmental
service, minister to several foreign governments and a familiar
public figure. His father lived to see him elected but by then was
far removed from the political scene. For Robert Taft, it was 36
years after his father's departure from the presidency that he
first ran for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In neither of these instances was there any temptation for the
candidate to draw on his father's administration to find aides.
</P>
<P>
   For George W. Bush, however, the circumstances smack of a
comeback and damage his credibility as an independent political
force.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is an important similarity between him and his
historical antecedents. John Quincy Adams was 58 when he became
president (with a minority popular vote). Robert Taft was in his
50s when he made his first serious bid, against Thomas E. Dewey in
1948. Bush is in his early 50s, about 10 years older than John F.
Kennedy was in 1960. It is unjust to think of Bush as ``Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   He deserves to be rated on his own merits, and he should be
discouraging parental visibility in his campaign, a lesson he
learned after the disastrous New Hampshire primary. As we've seen
so far, George W. Bush can fight his own battles.
</P>
<P>
   (John Eisenhower is author of ``Agent of Destiny: The Life and
Times of General Winfield Scott'' and the forthcoming ``Yanks,''
about World War I.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
