<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 13)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending July 29 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. GRANNY DAN, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.50.) A woman
</P>
<P>
   learns the secrets of her grandmother's past in czarist
</P>
<P>
   Russia.
</P>
<P>
   2. TEARS OF THE MOON, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   An Irish songwriter, shut off from the world, finds hope
</P>
<P>
   and happiness with a tomboy.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $14.) Five female characters
</P>
<P>
   narrate a novel set in the Belgian Congo during that
</P>
<P>
   country's fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   4. ASHES TO ASHES, by Tami Hoag. (Bantam, $7.99.) Kate
</P>
<P>
   Conlan, a former FBI agent, tracks a serial killer in
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   5. TARA ROAD, by Maeve Binchy. (Dell, $7.99.) Two women _
</P>
<P>
   one from Ireland, one from England _ learn a lot about
</P>
<P>
   each other and themselves when they exchange houses for
</P>
<P>
   the summer.
</P>
<P>
   6. JUPITER'S BONES, by Faye Kellerman. (Avon/HarperCollins,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) Detectives probe the death of an astrophysicist who
</P>
<P>
   became the leader of a cult.
</P>
<P>
   7. HANNIBAL, by Thomas Harris. (Dell, $7.99.) Seven years
</P>
<P>
   after his escape, the fiendish psychiatrist Hannibal Lecter
</P>
<P>
   is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   8. WHILE I WAS GONE, by Sue Miller. (Ballantine, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A small-town veterinarian, the wife of a minister, begins
</P>
<P>
   a flirtation with an old friend from her bohemian past.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE QUIET GAME, by Greg Iles. (Signet, $6.99.) A best-
</P>
<P>
   selling author and former prosecutor tries to reopen a
</P>
<P>
   30-year-old race murder case in the South.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE WHITE HOUSE CONNECTION, by Jack Higgins. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) Tracking an assassin who threatens the stability
</P>
<P>
   of Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is put
</P>
<P>
   to the test.
</P>
<P>
   12. LIGHTNING STRIKES, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket Star,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A drama student goes to live with her great-aunt,
</P>
<P>
   whose estate is filled with terrors.
</P>
<P>
   13. MCNALLY'S DILEMMA, by Lawrence Sanders. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Archy McNally investigates the death of a Florida
</P>
<P>
   playboy who lived a tangled life; written by Vincent Lardo
</P>
<P>
   after the death of Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   14. DAKOTA HOME, by Debbie Macomber. (Mira, $6.99.) A
</P>
<P>
   deadly storm in North Dakota brings together a rancher
</P>
<P>
   and the woman who desires him.
</P>
<P>
   15. A GAME OF CHANCE, by Linda Howard. (Intimate Moments/
</P>
<P>
   Silhouette, $4.50.) An undercover agent falls for the
</P>
<P>
   beautiful daughter of a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) HEARTWOOD, by James Lee Burke. (Island, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A defense lawyer confronts the richest _ and cruelest
</P>
<P>
   _ man in Deaf Smith, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Perennial/
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.) The story
</P>
<P>
   of the northeaster of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE HUNGRY OCEAN, by Linda Greenlaw. (Hyperion, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   A sea captain's account of her 30-day swordfishing
</P>
<P>
   voyage off the northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced
</P>
<P>
   by feelings of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. ISAAC'S STORM, by Erik Larson. (Vintage, $13.) An
</P>
<P>
   account of America's deadliest hurricane, which killed
</P>
<P>
   6,000 people in Galveston, Texas, in 1900, and the
</P>
<P>
   Weather Bureau scientist who failed to forecast it.
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   6. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man who
</P>
<P>
   survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $10.95.) The author of ``A Child Called `It''' recalls
</P>
<P>
   his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9. I'M A STRANGER HERE MYSELF, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) The author describes what it's like to return to
</P>
<P>
   the United States after living abroad for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $15.) A presentation of superstring theory, which is an
</P>
<P>
   attempt to mediate between quantum mechanics and general
</P>
<P>
   relativity.
</P>
<P>
   11. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor, $13 and
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest
</P>
<P>
   season in history.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer
</P>
<P>
   recalls his childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $13.) How a murderer and
</P>
<P>
   certified lunatic helped James Murray compile the Oxford
</P>
<P>
   English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor, $15.) A journalist explains the instant electronic
</P>
<P>
   global economy.
</P>
<P>
   15. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance
</P>
<P>
   to geography. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   2. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways to
</P>
<P>
   lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. THE OTHER SIDE AND BACK, by Sylvia Browne with Lindsay
</P>
<P>
   Harrison. (Signet, $7.50.) A psychic's guide to coping
</P>
<P>
   with the world and the future. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. THE FOUR AGREEMENTS, by Don Miguel Ruiz. (Amber-Allen,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) A code of conduct based on personal freedom. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK, by Joshua
</P>
<P>
   Piven and David Borgenicht. (Chronicle, $14.95.) Coping
</P>
<P>
   with nasty surprises.
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) RICH DAD'S GUIDE TO INVESTING, by Robert T. Kiyosaki
</P>
<P>
   with Sharon L. Lechter. (Warner, $19.95.) How to invest
</P>
<P>
   and reduce one's risk while doing so.
</P>
