<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-ALEC-GUINNESS-OBITUAR     08-07 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEC-GUINNESS-OBITUARY-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEC GUINNESS: A MASTERPIECE OF UNDERSTATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ by contacting one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 Includes a 450-word sidebar 
 By GAYDEN WREN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The traditional British actor is defined by a booming voice, a
commanding presence and the kind of flamboyant, scenery-chewing
brio that made Laurence Olivier, Richard Burton and Kenneth Branagh
legends.
</P>
<P>
   What irony, then, that Sir Alec Guinness, one of the finest
actors England ever produced, was a chameleonic performer who could
merge himself almost unrecognizably into any role, one who never
boomed when a murmur would do, one who seemed readier to blend into
the scenery than to chew it _ and yet who somehow made a bigger
impression on audiences than practically any of his peers. Guinness
died Saturday at 86. The cause of death was not revealed, but news
reports Monday said he was battling liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In a career spanning more than five decades, Guinness was never
bigger than the characters he played, but nonetheless cast a long
shadow over several generations of actors.
</P>
<P>
   To many, in fact, he was the best actor of his age, a master of
anything from Shakespeare to soap opera _ even if he was most
likely doomed to be forever remembered as Obi-Wan Kenobi.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most remarkable thing about Guinness was his
preternatural mildness, on and offscreen. It seemed almost fitting
that the actor who wrote a book entitled ``My Name Escapes Me''
(Viking Books, 1997) should be the only performer ever to win an
Academy Award for Best Actor for a movie in which his name was
misspelled in the opening titles.
</P>
<P>
   Born in London on April 2, 1914, as Alexander Guinness de Cuffe,
Guinness originally planned a more dependable career as an
advertising writer, but soon gravitated to the theater. Making his
London debut in 1934, he quickly made a name for himself in
classical drama. The actor/director John Gielgud signed him for his
company in 1937, and Guinness spent the next decade on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had had a minor role in ``Evensong'' (1934), it wasn't
until director David Lean cast him in two Dickens adaptations _
``Great Expectations'' (1946) and ``Oliver Twist'' (1948) _ that
Guinness really reached the silver screen. Particularly in the
latter, as a mesmerizingly corrupt Fagin, Guinness demonstrated an
understated style that perfectly suited the up-close-and-personal
approach of film.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a string of Ealing Studios comedies that Guinness
first caught the eye of American audiences. Low-budget but deftly
written and usually spiced with black comedy, such films as ``The
Man in the White Suit'' (1951), ``The Captain's Paradise'' (1953)
and ``The Ladykillers'' (1955) were perfect vehicles for his
low-key, impeccably timed humor.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Ealing films showed him to particular advantage:
``Kind Hearts and Coronets'' (1949) was the story of a young man
scheming to murder his way to a noble title, with Guinness playing
all eight murder victims, while his performance as a meek bank
clerk secretly plotting a spectacular robbery in ``The Lavender
Hill Mob'' (1951) earned him an Oscar nomination as Best Actor _ a
rare feat for an actor in a foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   But by this time Guinness was as marketable in America and
internationally as he was in England, and for the next several
decades he appeared in a number of big-budget, high-profile films,
usually in prominent roles that transcended character acting _ he
managed to be a star without looking like one.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive were four he did for Lean, his first
champion and always his favorite director. ``The Bridge on the
River Kwai'' (1957), ``Lawrence of Arabia'' (1962), ``Doctor
Zhivago'' (1965) and ``A Passage to India'' (1984) proved that,
paradoxically, an actor as physically small as Guinness could work
on Lean's epic screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' offered Guinness his greatest
role _ albeit one that he initially rejected as unplayable. As the
ramrod-stiff commander of a troop of British soldiers in a Japanese
prison camp, he managed to come across as punctilious, arrogant and
deluded _ and yet somehow hugely sympathetic as well. The role won
him the Academy Award as Best Actor, even though he was identified
in the opening credits as ``Alec Guiness.''
</P>
<P>
   As he aged, Guinness continued to find memorable roles. After
portraying the elderly but noble jedi knight Obi-Wan Kenobi in
``Star Wars'' (1977) and two sequels, he turned his gray, everyman
quality to good advantage as spymaster George Smiley in two
television adaptations of John Le Carre novels, ``Tinker, Tailor,
Soldier, Spy'' (1980) and ``Smiley's People'' (1982). He returned
to Dickens for the epic-length ``Little Dorrit'' (1986),
registering an impeccable performance as the heroine's
debt-imprisoned father, earning his second Oscar nomination as Best
Supporting Actor.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s Guinness moved gradually into retirement _ his
memory, he explained, was simply no longer up to the demands of
acting. Instead he returned to an earlier love, writing _ he'd
starred in his own stage adaptation of ``The Brothers Karamazov''
in 1946 and earned an Oscar nomination for his script for ``The
Horse's Mouth'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   Guinness produced a memoir, ``Blessings in Disguise'' (Viking
Press, 1985) and two published diaries _ ``My Name Escapes Me'' and
``A Positively Final Appearance'' (Viking Press, 1999) _ which
demonstrated the same self-effacing charm that had characterized
his work on stage and screen.
</P>
<P>
   And if it was his destiny to be remembered as a jedi knight, he
didn't particularly mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rather surprising to me that I should be remembered at
all,'' he told an interviewer in 1995. ``It might as well be for
that as anything else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: OBI-WAN AND THEN SOME
</P>
<P>
   Most of Alec Guinness' best films can be found on videocassette,
and a few on laser disk or DVD. A greatest-hits sampling might
include the following six films:
</P>
<P>
   ``KIND HEARTS AND CORONETS'' (1949).
</P>
<P>
   Guinness' flamboyant eight-role performance is matched by Dennis
Price's deadpan narration in a seminal British black comedy that
inspired everyone from Peter Sellers to Monty Python. Price is out
to knock off the eight relatives who stand between him and an
aristocratic fortune _ with Guinness playing all eight. Our
favorite: Lady Agatha.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LAVENDER HILL MOB'' (1951).
</P>
<P>
   No one could play timid nebbishes like Guinness, and this
delightful tale of a shy bank clerk plotting to rob a gold truck
suits him to a T. Full of understated British humor and subtle
character interaction, with a great supporting turn by Stanley
Holloway _ ``My Fair Lady's'' Alfie Doolittle. Don't blink in the
opening cafe scene, or you'll miss an astoundingly young Audrey
Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE BRIDGE ON THE RIVER KWAI'' (1957).
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the brisk Col. Nicholson struts into a remote
Japanese work camp at the head of a column of bedraggled British
prisoners, it's clear that Guinness is at the top of his game.
There's a lot going on in what may be David Lean's finest film, but
its core is a battle of wills between Nicholson and the Japanese
commander (Sessue Hayakawa, in a memorable, Oscar-nominated
performance). Guinness, who won the Academy Award as Best Actor for
his performance, is infuriating, inspiring and ultimately sad in a
performance that stays on track right down to the doubly ironic
ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HORSE'S MOUTH'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   Guinness also scripted this offbeat adaptation of Joyce Cary's
novel. As an eccentric painter who lives well outside the
boundaries of conventional society, he delivers one of his finest
performances. Ronald Neame's light directorial hand is just right
for a film that's as much a character portrait as a narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``SMILEY'S PEOPLE'' (1982).
</P>
<P>
   John Le Carre's George Smiley is the ultimate rebuttal to James
Bond, a meticulous bureaucrat whose greatest gift happens to lie in
the minutiae of spycraft. In this television miniseries and its
predecessor, ``Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy'' (1980), Guinness
makes Smiley so utterly believable _ and, in the final analysis, so
deeply sad _ that Mr. Bond might as well put away his license and
go home. Guinness' immensely detailed portrayal needs all of its
six hours to convey its full impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``STAR WARS'' (1977).
</P>
<P>
   Amid a cast of brash, young actors, director George Lucas
cannily placed Guinness as Old Ben Kenobi, the sun-creased desert
rat whose placid exterior masks his past as Obi-Wan Kenobi, once
and future jedi knight. Guinness had to wait until he was 63 to get
a worthwhile swashbuckling scene, but he makes the most of it.
After watching this Oscar-nominated performance, revisit ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace'' (1999) to appreciate Ewan McGregor's
skillful emulation of Guinness' performance for his role as the
young Obi-Wan.
</P>
<P>
   (Gayden Wren is the entertainment editor for The New York Times
Syndicate.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: To publish this ``separate-buy'' feature article, it must
be purchased. Please contact one of these sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
