commander (Sessue Hayakawa, in a memorable, Oscar-nominated
performance). Guinness, who won the Academy Award as Best Actor for
his performance, is infuriating, inspiring and ultimately sad in a
performance that stays on track right down to the doubly ironic
ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HORSE'S MOUTH'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   Guinness also scripted this offbeat adaptation of Joyce Cary's
novel. As an eccentric painter who lives well outside the
boundaries of conventional society, he delivers one of his finest
performances. Ronald Neame's light directorial hand is just right
for a film that's as much a character portrait as a narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``SMILEY'S PEOPLE'' (1982).
</P>
<P>
   John Le Carre's George Smiley is the ultimate rebuttal to James
Bond, a meticulous bureaucrat whose greatest gift happens to lie in
the minutiae of spycraft. In this television miniseries and its
predecessor, ``Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy'' (1980), Guinness
makes Smiley so utterly believable _ and, in the final analysis, so
deeply sad _ that Mr. Bond might as well put away his license and
go home. Guinness' immensely detailed portrayal needs all of its
six hours to convey its full impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``STAR WARS'' (1977).
</P>
<P>
   Amid a cast of brash, young actors, director George Lucas
cannily placed Guinness as Old Ben Kenobi, the sun-creased desert
rat whose placid exterior masks his past as Obi-Wan Kenobi, once
and future jedi knight. Guinness had to wait until he was 63 to get
a worthwhile swashbuckling scene, but he makes the most of it.
After watching this Oscar-nominated performance, revisit ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace'' (1999) to appreciate Ewan McGregor's
skillful emulation of Guinness' performance for his role as the
young Obi-Wan.
</P>
<P>
   (Gayden Wren is the entertainment editor for The New York Times
Syndicate.)
</P>
<P>
