<HEADLINE>
ALEC GUINNESS: A MASTERPIECE OF UNDERSTATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a 450-word sidebar 
 By GAYDEN WREN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 1,400-word appreciation of actor Alec Guinness by Gayden Wren,
entertainment editor for The New York Times Syndicate, has moved on
the ``e'' entertainment category.
</P>
<P>
   Wren writes: ``The traditional British actor is defined by a
booming voice, a commanding presence and the kind of flamboyant,
scenery-chewing brio that made Laurence Olivier, Richard Burton and
Kenneth Branagh legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``What irony, then, that one of the finest actors England ever
produced was a chameleonic performer who could merge himself almost
unrecognizably into any role, one who never boomed when a murmur
would do, one who seemed readier to blend into the scenery than to
chew it _ and yet who somehow made a bigger impression on audiences
than practically any of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a career spanning more than five decades, Sir Alec Guinness
was never bigger than the characters he played, but nonetheless
cast a long shadow over several generations of actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To many, in fact, he was the best actor of his age, a master
of anything from Shakespeare to soap opera _ even if he was most
likely doomed to be forever remembered as Obi-Wan Kenobi.''
</P>
<P>
   Includes a sidebar with recommendations of Guinness' six best
films available on video.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged: BC-ALEC-GUINNESS-OBIT-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF.
</P>
