<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN9-COX     08-07 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN9-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Is Bush's pedigree critical?
 &HT;    For release Aug. 9, 2000
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Far be it from me to pillage others for knee-jerk reactions
without recognizing that I, too, often am guilty of such
reverberations, as are almost all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I have been bristling about some post-Republican
convention knee-jerking regarding George W. Bush that I find to be
unfair. Say what you want about Bush (my thoughts remain in
opposition to his election) but some radio talk hosts and
columnists need to get over that ``silver spoon'' image they are
trying to hang on the Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   First, the same could be said of Al Gore; he wasn't exactly born
in one of those celebrated Tennessee log cabins.
</P>
<P>
   But more important is the argument by these antagonists that
Bush, delivered at birth with an oily but silver spoon in his
mouth, cannot relate to the poorer classes of Americans because he
never was in their class, never suffered, never was deprived of
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they contend, anyone born of the historically wealthy
Bush-Pierce-Walker clans correlates only to his peers and, thus,
can travel only in the environment of Big Oil, investment banking
and the steel industry.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it was Bush's acceptance speech that touched off the
reaction. After all, he did sound more like an earthy Democrat than
a Republican, espousing all that social compassion rather than the
desk-pounding rightist rhetoric of the old Newt Gingrich gang.
</P>
<P>
   But there certainly is precedence for an affluent president not
only to reach out to the quote, masses, unquote but to actually do
something about it. Anyone ever hear of Franklin Delano Roosevelt
and John F. Kennedy? For every humble beginning of a Lincoln,
Truman or Nixon, there is a rich man elected to the White House.
That does not foreclose on his ability or desire to do something
for people not born of his privilege.
</P>
<P>
   There are things about George W. with which I do not agree, but
his pedigree is not one of them. (Do not mistake me for a rich kid
either; my father drove a laundry truck then later sold throwaway
pillows.)
</P>
<P>
   Surely, FDR was among the most privileged of people to assume
the presidency, but his measures on behalf of the working class,
particularly the inception of the Social Security system, stood him
in the forefront of champions of the average (or lesser) American
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   JFK to this day is remembered as the president who launched long
overdue civil rights legislation and other major social programs
that were enacted during the succeeding Lyndon Johnson
administration. Brothers Bobby and Teddy likely ate their first
strained baby food from a gold spoon rather than a silver one, but
their political records are squarely on the side of the unrich.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Bush advocates a considerable number of stereotypical
GOP upper class causes, but that does not prevent him from being
similarly inclined to helping the poorer strata of America.
</P>
<P>
   There are some of us who believe his compassion from the pulpit
last week was more theater than reality and that, even if we're
wrong in that contention and Bush is sincere, it's not going to be
easy to push stronger social legislation through his more rigid
conservative compadres in the Congress. At least not until their
own fiscal agenda is achieved, after which little will be left for
the others.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, with his denim shirts and boots, likes to reflect a
down-to-earth guy who will continue to be that way in the White
House. Maybe that is the real him. His father certainly carried
himself that way and his mother is the epitome of the nice lady who
left a pie in the window sill.
</P>
<P>
   Those harshly opposed to George W. refuse to see the denim,
instead see only his Texas oil-rich experience without also
realizing that Lyndon Johnson, despite his youth as an elevator
operator, car washer, field hand and cafe worker, mixed well with
the Texas oil folks himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should be judged on his programs, when and if you sort out
what he can and cannot do. His pedigree is immaterial. We have
learned from presidents in the past that it matters not from where
you came, but where you are going.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 0957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
