<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4549 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     08-07 1610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In India, a Reality Drama for Real &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The line between fantasy and reality is perhaps never as pliable
as in the minds of people who love the movie screen, or so it
seemed in India last week. There, a real-life mustachioed villain
seized a fantasy-life hero and kept millions of people and their
officials in suspense about what might happen next.
</P>
<P>
   The villain of the piece is Veerappan, said by the authorities
to be an aging smuggler and elephant poacher who killed his
daughter and dozens of policemen. He has nevertheless played Robin
Hood to forest dwellers in southern India as he has eluded years of
efforts by the authorities to arrest him. But now he wants to be
allowed to live a normal life, and stop hiding.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, police say, he kidnapped and hid in the jungle one
of India's most revered movie idols _ 72-year-old Rajkumar, who
millions of Indians have seen on the screen as a Hindu god or a
king or a hero in some other garb. The star has made more than 200
films in all.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, the plan is for the real criminal to ransom the
fantasy hero for some sort of a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   The public's reaction was equal to the staggering audacity of
the crime. On Monday and Tuesday in Bangalore, a city otherwise
known mostly for its booming information technology industry, bands
of movie fans erupted in street protests bordering on violence and
brought the city nearly to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   And one novelist, U.R. Ananthumurthy, drew the appropriate
lesson. Bangalore, he said, ``belongs to the modern world system
and thinks it can ignore mass psychology. But it forgets that other
reality that lurks within.''
</P>
<P>
   Drop That Doubloon &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you drop a dollar bill on the sidewalk and do not pick it up
quickly, it is safe to say you have lost your rights to it. If your
sailing ship drops into the sea, though, is it still yours?
</P>
<P>
   Until now, probably not. But the idea of finding and salvaging
lost treasure just got a nasty legal jolt.
</P>
<P>
   In its years of conquering parts of the world, Spain left many a
ship on the ocean floor, often laden with riches, and these
provided juicy targets for adventurers. But with technology making
salvaging easier these days, Spain and other countries want to
reclaim these scraps of heritage _ and loot. And a federal appeals
court in Virginia has now ruled that two ships sunk off that
state's coast still, centuries later, belong to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Treasure hunters are not happy, and the one who found those two
ships is weighing an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ruling stands, it could mean, say, that the British
could lay claim to the superstar of wrecks, the Titanic. On the
other hand, it could also raise trickier issues. After all, much of
that Spanish loot was first stolen from Latin American natives. Who
has the prior claim now?
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   After Camp David, Thin Ice for Barak
</P>
<P>
   Israel's fractious parliament gave a little breathing room and a
thumb in the eye to Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his embattled
efforts to reach a compromise on Jerusalem with Yasser Arafat and
nail down the terms of a final peace accord this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In one vote on Monday, July 31, Barak's government survived a
no-confidence motion mounted by opponents of the peace effort. But
in a second vote that day, Barak's candidate for the largely
ceremonial Israeli presidency, Shimon Peres, was defeated in favor
of the opposition Likud candidate, Moshe Katsav. Two days later,
Barak's foreign minister, David Levy, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   A Civil Rights Probe
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos National Laboratory, where the atomic bomb was
developed during World War II, has come under investigation by the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, a federal civil rights
agency. The agency is looking into possible discrimination against
Asian and Asian-American scientists, some of whom have charged that
security measures put in place after the arrest of Dr. Wen Ho Lee,
a former Los Alamos scientist charged with mishandling nuclear
data, have focused unfairly on them. The commission began a similar
investigation of another weapons laboratory, Lawrence Livermore,
last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
<P>
   A New Climate Strategy  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Girding for talks that could shape a global treaty to avert
harmful climate warming, the United States said it could not meet
targets only by cutting back on burning coal and oil, which emit
heat-trapping carbon dioxide. It must get credit for the country's
forests and fields, which can sop up the same greenhouse gas.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, Russia and other countries with lots of green acres are
echoing the position. But Europe, largely shorn of forests, says
that's cheating, and some environmental groups, eager for more
solar panels and fewer power plants, agree.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREW C. REVKIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QR; 
 &UR; UNDATED: C. REVKIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Chooses Evolution
</P>
<P>
   In a blow to creationists, Kansas voters rejected the state
school board's decision last year to remove evolution from the
school science curriculum, paving the way for that decision to be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   In a Republican primary on Tuesday, voters defeated three
conservatives who supported the new science standards, in favor of
moderates who want evolution to be taught. That means evolution is
all but certain to be reinstated in the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution is still a battleground in other states, however. And
some opponents of the theory of evolution said the Kansas defeat
would only stiffen their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PAM BELLUCK
</P>
<P>
   Liberia's President Blamed In a Diamond-Driven War
</P>
<P>
   International efforts to end the diamond-driven civil war in
Sierra Leone, where rebels have wrecked the country and mutilated
thousands of civilians, are being thwarted by the president of
neighboring Liberia, U.S. and British diplomats said at a United
Nations hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberian president, Charles Taylor, has taken command of the
rebels' fight against government troops and international
peacekeepers, the diplomats said, adding that Taylor meets
regularly for strategy sessions with rebel officers, while
personally profiting from trading arms, ammunition and food for
smuggled diamonds. The Liberian government denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BLAINE HARDEN
</P>
<P>
   Soldier Sentenced for Murder
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. military court in Germany sentenced a U.S. soldier to
life imprisonment without parole for the murder of an 11-year-old
Kosovo Albanian girl. Staff Sgt. Frank Ronghi, 36, pleaded guilty
to sodomizing and murdering Merita Shabiu while on peacekeeping
duty in the Balkans. Ronghi's sentence was the most severe one open
to a military court holding a trial in Germany, where the death
penalty does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   A New Kind of Publisher
</P>
<P>
   Staking out a place for itself in the world of electronic
publishing, Random House, a unit of Bertelsmann AG, created a new
imprint to publish exclusively digital books. The company said 20
new titles will be available beginning in January, either for
downloading via the Internet or in single paperback copies printed
as ordered by high-speed presses; none of the books will be
distributed to bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK
</P>
<P>
   German Silence Is Challenged
</P>
<P>
   A bombing that wounded nine immigrants, six of them Jews,
prompted Germany's foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, to suggest
that a silent majority of Germans may be abetting such crimes by
not speaking out against them.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants, particularly in the formerly communist east, find
themselves repeated targets for neo-Nazi rightist groups, and
Fischer was clearly taking aim at the apparent passivity of many
Germans in the face of racist crimes that have become commonplace.
It is time, he said, that the silent majority was ``roused.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Bungled, but not Political
</P>
<P>
   One year before the 1996 presidential election, the Immigration
and Naturalization Service launched a program to naturalize 1
million immigrants. The timing raised eyebrows. Now a Justice
Department report has found that while the agency bungled the job,
and as many as 180,000 immigrants became citizens without proper
background checks, officials did not improperly meddle with the
program to beef up voter rolls by election day.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LIZETTE ALVAREZ
</P>
<P>
   A New Drug Front
</P>
<P>
   The nation's law enforcement community reported that it was
suddenly facing another potential front in its longstanding war on
drugs: a psychedelic drug nicknamed Ecstasy. It has gained wide
appeal among young  &QL; 
people, particularly those on the nightclub circuit, and in the
last 10 months, agents for the U.S. Customs Service have seized a
record 8 million doses at the nation's airports and other ports of
entry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, law enforcement officials seem to be at a loss over how
to combat it. _ By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ
</P>
<P>
   Questions on Brady Law
</P>
<P>
   A study in The Journal of the American Medical Association says
there is no evidence the 1994 Brady Law, which mandates background
checks of handgun buyers, has contributed to the recent sharp
decline in homicide.
</P>
<P>
   That is music to the ears of the National Rifle Association,
which argues that laws don't stop criminals from getting guns.
</P>
<P>
   But gun control advocates say the study is flawed, and even the
study's authors acknowledge that a major reason the Brady law may
not have been effective is its limited scope.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FOX BUTTERFIELD
</P>
</TEXT>
