<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MIDEAST-ARABS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE ASKS FOR ARAB UNITY. GETTING IT IS HARDER. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Political slogans tend to long outlive their
authors in this part of the world and none is more enduring, or
more musty with age, than the 1950s-vintage catch phrase ``Arab
unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years have passed since all 22 leaders of Arab League
countries last gathered for a summit meeting, which was held here,
in the aftermath of Iraq's surprise invasion of Kuwait on Aug. 2,
1990. It was not a pretty sight, marred by food fights between
angry Kuwaiti sheiks and bellicose Iraqi officials, and by
recriminations and vacillation all around.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the urging of the Palestinians, a few Arab leaders like
Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak and Jordan's King Abdullah have
renewed the perennial call for a new summit meeting, this time
billed as an emergency meeting for Arabs to regroup after the
failure at Camp David and to counter the spin from Washington that
the breakdown was due solely to Arab recalcitrance. Chances for a
summit meeting and a new Arab consensus are slim, Arab officials
now say. Still, the chimera of a united Arab front continues to
shimmer on the horizon _ and, suddenly, not just for the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long found the Arabs' fractiousness useful
in promoting bilateral peace talks and maintaining sanctions on
Iraq. But now Edward Walker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state,
has been sent on a tour of Arab states that maintain relations with
the United States; he is asking leaders to persuade Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to accept Israeli and U.S. proposals for a
final peace.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of those proposals is an offer of shared
administration of Arab East Jerusalem, but not of sovereignty over
it. So far, the public reaction to Walker's trip has been
resentment that the United States seems to be calling in its chits
in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, the Arab state of affairs is sufficiently dismal to
foreclose a decisive pan-Arab stand on Jerusalem and the need to
restore Arab sovereignty over its eastern sector,'' wrote Joseph
Samaha, a Lebanese analyst for the international Arabic daily
newspaper Al Hayat. ``But it's not that bad that the Arabs will
concede the loss of the city to Israel forever.''
</P>
<P>
   If a less fragmented Arab leadership would be helpful to
Washington and Israel for the first time in a decade _ and helpful
to Arabs who are nostalgic for the days when, collectively, they
counted for more _ it is also much harder to nail down now.
</P>
<P>
   First, the internal political and economic situation in the Arab
world is more fragile than it was a decade ago, when Washington
could stitch together an anti-Iraq alliance that included most Arab
nations and then proceed to establish its own primacy in the
region, where many countries are beggars for money and arms.
</P>
<P>
   Long-serving military figures who once could simply impose their
will on their people, like King Hussein of Jordan and Hafez Assad
of Syria, are gone. The nations they left behind for their sons and
successors suffer under sick economies with raging unemployment.
Moreover, their heirs are still consolidating power, making them
more sensitive to hints of internal discontent and to the threat,
real or not, of minority extremists who criticize anything that
seems to be catering to Israel or the West.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new cast of characters in Arab politics is
theoretically more free of the constraints of history than the old.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein and Assad, along with the assassinated Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, were warriors of the Arab-Israeli
conflict. Rabin carried an aura of victory, as the former commander
in the 1967 war, in which Jordan and Syria lost big chunks of
territory to Israel. But their 1967 defeats, and their failure to
regain either the West Bank or the Golan Heights through war or
diplomacy, weighed heavily on the shoulders of the two Arab
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the Syrian and Jordanian leaders also contributed
mightily to the lack of Arab unity. No friends of each other, both
also had hostile relations with Arafat, as did the late King Hassan
of Morocco, another leader who has bequeathed a regime to his son.
</P>
<P>
   While their absence from the scene could be considered helpful
to peacemaking and Arab unity, the legacy they left of failing
economies and ideologically rigid governments may sabotage those
goals for their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baggage of history on their sons is just as great,'' said
Kamel Abu Jaber, a former Jordanian foreign minister who is now
president of the Jordanian Institute for Diplomacy. ``That's the
historical danger of Camp David. It may revive in these young
leaders, who may be willing to compromise, a tendency to refreeze
into rigid attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, the Arab world is also running at different
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic fundamentalist movements, while brutally suppressed in
places like Egypt and Syria, are still alive and well elsewhere.
The ruling family of Saudi Arabia feels under constant threat from
extremists inside and outside the country who criticize it for the
continued presence of American troops on its soil. Fundamentalist
groups opposed to the Saudi policy of cool cooperation with the
West send out streams of e-mails each day accusing the royals of
corruption and decadence.
</P>
<P>
   In Kuwait, a new alliance of Islamists and nationalists has
warned the government against making contacts with Israel or
Israelis. So while people in Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and Egypt may
yearn for the presumed economic benefits of a comprehensive peace,
the domestic message to the rulers in the Gulf is far different.
``Nobody here cares about the supposed economic benefits,'' said
Ahmed Baghdadi, a professor of political science at Kuwait
University. ``In contrast, the religious movement in the National
Assembly is very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-MIDEAST-ARABS-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CAIRO: very strong.'' &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So the Old City, a tiny island that contains sites holy to
Islam, Christianity and Judaism, may be the one topic that can
unite the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place where Jesus Christ was resurrected, where Omar built
his mosque, where the Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven _ that's
not big stuff?'' commented Abdel Moneim Said, director of the Al
Ahram Center for Political and Strategic Studies. ``It's in the
Koran. It's in the prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Arab analysts warn that those concerned with the
Middle East should be careful of what they wish for. Unity in the
Middle East has historically been reactive: a collective ``no.''
The Arab League was created in 1949 to organize opposition to the
state of Israel. The Organization of the Islamic Conference, a
broader group, was created in 1969 to focus Muslim anger at an
attempt by a Christian extremist in Jerusalem to burn down Al Aksa
mosque.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if a final peace settlement is the goal, the region
may be better served by disunity, with each nation following its
own interests and path.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a final settlement, then here in Jordan at least
we hopefully can start talking about a country that is concerned
about something other than the Palestinian question,'' said Adnan
Abu Odeh, a former adviser to Jordan's King Hussein. ``These days,
unfortunately, the region is clouded with illusions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
