<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-KILLER-KID-TEXT-REV     08-07 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KILLER-KID-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS, MAYHEM AND GRIEF CAN FLOURISH WHEN FRIENDS DO NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   (The Week in Review)  
 and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (editors: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the enduring mysteries of the school shootings in places
like Littleton, Colo., and West Paducah, Ky., is how so many people
could have known so much but done so little to prevent bloodshed.
The Columbine High School massacre, in which 15 people were killed,
took place in April 1999. This May a 13-year-old boy fatally shot a
teacher in Lake Worth, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In case after case, the friends and acquaintances of the killers
had heard boasts, muttered plans for mayhem or seen such warning
signs as a fascination with guns that may have seemed dissonant
even in communities of sportsmen and firearms. But they did nothing
to stop the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The recently released testimony of teen-agers who knew one such
killer provide some explanation. At 14, Michael Carneal killed
three girls and injured five other students when he opened fire on
a prayer group at Heath High School in West Paducah, Ky., on Dec.
1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The following excerpts are from depositions of the teen-agers
that were filed in a civil damage suit in McCracken County Circuit
Court in Paducah. The questioner, in most instances, is Mike Breen,
a lawyer for the parents of the three murdered girls, Nicole
Hadley, Kayce Steger and Jessica James. The parents sued more than
50 people, including many of the teen-agers who knew Carneal,
claiming that they could have prevented the killings or, in some
cases, that they had helped plan them. The judge, William L.
Shadoan, dismissed the suits, ruling that only the killer could be
held liable for his crime. Carneal, now 17, is serving a life
sentence after pleading guilty, saying he was mentally ill at the
time of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM GLABERSON
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Jeremy T. Ellis, 10th grader at the time of
the killings, describing Carneal, a friend from the school band:
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   He was just this goofy kid that just did really silly stuff. And
I liked that, because I'm a silly guy myself. . . . He told me,
once or twice, that he thought it would be cool to walk _ or run _
down the halls shooting people. And he told me once he thought that
it would be cool to go to prison. . . . He told me that he would,
like, get keys to people's houses, and, like, just go up and unlock
the door and, like, steal medication and stuff, and money from
people's houses. . . . You, like, look back and you see all these
little things that he did that were like, sort of like warning
signs, sort of, but you didn't really realize them at the time. . .
. At the time, I thought I knew him, you know. But then, like,
after all this, I really didn't know him at all, because . . .
like, this silly person was just a cover-up of this other guy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Matthew R. Neamon, 9th grader, Carneal's
friend since second grade. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   He brought a gun to school, and he showed it to me . . . the
November before. . . . He had it in his backpack. . . . It was a
pistol . . . semiautomatic. . . . He was like, ``Do you want to see
something?'' And I was like, sure. And he showed it to me. And,
`Ooh, a gun' . . . There was a rumor on other days that he had one.
. . . Just ``Michael has a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it against rules at school to have guns there?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you tell anybody about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why not?
</P>
<P>
   A: Like I said, because I didn't want to get my friend in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Amanda M. Jones, ninth grader, was
Michael's girlfriend the fall before the shootings. (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ((He was)) usually quiet, but then sometimes he would get noisy
and annoying. . . . More when we were in high school, probably to
fit in. . . . He got picked on a lot because he was small and _ I
don't know _ he didn't play football, or anything. But a lot of
freshmen got picked on. . . . He wasn't a big part of the jock
population. . . . He just wasn't real tough and big. He was small.
. . .. He was stranger than we are, more strange.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you ever hear Michael talk about taking over the school?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah. Not as in seriously. A lot of kids talk about taking
over the school . . . No one likes school, so. . . . Every school
I've been to, someone would mention we should burn down the school.
It's not strange for someone to not like school. . . . It was
around Halloween, he brought a gun to school that he was trying to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know what kind of gun it was?
</P>
<P>
   A: A revolver? It's silver and the kind that has the spinny
thing that comes out. . . . For some reason, it didn't strike me as
odd.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Really?
</P>
<P>
   A: I just thought, well, he's trying to sell a gun. . . . I
didn't really _ I didn't think, ``Oh, goodness, he's going to kill
someone at school,'' because that just never had happened.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) William J. Alonso, a 12th grader, whose
younger brother was a friend of Carneal. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Q: He was ((at your house)) the Saturday before the shootings?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. . . . I talked to Michael Carneal. . . . His sister had
told me that he was doing stuff with credit cards, buying stuff off
the Internet with credit card numbers that were not his. And I
warned him about getting in trouble and getting caught. And I told
him that if he got caught, he had to shower in front of a bunch of
guys, and probably wouldn't like that. That's about all I can
remember of the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-KILLER-KID-TEXT-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: the discussion. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK. Did he have any weapons with him at the time?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, he did.
</P>
<P>
   A: There was a handgun and some rifles. They were . . . on the
floor, like, on a blanket type thing ((in my brother's bedroom)). .
. . There was no conversation about the guns.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You didn't say anything about them?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I did not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you tell anybody about the guns?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I did not.
</P>
<P>
   A: Why not?
</P>
<P>
   A: It didn't seem too out of place. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q: You go in there to counsel Michael Carneal about other
matters. You see other weapons there. You counsel Michael; is that
right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does he say in response to that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wait until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And how did you take that?
</P>
<P>
   A: I took it like he was going to pull a prank in school.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Matthew T. Barnett, 10th grader, another
friend of Carneal. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a statement here that you gave to the police. . . .
And it says . . . ``Michael Carneal said we should go into ((the
school administration)) office and shoot them while in their
offices. Barnett responded `Yeah, yeah,' but didn't think anything
about it.'' . . . What was your reaction to that statement, when
Carneal made it to you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not much of one. It's just idle conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You considered a statement that Michael Carneal wanted to go
in and shoot school personnel an idle statement?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure. I mean, I'm sure people, all over the place, say random
things like that, you know, not meaning anything by them. You know,
like, ``I really hate this,'' you know. And they don't mean
anything by it. And people don't take them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And so, people, according to you, don't take threats to
murder like this seriously?
</P>
<P>
   A: It wasn't a threat to murder, though. . . . It was probably
just us hanging around at school, at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Alan W. Coleman, a 12th grader and friend
of Carneal. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ((On the morning of the shootings)) I arrived at school
approximately 7:35 a.m. . . . Usually, I was there a little bit
later. But I did get there to see what Michael was going to do. . .
. Because he told us, on the Wednesday before Thanksgiving, that he
was going to do something. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you took him seriously enough, at least to the extent
that you thought he was going to do something that was going to be
worth watching, right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you showed up to school early that day so you could see?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: All right. And during the time that you were thinking about
this, between the Wednesday that he made the statement and the
Monday morning that he actually did it, did you contact anybody
about it and tell them?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why not?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was expecting a practical joke of some sort. . . . Perhaps
fireworks, water balloons, something of that nature.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Toby Nace, a ninth grader, was once one of
Michael's best friends, although they had drifted apart. (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   After we watched a movie, ``Basketball Diaries'' ((which
includes a fantasy of a violent school shooting)), he said that
would be neat to go in the school and shoot people that you don't
like. . . . And he said, if you're going to take over the school,
you could use those axes. . . . I just went along with him. I said,
``Yeah, if you're going to take over the school, you would have to
cut the phone lines,'' or something. . . . He just did stuff to get
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ((The morning of the murders)) I seen him put ear plugs in, and
((I)) say, ``Hey, it would be funny if you wore those during class
while the teacher is giving a speech.'' And he laughed. And then I
just turned around. And then, when I turned back, he was pulling a
gun out of his backpack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
