<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-TECH-SUITS-REVIEW-N     08-07 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TECH-SUITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANARCHIC E-COMMERCE: ONLINE DAVIDS VS. CORPORATE GOLIATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a business culture that has long fixated ambivalently on the
image of computer wizards brewing technological revolution in their
garage, the back-story to the pair of digital copyright battles
being waged in federal courts on either coast has a familiar ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Napster case in San Francisco involves a 19-year-old college
student who created a program allowing him to swap music files with
his friends. The program became so popular so fast that the major
record labels claim it has led to widespread music piracy,
threatening their ability to turn a profit and the incentive of
artists to create music.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD trial in New York began with a Norwegian high school
student who cracked the encryption program protecting Hollywood's
digitized movies from unauthorized copying. Leading movie studios
argue that unless a judge stops a Web site publisher from
distributing the 16-year-old's decryption code, they will soon
suffer the same fate as the record industry.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who you believe, these are either tales of David
vs. Goliath or of irresponsible hackers taking aim at the
establishment. But no matter which side you're on, both cases have
underscored the unprecedented ability of individuals armed with
digital technology to upset the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very much looking at a biological model of an
epidemic,'' said Esther Dyson, publisher of the technology
newsletter Release 1.0. ``On the Internet, a product doesn't
require a central host and it doesn't require central distribution,
it just spreads. It's new in business. It's been going on a long
time in viruses.''
</P>
<P>
   As more people connect to the Internet, with faster connections,
the information released on it takes on ever-greater momentum and
scale. Services like Napster are seen as only the beginning of a
technological siege for industries founded on traditional notions
of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many Internet watchers, Dyson among them, believe that
companies that put information online, from music to books to
software, may have to resign themselves to relinquishing control
over that material. The fact that you copyrighted something simply
may no longer entitle you to control it or get paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an idea whose time has come,'' said John Perry Barlow,
the vice chairman of the Electronic Frontier Foundation, and author
of an essay ``The Economy of Ideas,'' which in 1994 predicted a
fundamental shift in the way intellectual property is valued.
``We're dealing with a profound historical shift in the economy
that has been enabled by technology.''
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially what happened in the Napster and DVD cases,
and though federal judges saw fit to issue injunctions in each
case, that may be irrelevant in the world of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling moments in the Napster saga came
between the time Judge Marilyn Patel issued a temporary injunction
effectively shutting down the service and the stay that was granted
not quite 48 hours later by a higher court. Despite Patel's clear
statement that Napster was likely to be found guilty of
contributing to copyright infringement, millions of individuals
swarmed to download music from the service, or learn about
alternative services that provide the means to swap music files.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the DVD decryption code patched together by Jon
Johansen in Norway has been posted on hundreds of Web sites besides
the one that Hollywood has taken to court, many of which say they
are simply upholding their right to share technology information.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, technology and its users are undermining
traditional institutions, while asserting a populist sense of what
is ethical that may well clash with what is legal. That has raised
questions that go well beyond the outcome of the court battles.
</P>
<P>
   What happens, for instance, if Patel in San Francisco and Judge
Lewis A. Kaplan in New York come down on the side of the
entertainment industry, but the distribution of both copyrighted
music and a computer code that cracks legally protected encryption
continues undeterred?
</P>
<P>
   ``Law is very vulnerable when it makes orders that don't get
enforced,'' said Charles Nesson, director of the Berkman Center for
Internet and Society at Harvard University. ``Law consists of two
things, the coercive power to impose a sanction on someone who
violates it and the willingness of people to obey the law without
actually putting it to the test. The more you undermine the
credibility of law with the people who are governed by it, the more
you need sanctions to keep order.''
</P>
<P>
   But can any court arrest 20 million Napster users around the
world? Intellectual property has always depended on both legal and
physical barriers to copying, Nesson noted. With the physical
barriers all but removed, the reliance of copyright holders on the
law may be straining it beyond its capacity to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   These information-sharing technologies are still in their
infancy. Napster's file-swapping progeny, like Freenet and
Gnutella, dispense with any vestiges of central information
altogether. Everything from video games to Scientology texts are
being traded over such networks, which hit the Internet just a few
months ago. And the inventors of even newer ones with names like
MojoNation and COLAVision were demonstrating their wares last week
at a hacker convention in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what has become known as ``peer-to-peer'' technology,
such services have vastly simplified the ability of individuals to
trade files of any sort among themselves, and to decide for
themselves whether or not to obey copyright law. Most seem to be
choosing the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use Napster, I'd be crazy if I wouldn't,'' wrote one
14-year-old in an e-mail message after Patel issued her preliminary
injunction last month. ``It lets me sample the songs from a CD and
I get to see if I want to buy the CD or not. I don't find it to be
any damaging to any musicians. I actually think it is helping
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In part because that attitude may herald a shift in the law and
in part because the music industry will face other, less
centralized networks using similar technology, many legal experts
and economists believe that the record labels would be better off
adapting their business models than suing Napster for copyright
infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still very much a common-law culture,'' said Lawrence
Lessig, a law professor at Stanford University who has submitted a
brief urging that Napster not be shut down. ``If the law does not
accord with the view of the common kid, then the law will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of the Napster refugees flooding the Gnutella mailing list
with set-up questions last week seemed terribly concerned about the
outcome of the San Francisco case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can someone please inform me on how to start everything up,''
read one typical post by a new user, ``I wanna get to mp3's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
