<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late sleepers face schools for early risers
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Not all back-to-school supplies are bought
for kids. Myself, I bought vital equipment for a high school parent
_ a thermos bottle and a coffee mug with a nearly spillproof
plastic top.
</P>
<P>
   The high school's late bell will ring at 7:20 a.m., an hour I
have dedicated my life to avoiding. For the next several years, my
kids and I will be consigned to a world designed for morning
people. And a harsh world it is.
</P>
<P>
   My theory is this happened out of the stealth of morning people.
They are up first, so they have time to run about, get memos signed
and make rules for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   If a large number of parents aren't morning people, even larger
numbers of teens aren't as well.
</P>
<P>
   Medical studies of sleep published in the 1980s and 1990s have
found, unsurprisingly, that people sleep differently at different
stages of life.
</P>
<P>
   The medical literature says little kids bounce out of bed at
ungodly hours of the dim morning. But teens tend to putter around
the house past midnight and wake up at the crack of noon.
</P>
<P>
   Little kids are alert earlier in the morning. Adolescents are
alert later and need more sleep as they get older.
</P>
<P>
   This is one more new scientific revelation that parents have
known for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what do schools around the nation do? You guessed it. They
tend to start school later for students in lower grades and start
high school at hours associated with milking cows, shipping out to
sea and delivering
</P>
<P>
   newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Who's behind this? Morning people, I suppose. Coaches also like
it because they can hold practices earlier. School administrators
use it to schedule buses in shifts and get more use out of each
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Who else likes it? Oh, just about nobody. Only those annoying
morning people. And maybe convenience store operators and the
powerful spillproof car-mug manufacturers' lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and administrators in a Minnesota school district
looked at the research in 1996 and read a letter from Minnesota
Medical Association to the state's school superintendents that
urged later starting times for high schools. The Edina, Minn.,
school district responded by resetting tardy bells from 7:25 to
8:30.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators last year said that after almost three years,
absenteeism was down, grades were up and students and teachers were
more alert.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of parents found 95 percent liked the change.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no medical scientist, but later hours just make sense. You
can't reset the body's circadian rhythms by setting alarm clocks to
snarl before sunrise. You only end up with sleep-deprived teens who
can't remember what happened in first period.
</P>
<P>
   My house of late risers faces a hard transition next week. My
kids will be sleepwalking from the car. And my editors will have
their work cut out for them after I stumble through the doors and
try to make my fingers hit specific letters on a coffee-splattered
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm just a late riser staggering around a world organized
by people who bounded to their desks before I had time to stare
down my cornflakes. A half-shaven whiner. But for once, medical
science backs me up.
</P>
<P>
   Late rising is not slothfulness. It is the result of
half-understand bodily rhythms. It is one more strange thing that
happens to a normal brain during adolescence. Much like the enzyme
that makes them wear ugly
</P>
<P>
   clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Reforming us is futile and all we need is just another hour. And
caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
