<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The doctors are in
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Amos limps into the cafe this morning, picks
up his decaf from Robin, and hobbles over to join us. ``Looks like
you're just about fit for shootin','' Cal says to his old buddy.
``Whatsa' matter'' Lucy give you that swift kick you been asking
for?''
</P>
<P>
   Amos pulls over an empty chair to rest his leg on and sits with
an obvious effort. ``I think I got a toe nail growing in wrong.''
Benny says not to complain because at his age he's lucky to have
anything at all that's still growing.
</P>
<P>
   I scan the faces around the table. Most are well into their 70s.
Benny admits to 75, but he's been saying that for the whole 16
years I've been drinking coffee with him. Once, when someone asked
him how I had come by my seat at his table, he said it was because
I used to sit at the bar and make goo goo eyes at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' Gene asks Amos as he dumps the third creamer into his
cup and makes a face at the results, ``you taking that toe to the
doctor to get it hacked on?'' Gene's new here. Not a real farmer.
Moved onto 10 acres about a year ago, has one row of tomato plants,
and no idea of the leading question he's just asked.
</P>
<P>
   Amos wags his head. ``What do you take me for,'' he asks, ``some
kind of a sissy?'' Running off to the doctor, he reminds Gene, is a
city thing. ``Us country boys are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Three John Deere ballcaps nod agreement. Benny's wearing his
ten-galinvincibility are getting taller and I'm half-believing them
when the door opens and the two-man crew from the local EMS comes
in for breakfast. One stops and throws an arm over Amos's shoulder
and tells him how great he's looking. ``You know,'' he says to his
partner after a look around our table, ``I transported three of
these guys when they had their heart attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos, Benny, and Herb break into big grins _ some tough guys.
Cal turns to Gene and says the two of them must be the only ones
without a zipper in their chests, but Gene says nope, he's got one
too.
</P>
<P>
   Once mortality has been dealt with, however briefly, it's back
to business as usual. Benny has a cure for Amos's foot. He says
it's the same thing they do for horses. ``Fill a burlap bag
half-full of cow manure, stick your foot in it and tie it onto your
leg for three or four days. That'll sure cure what ails you.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos mutters something about having to live in the barn. Gene
asks Benny if he uses the same cure for a sore throat. He says not,
but he does have a cure for baldness _ chicken manure in your
shoes. The longer you wear it the more hair you'll grow.
</P>
<P>
   Gene doesn't know it _ and I won't tell _ but under that
outsized cowboy hat Benny's wearing, he hasn't got two hairs to rub
together. ``Ever practiced what you preach?'' I ask. He grins,
winks, and gives me the goo goo eyes right back.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
