<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4584 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CARTECH0808-COX     08-07 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CARTECH0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drivin' movies
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The 1990s were about the embracing of electronic
devices, ranging from computers to home theater, including movies,
music and video games.
</P>
<P>
   Now many of us are taking the next step: We won't leave home
without them.
</P>
<P>
   This very summer cars, SUVs and minivans are rolling with
dashboard-mounted TVs, five-speaker DVD systems, PlayStation and
Sega equipment for video games, onboard computers for global
communication, and even plain old VCRs gussied up to play tape from
camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big reasons for installing these systems is to
occupy kids during long vacation trips,'' said Justin Burns, a
mobile electronics specialist at HiFi Buys.
</P>
<P>
   Others, industry people say, are buying the fancy systems
because they enhance the feeling of luxury in prized sport-utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic entertainment systems can cost from $500 for a
basic console with video to as much as $16,000 to $20,000 _ largely
depending on the number of TV sets installed.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Haynie, a 16-year-old, may have the fanciest 1998 GMC
Jimmy in metro Atlanta, complete with a $7,000 personal computer
system installed by a team of specialists at HiFi Buys. Justin, who
just became old enough to drive, has his system featured in car
audio trade magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin and many others put these vehicles in competitions all
over the area,'' said Dennis Head, a mobile electronics specialist
who helped install the system. In other words, drag racing and
ear-splitting boombox rallies have given way to dueling
entertainment centers on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Though it has reached new heights, the trend is not brand new.
Ever since Oldsmobile introduced a videocassette player for its
minivans in 1998, car stereo enthusiasts have been one-upping one
another with dazzling audio systems, and now video.
</P>
<P>
   The industry, always on the lookout for new ways to hook
motorists, has jumped onto the bandwagon, and now every major
manufacturer is offering some form of video in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent element of the new systems is the 7-inch LCD
video screens that cost $1,100 each. Some vehicles feature as many
as five of them. For example, a system could consist of one on the
dashboard, one or more overhead and others in floor-mounted
consoles, particularly in big vehicles like Chevy Suburbans.
</P>
<P>
   The video systems typically include an electronic lockout to
discourage drivers from watching movies at the dashboard level,
even though expressway jams could hold you motionless long enough
to watch an episode of ``The Young and the Restless.''
</P>
<P>
   The systems do allow the motorist to watch on-screen readouts
from the global positioning service that guides the car to
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   While many new vehicles can come equipped with many features,
others prefer customized systems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the glories of the new fad is that on long trips family
members can each do their own thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of families bring the minivans in,'' says Jason Krimm,
owner of Stereo-in-Dash in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll hook up a VCR or DVD player and a few screens with
headphones, and you don't have to hear Barney singing. All the
noise will stay in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters take to the in-car video like ducks to water.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids come in, they make a beeline for our mock-up vehicle
that displays the video systems,'' said Shawn Simpson, a mobile
electronics specialist for HiFi Buys.
</P>
<P>
   And he might have added that when the kids come home from a
trip, enhanced by the entertainment on wheels, many of them won't
get out of the car. Some prefer to play their games in the van or
SUV than in their rooms in the house.
</P>
<P>
   So much fun, so much excitement _ but it comes at price.
</P>
<P>
   Most systems require some type of controlling head unit for the
dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   Add a few screens and a six-disc DVD/CD changer, and you'll be
looking at about $5,000 for a Pioneer system, typical of many.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic has a similar setup. Head unit for $2,000, DVD player
($1,200), 7-inch LCD screen ($1,100) and a Dolby processor for
surround sound ($800), all coming to about $5,100.
</P>
<P>
   While much of this is for fun, there are also elements that help
the work-minded motorist.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Clarion AutoPC, which runs on Microsoft Windows CE
software. The information superhighway can be accessed while on the
interstate with the mobile mini-computer's wireless connection _
with e-mail, stock quotes and faxed information just clicks away.
</P>
<P>
   Want to pass the time with trendy MP3 music files? Software is
on the way for the AutoPC to play your favorite downloads straight
from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other features of this computer on wheels described at the Web
site www.autopc.com/ can include a $1,300 voice-activated
navigation system and an onboard system to monitor gas consumption
and mileage, tip off impending engine problems and more.
</P>
<P>
   Though sales are sluggish at the moment, promoters of the
computer on wheels say potentially the motorist could have a full
office on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   But bombarding a driver with so many distractions does have its
critics. Highway patrolmen don't like them at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``These video systems pose the same threat as using a cellular
phone does,'' says Sgt. Eric Widmyer of the Ohio Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to include one of these systems, be sure that
all display devices are out of the driver's view. There's too much
happening on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   HOTTEST ADD-ONS
</P>
<P>
   Among the top selling add-on electronic items for cars and vans:
</P>
<P>
   1. Supplementary speakers, mostly bass subwoofers. Typical
12-inch woofer is $199.
</P>
<P>
   2. Radio upgrade, typical to high-quality radio/CD players such
as Alpine for $300 and up.
</P>
<P>
   3. Global positioning service such as the Alpine, at $1,499 to
cover the Southeast or $1,999 for the nation plus much of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   4. Radio-TV consoles for vans and sport-utilities, about $500.
</P>
<P>
   5. Seven-inch LCD video screens, about $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
