<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-HOMEGEAR0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will it butter the bread, too?
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A toaster that costs almost $400 had better come
with arms and legs and be willing to do the windows, too! That will
inevitably be your initial thought about this appliance. And the
fact that the Queen of England owned the very same trinket will do
little to sway your conviction that a $400 toaster is ludicrous at
best.
</P>
<P>
   But then Williams-Sonoma Inc. takes its beautiful, gleaming
Dualit Combi Toaster ($379; www.williams-sonoma.com) and reminds
you of your old $15 appliance and the frustration of having to
shove your bagel halves into the slots, then extract their charred,
crumbled remains with a pair of tongs. The Dualit's slots are wide,
allowing you to easily toast bread, bagels or English muffins.
There's even a separate slot for toasting whole sandwiches and a
slide-out tray that catches all the crumbs. With a slot rocker
switch, timer and manual ejector knob, this toaster will require
more attention than others. Without going so far as to say it's
worth its price, let's just say that once you have the pleasure of
using the Dualit, all the other toasters are bound to be . . . well
. . . toast.
</P>
<P>
   NEW IMAC EDITION IS TRULY SPECIAL
</P>
<P>
   Bearing in mind that Apple veritably coined the phrase ``user
friendly,'' it follows that the iMac DV Special Edition (SE)
($1,500; www.apple.com) offers everyperson home computing at its
finest. Bundled with an easy yet detailed tutorial and a formidable
suite of basic computing tools (Internet browser, e-mail, desktop
publishing, graphics editing), the iMac DV SE's crowning feature is
its DVD-ROM drive and the immensely popular iMovie software, a
video editing/moviemaking application for the home movie
enthusiast. Complete with trademark ``FireWire,'' digital video
transfer hardware normally sold separately (and at notable cost)
for Windows-based PCs, the SE is a forward-thinking computer in
that it does not accommodate analog video, the more familiar
camcorder format fast on its way to becoming obsolete. iMacs are
inherently less expandable than PCs, though more adaptable in these
later incarnations. Yet with specific users and hobbyists tackling
specific home computer tasks, the iMac DV SE is just what a great
many new-to-the-modern-era folks are looking for: scaled down,
professional-caliber computing that brings the ``friendliness''
back to user-friendly personal computers. Available in snow and
graphite colors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
