<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's a Pikachu in my PC!
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Learning, fun? _ hmmm . . . sounds dubious. But
Mattel Interactive's new Pokemon PokeROMs ($8;
www.pokemon.com/goods/pokeroms.html; for Mac and Windows) deliver
on this claim to a good degree as Pokemon icon Professor Oak leads
kids in activities that promote math and grammar skills. Each
session begins with a ``Concentration''-type puzzle, where math
equations and answers must be matched, each correct union revealing
part of a Pokemon. When the entire image is visible, it can be
saved or printed. The computerized board game finds up to four
players answering grammar questions to move across a virtual game
board. Difficulty can be tailored to children from grades 1 to 5,
but there are too few questions in each level and they quickly
become repetitive. The Pokemon observatory, where you search a map
for Pokemon and click hot spots to reveal them, is lackluster. Each
click seems to reveal a different shot of your Pokemon but, in
reality, only triggers a slide show that will reveal all of the
pictures if you don't click away fast enough. In spite of these
negatives, PokeROMs, available on small, mini CD-ROMs, offer a
non-violent, educational computer experience that children will
enjoy . . . for a while. Here's hoping Mattel adds new questions to
the Series 2 and 3 PokeROMs (due later this year).
</P>
<P>
   A SWING AND A HIT Hey, batter batter . . . Humongous
Entertainment has updated its Junior Sports collection with
Backyard Baseball 2001 ($20; store.humongous.com; for Mac and
Windows), an update of their best sports title, Backyard Baseball.
So what's different? Well, kids still can choose their own teams
(and team names) but in addition to the original cast of
characters, players also can choose from 31 kid versions of their
favorite big-leaguers such as Sammy Sosa and Randy Johnson
(hands-down the game's best pitcher). Also new in this version is
the option to build your own player from scratch, choosing his or
her batting, fielding, throwing and running skills. Special wacky
abilities are rewarded for outstanding play. A pitcher, for
instance, might get to throw fireballs, which actually burn on
their way to the plate. Batters might get to smack
``undergrounders'' (hits that travel under the playing field and
pop up at random spots). This game features Humongous' trademark
beautiful animation, silly humor and great play. All in all, it's
another home run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
