   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-STADIUM-ONLINE (San Francisco) _ The seventh-inning stretch
is coming up at Pac Bell Park and you realize it's been more than
two hours since you last logged in. Like a left-hander coming in
from the bullpen, relief is here. Starting Friday, Giants fans will
have limited access to the Internet at one of five ``Web Stations''
at the park, making it the first major league baseball stadium in
the nation to provide such a service. By VICTORA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ORIOLES-TRADES (Undated) _ The Baltimore Orioles' influence,
thanks to their 72-hour fire sale, will be felt throughout the
pennant races. They made the Atlanta Braves better by handing over
outfielder B.J. Surhoff. They strengthened the New York Mets by
donating shortstop Mike Bordick. They beefed up the St. Louis
Cardinals by contributing first baseman Will Clark and closer Mike
Timlin. They reinforced the Chicago White Sox by furnishing catcher
Charles Johnson and designated hitter Harold Baines. By JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-STANFORD (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ It's time for Stanford to
start playing football again, which can only mean one thing: Rose
Bowl. Hey, why not? The Cardinal did it last year against all odds,
in spite of having one of the nation's worst defenses
(statistically speaking, at least), and in spite of losing their
season-opening game by 52 points. So why not this year? By MARK
FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-PROPS (Undated) - Want to own a piece of your favorite
show or movie? Thanks to an explosion in online auctions, now you
can. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-ELEKTRA (SANTE FE, N.M.) - Last of five reviews of the
Santa Fe Opera season. New production of Richard Strauss'
``Elektra,'' the last one to be conducted by founder John Crosby.
By CHARLES WARD. (Pictures available from
http://www.santafeopera.org/PressPhotos/PressPhotos.htm)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The Dubya jokes are over. George
W. Bush is well on his way to becoming president, on the basis of
reading one 52-minute speech _ probably the most reading he's ever
done at one time in his life. There we go again, making fun of
Bush. Liberals can make fun of Bush's vast accomplishments in the
highly competitive field of ignorance, but it won't hurt him. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
