<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4596 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-FAMILY-COLUMN080     08-07 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAMILY-COLUMN0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walkie-talkies convenient during outings with kids
 &HT;    By Anne Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amusement park entrances spray visitors out in every
direction inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   From the front gates to the farthest ride, park-goers flow
outward like constantly moving spokes of a Ferris wheel.
</P>
<P>
   As each pair of eyes sets sights on a favorite ride or the next
amusement, the pair beside them sees an entirely different view.
All the while, the Ferris wheel keeps spinning.
</P>
<P>
   Park visits pack what could be days of entertainment into hours
of compressed fun. Amusement park strategists recommend splitting
large groups into smaller teams, giving everyone a stab at
achieving their goals.
</P>
<P>
   The chaotic atmosphere injects added energy into children and
makes a family trip more of a challenge. All this considered, there
is fun within those gated parks, and most people seem to find it.
</P>
<P>
   I recently traveled to Cedar Point, a place that calls itself
America's Roller Coast. The Sandusky, Ohio, location is a 364-acre
amusement/theme park and resort consisting of a confusing maze of
walkways hugged on all sides by rides and money-vacuuming
indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 70 rides, including 14 roller coasters. This
year's big attraction is the Millennium Force, a 310-foot-tall
world-record-breaking roller coaster with a peak speed of more than
90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium Force was high on the wish list of two in my van
load. Our group of five consisted of my 16-year-old niece and
12-year-old nephew, along with my two kids whose ages total 12. We
knew the disparity in age, size and taste would force us to
separate during the day.
</P>
<P>
   If the older kids were going to enjoy the day, we needed to get
them out of the ``Kiddy Kingdom'' and onto rides like Millennium
Force.
</P>
<P>
   A large tree close to the entrance was voted our meeting spot if
we lost track of each other. We set out together to get the lay of
the land, surrounded by people with walkie-talkies. Some also used
cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   People standing alone were having conversations using hand-held
devices. Brightly colored electronic companions kept them company
in lines, on rides and as they walked.
</P>
<P>
   We enjoyed several rides early in the day. My niece and nephew
separated from us to enjoy some long-lined rides for the
long-legged.
</P>
<P>
   While they sped through the skies aboard coasters, we stayed
closer to the ground on rides that accommodate the ``under 48''
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Each time we set a time and exact place to meet. By late in the
afternoon I was feeling a little cocky about our organizational
skills.
</P>
<P>
   I watched from the viewing area with my youngest child as the
other three soaked themselves on a water ride. We met them at the
exit and then separated quickly.
</P>
<P>
   This time my ``meet me here'' message did not come across
clearly. We lost track of each other, and I was not looking forward
to the walk back to the emergency meeting spot _ the tree at the
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   I turned on the cell phone in my pocket, although the kids did
not know the number. I took one last walk around. My nephew's
worried look was a welcome sight, and he took me to our other two
wet-and-weary travelers just as the cell phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   My niece had called my parents (collect from a pay phone), told
my mother they were lost, and asked my mother to track me the cell
phone number. It was not a bad plan, but the future plan is to buy
a set of walkie-talkies.
</P>
<P>
   These are useful tools for family trips to the mall, Disney
World or Stone Mountain Park. The casual walkie-talkies do not
require a license, unlike ham radios. There are no airtime charges
as with cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular of these fun two-way radios at Cedar Point was
the Motorola Talkabout. There are a few variations on the
palm-sized device.
</P>
<P>
   The Talkabouts are described in detail (and also available for
purchase) on the Motorola Web site (www.motorola.com). The popular
T289 radio features 14 channels, using 38 privacy codes. The T289
has a range up to two miles with fairly clear transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Kenwood (www.kenwood.net), Sony (www.sony.com), Audiovox
(www.audiovox.com), Radio Shack (www.radioshack
</P>
<P>
   .com) and Cobra (www.cobraelec.com) all make models. The radios
cost from $35 to $200 each.
</P>
<P>
   The more expensive they are, the more elaborate the features.
Some include hands-free operation, built-in weather radios and
scramble modes (for greater privacy).
</P>
<P>
   With the popularity of the devices growing and the airwaves
becoming more crowded, the most important feature is the ability to
break the channels into sub-settings. The 38 ``squelch settings''
on each channel (like the T289 features) help prevent overlap.
</P>
<P>
   The walkie-talkies operate using the Family Radio Service, the
UHF FM frequency created by the Federal Communications Commission
in 1996 for casual recreational use. The devices allow easy
communication for up to two miles but are open to interception. The
airwaves are public, and no conversation is guaranteed to be
private.
</P>
<P>
   These are certainly not the walkie-talkies of my youth. These
look like a lot more fun and might enhance the enjoyment of next
year's amusement park spin.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the review (``You're Never Too Old for 2-Way Radios'')
from AnchorDesk (May 4) at
www.zdnet.com/products/stories/reviews/0,4161,2561308,00.html.
</P>
<P>
   You can find two-way radios at many electronics retailers. You
may also want to try a shopping bot like MySimon (www.mysimon.com)
or Excite's bot (shopping.excite.com). Shopping bots, or robots,
are comparison services that give you a choice of price and
retailers with a quick Web click.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
