<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest Windows clearly a winner
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next version of Windows is supposed to be on the
store shelves in September, and this time it appears to be
something to get at least mildly excited about.
</P>
<P>
   Windows Millennium, which Microsoft has familiarly but
unfortunately nicknamed Windows Me, arrived through the transom
last week in its beta version.
</P>
<P>
   It installed flawlessly over Windows 98, and upon a cursory
examination, it obviously marks a new way of thinking within
Microsoft. The operating system is going the way of the desktop
computer makers _ dividing into two distinct camps, one for
business and one for home.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000, of course, is the all-business operating system.
Windows Millennium is the home system. Which is not to say that it
won't serve the same set of users that 95 and 98 did; certainly it
will.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly all the new stuff here is aimed at the home and
family. The thrust is toward a more stable system that requires
less expertise to maintain and fix, an integrated way of finding
help, and vastly improved digital media services.
</P>
<P>
   While the Media Player and Movie Maker are the sexy items, the
PC Health provisions are likely to be more important to more users
in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Microsoft says it has protected some 900 system
files against ``unauthorized'' rewriting or overwriting. Exactly
what constitutes ``unauthorized'' remains to be seen, but it should
be a big step in guarding against the willy-nilly damaging of these
files by someone who doesn't know what he or she is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Even better is the System Restore feature. This is the same
thing, basically, that utilities like Norton have offered for
years, with one major improvement _ it's automatic. Every day, and
every time a new program is installed, Restore makes a ``snapshot''
of the system and stores it away. If something goes haywire, you
can call up System Restore and revert to any one of aome of the
stand-alones but good enough to satisfy most folks for quite a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Audio processing has been fancied up with the addition of new
internal processors.
</P>
<P>
   I've been running the beta version for only a few days now, but
I've had little trouble with it. There seem to be some issued
involving Windows Explorer, which tends to get flaky now and then,
but those will surely be settled by September.
</P>
<P>
   I'm having another problem with a couple of programs, but I
suspect the trouble was there before I installed Windows Me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
