r l BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0808     08-07 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spelling returns to save us from reality TV
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Rat-eating reality shows and meaty dramas are
up, thigh-slapping sitcoms are down.
</P>
<P>
   Missing entirely from the prime-time landscape, however, is the
juicy genre of the 1980s _ the adult sudser. Rich, drunk, immoral
folks like the Ewings of ``Dallas'' and the Carringtons of
``Dynasty'' were an endangered species in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Now Aaron Spelling, the granddaddy of glamorous melodrama, is
bringing back the Over-the-Top Players. If you yearn for mansions
stocked to the rafters with dysfunctional, immaculately groomed sex
maniacs, stay tuned for ``Titans,'' an NBC glossy coming in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences love to see rich people have problems, and they love
to laugh at rich people's problems,'' Spelling said in Los Angeles
recently. ``And this show has something special: We've got a sense
of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so ``Dynasty'' wasn't campy? Apparently the 72-year-old
Spelling failed to catch the camp that made Alexis the most-loved
villain since J.R. Ewing. Were we really supposed to take seriously
those claw-exposed cat fights between Alexis and Krystle? It seems
impossible to believe, but Spelling insists his previous prime-time
soaps, including ``Melrose Place'' and ``Beverly Hills, 90210,''
weren't supposed to be funny. That's really scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titans,'' on the other hand, is an intentional romp from the
get-go. Chiseled hunk Chandler Williams (Casper Van Dien) comes
home to Beverly Hills from the Navy to find his tumultuous and
fabulously rich family a mess. His parents are divorced but live
across the street from each other in dueling mansions.
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Richard (Perry King) is about to marry Heather
(Yasmine Bleeth), a luscious, scheming young woman who recently had
a fling with Chandler _ unbeknownst to poor, dim-witted Dad. (The
wiggle walk in the wedding dress is a comedy highlight of the
upcoming season.) Chandler still has a thing for her; Dad's sexy
assistant has a thing for Chandler. The other Williams son is
ambitious and alcohol-obsessed, a nasty combination.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the street is the serenely calm mother,
Gwen (Victoria Principal), whose two daughters are a handful. The
three women run an upscale nightclub, which turns out to be a
terrible temptation for the daughter who is an alcoholic. Heavy
drinking runs in the family.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot ends with a bomb of a plot twist. Some critics laughed
so loud they worried about hurting Spelling's feelings as he sat in
the darkened room. It's always uncomfortable when a producer sits
in on a screening, and this one was no exception. In fact, it was
excruciating knowing this soft-spoken legend, the most prolific
producer in the history of television (starting with ``Zane Gray
Theater'' and continuing through ``Charlie's Angels'' and ``The Mod
Squad''), saw us howling like hunting dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' Spelling insisted sweetly when the lights came on.
``We want you to laugh at that last line! We're dead if you
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps less intentionally funny, however, are the beautiful-bod
poses struck in every scene by the well-endowed Bleeth and the
abs-of-steel Van Dien. She delivers every line through pouty lips
with eyelids drooping; he can barely spit his words out because
he's so intent on flexing his jaws. These folks are a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   For those who see the ``Survivor''-inspired reality trend as
poison, ``Titans'' may be the perfect antidote. It's a live-action
cartoon. Absolutely nothing about it is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do a reality show, I guess I'd do it in a house of
prostitution,'' Spelling quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas'' and ``Dynasty'' were blockbuster hits during the
Reagan era, when rich and famous were positive traits _ right up
there with family values. Spelling is counting on the dawn of the
new decade to cast a similar glow on the viewing populace. The
hectic, high-tech world we live in, he hopes, has created a
receptive mood for this glitzy escapist entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   There's more than a grain of truth in Spelling's theory that we
love to laugh at the overwrought woes of rich people. Maybe we're
jealous of the dot.com billionaires and the lottery-winning
multimillionaires, and we need to poke fun at them. We can't have
net worths as big as a European country, but at least we're not
having affairs with our parents' new spouses.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Spelling's intentional camp will
be as tasty to the masses as the allegedly unintentional camp of
yesteryear. It's going to be hard to top Alexis guzzling champagne
for breakfast, or J.R. cheating his own mother out of an oil well.
Those were heady times for prime-time soaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titans'' is a fast-paced romp on satin sheets. It could be
just the ticket for people tired of gritty cop shows and
peeping-tom reality. And it just might launch a new trend of
fantastic camp. A sly old fox like Spelling just might know what
he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
