<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-MIDDLE-SCHOOL0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUCK IN THE MIDDLE: Seventh-graders offer sage advice to
students starting middle school
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The leap from elementary to middle school can be
pretty scary.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth grade plunges you into a world of lockers, changing
classes and new faces. You're caught somewhere between being a
child and being an adult.
</P>
<P>
   To help those of you beginning middle school this month, News
for Kids consulted some experts: last year's sixth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   We got lots of good advice from those at Carl G. Renfroe Middle
School in Decatur, Ga., where some sixth-grade language arts
students wrote a survival guide for students following them. Plus,
other NFK readers volunteered their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Most listed these as challenges: making new friends while
keeping old ones, dealing with popularity and adjusting to a larger
school and more work.
</P>
<P>
   Below you'll learn how they dealt with those issues.
</P>
<P>
   F R I E N D S
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could redo one thing from sixth grade, I would have
participated more in school activities. I would have signed up for
after-school clubs or gone out and supported the football or track
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, I came home every afternoon and checked my e-mail and
went online. It made my mother and my friends mad at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had spent more time with them because that would have
made sixth grade easier.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Margaret Carter, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I hadn't gotten involved in disputes between other
people. I try now to only get involved if there is a way I can
help. If not, then I stay out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Joanna Harbin, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   POPULARITY
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about being popular. When I began sixth grade, I
was nervous and shaky.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is really nothing to be afraid of.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Norman Reese, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see the `popular' kids wear name-brand clothes, don't
feel you have to wear those same clothes to be liked. Just be
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gaia Friend-Jones
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that if my friends didn't like someone, I shouldn't
like them either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very rude thing to do, because once I met them, I
realized they were very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Madeline Moore, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   CLASSES
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard work in academics begins in sixth grade. But if you
work hard and try your best, you'll probably get good grades.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Vogel, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``At my school, the teachers sometimes surprise you and collect
homework for a grade. ... Do your homework carefully and check over
your answers. Doing this will save you a lot of bad grades, trust
me!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Julia Sevy, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to change something about last year, I would not have
mumbled back to the teacher. I would try my best on my tests, and I
wouldn't write in pen in math class.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ja'Darrin Bell
</P>
<P>
   ``You ALWAYS have to be organized. If that means taking 10
minutes each night just to straighten up papers, do it!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lauren Koester, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``To keep yourself organized, keep all of your stuff in a
binder, label your stuff with your name and make sure you don't
leave anything in any of your classes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kate Stucke,seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have tried harder in all my classes. My advice now is
pay attention more. Don't talk so much. Last, but not least, try,
try and try again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Brittany Baugher
</P>
<P>
   ``Write the homework down on your hand every day. Buy a little
notebook and write it down there. Do both things so you can be
absolutely sure not to forget what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Natalie Bundschu, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't get your locker open, get a teacher or friend to
help you. Keep your lunch and library account numbers in your
pocket. Don't tell everybody your locker combination.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kirk Riley, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid to ask questions if you don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Marquecia Stanley, seventh grade
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
