<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush accepts GOP nomination
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ George W. Bush officially became the Republican
Party's presidential nominee last week at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech, the Texas governor said he would take
advantage of good economic times to work toward ``great goals'' if
elected president in November. Bush said he wants to improve
education, cut taxes and close the divide between the rich and
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, who are
Democrats, wasted their chance to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the Democrats will meet to nominate Gore as their
presidential candidate. Gore is expected to announce his vice
presidential choice on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `QUEEN MUM' TURNS 100
</P>
<P>
   The mother of Britain's Queen Elizabeth II celebrated her 100th
birthday Friday. The queen mother waved to the thousands who lined
London streets and packed the square outside Buckingham Palace.
</P>
<P>
   She appeared before the crowd on the palace balcony before
heading inside for a family celebration.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, she won the hearts of Britons when she and
her husband, King George VI, refused to leave for safety while the
Germans bombed London.
</P>
<P>
   HARRY POTTER ITEMS COMING
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Harry Potter may be seeing the boy wizard everywhere
this fall. Shops in the United States are hoping to get Potter
sheets, toys, furniture and even underwear on the shelves in time
for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, readers who wanted to talk to Harry or join in his
wizard games had to use their imaginations. Very little merchandise
was available. With the success of the new ``Goblet of Fire'' book
and the coming of a Potter movie next year, manufacturers are
starting to crank out all things Harry.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Will kids jump on the Potter product craze or
just want the next book?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
