<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-GAMER0808-COX     08-07 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0808-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennis for all levels of playersc. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   The glory and majesty that is Sega's new sports sim, Virtua
Tennis ($40; www.sega.com; for the Dreamcast) is such that it could
elicit volumes on how fun the game is to play. But writing tomes
would mean less time to actually play this full-bodied, spectacular
game. Sega's latest stellar sports title is a graphics phenom that
is easy for beginners (controls consist of a minimum of buttons),
but challenging and rewarding for more advanced gamers. With a good
variety of courts, players and bonus games (including several
training courses reminiscent of the ``Crazy Box'' challenges in
Crazy Taxi), Virtua Tennis delivers the goods. If there's one
quibble, it's that there aren't any women players and some of more
famous players on the tennis circuit are missing. But if you can do
without the Williams sisters and Pete Sampras, this is as good as
tennis games get.
</P>
<P>
   N Gen Racing ($40; www.us.infogrames.com; for PlayStation)
brings aspects of Sony's Gran Turismo ultimate car racing game to
the sky. The object of N Gen is to win the race by A.) flying
faster than everyone else, that seems obvious, B.) picking up more
afterburners and blowing past the competition and C.) shooting down
the competition. There is nothing like a friendly race that turns
to machine guns and rockets to determine who's the best. To
progress to higher levels of competition in the game you must earn
licenses to fly higher performance aircraft. The quality of N Gen's
graphics are middle-of-the-road and the realism is . . . well, it's
not realism, but that is what keeps the game fun. You can bounce
off mountains, bridges and water and still have enough strength
left to shoot down your competition. The lower you fly, the faster
the aircraft can go, so contact with inanimate objects is
inevitable. The coolest thing the game also allows you to do is
modify your aircraft _ you can add canards, change engines and
modify the airframes to produce a plane that can handle and kick
serious tail-section. N Gen has two settings for flight-control:
Arcade and Pro. In the arcade-mode the aircraft handles simply, it
banks left and right and up and down. In Pro mode, pull out your
joy stick and hang on. The aircraft can now do anything that your
reflexes can handle; corkscrews, barrel rolls, upside down flying.
N Gen is nothing revolutionary, but it is a fun game if you like
racing, flying and the sense of speed.
</P>
<P>
   Who Wants To Be a Millionaire 2nd Edition ($40;
www.playstation.com; for the PlayStation) tries to emulate the
essence of Philbin's game show phenomenon by adding a dramatic
pregnant pause every time you select your multiple choice answer.
This is aggravating in a PlayStation game where we suffer enough
loading delays as it is. Ironically, that's the best this game has
to offer. It's trivia with Regis Philbin doing some voice work _
and most of that is just sampled from the actual show. - other than
that, tThere's almost nothing here remotely resembling a video
game: The graphic interface is sparse and cheap (you stare,
alternately, at two empty chairs, or text, or an empty set mock
up). And the capper: Questions must be answered within an allotted
time limit; unlike the show, contestants are not allowed to
reminisce about the 7th grade school teacher who taught extensively
on the subject; no hemming and hawing, no repartee with the host.
The nerve! Give me a time limit and then preprogram a pregnant
pause before telling me if my rushed answer is right or wrong?
Lame. Who thinks it's possible to be a millionaire by starting out
$40 in the hole and that much further away from being a millionaire
with nothing to show for it except for ``branded consumer who
doesn't deserve to be a millionaire'' emblazoned on their forehead?
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing quite as comforting as being on the right side
of a gun, especially when that gun happens to be an anti-tank
cannon. That's basically the premise and the entire essence of
gameplay in Wizardworks' BeachHead 2000 ($20; www.wizardworks.com;
for the PC), a lone bunkerman trying to thwart a full-on naval
assault in a WWII mock-up. A brazen game that pretty much could
have called itself ``Shooting Private Ryan,'' there's not much
depth or strategy involved here _ no cutting edge graphics, just
glorious explosions, huge kabooms and mindless, shameful catharsis
through random acts of genocide. Sickening, really, but wickedly
brainless and guilty-secret fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
