<HEADER>
A4611 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECHNOBUDDY0808-COX     08-07 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buying a good used PC might not be a bad idea
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I bought a used car last week. I can remember years
ago when it was routine to buy a brand new car every two or three
years. It was part of the American tradition just as much as
hand-cranked ice cream and Sunday afternoons spent on the front
porch.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have a front porch anymore, most of my friends would run
in panic at the thought of cranking an ice cream freezer on a 90
degree day, and I no longer buy new cars. I'm not alone.
Reconditioned used cars are becoming more and more popular as new
car prices cross the border between foolish and insane.
</P>
<P>
   The same market shift is coming to the PC world. Buying a new
machine will no longer be the automatic first choice.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's already happening. There have been some really
important changes lately _ including a slowdown in the growth of
the new PC market.
</P>
<P>
   But, more important than that, hardware has finally outdistanced
software. In the past, you almost had to buy a new and more
powerful computer every couple of years just to run the new
software. Computer programs once grew in complexity so fast that
you needed a super PC just to run ordinary programs such as word
processors and Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, even a 350 megahertz Pentium machine can handle almost
everything (games excluded) that a home user might want to tackle.
And a 500 megahertz machine is just about right. Given that, a used
computer is a real bargain. Besides, buying a used computer makes
even more sense than buying a used car.
</P>
<P>
   With a car, there are many parts that literally wear out.
Cylinders lose compression, normal wear and tear slowly destroys
transmissions and differentials, and even the interior of a car
slowly deteriorates. But in a computer _ other than the disk
drives, power supply, cooling fan and switches _ all the parts are
solid state electronics and, with ordinary care, these parts can
and should last for decades.
</P>
<P>
   For most novices, it's probably smart to buy from one of the
retailers that specialize in used computers. That way you will get
a warranty and also the assurance that someone has looked the
machine over to make sure that it's in good working order. (If you
know a lot about computers you will feel easy negotiating with an
individual and you'll probably get a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   But my assumption is that if you know a lot about computers, you
don't need my help in picking out a used machine).
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I would recommend for novices at the used computer
store.
</P>
<P>
   1. Find a place that has been in business for at least a year or
so. The marketplace _ long-term _ tends to filter out incompetents
and crooks.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pay close attention to the store's return and warranty
policy. And remember that _ as a practical (not legal) matter _
that only a written return and warranty policy has any value to
you. So make sure, if you buy a machine, that you leave with a
written statement not just a spoken promise.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stick to brand-name machines when you buy used. Some
off-brands are every bit as good as the name brands. But, when
buying used, it just makes sense to get the extra security of a
brand name. Besides, if you need service or advice, you are more
likely to be able to find someone who is familar with the quirks of
a well-known brand.
</P>
<P>
   4. Before you walk into the store make sure that you know the
selling price for equivalent new machines. That's the only way that
you'll be able to judge whether the price for the used machine is
fair. If, for instance, you can only save $100 or so by buying a
used PC, you're much better off with the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   5. While you may well get excellent advice at the store, it's a
good idea to get some independent help on what type of machine you
need before going in. Otherwise, you'll be in danger from a
fast-talking salesman who may try to convince you that a
too-powerful, or not-powerful-enough machine is right for you.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, look for a good used machine with a Pentium
500 megazhertz chip or better at the used computer store at a
substantial savings over what you'd pay for a new brand-name
machine.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in the market for a PC, I think it'll be worth your
time to take a look at the used machines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
