r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0808-COX     08-07 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: If it is not too expensive, I would like to
get my son a replica of the Maltese Falcon, like in the movie. I
have no idea where to start looking, so you came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pam Latham
</P>
<P>
   A: How about $50? The folks at Captain Bijou,
www.captainbijou.com or (256) 837-0049, sell these actual-size
plaster, jet-black-enamel-painted replicas of the famous Bogie
prop.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it really hotter than it used to be? My husband recently
attended his 45th high school reunion in San Antonio, and we all
commented on how much hotter it seems now than it was then. Is that
possible? Or were we just younger, unaware of air conditioning, or
what?
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Keith
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, in the last 10 years, the Earth has warmed approximately
1.2 degrees, reports the National Weather Service. Stir in global
warming, increased urbanization and the human adaptation to air
conditioning and I agree, it is hotter than it used to be. Q:
Please tell me where I can purchase aluminum straws. I bought a few
of them years ago. They are very attractive, handy and dishwasher
safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ N. Roberts
</P>
<P>
   A: Restoration Hardware sells aluminum tea straws with a
spoon-shaped bottom ($2.50 each or six for $15). Prefer to stay in
the house? Order at www.restorationhardware.com or by phone at
(800) 762-1005.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in writing to Queen Elizabeth II. Could you
provide an address? Also, how do you properly phrase a greeting to
her?
</P>
<P>
   _ Donna B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Those who are not personally known to the queen write to her
through channels. Address the envelope to The Right Honorable Sir
Robin Janvrin, Private Secretary to Her Majesty the Queen,
Buckingham Palace, London SW1A 1AA, England. The letter's
salutation should read ``Dear sir:'' referring to the secretary. Do
not even consider using Her Majesty or the Queen's nickname,
Lilibet. Looking for common ground? Her Majesty was an auto
mechanic and an ambulance driver in World War II, loves horses and
corgis, and has a noted disdain for helicopters, coffee and tennis.
Q: Someone gave me samples of Agnes B. Cosmetics, but I cannot find
them. Who sells Agnes B. Cosmetics?
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Moore
</P>
<P>
   A: The clothing designer's boutiques are all over the globe (New
York to Hong Kong). Order the cosmetics line from her catalog by
calling (800) 758-1337. And the B in Agnes B.? Bougeois, her
ex-husband's name.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend from Colorado recently asked me about the many goats
on ranches around Texas. What are they used for? Surely not just
milk?
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Keith A: Goats prosper in the climate of the Edwards
plateau, which is loaded with browse. New word? ``Browse'' is
shoots, twigs and leaves fit for animal consumption. The Lone Star
State's goat count is about 1.3 million, according to the Texas
Department of Agriculture. That's a lot of goats. Approximately
370,000 of these Angora goats are raised for mohair. Texas produces
more than 90 percent of the nation's mohair. Other goat products?
Cabrito (barbecued goat) and, yes, goat milk. Q: In light of our
water shortage, I am willing to bail the bath water to put on
thirsty shrubs and grass. Does shampoo and soap in the water hurt
the plants? Does softened water damage plants?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.B.M. A: Using bath water and even washing machine water as
part of your watering plan will not harm your lawn and shrubs,
according to the master gardeners at the Travis County Extension
Service. Of course, using biodegradable soaps is always advisable.
And the softened water? No problem. Your plants will also be
watered occasionally with rain (crossed fingers) and sprinkler
water.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please help us settle what has become a major dispute about
which shaker _ the one with the smaller number of holes _ the salt
and pepper go in. We have different answers from everyone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Larry D.
</P>
<P>
   A: The controversy may rage on, but the Salt Institute reports
the shaker with more holes is the pepper shaker. Pepper comes in
various sizes, while salt grains are uniform. Older salt shakers
have larger holes than newer ones. The recent ``salt as medical
no-no'' movement caused manufacturers to shrink the holes somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, salt was served from an open dish called a salt
cellar. Because it was a precious commodity, these dishes were
ornate _ gold, silver or carved wood. Positioned in the middle of
the table, important guests were seated near the host, ``above the
salt.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the history behind the tradition of a woman taking
her husband's last name when she marries?
</P>
<P>
   _ P. Andrews
</P>
<P>
   A: First names were the standard until surnames, usually a
reference to a job (Weaver) or relationship (Johnson, son of John),
became necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The guru of genealogy, David Baskin at the State Archives,
reports the custom is a natural outgrowth of the old theory of
English law that a woman's personality, upon marriage, became
absorbed or merged in her husband's. ``By taking her husband's
surname the woman declared that she was joining his family, an act
tantamount to becoming his property,'' adds Baskin. Plus, it is
convenient to have one's name on property in case of ownership
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Many women in England and the United States choose to keep their
surname (often their father's) after marriage. Since 1921, the Lucy
Stone League, named for the 1850s feminist, encouraged women to
retain their maiden names after marriage. Visit
www.lucystoneleague.org for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a recent moonlight beach walk, my girlfriend and I noticed
that the seaweed that washes up on the shore glows when touched.
Not just a dim glow, but an electrical, sparkling effect. The park
ranger confirmed that it was not our imaginations, but stated that
it was not the seaweed, but something growing on the seaweed that
was glowing; however, he didn't know what it was.
</P>
<P>
   Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   _ T. J.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hard to tell without a sample, but Texas A&AMP;M's Bill Wardle,
associate professor of marine biology, suspects you were looking at
Cnidarians (ni-DAR-ee-uhnz). This group of animals, relatives of
corals and sea anemones, spark when agitated. Chemicals are mixed
in the animals' body and a byproduct is light. Like the firefly the
Cnidarian is bioluminescent. Your touch registered as a threat, and
this sparking is to scare predators. (Neat trick _ wish I could do
it!)
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com; or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
