<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4637 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-07 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     W STANDS FOR REGULAR GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Dubya jokes are over. George W. Bush is well
on his way to becoming president, on the basis of reading one
52-minute speech _ probably the most reading he's ever done at one
time in his life.
</P>
<P>
   There we go again, making fun of Bush. Liberals can make fun of
Bush's vast accomplishments in the highly competitive field of
ignorance, but it won't hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Bush once said he wasn't good at ``sitting down and
reading a 500-page book on public policy or philosophy or
something.'' Most Americans would rather have an unanesthetized
root canal than read something Gorey like that.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Bush gave Texans the right to carry concealed
handguns. When do the rest of us get ours?
</P>
<P>
   So what if Bush didn't know who Tony Blair is. Who wants to know
who Tony Blair is?
</P>
<P>
   This is America, the land where nothing can stand in the way of
a man who says his favorite movie of all time is ``Austin Powers:
The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   What's Al Gore's favorite movie? ``White Men Can't Jump''?
``China Syndrome''?
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, Gore's image consultants are showing him tapes
of Adam Sandler movies and asking him to pick a new favorite flick.
Bush has put Gore and his handlers in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore does what comes naturally _ act smart, talk down, go for
the jugular _ he will seem even less presidential than he does now.
</P>
<P>
   But if he tries to find a new earthiness to match his new earth
tones, it'll seem like just another image make-over.
</P>
<P>
   It'll sound fake if, like Bush, he starts running on having
overcome his past. It'll sound like another Gore fib if he says he
wasted a lot of time at Harvard tooling around with his roommate
Tommy Lee Jones in an old Cadillac convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the story is true.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's strategy for winning was right there, and he didn't
pick up on it.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't such a wonk, and he definitely wasn't by Harvard
standards. He was a regular guy who had a motorcycle and dated (and
later married) a drummer in an all-girl rock band. He roomed with a
Texan with a football scholarship who later became a famous movie
star with a mesquite accent and plenty of lines in his face, none
resembling a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore knows Texans, and George W. Bush, you were a Texan
cheerleader at Andover.
</P>
<P>
   Who's the truer regular guy, the one who's the son of a
president and didn't do any studying at Yale? Or is it the one
who's the son of a senator and did his senior thesis on the role of
television in American politics and didn't learn much from it?
</P>
<P>
   That would be a fair fight, one we'd want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Bush pulled way ahead of Gore in the regular guy
department by not knowing who was president of Chechnya, however
you pronounce it and wherever the hell it is.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, Democrats thought not knowing about Chechnya
would hurt a presidential candidate. As the scion of an
aristocratic political family, Bush knows that's why presidents get
good hired help.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made the mistake of talking about foreign policy, trade and
all those topics in books Bush won't read. Gore even wrote a book
Bush (or you and I) wouldn't read.
</P>
<P>
   Lately Gore has been bragging about the economy. Even those who
find Austin Powers movies too sophisticated know there's one Al who
counts when it comes to the economy, and it's Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats completely underestimated Republicans and George W.
Bush. They complained about all the people of color put on camera
at a Republican convention filled with people of pallor.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats didn't get it. The idea wasn't to attract blacks to
the Republican Party. The idea was to make undecided white people
feel less guilty about voting Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have stolen compassion and education from the
Democrats. They made abolishing inheritance taxes a populist issue.
Now they've even pulled ahead of the Democrats in the field of
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   This is as good as a campaign promise. Never again will I make
fun of Bush or any other Republican, except maybe myself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
