<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOAST TO GUINNESS, THE ULTIMATE SELFLESS STAR 
</HEADLINE>
 ALECGUINNESS KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   Alec Guinness was the difference
between a great actor and a mere movie star.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In more than 40 films the venerated British actor, who died
Saturday at age 86, portrayed a gallery of characters as diverse as
any in the history of cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Mystics and crooks, bureaucrats and aristocrats, household
servants and even a brittle dowager. The one thing you never saw in
a Guinness movie was ... well, Alec Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of movie stardom, after all, is the performer's
ability to project an indelible sense of self. No matter what the
role, John Wayne is John Wayne. Katharine Hepburn is Katharine
Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if that sense of self is a sham, a facade
constructed to peddle a personality to glamour-starved consumers.
What matters is that we in the audience believe we know that
individual up on the screen. We're familiar with him or her, we
feel at home in this person's presence. We more or less know what
to expect, and that's why we pay to see them.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Alec wasn't having any of that. Here was a man whose
professional life seemed devoted to covering up any trace of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   While movie stars send the silent message ``Me! Me! Me!''
Guinness stood outside himself, diffidently observing his own
creations, seeming to say, in those bemused British tones, ``My,
my, what a curious fellow this is!''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, being a movie star is, to a great extent, about sex.
That's one reason gay and lesbian movie stars stay in the closet _
knowing the truth would ruin the fantasy life of filmgoers, who
imagine themselves in love with these beautiful people.
</P>
<P>
   But can anyone recall Guinness in a genuinely romantic role,
much less a sexy one? Either because of age or by an act of will, a
Guinness character invariably has moved beyond such trivial
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   No, as was made abundantly clear in his 1985 autobiography
Blessings in Disguise, Sir Alec was too modest, too gentle, too
nice a chap to even think of himself in such terms.
</P>
<P>
   The closest he came to actually showing off was in the 1949
comedy ``Kind Hearts and Coronets,'' in which he played all the
members of a stuffy British family. But even in that case, it was
obvious that his goal was to amuse us, not gratify himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's significant that after winning a Best Actor Oscar in 1957
for his portrayal of a by-the-book British officer in ``Bridge on
the River Kwai,'' Sir Alec almost never took the lead role in a
film.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he devoted himself to supporting parts that would allow
him to indulge his fascination with the eccentricities of human
character _ this from a man who appeared to have no eccentricities
of his own.
</P>
<P>
   And what a lot of characters he gave us! The Arab Prince Feisal
in ``Lawrence of Arabia.'' A KGB bigwig in ``Dr. Zhivago.'' Adolf
Hitler in ``The Last 10 Days.'' A bumbling blind butler in ``Murder
By Death.'' Obi-Wan Kenobi in the ``Star Wars'' series. A wry Hindu
intellectual in ``A Passage to India.'' A reprobate adventurer who
sires his own tribe of Amazon warriors in ``A Handful of Dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention his numerous roles on stage or his indelible
performance as spymaster George Smiley in the TV adaptations of
John le Carre's novels.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one could make a case that Alec Guinness was the finest
actor of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   We can say that now that he's gone. In life he would have been
too embarrassed to wear the crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
