<HEADER>
A4673 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-JAZZ-BOS &LR;      08-07 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JAZZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERNON REID GETS `SERIOUS' AT NEWPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The JVC Jazz Festival-Newport kicks off this year with a pair of
elegant old-timers, Bobby Short and Dave Brubeck, performing at
Friday night's opening festivities at the Newport Casino. The
festival's following two days, however, run the gamut of styles
from traditional to contemporary, with _ happily _ a handful of
things in between.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, artists as diverse as fusion supergroup Fourplay
(Bob James, Nathan East, Harvey Mason, and Larry Carlton), Nigerian
Afro-beat star Femi Kuti &AMP; Positive Force, and saxophonist (and
Miles Davis protege) Kenny Garrett appear on the Fort stage.
Sunday, the lineup spans the spectrum from eclectic vocalist
Cassandra Wilson to avant-garde composer John Zorn with his group
Masada to smooth-jazz titans Boney James and Rick Braun.
</P>
<P>
   New this year is an invitation-only symposium before the
festival proper, as well as a second Harbor stage at Fort Adams
State Park, the festival site, to showcase less bankable artists
during the weekend afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   It's there on the smaller stage that you'll find Vernon Reid
performing on Sunday. Rock fans know Reid as the founder and
guitarist of the alternative-metal band Living Colour, an all-black
quartet that helped upend the stereotype of hard rock as the domain
of white men. Reid considers Jimi Hendrix his predecessor and Lenny
Kravitz a disciple.
</P>
<P>
   Those more familiar with the experimental fringes, however,
remember Reid's early days playing in the New York underground
scene with Ronald Shannon Jackson's Decoding Society (which
appeared at the Newport festival in 1984), Defunkt, and Bill
Frisell, among others. Reid is, in fact, a dedicated eclectic. His
various projects have involved jazz, punk, hip-hop, electronica,
and funk, often simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Reid is a dazzling guitar technician, but more than that he's a
musical adventurer. Case in point is his 1996 solo debut,
``Mistaken Identity,'' which featured a core band composed of
clarinet (the ever-intriguing Don Byron), turntable, bass, drums,
and a keyboard invention called the Samchillian Tip Tip Tip
CheeePeeeee _ which Reid says is even stranger-sounding than its
name. Guest performers on the album, produced by Teo Mecero,
included rappers, a poet, and the actor Laurence Fishburne. Reid
plans to play material from ``Mistaken Identity'' at Newport.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made that album, in the aftermath of Living Colour, I
was really questioning who I had become, and also who I could
become,'' says Reid on the phone from New York. ``I still consider
myself a rock artist, because I think rock is expandable. It's
Slipknot but it's also Steely Dan. It's Soft Machine and Fats
Domino. The double-edged sword is we're just designed to
categorize, and there are those of us who don't really take to it.
I just play.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the year after he formed Living Colour, Reid and
journalist Greg Tate formed the Black Rock Coalition, an
organization dedicated to opening doors for black musicians who
weren't soul crooners or rappers. ``Basically the clubs weren't
booking my band, record labels weren't listening, so in the
beginning it was really me asking, `Hey, am I alone?' '' Reid
recalls. ``Greg and I used to just meet all the time and talk about
these things. Then one day he said, `What are we going to do about
it?' The mission became community, the survival of community.
Liberation can't be limited to one race.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid went on to record four albums with Living Colour _ 1998's
Grammy-winning ``Vivid'' produced the smash hit ``Cult of
Personality'' _ before disbanding in 1995. Pioneering as that group
was, Reid is adamant about pushing the edges of the stylistic
envelope furthur. Jazz, Reid says, is a key part of that process on
a number of levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in with the so-called avant-garde, the kind that
reexamines the structural forms of music as well as dialogues with
society,'' Reid explains. ``Spend any time with Ornette (Coleman)
and you realize he's not just a seminal improvisor but a seminal
thinker. I don't know how serious a jazz musician I am. I seriously
love it. It's been a big influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid has also begun thinking seriously about a political cause.
Outraged by the forced amputation of hands by terrorists in Sierra
Leone, Reid is hoping to organize a festival of percussion to
benefit the victims. ``The drum is the preeminent instrument of
African music, and this act of mutilation is so counter to the
spirit of the drums. A fitting reaction would be to use percussion
to help them.'' Reid invites anyone interested in helping out to
email him at optivern(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reid is putting together yet another rock band, with
``Mistaken Identity'' collaborator DJ Logic. They've done a few
gigs, but are still trying to find the right vocalist. ``A lot of
this is in flux. But the music is calling me again,'' says Reid.
``The possibilites are still endless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
