A4674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MYSELF-BOS &LR;      08-07 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MYSELF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO THE HEART OF THE `REAL' CHARLES MINGUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MYSELF WHEN I AM REAL 
The Life and Music of Charles Mingus 
By Gene Santoro 
Oxford University Press, 452 pp., $30 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it lasted only 56 years, Charles Mingus's was a life
lived in full. The bass virtuoso and composer was bedeviled by
racism, and fought fearlessly against injustice in any form. He was
a man of prodigious appetites, for everything from food to ideas to
women, four of whom he married. Mingus hung out with musicians, but
he also counted among his friends and acquaintances Orson Welles,
Allan Ginsberg, and Jackson Pollock. He could be charming or
callous, brilliant or belligerent. He considered himself a race
man, but seemed to favor the company of white women; he abhorred
drugs and addicts, but popped pills for much of his life. A man
guided by angels and demons, Mingus had an insatiable curiosity for
everything that crossed his path.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, there was his music.
</P>
<P>
   From the melancholy ``Goodbye Pork Pie Hat,'' his tribute to
Lester Young, to the frenzied joy of ``Better Get Hit in Yo'
Soul,'' he created some of the most challenging and glorious
compositions in the jazz canon. He played with the greatest
musicians of his time, including Duke Ellington, Charlie Parker,
Dizzy Gillespie, Thelonious Monk, and Bud Powell. Mingus approached
the bass as a vital, primary instrument _ and he played it as if
he'd invented it, caressing it like a lover, or slapping it like
somebody who owed him money. More than 20 years after his death
from Lou Gehrig's disease, Mingus still looms as one of the great
figures of American music, the unruly Spirit of jazz's Holy Trinity
alongside Ellington and Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Mingus is too much man to fit between the covers of
a book _ which is not to say Gene Santoro's unconventional but
meticulously researched biography is a failure. In fact, ``Myself
When I Am Real'' is a deliciously entertaining examination not only
of jazz's ``angry man'' and his music, but of the times in which
both flourished. In this, the first Mingus biography in 17 years,
Santoro casts Mingus as a central character in the restless drama
of a postwar America wrestling to find its identity politically,
socially, and artistically. Santoro places Mingus ``in his special
moment in American history's flow,'' as the New York Daily News
music critic writes in his introduction. His goal, he says, was to
``capture how a fragile, fertile network of real people and places
and a lifetime of encounters and events allowed Mingus to be Mingus
_ which is to to say, one of the most important composers, pivotal
artistic figures, and magnetic characters from the wild renaissance
explosion of talented oddballs who rumbled across the arts in
post-World War II United States.'' And mostly, Santoro succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Nogales, Ariz., in 1922, Mingus was raised in the Watts
section of Los Angeles by his biracial father and stepmother. His
birth mother died when he was less than six months old _ a loss
from which he would never fully recover, and one which fueled a
lifetime craving for female attention. His father was a strict
former Army sergeant who insisted his children study classical
music. Young Charles's first instrument was a trombone, but he soon
traded it for a cello. He would turn to the bass at 14, when an
older musician told him that a classical-music career as a cellist
was off-limits to a black man, but playing bass would always enable
him to make a living in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   He gave himself wholly to the bass, playing 17 hours a day. The
instrument was more than a ticket out of Watts; it gave Mingus his
own creative language. He took lessons from Red Callendar; he
absorbed the music of Ellington and pianist Art Tatum, as well as
Bach and Beethoven. He viewed jazz as music without limitation, one
which could borrow from any form from gospel to Colombian cumbias.
As his notoriety in the LA music scene grew, so did Mingus's
healthy ego. By his early 20s, he was calling himself ``Baron''
Mingus to align himself with jazz royalty _ Duke Ellington, Count
Basie, and King Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   As Mingus's story unfolds, Santoro keeps the backbeat with
perspectives on the socio-political churnings of those years, all
of which affected Mingus's life and music. Occasionally, his
juxtapositions can be as jarring as an off-note _ in the middle of
discussing a Mingus collaboration with poet Langston Hughes, he
tosses in a single-line mention of an early assassination attempt
on Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. That's on page 138, and King's name
doesn't pop up again until page 165.
</P>
<P>
   But usually, Santoro is on-target, and his writing often soars.
He clearly loves his subject, but doesn't shy from Mingus's
moodiness and misbehaviors. If Mingus wasn't all devil, Santoro
doesn't make him a saint. Instead, he makes him a man in full who
was not only influenced by the times, but left an indelible mark on
the latter half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creativity isn't necessarily straightforward in its dealings
with the world,'' Santoro writes. ``To put it another way, no one
has ever convinced me that the geniuses who have the lasting human
touch we call art are either monsters or role models, or even that
they should be. Shamans don't have to be horrible or nice. They
just have to work effectively in their surroundings, (and) account
for some of the planet's mysteries in ways the people they live
among can understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
