<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PAXMAN-BOS &LR;      08-07 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PAXMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ENGLISH 
A Portrait of a People 
By Jeremy Paxman. Overlook. 309 pp. $29.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeremy Paxman, the host of BBC's ``Newsnight'' current-affairs
program, is the most feared interrogator on British television, a
Ted Koppel with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Paxman once famously asked an evasive Tory Cabinet minister the
same question 12 consecutive times on live TV. In his provocative
contemplation on his own people, ``The English,'' he asks with
characteristic persistence, ``Who are we?''
</P>
<P>
   Paxman writes: ``The end of empire, the cracks opening in the
so-called United Kingdom, the pressures for the English to plunge
into Europe, and the uncontrollability of international businessset
me wondering. What did it mean to be English?''
</P>
<P>
   Those who subscribe to the misty-eyed view that England is a
place of warm beer, dog lovers, and cricket on the village green
might not like the answers Paxman supplies. Michael Howard, the
unfortunate Tory minister whose refusal to answer a simple question
earned him a dubious place in British TV history, would probably be
among those who consider Paxman part of that chablis-swigging,
sushi-chomping clique of self-loathing Englishmen at the BBC who
hate the queen almost as much as they hate themselves and the
masters who beat them at boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   But Paxman's search for the soul of the English recognizes his
country's virtues as often as its foibles. After all, the English
gave the world the most utilitarian language on the planet,
parliamentary and legal systems so enviable that even those who
rebelled against the British empire retained them, and Shakespeare
and the Beatles _ not to mention soccer and cricket.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Paxman does not shrink from telling the English what they
don't want to hear. That British empire on which the sun never set
is dead and gone, and now the English _ the dominant group of those
who make up Britons _ are living in shadow, trying to find an
identity that used to be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being English used to be so easy,'' Paxman observes. ``They
were one of the most easily identified peoples on earth, recognized
by their language, their manners, their clothes and the fact that
they drank tea by the bucketload.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, he concludes, ``the conventions that defined the
English are dead and the country's ambassadors are more likely to
be singers or writers than diplomats or politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   He exposes the myths that have led to the English suffering an
identity crisis even as those they once lorded over _ the Irish,
the Scots, and the Welsh _ are experiencing unprecedented bursts of
confidence, creativity, and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Paxman's most evocative chapter examines the greatest myth: Why,
in a nation where about 90 percent of the population lives in urban
areas, is there such a visceral, absurdly disproportionate
attachment to the countryside? He lays much of the blame at the
foot of one of England's greatest resources, its writers.
Wordsworth and A. E. Housman, Blake and H. V. Morton, J. B.
Priestley, Agatha Christie, John Betjeman, even George Orwell,
whose ``old maids cycling to holy communion through the morning
mist'' description of England was borrowed by the Conservative
prime minister John Major as recently as 1993, are all guilty of
perpetuating an image of bucolic, rural England that bears no
resemblance to reality, Paxman contends. Contemporary writers like
Martin Amis may pen authentic metropolitan-based novels, but it's
the historical novels set in the countryside that sell by the
bucketload, Paxman says.
</P>
<P>
   Originally published in Britain in 1998, the book has only
gained currency in the two years that have passed until the
American edition, making Paxman's observations seem all that more
prescient. The creation of home-rule parliaments in Belfast,
Edinburgh, and Cardiff has not only decentralized power but added
to the Englishman's angst. The battle over the English countryside,
best exemplified by the debate over outlawing fox hunts, has grown
only more divisive.
</P>
<P>
   Paxman casts a cold eye on the English, pulling no punches with
those who throw sucker punches. He finds English soccer hooligans
reprehensible, and has no time for those who suggest their violent
bigotry is a function of repressed nationalism. But he also tries
to explain their idiosyncrasies, which others often take as
rudeness or arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Having lived in Dublin before we moved to London, my wife and I
were stunned by the difference between the Irish, who think nothing
of inviting a new acquaintance to their home, and the English, who
are far more reticent. Paxman has an explanation for what he calls
``this curious reluctance to engage with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the English see as no more than respect for privacy looks
to others like disdain,'' Paxman writes. ``It is one of the
defining characteristics of the English; foreigners are forever
complaining about it. . . . Even foreigners sent to work in the
country can find that the only time their English colleagues invite
them into their homes is on the eve of their departure.''
</P>
<P>
   The English love nothing more than a backyard, which they call a
garden, with a high fence. But they socialize most often in pubs or
restaurants, Paxman says, not at home. ``In much of continental
Europe, you live on the street. It is the place where you eat,
drink, commiserate, flirt, laugh and pass the time of day. The
English answer to the street is the back garden, in which
socializing is by invitation only.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxman occupies a position of influence in British television
not unlike that occupied in American broadcasting by another
anchorman who made good on the book circuit, Tom Brokaw. While
Brokaw's homage to the American generation who lived through the
Depression and fought World War II is a good and honorable piece of
work, Paxman's book has far more edge and is a more important book
because it dares to examine what's wrong with the English. It is an
eminently frank, readable elucidation _ which, incidentally, is the
kind of word Paxman throws at BBC viewers around 11 p.m. on
weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   And while the old men sipping gin and tonics at the Marylebone
Cricket Club (who last year were forced to accept women as members)
might disagree, Jeremy Paxman's love of England shines through this
book. His criticism is constructive, not gratuitous, and it is
dispensed with the conviction that once shown the errors of their
ways, the English can admit it, learn from it, and move on, the
better for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen is the Globe's London bureau chief and European
correspondent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
