<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG COUPLE NEED TO SAVE MORE TO RETIRE EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We have no children, but would like to start a family soon.
We expect college tuition and other child expenses to increase the
amount of money that leaves our hands each month. I want to retire
at 35, and my husband wants to retire by 50. Can we retire at these
young ages and still have a good retirement? I keep telling my
husband we need to save more money; he says we are young and don't
have to worry, that we have more savings than any of our friends.
</P>
<P>
   S.S., Orange, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. My first instinct was to make some smart remark about
California Dreaming. But when I worked the numbers, they came out a
lot closer than I thought they would. Still, I don't think the plan
is workable. Here's how the numbers add up:
</P>
<P>
   After seven years, and presuming 10 percent average annual
portfolio growth, your own accounts would grow to $674,836. If you
project your husband's current balance and contributions to yours,
the combined pool would be $1,051,706. (These calculations do not
include the effect of any funds that might be added to your
profit-sharing plans by your employers.)
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume you leave your money intact for the next nine
years, and that your husband continues to save at the current
level. You'd have a combined balance of $2,460,197 by the time your
husband is 50.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds impressive, but now for the bad news: If inflation
averages 3.5 percent for those 16 years, you'd have the buying
power of about $1.3 million in today's money. And if you were to
put about a third of your money aside _ to protect you against the
many years of inflation during your retirement _ you could probably
expect to have a joint income of about $55,000 in retirement. That,
of course, is a far cry from the $170,000 you earn now, and even
from the $128,500 you are living on.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, during the first eight years of retirement, your
family income stream would drop from that $128,500 to $99,500,
which might be tough, in view of the substantial cost of raising
children. (If you were to have the children soon, they would likely
be entering college just after your husband retired.)
</P>
<P>
   So in the end, you are both right. You're right that you should
worry about your money. Your husband is right that you're both
young, and if you keep saving as you are, everything will work out
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Just to show you how I am thinking, I calculated the growth of
your joint portfolio if you both work for 16 years _ until your
husband is 50 and you are 44. If you save at current levels, you
would have $3,033,643. And if you raise your savings levels as your
incomes increase, and add in contributions to your profit-sharing
plans, the sum would doubtless be a lot more. I think such a plan
is a lot more realistic than what you propose. Because of its
complexity, I left out details of your portfolio. It's fine _ the
problem is that if you retire in seven years, you are simply asking
it to do more than is realistic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been saving for my grandson's college education. I add
odd amounts to the Proctor and Gamble account as Christmas and
birthday gifts. I add $50 a month to the Stein Roe fund, and $150 a
month to the Schwab Market Track Growth account. Am I missing
something with my strategy?
</P>
<P>
   J.K., Charleston, S.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're doing pretty well, although I'd make a few changes. If
you keep up your $200 monthly contributions for 11 years, your
grandson would have $88,319 at age 17, assuming overall portfolio
returns of 10 percent a year. And that doesn't reflect the effect
of your Christmas and birthday contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Of the accumulation projected above, $51,430 would be in the
account in your name, so your grandson's eligibility for financial
assistance would not be dramatically affected. (Of course, it would
have been better if you had put the dough in your own name right
from the start.) If you were to put all future contributions in
your own name, $63,372 of the pool would be invisible on the
applications for financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   As for the particular investments, if I were adding $50 a month
to one of the custodial accounts, I would certainly choose
Firsthand Technology Leaders over Stein Roe Young Investors. Yes,
the technology fund has much higher risk, but over 11 years you can
also expect it to deliver much bigger returns (although the
dazzling 152.6 percent gain of last year is probably something you
won't see again in the near future). As for Stein Roe Young
Investor, I focused a large part of a previous column on this fund,
about which I am less enthusiastic than I used to be. (I prefer a
straight S&AMP;P 500 Index fund.)
</P>
<P>
   But those are minor changes, and you should bear in mind that
shifting from Stein Roe Young Investors or an S&AMP;P 500 fund to
Firsthand raises the overall risk. In all likelihood, you should do
quite nicely if you just keep doing as you are doing. Diverting
that $50 a month to an account in your name is probably more
important than changing the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money musings: About a month ago, I noted the rise of the
Vanguard Index 500 fund to the head of the list of the world's
mutual funds, at least based on total assets under management. It
passed the legendary Fidelity Magellan fund, a development that was
far from surprising, since Magellan had been closed to new
investors for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Then a funny thing happened. Index 500 failed to pull away. In
recent weeks, Magellan has been getting closer and closer to
regaining the top spot. Entering last week, Index 500 had $105,583
million under management, while Magellan was right behind, at
$104,718 million. And the records show that if investors are
turning to Magellan instead of to Index 500, they are following the
numbers: Magellan had a year-to-date loss of 1.6 percent entering
last week, verrsus a loss of 2.7 percent for Index 500.
</P>
<P>
   In my mind, this is not the kind of mindless statistic such as
those that preoccupy diehard baseball fans. Many market followers
have been predicting for years that the worm would turn, and that
in a choppy market such as we are currently enjoying, well-managed
funds would once again show they can outperform the indexers.
</P>
<P>
   The trend of managed funds beating the indexes shows across the
entire large-cap universe.
</P>
<P>
   Index 500's 2.7 percent loss compares to a loss of 0.7 percent
for the median large-cap blend fund. In the large-cap growth
sector, Vanguard Index Growth showed a 2.8 percent loss, compared
to a median loss of 0.3 percent for its peers. Only Vanguard Index
Value was close to the median, losing 2.7 percent compared to a 2.6
percent median loss for large-cap value funds.
</P>
<P>
   If you want more evidence the indexers fear the heyday of the
index funds may be coming to an end, in the same issue of The New
York Times in which I found these fascinating stats, there appeared
a letter to the business editors from John C. Bogle, founder of the
Vanguard Group and generally considered the father of the index
fund. He was complaining that the Times had discontinued a feature
comparing the results of five market advisers with the market at
large, represented by the Vanguard Index 500 fund.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Bogle was able to show the index came out on
top, with its growth from $50,000 to $188,750 (during the
seven-year period covered by the newspaper feature) beating the
next-best performance, growth from $50,000 to $155,000.
</P>
<P>
   Let the race continue. This is the best way to drum home the
real message, the challenges and frustrations that even experts
face when managing fund portfolios to outpace an unmanaged index,
Bogle wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder whether some of his passion might be caused by the
end of the across-the-board market boom that served index funds so
well, and the return of a stock-picker's market. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
