<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRUST-TAX-BOS &LR;      08-07 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRUST-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWS WOULD ALLOW UNLIMITED TRUSTS _ FOREVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Thomas Jefferson uttered a word about equality among men,
Americans were already squeamish about allowing huge family
fortunes to pass from generation to generation. The idea reminded
them of European aristocracy, and it didn't fit the self-made-man
ethos of the New World.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward a couple of centuries to the newer New World.
</P>
<P>
   These days, jobs are plentiful, people are flush, and
aristocratic Europeans are the butt of jokes rather than a source
of fear and loathing. For a mostly middle-class America, dreams of
dot-com millions have replaced worries about redistributing wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from that cultural shift, two seemingly unrelated
trends are on the verge of shaking up financial and estate planning
in a way that would have shocked Jeffersonian America, if not
Jefferson himself.
</P>
<P>
   Congress on the one hand and state lawmakers on the other could
soon make it possible to pass down unlimited amounts of money to
future generations tax and penalty free. The twist: Not only is the
change unintentional, but it has gone largely unnoticed by both the
politicians creating it and the money pros who will have to
implement it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are being rushed into law without any thought to the
long-term consequences,'' said Ira Mark Bloom, a professor at
Albany Law School in Albany, N.Y. ``Unknowingly, perhaps, we're
setting in motion things which could have a tremendous impact on
future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   The repeal of two obscure pieces of legislation _ known as the
uniform rule against perpetuities and the generation-skipping
transfer tax _ would combine to cause that impact. People would
then be able to create trusts of unlimited size and keep them in
force for an unlimited number of years for an unlimited number of
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``For wealthy people, that's a pretty big deal,'' Bloom said.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the two trends has actually been in motion for
three years. The Alaskan legislature prompted it in 1997, when in
trying to attract bank deposits and trust accounts it killed off
the rule against perpetuities, which had been in force in all but
three other states.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about losing sizeable trust accounts across state lines,
eight other legislatures have followed suit. Trust accounts can be
an important source of revenue for states, since they provide
business for local financial professionals and, in most cases,
generate state income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Five more states have similar legislation pending, and one _
Florida _ recently amended its rule rather than scrapping it
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing to call this type of phenomenon is competitive
federalism, and the not-so-nice thing to call it is a race for the
bottom,'' Bloom said. ``It's hard for one state to be principled
when it's facing a tremendous loss of money to a neighboring
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule in question, so fiendishly complex that lawyers in
Massachusetts can't be held liable for malpractice if they
misinterpret it, essentially limits the time a trust can lock up
assets to 21 years after the deaths of beneficiaries living when it
was created.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a wealthy individual couldn't put land (or
anything else) worth millions of dollars in trust at her death with
the stipulation that her family live off the proceeds forever.
Within a century or so, at most, the land would have to be passed
to a person or group of people who would have to pay regular taxes
and would be allowed to do what they liked with the property.
</P>
<P>
   Scrapping the rule allows families to create so-called dynasty
or wealth-building trusts, which could survive multiple
generations. But estate planners say people haven't been stampeding
across state lines to create new accounts.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the second piece of the trend puzzle, the federal
government's generation-skipping transfer tax, limits the amount of
money people can pass on to any generation beyond their children to
slightly more than $1 million. Any more than that gets hit with a
55 percent tax _ on top of regular gift and estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact from repealing the perpetuities rule is clearly
limited by the (generation-skipping transfer tax),'' said Bruno
Graziano, an estate-planning lawyer and analyst with CCH Inc., in
Riverwoods, Ill. ``If they were to repeal the (federal tax), too,
that might be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that such a repeal could happen in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unnoticed in the hotly debated and widely reported
congressional bill that would eliminate the federal estate tax is a
provision that would also deep-six the generation-skipping tax. If
the bill becomes law, both taxes would be phased out over the next
decade, making limitless trusts possible.
</P>
<P>
   Both houses of Congress approved the estate tax legislation this
summer, but neither was by a veto-proof margin. The law's prospects
are therefore murky, since President Clinton has promised to reject
the bill when it reaches his desk this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush, on the other
hand, has said he would sign it if he is elected and is sent a
similar measure next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge potential change when you think about it,'' said
Neil Harl, an Iowa State University professor who has written three
books on estate planning. ``If people start to park their wealth in
permanent trusts, it would literally transform the economic
structure of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   It would also transform estate and financial planning for
millions of Americans who aren't in a hurry to give Uncle Sam money
and property they've earned over the course of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Millis estate planner Robert Matson said dynasty trusts would be
helpful for families in a variety of situations. That's especially
true in regions such as New England, he said, where soaring home
values and the rising stock market have combined to make the
current generation wealthier than any before it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once worked with a client who kept a bust of his great
grandfather in his office, and he literally had tears well up in
his eyes when I asked about the man,'' Matson said. ``The guy had
set up some kind of trust generations ago that allowed his great
grandson to buy a business of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good estate planning and that's the kind of thing
dynasty trusts would make easier to accomplish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom, of the Albany Law School, said he agrees the trusts would
be helpful for many, but he has joined University of Michigan law
professor Lawrence Waggoner on a lonely mission to convince
politicians to also consider problems with them.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom wrote an article on the downsides to the trusts in an
April issue of the journal Tax Notes, successfully testified
against a bill that would have repealed the rule against
perpetuities last year in New York, and has a prepared speech
(slides included) he gives to lawyers' groups and anyone else who
will listen. So far, though, he hasn't found many takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has been viewed as an esoteric topic only lawyers
and academics care about,'' he said this week. ``But it is clearly
something that should be looked at closely by a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bloom is no hard-and-fast advocate for the status quo,
either. He just wants state legislatures to consider the long-term
consequences of repealing the perpetuities rule, including the
widening of the wealth gap and consolidation of power in the hands
of corporate trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he asked, ``do you really want to allow somebody who
dies in 2010 to have dead-hand control over property thousands of
years from now?''
</P>
<P>
   To put the question in perspective, he asks people to imagine
the restrictions a rich landowner might have placed on his property
at the time of Christ. Then imagine trying to put those
restrictions into practice now for hundreds of thousands of living
decendents with property that could have grown to unimaginable
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are staggering, and we won't even get into the
problems such a trust could create in 10,000 years or 100,000
years,'' Bloom said. ``Changing the rules is expedient now, but we
don't seem to be taking responsibility for what it might do to
future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   As a middle ground, Florida recently extended its perpetuities
rule to allow trusts to remain in effect for 360 years. That's the
type of compromise Bloom would like to see more states consider,
since it addresses the demand for more lenient trusts without
creating the mind-boggling problems of perpetual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Matson, who is president-elect of the Boston Estate Planning
Council, said he suspects politicians haven't completely thought
through the issues yet. Once they do, he said, they will probably
come up with compromises that create a standardized system
nationwide that deals with Bloom's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too big of a deal in the estate planning world to
leave to chance,'' Matson said. ``It might take a little while, but
there are smart people who will figure these things out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
