<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-YOUNG-BOS &LR;      08-07 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YOUNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREVER NEIL YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 15 years ago, when Neil Young had just shifted into a
proudly contrarian country phase of his career, he was asked how he
had come to that point. ``I feel like I could be likened to an old
hound circling on a rug for the past five years,'' he answered,
``and I think I've finally found my spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Young was wrong, of course. Time has shown he never does quite
find his spot on that musical rug. It's for this reason, among
others, that he's earned the love and respect of multiple
generations. We never know where he's headed _ toward contemplative
acoustic-based pop or anarchic noise _ and we're pretty sure he
doesn't either. His latest work, ``Silver and Gold,'' is a highly
regarded, comfy kind of album: homespun, contented, easy on the
ears. Given this, it's likely he and his band _ which includes
guitarist Ben Keith, keyboardist Spooner Oldham, bassist Donald
``Duck'' Dunn, drummer Jim Keltner, and Young's wife, Pegi Young,
and Astrid Young on background vocals _ will let it rip and roar
when they play the Tweeter Center for the Performing Arts in Boston
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Step back and ponder this: How many still-active rockers who
began their ascent to fame and fortune in the 1960s are still
relevent artistically? That is, how many make new music we readily
anticipate? Precious few. Not Bob Dylan, Roger McGuinn, Joan Baez,
or Paul McCartney. Not the Beach Boys or Pink Floyd. Certainly not
Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash _ not without Young. We all know that had
Young not joined C S &AMP; N for their tour earlier this year, the show
would have been at the Orpheum, not the FleetCenter. It's Young who
provides the edge, be it on a simple, raging guitar lead or in that
whiny voice. Or, maybe, in the choice of song. You don't think it's
Crosby, Stills, or Nash's idea to howl through the murderous ``Down
by the River,'' now, do you?
</P>
<P>
   These aformentioned artists have their audiences. But going to
see them is, essentially, a nostalgic act: You hope Dylan's sonic
reinventions will at least remind you of the original song; you're
really happy McCartney trots out some Beatles hits.
</P>
<P>
   Young's success, with audiences and critics alike, is rooted in
his sense of musical adventure, of taking risks that may well
alienate somebody. That and his willing embrace of duality, of a
melody that glides and a feedback-ridden guitar lead. Calm and
chaos shake hands and dance.
</P>
<P>
   Young followed his major-league breakthrough of ``Harvest'' in
1972 with a wretched, meandering soundtrack to a film he wrote and
directed, ``Journey Through the Past.'' Two subsequent albums, ``On
the Beach'' and ``Zuma,'' were notable for desolate moods and
haunting songs. In 1976, responding to a stormy time in his own
life and in the lives of his friends and bandmates, Young headed
for the gutter and recorded the bleak, shaky, but often brilliant
``Tonight's the Night.'' At this point, much of his audience
decided to go elsewhere. From ``Heart of Gold'' to the heart of
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comes a Time'' was a return to folk-rock bliss in 1978. The
following year, Young responded to the challenge of punk rock with
``Rust Never Sleeps,'' arguably his best work. In the '80s he
released three tepid genre experiments: synth-pop (``Trans''),
rockabilly (``Everybody's Rockin' ''), and R&AMP;B (``This Note's for
You''). His label, Geffen, sued him for making records that didn't
sound like Neil Young records. There followed the glorious comeback
of ``Freedom,'' and still to come were the blitzkrieg of ``Ragged
Glory'' and the pastoral calm of ``Harvest Moon.'' Young, at 54,
fits in with young pierced punks as well as he does with a banjo
player and a fiddler on a backwoods dusty porch.
</P>
<P>
   He was the oldest guy to headline the multiband, jam-oriented
H.O.R.D.E. tour. He toured with New York avant-garde band Sonic
Youth and longtime punk heroes Social Distortion. He recorded an
album with Pearl Jam, ``Mirror Ball.'' None of this came off as a
music biz-generated attempt at Capturing That Youth Market (unlike,
say, Carlos Santana's hit of last year).
</P>
<P>
   What all this suggests is this: That while most rockers hit a
creative peak in their 20s or 30s, you cannot guarantee that Young
has hit his. His heyday might not be behind him _ and that keeps
you tuned in. Sure, when Young plays in concert he'll ding your
memory bell, but his is not a nostalgia trip. He may even play
unrecorded songs _ he's got a sizzling rocker called ``Ordinary
People'' that has seen release only on bootlegs.
</P>
<P>
   He's also got hundreds of other unreleased songs sitting in his
vaults, awaiting release. Young reportedly (key word
``reportedly'') has an eight-disc archival set covering the years
up through 1972 ready for release this fall. Right now, a
spokeswoman for his label, Warner Bros., says the box is not yet
listed for a release date. The first of a projected four, this
summing-up has been postponed before due to Young's idiosyncrasies.
</P>
<P>
   He's mercurial, Neil Young is. Lord knows, he's no closet
socialist _ he's asking his fans to get friendly with credit card
debt if they want to attend his shows. (Top ticket for this one:
$150.) He is far from the most technically brilliant guitarist
around, but in a pinch whom do you want to play the solo that
transports you to another realm? He's not the most pitch-perfect
singer, but who conveys both pleasure (``Rockin' in the Free
World'') and pain (``The Needle and the Damage Done'') better than
Young?
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, there's this. When Lynyrd Skynyrd took a shot at
Young for his antiracist ballad ``Southern Man'' in ``Sweet Home
Alabama,'' Young responded once by joining Lynyrd Skynyrd onstage
to sing that very song. Can you imagine how much fun Neil Young
must have had singing ``I hope Neil Young will remember/Southern
man don't need him around anyhow!''? You can't beat that kind of
perverse glee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
