<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LONGMAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY WON THE CUP _ AND SOMETHING MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GIRLS OF SUMMER 
By Jere Longman. HarperCollins. 318 pp. Illustrated. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time, Kristine Lilly remembered, when their parents
were their fans, when the US women's soccer team wore men's
uniforms, flew overseas on cargo planes, slept in squalid hotel
rooms, and lived on Snickers bars and Pop-Tarts.
</P>
<P>
   So when Lilly and her teammates walked onto the field a year ago
for the World Cup final and realized that the mammoth Rose Bowl was
filled, they were stunned. ``All I could see was people, a sea of
people,'' Lilly said. ``I could have bawled. We had been waiting
for so long for people to come and watch us.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the US women won the Olympic gold medal on home
soil, NBC didn't broadcast the final. Last year, more than 40
million people watched the match live. And after Brandi Chastain
tore off her jersey to celebrate her winning penalty kick against
the Chinese, she ended up on the cover of Time, Newsweek and Sports
Illustrated. ``GIRLS RULE,'' a headline said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody since the Boys of Winter, the 1980 US Olympic hockey team
that came from nowhere to win the gold medal at Lake Placid,
captured America's imagination the way the Girls of Summer did. And
if they didn't change the world, as author Jere Longman contends,
they undoubtedly changed the way the world perceives their game and
the women who play it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their World Cup rivals came from countries, particularly
in Latin America and Africa, where it is believed either that
females have no business playing soccer or that they are not worth
watching. Even FIFA, the international soccer federation which
declared that ``the future is feminine,'' had urged that the
tournament be held in small East Coast stadiums in order to
minimize empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   When more than 650,000 people bought tickets to see games from
coast to coast, and 90,000 (including President Clinton) jammed the
Rose Bowl for the final, nobody could deny that the women's game _
at least in the United States _ had come to full flower.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when the Americans had won the inaugural Cup in China,
they came home to find that nobody but family and friends realized
they had even been playing. Last summer, after watching a Gatorade
commercial in which Mia Hamm judo-flipped Michael Jordan, Buffalo
Bills quarterback Doug Flutie's 10-year-old daughter asked him,
``Who's that guy with Mia?''
</P>
<P>
   Longman, who covered the Cup for The New York Times, does an
admirable job of chronicling how Hamm and her teammates went from
anonymous ponytails to poster women. Using the final match as a
frame-by-frame centerpiece (possibly the best account ever of a 0-0
sporting event), Longman not only traces the evolution of the
women's game but deals with changing perceptions (and lingering
biases) about female athletes in general.
</P>
<P>
   Even after they had won the Cup and filled every venue they
played in (outdrawing even the pope at Giants Stadium), the US
women had to go on strike this year to achieve ``paycheck parity''
with the men's team. And Chastain's exuberant baring of her sports
bra (``A moment of temporary insanity,'' she called it) touched off
a national should-she-or-shouldn't-she-have? debate.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``The Girls of Summer'' decidedly more than a sports
book is Longman's willingness to tackle complex and controversial
issues like race and sex and gender politics on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between the US team and most of their rivals, as
Longman documents, was stunning. The Ghanaians came from a nation
which still subjects women to ritual genital cutting. The Nigerians
had been told that playing soccer would prevent them from bearing
children. The Brazilians were considered homosexuals by many of
their countrymen. ``We are not big, butch, masculine, lesbian
football players,'' Amy Taylor said last year, after she and her
Australian teammates had posed nude for a calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, helped by Title IX, had already fought and won
most of those gender battles. Nobody disputed their right to play
and few debated their femininity. ``The US team is Babe City,''
David Letterman proclaimed on his ``Late Show.''
</P>
<P>
   What the World Cup provided them, finally, was center stage and
a spotlight for their ``personality players'': Hamm; Michelle
Akers, their lioness-maned Alpha female; Briana Scurry, their ``big
badass'' goalkeeper; Julie ``Loudy'' Foudy, their outspoken
midfielder; and Chastain, their ``Hollywood'' showtimer.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans were the tournament's poster women (THIS IS MY
GAME . . . WATCH ME PLAY was the advertising logo), winning the
final was their destiny _ and their reward.
</P>
<P>
   You can't open a champagne bottle while the president is in the
room, a Secret Service agent told Cindy Parlow; a popped cork
sounds like a gunshot. ``Get him out,'' Parlow replied. ``I'm
opening it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Powers, a Globe sportswriter, covers the Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LODGE-BOS &LR;      08-07 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LODGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DRAWING-ROOM DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HOME TRUTHS 
By David Lodge. Penguin. 128 pp. $11.95 (paperback). 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fame can be a toxin posing as an elixir, though in the
post-Camelot age, that in itself is no profundity. David Lodge has
nonetheless chosen to make it the small truth and moral centerpiece
of ``Home Truths,'' which began as a stage play (first produced in
Birmingham in 1998) and here has been reworked and rewired as a
novella. The buff and polish don't much alter the original form:
``Home Truths'' still reads like a script with stage directions,
what with characters closing doors sharply behind them or posing,
front and center, for a moment of dramatic nothingness. This is
odd, and slightly unsettling, but it is still David Lodge _ which
means that, for a hundred-plus brief pages, one has the pleasures
of being in the textual company of one of the funniest
intelligences of contemporary English prose.
</P>
<P>
   Having hurled himself willy-nilly into the American
consciousness with his academic satire, ``Small World,'' and his
deadly on-target novel of neurosis, ``Therapy,'' Lodge is greatly
admired on this side of the Atlantic for being uproarious and wise
simultaneously. In keeping with the recent publishing trend of
milking the cash cow, this scant release comes at the crest of
Lodge's popularity. It will take you longer to park on the way to
procuring ``Home Truths'' than it will to finish the thing, which
should discourage only idealistic readers who still expect heft for
their buck. The rest of us will probably be content with the one or
two moments of splendid humor to be had here, along with the
charming but minor insights about celebrity that the novella
accentuates.
</P>
<P>
   The shuffling-but-noble protagonist is a 50ish fellow named
Adrian Ludlow, a once-heralded novelist who has semi-retired with
his wife, Eleanor, to a forgettable cottage in Sussex. The children
grown, Ludlow's moment in the sun no longer showing a tan line, he
now spends his days editing anthologies _ ``The Paragon Book of
Cricket Writing'' was a recent accomplishment. (Ellie, as Adrian
fondly calls her, seems only to read the Sunday papers in cotton
gloves and make saucy comments, a depiction that further diminishes
``Home Truths'' into a drawing-room drama.) In sharp contrast to
the Ludlows' pastoral quiet is their old friend Sam Sharp, a TV
screenwriter whose bank account far exceeds his creative gifts, or
at least his use of them. Having fallen for the shimmer of his
image in the reflecting pool, Sharp has given an interview to the
notorious Fanny Tarrant of the Sentinel Review _ a journalist whose
reputation has been made by the spike-heel marks she's left on her
subjects' backs. Sick with regret at Tarrant's published
revelations (among them his toupee), Sharp cooks up a plot to
extract revenge _ which, served cold, will wind up poisoning
everyone at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to his friend's vulnerable ego, Sam persuades Adrian
to pretend to give an interview to Tarrant; in fact, he'll be
taping her, then publishing his own story in a competing tabloid.
Feigning indifference but in fact longing for his own day back on
center stage, Adrian agrees; Ellie, who seems to have been the sane
conscience of these three since their school days, finds the whole
enterprise dangerous and absurd. She's right, of course: From the
moment Tarrant arrives, bearing her Sony tape recorder and sweetly
ruthless focus, we can see where this morality play is headed.
Tarrant will be the devil who appeals to each of their vanities _
the antagonist who makes them all worse, then better, than they
thought they could be.
</P>
<P>
   Theatrically, there's something strangely old-fashioned about
``Home Truths'' _ it bears tones of midcentury realism, when good
and evil knocked each other about in the ring until only epiphany
was left standing. The story's not-so-surprising surprise ending
doesn't translate so well to America as it must have played in
England; celebrity is a messy business everywhere, but with our
shrines and icons of vulgarity, we thought of it first and worst.
Thus we may be harder to shock and dismay: The somber, fallen honor
crawling around onstage at the close of ``Home Truths'' can't help
looking a bit ingenuous from these shores. But then privacy and
good intentions mean something different in the motherland, where
Buckingham Palace and Fleet Street still coexist, with each still
dependent upon the kindness of the other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
