<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
!!! 1/2 ``Alice and Martin'' Underrated French director Andre
Techine scores again with this tempestuous drama centering on a
woman (Juliette Binoche) who stands by her stressed-out man and
puts things to rights by plunging into his twisted family's
secrets. (R) 
 
!!! ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' Documentarians Randy Barbato and
Fenton Bailey may have come to jeer Tammy Faye Bakker and her
trademark cow-catcher eyelashes. But she charms her way past some
high kitsch levels until they wind up genuflecting to her toughness
and survival skills in the cutthroat world of televangelism and
celebrity. (PG-13) 
 
! ``Hollow Man'' This invisible-man thriller should have been an
inaudible-man thriller. Every increasingly ludicrous line defeats
hubristic scientist (Kevin Bacon, above) and lab-coated antagonist
(Elisabeth Shue). Claude Rains did it better in 1933. (R) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Saving Grace'' More amiable than original, this village
comedy set in Cornwall stars Brenda Blethyn as a nice widow, warmly
regarded by the townspeople, who unite in complicity to keep the
law off her neck as she tries to rid herself of debts by growing
marijuana. (R) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Space Cowboys'' Geezers in zero gravity. Clint Eastwood
stars as an astronaut who comes out of retirement with former
teammates Tommy Lee Jones, James Garner, and Donald Sutherland
because they're the only ones who remember the antique technology
necessary to fix up This Old Space Station. The heroics kick in,
but, like the astronauts, it all takes a while to get going.
(PG-13) 
 
!!! `Train Birds'' A winning, warm-hearted, low-key German comedy
about a shy railroad-timetable fanatic who discovers _ with the
help of a rose-fancying woman he meets on a train _ that the
fastest route sometimes isn't the best way to get where you want to
go. (Unrated) 
 

