<HEADLINE>
TAYMOR'S AMBITIOUS TAKE ON `TITUS ANDRONICUS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Titus'' (DVD) _ Julie Taymor's ambitious
interpretation of Shakespeare's ``Titus Andronicus'' features
fascinating performances by Anthony Hopkins and Jessica Lange. But
its dependence on idiosyncratic sets, emphasizing the supposed
timelessness of its situations, makes it look more like
``Caligula.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Smoke'' _ This odd movie with Kate Winslet, as a convert
to a cult, and Harvey Keitel, as the professional hired to
deprogram her, is best known for Winslet's frontal nude scene. Too
bad. Although Jane Campion's film has clunky moments and the story
line is not fully realized, the intellectual underpinnings are
ambitious. Raising questions about who really needs to be
deprogrammed is at the core of this intermittently compelling
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beatles Collection'' (DVD) _ The four-disc set includes
``Help,'' ``Magical Mystery Tour,'' ``The Making of a Hard Day's
Night,'' and a documentary on the Beatles' first US visit. The
sound quality is excellent on ``Help,'' but the others suffer
because the original soundtrack recordings are inferior.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD OF THE WEEK: ``My Dog Skip'' _ Frankie Muniz, of ``Malcolm
in the Middle'' TV fame, and a few Jack Russell terriers make the
adaptation of the late Willie Morris's paean to his boyhood pet the
summer version of ``A Christmas Story.'' Filled with the right
mixture of honest sentiment and childhood cruelty, the film is a
tearjerker that earns every sob. Except for the stringy soundtrack,
which tends to trivialize key moments, it's a marvelous evocation
of a Mississippi remembered through rose-colored glasses. The DVD
is special because of the alternate track in which Muniz explains
that the primary dog actor is the son of the terrier that plays
Eddie on ``Frasier'' _ and that the older dog (who plays Skip in
his declining years) didn't get along with his son, so that they
had to be separated. The detailed description of dog training for
the movies is superb, and only increases your appreciation of this
wonderful little picture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: Aug. 15: ``Erin Brockovich'' (DVD), ``It's
the Rage,'' ``Grey Owl,'' ``The Big Brass Ring,'' ``Ghost Dog''
(DVD). Aug. 22: ``The Tigger Movie'' (DVD), ``Mifune.''
</P>
</TEXT>
