<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING ONLINE FOR LEGAL MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody take my money, please.
</P>
<P>
   It all started after the Napster rulings: First a federal judge
shut down the digital music-swapping service, and then an appeals
court stayed the decision. It seemed like a good time to try
Napster alternatives, from programs like Scour Exchange and
Gnutella to relatively untested pay-to-download services that are
starting to emerge from the major record labels.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say upfront that I was willing to pay to play. But nobody
seemed to want to take my (employer's) money.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Blame Canada. But I'll get to that later.
</P>
<P>
   So what to buy? Sony was the first major record label to get
into the digital download business, in May, when it began offering
50 tracks at several online venues, including www.sonymusic.com.
EMI launched a more aggressive offering two weeks ago, selling
digital download versions of 200 singles and 100 albums on the
Internet. And last week, Universal announced plans to sell 60 songs
on a dozen affiliate Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   I decided on David Bowie's ``The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust
and the Spiders From Mars'' (from EMI). After all, Bowie is an
Internet legend in his current incarnation. He was recently honored
at the Yahoo Internet Life! Online Music Awards in New York, and at
53, he looked and sounded so great it made you wonder if there was
an aging picture of him hidden somewhere in a closet next to a
painting of Dorian Gray.
</P>
<P>
   I started my quest at the established online music outlets.
First stop, Amazon.com. They had Bowie CDs, but no digital
downloads. Ditto for CDNow.com. Just for kicks, I ordered the
$13.99 CD from Amazon, paying an extra $9.98 for overnight
delivery. More on that later.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was HMV.com, which features a prominent link to the
EMI downloads right on the home page. Progress! Two clicks later,
and I was ready to make my purchase. Well, sort of. First, you have
to register for the site, filling out the usual statistics. Then
you have to follow ``Four Easy Steps,'' which include downloading a
program called the Music License Manager and the latest version of
the Windows Media Player. Easy enough, if somewhat time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I bought the album for $13.99. But when I tried to get
my music, the site kept telling me that I couldn't access my
``digital wallet'' until I downloaded the Music License Manager and
the Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   After several hours of repeating the ``Four Easy Steps'' about
four dozen times, I called the help line. A very pleasant customer
service representative puzzled with the problem for a minute and
asked, ``Are you outside Canada?'' Well, yes. ``We're not allowed
to sell the downloads to people outside Canada.'' Why? ``It has
something to do with the licensing.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it: Blame Canada.
</P>
<P>
   By this point, I decided to see how long it took to download the
album on Scour Exchange, a Napster clone that is also under fire
from the music industry. It took all of five minutes to locate,
download, and install the software; within 20 minutes, I had MP3
copies of all 11 tracks on the album. I then downloaded Gnutella
and installed the program with relative ease. But the controversial
program doesn't work automatically, like Napster or Scour. Since it
doesn't have a central server, you have to know the address of a
computer already hooked up to the network. D'oh! I finally got an
address from one of the Gnutella sites and did a search for Bowie.
Hours later, I downloaded a copy of ``Suffragette City,'' not
exactly the most efficient way to acquire music. Gnutella, needless
to say, is not likely to become the next big consumer application
any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   But I still really wanted to pay for the album, which led me to
VirginJamcast.com. A few minutes later, I was ready to buy all
tracks for $12.23. Click . . . crash. Every time I tried to buy the
album, my browser crashed. I kept getting the message ``This
program has performed an illegal operation.'' But I was trying to
pay! I wasn't breaking the law! After a few hours and six computer
crashes, I gave up and sent an e-mail off to Virgin customer
service. The next day, I traded several e-mails with a techie named
Michael Griggs, who said that my trouble was probably due to the
fact that I was using Netscape and not Microsoft's Internet
Explorer. I tried Explorer, and bingo, I finally bought my digital
music, a day and a half later. Griggs cheerfully sent me on my way:
``Thanks, and have a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   But who are we kidding here? Even if Napster and Scour were shut
down, nobody in their right mind would spend this much time and
frustration trying to buy digital music online. Lawsuits and
copyright issues aside, the music industry isn't anywhere near
creating a system that customers will embrace; heck, it's hard
enough trying to get them to take your money.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, of course, has earned a good reputation for delivering
the goods. But the CD I ordered didn't arrive the next day. When I
called, an Amazon employee politely explained that sometimes
overnight orders actually take two days; the company also refunded
the overnight charge. But for reasons unclear at press time, the
package still hasn't arrived on my desk. UPS says it was dropped
off at the Globe, but it hasn't been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Internet shopping.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the middle of all this high-tech hassle, I got in my
car and drove to Newbury Comics in Harvard Square. I quickly
located the Bowie section, plunked down my credit card for the
album, and walked away satisfied. It was all so 20th century and
simple _ unless you count the truck that cut me off when I was
trying to park. But that's another story entirely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-TAPESTRIES-2TAKES     08-07 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TAPESTRIES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPESTRIES FIT FOR AN EMPEROR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MECHELEN, Belgium _ Like Linus, the Peanuts character who lugged
his blanket everywhere, Charles V took his textiles on his travels.
Only he couldn't simply toss them over his shoulder. The nine
tapestries in his monumental series called ``Los Honores'' average
25 to 30 feet in length. When you're the Holy Roman Emperor,
though, limits on carry-on baggage needn't apply.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 coincides with the 500th anniversary of the birth
of Charles V, who became emperor at age 19 and who at one point
ruled over territory from Hungary to Peru. Peripatetic, he made 40
foreign journeys during his reign, to points as distant as North
Africa. ``Los Honores'' often went with him, to hang in whatever
palace he happened to occupy. ``Portable frescoes,'' the tapestries
were called.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the celebration of Charles's 500th is the restoration of
``Los Honores,'' which is on view in this lovely Flemish town
through Oct. 8, after which it returns to Spain, the country that
actually owns it. There it will hang in newly created quarters in
the splendor of the Royal Palace in Madrid. It's here, after
considerable diplomatic and financial wrangling between the two
countries, because this is where Charles V grew up, under the
guidance of Margaret of Austria, his aunt. (He couldn't be brought
up by his own mother, Joanna of Castile, because she was both crazy
and, before her final lock-up, preoccupied with trotting her
husband's corpse around Spain.)
</P>
<P>
   The tapestries are also here because this is where they were
restored, at the world-famous De Wit Royal Manufacturers, which the
public can visit. The restoration took a year and wasn't simple. De
Wit had to develop 70 different shades of yellow to match the
different hues already present in the works, so that holes and bare
spots being filled in wouldn't jump out at you visually.
</P>
<P>
   History has been as unkind to Charles as he was to many of his
subjects. He's been accused of bribing and extorting his way to
power. In trying to finance an attempt to stamp out Martin Luther's
Reformation by imposing crushing taxes on Spain, he alienated all
concerned. He was particularly loathed in the proud Flemish city of
Ghent, even though he was born there. Feelings about him in Ghent
still run so high that, although there is a Charles V Street, the
statue of him that once stood there has been removed to a more
remote locale.
</P>
<P>
   Ghent refused Charles the money he wanted to wage war, and he
punished the city by demolishing its Abbey of St. Bavo. He
humiliated prominent citizens by having them beg for mercy while
barefoot and wearing nooses around their necks. Within the thick
walls of Ghent's old castle is a torture museum, filled with the
sort of knickknacks Charles's henchmen would have used:
thumbscrews, fingernail smashers, wrought-iron pin-studded collars,
racks for stretching people while blocking their nostrils and
pouring ice water down their throats.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention that Charles's entourage commissioned ``Los
Honores'' to illustrate the various virtues desirable in a ruler?
Faith, honor, prudence, and justice are among the noble qualities
the tapestries represent; they're a guide to good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In his attempt to conquer the universe, Charles was never
universally loved. So in the foreword to the tome that resulted
from a high-powered scholarly conference on Charles in Brussels
last year, Cas Goossens, chairman of the Flemish Charles V 2000
Committee, wrote that ``as a consequence of the controversy
surrounding Charles V's character, the committee opted to celebrate
not the man but his era.'' Take that.
</P>
<P>
   Charles was born in Belgium, died in Spain, and spent much of
his life commuting between the two. Thousands of art and history
buffs will retrace his routes this summer, as both countries host
exhibitions and events to mark what the Charles V Committee so
delicately calls ``his era.'' During a recent European trek I
checked out as many Chuck sites as I could fit into a tight
schedule. Mechelen, with the tapestries, was the high point, but
there were also surprises like Yuste, in southern Spain, the
middle-of-nowhere Hieronymite monastery Charles chose as his Golden
Age retirement home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tapestry central &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spain may own ``Los Honores,'' but the tapestries were made in
Brussels. What Detroit is to cars and Seattle is to computers,
Brussels was to 16th-century tapestry making. In the year of
Charles's birth, 15,000 of the 40,000 people living in the Belgian
city worked in the tapestry industry. The labor was slow going: A
weaver who worked all day without taking a break could complete a
patch about the size of his hand. Brussels tapestries were
celebrated for their brilliant hues. And with the 1517 arrival in
Brussels of Raphael's cartoons for the ``Acts of the Apostles,'' a
papal commission to be woven in the workshop of Pieter van Aelst,
Renaissance style arrived as well. Classical architecture and
perspective started turning up in tapestries. To accommodate the
new sophistication of imagery came new technical sophistication,
including the increase of the number of warp threads from 7 to 12
per centimeter. This allowed for such subtle effects as depicting
the transparency of water.
</P>
<P>
   A stunning exhibition that shows this evolution is in Brussels's
newly and splendidly restored St. Michael's Cathedral through
September, in honor of the Charles V anniversary. It stars the
so-called Golden tapestries, which, like ``Los Honores,'' were made
in Belgium but are part of the patrimony of Spain. They literally
and figuratively weave together biblical stories and stories of
Charles's family. (My favorite is an ``Annunciation'' with God
sending the news to the Virgin in a letter instead of via the more
common dove: a FedEx instead of carrier pigeon.)
</P>
<P>
   The ``Magna Aula,'' the room in the 12th-century Brussels palace
where Charles abdicated in favor of his son, Philip II, has also
just been reopened. It's underground: Brussels's medieval palace
complex was intentionally demolished to make way for a neoclassical
ensemble erected over the rubble. Those in search of more art from
Charles's era should visit the carved wooden retables in Brussels's
Cinquantenaire Museum, which are studies in horror. One shows St.
George being burned alive, beheaded, beaten, suspended upside down
with his hair set on fire, and otherwise having a tough time. If
you can get past the gore, the carving itself, by an anonymous
artist, is dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of tourist Brussels is its Grand'Place, one of
Europe's most ornate squares, ringed by gabled guild houses and the
Gothic Town Hall, whose stained glass and floor tiles are full of
Charles V's coats of arms and the double-headed eagle that
represented the Hapsburgs. Charles was as eager as a Donna Karan or
Ralph Lauren to stamp his logos on anything and everything. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nine-part masterpiece &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the show here, I'd never been a big tapestry fan. ``Los
Honores'' was a revelation, like encountering the high drama of
Rembrandt's ``Night Watch'' after you've yawned your way past other
Dutch civil militia portraits.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition represents the only time all nine of ``Los
Honores'' have been publicly exhibited outside Spain. One of the
world's greatest tapestry cycles, they, like the ``Acts of the
Apostles,'' were woven in van Aelst's workshop. The exact details
of their commission are lost, despite reams of scholarly research
on them. Charles's court probably commissioned them and provided a
down payment _ which proved insufficient to keep van Aelst afloat.
Deeply in debt, he had to hand them over to his bankers for several
years. Because Charles himself wasn't exactly flush _ his money
went for war _ he couldn't afford to buy them outright until 1526,
when he journeyed to Seville to marry the fabulously rich Isabella
of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Honores'' currently hangs in Mechelen's A. Spinoy Cultural
Center, the only climate-controlled space in town big enough to
hold it. The content of the tapestries is as monumental as their
scale. In all, 336 individuals appear in them, their names woven
into the fabric. Most are mythological characters from ancient
authors like Ovid and Petrarch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-TAPESTRIES-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-07 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TAPESTRIES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MECHELEN, Belgium: ... and Petrarch.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything about the exhibition is exquisitely done and
visitor-friendly, starting with the introductory video on the
tapestries' restoration, with before-and-after views that show how
filthy they were. (In the palace of La Granja near Segovia, their
former home, they were not only dirty but badly lit: You could
argue that no one's really seen them properly for a century or
more.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside the show, there's a window cut into a wall so you can see
the back of one tapestry, which is a mass of tangled threads, a
fascinating contrast with the meticulous front. The excellent
catalog by Guy Delmarcel is available in English. There's a superb
audio guide that virtually everyone but a scholar like Delmarcel
would be lost without. It comes in several languages, including
English, and if you listen to every bit of it, it takes an hour and
a half. (It's the random-access kind, so you can pick and choose.)
</P>
<P>
   The tapestries themselves are quintessential cases of horror
vacuui, crammed not only with figures but with elaborate
architectural settings. The subjects _ ``Fortune,'' ``Prudence,''
``Virtue,'' ``Faith,'' ``Honor,'' ``Fame,'' ``Justice,''
``Nobility,'' and ``Infamy'' _ are complex allegories, mixing
Christian and classical themes. The figures are dressed in
Renaissance attire, the equivalent of Shakespeare in modern dress.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the works dazzle, suggesting sumptuous textures
including marble, wood grain, ermine, and satin. However crowded,
the compositions are also supremely graceful, and the gestures of
the individual figures read as authentic and compelling. The use of
gold thread is so liberal the tapestries shimmer. (The gold came
dearly: Each tapestry cost half what Charles would pay for a
galleon.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Fortune,'' the blindfolded goddess scatters roses with one
hand and stones with the other, illustrating the unpredictability
of fate. By the time you get to ``Virtue,'' Fortune has been tamed,
chained between Temperance and Fortitude. Temperance wears a bridle
in her mouth and holds a clock, indication that she speaks
moderately and organizes her time well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith'' is, by contemporary standards, politically incorrect.
She holds Moses' tablets and the model of a church, while trampling
on Mohammed, who is cast as both infidel and military threat.
``Honor'' conducts a tribunal, with the righteous decorously
ascending to the podium as sinners try in vain to claw their way
up.
</P>
<P>
   On the right-hand side of ``Infamy,'' the final work and one
that uses Cain's murder of Abel as metaphor for all the sin of the
world to come, sits a figure identified as ``Author.'' He's
presumably the man who has written the whole program of the series.
He's just blown out his candle, which is still smoking. His labor,
which has resulted in one of history's most majestic and ambitious
tapestry cycles, is finished. His identity is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Los Honores'' stands to have a great economic impact on
this city, residents are hardly Charles-boosters, fully aware that
the emperor often failed to follow the guidance the tapestries lay
out so vividly. A student art show in the Minderbroeders Church,
coinciding with the ``Los Honores'' exhibition, includes a big,
gridded collage that combines the faces of Charles V, Chilean
dictator Augusto Pinochet, and Pope Pius XII, who failed to oppose
the Nazis publicly during World War II. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Charles's imprint &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles ruled Spain, but spent more time out of the country than
in it. But signs of his presence there abound. Madrid's Prado
Museum, for instance, owns an abundance of portraits of Charles and
his family, their trademark horsey Hapsburg faces staring out at
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hapsburg-ized existing architecture in Spain, making the
buildings blocky and big, and adding slate roofs. His Spanish
capital was Toledo, an austere city atop a mammoth granite
escarpment: On one of its main gates is the double-headed eagle.
(The major traveling ``Charles V'' exhibition that opened in Ghent
and is in Vienna through Sept. 10 then moves to Toledo's Museo de
Santa Cruz.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1557, the year before his death, Charles was carried over the
mountains of Estremadura in a coffinlike litter that is still on
display at his final destination, the monastery of Yuste. His
modest suite of rooms at Yuste is cool and dark; among the original
furnishings is a chair built with an extended footrest to ease his
gout. His bedroom opens onto the high altar of the church, so he
could stay in bed and see and hear Mass. After he died, he was
buried under the altar, as he'd commanded. He'd meant to stay in
this small stone church for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   But 17 years after his death, son Philip had Charles's body
moved to the stark grandeur of the new El Escorial Monastery, 30
miles from Madrid. A vast rectangle with 16 courtyards, it was
modeled after the grill on which San Lorenzo was martyred. Cheerful
it's not. Among its glories is its barrel-vaulted, fresco-covered
library, repository of 40,000 rare books and manuscripts. Among its
grimmest and gaudiest interior spaces is the round marble crypt
whose walls are lined with elaborate bronze and marble sarcophagi
on shelves, a scene that reminded me of the slots-with-beds that
Japanese businessmen rent when they're too tired to make it home.
In the sarcophagi are buried the kings of Spain _ including Charles
V, who, for all his might while alive, wasn't allowed to remain in
the ``final'' resting place he chose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
For information on this year's Charles V events in Belgium, visit
the Web site www.charlesV2000.org. The Charles V telephone number,
in Belgium, is 011-32-70-233-888. English-speaking helpers are
available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
For information on Spain, visit www.okspain.org, or call the
toll-free number 888-657-7246.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
