<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-COMMENT-ROCK-BOS &LR;      08-07 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNLIBERAL CHRIS ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's ``bigger and blacker.'' He's funnier than ever. But, for a
prominent member of the entertainment community in America today,
he's got some unorthodox political views.
</P>
<P>
   That Chris Rock speaks with the authority of a star is beyond
dispute. He went huge in 1996 with the Home Box Office special
``Bring the Pain.'' Now he's got a regular HBO gig, not to mention
his occasional appearances on ``Saturday Night Live,'' from which
he graduated. Last year, HBO broadcast his latest blockbuster
hourlong show from the legendary Apollo Theater in New York, and
has been replaying it frequently since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger and Blacker'' is profane, adult-only material that is
convulsively funny and, regarding racial and cultural divisions
within the country, extraordinarily perceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's views are also _ as he has alternately resisted or
grudgingly acknowledged in interviews _ not only politically
incorrect but also very un-liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a slithery black Ralph Lauren suit, Rock opens the
show saying he is terrified of going into white suburban high
schools these days because he's afraid of getting shot. What's
wrong with these young white kids? He's perplexed that pundits
wonder what music those kids have been listening to, what movies
they've seen.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the music and movies, he says (or words to that effect).
``Whatever happened to `crazy'?'' he demands. ``Did we eliminate
the word `crazy' from the dictionary?''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a concept: holding individuals responsible for their
own harmful acts and antisocial behavior _ rather than blaming
society, the media, and the low self-esteem that society has
allegedly inflicted on them.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the conservative agenda of Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of other examples, but first a word of caution.
The language in Rock's show is not something you would associate
with conservatives, or polite liberals either. Unless perhaps
you're referring to the extreme libertarian variety, those who
would preach that everybody should pretty much set his or her own
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched ``Bigger and Blacker'' several times, I couldn't
bring myself to do it again just to count the offensive words. But,
in the first 10 minutes, I counted the S-word five times, the
MF-word once, and the F-word 33 times. I let the H-words and the
A-words go.
</P>
<P>
   Rock is not running for president, and the people who go to his
shows or listen on cable TV know what they're getting. His is a
street-language schtick that is entirely in the tradition of club
comics, especially those deconstructors of existing mores such as
Lenny Bruce or George Carlin. Or, for that matter, most of the rap
music groups performing today.
</P>
<P>
   The language, in fact, may be just outrageous enough to make
those conservative ideas of Rock's palatable to some who might
otherwise dismiss them. Like his view of the behavior of some
single moms.
</P>
<P>
   What are they doing ``in a club at 2 in the morning on a
Wednesday night?'' Rock asks. ``Go take care of those kids before
they rob me in 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Or: ``If the kid calls the grandma Mom and the mommy Pam, the
kid's going to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock's views of the state of male-female relations today is
wickedly frank. Reducing almost everything to sex, he blames
Hillary Clinton more than the president for the Monica Lewinsky
scandal _ for, shall we say, not being there when Bill needed her.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of this is just for laughs, of course. It's comedy, not
Poli-Sci 101. But at its core, a surprising amount of his on-stage
rant, if distilled into serious public policy, would please the
right and offend the left.
</P>
<P>
   Rock started down this road in his controversial 1996 HBO
special, when he addressed the use of the N-word, the way it is
employed by some blacks. ``A black man that got two jobs, going to
work every day, hates a (expletive) on welfare. `Get a job! I got
two. You can't get one?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by the Commercial Appeal newspaper of Memphis since then
whether he wasn't showing Republican stripes, Rock said, ``I'm no
puppet for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a Pittsburgh Post-Gazette interview, he had bought at
least partway into the description. Asked whether he wasn't
``pretty conservative,'' Rock said, ``I'm not really political . .
. in a political sense, but in a social sense maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't ``social'' right where a lot of conservative concerns rest
today?
</P>
<P>
   And he told the San Diego Union-Tribune that, on core
conservative issues of law and order, family values, and individual
responsibility, ``I consider these to be common-sense issues. These
are not black and white isues, liberal or conservative issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because you don't put the conservative label on yourself
doesn't mean you don't hold those beliefs. Rock seems to dislike
the term because he doesn't like the way either established
political party addresses race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with Democrats is that they treat us like we're
kids,'' Rock told the Union-Tribune. ``But the Republicans really
don't give a (expletive) about us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my humble opinion,'' he concluded, ``most working-class
blacks are very conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to race and ethnic issues, he adopts the position
of enlightened conservatives _ not the anti-immigrant wing _ and
teaches inclusion, tolerance, and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to hate nobody,'' Rock advises.
``Whoever you hate will end up in your family. You don't like
Puerto Ricans? Your daughter will come home `Livin' La Vida
Loca'!''
</P>
<P>
   If congressman Rick Lazio stumbles between now and November, the
New York GOP may want to consider Rock as a Senate candidate,
considering his stand on taxes. ``One thing Clinton did I didn't
like _ raise taxes,'' he says. ``You don't even `pay' taxes. They
`take' taxes. You get your paycheck _ they're gone. That ain't a
payment, that's a `jack.' As in `hijack.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rock is shrewd enough and funny enough, and now successful
enough, that he can even take on America's black leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need a new leader,'' he says. ``We ain't had a
black leader in a while _ somebody that moves you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Martin Luther King, Malcolm X, and ever since then, a
bunch of substitute teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock says the problem with Louis Farrakhan, the Nation of Islam
leader, is that nobody's ever been in a barber shop and heard black
people sitting around talking about disliking Jews. ``You know who
I think the black leader should be?'' Rock says. ``Pat Riley. Coach
Pat Riley. No man has led more black men to the promised land than
Coach Pat Riley.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's another person out there that nobody's thought of.
He's a 34-year-old black comedian who seems to be in touch with a
lot of black people, if not with most of the Hollywood and black
political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   He'd have to do something about that language first.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas C. Palmer Jr. is a Globe staff member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
