<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GENDER-BOYS-BOS &LR;      08-07 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENDER-BOYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE BETRAYS ANGER, UNCERTAINTY OVER GIRLS `FAVORED' STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The debate has sent academics into on-air tirades, pitted
conservatives against liberals with increasing venom, and unleashed
a storm of shrill sparring around the country.
</P>
<P>
   It's the next chapter of the gender wars: the battle over
whether feminist academics, upset over a longstanding bias against
girls, have managed to tilt the balance so far that today's focus
on girls has come at the expense of boys.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives see evidence everywhere. Exhibit A: In 1999, the
Columbine High School massacre became the defining event for boys,
while the World Cup victory of the US women's soccer team
symbolized the spirit of the nation's girls.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the academic attack is Christina Hoff Sommers, an
anti-feminist philosophy professor at Clark University in
Worcester, a fellow at a conservative Washington think tank, and
mother of two boys. Throwing down the gauntlet in her new book,
``The War Against Boys,'' she mows down a host of academics she
charges with imposing girls' values on boys, engaging in shoddy
scholarship, and confusing a thesis with reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been societies that favored boys over
girls,'' Sommers said in an interview promoting her book. ``Ours
may be the first to deliberately throw the gender switch by
preferring girls. Little boys have become politically incorrect. .
. . Our society wars against boys when it views and treats the
normal behavior of young boys as wrong and in need of curing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommers cites a raft of statistics to support her view that boys
have not enjoyed academic favoritism. They include that boys trail
girls in reading and writing, girls take more Advanced Placement
tests than boys and more frequently enroll in college, and girls
read more books and outperform boys in art and music tests.
</P>
<P>
   Her critics say Sommers falls victim to many of her own charges.
They consider her academic sniping crude and misleading, her
conclusions akin to historical revisionism, and her work a harsh
diatribe that does little more than expand on her previous
feminist-thrashing book, ``Who Stole Feminism?: How Women Have
Betrayed Women.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Sommers's main targets is William Pollack, an assistant
professor of clinical psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and
co-director of the Center for Men at McLean Hospital in Belmont,
Mass. Pollack, author of the best-selling ``Real Boys: Rescuing Our
Sons from the Myths of Boyhood,'' agrees with Sommers that boys are
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But he does not believe that favoring girls accounts for boys'
current difficulties. And, unlike Sommers, who urges society to
encourage boys to be stoic, serious, and what some would call
typically masculine, Pollack prefers boys be liberated from macho
stereotypes and feel free to express their emotions. Sommers argues
that Pollack's prescription for helping boys only hurts them
further because it ``feminizes'' them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is she doesn't know anything about boys, she has
no training in the area,'' Pollack said in an interview. ``The only
way to make boys more feminine is to give them estrogen. I'm not
suggesting that. I'm just trying to remove the gender
straitjacket.''
</P>
<P>
   The two recently squared off on National Public Radio's ``Talk
of the Nation.'' And it didn't take long for the professors to
start swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers: ``I don't think that children need to be liberated from
gender roles . . . (and) I do not like the idea of calling them a
nation of Hamlets or our girls' `drowning Ophelias.' That's
absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack: ``I haven't called them Hamlets or Ophelias. In fact,
though, I've actually looked at boys . . . in my study in ``Real
Boys . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Sommers: ``Where did you publish this study?''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Williams, the show's host: ``Well, look, I don't want you
two to be snapping at each other. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack: ``I'm not trying to snap at all. I'm trying to talk
about boys. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Sommers: ``No, no. You did call them Hamlets in your book, and
you said they live in an inner state of Denmark. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The bickering between Sommers and her academic adversaries
carries on into the August edition of The Atlantic Monthly, which
in May published an 11-page excerpt from the ``The War Against
Boys.'' The magazine received more than 100 letters _ both critical
and admiring _ which was more than almost any story in the managing
editor's memory had garnered.
</P>
<P>
   Of those published, the first is from Carol Gilligan, a prolific
author on girls and a gender-studies professor at Harvard's
Graduate School of Education. Sommers dubs her ``the matron saint
of the girl-crisis movement,'' and spends most of her book
attacking Gilligan, criticizing her methods and pounding her ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan, in her letter to The Atlantic and in a recent
interview, dismisses Sommers's work as more character assassination
than academic acumen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sommers not only is inaccurate but also misses the larger
point and finds controversy where none exists,'' Gilligan writes.
``. . . It's sad that Sommers squanders the opportunity to open a
constructive dialogue on our differences of opinion and
interpretation and chooses instead to publish an inaccurate, ad
hominem attack that can lead nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Sommers's targets is David Sadker, author of
``Failing at Fairness: How America's Schools Cheat Girls.'' Among
other complaints, she takes the American University professor to
task for his ``call-out'' gap study, which found boys in class call
out more often than girls, while girls are more often scolded for
not raising their hand. Sommers accuses Sadker of exaggerating and
distorting the problem. The real issue, she believes, is that boys
are less attentive.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gilligan and Pollack, Sadker suggests Sommers is more
interested in her agenda than the evidence. She ignores a host of
facts showing girls continue to lag behind boys, he says. While
girls have made progress, they continue to trail boys on
college-entry exams, including the SAT, ACT, and GRE, and though
they take more AP tests, they score lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it may serve a political purpose to cast our work as
`boys against girls,' '' he wrote in a letter to The Atlantic,
``the truth is (his wife, a researcher) and I dedicated our
professional lives to battling sexist assumptions that wound both
our daughters and our sons. It is bias we oppose, not boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the rebuttals in stride, Sommers believes the backlash is
all part of the ebb tide against her anti-establishment views.
</P>
<P>
   She accuses Sadker, Gilligan, and others of belatedly paying
attention to boys' deficiencies, after her book came out. And she
gives short shrift to groups such as the American Association of
University Women, which she believes only now speaks
``ecumenically'' about improving schooling ``for all children.''
</P>
<P>
   If all the back-and-forth seems like nonsense or unnecessarily
incendiary to the public, it doesn't to Pollack or Sommers. While
both believe boys need help, their prescriptions remain at odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not calling for a revolution,'' Sommers said. ``Gender
equity has tended to mean helping girls. I'm just trying to draw
attention to boys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
