<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-STEPP-BOS &LR;      08-07 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STEPP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW WAY OF THINKING ABOUT OUR EARLY ADOLESCENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
OUR LAST BEST SHOT 
Guiding Our Children Through Early Adolescence 
By Laura Sessions Stepp. Riverhead Books. 359 pp. $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When our children are little, there are scores of books to help
us evaluate and navigate the joys and perils of parenting. The
older they get, however, the more the list of books worth reading
shrinks. No wonder that good ones _ ``Reviving Ophelia,'' ``Real
Boys,'' ``Raising Cain'' _ rise quickly to best-selling status;
we're starved for the sustenance they offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Last Best Shot: Guiding Our Children Through Early
Adolescence,'' by Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist Laura Sessions
Stepp, belongs on the shelf with them. This book isn't just
well-researched and insightful, it's a page-turner.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, maybe only if you have a 10- to 15-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Those five years have always been mysterious and confounding for
parents. Young adolescents are frequently moody and sullen, quick
to lash out for no discernible reason. Add to that the violent,
consumer-driven, anything-goes nature of our times, and being a
parent of a young adolescent is downright scary. Stepp, who writes
about family issues for The Washington Post and has a young teen
herself, acknowledges all this in a tone that is somehow
no-nonsense and sympathetic at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, she us offers hope.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the stupid things young teens do are things they are
supposed to do, she tells us: They are hard-wired to do them, they
can't help themselves. In other words, it's nothing personal, Mom
and Dad. Recognizing that alone can ease our burden and make us
more open to finding ways to communicate with our child rather than
be stuck in a rut critizing her. Stepp is so confident that we can
help our children come out the other end of these years safely and
sanely that she predicts, ``Our kids will one day become our
friends, unlike any we will ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sigh.)
</P>
<P>
   Sign me up.
</P>
<P>
   Stepp focuses on these years partly because she was stumped by
changes in her own 11-year-old son, partly because her research
showed that the 10- to 15-year-old has needs far different from
those of older adolescents and shouldn't be lumped together in
books about them. (She's not the first to make this distinction;
Charlene C. Giannetti and Margaret Sagarese in ``The Roller-Coaster
Years'' expertly examine these years, too, but with more of a
``how-to'' emphasis.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Best'' is divided into four sections that reflect the
overarching, developmental questions the 10- to 15-year-old
grapples with: What kind of person am I? How do I/Do I fit in with
my friends? Am I learning? How can I separate from adults but still
be connected to them?
</P>
<P>
   The topics come alive with the stories of 12 young people Stepp
met and virtually lived with in three refreshingly different but
still representative communities: South Central Los Angeles;
Ulysses, Kan.; and Durham, N.C. These are real people, not
composites (although their real names are not used), and they offer
not only a cross-section of academic performance but also of race,
family structure, and economic background. Don't be put off if you
don't see your child reflected exactly in one individual or
another. There's a good chance you will see a little bit of her
here, a little bit of him there. There were many places where I saw
myself, my husband, or my son, many pages I marked in the margin
with exclamation points so I could return to a particulary
elucidating thought.
</P>
<P>
   How often, for instance, have you heard and used the term ``peer
pressure''? See if you don't undertand it better after reading this
passage: ``Rebekah (a mother) did not say that Libby's friends were
a bad influence. She understood that peer pressure is misnamed,
that teens who drink or smoke usually do not stand over their more
reluctant friends coaxing them to join in. What they do is convey a
sense of fun and relaxation, and the young person who wants the
others to like her, who knows of no other way to unwind, or who
simply wants to try something new and forbidden, may be inclinded
to experiment. . . . Peer pressure, then, is really `me pressure,'
stress the child imposes on herself.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a blueprint for parenting, complete with
bulleted how-to points, this book will disappoint. (The closest it
comes is a ``To Do'' summary at the end of each chapter.) But Stepp
is not bashful about praising or damning parents of her subjects,
and it is often in these judgments that she helps us dispel
stereotypes that can miscolor our own efforts to rear children. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   --On hanging out at malls: ``The real problem with shopping
malls is not, as many parents suppose, that other young people will
be there whom the parent may not know, or that kids together get in
trouble.'' What we need to worry about, she writes, are the
``acquisitive, sometimes vulgar values that some stores parade in
front of kids who are just beginning to think about what kind of
people they want to become.''
</P>
<P>
   --On sex: ``Talking about the physical and emotional
implications of sex will not cause a child to run out and
experiment, as many parents fear. Neither will explaining one's own
feelings and values in very specific terms such as `I want you to
wait until you're married.' . . . Kids hate `The Big Talk,' but
they are hungry for good advice on how to say `no' and how to
manage emotional relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   --On getting a job: ``Parents are often reluctant to allow kids
to take outside jobs, either volunteer or for pay, for fear that
their studies will suffer. . . . We need to keep in mind that
collaborating on a job with a responsible adult may do more for a
kid's self-esteem, study habits, and manners than playing a
mediocre game of soccer. Jobs give kids lots of practice at making
decisions in a structured environment. Volunteer work is better for
most kids this age than a paying job and often appeals to their
newfound idealism.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest it sound as if Stepp is simply spouting off, her reporting
is documented throughout, and her conclusions are thoroughly
supported by research she cites in the text and in the extensive
notes and bibliography. Her essential message is not stunning in
its originality. Indeed, we've heard it all before: We need to be
acute listeners and astute observers of our young teens and, most
important, we need to stay in touch with them.
</P>
<P>
   What Stepp does offer is a new way of thinking about our 10- to
15-year-olds, and a new way of thinking about ourselves as parents
of these unique creatures. Staying in touch, for instance, doesn't
mean talking at our teens, which is what passes for communication
in most of our homes (even though we may not realize it), but
talking with them, especially asking them questions in a way that
gets them thinking. It means talking to other people about them: to
their teachers, their coaches, their peers, and the parents of
their peers. And it means showing our values and our thinking not
only through our words, but also through our actions.
</P>
<P>
   For a snapshot of what that means, read the last two pages of
``Our Last Best Shot.'' As the mother of a 12-year-old smack in the
middle of this journey, I found they brought tears to my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz is the parenting columnist for the Globe and
author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes: Understanding How Your
Children See the World.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
