<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ONAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 STIRRING THE EMBERS OF THE HARTFORD FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Stewart O'Nan is in the lobby of the State
Armory, spreading out photographs taken there during the late
afternoon and evening of July 6, 1944. That was when this was the
temporary morgue where people came to identify the bodies of women,
children, and a few men, killed that day when the celebrated ``big
top'' became a deadly firetrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circus Fire,'' O'Nan's account of the Hartford circus fire,
has just been published, but after immersing himself in the story
for the past five years, O'Nan has come to regard himself as a
``custodian'' of the memories of survivors and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On this day he uses old photographs to plot the route by which
family members, accompanied by a police officer and a nurse, walked
upstairs from the lobby to the drill floor where the bodies of 135
victims had been taken. Another 32 people died at local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still putting the pieces together,'' O'Nan says. ``That
interest in trying to figure out what happened and how it happened
is still with me.''
</P>
<P>
   On the drill floor, where several young women are setting up
displays for an Italian wine trade show, O'Nan leads the way down
its 269-foot length to the back wall. When family members arrived,
he says, ``they had to walk the whole length, all the way back to
where the bodies were.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several racks of folding chairs against the back wall
and that is where O'Nan talks about the fire and his role as its
custodian. ``We're sitting,'' he says, ``right where the bodies
were laid out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fire apparently started in a men's room behind the
grandstand. The cause remains a mystery, but once the fire started,
flames spread quickly up the canvas tent, fueled by its paraffin
waterproofing.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Nan describes those moments, ``Inside, the band played `The
Stars and Stripes Forever' over and over, as if the sound might
calm people knocked through the bleachers or buried under chairs,''
O'Nan writes. The master of ceremonies ``pleaded with the people in
the east end to leave through the side flaps, but they all clotted
helplessly at the bandstand exits. Children fainted in the crush.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the while, the fire was crossing the top of the tent. It
spread like a grass fire, a haystack fire, a giant orange wave.
Central Connecticut residents were familiar with shade tobacco
tents, how a blaze on the sheer canopies could outrun the fastest
man; it was like that.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, rescue workers began removing the bodies.
Brown Thomson's department store sent a delivery van to help move
them to the morgue being set up at the armory. The teenage shipping
room worker, O'Nan writes, remembered that many of the bodies ``lay
on stretchers, uncovered, frozen in grotesque positions.'' A man
told him that ``he'd tried to pick up a body and his hands had gone
through the flesh, right down to the bone. The bone was hot and
he'd burned his hand, jerking back as if he'd touched a hot
stone.''
</P>
<P>
   With his boss, the young worker lifted the bodies into the
truck, then headed downtown to the armory, ``trying not to think of
what was bumping in the back at every turn.''
</P>
<P>
   At the armory, ``searchers wandered solemnly through the cots,
handkerchiefs and ammonia-soaked gauze clutched to their noses.
State troopers in pith helmets and uniformed nurses bracketed them,
ready to step in,'' O'Nan writes. ``All it took was a blackened
piece of jewelry, a missing incisor, an appendectomy scar. One
little girl had cut her palm that morning, and her father had fixed
it with a Band-Aid. Her clenched fist still cupped the bandage.
Otherwise she was unrecognizable, her clothing burned away except
for her black patent leather shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims was a young girl, dead, but barely touched by
the flames, who became known as Little Miss 1565 (in reference to
her identification number at the site), who remains unidentified to
this day. Another young girl, a young boy, and three women also
remain unidentified, most likely because misidentified bodies were
buried in their place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Nan is 39, a Boston University-trained
engineer-turned-novelist. He lives in Avon, just west of Hartford,
with his wife, Trudy _ who was working as a Red Cross disaster
specialist much of the time he was researching the circus fire _
and their two children. It was moving five years ago to teach at
Hartford's Trinity College that spurred him to turn his attention
to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   A decade earlier, while researching his novel ``A World Away,''
O'Nan had come across the searing photograph of the clown Emmett
Kelly, covering his eyes as he lugs a bucket of water across the
circus grounds with a small tent burning in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The image stayed with him and after moving to Avon, O'Nan looked
for a book on the fire only to find there was none, other than
several ``based-on'' novels and a study of lawsuits against the
circus by two Yale Law School professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't make sense,'' O'Nan recalls thinking. ``So I guess
I ended up writing the book I wanted to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had already written five well-regarded novels, O'Nan
never thought of fictionalizing the story of the circus fire. ``It
had already become a kind of legend, with stories that were
overlapping and contradictory,'' O'Nan says. ``It deserved only the
most stringent, very best intentions of nonfiction.'' Turning the
story into fiction, he felt, might cheapen it.
</P>
<P>
   Having decided that, O'Nan had a model in mind, David
McCullough's ``The Johnstown Flood.'' He admired the account of the
impact of a disaster on a community and also felt a kinship with
McCullough because they attended the same elementary school, albeit
a quarter-century apart, in Pittsburgh's Point Breeze neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take the same approach as he did,'' O'Nan says.
``I wanted to show the connectedness of history, how it affects
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As O'Nan began researching the story of the circus fire, a
half-century after the tragedy, he quickly discovered that it is
``a story that endures in Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seemed to have a memory,'' O'Nan says. ``As I began
talking to people about the fire, it seemed that everybody knew
somebody who had been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the survivors were children who would be in their late
50s and early 60s today. ``So I'd have somebody who'd remember that
a neighbor's daughter had burn scars on her legs,'' O'Nan says.
Many of the witnesses, police officers, firefighters, doctors, and
nurses, are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The effect the fire had on the community was far different from
that of Boston's Cocoanut Grove Fire almost two years earlier. Many
of the nightclub's 492 victims were college students and
servicemen, while virtually all the victims of the circus fire were
local people, with relatives, childhood playmates, and classmates
still living around Hartford today.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed with the memories of tragedy, O'Nan was surprised to find
``a kind of nostalgia,'' he says. ``Not so much for the fire, but
for how the city was back then, how the neighborhoods were.''
</P>
<P>
   Although O'Nan still hears from survivors and witnesses, he is
deep into two new projects. He is ``468 pages into a very long
novel,'' he says, and finishing up another novel set in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I don't have to write nonfiction again for a while,''
he says. ``It's too hard. You can't make stuff up. You can't fake
it. You can't spin it. You have to take it as it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
