<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-GORE (Washington) _ In tapping Joseph Lieberman, the
first orthodox Jewish member of the U.S. Senate, as the nation's
first Jewish vice presidential nominee, Al Gore raises many
questions. We look at whether an overwhelmingly Christian
electorate will vote for a non-Christian, whether Lieberman will
help Hillary Clinton in New York and whether his strong criticisms
of President Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky scandal will help Gore.
By MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ By choosing to run for the White
House with Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Vice President Al
Gore came about as close as he decently could to poking President
Clinton in the eye. Lieberman, a senior Democratic legislator of
impeccable personal integrity, was the party's most thoughtful _
and most devastating _ critic of Clinton's moral lapse during his
affair with Monica Lewinsky. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
