Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-CLEANUP (Washington) _ The National Academy of Sciences
says that most nuclear weapons sites can not be cleaned up and that
so far the Department of Energy does not know how to isolate and
monitor them. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-FISH (Leland, Mich.) _ After 25 years of legal
wrangling, six Indian tribes are to sign a treaty with the federal
government under which the Indians would be compensated for phasing
out their use of gill nets, traps that killed large numbers of
fish. The traps have angered non-Indian residents, who say the have
caused a decline in fish in the Great Lakes and snarled outboard
engines. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-WAHID (Jakarta) _ President Abdurrahman Wahid
apologized for falling short of expectations in his first 10 months
in office and that he would name an executive minister to bring
order to his flailing administration. In a state-of-the nation
speech that opened a restive annual parliamentary session, Wahid
said he would concentrate more on foreign affairs and create a sort
of prime ministerial post to handle day-to-day running of the
government. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-KOHLER (Washington) _ Horst Kohler, the new director of the
International Monetary Fund, presents a plan to narrow the lending
agency's functions and to limit its interference in the policies of
developing countries. His speech at the National Press Club will be
his first major on-the-record address since he became director in
May. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Seoul, South Korea) _ Alarmed over the slow pace of
economic reforms in South Korea, President Kim Dae-jung replaces
his finance minister and seven other senior financial officials as
part of a broad Cabinet shakeup. The move comes as concern grows
over the debts of South Korea's biggest conglomerate, the Hyundai
Group. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSEN-SPLIT (Undated) _ An international arbitrator has split
up the accounting firm Arthur Andersen and its sister consulting
firm, Andersen Consulting, ending a a long, bitterly fought
dispute. Under the ruling, Andersen Consulting, the world's biggest
consulting firm, must give up the Andersen name and pay $1 billion
to the partners of Arthur Andersen. Anderson Consulting, however,
could have been liable for a breakup fee of as much as $14 billion
under the contract between the two firms. The arbitrator blames the
breakup on Arthur Andersen, whose chief executive, James Wadia,
quits after the ruling. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SMALL-SHOPS (Machida City, Japan) _ When it comes to
mom-and-pop stores, deregulation in Japan is hitting a roadblock
after a decade of change. Business associations, citizens groups
and ordinary Japanese that sat quietly as deregulation made banking
more convenient, liberalized the sale of gasoline and led to an
explosion in advanced wireless telephones are now rallying as
barriers that protect the shotengai, or local shopping street,
fall. Shopkeepers have traditionally been the backbone of the
Japanese neighborhood. They organize festivals that make the long,
sticky summers here tolerable. They are active in school affairs
and community sports. Shopkeepers lack the financial resources of
big corporations like N.T.T., says Hiroshi Yamada, the mayor of
Suginami ward in Tokyo, ``but the local shop owners can collect
something even more valuable: votes.'' By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ Watching developments in the strike
against Verizon Communications. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-WIRELESS (Undated) _ Looking at what the labor dispute
may mean for telecommunications companies with unionized work
forces. Will wireless upstarts like VoiceStream Communications
obtain a huge advantage? By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ASSOCIATES (Undated) _ Computer Associates
International says that it will spin off its software and services
businesses, and that it will later spin off its desktop accounting
business and some other technology operations. The company also
says that its chief operating officer, Sanjay Kumar will become
chief executive, replacing Charles Wang, who will remain chairman.
By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   BA-EARNINGS (London) _ British Airways says first-quarter
earnings fell 65 percent, hurt by higher fuel costs and the
strength of the British pound. The airline also says that merger
talks with KLM are continuing. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVISION-RESIGN (Undated) _ Univision Communications says Henry
Cisneros has resigned as president and chief operating officer to
help form a residential building concern. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins
``Public Interests.''
</P>
