<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     08-07 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Aug. 8:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NILE-VIRUS (Undated) _ West Nile virus appears to be
settling in for the long haul. More slowly than expected, but
steadily, the mosquito-transmitted virus is dispersing from last
year's focal point in northern Queens in New York, leaving a trail
of dead birds that so far extends north to Boston, west to
Syracuse, and south to Maryland. According to virus experts, this
pattern indicates that West Nile, which was first identified in
Uganda in 1937 and flares up sporadically in Africa, Europe, and
the Middle East, appears ensconced in the New World. Many
scientists expect that a scattering of human infections and a few
deaths may well become the norm in years to come. Still, these
experts say, the disease appears unlikely to become a significant
threat to public health. By Andrew C. Revkin. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICS-BIAS (Undated) _ Despite its image of arcane
intellectuality, particle physics is fast becoming a field with
plenty of heart-pounding, high-stakes suspense. The reasons lie not
so much in the field's recent string of discoveries as in how some
of them were made. Several large, multinational teams of particle
physicists, who design experiments to capture, measure and
understand the most elementary building blocks of matter, have
adopted an analysis technique that may best be compared to walking
a tightrope while blindfolded. The problem is bias, and it plagues
all realms of scientific experimentation. Recently, somewhat in the
spirit of biomedicine, research teams in particle physics have been
programming their computers to add unknown numbers, called
``offsets,'' to their data to make the outcome of their analyses
blind. When an experiment is over, the researchers open their
metaphorical sealed envelopes and discover what the value of the
offset is _ learning only then whether they are close to a routine
confirmation of theory, a Nobel Prize or a humiliating mistake. By
James Glanz. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CULTURE-THOUGHT (Undated) _ A series of studies comparing
European Americans to East Asias found people who grow up in
different cultures did not just think about different things, they
also think differently. Easterners appear to think more
holistically, paying greater attention to context and relationship,
relying more on experience-based knowledge than abstract logic, and
showing more tolerance for contradiction. Westerners are more
analytic in their thinking, tending to detach objects from their
context, to avoid contradictions, and to rely more heavily on
formal logic. By Erica Goode. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRENNER-DNA (Undated) _ A conversation With Dr. Charles
Brenner, 55, one of the world's first fully-employed free-lance
mathematicians, who has invented DNA software and discusses famous
DNA cases and issues. By Claudia Dreifus. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PORTUGAL-DINOSAURS (Lisbon) _ The Portugese government is
acting to protect the country's rich array of dinosaur fossils and
tracks, which are being threatened by erosion and development.
There are at least 20 Jurassic sites with sauropod track ways in
Portugal, along with more than 100 discovered eggs and dinaosaur
fragments. The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization, (Unesco) plan on naming a Portuguese site as a
Geoparque, which is a classification created last year for the
protection of natural resources. By Marvine Howe. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
Asian giant honeybee nest sites which were found to be occupied
year after year by swarms related to the hive, the Hubble Space
Telescope caught the comet Linear literally breaking up early in
July, and researchers had mapped the structure of the protein
rhodopsin, which functions in the retina. By Henry Fountain. (700
words).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRESBYOPIA (Undated) _ Scientists are still not sure exactly
what causes presbyopia (the inability for eyes to focus up close,
which affects people around the age of 50 and causes them to need
reading glasses) or what might reverse it. And for the last five
years they have been arguing heatedly over the risks and merits of
an experimental surgical procedure, scheral expansion surgery,
that, despite a host of scientific objections, appears to fix it.
By Abigail Zuger, M.D. (1550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYEGLASSES Undated) _ Historians say the first eyeglasses
were probably made by monks. George Washington once paid the
outlandish sum of $75 for a pain with hinges. And other facts and
theories on the history of glasses. By Clara Hemphill. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column:
Contrary to widespread belief, irritable bowel syndrome is a real
condition and not a psychosomatic disorder. The syndrome is
believed to stem from abnormal nerve connections between the brain
and gut. Exercise, diet and stress reduction are recommended. By
Jane E. Brody. (1220 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TESTES-CANCER (Undated) _ The Cases column: A young man with
testicular cancer, which is the most common solid tumor in men aged
15 to 34. The incidence has been rising worldwide, and in the
United States 7,000 to 8,000 new cases are diagnosed every year.
Like most cancers, it used to be a death sentence; today, with
advances in chemotherapy, it has a cure rate of 90 percent. By
Sandeep Jauhar (880 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Circulation journal reports today that blacks who have had
heart attacks are less likely to receive proven treatments to
prevent a recurrence, even when they are as inexpensive as aspirin
or beta-blockers. While the researchers said they did not believe
there was conscious discrimination, they said more study was needed
to determine why the disparities occurred. Racial disparities in
medical treatment have increasingly become an issue in medicine,
and numerous studies have documented its incidence and its causes.
(250 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers believe doctors are routinely overlooking broken
wrists in women over 55 as a first sign of osteoporosis. These
findings suggest that doctors need to be diligent about making sure
postmenopausal patients being treated for wrist breaks received
good follow-up evaluations. (275 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ In the current Annals of Neurology, researchers have found
that when a child has seizures more than once, the diagnosis
probably is epilepsy. Seventy percent of children who have a second
seizure go on to have more. Knowing this may help doctors decide
whether long-term medication, despite the potential for side
effects, may be appropriate. (225 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A patient experiencing tearing, congestion and a drooping eye
(which are normally associated with cluster headaches) but had no
headache has caused doctors to believed that these are symptoms in
their own right and not just responses to pain. (230 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A recent study from Johns Hopkins University suggests that the
mere act of breathing deeply may stretch lung tissue and cause the
release of a protective chemical that keeps the airways open. If
this chemical could be identified, researchers believe it could be
the basis of a new asthma drug. (180 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: How is the heat
of hot peppers measured; either through human testers or by the
amount of Capsaicin in the pepper. By C. Claiborne Ray. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILD-CAR-SEATS (Undated) _ Researchers who analyzed car
crashes report that many parents are not using child car seats and
booster seats correctly. A recommended test for a properly
installed car seat, is that it should not move more than one inch
in any direction after being pulled forward and from the sides.
(560 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44).
</P>
