<TEXT>
<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 5 August 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `MICROPOWER': ELECTRICITY PRODUCED, LITERALLY, IN YOUR
BACKYARD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELECTRIC-REVOLUTION-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It could be every bit as dramatic as the revolution that hit the
world's telecommunications industry in the 1980s. And it is
occurring in an unexpected business; but one in which can be seen
the same forces of innovation, competition and choice that
transformed yesterday's sleepy telephone monopolies into today's
high-tech predators. That business is electricity generation.
Stifle your yawns _ power is every bit as big a business as
telecoms. Indeed, America's $220 billion electricity market is
larger than those for cellular and long-distance telephony
combined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 325-word optional trim; total uncut is 1,075 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET CRUNCH CROSSES THE PUDDLE, LEAVES EUROBIZ IN A
MUDDLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EURO-DOT.BOMBS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recent events have not been encouraging for Europe's crop of
once optimistic Internet start-ups. They include such spectacular
collapses as that of boo.com, a spendthrift electronic sports-goods
retailer that met impressive standards of corporate extravagance
while blithely losing a bundle. This week clickmango, an online
health-care business, became the latest of a string of such dot.com
casualties. Over the next few months hundreds of European
fledglings are likely to suffer the same fate as boo.com and
clickmango. Hundreds more will merge into larger entities with a
better chance of survival. The process of consolidation will have
profound effects, some beneficial but some harmful, on all European
companies, not just online ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL FEATURE: U.N. PEACEKEEPING &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.N. FENCE-MENDERS IN LEBANON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNIFIL-LEBANON-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARKABA, LEBANON _ On the pine-scented slopes along the
Lebanese-Israeli border, a platoon of United Nations peacekeepers
at last arrives to start the job they were first given 22 years
ago. Twenty-five Ghanaian soldiers stake out a patch of soil
belonging to Lebanon, but repeatedly encroached upon by the Israeli
army. Having helped define the border, they must now prevent
incidents along it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAKE WOBEGORE: CAN DEMOCRATS STILL COUNT ON MINNESOTA? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAKE-WOBEGORE?-MINN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Democratic Party's campaign planners rarely
lose sleep over Minnesota. The state's voters have chosen Democrats
in all but three presidential elections since 1948, and in all the
six most recent ones. But this land of fishermen and Scandinavian
crypto-socialists is no longer a bastion of the Democratic
Farmer-Labor Party (as the Minnesota branch still insists on
calling itself). Recent polls put Al Gore and George W. Bush
neck-and-neck there. If Gore loses Minnesota, he loses the
election. ``Minnesota is no longer simply a kind of knee-jerk
liberal state,'' argues Stuart Rothenberg, the editor of a
Washington newsletter. ``It's just a bizarre state.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors...and MINNESOTA) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED, WHITE 'N' BLUE BLOODS: `WASPS' AND THE GOP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASPY-GOP-BUSH-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ There was a spectre haunting the Republican National
Convention last week: that of the WASP (White Anglo-Saxon
Protestant) establishment. The entire point of the convention
seemed to be to prove that Republicans are just like the rest of
America: multicolored, serially disadvantaged and not a jot
WASPish. Was this all a charade? Had the real Republican convention
been held months ago in some exclusive club? Was compassionate
conservatism conceived in a fit of giggles over port and cigars? Or
is the WASP charge just another bogeyman dreamed up by the people
who brought you the Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 850 words; total uncut is 1,075) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIRKS, QUIPS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (375 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SPOOK VS. THE CROOKS: PUTIN'S PROMISING START &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-GETS-A-GRIP-ECONOMIST-775&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Remember Russia this time last year, and pinch
yourself. Vladimir Putin was an inconspicuous bureaucrat. The
Kremlin, under the ailing President Boris Yeltsin, seemed set for a
humiliating defeat in the forthcoming parliamentary and
presidential elections. The government was a corrupt shambles.
Since then, two big things have happened. The first is that the
Kremlin bounced back. It found a candidate for the presidency in
Putin. Second, power has shifted inside the Kremlin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 175-word optional trim; total uncut is 1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITAIN &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CENTENARIAN POPULATION EXPLOSION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VIVA-CENTENARIANS!-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ On Aug. 4, Britain's Queen Mother celebrated her
100th birthday. The occasion has already prompted a national
service at St. Paul's Cathedral and a huge pageant in the center of
London. But her birthday forms part of a much larger national and
international trend _ the remarkable rise in the number of
centenarians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICAN EMBASSY IN JERUSALEM HITS A SNAG &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; US-EMBASSY-JERUSALEM?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST JERUSALEM _ Praising Ehud Barak for his courage at Camp
David _ while implicitly criticizing Yasser Arafat for showing less
_ U.S. President Bill Clinton has raised the controversial matter
of moving America's embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. He has
always wanted to do this, he said, but has held back because of the
damage it might do to the peace process. Now, ``in the light of
what has happened'' with the failed Camp David talks, he will be
reviewing the situation, and will come to a decision before the end
of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FUTURE OF MEXICO'S LEFTISTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO-LOST-LEFT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For much of the past decade, the left-of-center
Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD) could claim to be the main
opposition to Mexico's long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI). So the triumph of Vicente Fox, the candidate of the
center-right, in last month's presidential election has thrown not
just the PRI into disarray, but the left too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCE AND ECONOMICS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWFANGLED E-COMMERCE, OLD-FASHIONED CREDIT CARDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET-PAYMENTS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ For all the growth of e-commerce, it has lagged
behind in one significant respect: payments. Almost all goods and
services bought on the Internet are paid for by old-fashioned
credit- or charge-cards. Yet for many sorts of transactions,
plastic is inappropriate or unusable. Most attempts to launch rival
online payment-systems have been false starts. But over the past
few months, three big American banks have been having another try. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUMORS OF DOT.COMS' DEMISE ARE GREATLY EXAGGERATED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLOP-DOT.COMS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not the beginning of the end, more the end of the
beginning _ or perhaps only the beginning of the end of the
beginning. For all the talk of dot.com burnouts and layoffs, the
numbers from America suggest that worse is yet to come. The real
problem with Internet companies (aside from huge losses and
dwindling supplies of cash at many of them) is not that there have
been too many failures but that there have been too few. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DEATH INDUSTRY STRUGGLES TO STAY ALIVE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PALL-FUNERAL-BIZ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Barring a sudden outbreak of immortality, one would
expect undertaking to be a nice, steady business. Not so, according
to Fran Bernstein, an analyst with Merrill Lynch. The past 18
months have been rather depressing for America's funeral industry.
The top three U.S.-quoted companies, which control roughly a fifth
of the country's $30 billion market, have seen their share prices
collapse since the start of 1999. And a fourth is now in the final
throes of bankruptcy. Too much debt and too few deaths are largely
to blame. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
