<P>
   &UR; THE DEATH INDUSTRY STRUGGLES TO STAY ALIVE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PALL-FUNERAL-BIZ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Barring a sudden outbreak of immortality, one would
expect undertaking to be a nice, steady business. Not so, according
to Fran Bernstein, an analyst with Merrill Lynch. The past 18
months have been rather depressing for America's funeral industry.
The top three U.S.-quoted companies, which control roughly a fifth
of the country's $30 billion market, have seen their share prices
collapse since the start of 1999. And a fourth is now in the final
throes of bankruptcy. Too much debt and too few deaths are largely
to blame. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
