bricks-and-mortar execs who are anxious to curtail or shut down
their own dot-coms but don't want to be too vocal about it for fear
that their own rapaciousness would become obvious. No one wants to
be known as the exec who decided to pimp the capital markets with a
dot-com because he saw the markets were easy pickings.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously these dot-coms don't make any money. They are heavily
subsidized by the bricks-and-mortar portions, none of which
particularly likes these dot-com divisions.
</P>
<P>
   There's a ton of private ``I told you sos'' going on in every
newsroom, believe me.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't shut the darn things. That would be an outrage.
Instead, they now have to put the screws to their own internal
dot-coms, telling them, ``Look, you missed your chance, now become
profitable and at the same time don't look to us for a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   What a bind! Look for this story to go largely uncovered by the
newspapers. It is just too embarrassing for their printed words.
</P>
<P>
   DEERE IN THE HEADLIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   The dicey nature of cyclical investing surfaces every day. This
weekend, in my zeal to exploit the end of the Fed's rate hikes, I
earmarked Deere as a potential buy.
</P>
<P>
   Deere is the kind of classic cyclical that you buy when the Fed
is out of the way. Deere does well when the economy does well,
although, obviously it has a high farm component. Caterpillar acts
better because it is purer, but there is no doubt that Deere dances
to the direction of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, but there is one problem: the near-term fundamentals. They
are not good. In fact, they are so bad that Bear Stearns downgraded
the stock Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Had I just invested on a ``macro'' thesis, that is, looked at a
stock as a proxy for the Fed's moves, I would have bought Deere on
Friday. I would have been down fast.
</P>
<P>
   When you are looking for plays off the Fed, you still have to
worry about the near-term. If the near-term is OK, you can buy. If
the near-term is suspect, you have to wait, even with the macro
getting rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Deere downgrade has occurred, though, I am
wondering, after it reports, whether it wouldn't be a great way to
play the end of the hikes. I just don't want to jump the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (James J. Cramer is manager of a hedge fund and co-founder of
TheStreet.com. At time of publication, his fund had no positions in
any stocks mentioned. His fund often buys and sells securities that
are the subject of his columns, both before and after the columns
are published, and the positions that his fund takes may change at
any time. Under no circumstances does the information in this
column represent a recommendation to buy or sell stocks. Cramer's
writings provide insights into the dynamics of money management and
are not a solicitation for transactions. While he cannot provide
investment advice or recommendations, he invites you to comment on
his column at jjcletters(at)thestreet.com.)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
