<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STANFORD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STANFORD LOOKS TO FUTURE WITH ROSE-COLORED GLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ It's time for Stanford to start playing
football again, which can only mean one thing: Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, why not? The Cardinal did it last year against all odds,
despite having one of the nation's worst defenses (statistically
speaking, at least), and in spite of losing their season-opening
game by 52 points.
</P>
<P>
   So why not this year, when they will be trying to replace:
</P>
<P>
   _ An All-Pac-10 quarterback who is all over the school record
book.
</P>
<P>
   _ An all-Pac-10 receiver who is all over the league record book.
</P>
<P>
   _ A center who started 46 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   _ An All-Pac-10, all-important left tackle who started 37 games
during his Stanford career.
</P>
<P>
   _ A strong safety who is No. 2 on the Cardinal's career
interceptions list and was a unifying force in last year's
bend-but-don't-break defense.
</P>
<P>
   _ A pair of starting linebackers, a starting cornerback and a
starting nose tackle who was seen as the squad's most improved
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably more things going into this year to be
concerned about, more questions marks,'' said head coach Tyrone
Willingham.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's not as if Willingham and the Cardinal didn't
have their share of unsettledness when they headed into last season
_ only to pull it all together and wind up taking the school to the
Rose Bowl for the first time in 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   With that backdrop in mind, and with the Cardinal set to begin
fall workouts this week _ freshmen report Tuesday, with the full
squad having at it beginning Saturday _ here are the most pivotal
issues Stanford faces leading up to its season opener, Sept. 2 at
Washington State:
</P>
<P>
   The new quarterback: The issue is not so much replacing Todd
Husak _ though that's no small feat given his success _ it's more
the question of Randy Fasani.
</P>
<P>
   Fasani was the most highly recruited prep quarterback in the
nation back when he was at Del Oro High School near Sacramento in
1996. But after redshirting his first season at Stanford, he spent
the next two buried at No. 3 on the depth chart behind Husak and
Joe Borchard.
</P>
<P>
   With Stanford wanting to take advantage of his athleticism and
Fasani simply wanting to get on the field, he wound up playing just
about everywhere but quarterback _ tight end, linebacker, special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Husak graduated to the National Football League and
Borchard having opted for a pro baseball career, Fasani will get
more than the token, goal-line snaps he has collected to this
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy will be fine,'' Willingham said, ``because Randy is a
winner and Randy is a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The cohesion thing: Although last year's team began the fall
coming off a 3-8 season and with low outside expectations, it did
have experience and long-standing leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Now, things are a bit more uncertain. Fasani surely is a
leader-type, but he's new nonetheless. Plus, with Husak, Troy
Walters and Mike McLaughlin all gone from the offense, there's a
void in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Willie Howard and his Trench Dogs act are back on the
defensive line _ he's planning on unveiling a defense-wide nickname
at some point in the near future _ but five new defensive starters
mean some adjustments will have to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Said Howard: ``The big thing will be how we come together as a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   No time to waste: With the season opener also representing the
Pac-10 opener, the Cardinal won't have the kind of luxury they did
last season.
</P>
<P>
   As Willingham noted time and again after the team's 69-17
pasting at Texas to open 1999, the loss did nothing to derail the
Cardinal's goals. It was an approach that proved steadying and
prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, Stanford begins with a 7:15 p.m. kickoff at
Washington State. Granted, the Cougars are expected to dwell in the
cellar again this season, but remember, the Cardinal were expected
to finish near the bottom of the pack last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first thing you think of when you've got a
conference game to start the season is that there's no margin for
error,'' Willingham said. ``We have to come out quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Where are all the receivers? In addition to Walters _ ``I don't
know if you can replace a young man of that caliber,'' Willingham
said _ the Cardinal also must deal with the departures of Dave
Davis and Tafiti Uso.
</P>
<P>
   Davis flunked out of school and Uso cut short his career because
of a series of concussions, so the Cardinal lost their likely Nos.
2 and 3 receivers.
</P>
<P>
   They still have DeRonnie Pitts, whose talents were dwarfed
behind Walters to the point that Willingham said of Pitts,
``There's no question that he's the most underrated player in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, beyond Pitts, there's an untested group that
includes Ryan Wells, Caleb Bowman and Luke Powell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
