<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WESTNILEVIRUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSQUITO SEASON IS PEAKING. HERE'S HOW TO BE READY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by WEST NILE-PREVENTION)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CAROLYN POIROT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If you think this summer's mosquito menace
has evaporated with the hot, dry weather, think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the favorite breeding time of the Southern house
mosquito,'' said Scott Sawlis, an entomologist and vector control
supervisor for Dallas County Health and Human Services. ``They like
dry weather and stagnant water high in organic matter. Another rain
would flush away all the breeding beds in storm drains and gutters,
where we can't see them.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Texas Department of Health is expanding
its mosquito monitoring system to look for the West Nile virus
currently making news in the Northeast United States, in case it is
introduced in the state this year. The health department is also
checking more than 200,000 mosquitoes to make sure they are not
carrying any of the viruses that can be transmitted to human
beings, including the viruses that cause St. Louis encephalitis,
dengue fever, Eastern or Western equine encephalitis or West Nile
encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   All of the mosquito-borne viruses can cause brain inflammation,
with symptoms including a headache, sustained fever, nervous tics
or tremors, blurred vision, slurred speech and coma, according to
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile encephalitis, closely related to both St. Louis
encephalitis and dengue fever, was first seen in the United States
last summer, when it killed seven New Yorkers and made at least 62
others seriously ill. By the end of last year, the virus had been
found in 17 species of birds in New York, New Jersey, Connecticut,
Pennsylvania and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   This year, West Nile has been found in dead birds and mosquito
pools in New York and New Jersey, but no human cases have been
identified. The discovery of the virus has led to pesticide
spraying throughout New York City, including Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to combat West Nile, the National Institutes of
Health recently awarded a $3 million grant to a Massachusetts
biotechnology firm to try to create a vaccine for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to testing mosquitoes, the Texas health department
has added the West Nile virus to the battery of blood tests it
conducts on chickens and other birds, because the state is in the
migratory path of some of the birds known to carry that virus.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito season begins in May and continues up to November,
with the most critical months July, August and September. That's
when Southern house mosquitoes, as well as the tiger mosquitoes
associated with dengue fever, are at the peak of their activity,
Sawlis said.
</P>
<P>
   A large outbreak of dengue fever occurred in Texas last year,
with 62 cases reported, including one death. Dengue fever is
characterized by severe joint pain, fever, headache, muscle aches
and rash.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, the state hasn't detected any mosquitoes
carrying virus yet this year, but we are still in the red (danger)
zone until at least the end of August,'' said Ray Parsons,
assistant director for mosquito control for the health department
in Harris County, which includes Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 4,437 cases of the most common form of St. Louis
encephalitis reported nationally since 1964, according to the CDC.
The fatality rate for St. Louis encephalitis is 5 percent to 30
percent, the CDC says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most cases of St. Louis encephalitis are recorded in September
and October. We are monitoring carefully, hoping to catch it before
there is any human contact,'' said Glenna Teltow, section chief of
medical entomology at the Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis encephalitis and dengue fever are the most common
serious diseases mosquitoes transmit to people in Texas, but there
have also been human cases of Western and Eastern equine
encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   The deadliest of these viruses is Eastern equine. About
one-third of those who develop it die, and many others sustain
permanent brain damage. Fortunately, it is rare in humans. Since
1964, 153 human cases of Eastern equine encephalitis have been
reported in the United States, according to the CDC.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said several cases of Eastern equine virus have been
found this summer in horses in Louisiana, and one human case was
reported in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far this year, we haven't isolated any viruses from
mosquitoes, although we did find some evidence of St. Louis
encephalitis in chicken blood _ one in Dallas, and one in Lubbock _
earlier this summer,'' Teltow says.
</P>
<P>
   Local health departments, mosquito control districts and some
universities are involved with the Texas Department of Health in
the surveillance efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Southern house and tiger mosquitoes, the ones that
come on the heels of heavy rains are ``flood-water mosquitoes,''
which are very large and aggressive, and a major nuisance, but are
seldom carriers of disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lay their eggs in areas prone to flooding ... and when it
rains, you get instant mosquitoes,'' Sawlis said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-768, or e-mail:
cpoirot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
