<HEADLINE>
STONE COOL: STONE TEMPLE PILOTS COMES BACK WITH A VENGEANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Stone Temple Pilots, including Eric
Kretz, Dean DeLeo, Robert DeLeo and Scott Weiland.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Most rock bands with sordid, troubled histories are easy fodder
for VH1's documentary series ``Behind the Music.'' But Stone Temple
Pilots' drama could also be titled ``Behind the Bars.''
 &HT;    When the group's most recent album, ``No. 4,'' debuted at No. 6
on the Billboard charts last fall, STP was moribund because
frontman Scott Weiland was in a California jail, sentenced to one
year in a prison-operated drug-rehabilitation program for violating
his probation from previous convictions.
 &HT;    With the band unable to promote it by touring, ``No. 4'' quickly
fell off the charts _ one more setback in a rancorous five years of
false starts and all-too-frequent stops.
 &HT;    But since Weiland emerged on Dec. 30, released nine months early
and as clean and sober as he's ever been, STP's fortunes have
revived. With a hit in the song ``Sour Girl,'' ``No. 4'' has
returned to the charts and is approaching platinum status, while
STP is back onstage, touring with the Red Hot Chili Peppers after
playing a series of high-profile shows such as the opening date of
the Tattoo the Earth festival, as well as performing to 90,000
people at the Hard Rockfest in Chicago.
 &HT;    ``We've been working really hard,'' says the 32-year-old
Weiland, who in May married model Mary Forsberg. ``A lot of people
said that they didn't think we could do it, and it's happening. So
we're really about the way things are going, and I think more than
ever we're very grateful for what we're able to do in our lives,
which is play music and write music and perform live and make money
doing it.''
 &HT;    Now Weiland and his mates _ guitarist Dean DeLeo, brother Robert
DeLeo on bass and drummer Eric Kretz _ hope to live up to the
promise demonstrated back when the southern California quartet's
debut album, ``Core'' (1992), hit the Billboard Top 5, sold more
than 7 million copies and launched the hits ``Plus,'' ``Sex Type
Thing'' and ``Creep.'' The album also scooped up a number of
trophies at the MTV Video Music Awards and American Music Awards
ceremonies, as well as a Grammy for Best Hard Rock Performance.
 &HT;    Its second album, ``Purple,'' bowed at No. 1 in 1994, but cracks
were beginning to show in the group's veneer owing to Weiland's
drug addiction and, he says, the other group members' own habits.
 &HT;    Weiland's first drug arrest came on May 15, 1995, in Pasadena,
Calif., and while STP finished a third album, ``Tiny Music: Songs
From the Vatican Gift Shop,'' a schism sent Weiland on the solo
trail and the other three off to form another band, Talk Show.
 &HT;    ``We never broke up,'' Weiland insists. ``We never talked about
breaking up. There was a period of time where that question
definitely loomed, but there was never a conscious decision to bury
the band. I think all of us felt the same way, and that was that we
needed time apart from each other to sort of trudge our own roads
for awhile. And we did that.''
 &HT;    Dean DeLeo says that spending nearly two years apart inspired a
new appreciation for each other and created stronger bonds, both
personally and musically.
 &HT;    ``Those other things we did fizzed out rather quickly,'' DeLeo
says, though he admits that if Talk Show had sold better there
might not have been an STP reunion.
 &HT;    Still, the guitarist says, all concerned found their separate
endeavors ``pretty unfulfilling. There was a mutual thing missing
between us all. It wasn't the same without Scott, and for Scott it
wasn't the same without us. It was hard, man, being out there
without him.''
 &HT;    Weiland agrees.
 &HT;    ``We experienced what we had to experience in order to get where
we are now,'' he says, ``in our personal lives and in our
professional lives.''
 &HT;    DeLeo says that ``there was a tremendous amount of anxiety''
when rehearsals for ``No. 4'' began in January 1998. But after the
first session yielded two songs _ ``Sour Girl'' and the first
single, ``Down'' _ STP was clearly back on track. Musically, at
least.
 &HT;    On the personal front, Weiland acknowledges, it was a different
story.
 &HT;    ``I hadn't come full circle yet in dealing with my heroin
addiction,'' he says. ``I was still sort of on the fence, kind of
stepping in and falling out of recovery. Unfortunately I still had
a few more chemical misadventures to experience.''
 &HT;    It took his incarceration last fall to spur the singer to clean
up, but he says it will be for good.
 &HT;    ``It's definitely not a pleasant experience,'' Weiland says. ``I
was fortunate to have done my time in a wing of the county jail
that was converted to an experimental drug-treatment program _ you
don't have to deal with the jailhouse politics and the racial
politics that you deal with in a mainline.
 &HT;    ``But it's definitely not an easy program,'' he adds. ``The
rules are a lot more strict than they are in the general
population. But I was able to get into the solution, instead of
wallowing in the problem.''
 &HT;    Weiland says he's staying clean with a routine of exercise and
support-group meetings, as well as his bandmates' acceptance that
those aspects of his life must take precedence over some of his
band duties.
 &HT;    Any guilt he may feel over his past behavior has been dealt with
by the amends he's made to family and friends, he says, as well as
by accepting that ``that was where I was at at that time, and no
guilt or worrying or dwelling on it can change the fact that that's
something that happened.''
 &HT;    He can't help believing, however, that his addiction was not the
only cause of STP's problems since the mid-1990s.
 &HT;    ``We've all grown up a lot as individuals,'' Weiland says. ``My
troubles have been documented in the press and are public
knowledge, but various members of the band have had their hangups,
too.
 &HT;    ``Now I think everyone, in growing as individuals, has got a
better appreciation of what we were all going through in our
differences with each other,'' he says. ``It's made us a lot
closer, and has taken away a lot of the resentment and jealousy
that used to exist.''
 &HT;    It's also making STP work a lot harder, too, he says. The group
has been working on new material, and expects to add several
original songs to a greatest-hits album, tentatively titled ``Big
Bang Babies,'' that's slated for October release.
 &HT;    And while the group knows how much is at stake in
re-establishing STP's reputation as a live band, Weiland _ who also
guests on Limp Bizkit's upcoming album _ says the shows so far have
been better than ever, especially since he's performing clean.
 &HT;    ``I love it,'' he says, ``because performing loaded is sort of a
disjoint thing. Opiates are anesthetics _ not only do they numb you
physically, but they sort of numb you emotionally and spiritually,
too, so it's hard to connect with the music and what's going on
onstage.
 &HT;    ``I have a much easier time now becoming intoxicated by the
energy that's happening from the audience and the energy that's
being created from the four members of the band,'' Weiland says.
``I'm able to enjoy it. I'm able to be present for it, where in the
past a lot of times I was hoping I could get through the two-hour
set so I could get back in the hotel room and fix.
 &HT;    ``I'm very happy that's behind us now.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``No. 4,'' consult the official
Web site at www.stonetemplepilots.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
