w a BC-KEANU-REEVES-IN-THE-R     08-07 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEANU-REEVES-IN-THE-REPLACEMENTS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHOLE NEW BALLGAME: KEANU REEVES LEADS `THE REPLACEMENTS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Keanu Reeves in a scene from ``The
Replacements.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Keanu Reeves stepped onto the set of ``The Replacements,'' took
one look at his trailer and demanded a new one.
 &HT;    Sounds like a typical case of rampaging Hollywood ego, but we're
talking Keanu Reeves, a quirky guy who's predictable only in his
unpredictability. Reeves' beef was that his trailer was too big _
he demanded a smaller one.
 &HT;    ``I generally don't need much,'' Reeves says. ``I don't need
much space. Just give me a room, give me some water, maybe some
food in the morning.
 &HT;    ``I remember hearing this story about a British actor who was
playing Lear,'' he recalls. ``He came to rehearsals and was acting
like, `I'm this great actor and you should afford me all of this
and you should treat me like this.' He was a prick. He was being
terrible to everyone.
 &HT;    ``The director said to the other actors, `Don't treat him like a
king in rehearsals.' And all of sudden he had no power. He wasn't a
king,'' Reeves says. ``So it is only something that someone else
can give you.''
 &HT;    These days Reeves has a fair amount of power. He can request
script changes or an extra take. And, yes, he can get a smaller
trailer if he wants one.
 &HT;    ``On this film, I was the leading actor in the piece,'' he says.
``Hopefully, if you keep him happy, you'll make a good picture. So
it's like an investment.''
 &HT;    And it sounds as if Reeves is easy to keep happy.
 &HT;    ``Oh, no,'' he says, laughing. ``You should have seen some of
the meetings between Howard Deutch and I, but ... ''
 &HT;    Deutch is the director of ``The Replacements,'' a shaggy-dog
comedy about a bunch of football has-beens and wannabes who are
called upon to fill in for a striking professional team. Reeves
stars as Shane Falco, a once-promising quarterback who choked in
the heat of a major college game and never recovered, now earning a
living scraping barnacles off boats.
 &HT;    The film, which will open nationwide on Aug. 11, represents
Reeves' first outing since ``The Matrix'' (1999) re-established him
as a star of major proportions. The actor insists that he felt no
pressure, from within or without, to sustain his career momentum by
scoring another hit.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to act,'' he says during a conversation at New York's
Essex House. Dressed down in a thin green sweater and black jacket,
with a scruffy beard hiding a ruddy complexion, Reeves looks more
like an average Joe than like a $20 million man.
 &HT;    ``I really liked the script and I liked the character,'' he
adds. ``I liked these misfit hard-luck guys who get a second chance
to try and conquer their fears and develop as people. And I like
comedies.''
 &HT;    Preparing for the role, Reeves dove into a get-fit regimen. He
altered his diet, lifted weights, worked out with former pro
quarterbacks and participated, along with his co-stars, in a
three-week training camp.
 &HT;    ``It was important to me to be believable as a quarterback, so I
did all I could to achieve that,'' he says. ``Part of that was to
have the body, to embody it.''
 &HT;    Reeves is known as a stickler for authenticity when it comes to
character details. He likes to wear the proper clothes, walk the
right walk, nail the accent and so on. While it makes sense that
he'd want to appear convincing tossing a football, some might
wonder if it was really necessary to make so intense a commitment
to a sports comedy.
 &HT;    The actor winces.
 &HT;    ``Everyone was an accomplished actor,'' he says, ``and I think
everyone came with the same feeling of wanting to have authentic
characters, to have them be well-rounded and have a humanity, and
to have the comedy come from that. You feel like you're not just
watching a device, but people _ it was important to everyone on the
film to achieve that.''
 &HT;    Next up for Reeves is ``The Gift,'' a drama that casts him as a
wife-beater and co-stars Cate Blanchett, Hilary Swank and Giovanni
Ribisi. He'll chase that with the just-wrapped romance ``Sweet
November,'' which reunites him with Charlize Theron, his co-star in
``The Devil's Advocate'' (1997). Reeves plays a detached ad
executive who falls for free-spirited Theron.
 &HT;    Come November, after touring with his band Dogstar to promote
their debut album ``Happy Endings'' and squeezing in the film
``Hardball,'' in which he's cast opposite Diane Lane as the
unwilling manager of an inner-city baseball team, Reeves will join
Laurence Fishburne, Carrie-Anne Moss and writers/directors Andy and
Larry Wachowski in Australia to make two back-to-back sequels to
the surprise sci-fi blockbuster ``The Matrix.''
 &HT;    Reeves and company will train for four months, and then shoot
Down Under for a full year.
 &HT;    ``I'm looking forward to it,'' says Reeves, who will reprise his
role as Neo, a hacker who's more than he seems. ``It's an
extraordinary circumstance. The films have extraordinary
opportunities and extraordinary ambitions.''
 &HT;    Like everyone else on the planet, Reeves was stunned by the
success of ``The Matrix.''
 &HT;    ``I had no expectation,'' he says. ``I really didn't know how it
was going to be received. When I saw it, I thought it was better
than the film I thought I'd made.
 &HT;    ``It had an ambition to create a cinema that hadn't really been
seen in that form,'' the actor says. ``It was recognizable in anime
or graphic art, in cartoon form. It also had the ambition to tell a
story in a different way, using kung fu or the science-fiction
metaphor.''
 &HT;    As an actor, Reeves is not everyone's cup of tea. Some
moviegoers think he should have stuck with the goofy likes of the
``Bill and Ted'' films and spared people ``Point Break'' (1991),
``Bram Stoker's Dracula'' (1992), ``A Walk in the Clouds'' (1995),
``Johnny Mnemonic'' (1995) and ``Chain Reaction'' (1997).
 &HT;    Others regard him as an underrated dramatic actor, pointing to
``River's Edge'' (1987), ``My Own Private Idaho'' (1991), ``Speed''
(1994), ``Devil's Advocate'' and ``The Matrix'' as evidence.
 &HT;    Reeves long ago stopped defending his acting abilities, however.
Directors want him in their films, and studios are willing to pay
millions for his services. More than anything else, then, he's
concerned about maintaining his privacy and integrity in an
immensely public, often morally bankrupt business.
 &HT;    ``I want to work in Hollywood,'' Reeves says, downplaying his
reluctant-star reputation. ``The experiences I've had have been
some of the best in my life. I want to act.
 &HT;    ``If a film is successful,'' he concludes, ``that has other
consequences. And I'm willing to go through that. Sometimes it's
fun.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Replacements,'' consult
the official Web site at www.thereplacements.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
