<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-WRITER-SUE-GRAFTON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALPHABET SUPER: SUE GRAFTON MAKES MYSTERY LEGIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of mystery writer Sue Grafton.) 
 By MEL NOVIT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    After publishing 15 best-selling mysteries and creating one of
the most popular detectives in contemporary fiction, Sue Grafton
knows what she thinks of her own capabilities.
 &HT;    ``I am too stupid to do this,'' she says to herself about every
book she writes. ``I can't possibly figure this out. I have no
other images, stories, no other words, no other characters.''
 &HT;    Her millions of readers in 28 countries and 26 languages,
including Indonesian and Bulgarian, might disagree. Grafton's
alphabet series, featuring private detective Kinsey Millhone, began
18 years ago with ``A Is for Alibi'' (1982) and thus far has
reached ``O Is for Outlaw'' (Henry Holt, 1999), her 15th book and
one that President Clinton has been photographed toting around.
 &HT;    Her ``P Is for ... '' book, whose full title is still top
secret, is due from Penguin-Putnam early in 200l.
 &HT;    Speaking by telephone from her four-acre estate near Santa
Barbara, Calif. _ she also has a home in her native Louisville, Ky.
_ Grafton is brimming with confidence, having had what she
describes as ``an especially good day of writing.''
 &HT;    On days like this, she says, it seems as if she might make it
through the remaining 11 books in the series which the longtime
runner and power walker _ she does seven miles a day _ calls a
marathon: ``26 miles, 26 books.''
 &HT;    ``People used to be incredulous and were betting I couldn't do
it,'' says the 60-year-old mother of three and grandmother of two.
``Now they're rooting for me.''
 &HT;    They're also rooting for her alter ego, Kinsey Millhone, a
no-nonsense, kick-butt, now-35-year-old, twice-divorced, female
detective who thrives on a high-fat, high-cholesterol diet, booze
and perilous activities of all kinds. Millhone plies her trade in
l980s California, and Grafton ages her and her supporting cast
every few books.
 &HT;    Grafton takes particular pride in the fact that her fans are
about evenly divided between men and women.
 &HT;    ``Women have their husbands, sons and brothers reading my
books,'' she says. ``Men automatically think books written about
women by women are going to be about pantyhose and woman stuff, and
they're always startled when they like them.''
 &HT;    The Millhone stories are what Grafton calls ``closed
mysteries,'' mysteries with solutions. Rich in description and
detail, they are packed with well-researched, accurate information
on everything from water-reclamation plants and hotel management to
how a safe or a gun is constructed.
 &HT;    ``I do my own research,'' the author says. ``If you lay it off
on somebody else, you miss the good stuff.''
 &HT;    Not that it's easy. Grafton admits to being shy, adding that she
did use a researcher for ``A Is for Alibi,'' simply because she was
too shy to call the Los Angeles morgue.
 &HT;    ``I still find it intimidating to make calls to experts,'' the
author says, ``and I have to wait for a very brave day. When I was
researching `H Is for Homicide' (1991), I called the chief
investigator for the National Fraud Bureau in California. I got
halfway through introducing myself and he said, `I'm reading ``E is
for Evidence'' (1988).'
 &HT;    ``So I thought `Thank you, Lord. He knows what I'm doing _ I
don't have to explain.'''
 &HT;    Research only goes so far, however, and Grafton says that the
insights and revelations of her characters' dark sides spring from
her own imagination, including what she calls the ``sassy'' parts
that involve sexual elements and rough language.
 &HT;    ``I call these insights `my shadow,''' she says. ``The shadow
represents things about ourselves we tend to disavow. For the
average person, all of our criminal impulses _ our rage, our
pettiness, our meanness, our spite _ tend to be repressed. I
acknowledge all of these things in myself.''
 &HT;    She draws on her experience with a number of psychiatrists.
 &HT;    ``Some are good and some are bad,'' she says. ``The good ones
you learn from, like teachers. The one who helped me did so when I
thought my writing was flat and lifeless in `J Is for Judgment'
(1993).
 &HT;    ``My therapist, at that time, taught me Jungian theory _ that in
trying to look good for the world you repress the shadow and you
lose your creative energy.''
 &HT;    The shadow is only one of the various personas which Grafton
draws upon for her work.
 &HT;    ``I have many personalities,'' she says. ``That's how I
function. Many years ago I did the `Today' show, and my husband
videotaped the performance ... People asked me how it was, and I
didn't remember. Three weeks later I watched it, and there was this
perfectly poised woman with a very Southern accent just doing my
job for me. I named her `Georgia,' because of the accent.''
 &HT;    Grafton also acknowledges ``She Who Speaks,'' her persona for
public addresses _ ``she and Georgia are both showoffs and they
adore one another'' _ and ``The Warrior.''
 &HT;    ``When I trip into this one, my voice will drop an octave and I
think `You're dead meat,''' Grafton says cheerfully. ``She takes
care of business for me.''
 &HT;    Of course, there is ``She Who Writes,'' the persona who works
fanatically on her books and hates being criticized or tampered
with.
 &HT;    It was ``She Who Writes'' who turned Grafton against Hollywood
forever. Having begun her writing career as a screenwriter, she
soon soured on group-writing activities.
 &HT;    ``I hated Hollywood because I'm not a team player,'' Grafton
says. ``I didn't want to sit with five other people who were going
to help me with my work. I was treated kindly by them, if you want
to count being given soft drinks or coffee when you wanted them.
But where they trashed me was by taking their pencil to my work.''
 &HT;    As a result, Grafton long ago swore that none of her books will
ever be made into a movie.
 &HT;    ``I told my children I'd kill them if they ever sell me out _
I'll come back from the grave,'' the writer says, laughing. ``And
they know I can do it.''
 &HT;    Besides, Grafton says, she doesn't want a particular actress's
face to become that of Kinsey Millhone, because she doesn't want to
ruin her readers' fantasies.
 &HT;    ``No actress could ever satisfy all the conditions,'' she says,
while acknowledging that Kinsey is essentially a younger, thinner
version of herself. Grafton was once photographed for a book jacket
while perched on the bumper of Kinsey's famous Volkswagen, holding
a revolver.
 &HT;    Grafton is nearly finished with her ``P'' mystery, but says
there's no assurance that she'll make it to ``Z Is for Zero.''
 &HT;    ``If I got five more of them done and felt I was losing it or
cheating or getting bored,'' she says, ``I'd hang it up in a flat
minute.''
 &HT;    If she weren't a writer, she adds, she might enjoy being a
private investigator herself, or perhaps a skip-tracer, someone who
tracks down deadbeats.
 &HT;    ``I like sleuthing, finding out where people are and what
happened to them,'' Grafton says. ``I wouldn't mind working as a
criminologist or some kind of forensic expert. I tend to like jobs
with variety, where every day looks a little different.
 &HT;    ``I never dreamed I'd be able to make a living at writing.''
 c.2000 Mel Novit  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mel Novit is a Morton Grove, Ill.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``O Is for Outlaw,'' consult the
official Web site at www.suegrafton.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
