<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITER-JOE-ESZTERHAS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHAPSODIC INSTINCT: JOE ESZTERHAS ON POWER, SEX AND `AMERICAN
RHAPSODY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of screenwriter/novelist Joe Eszterhas.) 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Joe Eszterhas has gotten rich by airing other people's dirty
linen, but insists that he has none of his own.
 &HT;    Literally.
 &HT;    ``The maids constantly ask my wife why I never have any dirty
underwear lying on the floor,'' he says. ``I don't wear any.''
 &HT;    In short, the highest-paid screenwriter in Hollywood history is
perfectly willing to dish the dirt on himself _ which is only fair,
given the controversy he's stirred with his gossipy new roman a
clef, ``American Rhapsody'' (Knopf, 2000).
 &HT;    The novel is about politics and pop culture _ and, as you'd
expect from the screenwriter of ``Basic Instinct'' (1992) and
``Showgirls'' (1995), there's considerable dirt to be dished,
including a detailed recounting of the Monica Lewinsky scandal ...
narrated by the president's genitals.
 &HT;    ``I think of this book as an upraised middle finger to
society,'' Eszterhas says, ``and my biggest worry was that it was
too outrageous, too in-your-face and too graphic. But I just found
that my book will be No. 5 on the New York Times best-seller list.
I guess I'm just stirring the drink again, and people are enjoying
it.''
 &HT;    On a balmy day at Chicago's Four Seasons hotel, Eszterhas looks
harmless enough. He's a non-threatening, exceedingly polite
teddy-bear type who says he'd never meant to write a political
novel.
 &HT;    But something snapped after he had back-to-back movie flops with
``Telling Lies in America'' (1997) and the even-more-disastrous
``An Alan Smithee Film: Burn Hollywood Burn'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``One night I was scanning the channels and found myself on two
talk shows,'' he recalls. ``I thought, `You should be writing and
not talking so much.'
 &HT;    ``So I went to Maui with my wife,'' Eszterhas continues, ``and
we found out our phone was broken. It was sort of great to be out
of sync with the world _ it gave me a lot of time to reflect about
values.
 &HT;    ``Meanwhile, the whole Clinton-and-Monica-Lewinsky scandal blew
up,'' he says. ``I became a real couch potato _ I was consumed by
this thing. I started taking notes which turned into riffs. Riffs
turned into chapters.''
 &HT;    The novel's targets also include Hollywood, of course, and
Eszterhas freely names names, recounting anecdotes that may or may
not be true. Sharon Stone, Richard Gere and Michael Douglas are
among those who turn up in his pages.
 &HT;    ``The question has been posed: Will you ever eat lunch in this
town again?'' the screenwriter says, laughing. ``I intend to have
the best table at Spago for a long time.''
 &HT;    Despite the many juicy stories in the book _ Eszterhas recounts,
for example, a brief fling with Stone which the actress herself
refuses to confirm _ the writer insists that he's really kept the
juiciest stuff to himself.
 &HT;    ``In my mind, this is not a Hollywood tell-all,'' he says. ``If
I ever did a real Hollywood book, it would be thousands and
thousands of pages _ and then I'd have to move to Budapest. I don't
want to do that to my wife and the kids.''
 &HT;    The book's stories are all true, however, Eszterhas insists _ if
only because his publisher's lawyers demanded verification of every
item.
 &HT;    ``What they wanted was to physically see the backup,'' he
recalls, ``and I had 200 books on my living-room rug and untold
boxes of research materials and tape recordings that I put in their
hands.
 &HT;    ``At the end of this process, the lawyers said they had never
seen a book with this much backup.''
 &HT;    Eszterhas comes naturally by his flair for writing. Born during
World War II to a Hungarian novelist and a secretary, he spent his
first six years in an Austrian refugee camp. The family fled again
when the Russian army invaded Austria, ending up in Cleveland,
where Eszterhas' father got a job editing the newspaper of the
Catholic-Hungarian Society.
 &HT;    ``I didn't know English,'' the screenwriter recalls. ``I thought
my job was to learn as much about America as I could. Back then
music and baseball were my life. Elvis was my hero.''
 &HT;    That urge to learn about the society around him led naturally to
a career as a reporter. Eszterhas studied journalism at Ohio
University in Athens, then landed a job writing about music for the
Cleveland Plain Dealer, in the course of which he interviewed Jimi
Hendrix, Janis Joplin and other rock legends.
 &HT;    That in turn took him to Rolling Stone, where he covered
politics and celebrities for the magazine until a United Artists
executive asked if he would consider writing movies.
 &HT;    Eszterhas figured he might as well give it a shot, and cranked
out the script that later became the union saga ``F.I.S.T.''
(1978). He was off and running on a career which would include the
critically acclaimed ``Jagged Edge'' (1985) and ``The Music Box''
(1990), resounding flops such as ``Jade'' (1995) and ``Sliver''
(1993) and the box-office mother lodes ``Flashdance'' (1983), which
earned $200 million, and ``Basic Instinct,'' good for $352 million.
 &HT;    And, of course, the industry joke ``Showgirls.''
 &HT;    ``Women hated it,'' Eszterhas admits. ``A mistake was not making
an NC-17 film. We took seven seconds out of `Showgirls' to get an
R. Now I don't think that movie was strong enough.''
 &HT;    Eszterhas' personal life has been as vivid _ and as public _ as
most of his movies. Married since 1968 to fellow reporter Geri
Javor, he left her in 1992 during the making of ``Sliver.''
Meanwhile that film's producer, Bill MacDonald, ditched his wife to
become engaged to Stone, star of Eszterhas' hit ``Basic Instinct.''
Stone and MacDonald ended up breaking up, but Eszterhas married
MacDonald's ex-wife Naomi, and their marriage has lasted _ she's
expecting their fourth child together this August.
 &HT;    ``It's our fourth boy _ the others are 6, 4 and 2,'' Eszterhas
says, laughing. ``So all that macho stuff they accuse me of is
true.
 &HT;    ``I just love being a father,'' he adds more seriously. ``I was
blessed by God when I found Naomi. I call her my sunlight.
 &HT;    ``It did, of course, take me 50 years to get to this point.''
 &HT;    Joe Eszterhas, family man?
 &HT;    ``Yeah,'' he says cheerfully. ``I look like a Hell's Angel _ I
can't help that. The truth is I am a family man. I'm also shy and
self-conscious. Above all, I am a gentleman and a sensitive man.''
 &HT;    Well, perhaps in his own eyes. Others _ say, Bill Clinton, for
example _ might not agree.
 &HT;    ``I might have blown my meeting with the president,'' Eszterhas
concedes. ``A few weeks ago, I actually took the White House tour.
Several people asked the guide, `Who is that odd-looking person?'
The tour guide told them I was Russell Crowe from `Gladiator.'
 &HT;    ``Honestly, those tour guides looked very happy to get me out of
there,'' Eszterhas says. ``I asked to speak to the president, and I
was told, `He's out of the country.'
 &HT;    ``Do you think it was true?''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``American Rhapsody,'' consult
the Alfred A. Knopf Web site at www.randomhouse.com/knopf/aak. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
