<P>
   GORE PICKS LIEBERMAN
</P>
<P>
   VP-MAIN _ NASHVILLE _ Gore keeps a low profile here after word
surfaces that he has picked Joseph Lieberman as his running mate.
Meanwhile, Lieberman's staff is already in place, and reaction from
key Democratic groups is positive. (Foskett. Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VP-ANALYSIS A look at the political mathematics behind the
Lieberman pick. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. (With
column sig)
</P>
<P>
   VP-REACT _ Reaction from the Bush camp to Gore's VP selection.
(Heath, Austin American-Statesman). 15-18. ETA: 7:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   VP-LIEBERMAN-PROFILE _ WASHINGTON _ A look at the life and
career of Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut. (Malone, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, Politics
</P>
<P>
   VP-RELIGION _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), the first Jew on
a presidential ticket, is an Orthodox Jew who attends Saturday
prayer services and generally abstains from work on the Sabbath and
major holidays. So how will his religious beliefs affect
Lieberman's campaign schedule in the grueling sprint to election
day? If elected, how will he mesh his devotion to religion with his
duties? (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LIEBERMAN _ JERUSALEM _ If Vice President al Gore expects
his pick of Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman as a runningmate in
the upcoming presidential election will have any effect on his
standing in Israel, he may be a bit mistaken. Although news of
Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, being chosen as Gore's vice president
was near the top of the evening news here Monday, very few Israelis
_ or Palestinians, for that matter _ have ever heard of him.
Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by 4 p.m. (ET) on the NYT Wire in both
International and Politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NATIONAL NEWS
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   HUNLEY _ CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Twenty feet under water, the
Confederate submarine H.L. Hunley has already wowed divers who have
viewed the hydrodynamic design of the first sub to sink an enemy
vessel. Tuesday morning, amid the reverent ringing of church bells,
tens of thousands will scramble for the best viewing spots along
the Cooper River for a glimpse of the iron vessel as a barge
transports it to a North Charleston conservation laboratory. A
curtain riser on anticipation in Charleston. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Amos limps into the cafe
this morning, picks up his decaf from Robin, and hobbles over to
join us. ``Looks like you're just about fit for shootin','' Cal
says to his old buddy. ``Whatsa' matter'' Lucy give you that swift
kick you been asking for?'' Amos pulls over an empty chair to rest
his leg on and sits with an obvious effort. ``I think I got a toe
nail growing in wrong.'' Benny says not to complain because at his
age he's lucky to have anything at all that's still growing.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Not all back-to-school
supplies are bought for kids. Myself, I bought vital equipment for
a high school parent _ a thermos bottle and a coffee mug with a
nearly spillproof plastic top. The high school's late bell will
ring at 7:20 a.m., an hour I have dedicated my life to avoiding.
For the next several years, my kids and I will be consigned to a
world designed for morning people. And a harsh world it is. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   LOWES-FORESTS _ Lowe's will detail its new policy to phase out
``old-growth'' wood a day before its official announcement.
Environmentalists are giddy about Lowe's plan, which they say
outmuscles Home Depot's. Both retailers are requiring vendors to
prove their products come from well-managed forests. And both are
using standards developed by the Forest Stewardship Council, which
has big forest companies irked because they've developed their own
voluntary plan. We'll update Home Depot's progress, plus talk about
thorny issues in the South, where private landowners own most
timberland. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
