<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-TECHMUSEUM-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINO AND THE HOOP AT THE MIAMI MUSEUM OF SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of a visitor using a virtual-reality glove to
play virtual basketball is available on Newscom or by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 By TOBEY GRUMET 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About the last thing that comes to mind when you think about
Miami is technology. But, in addition to theme parks and white sand
beaches, there is a great technology museum just a 20-minute drive
from South Beach. It's the Miami Museum of Science. And while it
may not be as big as the American Museum of Natural History in New
York or as all-encompassing as the Smithsonian in Washington, D.C.,
the Miami Museum of Science has some great exhibits. And you can't
beat the location.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the museum for me is its Sports Challenge.
It's an interactive exhibit that shows you how your body works as
it plays. The centerpiece is the virtual basketball game, in which
you play one-on-one hoops with a computer-generated opponent _
without a ball. Your court consists of a runway to move around on
and a 72-inch Mitsubishi projection television.
</P>
<P>
   Actually playing virtual basketball was more difficult than I'd
anticipated. Here's how it works: First, you slip on a colored
glove that corresponds to a button of the same color on the TV
screen. Next, you have to virtually press the button on the screen,
which to an observer can look like a lively game of blindman's
bluff. It's really very frustrating. Once you manage to coordinate
the button pushing, you're matched up with your opponent and ready
to play.
</P>
<P>
   You quickly become so immersed that you don't even notice that
there's no real ball to shoot and no other human player to block.
You do notice the workout. Coming off the court, I was glowing more
than just a little. I took off the glove and handed it to the
10-year-old waiting in line who was ready to play some serious
hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Two interactive exhibits are designed to teach you about
balance. The first consists of a small step that works like a
miniature seesaw. You put your feet on either side of the step and
hold onto a bar in front of you. When you think you're balanced,
you let go of the bar. A stopwatch times how long you can stay on
the step without falling to one side or the other. Trust me, this
is not as easy as it sounds or looks.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that an average man's balance lasts 5 to 7 seconds
while an average woman's is just 3 to 5 seconds? I lasted for 6.3
seconds, as the years of ballet finally paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The center-of-gravity activity is much easier to master. Here
you have to crouch down, position your hands and knees near each
other on the floor and touch your nose to a dot on the floor. At
least you don't have to worry about falling over for no apparent
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, at another exhibit, is a giant tublike container that is
a big attraction for kids. They are given small silver balls to
hold, similar to those in a pinball machine. Then, they roll the
balls down the spiral well and watch them pick up speed as they get
closer to the center of the tub. This display depicts the effect of
gravity on objects caught in Earth's orbit.
</P>
<P>
   By sheer chance, the day I visited the museum was setting up a
brand-new exhibit called ``Dinosaurs! Journey Through Time.'' At
the time, Disney was getting ready to release its new movie,
``Dinosaur,'' and everyone was going dino-nuts.
</P>
<P>
   This may arguably be the most technology-driven dinosaur exhibit
of its kind. Instead of massive, reconstructed dinosaur skeletons,
the museum's dinosaurs are three-dimensional models made of foam,
rubber and hydraulic mechanics (which use air pressure to work).
So, as well as being able to articulate and move, these dinosaurs
look more realistic than the bone-and-air variety you see at other
museums.
</P>
<P>
   The half-constructed apatosaurus was so lifelike _ even though
his head wasn't yet attached _ that I had to stop to feel his latex
skin and squeeze his body, which squished like a rubber ball.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Duran, the director of exhibits, even let me hold a replica
of a woolly mammoth tusk, which was so big I almost fell over.
</P>
<P>
   If you visit the completed dinosaur exhibit, you'll be given a
``passport'' that will be stamped as you walk through the different
periods of evolution, from the Permian Period to the present. The
tour through time wraps up in the Wildlife Center.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
