<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNNINGSHOE-TECH-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE OLYMPICS NEAR, IT'S SHOE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of track star Ato Boldon springing out of the
starting blocks and one of the Adidas Performance Plate sole are
available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 By CLIFF GROMER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your heart is bursting but the tape and screaming crowds are
only yards away. Let it burst. Rolling across the finish line dead
_ but first _ is better than coming in second.
</P>
<P>
   Training, guts, mental attitude _ they all have a bearing on a
runner's performance. And let's not forget natural talent and
stamina. But there's another factor that can influence how fast a
runner's feet can pump over a track: what's on them. Running shoes
make a difference. Milliseconds make a difference, especially at
the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   To find out some of what's afoot at the upcoming 2000 Games in
Sydney, we spoke with Ciro Fusco, senior researcher for Adidas.
Fusco emphasized that there's no such thing as ``magic shoes.'' No
footwear can help an athlete perform better than his potential.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to minimize inefficiencies that detract from a
performance. Adidas sponsors Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tobago, one
of the best sprinters in the world. The fact that Boldon could best
most runners while wearing wooden clogs is beside the point. Most
runners never make it to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Running shoe theory is an evolving science with different
concepts falling in and out of favor at any time. One of Adidas'
competitors, for example, built its shoes on the principle of
energy return, or spring. Stepping down exerts energy into the
shoe, and that energy comes back to help the runner lift.
</P>
<P>
   Fusco doesn't buy that argument, saying energy return doesn't
work except maybe on a trampoline. The average running stride is on
the order of 12 milliseconds, so even if you have a shoe with
spring, he says, by the time the shoe can return the energy, your
foot is already in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Adidas approach to footwear and other sports gear is one of
energy maintenance. In track and field footwear, Fusco says, think
of the foot as a lever that is pushing an athlete forward while
he's running. This means that when a foot flexes, energy is lost.
</P>
<P>
   Minimizing flex is one way to minimize energy dissipation. Fusco
came up with this energy maintenance concept when Adidas asked him
to conduct research into Olympic gear after the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   When he started the project, Fusco studied how animals that run
evolved. Their heels didn't touch the ground anymore, Fusco found,
so their anatomy apparently had been modified. Such animals stand
on their toes and have very stiff metatarsal joints.
</P>
<P>
   The Adidas research team also worked with the University of
Calgary. A student, who is now a professor, was studying energy
dissipation and energy return at the joints.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the ankle, knee and hip joints in a person who was
jumping, for example, he found that energy is absorbed when there
is a contraction of the joint. Energy is returned when the joint
extends. During the milliseconds that this occurs, a small amount
of energy is lost due to internal dissipation.
</P>
<P>
   But when the student looked at the metatarsal joint, he noticed
something interesting. Energy was only being absorbed, or lost.
There was no energy return. He theorized that perhaps it was not
necessary to bend the foot during certain athletic movements such
as running.
</P>
<P>
   The student brought his findings to Fusco and talked about
stiffening the metatarsal joint to eliminate the dissipation of
energy at that joint. The idea seemed to fit Fusco's comparative
anatomy work and how to make a human foot run more like that of an
animal.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was a full-length, full-width shoe plate,
eventually called the Performance Plate by Adidas, which has the
right stiffness and flexibility so it does not impair movement.
With the plate, the joint isn't stiffened completely. The right
balance of flex and stiffness, needed to minimize energy
dissipation at the metatarsal joint, came only after tests with
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Running shoe spikes basically haven't changed in years, with the
exception of using a lighter-weight ceramic aluminum material.
Fusco and his team looked to see if their energy maintenance
philosophy also could be applied here to pick up a millisecond or
two.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic track surface is called Mondo, after the Italian
company that manufactures it. Rubberlike strips are applied to a
cement foundation, and the result is a uniform surface with good
traction. Sure enough, the friction of conventional metal spikes
puncturing the surface and being pulled out was a source of energy
dissipation. There was room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Mondo supplied Fusco and his team with specs on all of the
mechanical characteristics of the track. The data was used for
finite element analysis and extensive mathematical modeling to come
up with the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The team developed a Z-Spike, so called because of its Z-shaped
cross section. Unlike conventional spikes, the Z-Spike does not
penetrate the track for traction, it deforms it. The acid test,
though, was conducted with athletes.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fusco, the beauty of the Z-Spike is that only three
spikes installed on a shoe give the traction equivalent to a full
set (seven to eight) of conventional spikes. When athletes laced up
the shoes with the Z-Spikes without knowing what was on the
business end of the shoe, Fusco said, they later ``couldn't believe
they were running with only three spikes on the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of the Adidas Olympic running shoe technology will
be filtering down to the general consumer. The Performance Plate,
while customized for each Adidas-shod Olympian, will be optimized
in stiffness and other characteristics for Joe Runner. Fusco and
his research team, in the meantime, are already pursuing the next
breakthrough in running shoe technology, whatever that may be.
</P>
<P>
   And, as for the effectiveness of the new Adidas running shoe
technology, or developments from its competitors, the Games at
Sydney will tell that story.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
