<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MACULARDEGENERATION-T     08-07 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACULARDEGENERATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUG TREATS AGE-RELATED MACULAR DEGENERATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CAROLYN POIROT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Margaret Lewis, 78, went into her bathroom
one morning, stared at her face in the mirror, then shut her left
eye. No one stared back. She was terrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see my face, and that scared the devil out of me,''
Lewis said. ``I have grandchildren, and I love pretty things, and I
just can't ever lose my vision. I'd rather lose anything except my
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Pauline Bailey, 84, of Burleson, Texas, Lewis, who lives in
Fort Worth, drives a car, watches television, reads the paper and
says she does everything for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said her vision is the key to her existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live alone and drive myself wherever I need to go. My vision
is everything to me. I can't imagine not having it,'' Bailey said.
Two years ago she began using drops for glaucoma, but there was
nothing she could do then for the bleeding behind her left retina.
</P>
<P>
   Both women recently participated in a study of light-activated
Visudyne, the first-ever drug treatment to slow vision loss from
the most aggressive form of age-related macular degeneration.
</P>
<P>
   Age-related macular degeneration is the leading cause of
blindness in Americans over 60, affecting an estimated 200,000
people each year. A disorder of the macula, an area of tissue near
the center of the retina, age-related macular degeneration affects
the center of the field of vision, making objects appear dark or
out of focus.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, a laser treatment has been available for a limited
number of patients whose macular degeneration has not progressed
very far, but it carries a strong risk of burning away the center
of the retina entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The new photodynamic therapy involves injecting the drug,
Visudyne, into the patient's arm by IV, waiting a few minutes for
the drug to reach the blood vessels of the eye, and then shining a
low-power laser light into the patient's eye for 83 seconds to
destroy the abnormal vessels and scar tissue without damaging the
retina, said Dr. Gary Cowan, an ophthalmologist with Retina
Consultants of Fort Worth, who directed the study here.
</P>
<P>
   The cool, red-light laser activates the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The new treatment is now FDA approved for what's known as the
wet form of macular degeneration, which occurs when tiny blood
vessels break through a membrane behind the retina and leak blood
and fluid, causing increasing loss of central vision. There is
still no treatment for the dry form, which is caused by scar tissue
building up over the center of the retina.
</P>
<P>
   Age-related macular degeneration ``robs people of the central
vision needed to read, drive and recognize faces,'' Cowan said.
``If you can't stop it, most will lose reading vision in one or
both eyes, and will be unable to drive. You can find the doorway
and avoid furniture _ you can do a lot with peripheral vision _ but
(macular degeneration) is a serious blow to independence. You need
to be able to pull a can from the cupboard and know whether it's
beets or corn without opening it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of patients in pretty good health develop this.
They may have to go to an assisted-living facility because they
can't prepare their own meals, and they were very independent
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the new drug was based on a major study involving 22
medical centers, including the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The new therapy is not a cure, FDA officials caution. While it
can slow retinal damage, it cannot stop vision loss or restore
vision in eyes damaged by age-related macular degeneration, but
patients who take the drug are more likely to have stable vision
after a year than those who do not receive the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The therapy costs about $2,000 per treatment, according to a
spokeswoman for one of its developers, CIBA Vision, a unit of
Novartis AG. The cost is covered by Medicare. Patients in the
studies cited by the FDA received three or four treatments during
the first year. Other studies cited by CIBA Vision suggest that
patients may need only two treatments per year thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any better, but it's not any worse, and I hope
with this treatment it won't get any worse,'' said Bailey, who has
worn glasses for about 60 years. She began developing glaucoma and
macular degeneration two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said she was a little afraid of the treatment but that it
was completely painless, and she believes her vision is a little
better in the affected eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, with my good eye, I can still get on the computer, and I
read and see movies,'' Lewis said. ``If it just stays like it is
right now, I'll be satisfied the rest of my life. The main thing is
that it not progress anymore. If it starts leaking again or the
other eye starts, I'm ready to have the Visudyne again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687, or e-mail:
cpoirot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
