<SLUG> BC-BILTMOREESTATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANDERBILT HOUSE MIRRORS LUXURY OF A BYGONE ERA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL TEETER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ From any high point around Asheville, rugged
hills dominate the landscape for as far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   Especially during the summer, when a thick growth of foliage
adds to the vistas, it's easy to see why George Washington
Vanderbilt III decided 112 years ago that here, on a high Blue
Ridge slope, he would build a home. When completed in 1895,
Biltmore Estate and its centerpiece mansion stood ready to
challenge the grandeur of any other elite property, either in
America or overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The estate, located about 115 miles west of Charlotte, has long
been a stopping place for literary and artistic figures and world
leaders. Writer Edith Wharton, President William McKinley and Fort
Worth's Van Cliburn have visited the estate during its 105-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   But millions of tourists have also traipsed through the Biltmore
since it opened for tours 70 years ago, giving them a glimpse into
a world where a select few resided in opulence unimaginable even to
today's leading CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt, grandson of the railroad and steamship magnate
Cornelius Vanderbilt, in 1889 began construction of an estate that
would include a mansion that is the largest privately-owned home in
the nation, a winery, a botanical conservatory, and woodland and
agricultural land. The 250-room Biltmore house served as home to
Vanderbilt, his wife, Edith, and daughter Cornelia for much of the
year. After Vanderbilt died in 1914, the estate landed in the hands
of Cornelia Vanderbilt and her husband, John Cecil..
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, at the request of Asheville officials, Cornelia
Vanderbilt and Cecil opened the house for tours in hopes of helping
the area's economy as the nation wallowed in the first months of
the Great Depression, said Biltmore spokeswoman Sarah Thomas. The
estate has been accessible to the public ever since, except during
World War II, when Washington's National Gallery of Art sent many
of the nation's art treasures to Biltmore House for safekeeping
during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The estate attracts about 900,000 visitors a year, drawn by the
home's history, art, architecture and botanical treasures, though
most visitors are attracted first by the idea of a European-style
chateau in a rural setting in the United States, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York City, it would be impressive, but perched on the
side of the hill in the tradition of the great homes of Europe, it
is amazing,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon approach, the French Renaissance-style mansion reveals
design elements from European chateaus. A stone, spiral stair tower
by the main front doors is a detail drawn from the Chateau de Blois
in France's Loire Valley. Designers who worked on the estate
include architect Richard Morris Hunt, known as the creative mind
behind the pedestal of the Statue of Liberty and the main facade of
the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York. Frederick Law Olmstead,
who designed New York's Central Park, was the landscape designer.
</P>
<P>
   The chateau's interior features Renaissance-era tapestries,
Oriental rugs and furniture that was antique even as the house was
completed 105 years ago. Other items are original paintings by
Renoir, such as ``Child With an Orange,'' a game table that was
once the property of Napoleon Bonaparte and a piano played by
Cliburn during his visit to the estate in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is original. There is so much more in storage that
we don't know what to do with. There are 250 rooms in the house,
but only 90 of them are open,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore is one of a number of U.S. estates that welcome
paying guests. Several large properties can be seen in Newport,
R.I., and California's somewhat smaller Hearst Castle in San Simeon
draws about 820,000 visitors annually, said Dan Eller, spokesman
for the Hearst Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are American kings and queens, if you look at the
fortunes. The fortunes that these people had and the money they had
to spend are way out of the context of most Americans' lives. There
was no income tax. You made your money and you spent your money as
you wished,'' Eller said. ``Nobody can live like this today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Castle's somewhat smaller main residence is actually
broken into five buildings, Eller said. The Biltmore is a private
holding, with Cecil's son, William A.V. Cecil, serving as chief
executive officer of The Biltmore Co., a private, for-profit
company that operates the estate. The Hearst Castle estate is owned
by the California state parks system, Eller said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Biltmore Estate, the house is what catches the tourist's
eye, but other aspects of the estate are much more important, said
professor of architecture Jay C. Henry of the University of Texas
at Arlington. When work on the estate started, the land had been
denuded by overcutting and poor management by previous owners.
</P>
<P>
   Reforestation efforts under the direction of forester Gifford
Pinchot sparked a movement in landscape conservation in the United
States, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estate is more significant than just the house. It was a
badly eroded landscape, which was then restored,'' Henry said.
``And that helped begin the landscape conservation movement in this
country. In the long run, the restoration of the estate land is
more important than the house.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL INFORMATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Biltmore Estate is on U.S. 25 just north of Exit
50 or 50B off Interstate 40 in Asheville, N.C., 115 miles from
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $32 for adults, $24 for youths 10 to 15. Children
younger than 10 are admitted free with a paying adult. Admission
also covers attendance at special events held periodically on the
estate, with the exception of the summer concert series.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: Visitors should wear casual clothing, including
a comfortable pair of shoes. The mansion tours involved quite a bit
of walking, as do tours of the gardens or the winery. To take in
everything, visitors should be ready to spend most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore has its own gift shop, located in the estate
carriage house area, as well as a cafe, ice cream parlor and
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (800) 543-2961; www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
