<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEECH PROVIDES REASON TO VOTE FOR THE GOVERNOR
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: No. of days to election in last graf presumes Aug. 8
publication date.) 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he so often does, George W. Bush made liars of his critics
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   They had said that he wasn't ready for prime time, that he
lacked ``gravitas,'' that he didn't look or sound ``presidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush delivered a spectacular speech as he accepted the
Republican nomination for president to close out the Grand Old
Party's national convention. But he delivered even more: He
delivered the goods, laying out his compassionate conservative
philosophy in exquisite detail and establishing beyond a doubt that
he is more than ready to serve as president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits had said that Bush's most crucial objective was to
show the American people that he ``fit the chair,'' that he had the
right stuff for national and international leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And show them he did.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to take my word for it. If you think that I'm
a shameless Bush-booster who would say his speech was great even if
it was lousy, then consider the opinions of some card-carrying
members of the liberal media elite who surely wouldn't hesitate to
jump on Bush with both feet if he so much as missed a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose these power hitters at the Cable News Network
would fluff up a Bush performance just to make him look good?
</P>
<P>
   Judy Woodruff: ``Quite a speech. Quite a speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sesno: ``The speech was everything that was promised and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Candy Crowley: ``This was supposed to be the speech of his life,
and he may well have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was this comment by ABC pundit and former Bill Clinton
mouthpiece/strategist George Stephanopoulos: ``It was a pretty
magnificent speech.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Stephanopoulos said that Bush's speech was ``pretty
magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty magnificent in its own right, if you ask me.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, I know what the Bush-bashers are thinking. Anybody can
assemble a team of geniuses to write a speech, then practice
reading it for weeks on end and shoot the lights out reading it in
front of an adoring crowd of political fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yeah. Clinton has been doing it for years.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't just a top-flight performance of a well-written
speech. The speech ``was'' George W. Bush. It gave voice to his
hopes and dreams for his nation and its people. It put into words
his most heartfelt convictions about the importance of character
and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   If you were wondering, ``Why should I vote for Bush?,'' his
speech answered the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will confront the hard issues,'' Bush pledged, ``threats to
our national security, threats to our health and retirement
security, before the challenges of our time become crises for our
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we will extend the promise of prosperity to every
forgotten corner of this country: to every man and woman, a chance
to succeed; to every child, a chance to learn; and to every family,
a chance to live with dignity and hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good, you say? But words won't cut it, you say? It's
action you want?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind those critics who claimed that Bush offered no
specifics. He offered plenty of specifics.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor outlined specific ideas for dealing with
Social Security, Medicare, education, taxes and rebuilding the
military.
</P>
<P>
   True enough, the speech contained no interminable, Clinton-like
gift list of federal programs promising pie-in-the-sky solutions
for every imaginable human grievance or dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush offered vision. He offered leadership.
</P>
<P>
   He offered to ``usher in an era of responsibility'' _ an era in
which all Americans do their part to guarantee that the greatest
nation on earth achieves its potential.
</P>
<P>
   And he offered to restore honor and dignity to America's damaged
presidency:
</P>
<P>
   ``After all of the shouting and all of the scandal, after all
the bitterness and broken faith, we can begin again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wait has been long, but it won't be long now.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it won't be long at all. The election is only 91 days away.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
