<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TREATMENT: When Black Patients Get Slighted
</P>
<P>
   A new study offers still more evidence that when it comes to
health care, black and white patients do not always get equal
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation, the American Heart Association journal, is
reporting on Tuesday that blacks who have had heart attacks are
less likely to receive proven treatments to prevent a recurrence,
even when they are as inexpensive as aspirin or beta-blockers.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted at the Georgetown University, also found
smaller gaps in the treatment of women versus men and low-income
people versus higher ones.
</P>
<P>
   Racial disparities in treatment have increasingly become an
issue in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In this study, researchers evaluated what treatments patients
were given when they entered hospitals and when they left. They
looked at 169,079 Medicare beneficiaries hospitalized from 1994 to
1996.
</P>
<P>
   For patients who have just had heart attacks, so-called
clot-buster drugs and aspirin are known to improve the chances of
survival. After discharge, aspirin and beta-blockers can prevent a
recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   The study found, for example, that in the hospital, about 63
percent of the white patients studied were given clot-busting
drugs, but only about 56 percent of the black ones were. When the
patients left, about 55 percent of the whites got prescriptions for
beta-blockers, while about 50 percent of the blacks did.
</P>
<P>
   While the researchers said they did not believe there was
conscious discrimination, they said more study was needed to
determine why the disparities occurred.
</P>
<P>
   AGING: A Warning Sign Often Overlooked
</P>
<P>
   Doctors routinely overlook a serious sign of osteoporosis, the
condition that leaves older people _ primarily women _ susceptible
to repeated, often immobilizing bone breaks, according to a study
being released today.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which looked at 1,162 postmenopausal women who had
broken one or both their wrists, found that only a quarter had been
evaluated or treated for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The report was published The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery
and was prepared by researchers at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   A broken wrist, the researchers said, is often the first sign of
osteoporosis in women over 55, suggesting decreased bone mineral
density, thus making bones more fragile.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who breaks her wrist at this age may double her chance
of breaking a hip, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after analyzing patient records and pharmacy claims in the
six months after the wrists were broken, the researchers found a
serious failure to diagnose and treat osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the oldest patients, those most at risk, the level
of treatment was even lower.
</P>
<P>
   Only 9.1 percent of the women ages 85 to 89 in the study were
being treated for osteoporosis; 4.2 percent of those 90 to 94; and
4.7 percent of those over 95. This compares with a rate of 36
percent in the women ages 55 to 59.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the study, Dr. Kevin Freedman, said the findings
suggested that doctors needed to be diligent about making sure that
postmenopausal patients being treated for wrist breaks received
good follow-up evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in older patients,'' he said, ``treatment for
osteoporosis does work to maintain or increase bone density and
prevent fractures.''
</P>
<P>
   Osteoporosis is commonly treated with hormone replacement
therapy or drugs that restore the mineral levels in the bones.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: New Clues for Treating a Child's Seizure
</P>
<P>
   When children have seizures, doctors are sometimes put in
quandaries: should they assume the seizure is epilepsy and begin
medicating? Or should they wait and hope it is just an isolated
occurrence?
</P>
<P>
   A new study may shed some light on the best course. In the
current Annals of Neurology, researchers say they have found that
when a child has seizures more than once, the diagnosis probably is
epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of children who have a second seizure go on to
have more. Knowing this may help doctors decide whether long-term
medication, despite the potential for side effects, may be
appropriate, the study said. The report was prepared by researchers
from the Montefiore Medical Center and the Albert Einstein College
of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies, the researchers said, have shown that a single
seizure _ or a set of them over 24 hours _ does not necessarily
mean a child has epilepsy. About a third go on to have second
seizures, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings were based on a study of 407 children under 16
after their first seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the children at the highest risk for
continued seizures were those whose first two convulsions occurred
within six months of each other. Also at risk where those with
neurological conditions like cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   SYMPTOMS: Headaches, With and Without the Pain
</P>
<P>
   A headache without the head pain might sound contradictory, but
the condition, described in a new journal article, could lend
insights into an ailment known as the cluster headache.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors writing in the August 7 issue of Neurology described the
case of a 22-year-old man who had all the symptoms of a cluster
headache, except the pain.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to his doctor, he exhibited nasal stuffiness, a
droopy eyelid and contraction of one of his pupils, all signs of
the painful condition that affects about 1 in 1,000 people, mostly
men.
</P>
<P>
   The patient said he suffered one to three attacks a day, each
lasting an hour or two. After six weeks, the symptoms disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But six years later, the article said, the man came back.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he had the same symptoms, but also severe pain that
lasted 90 minutes, about twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   When he was treated with a drug used for cluster headaches,
sumatriptan, the pain and most of his other symptoms went away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report may guide future cluster headache research in
another direction,'' the author, Dr. Rolf Salvesen of the
University of Tromso in Norway, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   His patient's condition offers evidence that tearing, congestion
and drooping eye associated with cluster headaches are not, as many
believed, a response to the pain, but symptoms in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   TESTING: In Search of the Deep Breath Chemical
</P>
<P>
   The biochemistry of breathing deeply, the one thing an asthmatic
cannot do in the midst of the attack, may hold a key to helping
doctors treat people who have asthma.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study suggests that the mere act of breathing deeply
may stretch lung tissue and cause the release of a protective
chemical that keeps the airways open. Writing in the Journal of
Applied Physiology, researchers from Johns Hopkins University said
that if the chemical could be identified, it could possibly be the
basis of an asthma drug.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers came to the conclusion after studies involving
the drug methacholine, which narrows airways and causes wheezing in
people with asthma. In healthy people, the drug has no effect,
unless they take a series of shallow breaths before taking it,
early studies show.
</P>
<P>
   This time, asthmatic and healthy volunteers were asked to
breathe deeply before being given the drug. While the deep breaths
did not help the people with asthma, they did reduce the adverse
effects of the drug by 85 percent in healthy people, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
