<HEADLINE>
A SURFEIT OF SPADE SINKS `SAMMY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SAMMY 
Starring the voices of: David Spade, Andy Dick, Maura Tierney, Bob
Odenkirk, Jeffrey Tambor 
On: NBC 
Time: Tuesday at 8:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much David Spade is too much David Spade? Your answer to
that question may determine how you'll receive NBC's ``Sammy,'' the
latest of many animated series trying for prime-time popularity.
The sarcasm-laced comedy is produced by Spade, stars the voice of
Spade in two lead roles, and is a parody of the real-life
relationship between Spade and his father, Wayne Spade.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's an awfully tall glass of Spade, with no
bubbles and not a hint of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a little too much Spade for this viewer. The makers of
``Just Shoot Me,'' Spade's other NBC sitcom, got it right from the
start, portioning out the famously snide comic's gags in small
doses. Seemingly aware that Spade's adolescent ridiculing can
quickly turn bitter and grating, they've kept him as a supporting
player and softened his arrogance with geekiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy,'' on the other hand, finds Spade's angry, wounded
adolescence trapped in a hall of mirrors. The show revolves around
Spade stand-in James Blake, an ironic sitcom star voiced by Spade.
In each episode, he is victimized by his freeloading dad, Sammy, an
absentee father who appears out of the blue once his son has become
rich and famous. Sammy is a bad joke of a man, a shameless
womanizer who sneaks around his son's mansion with young actresses
and uses over-the-top come-on lines like ``Just quit the grinnin'
and drop the linen, we're going to do some sinnin'.'' In case we
aren't sufficiently annoyed by Sammy, Spade provides him with a
shrill, fingers-on-chalkboard voice.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting voices are easier to take, particularly Andy Dick
as James's agent and Maura Tierney as his assistant. And Julia
Sweeney puts in a warm guest appearance in the premiere as his
protective mother. She comes to Hollywood to save James from his
sleazy father, and, predictably, she becomes ensnared by his
low-rent charms. Quickly, though, she sees through his games and
wises up.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-hour of Sammy's tiresome pranks, you might find
yourself wanting to follow her out of his clutches once and for
all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
