<HEADER>
A4885 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-TEXAS-HOBBY-NYTS     08-07 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-TEXAS-HOBBY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AS THE TEXANS LIKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Monday, Aug. 7, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By PAUL W. HOBBY    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Politically, Texas is caught in crossfire because our
governor, George W. Bush, is running for president. Every
shortcoming, real or imagined, has been cited by his detractors as
proof of government failure or a heartless culture. Despite Bush's
warning in his nomination speech on Thursday not to ``mess with
Texas,'' the broadsides will continue because of the way America
elects presidents. A majority of Texans will be voting for Bush,
and the Electoral College will issue no transferable credits to Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Even if I didn't understand the politics of it all, the Texan in
me cares very little about whether others approve of us. If to be
different is to be criticized, bring it on. My deepest concern is
that someday we won't be different, that creeping suburbanization
will dilute a spirit based on perseverance and personal integrity.
</P>
<P>
   I am no shill for the Bush campaign; Bush replaced me as
chairman of a state agency after his first election and openly
campaigned against me in 1998, when I ran for state comptroller and
was the state's leading Democratic vote-getter. But I appreciate
what is different about Texas, and it boils down to this: In our
view freedom is so intertwined with individual risk that the two
are almost indistinguishable at the core.
</P>
<P>
   In my experience, many other places don't admire risk-taking,
but only the successes it may bring. Here, we admire boldness and
optimism even in failure, because real freedom has to include the
freedom to fail.
</P>
<P>
   As a progressive, I think government can work, can inspire, and
should help those who are deserving; but as a Texan, I strongly
resent the presumption of a bureaucracy that meddles in everyone's
life instead of focusing on the few bad actors who live outside the
social contract.
</P>
<P>
   Rugged individualism hasn't always served us well. We have been
slow to embrace collective notions like environmental planning,
lackluster in our commitment to public education and uneven in our
efforts to heal racial discrimination. But our way is still closer
to the American ideal.
</P>
<P>
   As good an example as any is the story of my family's visits to
our nation's beaches. Massachusetts made us take a life preserver
off our son because the government had decided that devices to keep
children from sinking can lead to overconfidence. California said
we could not throw a Frisbee or roast marshmallows without
permission. Florida said we needed a permit for our dog before we
could throw a ball to him.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, all our beaches are the property of people to enjoy
with an absolute minimum of ``mother-may-I.'' We welcome all of
those from elsewhere, but they can't expect the authorities to
guard them against every ripple of risk and every chance that
someone might behave badly.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude goes well beyond beaches. By careful design, we
allow our Legislature to convene only for four and a half months
every other year because the tendency of collective bodies is to
create process. And each little piece of process is a razor cut
bleeding away individual freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has some internal issues to address, but we don't need a
more expansive view of government to be mainstream American.
Jefferson didn't write the Declaration of Independence, and
Washington didn't cross the Delaware, so we could create a
government to protect us from ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul W. Hobby, a Houston businessman, is former chairman of the
Texas General Services Commission and was chief of staff to former
Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
