<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SEGAL-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      08-07 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGAL-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRIAL BEGINS FOR ADMIRED DOORMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Houston, Minneapolis)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The day after Anton Segal got smacked hard on
the head by an angry man with a makeshift weapon, friends rushed to
his side.
</P>
<P>
   They came from as far as Hong Kong to stand by Segal, 28, while
he lay in San Francisco General Hospital, unable to recover from a
blow that cracked open his skull. On Nov. 24, 1998 _ three days
after the attack _ Segal died.
</P>
<P>
   The police quickly learned that Segal, a doorman at the Roaring
20's strip club in North Beach, did not fit the stereotype of a
hoochie-coochie barker. A Harvard graduate and published writer,
fluent in five languages, Segal was ``a really sharp guy,'' said
homicide Inspector John Hennessey. ``This was a tragic loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses had recorded the license plate number of the suspect's
brown van. Within days the police arrested Daniel Alas, 32, an
ex-convict from San Mateo working as a plumber at San Francisco
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Alas' murder trial is being held this week in San Francisco
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   For Jim and YoYo Segal, Anton's parents from Houston, the
criminal proceedings mark the final chapter in a life that once
seemed pregnant with promise.
</P>
<P>
   Segal, a Texan of Japanese and Jewish ancestry, arrived in San
Francisco in April 1998 from Egypt. Before that, he had toured
Southeast Asia and lived in Japan. By the time he left Houston for
Harvard in 1987, he already had visited five continents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much more I want to see and do,'' Segal wrote in
his Harvard application essay. ``I want to learn how mountain
gorillas make love and war. I want to learn the clicking language
of the Bantu, to study Zorastrianism and Zen.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knew ``what I do not want to be. I do not want to be a
doctor, lawyer or industrial chief. I don't want a BMW and a
Manhattan townhouse. I prefer a camel and a yurt.''
</P>
<P>
   During Harvard registration, Segal loaned a pencil to a
``buttoned down, straight and narrow'' freshman from Minneapolis
named Stephen Yi. As they left the building, Yi recalled, they
encountered a political radical ``peddling extreme left-wing
literature. I, of course, thought this guy was a complete freak and
wanted to stay away from him. Anton just walked up and started
talking to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yi, who earned a law degree from Harvard and now works for an
Internet company in Pasadena, Calif., said he and Segal became fast
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Segal also befriended dorm mates Stu Finkel and Elizabeth
``Betsy'' Flanagan. Each would play a role in his final hours.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating with a degree in anthropology, Segal ``went
abroad and began teaching in Japan and working with young high
school and junior high school students there,'' his father said.
``He was very much an adventurer.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been genetic. Anton's dad, Jim Segal, had ``trekked
in Nepal, hitched through the Khyber Pass, worked in Japan, lived
with headhunters in Borneo,'' Anton proudly reported in his Harvard
application essay. In Japan, Jim Segal met and married a woman
named YoYo _ ``born Shintoist in wartime Tokyo, raised as a
Buddhist, educated in an Episcopalian school in Kyoto.''
</P>
<P>
   They settled in Houston when Anton was 10. They have two other
children: Laurie, 36, a psychotherapist in Long Island, N.Y., and
Erica, 28, a television producer in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Segals were supportive of Anton's adventurous lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``While other people were going for big bucks and big offices .
. . Anton really was interested in gathering stories of an
underclass,'' Jim Segal said. ``He lived on 30 cents a day. He
hitchhiked through China. He worked with many of the disadvantaged
people throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending several years abroad, Segal moved to California,
where he reconnected with his old Harvard chums, Finkel and Yi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had asked him if he wanted to come live with me in San
Francisco for the summer, so he took me up on the offer,'' Yi said.
Both were surprised when Segal landed a job as doorman at the
Roaring 20's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was sort of typical Anton, doing something wild
and crazy again, trying to experience something else that he could
write about,'' Yi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked working there because it was something unusual and
different and exciting,'' said Finkel, who is working on his
doctorate in history at Stanford University. ``It was the closest
he could come back here to the different sorts of experiences he
had abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Segal fit in well with the striptease crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was generous. He was a gentleman. He would never flirt with
the girls, but the girls would flirt with him because he was
trustworthy and he was kind,'' said Jaguar, 24, a dancer who goes
by her stage name. ``He knew all the homeless people on the street
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Segal had been on a fast track at the Roaring 20's. On the
evening of Nov. 21, he was going to manage the club by himself for
the first time, according to Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was scared,'' she recalled. ``He had fear in his
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Sam Archer, disagreed, noting the Segal _ while short
in stature _ was a prize-winning bodybuilder with a black belt in
tae kwan do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could look after himself but he would do anything to avoid
a confrontation,'' he said. ``He was a very confident man.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night a man the police identified as Alas approached
the Roaring 20's entrance, where Segal barred his way because he
was carrying an open beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told by one of the witnesses that when Anton turned Alas
away from the bar . . . he put his arm around the guy and said,
'Hey buddy, don't worry. Finish your beer and come on back and you
can get into the club,''' Jim Segal said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Alas returned later that evening and struck Segal
on the head with a piece of car security equipment known as The
Club. Segal crumbled to the sidewalk and his attacker fled in a
brown van.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the club, strippers whom Segal had befriended broke down
in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customers were crying,'' Jaguar said. ``They were punching
walls. They said, `Why did it have to be him?'''
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance picked up Segal and accelerated down Broadway. A
block away it slowed slightly while a pedestrian scurried out of
the way: It was Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That night I went for a walk in North Beach and saw an
ambulance and walked right by where it happened,'' she said. ``I
had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Alas was arrested, Segal had died. The charge was
first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gaines, the court-appointed lawyer for Alas, could not
be reached for comment, but motions he filed in court indicate a
possible line of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines might raise a combination of two legal defense concepts _
``voluntary intoxication'' and ``imperfect self-defense.'' In
short, he could claim that Alas was so drunk he believed,
incorrectly, that Segal represented a threat.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury accepts that argument, Alas might be found guilty of
voluntary manslaughter instead of murder.
</P>
<P>
   It would be his second felony conviction. In 1988, he received
three years probation on a robbery rap. Later his probation was
revoked and he was sentenced to two years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
