r e BC-SIDEBAR-WHIRL-LADN &LR;      08-07 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDEBAR-WHIRL-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Sidebar to `Whirl.' A copy of this story is also being
transmitted to lifestyle wire.)) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bewildering array of groups has erupted in the past couple of
years in Los Angeles, sponsoring various Net-related social and
business events. Here's a quick rundown on a few of the most
notable:
</P>
<P>
   VIC (at www.thevic.org) is the 800-pound gorilla of the Net
social whirl. When it was founded five years ago, its initials
stood for Venice Interactive Community. In a few weeks, with an
infusion of capital, a conversion to for-profit status and a
wide-ranging expansion to dozens of other cities, VIC will stand
for Virtual International Community, said executive director Brad
Nye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've created a monster that's too big for me,'' said Nye only
half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   VIC now has 20 employees running six to 10 events a month of
various sorts for 2,000 members who pay $125 to $250 a year to
belong, plus extra fees for some events.
</P>
<P>
   VIC also is opening the Digital Evolution Center, a
10,000-square-foot headquarters and career development facility
just off Santa Monica's Third Street Promenade.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly Zone Club features a couple of high-profile local
speakers as the evening's centerpiece, with cocktails beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Members also get subscriptions to tech business magazine Zone
News, access to libraries of business information, invitations to
special events and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all really comes down to creating the culture here,'' said
David Cremin of Zone Ventures. ``We wanted to catalyze the
technology culture. We've been able to accelerate and catalyze this
process. We're still a few years behind Silicon Valley, but a
couple of years ago we were a decade behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Zone Club's proceeds go to a variety of local
charities, such as New Economics for Women and L.A. Shares, that
help improve the community, Cremin said.
</P>
<P>
   STEP UP, which Kaye Popofsky founded to help mentor women in
entertainment and technology, also has a philanthropic aspect.
Every year it raises hundreds of thousands of dollars for
organizations devoted to breast cancer research and women's and
children's health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mantra is that community and social activities and career
shouldn't be separated, especially in entertainment,'' said
Popofsky.
</P>
<P>
   First Tuesday started in London about a year ago, and has now
spread to 85 cities, mostly in Europe but including 10 U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people here in Los Angeles saw First Tuesday
as an opportunity to tap into the global business over there,''
said local chapter founder Giovanna Imbesi.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which now charges $10 for its monthly events,
typically features a panel of notables discussing a key technology
issue.
</P>
<P>
   First Tuesday's L.A. operation is an outgrowth of another
long-running social/business gathering, Pho, named after the
Chinatown Vietnamese soup restaurant where people interested in
music and technology have gathered on Sunday afternoons for more
than two years. It, too, has spawned chapters in 10 other cities.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these and other groups, such as
iHollywood, the Association of Internet Professionals, e-Brew and
others, go the Digital Coast Roundtable's Web site, at
www.digitalcoast.org, which lists the groups and contact
information.
</P>
<P>
   Also, try the Southern California Technology Calendar, at
www.socaltechcalendar.com, for free listings of events by dozens of
tech groups of many kinds, from Santa Barbara to San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
