 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a night of painfully limited viewing options, consider taking
a look at two of the Sci Fi Channel's original series that are
making a minor splash for the cable network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Invisible Man,'' airing at 8 and repeating at 11, stars
Vincent Ventresca as Darien Fawkes, a former small-time thief who
agrees, as an alternative to prison, to become a guinea pig in a
secret government experiment run by his brother. The mysterious
Quicksilver gland implanted at the base of Darien's skull allows
him to become invisible at will, but also turns him toward the dark
side, a la Mr. Hyde. Tonight, he discovers his ex-wife is seeing an
undercover agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farscape,'' at 9 and midnight, is one of those
across-the-galaxy-with-a-crew-of-assorted-aliens shows that pay
homage to ``Star Trek.'' Ben Browder stars as our hero, Crichton,
who's found himself very far from home. Tonight he and the gang
have to save the fierce D'Argo (Anthony Simcoe, under lots of alien
makeup) by catching a shape-shifting parasite.
</P>
<P>
   A third series, the lesser ``Lexx,'' airs at 10 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NFL preseason football, CBS at 8: The New York Giants visit the
Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Blues,'' WB at 8: Back-to-back episodes of the animated
series based on the comic strip about the trials and tribulations
of new parents. Job envy and a trip to the family fun center are
tonight's topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence,'' NBC at 8: Syd's mentor (guest star John Getz)
thinks he's found a case of Munchausen by proxy, in which a mother
causes her child harm because she enjoys the attention it brings.
But Syd (series star Melina Kanakaredes) offers another diagnosis.
Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline,'' NBC at 9: How to get families out of public
housing? An experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Americans,'' WB at 9: Parents' Weekend bears down on the
school. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the Band,'' ABC at 9:30: Ikaika's out. How will they
ever replace him? (A rerun of the previous episode airs at 9.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan,'' Disney Channel at 7:30: Animated 1998 musical about a
young Chinese girl who takes her father's place in battle and
becomes a hero. Voice cast includes Ming-Na Wen, Lea Salonga, Eddie
Murphy, B.D. Wong, Donny Osmond and Harvey Fierstein. Matthew
Wilder (a one-hit wonder in the '80s with ``Break My Stride'')
wrote the songs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon, The First Movie,'' HBO at 7:15: If you don't already
have it on tape ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Say Anything ...'' FX at 8: John Cusack stars in this 1989
Cameron Crowe film about a high school senior in love with a
beautiful honor student. Ione Skye and John Mahoney (``Frasier'')
play the girl and her protective father. Cusack's sister Joan has a
small uncredited role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psycho,'' American Movie Classics at 8: OK, we've all seen
this 1960 Alfred Hitchcock chiller a hundred times, but it's still
one of the signature films of the second half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Rollins, Live and Ripped in London,'' Comedy Central at
9: OK, the pumped-up punk rocker and poet is not exactly Richard
Pryor or Robin Williams. And maybe this standup routine is more
performance art than comedy. Still, worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Awful Truth,'' Bravo at 11: Michael Moore's latest work of
TV anarchy looks at NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Sam Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Bob Costas, Maria
Bello of the new movie ``Coyote Ugly'' and musical guest Victoria
Williams.
</P>
<P>
