<HEADLINE>
$ADV10 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release THU., AUG. 10, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reba McIntyre hosts ``The 2nd Annual Family Television Awards''
at 9 on CBS. It may sound like a show with a specific audience in
mind, but it's not all ``Touched By An Angel.'' In fact, the
winners are a diverse, high-quality group.
</P>
<P>
   The show honors TV that the whole family can watch together. The
winners' list was announced last week, so we can tell you that CBS'
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' garnered the best comedy award, and
NBC's ``West Wing'' nabbed best drama.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Fox was named best actor for his final season on
ABC's ``Spin City.'' It's an odd ``family'' choice, considering how
much sex talk is on that show, but maybe he gets points for his
battle with Parkinson's Disease.
</P>
<P>
   Best actress _ you knew this had to happen, right? _ goes to
Della Reese of CBS' ``Touched By An Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Wonderful World of Disney'' gets the lifetime
achievement award. CNBC's ``National Geographic Explorer'' gets
best cable series. ABC's ``Oprah Winfrey Presents: Tuesdays with
Morrie'' wins best movie.
</P>
<P>
   In an ironic twist, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' lands the
award for best alternative programming _ whatever that is. Ironic
because ``Millionaire'' also airs at 9 tonight, on ABC, and will
likely get a larger audience than this special.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: And speaking of irony, isn't it
strange that the network airing the ``Family Television Awards''
also airs this demeaning spectacle?
</P>
<P>
   ``Piano Grand,'' PBS at 8: Bill Joel, Diana Krall, Dave Brubeck
and Jerry Lee Lewis are some of the performers in this two-hour
piano special honoring the great tinklers of the ivory. It's tied
to a major Smithsonian exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends,'' NBC at 8: The one where Ross begins dating a
student (Alexandra Holden) whose father turns out to be Bruce
Willis. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys on the Side,'' Fox at 8: Our chick flick du jour. Whoopi
Goldberg, Mary-Louise Parker, Drew Barrymore and Matthew
McConaughey star in this R-rated 1995 Thelma-and-Louise-and-Louise
tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown,'' UPN at 8: The opposite of the family-TV
awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC at 9: Debbie Reynolds guests as Grace's
mother, who brings along a man _ for Will. Grace is miffed. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed,'' WB at 9: Battle with a water demon at a summer camp
has a personal angle for the sisters. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``SpongeBob SquarePants,'' Nickelodeon at 8: SpongeBob and
Patrick convince Mr. Krabs to join in a friendly board game of
``Treasure Hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking Apart: Families Under the Influence,'' HBO at 7:15: A
look at how alcoholism affects three New York families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hustler,'' American Movie Classics at 8: Paul Newman and
Jackie Gleason at their best, with George C. Scott and more _ look
for Jake ``Raging Bull'' LaMotta _ in the 1961 pool room drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleopatra,'' Turner Classic Movies at 8: The 1913 silent
directed by Charles Gaskill, starring Helen Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swept Away ... By an Unusual Destiny in the Blue Sea of
August,'' Bravo at 8: Lina Wertmuller's arty, sexy, class-focused
1976 comedy about a shipwrecked aristocrat and a hunky Marxist.
</P>
<P>
   ``MTV Real World Reunion 2000,'' MTV at 11:30: Former castmates
get back together. Maybe they'll reveal what they really think
about ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Jennifer Lopez
and Eels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Sarah Jessica
Parker of ``Sex and the City,'' cable bigmouth Chris Matthews and
rainforest protector Sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: Spike
Lee, D.L. Hughley, Steve Harvey and Cedric the Entertainer. Think
they'll talk about race?
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Donald
Sutherland of ``Space Cowboys.'' &QL; 
