<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-FOSSIL-EXPANSION-1000     08-07 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSIL-EXPANSION-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL WATCH COMPANY DEVELOPS INTO A HIP, RETAIL CLOTHING CHAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 RICHARDSON, Texas _ There's something familiar about the brand-new
clothing store in one of the big malls in Fort Worth, 45 miles or
so to the east of Richardson. Quirky pop music (heavy on the Moby)
provides an energetic shopping soundtrack. Khakis and skirts, jeans
and T-shirts have coordinating accessories available at the
counter. For cotton collectors, grand-opening T-shirts are a gift
with purchase. And on well-spaced wood-and-metal tables, crisply
folded jeans and shirts are stacked in neat rows to draw in
youthful casual-clothes shoppers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The store has the fresh-scrubbed, adolescent ambience of
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch combined with the friendly attitude of Old Navy
and a design sensibility echoing that of the venerable Gap.
</P>
<P>
   But, nope _ it's Fossil, Inc. You know, the watch people. The
Richardson-based company _ which has been on a winning streak since
it sold its first watches in the mid-1980s _ has already made a
solid name for itself in the world of accessories. After years of
soaring sales of watches and leather goods, Fossil is branching out
into clothing; more than a dozen apparel stores will open across
the country this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a company that began in a warehouse with a ``watch''
product that didn't even work. How does a little company with a
handful of employees importing watches evolve into a worldwide
company _ with a reported $420 million in net sales last year _
ready to take on retail giants like the Gap? Maybe it's all about
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Marketing indeed. We've heard tales about the two Greek brothers
who started Fossil out of a garage 16 years ago. We want to know
more about Tom Kartsotis and his brother Kosta (who still are CEO
and president, respectively), but when we call Fossil we're told
the Kartsotis brothers don't give interviews. Not only are they
very private people, but, we are informed, Fossil isn't about the
founders. Fossil is about everyone who works there.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   So instead, we talk to John Talbott, who is the company's vice
president for, uh, marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott offers a tour of the company headquarters, complete with
a running commentary on the company's past, its present, its future
... and its marketing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a company that looks very closely at what's
selling,'' Talbott said. ``Our idea has always been to try a lot of
things and find out which ones the consumers respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes those consumers surprise you. The company first
hit it big in 1986 with a wrist sundial. As in, an ancient Egyptian
timepiece in convenient wristwatch form. That's right: Fossil's
first big watch wasn't really a watch at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work; it was just a plastic sundial,'' Talbott said.
But the item sold out in stores. Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   The company knew it was onto something big, though. The sundial
watch was part of a group called the Fossil Collection, novelty
watches that had a stonelike, ``fossilized'' look to them. The
entire collection sold well, so the company, which had opened two
years earlier as a watch-importing company, changed directions; it
started ``designing'' watches full time and changed its name from
the clunky Overseas Product Co. to the simple and catchy
``Fossil.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Fossil pays tribute to the product that made it big: In
front of the company's headquarters in Richardson, a giant yellow
sundial protrudes from the ground. (This one really works, we're
informed. We don't doubt it; these people make timepieces.)
</P>
<P>
   After the sundial, Fossil expanded its watch line and gained a
foothold in the fashion industry. In 1989, offbeat marketing
brilliance struck again. The company began packaging some of its
watches in colorful tin boxes decorated with black-and-white photos
and classic images from the 1950s. Guess what _ the boxes were a
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried a few (tins) with the '50s imagery, and lo and
behold, again we found out _ wow! Those watches that are in the tin
box are selling really well! Why don't we put everything in a tin
box?'' Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   So they did. The limited-edition tins _ with 120 new designs
every year _ have been given away with accessories purchases ever
since. The tins are collectors' items. The free-gift-with-purchase
concept makes Fossil products even more appealing. And the tins'
blend of modern and retro American design has become a Fossil brand
image.
</P>
<P>
   Tins are lined up in display cases at Fossil's headquarters,
mixed in with some classic watches and 1950s Americana. It's a
temptation to stand there, cooing over the cute boxes, but Talbott
is ready to whisk through the rest of the building. To the design
department, where designers use high-tech software and equipment
and work to get new products into stores while they're still
trendy. To the creativity department, where messy desks and easels
nearly hide the artists at work on new Fossil designs (Fossil
creates 250-300 new watch models each year). To the Web department,
where designers are working on the newest part of Fossil's Web site
(www.fossil.com), which offers clothing from the new apparel line.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Talbott's tour has made it back to the starting
point _ the marketing department _ we're completely sold on the
company. We don't just want a watch from Fossil _ we want a JOB
from Fossil. Fossil marketing has worked its magic again, even on
the cynical press.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   With Fossil's marketing techniques, it's no wonder the company
has grown steadily since its watch lines took off in 1986. It
expanded with leather goods in the early 1990s and soon after, the
company went public on the NASDAQ exchange as FOSL. In 1995, Fossil
moved into the sunglasses market; each new venture has been
welcomed by eager buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Fossil doesn't over-invest in inventory until a product shows
success with consumers, explained Talbott. When a product sells
well, Fossil then goes wild producing more, with numerous
variations; the unsuccessful products simply don't stay. Stores
don't keep much inventory around, so nothing gets old. And Fossil
has more than 30 outlet stores to get rid of old inventory.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Make more of what works and less of what doesn't' is
basically our methodology,'' Talbott said. ``It sounds so simple,
but it's really sort of different from the way a lot of fashion
companies operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, whatever the company's methodology is, it's working.
Fossil is distributed in more than 80 countries worldwide, with
subsidiaries throughout Europe, and in Japan and China. In fact,
Talbott said a full third of Fossil's business is in other
countries. And Fossil sells more products through another line
called Relic, which can be found in middle-tier stores, such as
Target and J.C. Penney.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said the current expansion of Fossil with an apparel
line was ``a natural evolution.'' It was simply time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought we would be in apparel,'' he said. ``We've
always kind of had that in the back of our mind.''
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, Fossil stores will open in more than a dozen
locations, including New York, Los Angeles, Atlanta, Seattle,
Minnesota's Mall of America.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   So what about this new clothing? It's nice. Casual.
All-American. But like Fossil's watches and other accessories, it's
not unusual or spectacular. Instead, it's basic, midpriced,
youthful _ and extremely well-marketed.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fort Worth store, which opened in the last week of July,
already has a lot of young people meandering through. That's
appropriate; the merchandise is aimed at buyers ages 16 to 24, many
of whom will probably wander over from the neighboring outposts of
Banana Republic and the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is on trends, said Julie Kramer, Fossil's vice
president of merchandising for stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's whatever's happening at the moment: beaded, western,
fringe, animal, studded, embellished in any way,'' she said. ``It's
very young and very trendy in nature _ right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiming merchandise at 16- to 24-year-olds ``right now'' is a
good business move for Fossil. The age group has tremendous
purchasing power, with lots of money to spend on clothing and
accessories; the average American teen had $94 a week of disposable
income last year. Fossil has gotten its share of that wealth
through accessories sales; the brand appeals most to young
consumers already.
</P>
<P>
   But the gimmicks and packaging _ in other words, great marketing
_ are what will attract young buyers to the clothing line.
Different jeans styles have names _ Norm, Jessie, Ginger, Dale.
Shirts have appealing freebies attached to hang tags _ on the
current knit tops, it's a mini-sticker book. Online buyers are
currently offered a free notebook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all kinds of really cool giveaway free items every
month _ maybe it's a notebook, maybe it's a sticker pad, maybe it's
a Christmas ornament,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   The giveaways will change constantly; so will the merchandise
and the labels. It's a brilliant marketing move _ which is just
what to expect from Fossil.
</P>
<P>
   There's a high emphasis on packaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, when you open a store, you can choose to
decide what you want to be ... or you can just copy someone,''
Kramer said. You can say, ``I want to be Banana Republic,' or `I
want to be Abercrombie' like the rest of the retail world wants to
be, and you go knock that off. Well, who needs another one of THOSE
out there?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   To the casual shopper, the new Fossil apparel store _ which also
offers a youthful selection of the company's watches and
accessories _ looks, well, a lot like those other stores.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something that works about Fossil. The jeans and
cotton shirts, khakis and knit tops are as appealing as they are
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   If Fossil clothing has a trademark look, it's a lack of a
trademark _ a look that Kramer calls random.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just Fossil,'' she said. ``We're random and it's
random. It all somehow comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FOSSIL TIMELINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1986 _ The first line of Fossil watches features a sundial
``watch'' that catches the attention of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   1989 _ Fossil introduces tin boxes, designed using graphics from
the 1950s. The tin boxes become a company trademark.
</P>
<P>
   1992 _ The company launches a line of small leather goods and
belts for women.
</P>
<P>
   1993 - Men's small leather goods appear, at the same time Fossil
goes public.
</P>
<P>
   1995 _ Fossil sunglasses are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   2000 _ Fossil apparel stores open, with 16 locations planned
across the country. The first is at Hulen Mall in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
