<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     08-07 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Aug. 8. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-WAHID (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ A newly humble President
Abdurrahman Wahid apologized Monday for falling short of
expectations as Indonesia gropes for a political path after 32
years of dictatorship and said he would name an executive minister
to bring order to his flailing administration. In a state-of-the
nation speech that opened a restive annual parliamentary session,
Wahid said he would in the future concentrate more on foreign
affairs _ he has visited 30 countries, some several times, since
taking office 10 months ago _ and create a sort of prime
ministerial post to handle day-to-day domestic administration.
Admired for his integrity, democratic ideals and intellect, Wahid
has drawn constant criticism for his disorganized and impulsive
leadership style, particularly at a time when Indonesia struggles
with economic collapse, sectarian violence and political disarray.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LIEBERMAN (Nashville) _ Vice President Al Gore picked Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut to be his running mate on Monday,
putting a Jewish candidate on a national ticket for the first time
in history but one whose more conservative voting record puts him
at odds with some of the party's bigger constituency groups. Gore
will not formally announce his selection until Tuesday. Lieberman,
58, is known chiefly on the national stage as the first Democrat to
condemn President Clinton during the Monica Lewinsky scandal,
branding his behavior ``immoral.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3,8,10,11.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-PROFILE (Undated) _ A man-in-the-news profile of
Senator Lieberman. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-SPLIT (Undated) _ Ending one of corporate America's
most bitter family feuds, an international arbitrator gave Andersen
Consulting the right to separate itself from its parent firm but
forced it to give up its name and to pay $1 billion in exchange.
The decision cleaves the world's largest consulting firm, with
65,000 employees, from Arthur Andersen, the largest accounting firm
with 77,000. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NILE-VIRUS (Undated) _ West Nile virus appears to be
settling in for the long haul. Almost one year after the Western
Hemisphere debut of the virus sent 62 people to hospitals,
eventually killing 7 of them with severe brain inflammation, the
bird-carried, mosquito-transmitted disease has struck again.
Despite widespread spraying, many scientists expect that a
scattering of such cases and a few deaths, mostly in the elderly or
infirm, may well become the norm in years to come. More slowly than
expected, but steadily, the globe-hopping virus is dispersing from
last year's focal point in northern Queens County, in New York,
leaving a trail of dead birds that so far extends north to Boston,
west to Syracuse, N.Y., and south to Maryland. According to virus
experts, this pattern indicates that West Nile, which was first
identified in Uganda in 1937 and flares up sporadically in Africa,
Europe and the Middle East, appears ensconced in the New World. By
Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CULTURE-THOUGHT (Undated) _ Western philosophers and
psychologists have based their discussions of mental life on a
cardinal assumption: that the same basic processes underlie all
human thought, whether in the mountains of Tibet or the grasslands
of the Serengeti. Cultural differences might dictate what people
thought about. But the habits of thought were the same for
everyone, exemplified by, among other things, a devotion to logical
reasoning, a penchant for categorization and an urge to understand
situations and events in linear terms of cause and effect. Recent
work, however, is turning this long-held view of mental functioning
upside down. A series of studies comparing European Americans to
East Asians has found that people who grow up in different cultures
do not just think about different things: they think differently.
By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-KRONE (Undated) _ Julie Krone, who made it to the winner's
circle 3,545 times in a 19-year career, becomes the first woman to
be inducted into the National Racing Hall of Fame. ``I want this to
be a lesson to all kids everywhere,'' Krone said in her acceptance
speech. ``If the stable gate is closed, climb the fence.'' By Joe
Drape.
</P>
</TEXT>
