<SLUG> BC-BAND-REALITYTV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VH1 REALITY SHOW PUTS FLICKERSTICK IN THE HOT SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For local rock band Flickerstick, ``The Real
World'' is their real world.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Fort Worth-based alternative-rock quintet filmed
a pilot for a new show on cable music channel VH1, ``Bands on the
Run,'' which, if picked up, will start airing next year.
</P>
<P>
   It's yet another ``reality'' program, in which the band's every
move will be filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Because the group signed a confidentiality agreement, similar to
those signed by the cast and crews of ``The Real World, Survivor,
Big Brother'' and other like-minded, tight-lipped shows, the band
cannot discuss the details of what happened on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   They must, in other words, carefully tiptoe through this
interview; ditto for their manager, Paul Bassman; the show's
director, Dan Cutforth; and, well, just about anyone and everyone
associated with ``Bands on the Run.'' ``Please don't quote me,'' is
a recurring, uh, quote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep our noses clean with VH1,'' said the
band's lead singer, Brandin Lea, when asked about the show. ``They
don't want us to talk about what happened because, well, they want
people to watch the show and see for themselves. The worst part
about it is, we don't know what we CAN say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This much is known, though: At this point, the show chronicles
the lives of the members of Flickerstick _ and two other national
bands _ while they're on a 13- to 20-week U.S. tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is following these three bands on tour, and
looking at life on the road, and the dynamics and inner workings of
a band,'' said Jane Lipsitz, vice president of development for VH1.
</P>
<P>
   And like on ``Survivor,'' a competition is involved.
</P>
<P>
   Lipsitz said the music channel will book the three bands in
various clubs, and whichever band promotes its shows the hardest _
in other words, gets the most people out to its gigs _ will win a
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what the (prize) is, but it'll be a
significant one for an independent band,'' Lipsitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The VH1 gig could not have come at a better time for
Flickerstick, which is rounded out by Brandin's brother, bassist
Fletcher Lea, guitarists Cory Krieg and Rex James Ewing, and
drummer Dominic Weir.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 15, the group will release a new CD, ``Welcoming Home
the Astronauts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one reason why we went ahead and decided to do this: to
get the CD heard,'' says Brandin Lea. ``We talked about it for a
long time, you know, `Do we really want to have cameras following
us around for weeks?' And we know we're gonna take some heat for
doing the show. We know we're going to be called sellouts. But we
decided that, yeah, we want people to hear our record, and this is
a great opportunity for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the gig could not have come at a worse time for viewership;
the airwaves are flooded with reality shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it kind of sucks that there are so many shows like
that,'' Brandin says. ``But this seems more like a documentary. And
the whole show could very well change. That's one reason they don't
want us to talk about it _ nothing about it is set in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before VH1 approached Flickerstick, there was already a
buzz surrounding them. Formed three years ago, the band quickly
developed a loyal local following, a crowd of friends and fans who
jammed places such as the Aardvark in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   About a year and a half ago, though, the band jettisoned its
hard-rock formula for its current, more accessible psychedelic-pop
sound. While a few fans turned their backs, the group soon found
itself playing to even bigger audiences. Today, their club shows in
Fort Worth are usually sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a completely different band now,'' Brandin says. ``We
put out a record a few years ago, but we've changed so much since
then that we'd like to forget it. We think of (the new record) as
our debut.''
</P>
<P>
   After the sonic makeover, in stepped Bassman, who offered to
manage the group and help fund the new disc. On a whim, Bassman,
who has worked with current chart-toppers Vertical Horizon,
submitted a demo of Flickerstick's new material to Billboard
magazine for an online talent search.
</P>
<P>
   Bassman said that Billboard was so floored by the demo, they
placed a track from it on a music-industry CD compilation, which
eventually made its way to VH1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called me up and said they loved the song and were
working on a TV show about bands that had family members in it, and
since Brandin and Fletcher were brothers, they wanted to interview
them,'' Bassman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it didn't even get past the initial production,'' he said.
``We kept in contact, and they called me again about `Bands on the
Run.' We had just finished recording the new CD, so I sent it to
them in its most rough as possible form. Even so, they loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed were weeks of interviews and showcases for VH1
reps, all of which have been kept hush-hush _ and all of which have
been filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Brandin admits that the presence of camera crews added a new
layer of pressure on an already somewhat turmoil-plagued band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that might be one reason why they like us, because
there is some inner-band turmoil,'' he said. ``And having the
cameras there definitely added to it. We thought there'd be a lot
more fun and games, but it was far more intense than we imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   One fear that the band realizes it will have to deal with is a
backlash _ from local fans who can't believe their favorite unknown
group is on VH1, as well as from people who scrutinize them simply
for being on the show rather than for their music.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be on TV before the radio, there's definitely going to be
some backlash,'' Brandin says. ``If there's anyone who doesn't like
us because we're on TV, well, they don't understand how cutthroat
it is to even be known in the industry. We've gotten this
opportunity to get around the bull and red tape. I'm sure there
will be consequences for it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is a pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
