<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHILD-CAR-SEATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH SUGGESTS PARENTS ARE NOT USING CHILD CAR SEATS PROPERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By QIQI CHENG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers who analyzed thousands of car crashes report that
many parents are not using child car seats and booster seats
correctly and that proper protection drops sharply for children 3
to 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics and government safety experts
recommend that babies up to 20 pounds travel in rear-facing car
seats; toddlers 20 to 40 pounds, generally those 1 to 4 years old,
in forward-facing car seats; and children between 40 and 80 pounds,
generally 4 to 8 years, in booster seats that make adult seat belts
fit well across children's hips, chests and shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   For the new analysis, researchers at Children's Hospital in
Philadelphia and the University of Pennsylvania examined State Farm
Insurance data on 30,000 crashes involving 48,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 30 percent of babies below the age of 1 who
should travel in rear-facing car seats were turned forward. While
most parents used car seats properly for children up to age 2,
fewer than half the 3-year-olds were given the proper protection,
with nearly a third being graduated to booster seats before they
reached the recommended 40-pound threshold.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking safety lapse was for children 4 to 8: 83
percent were inappropriately put in adult seats instead of the
recommended belt-positioning booster seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stress that child-specific restraint does not end
at age 2,'' said Dr. Flaura Koplin Winston, a pediatrics professor
at Children's Hospital and a principal researcher in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Even when parents were using car seats or booster seats, they
often made other errors, like failing to attach the seat tightly
enough or misusing the chest clip. In addition, 16 percent of those
12 and under were allowed to ride in the front seat, increasing
their risk of injury from a crash or air bag.
</P>
<P>
   The study found serious consequences from lack of proper
restraints. In crashes studied, 64 percent of injuries were
head-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the 2-to-5-year-olds, there is a fourfold decrease of
serious head injuries when those children are in car seats or
booster seats rather than inappropriately in adult seat belts,''
Winston said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration advises a
quick test on the car seat after its installation by firmly pulling
the base of the child seat forward and from the sides. A properly
installed car seat should not move more than one inch in any
direction.
</P>
<P>
   As for booster seats, Winston recommends belt-positioning
boosters that make the seat belts fit over children's hips, chests
and shoulders, rather than shield boosters, which use only lap
belts and could lead to ejection in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Among advice from manufacturers is: Do not use strap covers,
blankets or cushions under harness straps because they may
interfere with proper fit; secure car seats with lap belts that
will not change lengths while driving; adults should not hold
children in their arms or share the same seat belt (a 20-pound
child in a car can put an extra force of 400 pounds on the adult's
arms during a crash at 30 miles an hour), and do not allow children
to hold lollipops or ice cream on a stick while riding in the car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
