<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4934 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BUZZVIDEO-HNS &LR;      08-07 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUZZ </SLUG>
 VIDEO-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By BRUCE WESTBROOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   c.Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   After two smash films grossing a combined $840 million in
theaters, the Toy Story franchise is rocketing to infinity _ and
beyond the movie screen.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Buzz Lightyear, it's launching a new venture on video,
then speeding on to television.
</P>
<P>
   Now available in stores on VHS ($24.99) and DVD ($29.99) is
``Buzz Lightyear of Star Command: The Adventure Begins.'' Coming
this fall is a Buzz TV series.
</P>
<P>
   The new movie has traditional hand-drawn artistry, not the
computer animation of ``Toy Story'' and ``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its title, it's also less a prequel to ``Toy Story''
than a spinoff. After all, Buzz never was a space hero in ``Toy
Story,'' just a deluded plaything.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in this 70-minute film _ as in the rollicking first scene of
``Toy Story 2'' _ he has the bold adventures he once only dreamed
about.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Buzz is, indeed, a powerful Space Ranger in the good-guy
Star Command _ sort of like interstellar Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   As a link to the toy universe we know, the film opens with new
computer animation of the Toy Story gang celebrating the arrival of
this videotape, then popping it into a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   For the segment, Wallace Shawn and R. Lee Ermey return to voice
Rex and Sarge, respectively, while Woody is voiced by Tom Hanks'
brother, Jim.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure begins with Buzz proclaiming, a la ``Dragnet's''
Joe Friday, ``This is the universe. I work here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still voiced with endearingly cornball swagger by Tim Allen,
Buzz must battle Evil Emperor Zurg, introduced at the start of
``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Voiced by Wayne Knight of ``3rd Rock From the Sun,'' Zurg seeks
the collective wisdom of the three-eyed little green men (we first
saw them as toys in a vending machine) as a power source. His goal:
galactic domination.
</P>
<P>
   You expected free ice cream for everyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be all Zurg, all the time _ 24-7!'' Zurg exults in
crazed bombast.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz is bent on facing Zurg alone. He's lost one partner in
combat and resists endangering another.
</P>
<P>
   But as this film teaches, we all can use partners and pals.
Succinctly put, ``Everybody needs backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Buzz is preachy. It's even more action-driven than the
``Toy Story'' films _ too much so, at first.
</P>
<P>
   But it also unveils colorful new characters, including a
princess-turned-feisty Space Ranger (Nicole Sullivan), an amusing,
highly expressive robot named XR (Larry Miller), and an eager,
bulbous, fishlike janitor called Booster (Stephen Furst) who longs
to get his feet wet in space.
</P>
<P>
   The laughs lack the sneaky, adult-level wit of Toy Story, but
they're not overly childish, either.
</P>
<P>
   XR is seen reading ``Victoria's Circuits'' magazine, while Zurg
is an imperious hoot _ a testy tyrant who obsesses over image while
railing against his lackeys' incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   Zurg is high-maintenance, yet practical. When he creates a new
henchman he dubs ``Agent Z,'' he chortles, ``We'll save a fortune
on monogramming!''
</P>
<P>
   A few too many elements borrow from ``Star Wars,'' and the
Rangers' training room is straight out of the ``Danger Room'' of
old X-Men comics. But, as they say, steal from the best.
</P>
<P>
   As for the shift to flat, two-dimensional animation, once you
adjust, it's not bad.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect exquisite detail; this comes from a Japan-based
Disney studio geared to television. But the backgrounds are
fanciful, and the big-finned spaceships have a charming retro
style.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the film sags from too much action and not enough heart or
humor _ at least until the setup locks in. Then Buzz takes off with
spirited, adventurous fun _ and no interruptive songs.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one does arise over the end credits, and it's a stitch:
William Shatner does his ironic talk-singing for ``To Infinity and
Beyond,'' a campy fight song backed by the ``Star Command Chorus.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this space heaven, or what?
</P>
<P>
   A bigger question is, can Buzz carry the ``Toy Story'' franchise
alone?
</P>
<P>
   Like Shatner's Captain Kirk, Buzz can be a pill. His heroic
resolve is rigid and naive, and his arrogance goes almost to
infinity. But his new team helps to loosen him up and soften the
edges of his gung-ho gusto.
</P>
<P>
   They'll all be back this fall, when ``Buzz Lightyear of Star
Command'' becomes a TV series for ABC (with 13 shows for Saturdays,
starting Oct. 14) and the Paramount Network and syndication (with
52 shows for weekdays and Sundays, starting Oct. 2).
</P>
<P>
   Allen won't provide Buzz's voice then; Patrick Warburton
(``Puddy'' of ``Seinfeld'') gets the gig. But if he's as good as
Jim Hanks as a sound-alike, the cartoon universe may still be in
good hands.
</P>
<P>
   DVD extras: ``Buzz Lightyear'' on DVD will have an onscreen
comic book with an option: you can read it, or have a narrator read
it to you.
</P>
<P>
   Discs also will sport a trivia game, with scores tallied and
ranked, and a ``Rogues' Gallery'' game that's a ``who's who'' of
Gamma Quadrant villains.
</P>
<P>
   On disc the film also has a widescreen image. &QL; 
Grade: B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
