<HEADER>
A4933 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-ISRAEL-LIEBERMAN-0808     08-07 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LIEBERMAN-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI'S UNFAMILIAR WITH LIEBERMAN, BUT LIKE CHOICE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (p) Politics categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ He keeps to Judaism's kosher dietary laws, observes
the Sabbath and helps clean up the image of the Clinton
administration. That's what Israelis began learning about
Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most Israelis are not familiar with the man Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore chose to be his vice presidential
running mate. But news shows quickly began introducing the Jewish
state to the first Jewish ticket partner for a major American
political party.
</P>
<P>
   Evening broadcasts carried Gore's choice high in the news _
though it was beaten for top story by a minor political scandal
here. Newscasters named the synagogue he attends in Washington, and
speculated briefly on whether his religion would help or hurt him
get votes for the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jewish Israelis do not keep the same strict adherence to
Judaism's dietary and Sabbath laws as does Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's very well-known,'' said Amos Eiran, an aide
to the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin in an interview
with Cox Newspapers. ``But, people who know Washington are very
proud of the fact that a Jewish senator will at least be nominated
to be vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Eiran, a frequent commentator on U.S. politics, said Lieberman
frequently visits Israel and last came here a couple weeks ago. He
met with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and other officials on a
short visit.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lieberman knew Rabin well and is respected as a
consistent, though not ``blind'' supporter of Israel. Lieberman's
wife, Hadassah, volunteers in a project to help poor patients at
Jerusalem's Shaare Zedek Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli media, which had been fascinated by the impeachment
scandal of President Bill Clinton, said Gore chose Lieberman
because he is seen as a moral force in U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   David Clayman, the Jerusalem representative for the American
Jewish Congress, told Israel radio that he heard that Lieberman and
Gore have long been friends. In their days together in the Senate,
Clayman said, Gore sometimes helped Lieberman keep to Jewish tenets
against turning on lights during the Sabbath by walking home with
him and turning his lights on for him.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis speculated that a Democratic ticket with a pro-Israel,
Jewish, vice presidential candidate would cause pressure on the
Palestinians to make a deal on the peace process before the
elections. Palestinians said they would withhold judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that issues of Israeli relations don't become
paramount and that Mr. Gore and the Democrats are even-handed in
the peace process,'' Palestinian spokeswoman Hanan Ashrawi told
Israeli television.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.haaretzdaily.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
