<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NEWHOUS     08-07 2333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING JEWISH NO LONGER A HINDRANCE IN POLITICS, BUT SOME JEWS
REMAIN WARY
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, AUGUST 7, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news Monday that Vice President Al Gore would name an
Orthodox Jew, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, as his running
mate adds to the growing evidence that a candidate's religion is of
diminishing importance in national politics and that religious
prejudice is in decline as a factor in elections and high
appointive office, particularly for Jewish candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But many Jews don't believe it, and they fear awakening latent
anti-Semitism should they become too politically powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the all-but-nominated Democratic standardbearer, is
expected to announce his choice of Lieberman on Tuesday in
Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton named two Jewish jurists in succession to the
Supreme Court -- Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Steven Breyer --
without much more than routine notice.
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly, Jewish candidates across the country are being
elected to local and national office by non-Jewish voters.
America's 6 million Jews, about 2 percent of the nation's total
population, occupy 11 percent of the seats in the Senate. In the
House of Representatives, there are 23 Jewish members holding 5
percent of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish community leaders say it no longer much matters if a
candidate is Jewish. Jewish candidates win or lose, and are
nominated or passed over for nomination, but being Jewish is not
the reason when they are successful -- and it is not the reason
when they are unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   A Jewish Republican from Pennsylvania, Sen. Arlen Specter, made
an unsuccessful but serious bid for his party's 1996 presidential
nomination. Not all, but many, Jewish leaders believe it is now
reasonable to think a Jew could be elected president, assuming that
one was positioned to win the nomination of the Democratic or
Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   All of that certainly could not have been said 30 or even 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But while many Jews take pride in the trend and believe it
should be celebrated, other Jews find the dramatic change
troubling. They worry that acceptance and success can never be
taken for granted, that a strain of anti-Semitism still lingers
below the surface of American society and could erupt if too much
attention is paid to too many Jews who become too prominent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there some who are fearful of what non-Jews will say,
who are mindful of Jewish history and think it would be better for
Jews to be not seen and not heard, but that is a view of a
diminishing minority,'' said Jonathan Sarna, professor of American
Jewish History at Brandeis University,
</P>
<P>
   To Rep. Howard Berman, one of five Jewish members of the
California congressional delegation, such fears are a remnant of
the ``shtetl'' or ghetto mindset among a fearful ``old guard''
whose Angst-ridden doctrine warns, ``Do nothing to push the king,
or the mayor, or the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   But not entirely old guard.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Laszlo, a 30-something Washington-based pollster and
political consultant, who is Jewish, said she cannot feel
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darwin said it is not the smartest or the strongest but those
best able to adapt who survive and adapt sometimes means keeping
your head down,'' Laszlo said.
</P>
<P>
   To Laszlo, history is the best guide. ``While there is no reason
to think there is any problem in America now, there was no reason
to worry in Austria where my father lived when they put a yellow
star on him,'' Laszlo said. ``We are the only community that, when
we fail to be accepted, it's not just a matter of being unable to
be in the country club, it's a matter of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo admits her concerns are connected to her own experience
in 1994 when she failed to win the Democratic nomination for
Congress in a crowded primary in the Second District of North
Carolina, where she grew up. One competitor's tactic was to refer
to her as ``that Jew-girl from Durham,'' Laszlo recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there were risk of igniting anti-Semitism, that should
not deter Jews from seeking public office, said Ira Forman,
executive director of the National Jewish Democratic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always some kind of risk out front when you head
up,'' Forman said. ``Politics is about who gets what, when and how.
In America today, if you don't take the risk you're going to be
left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Forman is a Jew of the baby boom generation. ``I grew up in the
Midwest and I couldn't go to the country club two blocks from me,
but other than that I found relatively little discrimination,''
Forman said. ``I had two or three fights growing up when someone
called me a `damn Jew.' But my experience was not horrible. Yet you
can't say anti-Semitism doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing his own unsuccessful campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination (which Bob Dole won), Specter said he did
not lose because he was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of other factors,'' Specter said. ``It had a
lot more to do with my position on the political spectrum. I did
not appeal to Republican primary voters because I was too much of a
centrist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Specter insists that, if nominated, he would have had ``an
excellent chance'' of winning the presidency in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll of voters nationally in February of last year
found that 92 percent said they would be willing to vote for a
Jewish presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Specter challenges the notion that religion is
irrelevant to voters when the candidate is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a latent adverse reaction to Jewish candidates
today,perhaps not as intense as it was in the past, but it's still
there. I don't know if it's a 5 percent factor or a 9 percent
factor or an 11 percent factor, but it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Specter is sympathetic to Jewish concerns about the number
of members of the Jewish community in high profile positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have too many Jews in office, it gives support to the
frequent contention that Jews control Wall Street, Hollywood,
television and the newspapers. Jews also worry that if a Jewish
officeholder screws up, the Jewish community will be blamed,''
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not simple,'' Specter said. ``There's a tendency to say
that times have changed and you have minorities in all sorts of
positions, African-Americans and Hispanics. All that is true to an
extent, but you really wonder about how much tokenism there is and
how much bias and discrimination is close to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Others exude optimism. ``We've lived through Holocaust and
pogroms,'' said 84-year-old Hyman Bookbinder, a longtime lobbyist
on issues of concern to the Jewish community. ``We can't say the
battle is over, but the battle is substantially won.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in California, a state where both senators are Jewish,
many Jews still perceive anti-Semitism as a lurking threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a foreboding that Jews maintain that there may not be
a great deal of anti-Semitism now, but they don't want to admit
there might not be in future,'' said Earl Rabb, former director of
the Jewish Community relations Council in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   David Singer, who studies polling data for the American Jewish
Committee in New York, is struck by the gap between reality and the
Jewish perception of reality, between an increased willingness
among non-Jewish voters to vote for Jewish candidates, and the
disbelief among many Jews that this could be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is greater and greater acceptance of Jewish
candidates,'' Singer said. ``It's perfectly clear that their
Jewishness is irrelevant. Yet among Jews, you would not believe the
amount of resistance you get to this. There's this strange mind
warp we're in. American Jews remain convinced that there is a lot
of anti-Semitism in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It is another tragic legacy of the Holocaust, Singer said.
``It's this notion that `they hate us' and it doesn't matter how
much the situation changes.'' Singer calls it ``anticipatory
anti-Semitism -- a grim concern that things may be good at this
minute but who knows what's around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   What's around the corner may be the first Jewish president,
according to Jason Isaacson, director of governmental affairs for
the American Jewish Committee in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each generation and each passing year, we are closer and
closer to the reality in which ethnicity ceases to matter in
American politics,'' Isaacson said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a source of pride for various groups'' and nothing
less than ``a revolution'' in American society for Jews like
Isaacson, who remembers ``the bad old days when corporate board
rooms had few if any Jews; when Jews, with a few exceptions, were
essentially fenced off from access from elite preserves of society,
the best clubs, jobs and appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say all the old stereotypes and old prejudices have
completely vanished, but certainly at the elite levels of politics
and academia and business those old walls have crumbled,'' Isaacson
said. ``Achievement and experience are the indices and standards by
which potential candidates are for the most part being judged.''
</P>
<P>
   As examples, Jews have assumed the presidency at Ivy League
universities where rigid quotas on Jewish admissions were once in
place. Alan Greenspan heads the Federal Reserve Board. Sandy Berger
is the White House national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   There are clearly hate groups and strains of society that do not
accept Jews and remain intolerant of minorities generally. ``But
the overwhelming portion of the population is generally tolerant
and supportive of diversity,'' Isaacson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quotas have vanished and limits on any ethnic or religious
group are no longer applicable, or even thinkable,'' Isaacson said.
``And if this is a permanent fixture in American society, and I
hope it is, America has genuinely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin A. Cardin, a seven-term Democrat from Maryland, is
not convinced that religion has become irrelevant in politics.
``That's a little strong,'' he said. ``But it is clearly less of a
factor today than it was a decade or two ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern about a candidate's religion has been declining since
John F. Kennedy, the first and still the only Catholic to win the
presidency, broke that barrier in 1960, Cardin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a more diverse and tolerant society today,'' Cardin
said. ``People have gotten to know each other a lot better.''
Cardin believes the political process has matured enough ``to
permit a person qualified to be president who is Jewish to be able
to win,'' even if many Jews don't believe it yet.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thought a Catholic could be president,'' Cardin said.
``Or, now, a woman, or an African-American. That's a stereotype
that will be broken in our lifetime. We're beyond that. Of course,
until it happens, nobody from the community involved will believe
it can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a little soon to expect a Jewish president, according
to Sarna, the Brandeis professor. ``I expect we'll have a woman
president before we have a Jewish president,'' Sarna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it seems to me we'll have a Jewish president at some point
in time. I can never remember a time when so many of the candidates
talked about as potential vice presidential material are Jewish.
That seems to be a very interesting feature of the current
election. It remains to be seen if it's just talk or if something
will come of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lieberman, former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
and Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California were on early lists of
potential choices for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some things about this year's presidential race are
causing head-shaking in the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both major candidates are using the religion card,'' said Abe
Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith. ``Whether it's George W. Bush saying that Jesus is his
political philosopher or Gore making decisions based on `what Jesus
would do,' that's a problem. They are very specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are talking about Christ and Christianity. They are
saying that's how they would govern. In an autobiography, that's
one thing. When you go to church, that's wonderful. But on the
political platform, it takes on a different meaning. It plays on
church-state relationships, prayer in school, abortion, school
vouchers; it plays on all issues and that's anxiety-producing. It
brings about a sense of alienation not only to Jews but others,
Muslims, Buddhists, atheists and other ethnic groups. Don't forget,
we are becoming an amalgam of all kinds of religions and ethnic
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the cultural acceptance of Jews has been accompanied by
the diversity phenomenon that some Jews find less comforting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain fear in the Jewish community that even as
individual Jews have certainly risen up into elite circles that the
Jewish community itself is in some ways less significant in the
world of American religion,'' Sarna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once upon a time we talked about Protestants, Catholics and
Jews. Jews were one of America's `big three' religions,'' Sarna
said. ``Now there's a sense that America is a smorgasbord of
religions, of many minority faiths of which the Jewish community is
just one.''
</P>
<P>
   The change, Sarna said, is visible on ceremonial occasions.
Where once the priest, minister or rabbi once stood, a broader
selection of religious leaders now rise to deliver the
benedictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4945 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NEWHOUS     08-07 2333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING JEWISH NO LONGER A HINDRANCE IN POLITICS, BUT SOME JEWS
REMAIN WARY
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, AUGUST 7, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news Monday that Vice President Al Gore would name an
Orthodox Jew, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, as his running
mate adds to the growing evidence that a candidate's religion is of
diminishing importance in national politics and that religious
prejudice is in decline as a factor in elections and high
appointive office, particularly for Jewish candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But many Jews don't believe it, and they fear awakening latent
anti-Semitism should they become too politically powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the all-but-nominated Democratic standardbearer, is
expected to announce his choice of Lieberman on Tuesday in
Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton named two Jewish jurists in succession to the
Supreme Court -- Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Steven Breyer --
without much more than routine notice.
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly, Jewish candidates across the country are being
elected to local and national office by non-Jewish voters.
America's 6 million Jews, about 2 percent of the nation's total
population, occupy 11 percent of the seats in the Senate. In the
House of Representatives, there are 23 Jewish members holding 5
percent of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish community leaders say it no longer much matters if a
candidate is Jewish. Jewish candidates win or lose, and are
nominated or passed over for nomination, but being Jewish is not
the reason when they are successful -- and it is not the reason
when they are unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   A Jewish Republican from Pennsylvania, Sen. Arlen Specter, made
an unsuccessful but serious bid for his party's 1996 presidential
nomination. Not all, but many, Jewish leaders believe it is now
reasonable to think a Jew could be elected president, assuming that
one was positioned to win the nomination of the Democratic or
Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   All of that certainly could not have been said 30 or even 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But while many Jews take pride in the trend and believe it
should be celebrated, other Jews find the dramatic change
troubling. They worry that acceptance and success can never be
taken for granted, that a strain of anti-Semitism still lingers
below the surface of American society and could erupt if too much
attention is paid to too many Jews who become too prominent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there some who are fearful of what non-Jews will say,
who are mindful of Jewish history and think it would be better for
Jews to be not seen and not heard, but that is a view of a
diminishing minority,'' said Jonathan Sarna, professor of American
Jewish History at Brandeis University,
</P>
<P>
   To Rep. Howard Berman, one of five Jewish members of the
California congressional delegation, such fears are a remnant of
the ``shtetl'' or ghetto mindset among a fearful ``old guard''
whose Angst-ridden doctrine warns, ``Do nothing to push the king,
or the mayor, or the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   But not entirely old guard.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Laszlo, a 30-something Washington-based pollster and
political consultant, who is Jewish, said she cannot feel
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darwin said it is not the smartest or the strongest but those
best able to adapt who survive and adapt sometimes means keeping
your head down,'' Laszlo said.
</P>
<P>
   To Laszlo, history is the best guide. ``While there is no reason
to think there is any problem in America now, there was no reason
to worry in Austria where my father lived when they put a yellow
star on him,'' Laszlo said. ``We are the only community that, when
we fail to be accepted, it's not just a matter of being unable to
be in the country club, it's a matter of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo admits her concerns are connected to her own experience
in 1994 when she failed to win the Democratic nomination for
Congress in a crowded primary in the Second District of North
Carolina, where she grew up. One competitor's tactic was to refer
to her as ``that Jew-girl from Durham,'' Laszlo recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there were risk of igniting anti-Semitism, that should
not deter Jews from seeking public office, said Ira Forman,
executive director of the National Jewish Democratic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always some kind of risk out front when you head
up,'' Forman said. ``Politics is about who gets what, when and how.
In America today, if you don't take the risk you're going to be
left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Forman is a Jew of the baby boom generation. ``I grew up in the
Midwest and I couldn't go to the country club two blocks from me,
but other than that I found relatively little discrimination,''
Forman said. ``I had two or three fights growing up when someone
called me a `damn Jew.' But my experience was not horrible. Yet you
can't say anti-Semitism doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing his own unsuccessful campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination (which Bob Dole won), Specter said he did
not lose because he was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of other factors,'' Specter said. ``It had a
lot more to do with my position on the political spectrum. I did
not appeal to Republican primary voters because I was too much of a
centrist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Specter insists that, if nominated, he would have had ``an
excellent chance'' of winning the presidency in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll of voters nationally in February of last year
found that 92 percent said they would be willing to vote for a
Jewish presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Specter challenges the notion that religion is
irrelevant to voters when the candidate is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a latent adverse reaction to Jewish candidates
today,perhaps not as intense as it was in the past, but it's still
there. I don't know if it's a 5 percent factor or a 9 percent
factor or an 11 percent factor, but it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Specter is sympathetic to Jewish concerns about the number
of members of the Jewish community in high profile positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have too many Jews in office, it gives support to the
frequent contention that Jews control Wall Street, Hollywood,
television and the newspapers. Jews also worry that if a Jewish
officeholder screws up, the Jewish community will be blamed,''
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not simple,'' Specter said. ``There's a tendency to say
that times have changed and you have minorities in all sorts of
positions, African-Americans and Hispanics. All that is true to an
extent, but you really wonder about how much tokenism there is and
how much bias and discrimination is close to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Others exude optimism. ``We've lived through Holocaust and
pogroms,'' said 84-year-old Hyman Bookbinder, a longtime lobbyist
on issues of concern to the Jewish community. ``We can't say the
battle is over, but the battle is substantially won.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in California, a state where both senators are Jewish,
many Jews still perceive anti-Semitism as a lurking threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a foreboding that Jews maintain that there may not be
a great deal of anti-Semitism now, but they don't want to admit
there might not be in future,'' said Earl Rabb, former director of
the Jewish Community relations Council in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   David Singer, who studies polling data for the American Jewish
Committee in New York, is struck by the gap between reality and the
Jewish perception of reality, between an increased willingness
among non-Jewish voters to vote for Jewish candidates, and the
disbelief among many Jews that this could be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is greater and greater acceptance of Jewish
candidates,'' Singer said. ``It's perfectly clear that their
Jewishness is irrelevant. Yet among Jews, you would not believe the
amount of resistance you get to this. There's this strange mind
warp we're in. American Jews remain convinced that there is a lot
of anti-Semitism in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It is another tragic legacy of the Holocaust, Singer said.
``It's this notion that `they hate us' and it doesn't matter how
much the situation changes.'' Singer calls it ``anticipatory
anti-Semitism -- a grim concern that things may be good at this
minute but who knows what's around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   What's around the corner may be the first Jewish president,
according to Jason Isaacson, director of governmental affairs for
the American Jewish Committee in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each generation and each passing year, we are closer and
closer to the reality in which ethnicity ceases to matter in
American politics,'' Isaacson said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a source of pride for various groups'' and nothing
less than ``a revolution'' in American society for Jews like
Isaacson, who remembers ``the bad old days when corporate board
rooms had few if any Jews; when Jews, with a few exceptions, were
essentially fenced off from access from elite preserves of society,
the best clubs, jobs and appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say all the old stereotypes and old prejudices have
completely vanished, but certainly at the elite levels of politics
and academia and business those old walls have crumbled,'' Isaacson
said. ``Achievement and experience are the indices and standards by
which potential candidates are for the most part being judged.''
</P>
<P>
   As examples, Jews have assumed the presidency at Ivy League
universities where rigid quotas on Jewish admissions were once in
place. Alan Greenspan heads the Federal Reserve Board. Sandy Berger
is the White House national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   There are clearly hate groups and strains of society that do not
accept Jews and remain intolerant of minorities generally. ``But
the overwhelming portion of the population is generally tolerant
and supportive of diversity,'' Isaacson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quotas have vanished and limits on any ethnic or religious
group are no longer applicable, or even thinkable,'' Isaacson said.
``And if this is a permanent fixture in American society, and I
hope it is, America has genuinely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin A. Cardin, a seven-term Democrat from Maryland, is
not convinced that religion has become irrelevant in politics.
``That's a little strong,'' he said. ``But it is clearly less of a
factor today than it was a decade or two ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern about a candidate's religion has been declining since
John F. Kennedy, the first and still the only Catholic to win the
presidency, broke that barrier in 1960, Cardin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a more diverse and tolerant society today,'' Cardin
said. ``People have gotten to know each other a lot better.''
Cardin believes the political process has matured enough ``to
permit a person qualified to be president who is Jewish to be able
to win,'' even if many Jews don't believe it yet.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thought a Catholic could be president,'' Cardin said.
``Or, now, a woman, or an African-American. That's a stereotype
that will be broken in our lifetime. We're beyond that. Of course,
until it happens, nobody from the community involved will believe
it can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a little soon to expect a Jewish president, according
to Sarna, the Brandeis professor. ``I expect we'll have a woman
president before we have a Jewish president,'' Sarna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it seems to me we'll have a Jewish president at some point
in time. I can never remember a time when so many of the candidates
talked about as potential vice presidential material are Jewish.
That seems to be a very interesting feature of the current
election. It remains to be seen if it's just talk or if something
will come of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lieberman, former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
and Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California were on early lists of
potential choices for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some things about this year's presidential race are
causing head-shaking in the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both major candidates are using the religion card,'' said Abe
Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith. ``Whether it's George W. Bush saying that Jesus is his
political philosopher or Gore making decisions based on `what Jesus
would do,' that's a problem. They are very specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are talking about Christ and Christianity. They are
saying that's how they would govern. In an autobiography, that's
one thing. When you go to church, that's wonderful. But on the
political platform, it takes on a different meaning. It plays on
church-state relationships, prayer in school, abortion, school
vouchers; it plays on all issues and that's anxiety-producing. It
brings about a sense of alienation not only to Jews but others,
Muslims, Buddhists, atheists and other ethnic groups. Don't forget,
we are becoming an amalgam of all kinds of religions and ethnic
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the cultural acceptance of Jews has been accompanied by
the diversity phenomenon that some Jews find less comforting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain fear in the Jewish community that even as
individual Jews have certainly risen up into elite circles that the
Jewish community itself is in some ways less significant in the
world of American religion,'' Sarna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once upon a time we talked about Protestants, Catholics and
Jews. Jews were one of America's `big three' religions,'' Sarna
said. ``Now there's a sense that America is a smorgasbord of
religions, of many minority faiths of which the Jewish community is
just one.''
</P>
<P>
   The change, Sarna said, is visible on ceremonial occasions.
Where once the priest, minister or rabbi once stood, a broader
selection of religious leaders now rise to deliver the
benedictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
