<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4955 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-KODAK-CHINA-HARVARD-B     08-07 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KODAK-CHINA-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BETTER WAY TO CRACK CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Monday, Aug. 7, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from the July-August
issue of HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of
information on the art and science of business and management. For
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or about The Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 By WILFRIED R. VANHONACKER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The vast Chinese market has always attracted foreign companies,
but very few have been able to capitalize on the opportunities the
country affords. That failure can be attributed in large part to
the traditional investment vehicles available to foreign companies,
all of which create complexities and conflicts that hamstring
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one company, Eastman Kodak, is pioneering a new corporate
structure in China _ one that looks very similar to Western
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the uniqueness of Kodak's approach, consider how
most foreign companies operate in China. The most common corporate
structure is the joint venture, in which companies share day-to-day
operational control with a local partner. But doing so can paralyze
decision making, a fatal flaw in today's rapidly changing markets.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, for example, has seen its share of the market for
optical-fiber transmission equipment in China slide from 70 percent
to 30 percent because it must negotiate each technological change
in a product with a local partner.
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of local partners also exacerbates the effect of
China's narrow business licenses. Because Chinese regulations
restrict companies' geographic reach as well as the range of goods
they can manufacture and distribute, realizing economies of scale
and scope is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, for example, recently had six joint ventures in
Shanghai making soap, ice cream, skin cream and laundry detergent.
Theoretically, a foreign company could consolidate the distribution
of its various joint-venture products, but it would have to get
consent from all its Chinese partners. That seldom happens, because
the partners fear that the products from their individual joint
ventures would end up at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid such complicated management issues, some companies have
established wholly owned foreign enterprises, so-called WOFEs, but
they, too, have limitations, among them difficulty winning
contracts and forging local alliances. China's local governments
have routinely favored state-owned enterprises over foreign
ventures, especially since 1999, when the industrial ministries in
Beijing were abolished.
</P>
<P>
   There is a better way for companies to compete in China. Since
1994, businesses have been able to register as joint-stock
companies _ a familiar corporate structure in the West. All of
China's state-owned enterprises listed on the Shanghai and Shenzhen
stock exchanges have adopted this structure. But so far, only one
foreign multinational has taken this route: Eastman Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's joint-stock companies, which I call foreign investor
shareholding corporations, or FISCs, have allowed the company to
achieve a high degree of operational control. The FISCs eliminate
the trade-off between management control and market access by
granting local partners minority stakes in return for their
business assets, such as factories and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Because local partners lose direct ownership of those assets,
they can be excluded from the day-to-day management. But as part
owners, they remain interested in helping the FISCs perform, which
motivates them to help the venture secure access to the markets.
</P>
<P>
   The FISC structure also mitigates the economic impact of narrow
business licenses. For example, Kodak doesn't have to get its local
partners' consent to consolidate distribution of products from its
different operations.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Kodak has created two FISCs: Kodak (China), in which it
holds an 80 percent share, and Kodak (Wuxi), in which it holds a 70
percent share.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak (China) purchased the assets of two domestic photofilm
manufacturers, Xiamen Fuda and Shantou Era, in return for 10
percent stakes and the right to appoint one board member each;
Kodak named the remaining eight directors. Because there must be at
least five shareholders, the Guangdong and Fujian international
trust and investment corporations also took nominal stakes in Kodak
(China). For its part, Kodak put up $380 million in cash. Kodak
(Wuxi) worked out a similar arrangement with different
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear why the shareholding structure works for Kodak. But
it's important to realize that it works for China as well. It gives
Chinese authorities a face-saving way to allow industrial reform
through the back door.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the photo industry had been almost entirely closed
off to foreign corporations because the government wanted to
develop a domestic photofilm industry. Foreign companies such as
Kodak were restricted to licensing agreements or direct imports,
which attracted heavy duties. But domestic manufacturers could not
keep up with the industry's rapid technological innovations, and
all but one were technically bankrupt by the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's proposal to create FISCs was therefore considered a good
solution by Beijing authorities. No less than five central
government organizations, including three ministries, cooperated
with Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   China's State Development Planning Commission, which had been
involved in creating Kodak's FISCs, last year released a research
report supporting the ``Kodak model.'' And, in theory, the
regulatory framework already lets foreign corporations convert
existing joint ventures and WOFEs into FISCs, provided they have
been profitable for three years.
</P>
<P>
   If foreign corporations move in this direction on their own, it
will save Chinese authorities from having to embark on a wholesale
restructuring of the legal infrastructure of business.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the FISCs are well placed to obtain quick listings
on the Shenzhen and Shanghai stock exchanges, making it easier for
them to raise new capital. For all these reasons, many companies
will probably follow Kodak's lead.
</P>
<P>
   (Wilfried R. Vanhonacker is dean of CEIBS, a business school in
Shanghai.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on offerings
from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
