<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MIDEAST-FILM-LIFEBEAT     08-07 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-FILM-LIFEBEAT-1450-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE EASTERN FILMMAKERS FASCINATE THE WEST
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 By BRAD GOOCH 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Iranian video artist Shirin Neshat lives a long way from the
land of the chador, in a Chinatown loft in Manhattan, across from a
row of sweatshops. She dresses all in black and keeps her long dark
hair drawn severely back; she could pass for a SoHo art-world
character, circa 1978. Last February, Neshat returned from
Marrakech, where she had marshaled more than 200 people to film
``Fervor,'' a riveting tale of a man and woman who have an unspoken
epiphany while a mullah rants against sexual desire. It's an
11-minute immersion in the communal ecstasy of hidden Iranian
sensuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Iran, a man isn't allowed to make eye contact with a
woman,'' Neshat explains, sitting at a wooden table decorated only
with a vase of apricot-colored roses. ``But occasionally, when it
does happen, you get chills all over your body. Repression
heightens sexuality. My film is not so much a political analysis _
rather, it's romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, with intermittent peace talks and slightly relaxed
borders, the Middle East seems hesitantly welcoming yet still
esoteric enough to provoke fascination in the West. More than a
century ago, the American painter Frederic Church built Olana, his
lavish Moorish-style home on the Hudson, where it is said he
enjoyed lounging in the robes of an Arab sheikh. Eventually, the
public swooned over belly dancers, camels and palm trees while
puffing on Fatima cigarettes. Irving Berlin wrote ``In My Harem,''
Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney wore tunics and harem pants and
moviegoers poured into theaters to watch Valentino vamp in ``The
Sheik''.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it's artists in particular who are fascinated by the
Middle East. Filmmakers, video artists, painters, and writers from
Iran, Egypt, and Lebanon are being talked about for the first time
in years in the West. And American and European artists, in turn,
are showing signs of a new orientalism in their work and travel.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most prominent of the Middle Eastern artists
working today, Neshat gained notoriety for her early
black-and-white photographs in which she posed in a chador, a rifle
propped between her bare feet, her skin tattooed with calligraphic
lines by female Farsi poets.
</P>
<P>
   The images are opaque, offering few clues as to how a Westerner
should respond. Neshat's work has since evolved to more ambitious
double-screen films that are projected in simultaneous loops on
facing gallery walls as high as 12 feet, requiring audiences to
shift their gaze from, say, an image of a woman at a mosque in
Istanbul to a scene of white-robed worshipers in an American
church. Art critic Peter Schjeldahl, one of Neshat's many admirers,
has written that her meditations on chador culture ``emit an icy
heat of suppressed passions; they are among the first undoubtable
masterpieces of video installation.''
</P>
<P>
   While Neshat, who emigrated to America in the '70s, uses the
artistic freedom of the West as a foil for the regime back home,
filmmaker Abbas Kiarostami works within the system of Iranian
censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Regularly compared to neorealist masters Vittorio de Sica and
Satyajit Ray, Kiarostami has extracted uncanny performances from
young amateur actors and for more than 20 years has outfoxed the
mullahs by concealing political messages in ordinary dramas.
</P>
<P>
   In his film ``The Wind Will Carry Us'', which opens this month,
the protagonist is forever driving to a cemetery _ the only place
he can get reception for his mobile phone. Leading Iranian film
critic Jamsheed Akrami says, ``Before the revolution, Iranian
movies were banal Hollywood knockoffs. Afterward, deprived of
romantic formulas, directors were forced to be inventive. Now the
art films have turned into the dominant cinema. We may well be
witnessing a film renaissance from the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six-year-old filmmaker Ziad Doueiri, like Neshat, tackles
theo-politics from the safety of the West. Doueiri has lived in
L.A. since 1984 and has worked as a regular cameraman for Quentin
Tarantino. Doueiri's film ``West Beirut,'' is a memoir of his
misadventures as a teenager during Lebanon's devastating civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Banned in Syria, Jordan, Saudi Arabia and Egypt, ``West Beirut''
won the Francois Chalais Prize at Cannes in 1998 and debuted in the
States at the New Directors Film Festival last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the protagonist maneuvers through a war zone in an
attempt to get his Super 8 film developed, only to wind up in a
Lebanese brothel, waving his Christian girlfriend's bra to the
snipers as a flag of truce. It brings to mind the lyricism of
adolescence as epitomized by Franois Truffaut's ``The 400 Blows''.
``My high school in Beirut was French,'' Doueiri explains. ``We had
to watch a French movie twice a week and write about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Doueiri is navigating the same schizoid psyche as
Neshat, professionally and artistically. ``I was seeing a girl in
Paris, and she said, joking, 'I'm only going out with you because
it's hip to go out with an Arab these days.' In France, being a
'Ber,' meaning an Arab, is the cool thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Syrians and Israelis met in January to strike a peace
deal, says Doueiri, ``I thought, That's it; there's going to be
peace, and I'm making films about war. Then a friend from Paris
called and said, 'Don't worry. It will break down.' And two days
later, the negotiations did. And I said, 'Good!'''
</P>
<P>
   The comic and not-so-comic repercussions of being caught in a
cultural crossfire have also sparked the work of first-time
novelist Salar Abdoh, 35, as seen in his literary thriller, ``The
Poet Game'' (Picador). Abdoh fled Iran with his father and brothers
following the revolution in 1979, earning a master's degree in
English literature at the City College of New York and working as
the night manager at the Iroquois Hotel in midtown Manhattan, where
he wrote most of his noirish novel.
</P>
<P>
   Like a ventriloquist manipulating the stylish thrillers of
Graham Greene or John Le Carre, Abdoh tells the brilliant, dark
tale of a young man working for Iranian intelligence whose mission
impossible is to stop a New Year's Eve bombing in Manhattan planned
by a Hezbollah-style group of terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Abdoh relies on current media as the very wallpaper of his
imaginative world. ``The main female character is an
Italian-American who works with an Algerian terrorist cell called
the GIA,'' says Abdoh. ``So imagine my surprise a few months ago
when I read about this woman of Italian background caught at the
Canadian border who (allegedly) worked with the same Algerian
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Abdoh read from his novel at the Temple Bar in
downtown Manhattan. Neshat was among the predominantly Middle
Eastern audience crowded into the smoky lounge. Abdoh, tall and
wearing spectacles reminiscent of James Joyce's, was asked how he
got material for his novel. ``I read the same newspapers as
everyone else,'' Abdoh replied, somewhat disappointing those in the
audience who thought he must have been privy to secret information.
</P>
<P>
   Artists were once described by poet Ezra Pound as ``the antennae
of the race.'' Philip Taaffe, the American painter whose canvases
have been infused with a certifiable Middle Eastern aesthetic,
might seem the likely successor to Delacroix in his trekking
through Egypt, Syria, Tunisia, and Morocco. But, unlike work of the
orientalists of the 19th century, Taaffe's version is more about
collaboration than colonialism. ``I wanted to embody a culture,
rather than impose myself on it. I didn't just want something to
refer to, to (symbolize) the exotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the artists in exile from the Middle East are driven by
nostalgia and curiosity to either return or discover untouched
vistas. The draw for filmmaker Doueiri remains his hometown of
Beirut, which he last visited two years ago. ``When it's not being
bombed, it's such a fun place,'' he says, laughing. ``The bars you
go to are the fanciest you've ever seen, like the Sunset Room in
Hollywood or the Pink in Santa Monica. There's even a gay scene at
BO18. Imagine, a thriving gay scene in the Middle East!''
</P>
<P>
   When artist Y.Z. Kami travels from his home in New York to his
native Iran, which he left in 1973, he seems as much a tourist as
his peers from America. Recently, he traveled to the ancient ruins
of Persepolis, the palace of the king of Persia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all by myself,'' he says. ``There was this huge castle
and desert all around me. That could not happen anywhere else.
There would be 10,000 tourist cars.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to travel to Syria, where the medieval bazaars, or
souks, in Damascus and Aleppo are reportedly still intact. ``We
must hurry up and get there very soon, before they sign the peace
agreement with Israel,'' he says, his comment decidedly un-P.C.,
almost, well, orientalist. ``After that, everybody will be doing
the same thing, the tourists from everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   (Brad Gooch writes for ``Harper's Bazaar'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
