<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-OPTIONS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH COLLEGE? EARLY DECISION OPTIONS AND THE CAMPUS TOUR
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 By KRISTEN CARR  
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
 World rights  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From a high school senior's perspective, the advantages of
applying to college ahead of the pack are tempting: not only do you
receive a speedy ``yea'' or ``nay,'' but your odds of being
accepted increase markedly. Harvard, for example, admits 26 percent
of its early- decision applicants, versus only 6 percent of those
who apply under the usual deadlines; Stanford, 24 percent versus 14
percent. It's no wonder that more and more students are opting for
early decision.
</P>
<P>
   Its exact terminology is well known to high school students, but
it may not be to their parents. Through ``early decision I:'
seniors apply to a college by November 15; if accepted, they must
commit to that school and withdraw all other applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early decision II'' is no different except that the deadline
is extended to January 15, giving students a few more months to
decide whether to go this route. (Students applying for I or II
typically receive a reply within a month of submitting their
applications.) Under ``early action,'' students will receive word
they've been accepted as early as December 15 but do not have to
commit to the school until May 1. (Applicants for regular admission
generally hear back from colleges in April.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Early decision is great for a student who's mature enough to
distinguish among various colleges, who is sure about his first
choice and who has a better than reasonable chance of getting in,''
says Stephen Singer, director of college counseling at Horace Mann
School in Riverdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a simple antidote to all the anxieties that attend
getting into college. ``If you're not in the school's ballpark,
academically speaking, you're risking rejection,'' says Leonard
King, director of college counseling at the Maret School in
Washington, D.C. ``Waiting to apply later, when your latest scores
from standardized tests and your first-semester grades are
available, may help you get in.'' Provided, of course, those scores
and grades add up to a stronger academic standing.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that ``the more competitive the school, the less of
an advantage early decision presents,'' adds King. That's because
early decision often attracts the brightest, most motivated
students to begin with _ not to mention the fact that top schools
can well afford to be choosy. A rejection or deferral means that
students will have to start the entire process over again, this
time with a wounded ego _ and greater time constraints as they
scramble for an alternate school.
</P>
<P>
   Early decision can also limit a student's scholarship
opportunities. Once a school has locked in an applicant, there's no
more incentive for it to continue the wooing game. But not all the
benefits of bypassing early decision can be measured in monetary
terms: for many students, having the time to make the right
decision could yield the biggest payoff of all.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE TOUR
</P>
<P>
   With the college-selection process intensifying every step of
the way, it's no surprise that students and parents approach the
on-campus tour with SAT-level seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers of people making the tours have absolutely
mushroomed,'' says Singer. Amid the increasing frenzy, how do you
get the most out of this family ritual? Here are some tips to help
you make the college tour a real education.
</P>
<P>
   CONSIDER THE TIMING ``There should be an evolution in the way
you visit a school,'' says Singer. ``During the junior year, visit
schools so you can form some general impressions. The visits you
make in April or May of the senior year, when the student is
narrowing his choices, are the most important ones, because that's
when he's the closest, emotionally, to being an actual college
student. One's focus and priorities can change from junior to
senior year.''
</P>
<P>
   PHONE FIRST Alert a college admissions counselor of your arrival
date about a month in advance of any visit. That should allow
plenty of time to arrange for accommodations at a nearby inn and
set up interviews, meetings with professors and opportunities to
sit in on classes. Don't forget the schools' Web sites: most have
sections devoted to prospective students and offer the goods on
aspects of campus life _ academic or otherwise _ that students
might want to learn more about on a visit.
</P>
<P>
   BE SURE THEY'RE HOME Book your tours at the start of a semester,
so you're not there during spring break or final exams.
</P>
<P>
   AVOID THREE-DAY WEEKENDS Chances are many others will have had
the same idea. Check with admissions counselors to see which tours
have the most spots open.
</P>
<P>
   PRESS FOR AN INTERVIEW An interview provides the student with
the perfect chance to gather specific information. (Write questions
out in advance to save time.) It may not be as integral to the
admissions process as it was in the past, but it can't hurt to
schedule one. And why not help the admissions office match a face
with an application?
</P>
<P>
   DON'T OVERBOOK Allow at least half a day per stop and try not to
visit more than four colleges in a single trip. ``More than that,
and they're likely to just blur together,'' says Anne Ferguson, a
college counselor at the Hathaway Brown School in Shaker Heights,
Ohio. Taking notes can help keep each college's pros and cons
disdnct when it comes down to decision time.
</P>
<P>
   BREAK THE ROUTINE Visit coffeehouses and other student hangouts
to chat up the locals _ they might offer perspectives you won't get
from brochures or tour guides.
</P>
<P>
   GO SOLO Arrange for your child to visit on her own once she's
narrowed down her choices. Says tour veteran Libby Beckenbaugh,
mother of a sophomore at SMU: ``High school kids can get a much
better feel for the college if they're spending the weekend there
alone.'' Many admissions offices will happily arrange a stay in the
dorms with a volunteer host.
</P>
<P>
   (Kristen Carr writes for ``Town &AMP; Country'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
