<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-PREGNANCY-CANCER-LIFE     08-07 2035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGNANCY-CANCER-LIFEBEAT-1850-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE CURE FOR A MOTHER POSES A THREAT TO THE CHILD
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 By JANA STRIEGEL-WILSON  
 c.2000 New York Times
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many women of my generation, I waited to have a baby,
thinking I would be better prepared for parenthood emotionally and
financially. I was 38 in 1994 when I finally got pregnant _
particularly coveted after two years of wandering through the
fertility maze.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another price to pay for waiting. Three weeks
after learning the jubilant news of my pregnancy, my husband, Mark,
and I sat in a surgeon's office as he told us that a lump I had
found in my breast was malignant.
</P>
<P>
   My cancer was aggressive. The surgeon told us I had only a 25
percent to 30 percent chance of surviving five years, and counseled
me to weigh my prognosis carefully in relationship to my pregnancy
_ my child could be motherless.
</P>
<P>
   We left the office, and I still had not dropped one tear. That
night, I broke down and wailed in my husband's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer is the most common cancer in pregnant and
postpartum women, occurring in one in 3,000 pregnant women,
according to the National Cancer Institute. The average patient is
32 to 38 years old. And while there are no firm statistics, the
consensus is that the number of cases is rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidence of pregnancy breast cancer is increasing just
because women are getting pregnant at older ages, when breast
cancer is more common,'' said Dr. Jeanne A. Petrek, director of the
Evelyn H. Lauder Breast Center of Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pregnancy coinciding with breast cancer is a complex problem
without straightforward answers for the mother, as I soon
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   My case was reviewed by two tumor boards, panels of oncologists
who advise treatment for difficult cancer cases. Both the one in
Albuquerque, where I live, and another at Scripps Memorial Hospital
in San Diego advised that I follow the same plan: therapeutic
abortion, mastectomy, chemotherapy, radiation and tamoxifen
hormonal therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams of doctors were concerned, first, with saving my
life. They recommended removing what made the case so different _
the baby. The rising hormonal levels of pregnancy, which could
encourage cancer growth, would be halted. Treatment could be more
aggressive and started earlier. They considered this my best chance
for survival.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side were the doctors I came to refer to as the
``baby people'': Dr. Krista Wills, my obstetrician; Dr. Gary
Aisenbrey, my high-risk obstetrician; and Dr. Richard Giudice, my
oncologist. They cited case studies of pregnant women who delivered
healthy babies after receiving chemotherapy in the second and third
trimesters, once fetal organs and limbs are formed. They concluded
that specific chemotherapy drugs administered after the first
trimester were a reasonable risk for the baby and an effective
treatment for me.
</P>
<P>
   They also believed in the positive effect of keeping my
pregnancy. Depression and stress from aborting a deeply desired
child could weaken my immune system and reduce my body's ability to
fight the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   I was presented with these two opinions. The final decision
could only be mine, although my husband and I had to face the many
possibilities together. Our late-night discussions prompted
stress-induced insomnia and forced us to make a rule: no cancer
talk after 8 p.m. But still the questions haunted us day and night.
Were we willing to raise a child with birth defects? Could we give
up this pregnancy? Were he and I prepared to give my life for the
child's? Was he willing to be a single father?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we both wanted two things _ me alive and a healthy
baby. Mark said he would support me in the choices I made.
</P>
<P>
   Within three weeks of the first biopsy results I underwent a
lumpectomy, a bone scan, blood tests and ultrasounds to detect any
spread of the cancer and then the removal of my left breast.
Confirming the aggressiveness of the cancer, the mastectomy
revealed that five of the 13 axillary lymph nodes were invaded by
cancer cells. There were no indications the cancer had spread to
other parts of my body, however. This placed my disease at IIB of
IV stages.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the test results, I needed more information. I read,
ate crackers, drank ginger tea for morning sickness that lasted all
day, read and read some more.
</P>
<P>
   I scoured a database developed by Dr. John J. Mulvihill, the
director of the Program in Human Genetics at the University of
Oklahoma, containing information on some 300 pregnancies in which
the women were exposed to chemotherapeutic agents. The project
draws no conclusions, but as a guide to oncologists it gives
details of the type and amount of drugs used at particular stages
of pregnancy and the outcome of each case.
</P>
<P>
   In my research it became quickly apparent that pregnant women
with breast cancer generally have poor prognoses, not just because
of hormonal and biological changes experienced during pregnancy,
but also because of the delay of treatment until after delivery. In
addition, several medical papers cited evidence that termination of
the pregnancy did not change the outcome for the patients.
</P>
<P>
   As I read encouraging data for keeping my pregnancy, an intense
anger toward the tumor boards' cut-and-dried attitude grew and
grew. I wanted them to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If I could only talk to someone who had been through this
ordeal. I needed to hear these words from another woman: ``Yes, I
went through chemotherapy when I was pregnant with my son five
years ago. He's right in front of me this minute, running around
healthy and normal, and I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But back in those pre-Internet-chat-room days, I never did find
anyone in my same situation to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, based on the information I gathered, I made a leap of
faith. We would fight my cancer, we would keep the pregnancy, and I
believed our baby would be healthy. Most important, despite the
statistical chances of my survival, I chose to believe that I would
live to attend his high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   My belly started to round. My right breast swelled. The left
side of my chest was flat and smooth with a tidy scar running from
the center of my chest horizontally eight inches to the left and
finishing midway under my arm. My breast and most lymph nodes were
gone, but I still had my child. The baby had survived the
mastectomy in excellent shape, but we had a fight for our lives
ahead of us.
</P>
<P>
   At 14 weeks' pregnant, a ``safer'' time for the fetus, I began
my chemotherapy regimen: a combination of the drugs Adriamycin,
Cytoxan and ''5FU'' (fluorouracil) _ six months of treatments
delivered at three-week intervals. Radiation would begin after I
delivered my baby.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to finish the treatments a few weeks before the
baby was due. This would give me time to recover my strength and
rebuild my immune system before the physical demands of labor and
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelming exhaustion from the chemo possessed me every third
week. The first two weeks of every cycle I was just
pregnancy-exhausted. They told me I would lose my hair. I bought a
wig and waited. Each month my high-risk obstetrician performed an
ultrasound to monitor my baby's growth _ he was growing like a
champ.
</P>
<P>
   My oncologist was amazed at how well I tolerated the chemo. I
did not lose my hair. I pushed through my exhaustion to exercise;
forced myself to eat well; took vitamins and herbs to strengthen my
immune system; and thought positively about the future of our new
family.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was normal about my pregnancy. But we tried to make it
seem so and took joy out of my expanding belly, baby showers,
nightly caramel turtle fudge ice cream trips and exposing our
unborn son to classical music and lullabies.
</P>
<P>
   The weeks of pregnancy and chemotherapy treatments ticked by.
Everything went fine until eight weeks before my due date. I went
into premature labor, one of the risks on which all the literature
agreed. Medication and full bed rest stopped the inevitable for a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks early, after a five-hour labor and natural delivery,
I cuddled to my remaining breast my long-awaited baby: Tanner J.
Wilson, beautiful, healthy, normal.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days after Tanner's birth I underwent my eighth and last
chemo treatment. I submitted once again to weeks of fatigue and
weakness as the nurse inserted the IV into a vein in my right hand.
I knew I would lack the strength to care for our new son by myself.
But I had to have the last treatment. What if one renegade cell
remained? It had to be snuffed out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, six years later, Tanner shows no ill effects of exposure to
chemotherapy. He is articulate, delightfully curious and as
challenging as any 5-year-old when he digs in his heels. He runs,
cartwheels and kicks a mean soccer ball.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, one renegade cell did remain. My cancer returned. In
1996, when Tanner was 15 months old, we found it had spread to my
sternum, the breast bone. This time the treatment was high-dose
chemotherapy with stem-cell rescue. Stem cells, immature cells from
which all blood cells develop, are removed from the body, treated
to kill cancer cells, then frozen. After very high doses of
chemotherapy are administered to the patient, killing healthy cells
as well as cancer cells, the stem cells are returned in hope that
they grow new healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this aggressive regimen, in January 1999 a biopsy showed
that the cancer had remained in the sternum and was growing. I had
one radical option left.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, my oncologist, Dr. Giudice, helped me find a
talented and compassionate team of surgeons at the M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center at the University of Texas in Houston. I had my
sternum removed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a painful six-month recovery and with a new
strong-as-bone plastic sternum, I look and feel better than I have
in six years. I am writing children's books, enjoying my son and
husband and continuing to look at the world through the eyes of a
cancer survivor. We see things differently _ all colors are
brilliant, music creates pictures, nature is more precious.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Cancer Society, a person with a bone
metastasis _ cancer spread beyond the initial site to bone _ has a
16 percent chance of surviving five years, although general health
and individual circumstances can raise the odds.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, I am part of that 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although I had always been convinced I would be one of those
survivors, I still treasure each milestone we reach with Tanner.
When he was born, I would say to Mark, ``We'll be blessed if I live
long enough to see Tanner walk.'' Our next goal was Tanner out of
diapers, then riding his first bike with training wheels. Now, it's
time for me to meet his kindergarten teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Would terminating my pregnancy have prevented the recurrences or
changed my survival possibilities? The medical community has mixed
opinions. But regardless of my final outcome, I know that I would
not have done anything differently.
</P>
<P>
   (Jana Striegel-Wilson's ``Homeroom Exercise,'' a novel for 8- to
12-year-olds, will be published next year by Holiday House.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
