</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENS-HYDRANGEAS-LIFEBEAT-900-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 VERSATILE HYDRANGEAS ENHANCE ANY GARDEN
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 By MICHAEL WEISHAN  
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plant enthusiasts have a tendency to be rather florid, if you'll
pardon the pun, when they describe their favorite species. But
hydrangeas number among those species for which the word
``remarkable'' can be used without exaggeration. How many plant
families can trace their history back 70 million years, are native
to three continents, contain members that are bushes, trees and
vines, are both deciduous and evergreen and have flowers that can
completely change color from year to year or season to season?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to mention that almost all hydrangeas are extremely
hardy, easy to grow and tolerate both full sun and partial shade. A
variety of hydrangea exists to suit any garden, from clay pots to
meticulously cultivated acres.
</P>
<P>
   The genus hydrangea is actually divided into at least eight
subsections, which are further broken down into at least a dozen
species and hundreds of cultivars _ though there are so many
different kinds of hydrangeas that even the botanical
nomenclaturists are often in disagreement as to the exact number.
It simplifies matters that the most common types of hydrangeas seen
in nurseries today belong to only five species: macrophylla,
paniculata, quercifolia, anomala and arborescens, and from each of
these I've selected one or two varieties that I think are real
knockouts in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   HYDRANGEA MACROPHYLLA 'Generale Vicomtesse de Vibraye': The
macrophyllas, often called somewhat erroneously the Lacecap
hydrangeas, are the species that most often come to mind when
people think of hydrangeas. Native to the temperate maritime
climates of eastern Asia, these are the potted plants often seen in
florist shops; in fact, the Generale is a common variety for
forcing indoors and container growing.
</P>
<P>
   Flowering continuously from early summer with large, pale
blooms, this wonderful shrub will grow quite large if given the
moist, mild (hardiness Zone 6 or warmer), dappled shade it loves.
The macrophyllas are also the hydrangea species that are capable of
the famous color-changing trick: In acid soil (pH 6.5 or less) the
bloom is blue: Add a little lime, and presto, subsequent blooms
will turn pink. The flower heads are also excellent for drying,
turning a lovely dusky hue.
</P>
<P>
   H. PANICULATA 'Grandiflora': Also known as the PeeGee hydrangea,
``H. paniculata'' is a common sight in many parts of the country.
Generally forming a shrub 6 to 10 feet high, 'Grandiflora' can also
be pruned to form a small, single-stemmed tree _ a shape
particularly beloved by the Victorians. Pruned upright, the large
blossoms, opening pink and then gradually turning to white, are
able to dangle enticingly in even the faintest breeze.
'Grandiflora' flowers _ buried inside the bloom heads _ are famous
for their drying ability. ``H. paniculata'' is extremely hardy
(Zones 3 and 4) and prefers full sun. Another worthwhile cultivar
is 'Tardiva,' which, as the name suggests, blooms much later than
'Grandiflora.'
</P>
<P>
   H. QUERCIFOLIA 'Snow Queen': This is one of my favorite members
of the hydrangea family, and, unfortunately, one of the least
known. The species name ``quercifolia'' means ``oak-leaved'' in
Latin, and the epithet is apt.
</P>
<P>
   The large oak-like leaves emerge fairly late in the spring,
followed in midsummer by large panicles of creamy white flowers 6
to 8 inches long. Like most other hydrangeas, this one requires a
constant supply of moisture; given extended periods of dryness,
most hydrangeas will wilt miserably. But unlike its cousins that
prefer at least partial sun, this beauty will take a considerable
amount of shade, and for that reason I like to use oakleaved
hydrangeas in the landscape as backdrops to hosta, astilbe and
other shade-loving plants. Hardy to Zone 5, ``H. quercifolia'' has
the added benefit of lovely fall color _ the leaves turn purple-red
and remain on the plant for quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
   H. ARBORESCENS 'Annabelle': This is a stellar plant, and one
that should be in almost every landscape. Growing between 3 and 5
feet high, this American native is covered in huge white balls of
flower in June, some up to 12 inches in diameter. In fact, this
generosity in flowers may be its only flaw _ 'Annabelle' is so
floriferous that the huge blooms will often weigh down and
occasionally snap the branches after a heavy rain. This cultivar
also has the added benefit of reblooming, if the first round of
blossoms is removed when spent.
</P>
<P>
   Tolerant of light shade, 'Annabelle' requires a moist though
well drained spot with reasonably high fertility to produce the
best show. Hardy from Zones 3 to 9, this shrub is perfect for mass
plantings on the edge of the woods or lawn.
</P>
<P>
   H. ANOMALA subsp. ``petiolaris'': The lustrous, dark-green
leaves of this climbing member of the hydrangea family are the
perfect background for the large, fragrant white flowers, which
open in June and July and last for more than a month. Tolerant of
sun or shade, climbing hydrangeas ascend by twining, making them
ideal for growing up the side of a trellis or tree.
</P>
<P>
   Left on their own, the vines can reach 80 feet; in bloom, they
are an almost unimaginably beautiful sight. Virtually pest-free,
the only drawback to this species is that it is almost painfully
slow to get started: The first few years the plant seems to hardly
move at all, and then, suddenly, the growth is exponential.
Originating in China and Japan, climbing hydrangeas are hardy from
Zones 4 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Weishan is a contributing editor of ``Country Living''
magazine and host of ``The Cultivated Gardener,'' which airs on
Public Radio.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
