<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS WEB: PALMS HOLD PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors, in 12th graf: It took, etc., note that (Star) has been
used as a substitute for the asterisk) 
(For release Sunday, August 13) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, it's almost a consensus among Internet pundits that the
future of the Web rests in the hands _ or, perhaps more
appropriately, the palms _ of those who make wireless Internet
devices and software. Why would consumers want to be shackled to a
desktop computer, the thinking goes, when they could roam freely
with a hand-held device that gives them everything they need?
</P>
<P>
   Since mobile Internet devices like Web-connected cellular phones
and so-called personal digital assistants (PDA's) like the Palm VII
were born and bred for on-the-road use, futurists have dreamed up
especially rosy scenarios for travel applications.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the problem. Nearly all the talk surrounding mobile
Internet devices and applications is in the future tense.
</P>
<P>
   You will be able to program your phone to call you when you're
on the road and alert you to shoes that are on sale, in your size,
at the store you happen to be walking past at that moment. You will
be able to tap the screen a couple of times on your cell phone and
have a guide tell you about a tourist site without actually having
to have a human near you. (Heaven forbid that should happen.)
</P>
<P>
   And on it goes. The reality is that today's wireless Internet
offerings look a lot like the wired Internet offerings of 1995.
They're useful if you have patience and are willing to spend the
money on the hardware and the connection time. But they can also
present frustrating limitations.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that, because businesses see such huge demand
for wireless Internet gizmos, it won't take five years for the
technology to improve dramatically. Some particularly useful travel
applications, in fact, are arriving en masse this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every company that caters to the traveler has some
semblance of a wireless Internet strategy and is working hard to
refine it. For instance, Travelocity offers wireless users the
option of checking their flight status, and by summer's end will
allow users to change their flight itineraries from their wireless
phones. So if you get off your plane and discover _ along with the
other 200 people on the plane _ that your connecting flight has
been canceled, you can conceivably skip the mad dash to the
customer service desk and simply call up the Travelocity site to
make the change.
</P>
<P>
   Trip.com already has such a feature. By pushing a button on a
cell phone, you get options for rebooking your flight. So if you
are late for a flight or have already missed it, you can select
from the next available flights, press a button and see a
confirmation number on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Like many such services, this feature requires a little work
beforehand on a desktop computer. Typically, users must register
personal information and a credit card number with the site _ or,
in Trip.com's case, book a flight with the site _ so they can avoid
the maddening task of inputting numbers and text on a wireless
device.
</P>
<P>
   I recently tested a Palm VII, the latest technological wizardry.
It retails for about $500, with unlimited Internet access through
Palm.net for about $45 a month. I pretended I was lost going home
from an appointment, and tapped on the MapQuest.com icon.
</P>
<P>
   As with most other Internet sites on wireless devices, MapQuest
has, in the interest of speed, modified its site to include only
bare essentials _ no photos, no graphics. MapQuest started me
immediately with a form to fill in addresses for directions.
</P>
<P>
   It took a lot of tapping to get the addresses typed in, but
about five minutes later, I had step-by-step directions home.
Buoyed by my success, I checked the status of an imaginary flight I
was taking to San Francisco. I went to the Travelocity site on my
Palm and tapped the icon for departure and arrival information, and
it told me the scheduled times for departure and arrival. Then it
informed me that the actual times of departure and arrival were
``:61???'' and ``:92???(STAR)'' respectively. Lower down on the
screen, the site told me the asterisk denotes the estimated arrival
time, which helped clear things up tremendously.
</P>
<P>
   My trusty cell phone was next. I tried to get directions, but
that involved entering text using the phone's keypad. For this, you
hold down the ``2'' button, for instance, until the screen shows
the letter ``C,'' then press the ``7'' button until you get an
``S,'' and so on. Talk about a recipe for road rage.
</P>
<P>
   After about 10 minutes of this, my phone told me that my home
address did not exist, which made me consider driving my car over
my phone so that it, too, did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans who use wireless devices to gain access
to the Internet will be about 1.3 million by year's end _ most
through cell phones, with PDA's like the Palm VII accounting for
roughly 300,000, according to the Yankee Group, a technology
consulting firm. Analysts and executives say that will grow to 38
million by 2002, with 30 million cell phones connected to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the sudden growth is that the next generation of
wireless Internet devices will likely combine the phone and the
Personal Digital Assistant, eliminating the cost of multiple units.
Next year's cell phone/PDAs will also likely have touch screens,
with prices comparable to or lower than today's units, and faster
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Today's wireless devices typically connect at speeds of about 14
kilobits to 19 kilobits per second, a far cry from a 56-kbps modem,
but because the sites have done their best to create text-only
presentations, the sluggish connection is not too much of a burden.
And as connection speeds increase, Internet connection fees should
drop, analysts said, because telecommunications companies will find
other ways to pay the freight of the service, such as getting a
percentage of transactions made by users.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, offerings from Internet sites will improve
quickly, giving users more reason to get unplugged, as it were.
Zagat, for instance, now lets wireless users get the names of
restaurants in different cities, review their ratings, and press a
button to call the establishment. Starting next month, the
reservation will be made by pushing a button; in November, hotel
and spa ratings and reservations will be added.
</P>
<P>
   Through a service called Tellme (www.tellme.com), users can look
up Zagat's content _ and that of other Web sites _ by speaking
their requests into the phone. There is something odd about
speaking into a phone to get Internet content, but for someone who
doesn't want to risk life and limb to look at the screen on their
cell phone or PDA, the service is comforting.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers who want to take in a show or a sporting event
while on the road, Ticketmaster-CitySearch offers wireless options
_ and, notably, options that don't require you to type in ``Hootie
and the Blowfish'' on your cell phone. Through the Ticketmaster
wireless site, users choose a city and their area of interest, such
as music or sports, and choices appear on the screen. If users have
already registered their credit card information with Ticketmaster
on its nonwireless Web page (www.ticketmaster.com), they can buy
tickets with a press of a button or a tap on their PDA screen.
</P>
<P>
   Such oases will be increasingly common. And while such features
will be enough to lure some of the more technology-addicted
travelers to hand-held devices, for those who want more potency and
less potential from their wireless, it's a wait-till-next-year
story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
