<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-NEWARK-AIRPORT     08-07 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NEWARK-AIRPORT-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING 33.9 MILLION PASSENGERS TO, FROM, AND AROUND NEWARK
AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As air travel set a record earlier this summer _ with major
domestic airlines flying fuller planes than at any time since World
War II _ Newark Airport, the New York area's busiest, was putting
its monorail on sick leave. The system was partly shut for repairs
on July 8 and will be completely closed after Labor Day, possibly
till the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year-old monorail has been handling 30,000 people a
day, getting them, their luggage and wheelchairs in from car-rental
sites and parking lots, shifting them among the three terminals and
returning them to drop-off spots. Now, according to John S. Jacoby,
assistant manager of airport services for Newark, the contractor
must repair a flaw that causes the rails to ice over in winter.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was not happy news for Newark, the nation's 11th
busiest airport, which handled 33.9 million passengers in the 12
months that ended April 30, as against Kennedy Airport's 32.2
million. Newark, already in the midst of construction projects
affecting most of its 2,000 acres, decided to postpone the full
shutdown until after the summer crush. Jacoby said it was hoped the
repair could be completed in three months, but a return by
Thanksgiving is doubtful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The monorail is now serving only the central portion of its
normal route, linking Terminals A, B and C and Station D-1, the
site for Avis, Hertz and National, and some parking. It skips three
stops: D-2, a site for Budget and Dollar and the pickup spot for
off-airport rental companies; D-3, a parking area, and E, which
serves a parking area, vans from hotels and motels and off-airport
parking, and valet parking. The stops not reached by the monorail
are served by 35 buses marked by construction-orange signs. After
Labor Day, more than 50 buses will fill in.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which operates
the airport, suggests that travelers using Newark allow at least 30
minutes more travel time than their airline recommends; it is
probably smart to add 15 minutes more to figure out what you are
doing. Here is a little help:
</P>
<P>
   All air passengers must at some point rely on rubber-tired
wheels to get to Kennedy, La Guardia or Newark; short of using a
helicopter, it remains impossible to get all the way without
risking traffic tie-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Until a new station links the Amtrak-New Jersey Transit rail
lines to a new monorail station, planned for a year from now,
Newark has the poorest junction with rapid transit. Most New
Jerseyans get there by car, and Jacoby believes they prefer it that
way.
</P>
<P>
   He says the airport has 16,000 parking spots, and 6,500 more are
being created in two huge garages, one by Monorail Station E and
one by Continental's Terminal C. These are expected to open next
year. Construction, however, is tearing up existing lots in
sequence, and Jacoby says it is impossible to say from day to day
how many spaces are lost. Despite this, he says, lots are seldom
entirely filled; the big complaint is that people cannot park where
they want.
</P>
<P>
   On holidays, when business travel slows and leisure travel
rises, the long-term economy lots can be swamped with vacationers
seeking $8-a-day rates. Then, Jacoby said, drivers may be directed
to spaces in daily lots, where they are given parking checks that
entitle them to a bargain: $8 instead of $24 a day. When everything
does fill, he said, directions are posted to private areas off the
airport. In such situations, Jacoby said, the operators may
distribute discount coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, travelers using private cars should enlist someone to
drop them off. The bad part of that plan is the return, when the
pickup person must call to see if the plane is on time, which in
May happened only 66.4 percent of the time at Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is valet parking, at $18 a day. Customers
tell the attendants when they are due back, and get a phone number
to call with changes. The car is brought from a remote lot in time
for the return.
</P>
<P>
   Families with children who want to use the cheaper lots should
budget time for two loops through congested roadways. On the first,
an adult should deposit everyone else and all the bags to start the
check-in. Then the driver should park and ride the free bus back to
the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to Newark from the east shore of the Hudson usually
involves taking a bus from the midtown Port Authority Bus Terminal,
Penn Station or Grand Central. The timetable says Olympia Airport
Express, but Coach USA now owns the company. The fare is $11 one
way, $20 round trip. A round-trip fare of $10 is available to
passengers displaying Medicare cards or New Jersey Transit Reduced
Fare identification cards. Reduced-fare MetroCards with photos,
used in the New York City transit system by senior citizens, are
not recognized.
</P>
<P>
   The right terminal at Newark is not an automatic choice,
particularly if you are flying Continental, which handles half of
Newark's passengers. It has flights at Terminals A, B and C,
depending on the destination.
</P>
<P>
   Its flights to Chicago, Atlanta and Dallas leave from Terminal
A. Terminal B is the international arrivals building, but
Continental's London flights leave from there. The majority of the
line's flights use Terminal C, although pressure like this summer's
can cause the line to shift to any available gate: on June 30, the
line reported 89.7 percent of its seats were filled, a record. A
system called code-sharing also confuses the issue because a flight
sold under one airline's name may be flown by another line out of
that line's gate. Gates 10 to 39 are in Terminal A. Gates 40 to 68
are in Terminal B. Gates 70 to 121 are in Terminal C.
</P>
<P>
   Until Labor Day, the monorail is the best way to travel between
terminals. It runs on the outside curve of the three terminals at
the concourse level, reached by escalators and elevators. It
accommodates wheelchairs and luggage carts. (Domestic passengers
pay $1.50 to rent carts; people coming through Customs get them
free.) In two midday tests, monorails arrived pretty promptly.
</P>
<P>
   The bypass buses, by Jacoby design, do not pick up passengers
while they discharge them: they pick up, go someplace and
discharge, then start over. Bus arrivals are designed to be five
minutes apart. These buses are boarded in the outdoor bus bays to
the left of each terminal as you exit. The buses are tied into a
global positioning system using satellites so that dispatchers can
direct them where they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   The buses frequently have luggage racks, but luggage carts
cannot be rolled aboard, as they can onto the monorail. So
passengers using bypass buses will have to cough up another $1.50
for a new cart. Wheelchairs also cannot go aboard the buses.
Red-jacketed customer service representatives call for
wheelchair-accessible vans.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, despite the dust and mud outside, the inside of
Terminal C presents a much improved environment. Staples, Speedo,
the Museum Co., the Discovery Channel and other places to buy
things you might want or need have opened in recent months. A
counter that sells CD's is just outside the Continental Young
Travelers Club, where children traveling alone await connecting
flights if their parents pay a fee of $60 or more. On a recent
Tuesday, eight young people were inside watching television; the
Garden State Diner was SRO.
</P>
<P>
   Sets of benches have been placed at the marked meeting spots for
limousine drivers; considering Newark's record for delays, it seems
like a humane gesture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
