<P>
   AMD _ AMD's former communications products division made its
debut Monday as Legerity Inc., an Austin-based spinoff that wants
to be a player in the market for chips going into high-speed
Internet access equipment. The company has 200 workers in Austin
and is planning to hire more, including a chief executive. In the
meantime it is leasing space from AMD. (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   LOWES-FORESTS _ Lowe's will detail its new policy to phase out
``old-growth'' wood a day before its official announcement.
Environmentalists are giddy about Lowe's plan, which they say
outmuscles Home Depot's. Both retailers are requiring vendors to
prove their products come from well-managed forests. And both are
using standards developed by the Forest Stewardship Council, which
has big forest companies irked because they've developed their own
voluntary plan. We'll update Home Depot's progress, plus talk about
thorny issues in the South, where private landowners own most
timberland. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   PORT-WAR _ The world's largest shipping line, Maersk Sealand, is
pitting Charleston against Savannah in competition for Maersk's
South Atlantic shipping business. The line has said a critical
factor will be in the two ports' ability to deepen their channels,
two environmentally sensitive projects. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS AND INFOBOX.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
