<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4978 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-07 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE OPTS FOR INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By choosing to run for the White House with Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Vice President Al Gore came about
as close as he decently could to sticking a finger in President
Clinton's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a senior Democratic legislator of impeccable personal
integrity, was the party's most thoughtful _ and most devastating _
critic of Clinton's inexcusable behavior during his affair with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans never directly mentioned her during their
convention, but they didn't have to. They constantly deplored the
decline of presidential character and the administration's failure
to respect the dignity of the Oval Office. Everybody got the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is Gore's answer to the concentrated, oily GOP
campaign to lump the vice president's behavior with that of the
president. ``We will never think of one without thinking of the
other,'' GOP vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney intoned.
</P>
<P>
   It was practicing guilt by association at the highest political
level. We were encouraged to believe that there is no philosophical
or ethical difference between Clinton and Gore, even though insofar
as anyone knows, Gore's private life is spotless.
</P>
<P>
   And judging by the polls immediately following the GOP
convention that give Gov. George W. Bush a healthy lead of 17
percentage points, the assault was working.
</P>
<P>
   So Gore picked a little-known but respected Orthodox Jew who was
the first of his party to stand up on the Senate floor and condemn
Clinton's behavior as ``not just inappropriate but immoral It is
wrong and unacceptable.'' The popular senator delivered a stern
lecture about the importance of good values in family and political
life.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he thought the president ought to be censured,
and ultimately he refused to jump party lines to convict Clinton of
any impeachable offense. But his criticism shook the Clinton White
House, encouraged other Democrats to join in and reinforced his
image as the moral conscience of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's religious values are not cosmetic, as they are with
some politicians. He practices what he believes. He is so serious
about his faith that he refuses to campaign or do nonessential
chores during the Jewish Sabbath, which he observes from sundown
Friday to sundown Saturday. His interpretation of religious family
values has also led him to crusade against sexually explicit and
violent films, music, television programs and video games.
</P>
<P>
   With Lieberman, Gore is practicing what the Republicans preached
in Philadelphia _ inclusiveness. As the first Jew on a major
party's national ticket, Lieberman will test the country's true
tolerance of religious diversity.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a measure of our country's greatness that our leaders
do not fear to tread where others have never gone before. In the
relatively dark ages of 1960, Sen. John F. Kennedy similarly
challenged public resistance to the idea of a Catholic president
and broke that particular barrier forever. Religion has not been a
dominant issue since, although Christian, especially evangelical,
leaders have until this year heavily influenced GOP politics.
</P>
<P>
   A recent CNN-USA Today Gallup poll indicates that 92 percent of
those surveyed said they would vote for a Jewish person for
president, but nobody knows whether some people simply refuse to
admit to anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, this was Gore's bold move to shake up the
established thinking, much as Walter Mondale in 1984 chose
Geraldine Ferraro as the first female running mate on a major
ticket in hopes of breaking President Ronald Reagan's lead in the
polls. It didn't succeed but it did attract women in droves to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The gray-haired Lieberman, 58, is not the symbol of
forward-looking youth that Gore had indicated he was seeking when
he considered junior senators. Instead, he opted for a running mate
who is qualified to become president if necessary, who supports
abortion rights and gun control and who is generally in the middle
of the road on defense and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   To attack Lieberman as a liberal counterpoint to Cheney's
extreme conservatism won't wash, based on Lieberman's record. He is
the chairman of the Democratic Leadership Council, a vehicle to
advance moderate Democratic policies that Clinton also once headed.
He is, in fact, a Clinton-style Democrat in legislative and
economic matters. Wall Street should be comfortable with this
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was not disloyal to his party in condemning the
president's bad behavior. Nor is Gore disloyal in running with a
man who openly disapproved of an immoral White House. Gore himself
has said he thinks Clinton did wrong in the Lewinsky affair, while
sticking to his general support of administration policies and
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not Clinton any more than Dubya is Daddy Bush. This is a
new ball game. And the sooner the country accepts that and gets on
with the real election contest, the better off we will all be.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VP-REACT08-COX     08-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-REACT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP says Lieberman sounds like a Republican
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a back-handed compliment, the George W. Bush presidential
campaign on Monday hailed the opposition's newly announced running
mate as a good man with some good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Connecticut Sen. Joe Lieberman's ideas are so good,
according to Bush-Cheney campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer, that
they sound more Republican that Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush and Secretary Cheney respect Joe Lieberman for
his intelligence, his integrity, and for many of the positions he
has taken, positions which Governor Bush and Secretary Cheney
support but Al Gore has attacked,'' Fleischer said. ``From Social
Security reform to missile defense, tort reform to parental
notification (abortion), and from school choice to affirmative
action, Al Gore has chosen a man whose positions are more similar
to Governor Bush's than to his own.''
</P>
<P>
   It adds up to good news for Bush, Fleischer added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Al Gore is willing to select a running mate
whose positions he has attacked throughout this campaign will cause
many to question Al Gore's commitment to the positions he takes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut on Monday, Lieberman said he and Gore ``have
walked pretty much the same path,'' but acknowledged some
differences on issues.
</P>
<P>
   Those differences include the Democratic ticketmates' positions
on school vouchers. Gore takes the party line that vouchers are a
one-way ticket to ruination of the public schools. Lieberman has
sponsored several measures that would have set up experimental
programs allowing parents to use government education dollars to
send their kids to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush favors that concept, which Lieberman has backed away from
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also sides with Bush _ and against Gore _ on the
concept of partial privatization of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Lieberman, a vocal critic of President
Clinton's liaisons with Monica Lewinsky, though he voted not to
remove the president from office, comes in the wake of the Bush
campaign's effort to link Gore with the worst of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, as the man from Hope goes home to New York, Mr. Gore
tries to separate himself from his leader's shadow,'' Cheney said
in his acceptance speech in Philadelphia last week. ``But somehow
we will never see one without thinking of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lieberman selection, the first Jew to be on a national
ticket, also could bring new focus to Bush comments that brought
questions from some Jews in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, prior to his successful 1994 gubernatorial campaign,
Bush, a Methodist, said his religion tells him that heaven is open
only to people who accept Jesus Christ as their savior.
</P>
<P>
   He later said the comment was misunderstood. In 1998, after a
discussion with Bush, Abraham Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League, said he believes Bush harbors no religious
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Foxman, who on Monday hailed Gore's selection of Lieberman for
the Democratic ticket, issued a 1998 statement saying Bush had
proven his ``commitment to tolerance, diversity and the principles
of religious freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Foxman, Bush said he was ``troubled that some
people were hurt by my remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Judgments about heaven do not belong in the realm of politics
or this world; they belong to a higher authority,'' Bush told
Foxman.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Bush drew criticism for issuing a gubernatorial
proclamation designating June 10 as ``Jesus Day'' in Texas in
conjunction with the annual March for Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish Congress criticized Bush for mixing state
and church, calling the proclamation an ``egregious example'' of an
elected official trying to ``accommodate the religious views'' of
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides responded by noting he also had issued proclamations
honoring other religious organizations and places of worship.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
