</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-WAHID-ART-2     08-07 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-WAHID-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT TO LEAVE   HIS DAILY DUTIES TO SUBORDINATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A newly humble President Abdurrahman Wahid
apologized to the nation Monday for falling short of expectations
as Indonesia struggles to build a working democracy and said he
would name an executive minister to bring order to his flailing
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a state-of-the-nation speech that opened a restive annual
parliamentary session, Wahid said he would begin concentrating more
on foreign affairs and would create a sort of prime ministerial
post to handle day-to-day domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Admired for his integrity, democratic ideals and intellect,
Wahid has drawn constant criticism for his disorganized and
impulsive leadership style. He has talked in the past of delegating
daily administration to a chief-of-staff. The harshness of much of
the attacks reflects what many analysts call the political
immaturity of a nation whose growth was stunted by three decades of
authoritarian rule under former President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has made foreign affairs something of a hobby, visiting 30
countries _ some of them several times _ during his 10 months in
office, even as Indonesia struggles with economic collapse,
sectarian violence, separatist movements and political disarray.
</P>
<P>
   The president, 60, who is virtually blind, has talked in the
past of delegating daily administration to a chief-of-staff. He had
his speech read by an aide today as he sat nearby, occasionally
dozing off. Wahid said Monday that the new ministerial post would
be part of a broad reorganization of his bloated and feuding
cabinet, which is widely expected to include the creation of a more
focused and professional economic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not comfortable with details, so he will need somebody
to run day-to-day governance for him,'' said Sarwono Kusumaatmadja,
a cabinet member who is minister of maritime affairs.
</P>
<P>
   After clashing repeatedly with the noisy legislature over the
past months, Wahid suddenly changed tack Monday, as he often does,
and was contrite.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the people of Indonesia, I humbly apologize for being
unable to fully solve the prevailing problems during the last 10
months,'' he said. ``Rest assured, however, that we would work even
harder to strive for more accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really more than willing to do whatever necessary to
improve the performance of the government by adopting proper
policies and strategies and sharpening agendas and priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's speech, lasting nearly 90 minutes, was a powerful tour
of the political scene, laying out his vision for a tolerant,
inclusive, democratic nation and echoing many analysts in blaming
the current problems on the aftermath of Suharto's 32-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, 79, who was forced from office in May 1998, was charged
with corruption last Thursday. His case is expected to be presented
to a court this week.
</P>
<P>
   The day's session was also a demonstration of the chaotic new
openness and personal quirkiness that have supplanted Suharto's
dour style and harsh grip on all aspects of national affairs.
</P>
<P>
   After opening _ as always _ with a joke or two, Wahid said that
his political secretary, Marislam Simanjuntak, would read his
speech for him.
</P>
<P>
   Then Wahid, who tends to fall asleep at public meetings, dozed
off several times during the reading of his own speech. In what
appeared to be a planned tactic, an adjutant woke him each time by
handing him a hard candy to suck on.
</P>
<P>
   In another signal that the Suharto years were over, the assembly
began with a clamor when a dozen or so of the 700 delegates sought
to make procedural points by shouting ``Interruption!
Interruption!''
</P>
<P>
   The interruption is a parliamentary motion that allows delegates
from the floor to be heard. During Suharto's 32 years in power this
break with enforced unanimity was almost never heard; indeed it led
at least once to the expulsion of a member from the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   There was widespread speculation Monday that the new executive
manager would be a prominent former lieutenant general, Susilo
Bambang Yudhoyuno, a military reformer who is now the minister of
mines and energy.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the government said Vice President Megawati
Sukarnoputri, a powerful figure who leads the country's largest
party, might want the job for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Such a development, they said, could complicate government by
creating competing power centers. Though Megawati is not herself an
aggressive manager, she has created a respected minicabinet of her
own.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the morning, Megawati, whose passivity contrasts with
Wahid's puckishness, showed no expression, busying herself with
wiping her neck and her glasses with a small cloth and rattling a
small fan beside her face.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session was remarkable for one other development: the
excitement was confined to the parliament chamber. This is the
first major political event since Suharto's departure that has not
been accompanied by turmoil and bloodshed on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Though security forces prepared, as they have in the past, with
a huge contingent of nearly 30,000 soldiers and police officers,
there were no mass rallies. The small orange buses with students
dancing on the roofs, the face-offs with police, the stone-throwing
and baton charges of past demonstrations were conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things will stay calm,'' said Sarwono. ``It has become
very hard to mobilize and agitate the people now because the public
is sending strong signals that they want stability.''
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, perhaps, Wahid has made headway as he seeks to
calm the nation. Analysts agree that most of the problems for which
he absorbs the blame run deep and defy quick solution.
</P>
<P>
   Having acknowledged his shortcomings, Wahid, in his prepared
speech, strongly affirmed the ideals that are the banner of his
administration as it seeks to pull Indonesia toward cohesion and
cooperation and away from the bloodshed and fragmentation that
threaten it in the wake of Suharto's departure.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that he had taken the difficult step of bringing the
politically powerful military under civilian control, had promoted
human rights and permitted a free and open press, had taken steps
to combat government corruption and had worked to nurse an economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, he had opened negotiations with separatist
movements in Aceh and Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
   A number of these actions have had decidedly mixed results. The
military remains divided and restive with a breakdown in the chain
of command that has contributed to horrific bloodshed in the Maluku
Islands, where more than 3,000 people have been killed in the past
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Violence also continues in Aceh and Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Corruption remains widespread and Wahid himself has come under
attack for several questionable deals and allocations of funds.
Most troubling, the faltering economy _ which precipitated
Suharto's fall _ has not been healed.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's promised government changes could directly address this
problem. Although analysts say some economic fundamentals now
appear stronger, the currency has continued to slide in value and
foreign investors have stayed away. This has largely been because
of political uncertainties that have been aggravated by Wahid's
unpredictable style and the disarray of his economic management.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parliamentary session, which will last until Aug
18, was preceded by a surge of political squabbles and calls for
his impeachment, most prominent politicians now say they will give
the president another chance to bring his administration under
control.
</P>
<P>
   Sarwono said there is no chance now that an impeachment motion
will go forward, as some legislators have warned. ``Nil. Zero. Hot
air,'' he said of the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a high probability of more hot air. The legislature
is angry, divided, filled with muscle-flexing and political
agendas. There are still 11 days to go before the session ends. The
legislators' turn to take the floor begins on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
