<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4984 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-BAYLOR-8     08-07 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-BAYLOR-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
 (EDS: Accompanied by
BAYLOR-TIMELINE and BAYLOR-PROJECTS) RESEARCHER SUGGESTS
OSTEOPOROSIS MAY BE DISEASE OF BRAIN AS WELL AS BONE (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By JESSIE MILLIGAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   The search for a cure for one of the most debilitating diseases
of old age is under way, here in the laboratories of Baylor College
of Medicine in Houston. Outside, nine floors below the urban
multistory medical school, the city is crippled by fractured
streets and sidewalks under repair.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unsettling thought that someday, in the normal course of
the weakening of human bones, the pedestrians scurrying around the
construction outside may not be able to walk at all.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the old streets of Houston, the old human infastructure
cannot be as easily rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Bone disappears as we age. It becomes less dense, more porous.
Once adult bone is gone, it is gone forever. No one knows how to
rebuild it. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Baylor labs, French-born Gerard Karsenty, physician,
professor and researcher, and a team of other scientists are
working on a project that may help us to rebuild our own
infrastructure from the inside out.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor, a detective of sorts, one who tracks missing bone,
says he has discovered that the brain has the power to signal the
skeleton to rebuild itself.
</P>
<P>
   It could be, if Karsenty can figure out how to signal the brain
to rebuild bone, that this discovery may someday lead to a cure for
osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoporosis, a gradual loss of bone density as the body ages,
leaves skeletons more fragile and susceptible to fractures,
including debilitating breaks to hips and spines. Karsenty
estimates that 28 million Americans _ particularly thin, elderly
Caucasian and Asian women _ have fragile bones, and of those about
half have become crippled by it.
</P>
<P>
   Although osteoporosis strikes far more women than men, more
whites than blacks, more old than young, the disease shows up
across racial and age lines.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoporosis is insidious, silent. Not many people who have it
even know they do, not until they get a serious fracture. By then,
the bone is gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   All doctors can do now is recommend preventative steps to stop
further bone loss. The National Osteoporosis Foundation says
calcium, vitamin D, weight-bearing exercise and strength training
all prevent bones from degrading. Four medications also are on the
market to prevent further bone loss for those who have been found
to have osteoporosis. Estrogen-replacement therapy is considered
helpful in preventing excessive bone loss in post-menopausal women,
although it carries with it negative side effects such as the
increased risk for breast and uterine cancers.
</P>
<P>
   A cure would help millions. Karsenty is on the path.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-two years ago, in France, Gerard Karsenty was born into a
family where medicine is a tradition. His father was an
opthalmologist _ an eye doctor. The younger Karsenty wanted
something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A physician delivers a treatment. I want to create a
treatment,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   What he wants to do, he says, is study the core of our being,
the very framework that holds everything else together, the very
skeleton that degrades as we age.
</P>
<P>
   He studied medicine at the University of Paris, graduating in
1984. The most prestigious medical research institutions in the
United States saw his promise. As a post-doctoral fellow, he
studied molecular, cellular and nutritional endocrinology at the
National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md., and genes at the
National Cancer Institute before moving to the University of Texas
M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston in 1987. In 1998, he moved
to Baylor as a researcher and as a professor, where he teaches the
next generation of doctors about human and molecular genetics.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Karsenty, gray-haired, sturdy of frame, not a top candidate for
osteoporosis himself, has devoted his research to the study of
bones. You can ask him, ``Do you have anyone in your family who has
osteoporosis?'' and he will look at you like he doesn't know how
could you possibly even ask that. And he will say, ``Everyone gets
osteoporosis.'' If they live long enough, he explains, because
eventually bone will break down.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, Karsenty decided to link the most
well-known facts about bones and bone loss in a study with his
colleagues at Baylor, scientists Patricia Ducy, Shu Takeda and
Jianhe Shen, as well as five researchers from the University of
Hamburg, Germany, and one from the U.S. National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   If outlined on a blackboard, their hypothesis would look
something like this:
</P>
<P>
   1. Bone mass is affected by menopause. When the hormone estrogen
is switched off, bones become more breakable.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bone mass is affected by obesity. Fat people are at less of a
risk than thin people. In 1994, the medical community became aware
of a hormone called leptin. Leptin works through the brain to
regulate weight. If we don't have much leptin, we are fat.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothetical questions: If the hormone estrogen affects bone
mass, could the hormone leptin also affect bone mass?
</P>
<P>
   So for about two years, Karsenty and the team _ working in three
separate labs in Texas, Maryland and Germany _ have been studying
mice. About 1,000 of the small rodents, scurrying through the
sawdust in glass aquariumlike cages in the labs, are observed.
</P>
<P>
   They study mice that have no ability to reproduce, and they
study mice that can reproduce. Males and females are studied.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a former Baylor public affairs employee writes a
press release that says the sterile mice studied are menopausal,
but really, they are not. The mice lack hormones, just as
menopausal women do. But the nonreproducing mice in the study have
been sterile since birth.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers inject leptin into the hypothalamus region of
the mice's brains. By studying mice bones under a microscope, they
discover that when the hormone leptin is present, the bones do not
rebuild. When the hormone leptin is in low supply, the bones get
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The research represents a milestone, said current Baylor
spokesperson Lynn Foltin. For the first time, scientists can say
that the brain controls bone mass. Bone is not kept strong only by
nutrition, weight-bearing exercise and strength-training. Hormones
affecting our brains also are at work.
</P>
<P>
   The research opens a new door for more researchers to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osteoporosis may be a brain disease as much as it is a bone
disease,'' Karsenty said.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the cure? Not yet. It may be pointing researchers that
way, but there is a big kink to work out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, it is the roly-poly lab mice that have great
bones.
</P>
<P>
   They are obese little guys, weighing 60 grams instead of the
normal 20 grams.
</P>
<P>
   So the challenge for Karsenty and his team is to figure out how
to regulate leptin without making mice obese. They also must figure
out how the brain sends messages about leptin to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Studies with humans have not been done. Karsenty said leptin and
bone loss work the same way in mice as they do in people, so he is
confident the results can someday be transferred to human medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Much work remains.
</P>
<P>
   Karsenty's results so far have been reported in the medical
journal Cell, and elsewhere. The study has met with everything from
great joy to great incredulity, he said. But that's the way it is
with discoveries. Not everyone will be happy to be led off into a
new direction. Most osteoporosis research now centers on the impact
of calcium and exercise, not on the impact of hormones regulated by
the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Karsenty will not divulge the amount of money spent on the
research.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue to do more research.
</P>
<P>
   It could take five years, it could take 20 years to complete the
research, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no deadlines in my lab,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he continues, searching for the way to build bones, the very
frame of our existence.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4987 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-BAYLOR-8     08-07 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-BAYLOR-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER SUGGESTS OSTEOPOROSIS MAY BE DISEASE OF BRAIN AS WELL AS
BONE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by BAYLOR-TIMELINE and BAYLOR-PROJECTS) 
 (Resending to fix coding)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
