<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TEEN-MOVIES-2TAKES-NY     08-07 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS NOTEBOOK: BEHIND THE GROSS-OUT HUMOR, THE TEEN-AGE MOVIE IN
HIDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the movie box office, like the pop music charts, is ruled by
the taste and purchasing power of high school students, why are
there so few credible representations of adolescent life on today's
movie screens?
</P>
<P>
   The American teen-ager was invented some time in the 1950s, a
cultural byproduct of the baby boom, the rise of the suburbs and
the explosive growth of television and the recording industry. From
the start, the teen-ager was a source of anxiety and an object of
longing _ the vision of a terrifying, amoral future and the image
of an irrecoverably innocent past _ as well as an irresistible
target for marketers of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Eisenhower years saw the convening of congressional
committees to assess the dire menace of comic books and the
supposed epidemic of juvenile delinquency. The rise of rock 'n'
roll sparked a culture war that has never really abated through
decades of psychedelia, heavy metal and gangsta rap.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all a lot of grown-ups got rich holding magic
mirrors up to pimply faces, selling young people and the rest of
the world a series of confused, beguiling fantasies about life in
the shopping malls, study halls and dormitories of America.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last half-century, teen-age life has seemed at once
unalterable and ephemeral. Its defining themes _ rebellion against
parental, academic and political authority, sexual and romantic
exploration, wanton irresponsibility and uncompromising idealism _
recur from decade to decade, but the reference points are always
perishable and specific.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing ages faster than youth culture. The pop songs and
fashion statements that define one generation's horizons of
experience quickly appear ridiculous to the children and younger
siblings who follow. (Did you really think that haircut looked
good? How could you listen to that?) But at last the bell-bottoms
and make-out anthems are rescued from the thrift shop shelves and
the cutout bins, rediscovered as retro chic, classic rock and old
school flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The first teen-agers are now grandparents. The cinematic emblems
of their wild youth are either long dead (James Dean, Elvis
Presley) or unrecognizably altered (Marlon Brando, Warren Beatty).
But Hollywood's ambivalent attention to the young and its ardent
courtship of them are perhaps more intense than ever. A summer that
in box office terms seemed to be headed for disappointment a month
ago has been miraculously redeemed, in no small part because of
youthful enthusiasm for ``Scary Movie'' and ``X-Men.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if these movies appeal to young people, neither is
strictly speaking a teen-age movie. Since last summer, a parade of
forgettable prom-date and college-sweetheart romantic comedies has
marched into theaters and almost as quickly marched out again. As
is so often the case, television has done a bit better, offering
watchable prime-time soap operas with a canny, covert
cross-generational appeal. And now, with ``American High'' on Fox,
the nation's insatiable demand for reality-based programming has
met its queasy fascination with the almost grown.
</P>
<P>
   I can't help wondering how many members of the generation
depicted in ``American High,'' R.J. Cutler's documentary series,
will be watching. My suspicion is that a significant segment of the
audience will be people in their 20s and 30s, a group whose morbid
devotion to programs like ``Freaks and Geeks'' and ``My So-Called
Life'' couldn't generate sufficient ratings to save them from
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of personal disclosure is in order: I'm one of these
people, and my complaint that there are no good movies out there
for teen-agers may really be an expression of my frustration that
there are no good teen-age movies out there for me. And this
frustration may arise from the fact that my own teen-age years _
the years of my most passionate and indiscriminate consumption of
popular culture _ happened to take place in the 1980s, what should
now be regarded as the golden age of adolescent cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone, including me, necessarily thought so at the
time. John Hughes, who produced and directed a string of winsome,
bittersweet comedies in the mid-1980s _ including ``The Breakfast
Club,'' ``Pretty in Pink'' and ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off'' _ was
hardly beloved by serious cinephiles, and he has yet to be given
sufficient credit for updating the elegant studio comedies of the
1930s in the post-production-code, blockbuster-driven Hollywood of
his own era. By then, in any case, the youth picture itself already
seemed formulaic and tired. In 1982, in The New York Times, Janet
Maslin asked, ``Can there be anything about life in high school,
especially high school in a suburban California high school, that
the moviegoing public hasn't already seen?'' This was in a review
of ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' a movie that answered the
question, Maslin acknowledged, with a qualified ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Many high school seniors who have been going to licit,
unaccompanied viewings of R-rated movies for less than a year were
born during the first release of ``Ridgemont High,'' and they may
marvel at the aspects of life in high school that the film shows
that the moviegoing public no longer sees. The movie, directed by
Amy Heckerling, is best remembered for starting the film careers of
Sean Penn, Jennifer Jason Leigh and Cameron Crowe, who wrote the
screenplay based on a novel he had written after spending a year at
a suburban California high school and who went on to direct the
fine school-of-John-Hughes romance ``Say Anything'' (as well as
``Jerry Maguire''). But it is most remarkable for its candor about
the sexual lives of its characters.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Hamilton, the high school junior played by Leigh, loses
her virginity, painfully and half consensually, to a 26-year-old
stereo salesman who doesn't bother to call her again. Later,
pregnant after an unsatisfying encounter with one of her
classmates, she has an abortion, an occurrence almost unimaginable
in the cautious Hollywood of today. But from these grim events,
Heckerling and Crowe managed to conjure a plausible happy ending,
in which Stacy ends up going steady _ but not going all the way _
with the shy, decent Mark Ratner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' arrived before ``date rape''
and ``secondary virginity'' had entered the lexicon as slogans in
the continuing ideological struggle over the sexuality of young
people, young women in particular. It tackled this delicate subject
without excessive moralism or melodrama. Some of the film's more
graphic and uncompromising scenes were cut, but the movie retains a
feeling of unsentimental honesty that somehow doesn't spoil its
governing spirit of lighthearted comedy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the last year or so, movies like ``Election,'' ``Rushmore''
and ``Outside Providence'' have attempted a similar blend of
seriousness and humor, and they have suffered at the box office
despite critical praise. But these are not so much teen-age movies
as movies that use the universality of teen-age experience to tell
delicate, idiosyncratic stories about sexual politics, class
antagonism and the mysteries of desire. ``Election'' and
``Rushmore'' also trotted out two of the icons of '80s teen-movie
bad behavior _ Matthew Broderick of ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off''
and Bill Murray of ``Meatballs'' and ``Caddyshack'' _ and subjected
them to brutal comic debunking. It turns out that Ferris grew up to
be the kind of teacher he loved to torment and that Bill Murray's
smug infantile charm ripened into chastened middle-aged charm.
</P>
<P>
   But where are this year's equivalent movies _ for mature
audiences of any age _ about being young? Since January, alongside
the clockwork release of Freddie Prinze Jr. vehicles (the latest
and weakest of which, ``Boys and Girls,'' is about to reopen, a
last stop on its way to video), a handful of flawed, worthy
examples have come and just as quickly gone, including Sarah
Kernochan's ``All I Wanna Do'' and Colette Burson's ``Coming
Soon,'' which lasted all of a week on a single New York screen.
</P>
<P>
   Burson's sly farce about a high school senior looking for sexual
satisfaction was evidently too hot for the big studios or the MPAA
to handle. The display of semen to comic effect _ most recently and
explosively evident in ``Scary Movie'' _ is permissible, but frank
discussion of female orgasm remains taboo. A strange hypocrisy
about sex _ too complex and involuted to be a simple double
standard _ haunts the culture. The most interesting youth movies _
``Road Trip'' (featuring MTV star Tom Green), ``Loser'' (uniting
Jason Biggs from ``American Pie'' with Mena Suvari from ``American
Beauty'') and even ``Scary Movie'' in addition to the more serious
ones I've mentioned _ at least engage this hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   The equation of sex with other bodily functions _ its reduction
to the level of scatology _ isn't so much an assault on taboos as a
way of evading them. Strange sensations and scary emotions are
neutralized by being made occasions for infantile humor. ``Scary
Movie'' tries to make its audiences feel safe by turning male
sexual anxiety _ about being straight or gay, about the adequacy of
one's equipment _ into occasions for unembarrassed laughter. ``Road
Trip,'' with unlikely grace, balances this kind of comedy with the
old-fashioned romantic kind and even manages to respect its female
characters (despite its propensity for showing them stripped down
to their underwear).
</P>
<P>
   Is there any place for a teen-age romantic comedy that
illuminates the risk and absurdity of sexual initiation without the
protection of gross-out humor? Heckerling's new film, ``Loser,''
makes an attempt, but the brave realism and satiric accuracy that
distinguished both ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' and
``Clueless,'' Heckerling's 1996 updating of Jane Austen's ``Emma,''
seem to have deserted her _ or else to have been taken away. There
are glimpses of the danger that haunted Ridgemont High: the heroine
works as a waitress in a sleazy strip club, and the foppish
fraternity-boy villains keep a stash of roofies, or date rape
pills. But the movie skitters away from its darker implications and
ends up hovering in a confused limbo between romance and satire
rather than achieving equipoise between them.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 or 15 years from now, everything may look different,
which is to say, nothing may have changed. ``Loser'' and
``Election'' may have found their way into the home-viewing canon
of wistful 30-year-olds who stare in mute incomprehension at what
the kids are watching and think, Where are the teen-age movies for
me today? Where is my so-called life?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
