<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4993 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-ROCKIES     08-07 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-ROCKIES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ENDURING APPEAL OF THE CANADIAN ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the genteel days of railroad tourism, the Canadian Rockies
had predictable, limited flows of visitors who came to gawk at
dramatic mountain crags that were marketed around the world as the
second Switzerland. But now Banff National Park, the oldest park in
Canada's system, has a busy, largely four-lane highway transecting
it and an international airport only 90 minutes away, in Calgary.
Flying to Calgary from Tokyo or piloting motor homes from Michigan,
an estimated 4.4 million people visit the park every year, with
another 4 million indulging in what park officials call
``windshield tourism'' as they drive through on the Trans-Canada
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   In the peak days in July and August, the population of Banff can
easily quadruple from its year-round population of 7,000. ``It's
like a wall of metal,'' Pamela L. Veinotte, a Parks Canada tourism
manager, said of the lines of recreational vehicles that wind up
one mountain road to a major attraction, Moraine Lake, where still
waters are framed by granite peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Even with high gasoline prices, the American tourist crush is
not expected to abate this summer. Canada is a travel bargain as
the American dollar fetches almost $1.50 Canadian. Even if Air
Canada pilots conduct a slowdown or go on strike this month over
pay and working issues stemming from the airline's ongoing merger
with Canadian Airlines, there are alternatives. U.S. carriers offer
direct flights linking Calgary with major American cities _
Chicago, Dallas, Denver, Houston, Los Angeles, Salt Lake City and
San Francisco. With a North American open skies agreement that
began to take effect five years ago, the number of Americans flying
to Canada increased by almost 60 percent during the 1990s, putting
Canada on a par with Britain as Americans' favorite air travel
destination after Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   To cope with this summer's crowds at Canada's most heavily
visited park, planners have taken new steps to induce
recreational-vehicle drivers to take shuttle buses, to reduce
conflicts between tourists and wildlife and to cut down on the
herds of tourists tromping through Chateau Lake Louise, the
venerable resort hotel on the edge of the emerald lake.
</P>
<P>
   Starting last June, visitors have had the option of riding free
shuttle buses between the Lake Louise Campground and Lake Louise
and between the campground and Lake Moraine. Although passers-by
may hail the buses, priority is given to drivers of recreational
vehicles. As North American baby boomers age, park officials have
detected an increase in motor homes and a decrease in back country
camping.
</P>
<P>
   Also in June, managers at Chateau Lake Louise began to put much
of the 488-room hotel off limits to nonguests, with the exception
of the eight restaurants and a shopping arcade. Guests, some of
whom were paying $250 a night for a room, had long complained of
tourists filling up easy chairs in the hotel's famous Lakeview
lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the crowds _ people were paying a premium rate for a
world-class experience for Lake Louise and were not getting it,''
Janet Eger, the hotel's director of public relations, said of the
new restrictions on public access.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist encounters with bears, elk and wolves have long been a
problem along the park's central valley and the park's two towns,
Banff and Lake Louise. After tourists were injured by elk during
calving season in the spring and rutting season in the fall, park
officials moved last winter to relocate about two-thirds of Banff's
elk population of 400 animals to remote park areas. Two small herds
remain and are easily visible off the eastern edge of town, around
the city golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals notice the amount of flowers that are not eaten at
night,'' said Dennis R. Shuler, Banff's part-time mayor. To
minimize conflicts with grizzlies, park officials have cracked down
on bird feeders, on the grounds they attract bears, have
temporarily closed some campgrounds and trails, and have harassed
bears with noisemakers to teach them to stay away from humans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Moraine Lake, where several trails were closed in past
summers because of grizzlies in the area, the park is experimenting
with allowing hikers to go out in groups of six or more, on the
theory that there is greater safety in numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Wardens patrol the Bow Valley Parkway, an unfenced valley road
that parallels the Trans-Canada Highway, looking for ``bear jams,''
or traffic backups in front of bears and other wildlife. One road
section now has a temporary speed limit of 20 miles an hour because
a wolf litter was spotted near the road in early June. After a
cougar attacked and injured a loose dog near Banff in April,
wardens increased warnings to visitors to keep dogs on leashes.
</P>
<P>
   Although hotels in the park offer 8,800 beds, space tightens in
the peak season of July and August. In May, the neighboring town of
Cranmore closed off one loophole, passing a law that forbids
homeowners from renting their homes for periods of less than 28
days. In illustration of how tourism pressure is spilling out of
the park, Cranmore now fines illegal tourist homes up to $3,000 _
more than double the fines for unauthorized logging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
