<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4995 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0808-COX     08-07 1780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman selected over five others as Gore's running mate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore has selected Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman to be his
running mate, rounding out the Democratic ticket with the first
Jewish vice presidential candidate in American history. Gore
offered Lieberman the job in a telephone call Monday, and Lieberman
accepted. Picking the moderate Democrat and self-styled moral
crusader as his running mate signals an effort by Gore to win over
independent and Republican voters and distance himself from
President Clinton's controversies. Lieberman, 58, beat out five
other finalists: Sens. Evan Bayh of Indiana, John Edwards of North
Carolina, John Kerry of Massachusetts; House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt of Missouri and New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   FORGIVE AND FORGET
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton praised Sen. Joseph Lieberman as a longtime
friend and innovative thinker, but did not mention Lieberman's
stern criticism of his behavior in the Monica Lewinsky affair. ``I
think he's one of the most outstanding people in public life,''
Clinton said. In August 1998, when most senators were steering
clear of comment on the Lewinsky sex scandal, Lieberman stunned the
White House by calling Clinton's behavior ``immoral'' in a speech
from the Senate floor. Lieberman's speech helped open the way for
an impeachment process that eventually ended in the president's
acquittal. In the end, Lieberman voted with the president.
</P>
<P>
   THE GLOVES COME OFF EVEN BEFORE CALL COMES IN
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman wasted no time in going after the
Republican presidential ticket -- blasting its nominees even before
being officially asked to be the Democratic vice presidential
nominee. The official announcement will come today. Addressing
union members at an AFL-CIO event in Hartford before Al Gore called
to offer him the slot, Lieberman tagged the Bush-Cheney ticket a
far-right pairing. He said the Republicans would recklessly spend
budget surpluses built up under the leadership of President Clinton
and Gore and make massive tax cuts that would leave no money for
Medicare, defense or education. ``If that is their idea of
compassion, I'd hate to see their idea of contempt,'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   YOU WIN SOME, YOU LOSE SOME
</P>
<P>
   Under Connecticut law, Joseph Lieberman can run for both vice
president and his third term in the Senate. His re-election has
seemed all but sure: A recent Quinnipiac University poll showed
Lieberman supported by 71 percent of respondents, compared with 14
percent for Republican challenger Philip Giordano, the mayor of
Waterbury. But if the Democratic ticket wins the White House and
Lieberman also wins re-election, he will have to resign his Senate
seat. It would fall to Republican Gov. John G. Rowland to appoint
someone to fill the seat, affecting Democratic efforts to regain
control of the Senate, where the Republicans now hold a 54-46
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   BOUNCE OR TROUNCE?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has jumped into a 17 percentage point lead over
Al Gore, reaping a 13-point bounce from last week's Republican
convention, according to a Reuters/Zogby poll released today. The
poll of 1,000 likely voters found Bush winning 49 percent of the
vote, and Gore polling 32 percent. Ralph Nader won 6 percent;
Reform Party hopeful Pat Buchanan scored 1 percent and the rest
were undecided or favored others. The statistical margin of error
was plus or minus 3.2 percent. However, on a historical note of
caution, Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis led Bush's father, then
Vice President George Bush, by 17 points after the 1988 Democratic
convention but Bush wound up winning the election easily.
</P>
<P>
   ONE JOE ON THE TICKET, REGULAR JOES ON STAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles next week will
showcase working Americans, their daily struggles and the issues
important to them, party officials said today. In a departure from
the usual political speeches, the convention will feature half-hour
panel discussions with three-to-six participants. Dubbed ``American
Dialogues,'' the discussions will be moderated by a prominent
Democrat each night and highlight everyday issues such as health
care, education, crime, retirement and middle-class tax cuts, among
others. Doug Hattaway, a campaign spokesman for Al Gore, said
George W. Bush is giving voters ``cotton candy and we're giving
them real nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY HAD GEORGE P., WE'VE GOT FORD JR.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Mario M. Cuomo or Ann Richards, keynoters of conventions
past. The main speaker for the Democratic convention will be a
30-year-old congressman from Memphis who is virtually unknown in
national politics. Meet Harold E. Ford Jr., who, in 1996, became
the youngest member of Congress when he won the seat that had been
held by his father_Tennessee's first African -American congressman.
Ford said his 15 to 20 minute speech will be ``positive, uplifting
and forward-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   THE STATE OF THE UNION MEETS THE ACADEMY AWARDS
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential nomination all but certain, the real
pressure for the delgates attending the convention will be to snag
invites to the A-list parties. The hosts are under pressure too,
competing to get Hollywood's top television and movie stars to turn
out for their public gala or private gathering. A $1,000 donation
to Hillary Clinton's Senate campaign will allow donors to party
with her, the president and the likes of Stevie Wonder, Toni
Braxton, Cher and Melissa Etheridge. For another $24,000, donors
can stay for dinner and hear Michael Douglas, Shirley MacLaine,
John Travolta, and civil rights leader Rosa Parks pay tribute.
Barbara Streisand will hold a $1,000 a-head Al Gore fundraiser. And
of course there's the most controversial of all parties: the
Hispanic Unity PAC fund-raiser at the Playboy mansion. Gore is not
attending the event and reportedly asked organizer Rep. Loretta
Sanchez of California to cancel it.
</P>
<P>
   AS IF THEY NEEDED ANY MORE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Dick Cheney will receive $67.56 million in
public funds for the general election, the Federal Election
Commission announced. Bush and Cheney requested the money after
receiving their party's nomination at the convention last week.
Under election law, major party nominees are entitled to federal
funding for the general election if they agree to national spending
limits. They may spend no more than the public funding plus a
combined total $50,000 from their personal funds. The candidates
may also raise money from supporters for legal and accounting
expenses, subject to FEC rules. The Democratic ticket of Al Gore
and Joseph Lieberman will be eligible for federal money after the
party's convention in Los Angeles next week.
</P>
<P>
   GOP DIPS INTO PIGGY BANK
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party is launching a $100 million campaign that
will dwarf the spending of George W. Bush and Al Gore in an effort
to get indifferent voters to go to the polls in November. Victory
2000 targets wavering citizens_over the air, on the phone, in the
mail and on doorsteps_in hopes of boosting turnout among those who
seem most likely to come down on the side of Bush and other GOPers.
In '96 and '98, Democrats and their union allies did a better job
of turning out their most reliable voters than did Republicans. But
this year, with evidence that the Republican base is already more
than 90 percent committed to Bush and eager to oust the Democrats
from the White House, the GOP is investing an unprecedented
treasury in going after the undecided and the weak partisans.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHOICE IS CLEAR: VOTE FOR ME OR PERISH
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, who heads to the Reform Party's nominating
convention this week without a running mate or the assurance that
he will survive an attempt to throw him off the ballot, said he is
sure to win the Party nomination and declared the fractured third
party will die if he doesn't gain the nod. ``If I don't get this
nomination, it is pretty much the end of the Reform Party,'' he
said. Buchanan, a former TV commentator who left the Republican
Party, predicted he would win the overwhelming majority of
delegates at the convention that begins Thursday in Long Beach,
Calif. The Reform Party that Dallas billionaire Ross Perot built
has split into pro- and anti-Buchanan factions.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT WORRIES AL WILL GET GORED
</P>
<P>
   Some might expect a lame-duck president to assume the role of
political cheerleader, but at the moment President Clinton sounds
more like a coach worried that his team is trailing at halftime.
Wrapping up a speech at a fund-raiser on Cape Cod, the president
warned Democrats, ``Don't blow this election.'' It was the latest
in a series of wary comments he has made about the general
election. Clinton has also complained about polls showing that Al
Gore gets little credit for the nation's booming economy. The
concerns have been expressed in unscripted settings, such as
evening fund-raisers and news interviews. He has never publicly
said that he believes the Gore campaign is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   FOR DAD, MUM'S THE WORD
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush admitted he went too far when he
threatened last week to tell Americans what he thought about
President Clinton. The former president had warned that he would
drop a self-imposed ban on criticizing Clinton if the current
occupant of the White House continued attacks on Bush's son, George
W. Bush. Clinton, who defeated the elder Bush in the 1992
presidential race, recently said Bush's son was running only
because ``daddy was president.'' Bush responded by saying, ``I'm
going to wait a month... If he continues that, I'm going to tell
the nation what I think about him as a human being and person.''
But in a Time magazine interview, Bush said his response was
inappropriate. ``I went too far,'' he said. ``That's it. I'm not
going to say any more.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE 'SLICK WILLIE' WAS ON TO SOMETHING
</P>
<P>
   George and Al take note: A team of psychologists has determined
that great presidents are ``not above tricking, cajoling, bullying,
or lying if necessary. They are politicians playing the right tune
to each crowd.'' That's the conclusion of three reserachers, who
made their presentation to the American Psychological Association.
For their study, the researchers consulted with 115 presidential
historians who helped rate the nation's 41 presidents on a complex,
600-question psychological scale. The psychologists found that the
best presidents were extroverted, assertive and slightly
disorganized.
</P>
<P>
   -- Compiled by Saeed Ahmed from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
