<HEADER>
A4998 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ENGLISH-BREAKF     08-07 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ENGLISH-BREAKFAST-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOYS OF THE FULL ENGLISH BREAKFAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not as if we had a secret hankering for cholesterol. But,
often as not, like Mount Everest _ and in more ways than one _ it
was simply there. I'm talking, of course, about the Full English
Breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   My brother, David, and I had chosen to vacation with our
youngest children in the Lake District, retracing youthful
footsteps in places where the very mention of our boyhood escapades
(``See that rock face? Well, we climbed that,'' etc.) produced
either knowing exchanges of rolled eyes between our offspring or _
yet more of a put-down _ a studious page-turning in their
undeclared competition to be first to finish the latest Harry
Potter.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the relief of my youngest daughter, Rebecca, 12, and
nephew Ted, 11, we had chosen accommodations from a guide to
Britain's best bed-and-breakfast establishments rather than the
faux-nostalgia of flapping canvas and off-putting sanitary
arrangements associated with a camping holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Very quickly we discovered that things had moved on in the B&AMP;B
world, at least in the places listed in our guidebook, and at least
when judged by distant memories of impromptu overnight halts with
our own parents. En suite bathrooms had become de rigueur _ a
marked departure from the days of chilly expeditions across
unfamiliar corridors in quest of the facilities. Residents' lounges
and television sets, too, were no longer unusual. Some places even
offered evening meals and wine lists, with reservations and maps
available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing had not changed: the idea that the day cannot be
started adequately without the ingestion of mountains of food. Not
just any food. This being the northwest of England, the usual
attributes of a Full English _ fried bacon, fried eggs, fried
mushrooms, fried tomatoes _ were complemented by chunks of
Cumberland sausage (a spicier, meatier variant on the less muscular
southern sausage) or black pudding, a close relative of the German
Blutwurst, or blood sausage. Fried bread and baked beans were
offered as optional extras for those craving just that extra little
something to titillate the palate. Cereals were mere hors
d'oeuvres. Buttered toast and jam provided a kind of dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than breakfast in a New York diner with its
pick-and-mix perils of hash browns and muffins and eggs over easy,
the Full English comes as a complete package. Like a cigarette
pack, it should be served with the equivalent of a surgeon
general's warning: this breakfast will damage your relationship
with the bathroom scales, at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   As Nancy Reagan counseled, we could have said no. But we didn't,
and neither did any of the other guests we greeted as they came to
grips _ sometimes with a furtive delight, like children at a
midnight feast _ with this most British of offerings. Somehow, the
dietary prescriptions, the regime of juice and muesli and herbal
tea, all fell away. Somehow, the slightly forced oohs and aahs and
I'll-never-eat-all-of-its that greeted the arrival of each serving
gave way to determined assaults and plates wiped clean.
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable thing of all is that this meal, this
sceptered dish, this Full English bears no relation at all to what
most people in England eat for breakfast. Its title is a marketing
device, an extension of the branding of England that seeks to
persuade visitors that the English are all ruddy-cheeked,
tweed-clad, hearty types who live in Tudor cottages and sometimes
dress in bizarre but colorful medieval uniforms. Its basic
assumption is that England is still a rural country where chicken
and pigs are reared to provide sustenance for bucolic yeomen.
</P>
<P>
   In the frenzy of modern England, particularly in the driven
southeast around London, very few people have the time or the
inclination to gird themselves with skillet and cooking oil to
prepare breakfast even as they shower, scan their stock prices,
recharge their cell phones and brace for the subway. Increasingly,
breakfast-time eateries (with some notable exceptions) are far more
likely to offer lattes and cappuccinos and croissants than mugs of
sweet, milky tea and latherings of dubious pork products.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in B&AMP;Bs and hotels across the land, the Full English
endures. Why? Not simply because it's there, as the mountaineer
George Leigh Mallory said of Mount Everest. But because it wasn't
always there for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, that Britain's baby boomers grew up in
the shadow of food-rationing after the Second World War, when eggs
and bacon were prized rarities. Their forebears lived through two
world wars and the intervening depression. In Victorian times,
particularly in the industrial north, the Full English might have
been served from the chafing dishes in the toffs' dining room,
along with grilled kidneys, kippers and kedgeree, but for the
toiling masses, bread and lard was a more likely breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   There is something faintly decadent about sitting down to a meal
that may well be completely unnecessary. But the Full English is so
quintessentially English because of its association of prosperity
with plenty: eat at any roadside pub or restaurant in middle
England and you soon discover that the size of the serving really
does matter, and not just at breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   It is inconceivable that, say, an Italian breakfaster (with the
same distant memories of wartime hardship) would gorge on extra
cornetti when one cornetto (croissant) suffices, grazie. Yet, on
the way back from the Lake District, when we rewarded our children
for tolerating our recherche du temps perdu with a visit to the
huge amusement park called Alton Towers, the meals on offer along
the byways of the English Midlands included chicken tikka masala
with fries, lasagne verde with fries and pizza Margherita with
fries.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is only so much anthropology to be squeezed
from a breakfast, however Full or English it may be.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lake District, surrounded by soaring crags and distant,
rugged peaks, it was easy enough to justify the excess: after all,
we had hills to climb, streams to ford, memories to recount, B&AMP;Bs
to reach before nightfall. We would need solid fare to sustain us.
</P>
<P>
   As we checked into our last B&AMP;B before the amusement park in the
Midlands, the owner ventured that, considering the vertiginous
rides ahead of us, we might prefer a lighter breakfast _ a
half-English, or quarter-English even: toast and tea, fruit juice
and cereal. We assented with something like relief _ and perhaps a
premonition that end-of-vacation reality was about to reclaim us to
a more frugal world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
