<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A system of thunderstorms over parts of the southern Great Lakes
on Tuesday morning will move east-southeast across Ohio into
western Pennsylvania and western New York during the day. If the
system maintains its intensity, there will be a risk of severe
weather in this region, with damaging straight-line winds posing
the biggest threat in a few spots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, potent thunderstorms are possible later Tuesday
across parts of southern Wisconsin and southern Michigan as another
upper-air disturbance arrives in the fast current of steering winds
high over the northern-tier states.
</P>
<P>
   A tandem of easterly waves, which are disturbances moving from
east to west over low latitudes, will increase the chance of
showers and thunderstorms along the western Gulf Coast and
east-central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SUNDAY FLOODS
</P>
<P>
   Recurrent thunderstorms deluged the Laurel Highlands of
southwestern Pennsylvania with as much as 5 inches of rain on
Sunday, causing flash flooding. Heavy rains in mountainous and
hilly terrain are infamous for producing flash floods. For
starters, the sloping terrain can augment the lifting of humid
surface air, thereby energizing thunderstorms. Rain falling at high
rates from terrain-enhanced thunderstorms then runs off rapidly and
gets quickly channeled into the valleys below. The sudden rush
overwhelms streams and river tributaries with a flooding surge of
water. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
