<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-BOWL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS FATHER'S SON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Femi Kuti proved in a potent set Sunday at the Hollywood
Bowl, the Afrobeat apple doesn't fall far from the tree.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone owns the rights to the syncopated, polyrhythmic sound,
it's Kuti, the 38-year-old son of the late Nigerian Afrobeat
superstar and political irritant Fela Anikulapo-Kuti.
</P>
<P>
   While somewhat similar, Femi's high-energy music differs from
his father's in several key ways. As demonstrated in concert and on
his well- received debut album, ``Shoki Shoki,'' Kuti's songs
average six or seven minutes; Fela's hypnotic jams often topped 30
minutes on record and stretched to more than an hour in concert.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Femi's tight, well-rehearsed, 15-member Positive Force
band adds accessible pop elements to Afrobeat's James
Brown-inspired groove, and with just one guitarist, three
dancer-singers and a small horn section, the number of people on
stage was less than a third of Fela's usual sprawling backup unit.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,305-strong Bowl crowd took some time to warm up to Kuti's
inviting opening set. As the sun dimmed, though, the initial
scattered dancers were joined by others and by the time Kuti
launched into his most tuneful number, the lascivious ``Beng Beng
Beng,'' almost the entire audience was up on its feet, swaying
joyously.
</P>
<P>
   Kuti, who closely resembles his father, left politics out of the
performance, except once when mentioning that his music seeks to
put a positive spin on a country widely known for AIDS and civil
unrest. By comparison, Fela would often stop the music to rail
against the World Bank or other governmental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Kuti didn't perform an encore.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was ex-Brown saxophonist Maceo Parker, who offered a set
of mannered funk that only caught fire when he covered tunes
associated with his former boss.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's staccato approach was most effective on simmering
readings of ``Pass the Peas,'' ``Doing It to Death'' and ``Cold
Sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   While the spotlight was plainly on Parker _ who at one point
spread his arms wide and announced ``I'm Maceo Parker!'' in case
there was any question _ his band was underused and two backup
singers mostly danced throughout the set while the audience largely
remained seated.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who left the Brown band to go solo in 1988, probably
would have been more effective Sunday as an opening act for Kuti,
whose warm persona invited audience participation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Kuti/Parker bill was an imaginative one, and
hopefully it signals more world music to come at the Bowl. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
