<HEADLINE>
DELTA HIRES E-COM FIRM TO STREAMLINE AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enigma Inc., a privately held business-to-business e-commerce
company, said Monday it has a contract with Delta Air Lines to
provide software that will allow the airline to customize some
repair manuals and increase maintenance efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, worth several hundred thousand dollars, will allow
Delta mechanics to have electronic access on the shop floor to
maintenance manuals for the Pratt &AMP; Whitney PW4000 engines. Eight
percent of the passenger jets in Delta's fleet are powered by the
PW4000.
</P>
<P>
   While several airlines used Enigma products because suppliers
such as engine manufacturers use them, Delta is the first airline
to purchase the software, called Xtend. Xtend allows the airline to
add its own maintenance procedures to those of the manufacturer,
and bring the system behind its own firewall.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important features of Xtend is that the
enhanced navigation capabilities provided by Pratt &AMP; Whitney in
their e-catalogs will apply to our customized data as well,'' Mike
Lane, manager of the airline operations portfolio at Delta, said in
a statement. ``Xtend is the only e-publishing product that
intelligently supports the enormous amount of complex content
involved in jet engine maintenance and repair.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Clark, vice president of marketing for Enigma, said
the &UR;  &LR; Burlington, Mass. company hopes Delta will purchase additional
software for other engine types.
</P>
<P>
   The software allows Delta to modify Pratt &AMP; Whitney manuals and
access them electronically on Delta's intranet. It also links to
illustrated parts catalogs and parts lists, and ties in to
inventory management programs, said Clark. The system will also
greatly accelerate acceptance of service bulletins issued by the
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``By automating its maintenance information processes, Delta
further underscores its commitment to reducing aircraft equipment
downtime,'' Nathan Shuchami, vice president of aerospace at Enigma,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Enigma said Delta expects the system to reduce the length of its
overall maintenance cycle by as much as 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
