<HEADLINE>
PILOT, WEATHER WOES BRING UNITED FLIGHT CANCELLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines canceled 180 flights Monday _ 7.5 percent of its
daily schedule _ as wildcat actions by pilots working without a
contract and bad weather continued to disrupt the world's largest
airline.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer punctuated with cancellations and delays, United has
been particularly hard hit in the last few days. The airline
canceled more than 120 flights Sunday and about 150 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While hubs in Chicago and San Francisco were particularly hard
hit, Logan International Airport in Boston was not unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, four flights into Boston were canceled, as were four
outbound flights, said Matt Triaka, an airline spokesman. Triaka
did not know if weather or labor issues were responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Juves, spokesman for the Massachusetts Port Authority,
which owns and operates Logan, said the cancellations resulted in
minor disruptions. Most passengers were put on later flights, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds in San Francisco, residual effects of bad weather in
the Midwest, and a line of storms along the East Coast all
contributed to the delays. But United was particuarly hard hit
because of labor problems with its 10,000 pilots, who have been
working without a contract since April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing some operational challenges today,'' Triaka
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because pilots refused to work overtime, United had already
pared its summer schedule by 3 percent, but pilots are still
balking at working overtime and taking other actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are starting to see is a sharp increase in the number
of pilots calling in sick,'' Triaka said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a very challenging operational environment, and
challenges for the customer service people, who need to
reaccommodate passengers on the next flight out,'' Triaka said.
``If we can't get them out on United flights we are trying to book
them on other airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   If a labor problem causes a cancellation thaty strands
passengers overnight, United will give them hotel vouchers, the
airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots and the airline are meeting daily with the Natioanl
Mediation Board, and both side are hopeful a new contract can be
reached next month. One issue is the proposed takeover of US
Airways by United, and how the airlines would merger their pilot
seniority lists.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Air Line Pilots Association were not
available for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
