<SLUG> BC-NETMORF-BARNES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETMORF, BARNES &AMP; NOBLE IN DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NetMorf Inc., a new Boston company that converts World Wide Web
pages for display on Internet-connected wireless telephones and
other devices, announced its biggest deal to date, with Barnes &AMP;
Noble's online book-selling site.
</P>
<P>
   BN.com, which already offers online purchasing through wireless
Palm pilots and three national wireless carriers, agreed to use
NetMorf's ``SiteMorfer'' service as its standard ``mobile
commerce'' platform for those devices and future wireless Net
services such as computer screens in cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms were not disclosed. The companies said, however,
that in addition to a fixed fee, privately held NetMorf will
collect a small bounty on each sale transacted through a
SiteMorfer-enabled site. The year-old company considers recurring
e-commerce revenues crucial as it aims to grow and potentially go
public.
</P>
<P>
   While NetMorf aims to simplify the transacation as much as
possible, using a wireless phone to buy a book from BN.com or
rivals such as Amazon.com can be a chore, requiring people to press
numbers repeatedly on the phone keypad to spell the name of a book
they want to buy and enter a shipping address.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Albert, director of wireless with BN.com, said he could
not comment on how many sales the company is actually completing
through wireless connections.
</P>
<P>
   However, Albert said, ``We're very pleased that mobile commerce
is real. From the day we launched, we've been getting sales every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to wireless Palm VII devices and Palm V's outfitted
with Omnisky access, BN.com is a featured link on AT&AMP;T Wireless,
Sprint PCS and Verizon Wireless and reachable through other
carriers' phones at mobile.bn.com. Barnes &AMP; Noble says it has 15
million titles in its catalogue, with 800,000 in stock, but its is
widely considered to lag Amazon in sales and user features.
</P>
<P>
   Albert said BN.com considered several different vendors before
concluing NetMorf was ``the ideal partner'' to oversee both current
wireless sales operations and ``as new devices come out determine
how to adapt to these devices.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nasdaq trading Monday, BN.com stock rose $1.4375 to $5.1875.
It traded as high as $23.50 last October.
</P>
<P>
   Other announced customers for NetMorf services include
CEOExpress.com of Boston, a customizable Web information portal;
PurchasingCenter.com of Burlington, Mass., which sells industrial
and maintenance supplies; and, AnyDay.com, a Cambridge, Mass.
online meeting planning service recently bought by Palm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
