<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPARTY-BIGPARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPARTY TO BUY SOME BIG PARTY   STORES, INVENTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Looking to add a brick-and-mortar component to its
e-commerce and catalog operations, iParty Corp. has agreed to buy
some of the assets of The Big Party, a chain that sells balloons,
decorations, and other party-themed merchandise at 54 stores.
</P>
<P>
   Because The Big Party is in bankruptcy protection, the deal to
buy the inventory, fixed assets, and leases of 33 stores, including
possibly 18 stores in Massachusetts, requires the approval of a
Bankruptcy Court in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the transaction were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of iParty's management team, chief executive Sal
Perisano and his wife, senior vice president Dorice Dionne, are
cofounders of The Big Party, which opened its doors in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern Denny &AMP; Co., a Boston investment firm, assumed ownership
of The Big Party two years ago after he and his wife decided ``we
were ready for a change,'' Perisano said.
</P>
<P>
   As retail evolves into the 21st century, many experts believe
the shrewdest merchants will offer their goods in three channels _
in stores, on the Web, and through catalogs _ and let consumers
decide which channel is the most convenient for them.
</P>
<P>
   To the best of Perisano's knowledge, the acquisition of The Big
Party stores will make iParty the first retailer in its category to
be able to pursue such a three-pronged strategy in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the early-adopter advantage,'' he said, noting that
once stores are renamed iParty.com, they should help drive more
traffic to iParty's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The company began selling its wares at www.iparty.com last
October and added a catalog in April, Perisano said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to The Big Party and Halpern Denny were not returned, so
it is not clear what will happen to its remaining stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Party, which claimed $69 million in sales in 1999, filed
for bankruptcy protection earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   At Party &AMP; Paper Retailer magazine, editor Trisha McMahon Drain
said The Big Party's woes may be an isolated incident in a mostly
healthy industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to Drain, industry sales grew nearly 5 percent last
year to $12.06 billion. Of The Big Party, she said, ``I think they
may have tried to expand too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisano remains convinced that the idea behind The Big Party
remains sound if the stores can operate with lower overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Party and iParty share the same core customer, a woman
between 25 and 50 who in many cases is organizing a party for a
child, he said. Halloween is a major event for party retailers, and
Perisano hopes The Big Party stores can be integrated into iParty's
operations by then.
</P>
<P>
   IParty has attracted $28 million in venture capital funding,
Perisano said. Through a reverse merger transaction, the company
began trading on the American Stock Exchange in January, with the
opening trade at $4.125 per share. Shares closed unchanged Monday
at 50 cents. For its most recent quarter, iParty lost $5.5 million
on sales of $146,834.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1818EDT &QL; 
