<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYLOR-PROJECTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE THE LABS: OTHER PROJECTS UNDER WAY AT BAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies OSTEOPOROSIS-BAYLOR)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its 100 years as one of the nation's leading research
institutions, Baylor College of Medicine has tackled projects big
and small. Its researchers helped map the human genome. It is
working on conquering the flu virus. Its researchers delve into
allergies. They also work on cancer, AIDS and infectious diseases,
as well as a range of other research projects affecting neonatal to
geriatric medicine.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News and World Report this spring ranked Baylor among the
top 10 percent of U.S. medical schools. Baylor tied with the
University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, for 12th place among 125
accredited medical schools. The ranking is based on several
factors, including research activity and number of faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has a $239 million research budget this year, one of the
largest medical research budgets among U.S. universities. About
1,570 faculty members are involved in research.
</P>
<P>
   Among the medical research projects under way at Baylor, a few
stand out:
</P>
<P>
   Baylor _ where genetic research has been taking place since 1970
_ was selected as one of the U.S. research centers to sequence the
human genome, the strands of genes that now can be studied to find
genetic causes for disease. The project, funded by federal grants
of more than $92 million, involved eight researchers working for 10
years, along with researchers at several other institutions. The
first draft of the human genome was completed this year, and Baylor
is continuing research on the causes of diseases, using information
from that draft.
</P>
<P>
   Under grants of more than $5 million, Baylor researchers are
developing cancers in mice that mimic human breast and prostate
cancers, which will allow researchers to see how cells change from
healthy to malignant. Eventually, researchers hope they will find
the gene that turns those cancers on and off. Previous studies have
created cancer in mice for study, but they have not replicated the
pattern of human cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health in April awarded $15.5 million
to Baylor for studies on all aspects of tuberculosis. During the
next seven years, TB specimens and blood samples will be collected
from 500 TB patients in the Houston area, where the rate of the
infectious disease is two to three times the national average.
</P>
<P>
   A study is under way to learn more about how humans can stay
healthy during long space flights. Studies include those on sleep
deprivation, exposure to constant darkness or constant light, bone
loss, radiation effects, nutrition and other physical and
psychological factors that must be understood before man can become
an interplanetary traveler.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor Flu Center is testing to see how 15,000 children in
Temple, Texas, respond to a nasal spray that it is hoped will work
better than a vaccine in controlling the spread of flu.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
