<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR COLLEGE OF MEDICINE'S BIG MOMENTS: A CENTENNIAL TIMELINE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies OSTEOPOROSIS-BAYLOR)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1900: The Medical Department of the University of Dallas is
founded.
</P>
<P>
   1903: The department becomes part of Baylor University in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Baylor University College of Medicine moves to Houston to
an old Sears &AMP; Roebuck warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   1947: To house the college, the new Roy and Lillie Cullen
Building opens its doors at the Texas Medical Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   1951: The college of medicine offers its first graduate degree.
Also, The Methodist Hospital becomes the first of the Houston
hospitals to affiliate with Baylor, allowing students to gain
experience on its staff and the community to gain from Baylor
innovation. Eventually, other affiliated hospitals will include
Texas Children's Hospital; St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital; Ben Taub
General Hospital, serving the indigent; the Institute for
Rehabilitation and Research; and the Houston Veterans Affairs
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   1968: The first multi-organ transplant is performed at The
Methodist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   1977: The Neurosensory Center of Houston, owned jointly by
Baylor and The Methodist Hospital, opens. The center treats
disorders of the eyes, ears, nose, throat, brain and nervous
system.
</P>
<P>
   1978: The Children's Nutrition Research Center, operated by
Baylor and the Texas Children's Center, opens. So does the Michael
E. DeBakey High School for Health Professions, a project of Baylor
and the Houston school district.
</P>
<P>
   1982: Baylor establishes the Center for Ethics, Medicine and
Public Issues with Rice University and the Institute of Religion.
</P>
<P>
   1988: The Roy M. and Phyllis Gough Huffington Center on Aging is
established at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   1990: Baylor and Rice University in Houston begin to offer joint
programs, which eventually will include the Science Academy of
South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   1991: Baylor is designated one of the handful of U.S.
universities to map the human genome, a project the facility helped
complete in 2000, its 100th year.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
