<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VODKA-WARS-ART-NYT &LR;      08-07 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODKA-WARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MOSCOW, FIGHTING TO CONTROL THE VODKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT22 and NYT23 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ No shots have been fired yet, but there is a war going
on under the leafy summer canopy that shades the streets in the
Lefortovo district of the Russian capital. Here, on 20 acres of
factory grounds, thousands of workers are daily engaged in the
production of one of Russia's most essential commodities _ vodka.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely because vodka is such needed balm for the Russian
soul, the country has been riveted _ in the political lull of
August _ by the struggle for control of the Krystall factory, one
of the country's oldest vodka producing plants that last year
rolled out 130 million bottles of famous brands like Stolichnaya
and Krystall itself.
</P>
<P>
   Given the factory's well-known trade marks and estimated value
of $600 million, it was perhaps only a matter of time before this
economic plum became one that rival forces sought to pluck. The
only thing both sides agree on is that the federal government's
attempt to reconsolidate control over the lucrative vodka industry
_ an effort intensified since President Vladimir V. Putin was sworn
in in May _ set off the latest of Russia's business battles.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, armed paramilitary police stormed the factory's
administration building, ordering everyone out, ostensibly so tax
authorities could seize some documents. Once the building was
secured, the troopers made way for Alexander Romanov to enter and
occupy the general manager's suite, along with dozens of muscular
private security guards hired for the occasion. Then the SWAT team
departed.
</P>
<P>
   Romanov, 37, has never worked at Krystall and knows little of
the vodka business _ aside, presumably, from consumption. For
several years, he has been a vice president for public relations
and other duties at Rosneft, Russia's state-owned oil company. He
describes himself as a highly trained ``top manager'' and
grudgingly acknowledges that he went to school with the deputy
minister in the state property administration, who happens to be
leading one of the warring factions on Krystall's board.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 feet away from Romanov's second-floor encampment, the
chief accountant and acting general manager of the Krystall
factory, Vladimir Svirsky, also 37, leads the other board faction,
which controls 40 percent of the stock. This group has set up
defensive positions at the entrance to the production lines where
frightened workers tried to complete their shift Friday, hoping to
avoid violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't be happening in a factory as important as
this,'' said Svetlana Soborova, who has worked at Krystall for 18
years and now sells the final product in the company's retail
store.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on a weekend when a state of emergency had been declared in
Moscow to guard against possible terrorist acts on the anniversary
of the uprising by rebel forces in Chechnya, neither the courts,
nor police, nor federal government seemed willing to act.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood around the 100-year-old factory became a sea of
muscle, with private security guards hired by each warring camp
facing off in front of the huge enterprise, in which the state has
a 51 percent controlling interest. Each side sent patrols out to
roam the streets and alleys around the factory looking for ways to
outmaneuver each other and get control of the premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia unfortunately we have the phenomenon of a weak
state, where the legal institutions, too, are very weak,'' said
Grigory Koshkarov, a factory financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Russia's leaders have been rediscovering a truism
of the Soviet era _ that vodka, and the tax revenues derived from
its sale, can be the salvation of a beleaguered national budget.
</P>
<P>
   But that will hold true now only if the government can
re-establish control over the vodka industry, where half or more of
the market has been seized by an enormous industry of illegal and
counterfeit distillers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the government collected $470 million in taxes on
alcohol production, and some estimates indicate this number could
double under tighter state control.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after being sworn in in May, Putin signed a decree creating
a new state-owned conglomerate, Rosspiritprom, to consolidate state
control over 50 distilleries in which the Russian government owns a
majority stake and 20 others in which it is a minority shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown over Krystall follows months of maneuvering in the
boardroom and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Romanov went to court last spring seeking to enforce the board's
decision to appoint him acting general manager of the plant, but
the court ruled the appointment was illegal because opposing
directors did not receive 10 days' notice.
</P>
<P>
   Romanov claimed that his rival Svirsky bribed the judge, but
then acknowledged he had no evidence. The board met again in June
and reaffirmed Romanov's appointment, but Svirsky and his directors
walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Svirsky asserts that one or another of Russia's business
oligarchs close to the Kremlin is behind Romanov's appointment and
is seeking to get control of the 40 percent stake now controlled by
employees, managers and their allies. But Svirsky too said he had
no proof.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting for the courts to act on its subsequent
petitions, Romanov's faction orchestrated Friday's takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am authorized by the government to take over the management
of this factory,'' Romanov said. ``Fifty-one percent of the shares
are in the hands of the state, but there is such chaos here.,''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Romanov presented himself as the vanguard of
state power come to reclaim the alcohol industry from incompetents,
thieves and ``swindlers.'' He accused Svirsky of disobeying board
directives, and of trying to become a ``new oligarch'' by amassing
40 percent of the company shares and behaving like ``Napoleon.''
</P>
<P>
   Svirsky countered that his board faction was fighting to keep
control of management, which he said was justified by record
profits and tax payments posted in 1999. ``We are trying to prove
our right to work at this enterprise by the results of our work,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday night, Romanov and Svirsky were showing the strain.
Desktops were littered with the detritus of cold cuts and fast
food. Svirsky needed a shave and Romanov had been sleeping in his
clothes and worrying about Svirsky's guard dogs, one of them known
as a ``man eater,'' that might be loosed on his men if they entered
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Svirsky addressed employees returning to work,
telling them to ignore any orders from Romanov's men. And the board
chairman, Yevgeny Panteleev, reiterated his support for Romanov's
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the face of our Russian democracy,'' said a somewhat
grizzled security guard in front of the factory gate. ``Now it is
up to Putin,'' he added, who has pledged to establish a
``dictatorship'' of law in Russia and end the kind of anarchy on
display here.
</P>
<P>
   Notably invisible in the conflict has been Moscow's powerful
mayor, Yuri Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor does not want to intervene in this dispute because
the city's shares are going to the federal government,'' said
Romanov. ``The federal government does not want to intervene until
the shares are turned over.''
</P>
<P>
   Svirsky has effectively blocked both actions by hiding the
corporate seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am like a kamikaze,'' Svirsky said, ``and I will fight for
my rights to the death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
