<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ATTACKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN RISES IN GERMANY OVER ANTI-SEMITIC ATTACKS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Two Jewish cemeteries were desecrated in the western
German state of Rhineland-Pfalz and an explosive device found
outside a Jewish family's home in Bavaria, the police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents contributed to a climate of mounting concern in
Germany over anti-Semitic and anti-immigrant violence by rightist
groups. The attacks are not new, and they reflect the activities of
a small minority, but evidence that extremists are now better armed
and organized has alarmed the government.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder is currently on vacation in
Mallorca. But his spokesman, Uwe-Karsten Heye, met Monday with Paul
Spiegel, the leader of the Central Council of German Jews, to
promote a new initiative called ``Show Your Face.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting in Duesseldorf, where a bomb last month
injured nine immigrants, six of them Jews, Heye said an advertising
campaign would begin next month in which famous Germans, including
sports and film celebrities, would exhort the nation to show zero
tolerance for racists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to encourage people to do something against xenophobia
and anti-Semitism,'' Heye said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said Germans had
been too silent in the face of rightist violence. His statement
struck a chord in a nation where the need for ``Zivilcourage'' _
personal courage rooted in a strong moral conscience _ has been
exhorted as an essential quality since the Third Reich demonstrated
the dangers of passivity.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel said Germans must act together to isolate and undermine
rightist agitators, whose propaganda has thrived particularly in
the formerly communist east. Among many youths, often socially
alienated and without work, shaved heads, racist slogans,
black-leather attire and para-military discipline have proved an
appealing route to an elusive sense of identity and togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many people as possible have to say we don't want to let a
group of outlawed madmen destroy what we've built up over the past
55 years,'' Spiegel said. A number of recent incidents, including
the latest, have occurred in western Germany, suggesting that
rightist groups may be broadening their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the Schroeder government had given scant attention to
rightist violence, concentrating its efforts on deregulating the
German economy. But it has become clear to Schroeder that his aim
of making Germany a competitive ``global player'' _ to use a phrase
in vogue in his coalition _ is scarcely compatible with repetitive
outbreaks of nationalist thuggery.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest incidents, a total of 11 graves in the villages of
Rockenhausen and Dielkirchen, near Kaiserslautern, were desecrated.
The police said Nazi swastikas and SS slogans were daubed on
headstones in light gray paint.
</P>
<P>
   The desecration of Jewish cemeteries is not uncommon in Germany.
Last year more than 100 headstones were smashed or overturned in
Berlin's Weissensee cemetery, and Julius Schoeps, an expert on
German Jewish affairs, said that there had been more than a
thousand cases of desecration in the years after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 2,300 Jewish cemeteries in Germany, reflecting
centuries of Jewish presence in a country where more than 500,000
Jews lived before Hitler's rise to power. In many places,
particularly smaller towns and villages, these cemeteries
constitute the last trace of Jewish life in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern Bavarian town of Bamberg, police found an
explosive device outside a Jewish family's home after it was
spotted by a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``After recent incidents, people have become more vigilant,'' a
police spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
