<HEADER>
A5037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LESSING-BOOK-REVIEW-N     08-07 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LESSING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEN, IN THE WORLD':   HIS WEIRDNESS ATTRACTS   THE EVEN MORE
WEIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, Doris Lessing wrote a grisly little horror
tale called ``The Fifth Child,'' a sort of highbrow ``Rosemary's
Baby,'' which recounted the story of a monstrous child born into a
middle-class London family. The child, Ben, looks like a grotesque
gnome or troll and displays an equally ugly personality: he kills
the family's dog and cat, tortures his brothers and sisters and
thoroughly disrupts the family's heretofore idyllic life.
</P>
<P>
   When the sequel to that book, ``Ben, in the World,'' opens, Ben
is 18 and on his own, roaming the streets of London. He now looks
like a yeti or caveman and still has fits of brutal anger. He
feasts on birds he catches with his bare hands, and when he sees
one of his brothers in a park he can barely suppress his murderous
rage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this Ben is more sinned against than sinning. Whereas the
Ben in ``The Fifth Child'' was often an active agent of disruption,
the Ben in this volume is usually a victim, mocked and abused by
others who cannot accept his otherness.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger difference between the two books, however, lies in
the author's handling of Ben's story. In ``The Fifth Child''
Lessing created a perfect balance between naturalistic detail and
fablelike allegory. In fact the sense of terror that the book
generated in the reader stemmed in large measure from the
insinuation of a frightening, inexplicable creature into a
thoroughly ordinary, recognizable world; it was as if
Frankenstein's monster had been plunked down in a London _ or New
York _ suburb and sent to school with our children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben, in the World,'' in contrast, reads entirely like a fairy
tale, and a not very compelling one at that. All of the subsidiary
characters _ including a whore with a heart of gold and an evil Dr.
Mengele-type scientist who wants to perform strange experiments on
Ben _ are either kindly good Samaritans trying to help Ben or evil
villains out to exploit him. All of Ben's encounters with these
people have the contrived feel of incidents meant to illustrate
society's reaction to people who don't fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Because nothing feels very real in this novella, because Ben and
everyone else seem like cardboard cutouts, the reader feels neither
pity nor fear for the characters, only a vague sense of irritation.
``Ben, in the World,'' like the author's last novel, ``Mara and
Dann,'' points up a curious development in Lessing's recent
fiction: a seemingly arbitrary decision to jettison both the
visionary grandeur of the ``Canopus in Argos'' series and the
psychological nuance and social detail of her early ``Martha
Quest'' stories in favor of a more primitive, knee-jerk brand of
story telling.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Ben, in the World,'' the story Lessing tells
consists of little more than a series of picaresque adventures that
take Ben from England to France to Brazil. In London Ben meets a
kindly old woman who takes him in off the streets and tries to care
for him. He next meets a hooker and her pimp, who decide to use him
as an unwitting accomplice in a drug deal: they load him up with
suitcases stuffed with cocaine, put him on a plane to Nice and
arrange for him to be met by a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   In Nice Ben is taken up by a would-be film director who wants to
make a movie starring him as a kind of Neanderthal alien. The
director takes Ben to Rio, where another former hooker befriends
him. She and her friends must later try to rescue Ben from a
villainous scientist who has kidnapped him and taken him to a
remote laboratory referred to as ``the bad place.'' The scientist,
not Ben, we're reminded, is the real monster _ ``a monster of
cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessing spends a great deal of space describing how this
scientist demeans Ben by locking him in a cage like an animal, but
she dwells at obnoxious length on Ben's animal-like appearance and
behavior. She describes him barking during sex and whimpering in
his sleep. She repeatedly discusses his hairy body, his heightened
sense of smell, his voracious appetite for raw meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``His hunger hurt and threatened him,'' she writes, ``It was not
an easy hunger: the thin taste of bread or a bun could not satisfy
it. It was a need for meat, and he smelled the rawness of blood,
the reek of it: yet this hunger was dangerous to him. Sometimes,
when he had gone into a butcher's shop, pulled there by the smell,
his body had seemed to engorge with wanting, and his arms stretched
out of their own accord towards the meat.''
</P>
<P>
   Such descriptions make Ben out to be some sort of generic
creature, endowed with only the most instinctual reactions and
responses, and Lessing does nothing to give him a discernible
personality. Her other characters are described in an even more
cursory manner, their fates dismissively summed up in a careless
sentence or two. We learn that the London hooker and pimp use their
cocaine profits to become part of the landed gentry: ``So you could
say that this part of our tale had a happy ending.'' We learn that
the Brazilian ex-hooker and her boyfriend marry and start a new
life: ``So their story at least has a happy ending: things turned
out well for them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ben, Lessing concocts a fate for him that's as
preposterous as it's predictable. A fitting end, in a way, for such
a flimsy, crudely written story.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BEN, IN THE WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   By Doris Lessing
</P>
<P>
   178 pages. HarperCollins. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
