<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIEBERMAN TOOK A LONELY AND UNUSUAL ROUTE TO THE NATIONAL TICKET
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a town where the first rule of political success
has long been ``go along to get along,'' Joseph I. Lieberman has
bucked his party's positions and spoken out against its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The second-term Connecticut senator rose to national fame two
years ago when he became the first of his Democratic colleagues to
deliver a public rebuke to President Clinton for having an affair
with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such behavior is not just inappropriate,'' Lieberman said in
extended remarks from the Senate floor. ``It is immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spoke out despite a friendship dating back to 1970,
when Clinton, then a law student at Yale University, helped
Lieberman campaign for Connecticut's state Senate. Even a
telephoned plea from Clinton during a trip to Moscow failed to
dissuade the senator from delivering the stinging criticism.
Lieberman's only concession was to wait until Clinton had left
Russia and landed in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time Lieberman had challenged the
integrity of the Clinton administration. In 1997, he was the only
Democrat on a Senate investigating committee who asked tough
questions about the Democratic campaign finance scandals of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A central element in that scandal was the role of Vice President
Al Gore, who Tuesday plans to name Lieberman as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman stopped short of blaming Gore personally, but he had
harsh words for the now-famous fund-raising event attended by Gore
at a Buddhist temple. Calling the event ``surreal,'' Lieberman
warned in a Senate report that there would be more ``hustlers
trying to put their change into the subway turnstile at the White
House gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft-spoken and courtly, Lieberman has hardly been a
flame-thrower on Capitol Hill. Instead, he has quietly tried to
rechannel the mainstream of his party, on both values and issues.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the Democratic Leadership Council, a group of
moderates that Clinton helped form, Lieberman has pushed for
greater emphasis on a strong defense, more parental choice for
education, including experimentation with vouchers for private
schools, and including some form of individual investing in the
Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Republican National Committee on Monday produced a
long list of issues where Lieberman is closer to Republican nominee
George W. Bush than to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But what largely distinguishes Lieberman's career has been a
concern over a moral decline that has sometimes brought him into
strange alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of the leaders of his party who have visited
Hollywood chiefly to gather big bucks for campaigns, Lieberman took
the entertainment industry to task for sex and violence. His
campaign was credited for helping pressure the TV networks into
developing a rating system to help parents guide their children's
viewing habits.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has continued to monitor the system and to criticize
it as inadequate. He once called the system ``a turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining forces with William Bennett, a former education
secretary and staunch Republican conservative, Lieberman took aim
at ``gangsta rap'' music for glamorizing criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Taking such stands is an outgrowth of Lieberman's faith, which
he wears much more openly than many in public office. An observant
Orthodox Jew, he works on the Jewish sabbath, between sundown
Friday night and sundown Saturday, only when necessity demands it.
</P>
<P>
   He has cast Senate votes on the sabbath, including during the
Clinton impeachment trial, even if it meant walking home 4 1/2
miles to avoid breaking rules against using conveyances. He has
also attended national security meetings at the White House on the
sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is he allow to perform duties that would benefit the
public, but he is obligated to'' by Jewish law, said his
administrative assistant, Bill Andresen (cq). ``There is no
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   However, campaigning is another matter. Lieberman has twice
skipped his own state Democratic nominating convention to observe
the sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Usually that is private time for Lieberman, a family man whose
father owned a Stamford, Conn., liquor store where he read
philosophy and the Torah between customers.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah, have practicend-term
Connecticut senator rose to national fame two years ago when he
became the first of his Democratic colleagues to deliver a public
rebuke to President Clinton for having an affair with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such behavior is not just inappropriate,'' Lieberman said in
extended remarks from the Senate floor. ``It is immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spoke out despite a friendship dating back to 1970,
when Clinton, then a law student at Yale University, helped
Lieberman campaign for Connecticut's state Senate. Even a
telephoned plea from Clinton during a trip to Moscow failed to
dissuade the senator from deliverin
</P>
</TEXT>
