<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5043 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-KENTUCKY-0808-COX     08-07 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KENTUCKY-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROAD TO COLLEGE FOOTBALL: KENTUCKY
 &HT;    Wildcats' hopes rest on arm of 275-pound quarterback
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Alabama defensive end Kenny Smith was standing in the
lobby of a Birmingham, Ala., hotel last month when a reporter asked
him if he'd seen Kentucky's new quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dude with the blond hair?'' Smith asked. ``He's a
quarterback? Nah, he's got to be a lineman.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was staring down Kentucky redshirt freshman Jared
Lorenzen, who was named the Wildcats' starting quarterback this
summer. At 6 feet 4 and 275 pounds, Lorenzen isn't your everyday
signal-caller.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a quarterback?'' Tennessee linebacker Eric
Westmoreland asked after catching a glimpse of Lorenzen at SEC
Media Days. ``I've only hit linemen that big.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzen is bigger than a lot of linemen. He outweighs
Kentucky's starting tight end and three of its four defensive
linemen who were projected starters going into preseason camp. He
is the heaviest quarterback in Division I-A, outweighing his
closest competitor _ UNLV's Jason Thomas _ by more than 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lorenzen) is never going to be a small guy; he'll always be
huge,'' Kentucky coach Hal Mumme said. ``He hasn't seen 230
(pounds) since the eighth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumme is hoping his oversized quarterback can help the Wildcats
overachieve this season. He first met Lorenzen four years ago when
the sophomore from Highlands High School in Fort Thomas, Ky.,
attended the Wildcats' summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of camp, Lorenzen told Mumme he wanted to be
Kentucky's quarterback one day. Mumme responded, ``You might be an
offensive lineman for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mumme's assessment of Lorenzen changed when he saw his left
arm. Lorenzen won every competition at Kentucky's ``Top Gun'' camp.
He threw the ball 72 yards; nobody else threw it past 60.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats were one of the few teams that recruited Lorenzen
as a quarterback, even after he led Highlands High to the Class AAA
state championship as a senior. In his final prep season, Lorenzen
passed for 3,392 yards and 45 touchdowns and was named the state's
``Mr. Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio State, Purdue and all of the other Big 10 schools were
recruiting me as a lineman,'' Lorenzen said. ``They told me they
weren't going to play me at quarterback. Coach Mumme was the first
and only head coach to call me. I knew he would give me a chance at
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Lorenzen didn't expect to get the starting job this
quickly. Last season, Kentucky quarterback Dusty Bonner led the SEC
in passing efficiency and averaged 297 yards per game. The Valdosta
native completed 65 percent of his passes and threw an SEC-high 26
touchdowns. Bonner also guided the 'Cats to their second bowl game
in a row, a feat the program had not accomplished since 1983-84.
</P>
<P>
   After spring drills, Mumme said however, Mumme changed his mind.
He called Lorenzen into his office and told him that he'd start the
Sept. 2 opener at Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocked the heck out of me,'' Lorenzen said. ``He told me I
was going to start. I didn't have a clue. I was speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Bonner, who transferred to Division I-AA Valdosta State a
few days after Mumme's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Dusty made the right decision,'' Mumme said. ``In
our system, two quarterbacks don't work well in the equation. The
receivers need continuous repetitions with the quarterback. That's
why we will always be a one-quarterback school.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumme was discouraged by Bonner's play late last season, when
the Wildcats averaged only 18 points and lost three of their final
four games, and he prefers Lorenzen's arm, which he claims is
stronger than Tim Couch's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is accurate and has great touch. There is not a drawback to
Jared,'' Mumme said. But Mumme's decision is still a risky one.
After three non-conference games against Louisville, South Florida
and Indiana, the Wildcats open their SEC schedule with road games
at Florida and Mississippi. Lorenzen will face two of the SEC's
more intimidating environments early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it puts more pressure on me because we don't have an
experienced quarterback behind me,'' Lorenzen said. ``If people
realize I'm going to have some bumps in the road, I think we'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mumme's controversial about-face, Lorenzen isn't the only
one who will be judged by his performance this season.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY
</P>
<P>
   -Location: Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   -Enrollment: 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   -Coach: Hal Mumme, 18-17 in three seasons at Kentucky, 83-44-11
in 11 seasons overall.
</P>
<P>
   -Nickname: Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   -Stadium (capacity): Commonwealth Stadium (67,530).
</P>
<P>
   -All-time record: 517-488-44.
</P>
<P>
   -Conference championships (number of titles, title years): Two _
1950 and 1976 (tied with Georgia).
</P>
<P>
   -1999 record (overall, conference): 6-6, 4-4 in SEC East
</P>
<P>
   -Schedule: Sept. 2 at Louisville; Sept. 9 vs. South Florida;
Sept. 16 vs. Indiana; Sept. 23 at Florida; Sept. 30 at Mississippi;
Oct. 7 vs. South Carolina; Oct. 14 at LSU; Oct. 21 vs. Georgia;
Nov. 4 vs. Mississippi State; Nov. 11 vs. Vanderbilt; Nov. 18 at
Tennessee.
</P>
