<P>
   LIEBERMAN-ASSESS (Washington) _ After struggling mightily for
two years to move out of President Clinton's shadow, Vice President
Al Gore, in a bold but risky choice of a running mate, effectively
thrust Clinton and impeachment front and center in the 2000
presidential campaign. It was clear from the Republican convention
last week that the Republicans will not be timid in making the
moral lapses of Clinton a basic subtext of their campaign. The
thinking of the Gore camp is that by picking Lieberman, the most
vociferous critic of Clinton during the impeachment proceedings,
Gore will confront such criticism head on and underscore his
independence from the President. While no one can predict how the
Lieberman choice will play _ pr play out _ one thing is certain: It
was not a play-it-safe choice as was Gov. George W. Bush's
selection of Dick Cheney. There several obvious plusses to the
Lieberman choice _ but there are also several minuses. A news
analysis by Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-TIMBER (Undated) _ In a major shift, timber companies have
stepped up logging operations in the South, where they face less
regulation than in the carefully monitored tracts of largely public
land in the Pacific Northwest. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-SPLIT (Undated) _ Ending one of corporate America's
most bitter family feuds, an international arbitrator gave Andersen
Consulting the right to separate itself from its parent firm but
forced it to give up its name and to pay $1 billion in exchange.
The decision cleaves the world's largest consulting firm, with
65,000 employees, from Arthur Andersen, the largest accounting firm
with 77,000. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND-TANKS (Hartford, Conn.) _ Nineteen months after the
federally imposed deadline that required owners of underground
fuel-storage tanks to close or upgrade their tanks to prevent leaks
and spills, more than 110,000 tanks remain illegally in the ground
nationwide, EPA officials said. And in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut, state records show the majority of illegally operating
fuel tanks _ and therefore those most likely to be a threat to
drinking water wells _ are owned by municipal, county and state
government agencies. By Paul Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Undated) _ Factors affecting U.S. policy on the
Indian subcontinent. By Judith Miller and James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SAFIR (New York) _ Howard Safir, the New York City
police commissioner, is reported planning to announce his
retirement on Tuesday. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
