<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5046 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-LAKE-ERIE-$ADV     08-07 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LAKE-ERIE-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHIPELAGO OF LEGENDS AND PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: See also TRAVEL-GREAT-LAKES, TRAVEL-LAKE-SUPERIOR)  
 (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By RYAN J. DONMOYER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tucked in the backyard of a rapidly developing suburban
community on Johnson's Island in Lake Erie, 206 gleaming white
marble tombstones rise in perfect rows from carefully manicured
grass. The stones are marked with names, military ranks and the
occasional ``unknown,'' but no dates. These sons of the Confederacy
rest while one of their own _ in the form of a bronze statue _
stands guard. Oddly, the statue does not face south. Instead, it
looks out over the lake to Canada, less than 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The graveyard, on the 300-acre island in northwest Ohio, is all
that remains of a 40-acre Civil War prisoner of war camp that held
some 2,800 Confederate officers and enlisted men from 1862 to 1865.
``You're walking around and you'll see `so-and-so from Fifth
Alabama Infantry,''' said Dick Spicer, president of the Port
Clinton, Ohio, Chamber of Commerce, when we stopped by to pick up
some maps and brochures. ``It's not something you see very often in
the North.''
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery is but one memorial among dozens on the Lake Erie
islands, a region saturated with pivotal, and forgotten, history.
As boys, my friend Ben and I had made annual pilgrimages to Cedar
Point, the amusement park in Sandusky that overlooks the cemetery.
In college, we made a beeline for the bars on South Bass Island.
Now, as adults, we were going back to the playground of our
adolescence, and discovering a fascinating side of the region.
Within a day of our visit in late April, I felt as if I was living
in a history textbook.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are about a dozen islands in the lake, people
live year-round on just six of them, including Johnson's Island.
Each has a distinct character. South Bass Island, also known as
Put-in-Bay, is the most popular. It fancies itself Ohio's answer to
Key West, complete with a strip of bars with names like the Round
House and the Beer Barrel Saloon. Kelleys Island, the largest
American territory in the lake, is quieter and quaint with a rich
history of winemaking. Middle Bass and North Bass Islands are less
populated and have few tourist amenities. Pelee Island, Canada's
southernmost inhabited point, and Lake Erie's largest island, is
another wine-growing area that produces potent, sweet ice wines.
The other islands are either privately owned or too small to be
hospitable.
</P>
<P>
   It was off the Lake Erie Islands that an epic naval battle in
1813 decided the northern boundaries of the United States. Later,
as bored Confederate prisoners played poker with useless
Confederate money on Johnson's Island, Jay Cooke, a banker who sold
war bonds to to help the North finance the Civil War, bedded down
in his summer castle on Gibraltar Island, only a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Across from Gibraltar, South Bass Island became a watering hole
at the turn of the century, as steamships delivered tens of
thousands of people on weekends to drink at the myriad saloons and
stay at what claimed to be the world's first fully electrified and
largest wood-frame hotel, the Victory. In 1919, it burned in a
spectacular fire that was visible in Detroit, some 60 miles away.
The Lonz Winery, operating on Middle Bass Island since the 1800s
and the largest wine producer in the United States by 1875, was a
popular destination. But it was forced to close in July after a
terrace collapsed, killing a visitor and injuring 75 others.
</P>
<P>
   People still tell how during Prohibition, most residents of the
islands were connected to the rum-running operation of crime gangs
on Middle Island, just over the border in Canadian waters and just
out of reach of the United States officers. Other historic
attractions _ the oldest continuously operating lighthouse on the
Great Lakes in Marblehead, mysterious mansions and shipwrecks
galore _ complement such natural wonders as huge underground caves
and ancient glacial grooves. It would take a few weeks to explore
the histories and intricacies of every island and the Ohio
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the ghost stories. On a stormy night in 1915, a
group of Italian laborers on Johnson's Island reported seeing the
Confederate statue turn to face the graves. When it blew its bugle,
ghostly soldiers emerged from the mist, the laborers said, stood at
attention in rotting gray uniforms, and marched away. A dozen men
killed in an 1840s quarry accident on Kelleys Island were rumored
to take their revenge by throwing a chain around ship propellers,
causing at least some of the 40,000 shipwrecks in the Great Lakes
in the last 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   On the mainland, trailer parks, marinas and low budget hotels
sit alongside tacky attractions like miniature golf courses and a
``prehistoric forest'' filled with life-size dinosaur models. The
islands, however, have kept their well-preserved Victorian villages
and avoided the mainland clutter.
</P>
<P>
   South Bass Island alone has at least 130 buildings that are
recorded by the Ohio Historic Preservation Office for historical or
architectural significance, and all of Kelleys Island is on the
National Register of Historic Places. Bed-and-breakfasts abound;
with the exception of a Dairy Queen and a Taco Bell in Put-in-Bay,
there isn't a name-brand restaurant or hotel chain to be found on
the islands.
</P>
<P>
   Ben and I spent an hour roaming the Confederate graveyard and
drove across the causeway that connects Johnson's Island to the
mainland, where we caught a ferry to Put-in-Bay. As we inched
closer to South Bass Island, I was surprised to see how flat it is.
South Bass was carved by the same glaciers that made the Great
Lakes tens of thousands of years ago, and is as low-lying as any
cornfield in central Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The island's dominant feature, Perry's Victory and International
Peace Memorial, is a Doric column of pink granite. Rising 352 feet
from an isthmus in the middle of the island, it is visible from all
the islands and most of the mainland, and is the third tallest
national memorial in the United States, after the the Gateway Arch
in St. Louis and the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   It was constructed between 1912 and 1915 to commemorate
Commodore Oliver Hazard Perry's daring victory over the British
fleet during the Battle of Lake Erie on Sept. 10, 1813. After the
battle, Commodore Perry wrote his immortal telegram to President
William Henry Harrison: ``We have met the enemy, and they are
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   As the memorial grew closer, the significance of that battle
began to sink in. Less than 10 miles west of where we were sailing,
Commodore Perry and a racially diverse crew of sailors and soldiers
had defined the borders of a young United States and left the door
open for Manifest Destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Had the commodore lost, ``we probably would have ended up with
at least all the water in the Great Lakes belonging to Great
Britain and Canada,'' Edwin R. Isaly, curator of the Lake Erie
Islands Historical Society in Put-in-Bay, told us when we stopped
in to browse the society's impressive collection. Among its
treasures are expansive murals of the Battle of Lake Erie, models
of famous ships that have sailed the Great Lakes and antiques
rescued from the the Victory Hotel fire.
</P>
<P>
   We docked at the lime kiln dock on the southwest tip of the
island and drove a few minutes to the middle of the island for a
closer look at the Perry monument.The Canadian and American flags
flew side by side in a 25-acre park surrounding the monument,
symbolizing the longest unguarded international border in the
world. Around us, actors clad in period costumes re-enacted life as
it was in 1813.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the monument, we were greeted with a panoramic
view encompassing the Michigan mainland, Kelleys Island, the
120-year-old Cedar Point amusement park, Middle Bass and North Bass
Islands and the southern shore of Ontario. We also had fantastic
views of Pelee Island in Canada and the gangster haven of Middle
Island on the international border, where the remains of a
Prohibition-era casino and bordello is the only structure still
standing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we could see Put-in-Bay, which looks like a
Hollywood version of a New England fishing village _ only you're
more likely to find fried perch or walleye than ocean fish to go
with your beer. They do consume a lot of beer in Put-in-Bay,
especially in the stretch of bars along Delaware Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   We could hear the strains of ``Love Shack'' by the B-52s coming
from the Round House bar as we walked along Bay View Avenue to
DeRivera Park, a leafy square with playgrounds, gardens, gazebos
and a bathhouse that separates the marina from the strip of bars in
grand, Colonial-style buildings. The abundance of antique cars
idling around the park only added to the town's ``Ragtime''
ambience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In DeRivera Park, a row of 19th-century cannons aim across the
bay at Cooke Castle on Gibraltar Island, which has the highest
elevation of the islands and was used by Commodore Perry as a
lookout before the Battle of Lake Erie. Although the island is
close enough to swim to, visitors are allowed only by special
permission from Ohio State University, which owns Gibraltar. The
University frequently sponsors a weekly lecture series during the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Before we joined the party on Delaware Avenue, Ben and I checked
into a hotel. We sampled two neighboring Put-in-Bay lodgings. Our
rooms at each were clean and serviceable but far from luxurious.
</P>
<P>
   The first hotel, the two-year-old Islander Inn on Erie Street,
fit in well with Put-in-Bay's party atmosphere, with a Caribbean
resort theme, inclusing brightly appointed rooms and an outdoor
pool with swim-up bar. Nearby, Parker's Inn on Catawba Avenue was
more sober, with a neutral decor, and emphasized that it would not
tolerate rowdiness.
</P>
<P>
   At the Erie Isle Tavern in Parker's Inn, Ben enjoyed salmon
roulades stuffed with goat cheese, pine nuts, spinach and
portobello mushrooms. I opted for the tender filet mignon
medallions. The tavern's extensive wine list offered a classy
alternative to the fraternity row scene around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we took a ferry to Kelleys to investigate the
quieter side of the islands. On Lakeshore Drive, stately
turn-of-the-century homes line the road, most with wraparound
porches, impeccably manicured lawns and a lake view. By the time we
arrived at the two-block downtown, Kelleys seemed like the antidote
to Put-in-Bay's excesses. The 150 or so permanent residents appear
to want to keep it that way, if the many ``no trespassing signs''
are any indication. some residents of Kelleys are so wary of
encroaching tourism that they ``moved over to Pelee Island to get
away from the crowds,'' said Robby Zettler, co-owner of the
Kelley's Island Wine Co. on Woodford Road. This lone survivor from
two dozen wineries that made the island famous in the 19th century
is now one of its most popular restaurants. Zettler served us a
plate of bread and cheeses with a sampler of the winery's dry wines
as she described the quirks of the island.
</P>
<P>
   On the northwest side, for example, 396-foot-long, 30-foot wide
glacial grooves illustrate the raw power of the geological forces
of the ice age. On the other side of the island is Inscription
Rock, a 32-by-21-foot limestone boulder covered with pictographs of
animals and people carved by the Erie Indians, who spent summers
here in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   There is also plenty of kitsch. Near inscription rock, a
seven-foot white plaster model of the Statue of Liberty stands in
front of a Victorian bed-and-breakfast, Kelley Mansion. A sign in
the yard boasts improbably that it is ``the most famous mansion in
the world.'' Its most famous feature is a grand, self-supporting
circular staircase built without nails.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, there are tours and overnight stays, but Ben
and I were too early _ the windows were still boarded up and the
lawn was overgrown, giving the weathered mansion a sinister
appearance. ``It's the kind of place where you look around,'' Ben
said, ``and you keep expecting someone to be looking back at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds are, that someone would be wearing gray and carrying a
musket.
</P>
<P>
   GUIDE TO THE OHIO KEYS
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Erie Islands are 70 miles west of Cleveland and 55
miles east of Toledo on Ohio Route 2, which runs parallel to
Interstate 80-90.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Boat Line, (800) 500-2421, www.millerferry.com, runs
ferries to South Bass and Middle Bass Islands from Catawba Point,
at the end of Ohio Route 53, off Route 2 near Port Clinton. The
ferry runs every half hour from 7 a.m. until 8 p.m. in summer, but
there can be long waits on Friday and Sunday. The 18-minute trip
costs $5 each way, $1 for children ages 6 to 11. It costs an
additional $2 each way for a bicycle and $10 for a car. A car is
not necessary since it is easy to rent golf carts on the islands.
On weekends, ferry operators require that anyone taking a car show
proof of accommodations because parking is at a premium in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Jet Express, (800) 245-1538, runs a passenger-only ferry
from Port Clinton to Put-in-Bay from 8 a.m. until about midnight.
The round-trip weekend fare is $20.50, $3 for children 5 to 12.
Bikes cost $5. Fares are less during the week and at night.
</P>
<P>
   Neuman Boat Line, (800) 876-1907, runs the Kelleys Island ferry
from Marblehead. Round-trip fares: $10; $5 children 6 to 11; an
additional $17 for a car, and $3.50 for a bike.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO
</P>
<P>
   To visit the Confederate Graveyard on Johnson's Island, take the
self-guided Marblehead Circle Tour in Ottawa County on the
mainland. A causeway connects Johnson's Island, off Route 135; it
costs $1 to cross. The cemetery is about 200 yards on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's Victory and International Peace Memorial, on Bay Avenue
on Put-in-Bay, (419) 285-2184, is open daily from late April
through late October. It costs $3 to ride to the viewing platform,
317 feet up.
</P>
<P>
   Western Lake Erie has some of the best freshwater fishing in the
world, with perch, catfish and crappie in plentiful supply. There
are lots of charter companies in the area. Fishing licenses ($15
annually for Ohio residents, $24 for others, or $7 for a day) can
be bought in Put-in-Bay at East Point Cottages, (419) 285-2204, and
at the Press House Corner Market, (419) 285-2716.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Point, 1 Cedar Point Drive, Sandusky, (419) 627-2350,
offers 68 rides, including 14 roller coasters. Admission ranges
from $22 to $79. Open daily through Labor Day and on weekends
through Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   Reservations are a must on the islands in peak season. We stayed
a night at the Islander Inn, Post Office Box 309, 225 Erie Street,
Put-in-Bay, (877) 500-7829, fax (419) 285-3012. Its Caribbean decor
includes palm and banana trees, and wicker and rattan furnishings
in the 70 rooms. High-season rates range from $115 on weeknights to
$200 a night on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   We also stayed at Parker's Inn, 432 Catawba Avenue, Put-in-Bay;
(419) 285-5555 fax (419) 285-5556. The inn has 50 standard rooms,
with doubles ranging from $69, in off season, to $179, including
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   There are B &AMP; Bs on most of the islands, as well as cottages for
rent. For a sampling, visit the Put-in-Bay Web site,
www.put-in-bay.com &QL; 
/accomod.htm. For lodging options on Kelleys Island, go to www &QL; 
.kelleysisland.com/accm.html. You can also call the Ottawa County
Visitors Bureau at (800) 441-1271 or the Sandusky-Erie County
Visitors Bureau at (800) 255-3743.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT
</P>
<P>
   The Erie Isle Tavern, in Parker's Inn at 430 Catawba Ave.,
Put-in-Bay, (419) 285-5557, serves excellent seafood and has an
impressive wine list. Dinner was about $77 for two, with wine.
</P>
<P>
   All visitors eventually end up at the Frosty Bar, (419)
285-3278, on Delaware Avenue in Put-in-Bay for pizza or breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The Round House Bar, 60 Delaware Avenue, (419) 285-2323) has
live music every afternoon and evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Beer Barrel Saloon, down the street, (419) 285-7281, has
what it says is the longest bar in the world _ 405 feet, 10 inches
_ zigzagging on one side, as well as live music and food.
</P>
<P>
   On Kelleys Island, the Kelley's Island Wine Co., 418 Woodford
Road, (419) 746-2537, serves an excellent cheese plate with its
wine samples, as well as a menu of steaks, chicken and quesadillas
during the evenings, with entrees costing about $10. We paid about
$8 each for a cheese plate. Wines cost $8.75 to $12 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
