<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HUNLEY0808-COX     08-07 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNLEY0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confederate sub to return to shore today
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SULLIVAN'S ISLAND, S.C. - This morning, as the barge carrying
the Confederate submarine H.L. Hunley nears Charleston Harbor, the
bells of Stella Maris Catholic Church will ring first.
</P>
<P>
   Other churches will join in during the historic sub's 13-mile
journey from the ocean floor where it sank 136 years ago to its
North Charleston conservation laboratory. As much as scientists,
history buffs and tens of thousands of others eagerly await a
glimpse of the historic Confederate relic, the sub's journey is
also a funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not have a proper burial,'' said Michael Osbourne,
the Stella Maris deacon who will signal the Hunley's approach to
bell ringers in the church's tower. ``It is simply a traditional
way of paying respect to the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 14 men who died the night of Feb. 17, 1864, it's a trip
long overdue, organizers say.
</P>
<P>
   Five Union sailors died after the Hunley rammed the USS
Housatonic with a long spar affixed with a charge of black powder.
As the ship sank, marking the first time a sub had sunk another
warship, the Hunley backed away. Its crew flashed a blue light,
signaling fellow Confederates on shore that it was returning home.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hunley sank mysteriously, and its nine Confederate
crewmen also died.
</P>
<P>
   Today as the barge reaches the pier at the conservation lab,
Confederate re-enactors will flash a blue light, one of many
symbolic acts to welcome the Hunley home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ringing for the crews of the Hunley and the Housatonic
who died that night,'' said the Rev. Lawrence McInerny, pastor of
Stella Maris, the church organizing the bell-ringing tribute. It
will ring its eight bells half muffled, a custom at memorials for
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunley, McInerny said, will be ``treated as a military
tomb.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 Confederate re-enactors will take up positions
along the Cooper River, firing cannons and rifles in salute as the
Hunley passes. Women dressed in Confederate garb will toss flowers
into the river from the deck of the retired USS Yorktown,
considered by organizers to be one of the best spots for viewing
the Hunley.
</P>
<P>
   Today's trip will be the public's first opportunity to glimpse
the sub, or at least its outline encased in metal supports, slings
and foam-filled bags intended to stabilize the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Marietta, Ga.-based Flexible Products Co. donated the
foam-filled bags. One of the company's sales representatives, Bill
Youmans, a Savannah native with family ties to Charleston, has
traveled four times to the recovery site, four miles off Sullivan's
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard so many stories about the Hunley from my grandfather
when I was a little boy that it was natural for me to get
involved,'' said Youmans, 51.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively small number of people have seen the Hunley's spar,
one of the sub's technological marvels already recovered by divers.
It is submerged in a shallow tank of water at the conservation lab.
</P>
<P>
   One who has seen the long orangish shaft is Jim Tapley, a
retired submarine mechanic from the now-closed Charleston Naval
Yard. A volunteer in today's Hunley activities, he was reluctant to
touch the spar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to look at it, it was quite a thing,'' Tapley said.
</P>
<P>
   While the NAACP has protested another Civil War relic _ the
Confederate battle flag at the Statehouse _ the Hunley has drawn no
protests. ``We do not look at this as a North-South thing,'' said
Tapley, commanding officer of the Charleston Torpedo Division, a
group of naval re-enactors. ``We look at it as a groundbreaking
military treasure that we can now examine and learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the lead scientists who in coming weeks will cut open the
Hunley's iron hull says she's keenly aware of the vessel's
historical significance, as well as the sensitivity of its probable
contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a sardine can that we're opening,'' said Maria
Jacobsen, senior archaeologist at the Hunley conservation lab.
``These are human remains we are dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
