<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LIEBERMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN'S MORAL EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moral outrage has been a hallmark of Joseph I. Lieberman's
political career for two decades. His passionate voice and his
common-sense approach to many issues are welcome additions to the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, in choosing the two-term Connecticut
senator as his running mate, has picked a man with relatively
little national reputation or stature. Only once has Lieberman led
the news, when he criticized President Bill Clinton for his
behavior with Monica Lewinsky, saying ``It is immoral. And it is
harmful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention made two strong statements, claiming
diversity for the GOP and tarring Gore for his relationship with
Clinton. Lieberman's selection _ as the first Jewish candidate for
national office and the first Democrat to criticize Clinton _
blunts both Republican initiatives effectively. But if Gore's
choice is meant merely to inoculate him from GOP criticism, it is a
poor rationale.
</P>
<P>
   We hope and expect voters have grown beyond prejudging a
candidate based on religion. Vice presidential nominees should be
judged primarily for their ability to work with the presidential
candidate and to take over in the White House if necessary.
Lieberman still has much to prove.
</P>
<P>
   In his public career, he has been an independent thinker, often
with a moral edge. As attorney general of Connecticut, he
investigated a failed child support system, not only as a policy
issue but also from the principle that parents need to accept the
responsibility for raising their children. A genuine intellectual,
he wrote a book on the subject in 1985. Similarly, there has been a
tone to his support for campaign finance reform, for the V-chip to
screen out televised sex and violence, and for other issues that
has seemed sanctimonious at times and appropriately outraged at
others.
</P>
<P>
   He is more centrist than most of the others on Gore's short
list, supporting some privatization of Social Security and, more
troublingly, questioning affirmative action and supporting a pilot
school voucher plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' job now is to convince voters that Lieberman is a
good answer not just to the GOP's past convention, but for the
nation's future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BAGHDAD-BOS     08-07 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BAGHDAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING CLEAR ABOUT SADDAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be true that party platforms nowadays are, for the most
part, artful patchworks of subliminal signals, lacking real
meaning. A promising exception to that rule is the two-paragraph
plank in the Republican Party platform concerning the unresolved
problem of Saddam Hussein's continued misrule in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's critique of Clinton administration dithering in its
Iraq policy is on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has pretended to support the removal of
Saddam Hussein from power, but did nothing when Saddam Hussein's
army smashed the democratic opposition in northern Iraq in August
1996,'' the Republican platform laments. ``The administration also
surrendered the diplomatic initiative to Iraq and Iraq's friends,
and failed to champion the international inspectors charged with
erasing Iraq's nuclear, biological, chemical, and ballistic missile
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   These are stipulations of fact, notwithstanding the partisan
intent of the platform's authors. What those Republican authors
omit, of course, is that former President George Bush, vice
presidential nominee Dick Cheney, and former chief of staff Colin
Powell were the decision-makers responsible for failing to support
the popular uprising of Iraqis in March 1991, just after the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   That revolt of soldiers and civilians could have toppled
Saddam's Baathist dictatorship if Bush, Cheney, and Powell had not
permitted its helicopter gunships, tanks, and heavy armor to move
through the airspace and land routes controlled by America's
victorious troops, enabling Saddam's forces to massacre Iraqis who
heeded the elder Bush's call for them to overthrow the dictator.
</P>
<P>
   If George W. Bush and Cheney could admit the errors the last
Republican administration made in Iraq, the party's prescription
for Iraq policy in 2001 would sound more credible.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cheney has never ceased pretending that the only
choice Washington had in 1991 was to send US troops to Baghdad or
leave Saddam in power.  &UR; Today &LR;  his party's platform calls for
basing ``a comprehensive plan for the removal of Saddam Hussein''
on support for the Iraqi National Congress, ``an umbrella
organization reflecting a broad and representative group of Iraqis
who wish to free their country from the scourge of Saddam Hussein's
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   This plank of the Republican platform proposes a clear and
plausible means for rectifying the mistakes on Iraq made by
President Clinton and the Bush administration. It has the great
virtue of favoring a democratic future for Iraq after Saddam, and
it has the corollary advantage of helping Iraqis to overthrow the
criminal who has tortured and murdered so many of their
compatriots. This is preferable to accepting the counsel of some
Arab regimes that warn of Iraq's fragmentation into separate
entities should a Sunni Moslem minority no longer rule in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a service to the voters if George W. Bush and Cheney
were to debate Iraq policy in the fall campaign. Because of
Saddam's revived missile program and his chance to pursue nuclear,
chemical, and biological weapons again in the 20 months since UN
inspectors were kicked out of Iraq, the vengeful despot looms as a
true threat to his neighborhood and to the cause of
nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
   But if Bush and Cheney wish to give a public airing to the
criticisms of Clinton or the policy proposals in the Republican
platform, they will first have to address the contradiction
implicit in that document. They will have to acknowledge that the
party's present critique of Clinton's Iraq policy applies equally
to some of the same Republican officials who now advise George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam has benefited too long from schizoid policy-making in
Washington. If Bush and Cheney want a substantive debate of the
crucial issue of Iraq, they will have to make it plain that they no
longer accept the premises of the original Republican containment
policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
