<HEADLINE>
PREVIEW OF NO. 16 OHIO STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
No. 16 Ohio State Conference: Big Ten Coach: John Cooper (103-39-4
in 12 seasons, 185-79-6 overall in 23 seasons) 1999: 6-6, 3-5 in
Big Ten, tied for 8th Bowl: None Starters returning: Six on
offense, seven on defense Key players: Senior WR Ken-Yon Rambo,
senior WR Reggie Germany, senior DE Rodney Bailey, junior QB Steve
Bellisari. Reasons to smile: Despite last year's .500 record, Ohio
State is loaded with talent. In a conference with many top
recievers, the Buckeyes might have two of the best in Germany and
Rambo. The defensive line is experienced and talented. Reasons to
frown: Bellisari is the team's quarterback, but he has to prove he
can win in the Big Ten. Last season, the Buckeyes never jelled as a
team. Finding that cohesiveness will be a challenge. A glorious
season if: Bellisari gets the job done at quarterback, a productive
tailback emerges and the defense plugs some holes. Datebook: The
Buckeyes get Big Ten challengers Penn State, Michigan State and
Michigan at home. However, Ohio State must play at Wisconsin on
Oct. 7 and at Illinois on Nov. 11. The nonconference schedule is
highlighted by a dangerous trip to Arizona on Sept. 9. This and
that: Ohio State is in the process of expanding Ohio Stadium.
Seating capacity is being increased from 89,000 to approximately
96,000. The $187 million project won't be completed until 2001, but
construction isn't expected to affect this season's home games. ...
Despite his 2-9-1 record against rival Michigan, Cooper signed a
five-year contract extension last year worth a guaranteed $1.1
million annually. ... Cooper reworked his coaching staff in the
off-season. He moved Chuck Stobart from receivers coach to
offensive coordinator and moved Jon Tenuta from defensive-backs
coach to defensive coordinator. ... Steve Bellisari's older
brother, Greg, a former Buckeyes' linebacker, is a
graduate-assistant defensive coach with the team.1999 statistical
rankings OFFENSE Rushing 38 Passing 80 Scoring 75 Total yards 74
DEFENSE Rushing 71 Passing 65 Scoring 48 Total yards 54
2000 schedule Sept. 2 Fresno State Sept. 9 at Arizona Sept. 16
Miami (Ohio) Sept. 23 Penn State Oct. 7 at Wisconsin Oct. 14
Minnesota Oct. 21 at Iowa Oct. 28 at Purdue Nov. 4 Michigan State
Nov. 11 at Illinois Nov. 18 Michigan
SPOTLIGHT QB's improvement key for Buckeyes Ohio State coach John
Cooper says, ``Without a quarterback, you just don't have an
offense.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's Buckeyes offensive coordinator Chuck Stobart talking
about junior quarterback Steve Bellisari: ``Make no doubt _ he's
the man.''
</P>
<P>
   And in those two statements, you've got Ohio State's season in a
nutshell. Bellisari retains the quarterback job he won early last
season. But if he doesn't significantly improve, the Buckeyes could
be headed toward another 6-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like this season has taken forever to get here,''
Bellisari said. ``I've been wanting to erase some of the things
that happened last year. The only way to do that is by playing. I
feel we're going to be more competitive. After a season like that,
it's a motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellisari beat out Austin Moherman for the starting spot in
September. However, the on-the-job training was difficult. It has
been 20 years since an Ohio State quarterback had worse statistics.
Bellisari ranked 10th in the Big Ten in passing efficiency,
completing 101 of 224 passes (45.1 percent) for 1,616 yards. He had
12 touchdown passes, nine interceptions and completed more than 50
percent of his passes only twice in 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the middle of last season, Ohio State won three of
four games, including victories against bowl-bound Purdue and
Minnesota. In those games, Bellisari used quarterback draws and
scrambles to move the ball. Stobart plans to put more plays in this
season's offense to take advantage of Bellisari's mobility,
including some options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has been in our program for a couple of years,''
Cooper said. ``This year, he has a much better understanding of
what he can do, and, most importantly, we have a much better
understanding of what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellisari's previous claim to fame came as a freshman reserve
when he killed time playing on Ohio State special teams. At
6-foot-3 and 220 pounds, the athletic Bellisari is often compared
to Steve Young. So far, that comparison has mostly been made
because Bellisari and the former 49ers quarterback both throw
left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always say losing builds character and stuff, but it was
tough,'' said Bellisari, who was intercepted twice in the Buckeyes'
season-ending 24-17 loss at Michigan. ``I look at it as a
motivating factor. I don't ever want to feel that way again. I was
more frustrated than anything. I'm a very competitive guy. I mean,
I don't like losing even a Play Station game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
