<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN, DEREGULATION THREATENS TRADITIONAL MOM-AND-POP SHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACHIDA CITY, Japan _ Sales started sliding at the Katos' small
sake shop here a decade ago, when trucks began coming into the
neighborhood and selling cut-price beer and other alcoholic
beverages off their tailgates.
</P>
<P>
   Now the trucks have been put out of business by convenience
stores, supermarkets and discount shops, but Yoshiro Kato and his
wife, Mitsuko, soldier on, determined to resist forces that could
turn shops like theirs into quaint memories of a Japan that no
longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deregulation,'' she said. ``People in government say
Americans have deregulation, so we should too, but those saying
that don't understand the feelings of people like us who are just
struggling to survive. It's like they're telling us, just hurry up
and die, would you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kato has suppressed her anger many times as once-loyal
customers walk past the shop in this Tokyo suburb, lugging heavy
bottles of alcohol from the supermarket nearby. She does not blame
them for the shop's waning business. Her own children, she said,
frequent discount stores, lured by ample parking space, late hours
and low prices.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 10 years have passed since Japan began to dismantle the
litany of licenses, permits and other regulatory approvals that
were long part of breaking into business here. Under deregulation,
competition has grown, the number of stores has increased and
Japanese consumers now enjoy many of the same benefits as Americans
in areas ranging from convenience banking to the purchase of
gasoline. But the endangered shotengai, or local shopping district,
has become a rallying point against deregulation among Japanese
worried that they are destroying something precious.
</P>
<P>
   In some isolated cases, the forces opposing deregulation are
prevailing. Neighborhood groups have banded together to fight
incursions by big store chains. And in a throwback to a more
regulated era, large retailers must now get permission from local
committees to open stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deregulation has been accepted without any criticism in Japan
as a great measure for reviving the economy,'' said Shoji Muranuki,
leader of a citizens' group that won concessions from a retail
chain seeking permission to open in their neighborhood. ``But how
can we say that deregulation is helping the economy when so many
local shopkeepers and merchants are hurting because of it?''
</P>
<P>
   Groups like Muranuki's and business associations that sat by
quietly as the effects of deregulation spread are now increasingly
vocal about drawing the line somewhere. Breaking up a telephone
monopoly like the Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. is one
thing, they say, but destroying the livelihoods of local
shopkeepers is going too far. This sympathy for local shopkeepers
has given them a powerful means of defense that NTT does not have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is like the difference between an elephant and
an ant,'' said Hiroshi Yamada, the mayor of Suginami ward in Tokyo,
when asked to compare the power of small shops to that of NTT, the
telecommunications giant that is under heavy political pressure to
accept further deregulation. ``NTT bows to the politicians, but the
politicians bow to the local shopkeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Shopkeepers have traditionally been the backbone of the Japanese
neighborhood. They organize festivals that make the long, sticky
summers here tolerable. They are active in school affairs and
community sports. They hang out in front of their shops, chatting
with patrons and handing out candy or small toys to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might be feeble in terms of their sales power, but they
have a big say in what happens in local areas,'' Yamada said. They
lack the financial resources of big corporations like NTT, he said,
``but the local shop owners can collect something even more
valuable _ votes.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young member of Parliament a few years ago, Yamada was a
strong proponent of deregulation. But as a local politician, he has
pressed for passage of an ordinance to restrict activities of large
discount stores in the interest of protecting his constituents from
the traffic jams they fear will blight their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I have come to the front line, I have learned that
just legislating deregulation does not make deregulation
fruitful,'' he said. ``I realize that many conditions need to be
imposed to make deregulation work in society.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be, but the shotengai is one of the biggest drags on
Japan's sputtering economy. According to a new study by the
McKinsey Global Institute that blames Japan's economic troubles on
low productivity, traditional shops like the Katos' are far less
productive than their counterparts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many shops stay in business in part because of high tax
penalties that discourage them from selling their property.
Government loan guarantees and subsidies also make it easier to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   But the McKinsey study discloses another important source of the
traditional shopkeeper's power: Mom-and-pop shops account for 55
percent of retail employment here, while the entire retail industry
accounts for 12 percent of total employment and 5 percent of the
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Kabun Muto, a senior member of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party, is making a name for himself as a champion of small
liquor-store owners like the Katos in particular and a critic of
deregulation in general. He has submitted a bill to postpone
further deregulation that could hurt neighborhood stores.
</P>
<P>
   Muto and the 220 representatives who support him also oppose the
relaxation of rules on taxi licensing. Muto contends that looser
rules have given the Japanese mafia a toehold in the cab business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less intervention by the bureaucracy now,'' said
Muto, whose family owns a sake brewery. ``But in creating such an
open environment, we have weakened society, and people would have
different opinions about whether that's a good thing or not.''
</P>
