<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-SMALL-SHOPS-ART     08-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SMALL-SHOPS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MACHIDA CITY, Japan: or not.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question for Japan is whether the social costs that concern
Muto _ the loss of livelihood by shopkeepers who are often pillars
of their communities or a potential increase in troubled youth _
offset the benefits of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year that ended in March 1998, the Economic
Planning Agency estimated that deregulation had created 8.6
trillion yen, or $83 billion at current exchange rates, in consumer
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also concluded that growth was notably strong that
year in deregulated businesses like telephone services, electricity
and gasoline, even as the overall economy shrunk. ``The progress in
the last few years has been marvelous,'' said Yoshihiko Miyauchi,
chairman of the government's Regulatory Reform Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He regards Muto's campaign and the lobbying of the All-Japan
Liquor Merchants' Association, whose officials paid 300 visits to
politicians last year and contributed 40 million yen, or about
$381,000, to the ruling party, as a sign of how far deregulation
has penetrated the economy. ``One reason we have these types of
movements is because the efforts we have made are having an
effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Japan is falling behind the rest of the developed
world, Miyauchi said. ``We are walking in the right direction at a
very leisurely pace, congratulating ourselves for our progress,
while other countries are running this race like Olympic
athletes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those pressing for fast-paced regulatory change here seem more
like, well, Don Quixote, which happens to be the name of a discount
store chain that has become the bane of anti-deregulation forces.
The Don Quixote store in Suginami, where Yamada is mayor, has
become a cause celebre among proponents and opponents of reform,
with its extended hours, large parking lot and cut-rate prices.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood residents and local merchants united last year and
gathered 6,271 signatures in their campaign to keep the Don Quixote
store out. They worried that the store would attract motorcycle
gangs, increase traffic and worsen pollution. They feared that some
merchandise, ``adult'' toys and videos and knives, in particular,
would end up in the hands of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, ``if the store operated 24 hours a day, regular shops
could not compete,'' said Muranuki, a retired salaryman who leads
the group. ``Already, our shops are suffering from large-sized
retailers like supermarkets.''
</P>
<P>
   The group won some concessions from Don Quixote. The store
agreed to close from 6 a.m. to 10 a.m. daily, to avoid flashy
advertising and handouts that might lead to litter, and to keep
certain goods off its shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Suginami Assembly passed an ordinance in early
July that allows the mayor to block the opening of stores larger
than 500 square meters if he thinks the owner has failed to address
local concerns about ``the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance thus resurrected restrictions on retailers that
were recently abolished by the national government. ``Now, the
entire nation is focusing on what's happened here,'' Muranuki said
proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Takao Yasuda, the president of Don Quixote and a passionate
proponent of deregulation, contends that the citizens won a Pyrrhic
victory. His store did open, and its sales are running 30 percent
above expectations. ``We are closed in hours when few customers
would visit the store anyway, and if the store is closed, we can do
preparatory work, like straightening up the cash registers and
shelves,'' Yasuda said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group that opposed the store concede that their
worries have proved unfounded _ and take credit for it. They still
watch the store, patrolling the parking lot between 10 p.m. and 11
p.m. and making spot checks of the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the shop isn't causing any trouble,'' said Kyoko
Hashiguchi, the group's secretary. ``Traffic jams outside the store
are much less than we expected because local people seem to ride
their bicycles to the store.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yasuda is concerned about the precedent the fight in
Suginami established. The citizens' appeal to quality-of-life
concerns has resonated with the media and with politicians in a way
that complaints solely about the economic impact of deregulation
have not.
</P>
<P>
   Their ability to enlist the local government in their cause is
also alarming, he said. The local ordinance's vague command that
retailers must ``protect the environment'' leaves plenty of room
for government interference, Yasuda said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ordinance itself is not so strong, but I worry that it is
rather arbitrary and fuzzy in its meaning,'' Yasuda said. ``That
means that in a uniquely Japanese way, the local government can
exercise its own power of interpretation, and that worries me.''
</P>
