<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-'COYOTE'-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-COYOTE-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `COYOTE UGLY' A KICK BUT NOTHING TO HOWL ABOUT
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to defend (beginitalic)Coyote Ugly (enditalic)as being
much of a movie. It's more like a collection of music videos, or a
pretty good LeAnn Rimes CD, or a fashion show for belly shirts,
leather pants and cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that's all it's trying to be.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which could be retitled (beginitalic)Urban
Cowgirl(enditalic), delivers exactly what it promises - gorgeous
women in skimpy clothing, dancing in a rowdy bar. And it does so
with such an amiable tone, you can't help but like the silly thing.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Coyote Ugly (enditalic)is all about titillation,
since its PG-13 rating won't allow anything more. The movie is
essentially one long parade of belly buttons.
</P>
<P>
   While men will enjoy it for obvious reasons, there's also plenty
here to attract women, including two strong female characters in
leading roles.
</P>
<P>
   Piper Perabo gives a winning performance as Violet, an aspiring
songwriter from the sticks who goes to work in a crazed New York
bar to make ends meet. The winsome Perabo seems to have emerged
unscathed from (beginitalic)The Adventures of Rocky and
Bullwinkle(enditalic), which is no mean feat.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Bello ((beginitalic)ER(enditalic)), does a nice job as
Lil, the tough bar owner who hires Violet to add some innocence to
the mix. Given a caricature to play, Bello pumps life into the
role.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this chaos, there is John Goodman, doing a
heart-warming turn as Violet's widowed father, who doesn't want her
to leave for the big city. When the film threatens to slow down,
Goodman buoys it with one funny line after another. He also injects
a much-needed shot of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the bar. Though supposedly patterned after a real
tavern, (beginitalic)Coyote Ugly (enditalic)seems like no other.
First off, the bartenders, or ``coyotes,'' all look like models
(one is played by real-life supermodel Tyra Banks). Between serving
drinks and setting the bar on fire, they turn up the music and
dance in their cowboy boots and halter tops, whipping the patrons
into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the movie's trademark scene, and to make sure you don't
miss it, they show it about six times. After awhile, this becomes a
bit repetitious, as if the filmmakers couldn't think of much else
to do.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who ever tended bar, the movie must seem pretty
ridiculous. But this is more about fantasy than reality.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the gaps between the dancing, producer Jerry Bruckheimer
added a paper-thin love story, featuring hunky Adam Garcia as
Kevin, Violet's would-be boyfriend. We know Kevin is a nice guy,
because he collects comic books. There's a cute little back-story
that has Kevin trying to persuade Violet to overcome her stage
fright and perform her songs on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Perabo gets a little more help than that. In the
movie, her singing is dubbed by country-Western star Rimes, which
is a little like subbing Michael Jordan into a pickup game at the
Y.
</P>
<P>
   Still, (beginitalic)Coyote Ugly (enditalic)has a pretty good
beat, and you can dance to it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
