<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LIEBERMAN JOINS AN EXCLUSIVE CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Democrats nominate Joseph Lieberman for
vice president next week, they will inscribe the Connecticut
senator's name beside those of others who have ripped down barriers
that prevented individuals from attaining or seeking high office
because of religion, race, gender or geographic base.
</P>
<P>
   The club to which Lieberman _ an Orthodox Jew _ will be admitted
is very small and exclusive. Its members have weathered storms over
their religious affiliations, the color of their skin, their sex or
their area of origin. The club has included:
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Gov. Alfred E. Smith, who in 1928 became the first
Catholic to be nominated by a major party for president. His quest
failed.
</P>
<P>
   _ John F. Kennedy, the first Catholic to be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Rep. Geraldine Ferraro, nominated for vice president
by the Democrats in 1984, the first woman in either major party to
be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   _ Housing and Urban Development Secretary Robert Weaver, the
first black Cabinet officer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Labor Secretary Frances Perkins, the first woman to serve in
the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lieberman, all were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   To that list, we could add the name of Thurgood Marshall, the
first black named to the Supreme Court and that of Sandra Day
O'Connor, the first woman appointed to the high court. Marshall was
a Democrat; O'Connor is a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly Eleanor Roosevelt was a member of that elite group
as the first lady who cast aside the strictures that had bound her
predecessors and established own career as an outspoken proponent
of racial equality, federal aid for the poor and the peace-keeping
efforts of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Should Hillary Rodham Clinton win the Senate seat she is seeking
in New York, she would achieve a remarkable first. No other first
lady has sought public office.
</P>
<P>
   A further addition to the group is Jimmy Carter of Georgia, who
in 1976 became the first individual from the Deep South to be
elected president since before the Civil War, which ended in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   In l916, Woodrow Wilson ignited a religious conflagration when
he nominated Louis D. Brandeis as the first Jewish member of the
Supreme Court. Brandeis' ability was never in question, but his
religion and his liberal reputation were.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually became one of the court's great justices.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the walls that bar admittance of able Americans to the
upper reaches of government have tumbled down in recent years. But
each success has been the product of a struggle that pitted
American against American.
</P>
<P>
   The problems faced by those who are confronted by bigotry was
addressed memorably by Kennedy in his successful 1960 campaign for
president. Appearing before the Houston Ministerial Association,
Kennedy declared: ``I believe in an America where the separation of
church and state is absolute _ where no Catholic prelate would tell
the president (should he be a Catholic) how to act, and no
Protestant minister would tell his parishioners for whom to vote _
where no church or church school is granted any public funds or
political preference ... an America that is officially neither
Catholic, Protestant nor Jewish _ where no public official either
requests or accepts instructions on public policy from ... any ...
ecclesiastical source ... where there is no Catholic vote, no
anti-Catholic vote, no bloc voting of any kind and where religious
liberty is so indivisible that an act against one church is treated
as an act against all.''
</P>
<P>
   To that powerful defense of the separation of church and state,
Kennedy added: ``I am not the Catholic candidate for president. I
am the Democratic Party's candidate for president, who happens also
to be a Catholic. I do not speak for my church on public matters,
and the church does not speak for me.''
</P>
<P>
   What criticism Lieberman may face in the upcoming presidential
campaign is anybody's guess. But he should be able to weather
anything that is thrown at him, by remembering the ordeal faced by
other members of the exclusive club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
