<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SAMMY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-07 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SAMMY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAMMY': AN ARCHIE   FOR 2000   WITH A TASTE   FOR LECHERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By NEIL GENZLINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's too bad, really, that ``Sammy,'' David Spade's new animated
sitcom, didn't make its appearance about 30 years ago. That was the
moment in history when loutishness could be lovable, as Norman Lear
showed us with Archie Bunker. Alas, Spade's Sammy, who makes his
debut Tuesday night on NBC, is a lout born too late.
</P>
<P>
   When Archie and ``All in the Family'' landed in living rooms in
January 1971, the notion of what is today called politically
incorrect behavior was still a hazy one; part of the show's
scandalousness was that it was educating and defining as it went
along. ``See?'' the subtext of each episode read. ``This is what
bigotry and insensitivity are, and now let's all share a laugh over
someone who's a step behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The title character in ``Sammy,'' who is billed as being based
on Spade's own father, is a sort of hypersexed Archie, spewing
bawdy bedroom talk the way Lear's character served up invective
about blacks and Poles. Sammy, who abandoned his wife and three
young sons at some point in the distant past, has reappeared in
order to mooch off one of those sons, James, who has become a
television star. Part of the fun of the show is that Spade provides
the voices of both father and son.
</P>
<P>
   The notion, apparently, is that Sammy and James form a bond in
adulthood that they never had as father-son; Sammy's eccentricity
is supposed to be endearing as well as offensive. Today, though,
that's too much to ask. There are certainly still plenty of lechers
among us, some even as openly lascivious as Sammy, but we're beyond
the point where thinking people will put up with them. It's the
back half of the ``Arthur'' syndrome at work: Dudley Moore's drunk
was amusing and poignant in the original 1981 film but an
embarrassment in ``Arthur II'' in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   This makes ``Sammy'' not quite work, even though many of its
component parts are quite good. There is subtle wit and social
commentary sprinkled throughout the show, as when James, accepting
a drink from his immigrant maid at poolside, asks her:
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever had one of those days where things work out
better than you could have possibly imagined, and you realize
everything you were worried about just disappeared, and the sun is
shining and the birds are singing and you just feel completely at
peace with the world?''
</P>
<P>
   The maid answers, ``Almost every day is like that for me.'' Then
she adds deferentially, ``I'll go clean the toilets now.''
</P>
<P>
   Also welcome is the way the animated format, unencumbered by the
pacing requirements of a laugh track and/or live audience, allows
such lines to be delivered the way they would be in real life: as
fleeting asides, or muttered, or thought rather than spoken. Thus
Sammy, after making a throat-scarring bear growl during a barroom
brawl with another son, Gary (Bob Odenkirk), can pause just long
enough to say under his breath, ``Note to self: Don't make bear
noise; it hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice work in ``Sammy'' is notable. Maura Tierney as James'
gorgeous assistant, Andy Dick as his agent, Harland Williams as the
third brother and others catch their characters nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Especially impressive is Spade's rich and nuanced rendition of
Sammy, who is braying vulgarly one minute and whimpering pitifully
the next. With the animation nothing special and the plot lines
fairly standard sitcom stuff, the best way to take in ``Sammy''
might be with eyes closed, just focusing on the vocal techniques.
Maybe then it would be possible to drift back to those salacious,
sexist days of yore.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SAMMY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 p.m. ET Tuesday on NBC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created by David Spade and Drake Sather; Spade, Sather, Brad
Grey, Marc Gurvitz and Richard Raynis, executive producers; Joe
Fury, executive consultant; Frank Van Keeken, supervising producer.
Produced by NBC Studios and Brad Gray Television. Animation
production by Adelaide Productions Inc.
</P>
