<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMD completes spinoff of communications products division
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Employees of Austin's newest chip maker headed
to a minor league baseball game Monday night to celebrate, but
their infant company, Legerity Inc., already has a solid batting
average.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff from Advanced Micro Devices Inc. has a solid
customer base, $300 million in annual sales, a veteran staff of 250
and a portfolio of several hundred patents.
</P>
<P>
   Now all it must do is recruit a new chief executive, fill about
60 job openings, find a new headquarters site and beef up its
product portfolio. All those moves are part of a plan for a public
stock offering within 18 months, company executives said. To
accomplish all that, the new company will have to live up to its
name, which means quick and agile.
</P>
<P>
   A California investment group, Francisco Partners, completed its
purchase Monday of AMD's former communications products division
for $375 million, allowing the formation.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Partners agreed to buy the AMD division in May after
the chip maker said it would sell the communications division to
concentrate on its other product lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at ourselves as a $300 million startup,'' said company
chief operating officer Gary Ashcraft, a 25-year veteran of AMD.
``We have real customers and real products and real profits that
can fuel our growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has made chips used in voice communications
equipment for many years, but it has plans to move into more
advanced chips used in high-speed Internet access gear.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Legerity has a solid base of business and
technical expertise to build a solid company in a fast-moving
telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good little division,'' said analyst Fred Zieber with
Pathfinder Research of San Jose, Calif. ``It was an orphan within
AMD,'' he said, which has been preoccupied in recent years with its
rivalry with Intel Corp. to gain a foothold in the microprocessor
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year from now they could be the hottest company in the
world,'' Zieber said. ``It's amazing what getting rid of the parent
company can do for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Legerity is an independent company, but it still has ties to its
former parent. AMD has agreed to manufacture, test, package and
ship many of the new company's chips for the next five years. AMD
retains a 10 percent ownership interest in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Legerity also is leasing 35,000 square feet of space from AMD at
a former Lockheed site in Southeast Austin. The company expects to
find a new headquarters by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 60 job openings that it is trying to fill in
engineering, marketing and finance.
</P>
<P>
   The company already has filled several senior level positions
from the ranks of AMD managers. Russ Apfel is chief technology
officer; Homer Lloyd is vice president of marketing; Michael
Stibilia is director of systems architecture; Michael Hogan is
director of CMOS product development; and Duncan Ashworth if vice
president of bipolar products and process technology.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Kirk Ladendorf at kladendorf(at)statesman.com or
445-3622.
</P>
