<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN'S CONSERVATIVE RECORD IS NO HELP TO GORE, GOP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 (With GORE-LIEBERMAN) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans praised the selection of Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman as Vice President Al Gore's running mate Monday but
contended that Lieberman had major differences with Gore and that
his conservative record would not help the ticket with core
Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesmen for labor, teachers and environmental and abortion
rights groups enthusiastically spoke out for the Democratic ticket
and brushed off Lieberman's occasional votes against their
positions.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Gov. George W.
Bush, called the Connecticut senator ``a good man who Governor Bush
and Secretary Cheney respect.'' He added, ``From Social Security
reform to missile defense, tort reform to parental notification,
from school choice to affirmative action, Al Gore has chosen a man
whose positions are more similar to Governor Bush's positions than
to his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Mahe, a veteran Republican consultant, said the choice
probably has ``a small political downside'' for Gore because it
``further erodes his support on the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford May, chief spokesman for the Republican National
Committee, called the choice ``a stick in the eye to the Democratic
labor base, the teachers union bosses.'' He said the selection
``does nothing to solidify his base, and he needs to.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 70 percent of Democrats support Gore, according to a new
CBS News Poll, while 88 percent fo Republicans back Bush. May and
Ed Gillespie, a Republican consultant, both said they looked
forward to the first ``Gore-Lieberman debate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota
disagreed. He said, ``I think it will excite the base because it is
a clear indication that Al Gore is determined to win this
election.''
</P>
<P>
   And spokesmen for core Democratic constituencies backed him up.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Feldman, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, called Lieberman a man of ``great integrity, a thinking
man'' and ``a very strong supporter of labor and of education.''
She minimized his votes for school vouchers, saying, ``He voted
just a couple of times for an experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rosenthal, political director of the AFL-CIO, said despite
differences over trade issues and school vouchers, Lieberman ``has
had a very strong voting record on behalf of working families.'' He
said the choice ``helps make this an election about things that
matter to workers: Social Security, health care, education,''
instead of ``muddying the water with a lot of talk about
morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, another major force in the
Democratic coalition, was equally enthusiastic. She called it ``a
bold and excellent choice.'' She said ``It's also a statement about
Gore's commitment to pro-choice values and a woman's right to
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   May's office released a letter it said Lieberman had written in
1989 that included this statement: ``I also support a requirement
that parents of a minor be notified before an abortion is
performed.'' But Michelman dismissed releasing the letter as a
``desperate tactic,'' saying that whatever Lieberman may have
thought then, what mattered was that on two subsequent occasions he
voted in the Senate against parental notification measures
involving abortion.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of applause from Democrats. Al From,
president of the moderate Democratic Leadership Council, called
Lieberman ``a terrific choice for America, the Democratic Party and
the New Democrat Movement.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Senate's leading liberal, Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
said, ``Joe Lieberman is a giant in the Senate. He's worked
brilliantly, effectively and tirelessly to promote the highest
values of public service and integrity in public office.'' Kennedy
cited Lieberman's efforts on issues including the minimum wage, the
environment, education and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, the other Democrat from Connecticut,
called Lieberman's selection ``a reach to the future.'' He recalled
attending the 1960 convention with his parents in Los Angeles,
where Democrats nominated John F. Kennedy, and hearing people
complain, ``You can't elect a Catholic president.'' He said, ``I
think there is some symmetry that 40 years later in that same city
we are going to nominate an Orthodox Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Republicans would not discuss what made the choice
historic: Lieberman's religion. ``I think it's irrelevant,'' May
said.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League,
said that while ``approximately 12 percent of the American people
have strong anti-Semitic views, these people don't vote anyway.''
He said that with at least 70 percent of Jews already voting
Democratic, there was little room for the party to gain simply by
having Lieberman on the ticket. He called the selection ``a wise
choice, a dramatic choice. It says a lot about America. From our
perspective I think it's a milestone.'' .
</P>
<P>
   While the Bush campaign gave the impression that the selection
did not trouble them, Bill Kristol, a Republican strategist and
publisher of The Weekly Standard, said the choice destroyed the
argument that the Democrats were seeking ``a third term for
Clinton-Gore.'' He said Lieberman's selection made the ``character
issue considerably less relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   The news ``stopped the Bush story in its tracks,'' Kristol said.
``It ended the `bounce' today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
