u a BC-RACE-CLASSROOMS-BOS &LR;      08-07 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-CLASSROOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES BENEFITS OF RACIALLY-MIXED CLASSROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Students who attend racially-mixed schools say they are more
willing to live and work in a multi-racial society, according to a
Harvard University study that aims to measure the benefits of
classroom diversity _ and blunt challenges to school desegregation
plans across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Rights Project, a Harvard think tank, says the survey
of high school juniors in the racially-balanced schools of
Louisville, Ky., provides ``strong evidence'' to support districts
that assign students to schools based in part on their race. The
survey was released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Louisville students' opinions on race are very different
and very much more optimistic than what you see in other surveys
about race,'' said Gary Orfield, who heads the Civil Rights
Project.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, an overwhelming majority of the 1,164
students surveyed said that exposure to people of a different race
had given them a greater understanding of that group's views, and
80 percent said their school experience had helped them get along
better with members of other races.
</P>
<P>
   Also, about 90 percent of the students who responded said they
were comfortable or very comfortable discussing controversial
issues related to race _ a far higher percentage than in surveys of
the general population, Orfield said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the students surveyed attended high schools with a black
student population of between 20 and 50 percent. The survey's
response rate was more than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have grown up in an intensely desegregated setting and
they feel very comfortable in it and plan to live and work in it as
adults,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Orfield added that the survey, which will be followed by similar
studies in other districts around the country, tackles the question
posed by a federal appeals court in 1998 when it struck down the
race-based admissions policy of the prestigious Boston Latin
School: exactly how does such a policy advance educational goals?
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Michael McLaughlin, who represented a white Boston
student in challenging the Latin School's race-based admission
policy after she was rejected in favor of 10 minority students with
lower test scores, dismissed the study as ``advocacy research'' and
``pseudo-science.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin noted that the Harvard survey lacks a reliable
control group and fails to account for factors other than classroom
diversity that might have influenced the students' attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to believe what they're going for,'' McLaughlin
said. ``But as a matter of science and law, you will never get
there because it is too easily disproven. We're trying to prove
amorphous concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin insists he supports affirmative action to correct
clear cases of past discrimination. But he noted that the Boston
School Department and other districts use racial diversity as their
goal, yet never define the term.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, he argued, the schools would have to cite specific
percentages of minority students, thus leaving them open to charges
of using quotas, which are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is essentially trying to get a result that cannot be
scientifically evaluated. It's just wishful thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
