<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NEWBORNS-SCREENING-BO     08-07 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBORNS-SCREENING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARYING TREATMENT FOR NEWBORNS COSTING LIVES, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many states are failing to adopt new technologies for testing
blood samples of newborns, allowing children to die needlessly from
undetected rare but devastating diseases, according to a national
task force report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, sponsored by the Health Services and Resources
Administration and the American Academy of Pediatrics, said broad
disease screening of infants belongs on a national agenda even
though states traditionally determine on their own what diseases to
test for. Currently, a baby may become retarded or die from an
undetected disease in one state while another infant across the
state line gets timely treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the March of Dimes immediately criticized the
report for not going further and identifying a ``menu'' of tests
all states should mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is extremely fragmented and in terrible disarray,
so that newborns in the United States aren't well served,'' said
Dr. Donald R. Mattison, medical director of the March of Dimes, in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   It is urgent, he said, that a nationwide testing program be
standardized ``so that every single baby that's born with a disease
for which there is treatment has an opportunity to have that
disease detected or treatment.'' About 4 million babies are born
each year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report was of necessity ``a compromise'' among members who
varied in their enthusiasm for expanded screening, Dr. Harvey Levy
of Children's Hospital in Boston, a member of the task force,
sponsored by the Health Services and Resources Administration and
the American Academy of Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   He echoed the report's call for a ``national consensus'' on
disease tests, but noted that many state health officials ``are
very jealous about their prerogatives in newborn screening,'' and
don't want outside interference.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward McCabe, cochair of the task force, said that he
welcomed the March of Dimes' criticism, but defended the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time it's been stated that there should be a
national agenda'' on an issue that has traditionally been
controlled by stastes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 rare metabolic diseases can now be detected through
high-tech analysis of a blood sample taken at birth. In many cases,
they cause severe retardation or developmental disorders or death,
but if treated promptly with special diets or medication, the
infants can lead fairly normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is a pioneer in newborn screening, and over the
last two years has expanded its list of required tests to about 30.
The additional tests can be carried out because of a relatively new
technology called Tandem Mass Spectrometry, or TMS. Some states
only test for three or four or five diseases, and may not employ
the most reliable test methods, said the task force report, which
appears in a special supplement to the August issue of the journal
Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   A Maine couple, Alex and Susan Millett, said Monday they are
petitioning the state to require testing for a rare disease that
wasn't immediately diagnosed in their daughter, Gabrielle, who is
now 6 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Susan Millett said, blood from Maine newborns is
sent for testing to Massachusetts, where the test in question _ for
a disease called proprionic acidemia _ is part of the mandatory
set. But because Maine doesn't require it, no one notified the
Milletts that Gabrielle was affected.
</P>
<P>
   When the newborn was lethargic, not eating well and vomiting, no
doctor suspected the disease until two weeks later when Gabrielle
was hospitalized with seizures and became comatose. Medication and
a special low-protein diet would have prevented much of the brain
damage she suffered, said Susan Millett Monday. And if her newborn
heelstick blood sample had been tested for the disease, ``we
wouldn't have gone two weeks just thinking she was sleepy,''
Millett said.
</P>
<P>
   The March of Dimes, a voluntary health agency dedicated to
preventing birth defects, recommends a core group of eight
screening tests for all newborns. They are for PKU
(phenylketonuria), congenital hypothyroidism, congenital adrenal
hyperplasia, biotinidase deficiency, maple syrup urine disease,
galactosemia, homocystinuria and sickle cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, sickle cell anemia is the most common, affecting 1
baby in 400, and the rarest is homocystinuria, affecting 1 in
275,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
