<HEADER>
A5096 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NEWHOUS     08-07 1729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC PLATFORM HISTORY PROVIDES BAROMETER OF EMERGING
POLITICAL
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, AUGUST 7, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of members of the Democratic Platform Committee
meeting in July (NNS1) 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They call themselves the world's oldest political
party, and the Democrats bear the burden of their own history.
</P>
<P>
   The very first Democratic platform in 1840 supported slavery and
forbade the federal government to undertake any ``general system of
internal improvements'' for the American people.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the party's philosophy since then is chronicled
in a century and a half of subsequent platforms, which stand as
barometers of changing public opinion and emerging trends across
most of the nation's political history.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Democrats became champions of civil rights and
advocates of federal action on every front, as well as federal
spending to improve education, nutrition, housing, employment,
health and transportation; fight poverty; raise living standards;
and create the Social Security system to ease retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The record also shows the Democrats hopping from one side to the
other on a wide variety of issues right up to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Party platforms have called for higher taxes and lower taxes,
less defense spending and more defense spending, denying entry to
immigrants and welcoming immigrants, isolating China and bringing
China into the world community, states' rights and civil rights. At
different times, the Democrats have been for and against the use of
military force, for balanced budgets and for deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sentient entity called the Democratic Party, no
disciplined, coherent party structure,'' said Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass. ``It's a lot of competing, conflicting people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in the last 100 years particularly, the Democrats
have managed to forge a distinct identity around certain repeated
principles that contradict those the party proclaimed in its
earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Democratic Party that first called in the platform of
1908 for an income tax on individuals and corporations. In the same
platform and successive ones, the Democrats firmly allied
themselves with organized labor, endorsed the eight-hour workday,
proposed creation of the Labor Department, asserted that ``there
should be no abridgment of the right of wage earners to organize
for the protection of wages and the improvement of labor
conditions,'' and rejected claims that labor unions should be
regarded ``as illegal combinations in restraint of trade.''
Establishment of a minimum wage and then periodic demands to
increase it became staples of Democratic platforms, along with the
principle of overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   Health care has been another perennial platform issue for the
Democrats. The party proposed a national bureau of public health in
1908 and federal tuberculosis sanitariums for the needy in 1916,
and promised in the platform of 1928 to ``appropriate all monies
necessary'' for federal research to find cures for cancer, polio
and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The 1948 platform proposed a federal program of disability and
sickness benefits and 13 weeks of maternity benefits for working
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   By 1952, the Democrats sounded alarms over the rising cost of
medical care and promised to pour federal money into research,
medical training, hospital construction, preventive medicine and
rural health services.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960 platform called for a federal program to provide health
care to all retired persons without a means test. ``This has first
The addition of prescription drug benefits to Medicare was in the
party's 1972 platform, which also called for a program of universal
national health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Early Democratic platforms generally toed a line in support of
states' rights -- essentially a euphemism for discrimination and
segregation. But in 1948, divided Democrats departed from that
tradition and, led by Hubert H. Humphrey of Minnesota, adopted
strong new civil rights language committing the party to efforts to
``eradicate all racial, religious and economic discrimination,''
and declaring that ``minorities must have the right to live, the
right to work, the right to vote, and the full and equal protection
of the laws on a basis of equality with all citizens as guaranteed
by the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Southern delegates refused to support the Democratic
presidential nominee, Harry S. Truman, because of his civil rights
program, and a Southern faction known as Dixiecrats broke away to
nominate Gov. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina instead.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Irony abounds in the policy gyrations of Democrats seeking to
synchronize themselves with the swinging pendulum of politics.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960 Democrats who nominated John F. Kennedy for president
adopted a platform vow to beef up the Internal Revenue Service and
crack down on tax cheats. ``We will add enforcement personnel and
develop new techniques of enforcement to collect revenue which is
now being lost through evasion,'' the party thundered.
</P>
<P>
   By 1976, Democrats were banging out a different tune. ``We will
protect the rights of all taxpayers against oppressive procedures,
harassment and invasions of privacy by the Internal Revenue
Service,'' the platform said.
</P>
<P>
   The current opposition of President Clinton and congressional
Democrats to Republican bills repealing the estate tax, the
marriage penalty and taxation of Social Security benefits seems at
odds with some of the party's earlier platform pledges.
</P>
<P>
   A 1980 plank declared that the Democratic Party would ``oppose
any effort to tamper with the Social Security system by cutting or
taxing benefits as a violation of the contract the American
government made with its people.'' The Democratic Congress passed a
bill taxing Social Security benefits in 1993 and Clinton signed the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The 1980 platform pledged to ``end tax discrimination that
penalizes married working couples'' -- Clinton vetoed a
GOP-sponsored bill last weekend -- and the 1976 platform said
Democrats would ``overhaul federal estate and gift taxes to provide
an effective and equitable structure to promote tax justice and
alleviate some of the legitimate problems faced by farmers, small
businessmen and women and others who would otherwise be forced to
liquidate assets in order to pay the tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has rendered once-respectable party positions politically
incorrect, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, immigration and the platform of 1900. The
Democratic Party declared itself in favor of ``continuance and
strict enforcement of the Chinese exclusion law, and its
application to the same classes of all Asiatic races.''
</P>
<P>
   But other old planks could fit perfectly into this year's
political debate:
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform: ``We pledge the Democratic Party to the
enactment of a law prohibiting any corporation from contributing to
a campaign fund and any individual from contributing any amount
above a reasonable maximum.'' That's from the platform of 1912.
</P>
<P>
   Narcotics: ``Recognizing in narcotics addiction, especially the
spreading of heroin addiction among youth, a grave peril to America
and to the human race, we pledge ourselves vigorously to take
against it all legitimate and proper measures for education,
control and for suppression at home and abroad.'' -- 1924
</P>
<P>
   Family values: ``We hold these truths to be self-evident -- that
government in a modern civilization has certain inescapable
obligations to its citizens, among which are: protection of the
family and the home.'' -- 1936
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity: ``We have achieved the longest and strongest
peacetime prosperity in modern history.'' -- 1964
</P>
<P>
   Global trade: ``World trade is essential to economic stability.
The growing interdependence of nations, particularly in economic
affairs, is an established fact of contemporary life.'' -- 1968
</P>
<P>
   Guns: ``Promote the passage and enforcement of effective
federal, state and local gun control legislation.'' -- 1968
</P>
<P>
   Medicare: ``Medical care for the aged should be expanded to
include the costs of prescription drugs.'' -- 1968
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, Democratic platforms heralded a steady parade
of public policy concerns leading to federal action.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, when the nation was mired in recession, the Democratic
platform urged the government to launch public works projects to
create jobs for the unemployed, and by 1940 the party's platform
asserted ``the obligation of government to provide work for
deserving workers who cannot be absorbed by private industry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the 1932 Democratic platform call for unemployment and
old age insurance that was precursor to the Social Security Act
four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action as a remedy for past discrimination was born
in the Democratic platform of 1972, along with support for
multiculturalism, bilingual education and legal services for the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic platforms have expanded the national political agenda
to include the principles of economic and social justice, disaster
assistance, farm programs, support for the arts, consumer rights,
occupational health and safety, and the rights of children, women,
poor people, the disabled and the mentally retarded. In 1972, ``the
right to be different'' was a platform plank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing. If you look back over this century's platforms,
there is a populist thread, a constant theme of Democrats standing
up and fighting for others,'' said Democratic National Chairman Joe
Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, modern Democratic platforms ranged from support of
abortion rights and demands for ``full warranties'' on new cars, to
warnings about global warning and ozone depletion and the
designation of tobacco as ``the single greatest threat to the
health of children.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the 1996 Democratic platform, echoing Clinton, declared
that ``The era of big government is over.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past is prologue, don't bet on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
