<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-ECON-ART-NYT &LR;      08-07 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ECON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREA REPLACES TOP OFFICIALS IN EFFORT TO GET ECONOMY ON
TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Worried about the slow pace of financial
reforms in South Korea and the stubbornly high debts of its big
businesses and banks, President Kim Dae-jung replaced almost half
of his 19-member cabinet Monday, including the nation's top
economic officials.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, coming halfway though Kim's term of office, were
almost entirely related to the performance of South Korea's
economy, which has made a remarkable recovery since the severe
economic crisis that began nearly three years ago but lately has
been showing signs of increased stress.
</P>
<P>
   Kim selected the new cabinet members based on what his
spokesman, Park Joon-young, called the degree of
``reform-mindedness and expertise under the belief that we must
gain national competitiveness and enter the ranks of advanced
nations in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet shuffle is the second in seven months after Kim
replaced half of his ministers in January ahead of the nation's
April general election.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant change in the cabinet was the appointment
of Jin Nyum, 59, who had been serving as planning and budget
minister, charged with privatizing the nation's state-run
companies, as the new minister of finance and economy.
</P>
<P>
   Jin replaced Lee Hun-jai, who had been appointed in the last
cabinet shuffle. Lee has been criticized for the slow progress in
reducing debts at banks and major business groups and in lowering
control by the founding family members of the nation's powerful
business conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   ``After implementing the first round of corporate and financial
reforms, the government failed to play a strict supervisory role,''
said Nam Jooha, professor of finance and economy at Sogang
University. ``That has led to fears of another economic crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his seven-month tenure as finance minister, Lee was head
of the Financial Supervisory Commission, which has been overseeing
the restructuring of the nation's business conglomerates and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   During the early stages of the government's reform drive shortly
after the economic crisis in late 1997, Lee's strict enforcement of
the government's corporate restructuring plans won him praises from
the foreign business community. Also this week, Lee was
hospitalized for acute appendicitis, and he received news that he
had been dismissed while still in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The most high-profile sign that the previous cabinet had not
been dealing effectively with South Korea's economic problems was
its struggle with the Hyundai Group, the nation's largest business
group. Hyundai has resisted efforts to get the conglomerate's
founder, Chung Ju-yung, and his family, to loosen controlling
stakes in their industrial empire. Despite continued government
pressure and threats from creditor banks to seek immediate
repayment of huge amounts of loans, the Hyundai Group has yet to
produce a plan that promises a reduction of Chung's stake to levels
acceptable to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the past, there has been a tendency for
confrontation,'' said James Rooney, former president and chief
executive of Templeton Trust Investment Management Co. in South
Korea. ``I think Jin Nyum is known for being more conciliatory.
There will be more cajoling and encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Jin had served as the chairman of the Planning and Budget
Commission since 1998 and became minister in May last year, when
the commission was raised in status to a ministry. He also served
as the court-appointed manager of Kia Motors Corp. in 1997, and was
responsible for rescuing that automaker from a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While Jin vowed ``to achieve concrete results within five months
to a year,'' investors did not seem impressed with his appointment.
The Korea Composite Stock Price Index, a barometer of the country's
economic mood, fell 4.85 percent. The new cabinet faces a difficult
task. Despite South Korea's efforts to clean up its bad debts and
untangle decades of murky finances among business conglomerates,
domestic banks are still struggling with billions of dollars of
loans that have not been repaid.
</P>
<P>
   The international debt ratings company, Standard &AMP; Poor's, said
recently that the government would need to spend about $126 billion
or one-third of South Korea's gross domestic product, to clean up
the bad debts in its financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   The president also replaced Lee Yong-keun, the chairman of the
Financial Supervisory Commission, which oversees the restructuring
of the nation's business groups and banks.
</P>
<P>
   The newly appointed chairman of the commission is Lee
Keun-young, 63, chairman of state-run Korea Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also spent 20 years in the finance ministry's tax division
and is credited with playing an important role in the dismantling
of Daewoo Group, once South Korea's second-largest conglomerate,
which owes creditors at least $80 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
