<P>
   &UR; GORE-LIEBERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans three pages of stories and photos on Al
Gore's selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LIEBERMAN (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Ledeall: Vice President Al
Gore picked Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut to be his running
mate on Monday, putting a Jewish candidate on a national ticket for
the first time in history. Gore will not formally announce his
selection until Tuesday. Lieberman, 58, is known chiefly on the
national stage as the first Democrat to condemn President Clinton
during the Monica Lewinsky scandal, branding his behavior
``immoral.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3,8,10,11,15.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-PROFILE (Undated) _ Man-in-the-news profile of the
vice presidential candidate. By Robert D. McFadden. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-ASSESS (Washington) _ After struggling mightily for
two years to move out of President Clinton's shadow, Vice President
Al Gore, in a bold but risky choice of a running mate, effectively
thrust Clinton and impeachment front and center in the 2000
presidential campaign. It was clear from the Republican convention
last week that the Republicans will not be timid in making the
moral lapses of Clinton a basic subtext of their campaign. The
thinking of the Gore camp is that by picking Lieberman, the most
vociferous critic of Clinton during the impeachment proceedings,
Gore will confront such criticism head on and underscore his
independence from the President. While no one can predict how the
Lieberman choice will play, one thing is certain: it was not a
play-it-safe choice as was Gov. George W. Bush's selection of Dick
Cheney. There several obvious plusses to the Lieberman choice _ but
there are also several minuses. A news analysis by Richard L.
Berke. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RECORD (Washington) _ In two terms in the Senate,
Joseph Lieberman has often taken positions at odds with Vice
President Al Gore and important constituencies of the Democratic
party on school vouchers, regulation of managed care, capital gains
taxes and product liability. But he sided with the Clinton
administration on all important budget votes, and unlike many other
Democrats, supported the administration's positions on trade and
welfare. His views are completely in tune with the vice president's
on abortion, the environment, gun control and gay rights. And he
usually supported the Clinton administration on foreign policy
issues. By David E. Rosenbaum. (1125 words)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-REACT (Washington) _ Republicans reacted to the
selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as Vice President Al Gore's
running mate Monday by praising the choice but contending that
Lieberman had major differences with Gore and his conservative
votes would not help the ticket with core Democratic voters. But
spokesmen for labor, teachers, environmental and abortion rights
groups enthusiastically spoke out for Gore and brushed off his
occasional votes against their positions as unimportant. By Adam
Clymer. (1125 words)
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RIGHT (Undated) _ In Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Al Gore
has managed to choose as his running mate an Orthodox Jew whom many
Christians _ and especially conservative evangelicals _ regard an
ally on many social and moral issues. Although he wears a yarmulke
on his head, Lieberman has been seen by some Christians as a
kindred spirit for his willingness to wear his religion on his
sleeve. His talk of the Talmud inspiring both his values and his
vote has often been cited by those Christians who believe the Bible
ought to guide public policy. By Laurie Goodstein. (990 words)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-JEWS (New York) _ Regardless of political leanings or
depth of spirituality, American Jews expressed great pride Monday
that one of their own, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, had
been picked by Vice President Al Gore to be his running mate. By
Clyde Haberman. (990 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-CLINTON (Undated) _ In a Senate speech on Sept. 3,
1998, Sen. Joseph Lieberman sharply criticized President Clinton's
conduct in the Monica Lewinsky matter, but he voted against
impeaching the president, giving his reasons in a statement
released on Feb. 11, 1999. Exerpts from these two statements. (1750
words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ANNOUNCE (Undated) _ The Gore campaign is getting all the
publicity they can out of the selection of Joseph Lieberman as a
running mate. They're stretching it out over two days. By Peter
Marks. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
