<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-ANALYSIS0808-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore's VP pick rivals Clinton, not Cheney
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Baxter
</P>
<P>
   c 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - With as long as they've had to look at the short list,
Vice President Al Gore wasn't likely to throw the Republicans off
balance with his choice of a running mate. But in picking Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, Gore may have achieved the closest thing to
leverage he could have hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman isn't the anti-Cheney some in the Bush camp thought
Gore might choose: a Democrat with youth and pizazz to counter Gov.
George W. Bush's choice of former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Any of the others on the short list _ Sen. John Edwards of North
Carolina, Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana and Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts, would have been more of a counter to Cheney than
Lieberman. Instead, Lieberman can be thought of as a counter to
Gore's former running mate, President Clinton _ and a finely
balanced one. The Connecticut Democrat was the first leader in his
party to denounce Clinton's personal behavior during the Monica
Lewinsky affair, but he also holds one of the president's old jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his fifth year, Lieberman holds the record for the
longest term at the helm of the Democratic Leadership Council, the
centrist, business-friendly organization that Clinton chaired when
he was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   That association gives Lieberman a claim on Clinton's economic
legacy, without an endorsement of his peccadillos _ which is where
the Gore campaign wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   If his advantages are so obvious now that he's picked, why
didn't Lieberman stand out more on the short list?
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the first Jew ever chosen for the vice-presidential
nomination, which may have seemed a deficit a couple of days ago,
when Democratic National Committee chairman Ed Rendell remarked
that Lieberman would be a ``slam-dunk'' if he wasn't Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's the nominee, however, there doesn't seem much
downside, and Rendell's comment sounds in retrospect a bit much
like a setup line. The ticket might lose some votes simply because
he is Jewish, but Lieberman will be an asset to the Democrats in
those states _ California, Illinois, Florida and New York _ where
they have to begin gaining ground back from the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is Orthodox, which will set off a quite separate
conversation within the American Jewish community. For the rest of
America, the biggest upshot of this is that in an age of
considerable lip service to ``faith traditions,'' he is one
candidate who actively practices one.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Lieberman may not have been high on the radar
screens, however, is that for whatever his advantages, he doesn't
leap out as a choice for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting the the 58-year-old former Connecticut attorney
general insures that this will be the first presidential election
in a decade with no big generational differences between the two
tickets, and that deprives Gore-Lieberman of part of the excitement
the Clinton-Gore ticket generated.
</P>
<P>
   In his younger days, Lieberman organized anti-war rallies, but
the mature man is identified among the Washington scolds who decry
violent video games, dirty rap lyrics and other signs of moral
decline. That's part of the reason he's a good antidote to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't be a scold on the stump. How well will Lieberman
play with all those crowds to whom Clinton played so well? We
should know shortly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
