<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VP-RELIGION08-COX     08-07 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-RELIGION08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religion no conflict with job, senator says
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The most important Jewish holidays fall during the
grueling campaign sprint between Labor Day and the election. Don't
expect Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), an Orthodox Jew, to choose
politics over worship.
</P>
<P>
   But if elected vice president, Lieberman already has made it
clear that he will not set aside his duties because of religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always tried to separate pure politics on the Sabbath,
which I don't do, from governmental responsibility,'' he said in an
interview with The New York Times last month. ``It seems to me my
religion, as I understand it, not only permits me to fulfill
important work associated with being a public servant, but actually
requires me to do so because people are depending on me. I don't
see that as an issue at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, he has cast votes on Saturday, the Jewish
Sabbath, although he has walked to work to adhere to restrictions
on using cars on the Sabbath. Of the three main branches of Judaism
in the United States _ Reform, Conservative and Orthodox, the
Orthodox are the most observant.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman will be the first Jew on a major party's presidential
ticket. If the past is any guide, he will not campaign on the
Sabbath or on Jewish holidays.
</P>
<P>
   When Lieberman ran against Republican incumbent Sen. Lowell
Weicker in 1988, he did not attend the Connecticut Democratic
convention that nominated him. Instead, he sent a videotaped speech
to the Saturday gathering.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 17 campaign days that year between Labor Day and the
election, and he won a very close election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you have a politician to whom visibly something other
than politics is important,'' said Rabbi Barry Freundel, leader of
the Kesher Israel Synagogue that Lieberman attends in Georgetown.
``But he is not a guy who comes up to you and says, `Hi, I'm an
Orthodox Jew.'''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Jewish groups praised Lieberman's selection as a
milestone in American politics, and several political scientists
said Lieberman's religion would matter only to a very small segment
of the electorate that already was unlikely to vote for Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup organization, which has measured Americans'
willingness to vote for Jewish candidates for the past 60 years,
found last year that 92 percent of Americans said they would vote
for a Jew for president.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains some uncertainty about how the nation will
react to the prospect of a Jew being a heartbeat away from the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can calculate the effect of having a Jew
on the ticket,'' Democratic Party Chairman Ed Rendell, who is
Jewish, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   And James Thurber, a political science professor at American
University, said Lieberman's views about Israel and the Middle East
may be a legitimate issue in the campaign. But Lieberman's strong
support for Israel places him with the vast majority of his Senate
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's rise to national prominence may serve to heighten
the nation's awareness of what it means to be Jewish, beyond
expressions and ethnic foods that have become American staples.
</P>
<P>
   On that front, there apparently is some work to do.
</P>
<P>
   A Southern Democrat jumped to Lieberman's defense Monday, saying
Lieberman's religion will not count against him in the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Americans do not care, Sen. John Breaux (D-La.) said, where
someone ``goes to church on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
