<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-SPACECOWBOYS-REVIEW-A     08-07 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACECOWBOYS-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SPACECOWBOYS-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `SPACE COWBOYS' GOES WHERE PLOTS HAVE GONE BEFORE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In space, no one can hear you yawn.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a good thing, too, especially when it comes to
(beginitalic)Space Cowboys(enditalic), a by-the-numbers action
picture that dusts off every old saw in the tool shed.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe a movie with Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee
Jones and Donald Sutherland can be this dull and silly. But
(beginitalic)Space Cowboys (enditalic)manages it easily, mostly
through a painfully formulaic, predictable script.
</P>
<P>
   Example: At the beginning of the film, younger versions of
Eastwood and Jones parachute out of a crippled plane, after Jones'
character pulls a wild stunt. So what does Clint do when they land?
Naturally, he walks right over and punches Jones in the kisser.
Isn't that cute?
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue is so cliched that the Loud Plot Explainer sitting
behind me managed to deliver every punch line before the stars
could. And unlike the characters in the movie, this guy was no
rocket scientist.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, (beginitalic)Space Cowboys(enditalic) is like a
comfortable old shoe. We know how things are going to play out, and
it's supposed to be fun to watch Eastwood squint and deliver his
lines in a gravelly voice as he and the gang go through the
motions.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood plays Frank Corvin, a former test pilot and engineer
who's called on to repair a wayward Russian satellite, because it
employs an obsolete guidance system that only he understands. Only
problem is, Frank is pushing 70, much like the other members of his
team, who were set to go into space in the late '50s, only to be
passed over for a monkey.
</P>
<P>
   They include flashy pilot Hawk Hawkins (Jones), astrophysicist
Jerry O'Neil (Sutherland) and robotics expert Tank Sullivan (James
Garner). Yes, we know Garner did a bad movie named
(beginitalic)Tank(enditalic), and here he is as Tank again. How
clever.
</P>
<P>
   Frank's foil is NASA bureaucrat Bob Gerson (James Cromwell).
Frank and Gerson spend a lot of time arguing in Gerson's dimly lit
office, when his assistant (Marcia Gay Harden) is not giving dull
briefings in a dimly lit conference room.
</P>
<P>
   The movie spends an inordinate amount of time with boilerplate
(beginitalic)Armageddon(enditalic)-type setup: Frank assembles his
team members, who are scattered around the country. They are all
doing supposedly hilarious things (Garner is a preacher, Sutherland
a roller coaster designer, etc.), and Frank must coax them back
into the space program.
</P>
<P>
   The training sequences bring the occasional chuckle. Frank and
his fellow senior citizens have to pass NASA's tough physical
tests, and there are plenty of scenes of them doubled over on the
running track or trying to outdo those whippersnappers in the
weight room.
</P>
<P>
   The film is also filled with all those tired arguments, which we
know can only end one way. Frank initially turns down NASA and then
shows up; Hawk turns down Frank and then changes his mind. Gerson
tells Frank he can't go, when the whole audience knows there is no
movie if Clint Eastwood doesn't end up in outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Once they get into space, the movie gets really silly, with plot
holes you could drive the space shuttle through. But at this point,
you are so anesthetized by the tinny dialogue and deadly dull
setup, you may not even notice. The ending is just as predictable,
and there are at least three major plot points left unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
