<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      08-07 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WEBS&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DAVE WALKER'S WEB SITE &AMP; MAGAZINE REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (RETRASMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Dave Walker's reviews of a Web site and current
magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   The peak months of the hurricane season begin with August, and
though we're more concerned here with blowing dust and palm fronds
than storms of mass destruction, the National Hurricane Center's
official site offers armchair meteorologists as much data as they
can handle. No, more. In addition to up-to-the-minute satellite
images, landlocked storm buffs will find tracking charts and
detailed accounts of aircraft reconnaissance missions as well as
long-term forecasts. (According to the center, conditions have
aligned to make this season a busy one, at least in the Atlantic.)
If the Weather Channel isn't interactive enough for you, this could
become a favorite bookmark.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES
</P>
<P>
   ``PSYCHOLOGY TODAY''
</P>
<P>
   In the cover story, Robert J. Sternberg asks readers to cast
themselves in their own love story. The idea: ``As much as
psychologists have attempted to explain the mysteries of love
through scientific laws and theories, it turns out that the best
mirrors of romantic experience may be (beginitalic)Wuthering
Heights, Casablanca (enditalic)and (beginitalic)General
Hospital(enditalic)(beginitalic),(enditalic)'' he writes. A reader
quiz helps decide your type - you know, cop or comedian, princess
or martyr. We took the quiz on our lunch hour and discovered that
our type is one of the lesser (beginitalic)Chicken Run
(enditalic)hens. (beginitalic)Bawk(enditalic)! Other features
include a short list of a few new concepts in infant development
and an iffy examination of intuition headlined, ``Do we really have
a sixth sense?'' Later, Roger Fouts confesses that one of his
oldest and dearest friends is a chimpanzee.
</P>
<P>
   ``UTNE READER''
</P>
<P>
   Staying rooted in a restless world is this issue's theme, and
the centerpiece is Bill Kauffman's celebration of provincialism. He
picks big government, big business and Hollywood as the culprits in
our drift toward soul-sapping rootlessness. ``For almost 60 years,
the placeless have waged war on the rooted, stealing their
children, devastating their neighborhoods, wiping out local
peculiarities and idiosyncrasies,'' he writes. ``What we have is
class war - though this war has never been acknowledged because the
casualties are places and attachments and sentiments; nothings,
really; everythings, in fact - waged by the mobile against the
immobile, by the cosmopolitan against the rooted, and the winners
are the professionals, people so depraved that they would actually
move to a different place for mere money. How bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``INC.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to back profiles reveal both ends of the CEO spectrum. The
first shows how Paul Eichen has changed his life by building a
company ``whose only reason for being is to make life good,''
writes Michael Hopkins. Eichen's Rokenbok Toy Co. operates north of
San Diego employing lots of north of San Diego values, such as a
casual dress codes and rampant collegiality. Mellow, man. Then flip
a couple of pages and meet supersalesman Pat Cavanaugh, who can
work the phone to the tune of 200 calls a day and who pesters
underlings with things-to-do-Monday voice mails on Sunday night.
Manic, man. Elsewhere, there's a cool piece about entrepreneurs who
have built their own museums, including Russ Manoog, founder of the
American Sanitary Plumbing Museum in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``NEW REPUBLIC''
</P>
<P>
   Decrying limited commercial-network coverage of this summer's
political conventions, the editors launch their Page 9 editorial by
recalling the 1934 Communications Act, which granted broadcasters
use of the airwaves on the promise that they serve the ``public
interest, convenience and necessity.'' Nostalgia has its place -
that pony left the barn a long time ago {ndash} yet the point
remains: By abandoning their civic obligation to cover, uh, civics,
the nets have become negligent corporate citizens. Meanwhile, the
cover story profiles Bill Daley, recently drafted to reorient Al
Gore's campaign for the general election. We'll pause here for
network newscast devotees to ask ``who?'' Glad you asked. The
youngest child of legendary Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley, he's
``the most creative operative in the Democratic Party,'' says the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: Please credit Dave Walker.
</P>
</TEXT>
