<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-FAMILYCIRCUS-AZR &LR;      08-07 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILYCIRCUS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-FAMILYCIRCUS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BIL KEANE'S `FAMILY CIRCUS' INCITES SATIRE(a) 
 &HT;    (RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent flap over (beginitalic)Family Circus(enditalic) and
pool safety serves as a reminder that Bil Keane's seemingly gentle
comic strip long has been a hotbed of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The strip in question - depicting the strip's daddy, Bill,
paying scant attention to his pool-paddling brood - caused a
firestorm of protest from local firefighters, and Keane quickly
altered the strip for poster reprint by adding a cautionary
caption.
</P>
<P>
   But the scuttlebutt echoed strongly the impassioned reaction to
the (beginitalic)Family Circus (enditalic)compilation
(beginitalic)What Does This Say?
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)Reader emotion flowed onto the reader-input screens
of Amazon.com and was so memorable that the online retailer
included the typed tussle in recent anniversary celebration of
wacky reader exchanges. The collective manifesto - which admittedly
may be tongue in cheek - is still archived in full on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keane is a genius,'' writes one correspondent.
``(beginitalic)Family Circus (enditalic)is a deconstruction of
modern suburban emasculation - sort of like the movie
(beginitalic)American Beauty(enditalic) but far more clever. I
offer my apologies to Mr. Keane. I am simply not good enough to be
in the presence of his work. I will now poke out my eyes with my
mother's brooches, such is the shame I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Another correspondent calls the strip ``the cartoon equivalent
of the faceless black monolith in the first segment of
(beginitalic)2001: A Space Odyssey (enditalic)that begets
technology and civilization among a race of ape-men. {ellipsis}
These original masterpieces have lost none of their stark,
visionary power.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another digs for the political subtext ruling the world of
Billy, Dolly, Jeffy, et al.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nihilists and existentialists, look out!'' the writer writes.
``The profound truths conveyed through the heartwarming, hilarious
predicaments of four whimsical moppets and their parents will rock
your world view! Secular humanists, manicurists, clergy and lawyers
alike will (laugh) out loud or --at least chuckle in
self-realization at the sheer depth of humanity presented in Bil
Keane's tours de force. Belongs on the shelf with Kant, the Bible,
Nietzsche, Jung {ellipsis} to delve into again and again. Sure to
age gracefully and not to be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   One critic writes that though (beginitalic)Family Circus
(enditalic)''was once viewed as a lighthearted romp through
middle-class society. Deeper study might reveal the Marxist
overtones of the comic. This is exactly the kind of message that we
want the youth of America to absorb. We want young girls to realize
that even after many years it's never too late for a new hairstyle.
Change and revolution is coming, and Bil Keane is leading the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane, reached at his Paradise Valley home, said he seldom
objects to (beginitalic)Family Circus (enditalic)satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They select the (beginitalic)Family Circus (enditalic)because
of its innocence and its (depiction of ) American family life and
apple pie and motherhood,'' he said. ``It's the perfect target.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that 188 million people read it daily gives it an
armor that they hardly can pierce, and to me it's always flattering
they feel that the feature is known enough for them to take
potshots.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at dave.walker(a)arizonarepublic.com or
602-444-8625.
</P>
