<HEADER>
A5141 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     08-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV13-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV13 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 13, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's EVERYDAY ETHICS column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the EVERYDAY ETHICS column _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CO-OP SNOOP
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a member of my co-op board. A prospective buyer's tax
return showed that she had deducted the entire cost of her Ivy
League MBA, a clear violation of the tax laws. I am appalled by her
deceit and wonder if it is a legitimate reason to reject her
application. Should I report her to the IRS?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, New York
</P>
<P>
   A: You should neither reject her application nor report her to
the IRS, at least not based on what you've described. You have no
idea if her deduction was deceitful or an honest error _ or if
indeed it was an error at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If education or training is undertaken to qualify you for a
new profession, it is not deductible,'' says Curtis Arluck, a
partner in the accounting firm Weikart Associates. ``But if it's
further training within your field, it may be deductible.'' Either
way, the case should be settled by the IRS, not a co-op board. And
the IRS has every opportunity to do so if it wishes: the woman
declared her tuition on her tax forms, after all.
</P>
<P>
   While you have a legitimate interest in assessing a prospective
buyer's financial strength, you should use each applicant's private
information for that purpose only, not to snare tax cheats or
otherwise clean up Dodge City. Unless you learn that an applicant
is engaged in a serious and ongoing crime _ a string of grisly
murders, say, or touring with 'N Sync _ then you must respect her
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When my eyeglasses needed a new screw to hold the lens in
place, I went to the village optician. He fixed them and declined
my offer to pay. Ten minutes later, I noticed the lenses were
cracked. I presume he just made them too tight. I feel he should
pay at least part of the replacement cost, but since I did not pay
for his services, am I wrong to hold him responsible?
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Rogavin, Westchester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: If the optician broke your glasses, he should replace the
lenses. He might argue that his refusal to accept payment
transformed your encounter from a commercial transaction to a
favor, and you can't hold someone accountable for a favor. He'd be
wrong to think so. This was a professional service _ probably
rendered with the thought of your repeat business _ and he should
stand behind his work. Some opticians who do free repairs post an
at-your-own-risk sign, but if that's his policy he should make it
clear before starting the job.
</P>
<P>
   Why not go by the shop and talk to him? However, if he declines
to cover your cost, don't be surprised, and if he tries to put you
in pink rhinestone harlequin frames, don't be persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When newsstand dealers discard unsold papers, they tear off
part of the front page for reimbursement, bundle the papers and
place them by the garbage, presumably for recycling. One day I
undid the bundle and helped myself to a paper. The newsstand
attendant told me to put it back. I said that it was garbage and
that I'd return after he left and take it. Was I wrong?
</P>
<P>
   _ N.R., New York
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. No matter how you figure it, you are stealing from
someone _ the publisher, the news dealer or the recycler. Further,
the continued existence of newspapers, something you seem to value,
depends on readers buying a paper. Why not try that? Incidentally,
all of us who have written for a paper have heard it called
``garbage,'' but it still hurts our feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist(at)nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
