u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      08-07 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON, UNIONS SAID MAKING SLOW PROGRESS IN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As pickets rallied Monday, Verizon Communications and its unions
moved closer to resolving a two-day-old strike over job security
and the unionization of wireless employees.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout by 85,000 telephone customer service representatives
and technicians left millions of consumers in a dozen Eastern
states with delays in directory assistance and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, 2,500 customers lost telephone service in the
Bronx, and an additional 600 reported no service in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company confirmed that five incidents of
vandalism occurred at Verizon facilities in New York City, but it
was not clear Monday whether the damage was related to the strike.
A company spokesman said several cables were cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers staged mass picketing and rallies
at dozens of corporate sites on the East Coast that each drew
between 350 and 1,200 telephone operators, customer service
representatives, and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Union workers struck Verizon, which was created by the merger of
Bell Atlantic and GTE, at 12 a.m. Sunday, affecting some 25 million
consumers from Maine to Virginia. Talks between management and
labor ended at 1 a.m. Monday, and resumed seven hours later, a
company official said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said considerable progress had been made since the
parties reached an impasse over labor groups' push to unionize
3,500 nonunion workers at Verizon Wireless, a subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA and IBEW are seeking contract language that would allow
them to use card check neutrality agreements. Under such a plan,
workers at the wireless unit would automatically gain bargaining
rights after a majority sign union cards. This method bypasses
union elections, which can be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues on the table include outsourcing and the transfer
of technical and customer service jobs from the East to
right-to-work cities in the South, where union representation is
not as high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finding the talks to be productive, and we are
encouraged,'' Verizon spokesman Steve Marcus said. ``Although we
still have to work through some serious issues, we are hopeful that
we will be able to resolve these issues and reach an agreement on a
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap has definitely closed,'' noted Steve Early, an
international representative for the CWA in New England. ``The
company made an improved offer to try and settle outstanding issues
involving 42 union technicians at Verizon Wireless in New York, and
details for card check neutrality are being hammered out.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, negotiators broke into small groups and began working on
the renewal of a contract for 42 wireless technicians in New York
who are represented by the IBEW. The workers are the only unionized
members in the company's fast-growing wireless division.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials have complained that wireless workers earn less
and receive a smaller benefits package than their unionized
colleagues in the company's traditional wireline division.
</P>
<P>
   Details pertaining to the outsourcing of work involving the
installation of high-speed digital subscriber lines in Pennsylvania
and New York have not yet been finalized. However, negotiators
Monday were trying to determine whether the company would use
independent contractors or a separate unit of lower-paid union
members to install DSL service lines. The latter would be employees
of Bell Atlantic Communications Systems Inc., a subsidiary, and
would work under a different contract.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, meanwhile, the Court of Common Pleas issued an
injunction restricting the number of pickets at any company
entrance to four. A similar injunction was issued in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported more than 350 people, dressed in
black T-shirts stamped with a cobra and the words ``Will strike if
provoked'' rallied at Verizon Communications headquarters in
Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   And in Andover, Mass., some 500 pickets rallied outside a
Verizon office park at 6:30 a.m. The strikers, who wore red and
white placards with the words ``CWA ON STRIKE,'' said they were
concerned that Verizon could move some New England jobs to other
regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wages are only a part of this,'' said Michelle McCormack, a
32-year-old customer service representative and mother of three.
``We're out here because we want job security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
