<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BOTTLED-WATER08-COX     08-07 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTTLED-WATER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drinking with care
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TESTING AT THE TAP
</P>
<P>
   If you want to find out what's in your tap water, the place to
start is your local public water utility. Ask for the most recent
``Consumer Confidence Report.'' This report should tell you where
your water comes from _ whether it's surface water (from rivers or
lakes), groundwater (from underground rivers or streams) or some
mixture. It will also tell you whether your water exceeds the
limits for any of the 80 contaminants regulated by the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency. You should also ask for a printout
of the levels of all 80 contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   If you get your water from a well, you'll need to get it tested.
Call the EPA Safe Drinking Water Hotline
</P>
<P>
   (1-800-426-4791) for information on how to obtain a list of
certified labs that will test for lead, turbidity, arsenic,
parasites and other contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   CONSIDERING A WATER FILTER?
</P>
<P>
   Water filters vary widely in what they can remove, how much they
cost and how expensive they are to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Varieties include tabletop carafes that require frequent
refilling; faucet-mounted units that can be switched from a filter
to a nonfilter position; and under-the-sink units that supply
filtered cold water from a separate spigot or the main faucet.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $20 to $500; replacement filters can add up to
$150 a year. Before shopping, determine what you want to remove
from your tap water and the degree of convenience you desire.
</P>
<P>
   A carafe uses a carbon filter that improves flavor and removes
chlorine, DBPs and lead, but not microorganisms. Carafes are
inexpensive and handy for use in bathrooms and bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Faucet-mounted, countertop and under-the sink filters use more
sophisticated carbon filters, some of which can remove
cryptosporidium bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   There are also rather expensive countertop, under-sink or
basement systems that cleanse water by a process called reverse
osmosis. It works slowly and wastes a lot of water; it also removes
beneficial fluoride from the water.
</P>
<P>
   NSF International is an independent organization that tests
water filters and bottled water for purity. An NSF publication
titled ``Water Wise: The Consumer's Guide to Safe Drinking Water,''
which lists all the water filtration units tested by NSF and what
they remove, is available for $5. Write to NSF International, 789
N. Dixboro Road, P.O. Box 130140, Ann Arbor, MI 48113-0140, or call
toll-free
</P>
<P>
   1-877-867-3435. The Web site is www.nsf.org.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Center for Science in the Public Interest, New York
Times
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
