<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERS-HMO08-COX     08-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERS-HMO08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medicare HMO closings have many scrambling
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I want my HMO.
</P>
<P>
   That's the cry of thousands of Georgia senior citizens notified
in the past month that their Medicare HMOs are going out of
business _ taking with them such benefits as cheap prescription
drugs, annual exams, hearing tests and other services not normally
included in the traditional Medicare plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a national crisis within the past three
years,'' said Susan Pisano, spokeswoman for the American
Association of Health Plans. ``But it's simply not financially
feasible for these HMOs to stay in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention. Although Medicare HMOs serve an older population,
their demise could be a harbinger of larger problems for managed
care. Right now, 1.4 million Georgians depend on HMOs, and all of
these managed care companies _ whether they are Medicare, Medicaid
or private plans _ are struggling to contain rising medical and
prescription drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   So why are Medicare HMOs having such financial woes? And what
can you do if yours goes out of business?
</P>
<P>
   Insurers that offer Medicare HMOs say the key problem is
inadequate federal payment for benefits. Under a traditional plan,
Medicare is a fee-for-service plan, with the federal government
paying a set amount for services or treatment rendered. But under
an HMO, the federal government contracts with an insurer to provide
all treatment of its older citizens for a monthly, per-head, capped
amount. In order for the insurer to stay in business, that amount
has to at least cover the cost of treatment and prescriptions used
by the members enrolled in the HMO.
</P>
<P>
   But insurers say the federal compensation is not covering their
costs, making Medicare HMOs unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most plans in most locales are getting a 2 percent increase in
payment (annually) when their expenses are going up 7 to 8 percent
a year,'' Pisano said. ``It doesn't take that long for that to
become unsustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office report, released in July, said there
is enough money for basic services, but not enough for all the
perks that patients love. It recommended Congress figure out
exactly what the HMOs should cover and adjust funding accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, three out of five insurers offering Medicare
HMOs in Georgia have announced they are pulling out, including
Aetna US Healthcare, Cigna HealthCare and UnitedHealthcare. And
that means about 20,000 seniors _ almost half of those enrolled in
Medicare HMOs in Georgia_ have been notified their plans will not
exist after Dec. 31, according to the Georgia Insurance
Commissioner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, doctors also have been notified. And many
are canceling their contracts with the HMOs now, leaving thousands
of patients scrambling to find new doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Newman, 69, joined Cigna's Medicare HMO last year, and
was thrilled with it. The plan paid for his treatment for prostate
cancer and paid for medication and care related to his high blood
pressure and kidney problems. But in June, he was notified that
Cigna was pulling out of the market. And then his primary care
physician canceled his contract. That meant Newman had to pick from
a list of three new doctors he didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was left holding the bag,'' Newman said. ``This is a dirty
trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elizabeth deGive, a Rockdale County internist, is seeing
similar problems among the 400 patients in her practice recently
dropped by Cigna. ``Quite honestly, the patients who would choose
an HMO are often people who have high medical costs _ numerous
prescriptions and visits _ and they're trying to get by on a fixed
income,'' deGive said. ``They tend to be our sicker, more
complicated cases.''
</P>
<P>
   So many seniors were upset and confused about the changes, a
handful of Medicare representatives and physicians held a series of
meetings at the Newton County Library in Covington last week to
explain their options. Almost 200 people showed up for the first
meeting _ with some having to be turned away because of fire laws.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the seniors who have lost their HMO have the option of
joining another one in their county. According to the Insurance
Commissioner's Office, only 2,303 _ in Newton and Spalding counties
_ would have to travel over county lines to rejoin an HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies _ Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Georgia and Kaiser
Permanente of Georgia _ still offer Medicare HMOs. But even they
acknowledge that the future is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to construct a business plan for 2001 that
allows us to remain in the Medicare business,'' said Dick Shirk,
Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Georgia's chief executive officer.
``But if we cannot get the funding to maintain this, we're going to
have to rethink beyond 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   So what should you do if you've just learned of your HMO's
demise? Signing up with another HMO can be a solid tactic if your
doctor is part of the new network. Seniors can also decide to
return to the traditional Medicare plan.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good idea to purchase a supplemental plan to cover
the holes in the traditional plan.
</P>
<P>
   You can also learn more about Medicare by contacting:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Georgia Insurance Commissioner's Office, which offers a
help line at 404-656-2070, which is open 8 a.m. to 7 p.m. weekdays.
It also offers a free brochure called ``Medicare and You.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Health Care Financing Administration, which manages
Medicare and offers a help line at 1-800-633-4227 from 8 a.m. to
4:30 a.m. weekdays or you can get tips from www.hcfa.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Your current HMO, even if it's going out of business. Not only
are there important deadlines that indicate how fast you need to
change to another HMO or to the traditional Medicare plan, but the
HMO should also offer packets of information by October explaining
your options.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
