<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTANDS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC News chief under spotlight in New Yorker
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a fascinating New Yorker ($3) profile, Jane Mayer focuses on
ABC News President David Westin and his crusade to revive network
news. So far, Westin's claim to fame is his decision to send
Leonardo DiCaprio to interview Bill Clinton. Longtime news staffers
complain that Westin's concern about offending top executives at
Disney, the network's parent company, has resulted in ``an
atmosphere of self-censorship and timidity.'' Adding to the
discontent are Westin's close ties to Diane Sawyer and his marriage
to Sherrie Rollins, former public relations executive at ABC and
ex-wife of political adviser Ed Rollins.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tiger beat: Any golfer who played like Tiger Woods did in the
1997 Masters wouldn't have changed a thing _ not even his
underwear. But, as Time ($3.50) notes in its cover story on Woods,
the best golfer in the world decided that he needed to revamp his
swing completely. The gamble paid off and Woods went on to win the
British Open by a record margin. He also reinvented his private
life, Time reports, by dumping his caddie, his agent and his lawyer
and reshaping his image. The picture of Woods as a somewhat aloof
racial pioneer in the early Nike ads has been replaced with lighter
TV spots showing him juggling a golf ball on a wedge and conducting
classes on how to be Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Double issue: Teen People ($3.99) does a flip in its September
issue, with a regular cover about hot summer concerts and a back
cover shot of Serena Williams introducing a special section on the
Olympics. Featured athletes include soccer great Mia Hamm, track
star Marion Jones and weightlifter Cheryl Haworth of Savannah.
Already the holder of all U.S. records for her weight and gender
class, Haworth, 17, is favored to win a medal in Sydney. The
270-pound athlete also encourages girls to overcome the stereotype
that they must be pencil-thin to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Politics then and now: Newsweek ($3.50) wraps up the
Republican convention neatly in 10 pages, then devotes 12 pages to
Newsweek editor Evan Thomas' biography ``Robert Kennedy: His
Life.'' In this excerpt, Thomas describes how the multifaceted
politician matured during the Cuban Missile Crisis in 1962. ``He
blended high moralism and shifty pragmatism in a peculiarly
Kennedyesque way to edge the United States and the Soviet Union
back from the abyss,'' Thomas writes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leaving (late) on a jet plane: In a cover story on runway
rage, U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) looks at the reasons behind
the long lines and lengthy delays at the nation's airports.
Basically, the reporters conclude, there are too many planes and an
outdated air traffic control system that would cost $30 billion to
modernize. Other factors include lack of airport expansion and
labor squabbles. As a result, the number of verbal and physical
attacks on flight attendants is soaring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) offers an A-to-Z
guide to the battle over Napster, part two of an interview with
``Harry Potter'' author J.K. Rowling, and a report on the boom in
black movies this summer. ... Continuing its tradition of putting
scantily clad women on its covers, Maxim ($3.95) features the bar
belles of ``Coyote Ugly'' in the August issue. For those who simply
like to read the articles, don't miss Col. David Hackworth's report
on the three most likely scenarios for the start of World War III.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the Web: The weekly Access Internet Magazine has launched
accessmagazine.com, a companion Web site with longer versions of
stories from the magazine, an interactive Q&AMP;A and ``In Focus,'' a
daily report that analyzes and explains the impact of industry news
and trends on Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
