<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5148 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-GORE-HNS &LR;      08-07 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IMPACT OF LIEBERMAN'S RELIGION ON RACE COULD BE NIL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The religion of Sen. Joseph Lieberman, who next
week will become the nation's first Jewish vice presidential
nominee of a major political party, may have little or no impact on
the outcome of the election, some experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore will announce his selection of the
Orthodox Jewish senator from Connecticut as his running mate
Tuesday in Nashville, Tenn. The senator told reporters he received
a call from Gore Monday morning offering him the second spot on the
Democratic ticket. The two men prayed together during their phone
conversation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a Gallup Poll of 1,000 likely voters taken March 29 of last
year, 92 percent said they would vote for a well-qualified
candidate ``who happened to be Jewish.'' In 1937, in a similar
poll, only 42 percent said they would vote for a Jewish candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Religion has not been an issue in presidential politics since
John F. Kennedy became the first Catholic to win the presidency in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts divided on how voters will view a Jewish vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Some said Lieberman will help Gore win over religious voters and
will raise the public's opinion of the ticket's moral standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes it harder for (George W.) Bush and (Dick) Cheney to
argue that there's one ticket that represents truthfulness and
morality and one that doesn't,'' said Norm Ornstein, a senior
fellow at the American Enterprise Institute, a Washington-based
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein said that in past elections, Lieberman has received
significant support from Catholics and evangelical Protestants.
``Religious people respect other religious people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pitney, a political science professor at Claremont McKenna
College in Claremont, Calif., predicted that Lieberman's religious
background will be a plus among members of the Christian Right. ``A
lot of people in the Christian Right would much rather have a
Jewish person of piety and integrity than a nominal Christian of
dubious character,'' Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Louis P. Sheldon, head of the Traditional Values
Coalition, a conservative lobbying group, also praised Gore's
choice while taking a dig at the vice president himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Lieberman has an identifiable moral compass and would be
an improvement over the morally-challenged Al Gore,'' he said. ``By
selecting Lieberman, Gore is trying to distance himself from
Clinton and send a message to the American people that he
disapproved of Clinton's sexual antics.''
</P>
<P>
   But other observers questioned the impact of Lieberman's
religion on the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can calculate the effect of having a Jew
on the ticket,'' Democratic National Chairman Ed Rendell said last
week. ``If Joe Leiberman were Episcopalian, it would be a slam
dunk.'' Rendell became Philadelphia's first Jewish mayor in 1992
and served until last year, when he took the party post.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant David Axelrod, who also is Jewish, said
Lieberman could hurt Gore in the South and other conservative
states. But he added that Bush already has substantial leads in
those states.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, where a number of states are too close to call,
Lieberman's religion is ``less of a problem,'' he said, adding,
``If you look at the swing states, starting with New Jersey to
Wisconsin, every one of them has elected a Jewish senator or
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Gore's effort to distance himself from Clinton by
choosing Lieberman could end up helping a cause dear to the
president's heart: Hillary Rodham Clinton's quest to win New York's
U.S. Senate race against Long Island Republican Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton needs the overwhelming support of New York's
Jewish vote if she hopes to win the race, but most polls show her
garnering only slightly more than half of it. However, Ornstein
said Lieberman's likely campaign stops in the state will be ``a big
plus for Hillary. It will excite a lot of Jewish voters, who
represent 10 percent of the electorate in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Jews have traditionally voted Democratic, and in the last
presidential election, Bill Clinton won some 75 percent of their
vote. However, their loyalty to the party cannot be taken for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was re-elected with
more than 70 percent of the Jewish vote in 1997, when he trounced a
liberal Jewish candidate, Ruth Messinger. In the 1992 Senate race,
Republican Alfonse D'Amato beat the popular Jewish state
attorney-general, Democrat Robert Abrams, and won a surprisingly
high 41 percent of the Jewish vote in the process.Lieberman has not
always voted according to the Democratic Party line. He once
sponsored a bill to set up experimental voucher programs, letting
parents use federal money to send their children to public or
private schools, including religious schools. Gore opposes such a
plan, saying it would undermine public education.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Lieberman backed education proposals that do not
include vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   He voted to expand tax-free education savings accounts to help
parents cover education expenses in all grades and at public and
private schools, including religious schools _ an idea promoted by
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He has also spoken in favor of partially privatizing Social
</P>
<P>
   Security, as proposed by Bush and opposed by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Monday that the most important thing Lieberman
brings to the Democratic ticket is integrity. Pitney said
Lieberman's reputation as a religious man of unquestioned morals
will help Gore distance himself from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Lieberman represents a shot of anti-Clinton vaccine,''
Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a longtime friend of Clinton, was the first Senate
Democrat to publicly criticize him on the Senate floor for his
behavior in the Lewinsky scandal. He called the president's
behavior ``immoral'' and his denials of wrongdoing ``intentional
and premeditated.'' In the end, however, Lieberman voted against
impeaching Clinton, saying he thought the president should be
censured instead.
</P>
<P>
   William F. Connelly., a political science professor at
Washington and Lee University in Lexington, Va., said Lieberman
cannot inoculate Gore against the reputation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately Al Gore will stand or fall on the basis of his
close association with Clinton,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, often called the moral conscience of the Senate,
strictly observes the Sabbath, from sundown Friday until sundown
Saturday, refusing to use a telephone or drive a car. He also won't
campaign on Saturdays, an observance that kept him from attending
his own state nominating convention in 1988, the year he was first
elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com or judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
