<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `BOOK' ON LIEBERMAN: `MR. ETHICS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence Fuchs of Weston wrote ``the book'' on the political
behavior of American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday Fuchs, a veteran Democratic activist and Brandeis
professor, said he was surprised by Vice President Al Gore's choice
of US Senator Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had asked me who'd be the first Jew on a national
ticket, I would have said a highly assimilated one, not an Orthodox
Jew,'' said Fuchs, who wrote ``The Political Behavior of American
Jews'' in 1956. ``Usually, you don't crack through with a seriously
religious person.''
</P>
<P>
   Jews and non-Jews from around the region Monday reacted
favorably to the choice of Lieberman, noting the political appeal
for Gore of a running mate with a reputation for moral rectitude
and high ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, saw historical significance in the choice of
the nation's first Jewish vice presidential candidate _ coming as
it does on the 40th anniversary of the Democrats' nomination of
Kennedy, also in Los Angeles, who would become the nation's first
(and only) Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has transcendent meaning for the Jewish community,'' said
Barry Shrage of Newton, Mass., president of Combined Jewish
Philanthropies of Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Perlmutter of Newton, author of ``Legacy of Hate,'' a
book on the history of anti-Semitism in America, said Gore's choice
shows that respect for religious diversity in America is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted for him and for the country,'' said Perlmutter,
the former director of the Jewish Community Relations Council of
Greater Boston. ``Who could have predicted just a few years ago
that they would take a Jew on a national ticket, and an an
observant one, but why not? Bush is running as a devout
Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah, who grew up in Gardner, Mass.,
are Orthodox Jews who observe the Jewish Sabbath from sundown
Friday to sundown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has said that he won't campaign during that period
but will vote on legislation, attend important meetings or
otherwise do work that promotes ``the respect and protection of
human life and well-being.'' Gore staffers said Lieberman has an
apartment within walking distance of Capitol Hill so he can go to
work on the Sabbath without breaking the stricture against riding
in automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Frelich, his second wife, was born in Prague in 1948
and moved to Gardner when she was 3, according to a spokesman for
the senator. She graduated from Boston University in 1970 and has a
master's degree in health care administration.
</P>
<P>
   While many observers suggested that Lieberman's religion would
help Gore get a needed jolt of attention before next week's
Democratic convention, Fuchs, the Brandeis professor, urged
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is a bid for the Jewish vote,'' said Fuchs,
noting that the great majority of America's more than 5 million
Jews already vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the fact that Lieberman is Mr. Ethics, the
conscience of the Senate, a man whose morality and piety are
without compromise,'' said Fuchs, who was an aide to President John
F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Lieberman, he said, was a way for Gore to ``declare his
independence from the more tawdry aspects of the Clinton
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   However Shrage, the head of Combined Jewish Philanthropies, said
that it was hard to overplay the significance for American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's a symbol of just what an amazing country America
has been for the Jewish people,'' said Shrage, a second-generation
American whose grandparents were born in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Shrage, who is an Orthodox Jew himself, said Lieberman
represents a stream of Orthodoxy that he called modern, centrist
Orthodoxy. He said that strain is associated with Yeshiva
University in New York and respects plurality, both within the
Jewish world and beyond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
