<SLUG> BC-MTV-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRESH APPROACH FOR MTV
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Page through concert listings these days, and you'll notice
there are more pop bands from the '70s and '80s on the road than
current recording artists. Joining the fray is the Jackson Decker
Band, an '80s phenomenon that, we are repeatedly told in the
opening moments of MTV's new series ``Live Through This'' was
wildly ``influential'' on hip '90s groups.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the music we hear the band perform, that's a little
hard to believe _ their music is generic, anthemic rock that's out
of fashion in today's music climate. The show's title is cribbed
from the biggest album from Courtney Love's band Hole, which hardly
resembles the band here, but then again, this is MTV _ not
late-night Cinemax.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Live Through This'' is an interesting concoction _
there are hints the show will examine the band's current
irrelevance as the series progresses. The series, about the band's
reunion tour _ to lure MTV viewers, the story has the band members
all bringing their wildly attractive children, all in their teens
or early 20s, along for the ride (on their own bus, without parents
to chaperone!). And the tour manager is the grumpy guitarist's
smart, centered son (Tom Lock), who must contend with his father's
abuse and his own lingering feelings for the lead singer's daughter
(Sarah Manninen).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numerous soap-operatic angles _ will the lovestruck
kids reunite? Is the band's guitarist (David Nerman) as big a jerk
as he seems? Will the recovering alcoholic diva (Jennifer Dale)
sing? And shouldn't they have hammered out that last question
before even announcing the tour, let alone dragging in the media
for the first open rehearsal? _ it's a surprisingly reflective
series. It examines, albeit peripherally, how these musicians
didn't really grow up and how they didn't plan for the future,
which accounts for this tour _ part reliving their glory days and
part just another pathetic has-been act humping it on the road for
a much-needed payday.
</P>
<P>
   MTV, which has presented scads of original programming in the
past, declares that ``Live Through This'' is noteworthy because it
represents ``the channel's first-ever hour-long drama series''
(distinctions, always parsing out the slim distinctions). But it's
actually distinctive because it likely represents the first time
people older than 30 have been given significant air time on the
network (outside, of course, of Kurt Loder). One wonders what the
MTV demographic will make of all those fogeys crowding their sacred
screen; the show probably makes more sense on MTV's sister network
VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live Through This'' is, almost characteristically, something
you'd never expect from MTV _ a show that's purposefully not hip.
Which, given the way MTV works, probably makes it all that much
cooler. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Live Through This.'' &QL; 
What: Drama about a popular '80s band's reunion tour _ with their
nearly grown kids in tow. &QL; 
Who: Bruce Dinsmore, David Nerman, Jennifer Dale, Ron Lea, Tom
Lock, Sarah Manninen, Jane McGregor, Jessica Welch, Matthew Carey. &QL; 
Where: MTV. &QL; 
When: Wednesdays at 10 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
