<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-GORE (Washington) _ Some experts say the religion of
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, who next week will become the nation's first
Jewish vice presidential nominee of a major political party, may
have little or no impact on the outcome of the election. Religion
has not been an issue in presidential politics since John F.
Kennedy became the first Catholic to win the presidency in 1960. By
MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-MIDEAST (Jerusalem) _ Israelis hail the selection of
Joseph Lieberman as Al Gore's Democratic running mate, while
Palestinians worry that the Connecticut senator's tough pro-Israel
stance could be an impediment to peacemaking. Lieberman has
consistently stood behind Israel during peace negotiations with the
Palestinians and Syrians and once labeled Yasser Arafat as a
``villain.'' By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RECORD (Washington) _ A look at Sen. Joseph
Lieberman's voting and political history, including areas where he
is at odds with Vice President Al Gore. By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-CLINTON (Washington) _ Joseph Lieberman was the first
Democratic senator to scold President Clinton for the Monica
Lewinsky scandal, calling for his censure rather than impeachment.
In his Senate floor speech 19 months ago, Lieberman said of
Clinton's sexual affair with the former White House intern, ``Such
behavior is not just inappropriate, it is immoral and it is
harmful.'' By MICHAEL HEDGES.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Washington) _ A long-simmering battle for control
of the Reform Party moves to the front burner over the next several
days when the party meets in Long Beach, Calif., to nominate a
candidate for president. The winner will control the party and the
$12.6 million in federal money that will become available to its
presidential nominee. By LETITIA STEIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ By choosing to run for the White
House with Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Vice President Al
Gore came about as close as he decently could to poking President
Clinton in the eye. Lieberman, a senior Democratic legislator of
impeccable personal integrity, was the party's most thoughtful _
and most devastating _ critic of Clinton's moral lapse during his
affair with Monica Lewinsky. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ When the Democrats nominate
Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman for vice president next week, he
will become a member of an exclusive club of political
groundbreakers. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
