<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-07 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HIGH NOON AT GORE GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My early years in journalism were spent searching for colorful
things to say about Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   I have here a list of the best and worst members of the
Connecticut state legislature circa 1978. Lieberman was sixth-best.
Most of the people who came in ahead of him are either dead or
lobbyists, so when it came to potential running mates from the
Nutmeg State, Al Gore pretty much got the pick of the litter.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut magazine compiled the list, but I was in charge of
the lively prose. This is the lead I came up with: ``Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Lieberman is a man who's given a whole new
meaning to the term `low key.''' In another profile, I noted that
the then 35-year-old Lieberman was one of those guys who look
middle-aged at 30, and would still look middle-aged at 80. He's
become fond of quoting that in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   This is one laid-back Democrat, a subtle mix of interesting and
boring that solves almost all the main problems facing Al Gore
except how to get anybody to listen to the convention speeches.
It's a perfect match. Gore can be stiff but not pompous. Lieberman
can be pompous but not stiff. And who else would qualify as a
compelling, thinking-outside-the-box choice without looking more
exciting than the top of the ticket?
</P>
<P>
   The running-mate-to-be seemed positively giddy Monday afternoon,
and giddy is not normally one of his adjectives. ``I can't think of
a place I'd rather be at this momentous time of my life than with
you, the working people of Connecticut,'' he told a convention of
the state AFL-CIO in Hartford. Then he launched into reminiscences
of Connecticut labor leaders of yore, the late Gov. Ella Grasso,
his parents and his salad days in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman won his first race when he was only 28, so the 10
years he spent as a state senator shaped him as a politician. It
was a peculiar time in Connecticut history. Every state legislature
has a moment when it gets golden. (Well, maybe not Alabama.) You
hit a stretch where the people who get elected seem unusually
smart, and the good-government tools like open meetings and public
hearings and full floor debates actually work the way they're
supposed to. Connecticut was golden like that in the 1970s, and the
result was a rather extraordinary level of bipartisanship that
seems to have marked Lieberman for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a great deal of civility there. We had open caucuses
and the Democrats came into our caucus room to discuss tax
policy,'' said Lewis Rome, a lawyer who was Senate minority leader
at the time and calls the senator ``a moral force.'' (Rome, by the
way, finished first in that best-legislator poll.)
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's ability to rise above party politics is his biggest
strength as a legislator, and he probably couldn't have learned it
if he'd spent his formative years in the House of Representatives
of the 1990s. ``If he has any detractors in the Senate it's because
of his bipartisanship,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer of New York, who
describes Lieberman as ``almost a Gary Cooper type in the Senate.''
(Becoming the first Jewish candidate on a national ticket is nice.
But every male politician's fantasy is being called the Gary Cooper
of the Senate.)
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been much more daring as a U.S. senator than he
was when he was younger. He used to have one of those careful,
work-your-way-up careers. He lost a bid to become lieutenant
governor, then ran for Congress in 1980. He was defeated by Larry
DeNardis, the current president of the University of New Haven, who
recalls that the campaign was so issue-oriented even the League of
Women Voters got tired of hearing them debate.
</P>
<P>
   He became attorney general and then made the first big, risky
move of his career in 1988 when he ran against Sen. Lowell Weicker.
``Before a big speech he'd drop down and do push-ups to get his
blood running,'' said Marla Romash, who was the campaign
communications director.
</P>
<P>
   This is an excellent potential bonding tool for the campaign, in
which Al Gore is known to do stomach crunches during long flights.
Perhaps instead of the traditional post-convention whistle-stop
tour, they could travel from one athletic field to another. In your
heart, you know they're fit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
