<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-TIMBER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LOGGING SHIFTS TO THE SOUTH, NEW WORRIES EMERGE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION MILLS, N.C. _ In a major shift, timber companies have
stepped up logging operations in the South, where they face less
regulation than in the carefully monitored forests of the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Timber harvests in North Carolina, Tennessee and 11 other
Southern states increased by 50 percent from 1977 to 1997, from 6.8
billion cubic feet to 10.2 billion cubic feet, according to the
draft of a federal report, the Southern Resources Assessment. And
the trend has accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these Southern states _ from Virginia west through Texas
_ account for two-thirds of the 16 billion cubic feet of timber
harvested in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said that almost all of the logging in the
South has been conducted responsibly. And they point to the very
forests now being cut as an example of that stewardship. Most
Southern forests, they said, were logged extensively as long as a
century ago and then cut again in successive logging cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials and industry critics said the geographic shift
reflected, at least in part, the relative permissiveness of the
South, where most forests are in private, not public, hands, and
where logging is subject to few regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Southern states have given free rein to logging on
private land, in contrast to the West, where state regulations are
stricter and where the abundance of federally owned forests means
that cutting must meet tight federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 70 percent of the 214 million acres of forest in the
South is held by private, nonindustrial owners, with an additional
20 percent owned by the forest products industry.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, which is typical of Southern states, logging
on private land does not require state approval, and the state does
little to monitor the extent of timber harvests.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, federal officials and industry critics said, they
are seeing several troubling trends. For the first time, softwoods
like pine are being harvested faster than they can be replaced, and
projections in the Southern Resources Assessment suggested that the
more valuable hardwoods face a similar fate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also pointed to a wider use of clear-cutting
operations that have laid bare vast tracts of forest.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless appetite for wood is being fed by an economy that
has produced a strong market for construction. Small towns like
Union Mills in western North Carolina have felt the boom in the
form of chip mills, like the one here owned by the Willamette
Industries Inc. of Portland, Ore., that grind enormous quantities
of wood into chips for making paper. More than 100 such mills have
sprung up across the South in the past 15 years, most since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among those concerned about the shift in logging has been the
chief of the U.S. Forest Service, Mike Dombeck. Over the past 20
years, Dombeck said in a speech in June to a group of writers, a
huge surplus in the growth of timber over harvests in the South has
been all but eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is a question of basic sustainability,'' Dombeck
said. ``Harvest levels cannot exceed growth if forests are to
continue providing healthy fish and wildlife habitats, clean and
pure drinking water, and scenic beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   In the South, according to federal estimates, the growth deficit
is widest on land owned by the timber industry, which is about 20
percent of the forests and where removals in 1997 exceeded growth
by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even in cases where forests are being replanted, as is
encouraged but rarely required in Southern states, it is often with
varieties like the fast-growing loblolly pine, a tree that is a
valuable commercial crop but one that biologists say is less likely
to promote animal habitat than the natural mixed forests.
</P>
<P>
   Timber industry officials said that the concerns are groundless
and that most logging was being conducted with an eye to the future
health not only of the forests but of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   They also acknowledged that in isolated cases, too much timber
has been cut too fast with too little thought about what replaced
the existing forest. But logging, they said, was the only way to
clear old, marginal timber and make way for healthier, newer trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a resource that's getting old, and its growth is
slowing, and the removals are increasing,'' said Bob Slocum,
executive vice president of the North Carolina Forestry
Association, an industry group. ``So you might have a period where
your removals are exceeding the growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said it is important to remember that the timber in the
South was extensively cut in the early 20th century and that it is
again time for harvesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would argue that the more important issue is what happened
to the land after the harvest,'' he said. ``If it stays in
forestry, you're going to be OK. But if you pave it over, if you
replace it with a Home Depot or Wal-Mart, it's going to be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry critics have cited the speed and scope of the logging
in the 13 states as their main concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic fact is that the Southeastern states were ill
prepared in the extreme for this incredible acceleration of timber
products,'' said Lark Hayes, who, as a senior lawyer for the
Southern Environmental Law Center has helped lead an effort to
impose greater controls over timber operations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Missouri, under Gov. Mel Carnahan, imposed a
two-year moratorium on permits for chip mills. North Carolina is
also considering a moratorium, as part of a study ordered by Gov.
Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   But it is in small communities like Union Mills where the newest
outrage can be heard. Local voices of opposition have brought a new
tone to environmental activism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a bunch of tree huggers, and we do want to use the
forest,'' Caroline J. Edwards, a seventh-generation North Carolina
resident who works as a soil scientist and forest management
consultant, said in the county seat town of Rutherfordton, N.C.,
not far from Union Mills. ``But we want to use it wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shannon A. Buckley, who as district procurement forester for
Willamette in western North Carolina has been at the center of the
local fight, offered a contrasting view that restrictions of
logging would be a blow to property rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all got to come from a willing seller,'' Buckley said of
the 300,000 tons of wood chips the mill could produce each year for
Willamette's expanding papermaking operations in Kentucky and
Tennessee. ``If the landowners don't want to sell the wood, it's
not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, groups like the Southeast Forest Project have tried
to pressure Vice President Al Gore, as an environmental advocate
and a native of Tennessee, to address concerns about chip mills and
Southern forests.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments, Dombeck has been careful to point out that the
widespread private ownership of Southern forests means that there
may be little the government can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not public lands I'm talking about, and we will not
try to regulate private forest land,'' Dombeck said in a recent
speech to members of the American Forest and Paper Association. ``I
challenge you, the world's foremost leaders in private forest
management, to show leadership on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Resources Assessment, which should be completed
next year, is expected to provide a more detailed look at Southern
forests. But one picture of the transformation can be gleaned from
periodic estimates by the Forest Service, which tries to gauge the
nation's timber supply.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, the studies show, the growth of timber stock in the
South exceeded harvests by 75 percent. But by 1997, the most recent
year for which statistics are available, the gap had dropped to
less than 5 percent, as harvests increased and growth declined.
</P>
<P>
   Among softwoods, the regionwide ratio changed from a large
surplus in 1977 to a deficit of 10 percent. Among hardwoods like
oak, hickory and poplar, the surplus has also dropped, prompting
researchers to warn that those woods will also fall into deficit
within the next decade if the current increase in logging remains
unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   And though 20 years ago, about 15 percent of the nation's timber
production came from national forests, mostly in the Northwest,
that figure has dipped below 5 percent, driven by a series of
federal decisions aimed at protecting the environment, and in
particular by the 1994 Northwest Forest Plan, crafted to meet a
court-ordered directive to save the endangered spotted owl.
</P>
<P>
   As across most of the country, logging in the South takes place
far from the cities and the Interstate.
</P>
<P>
   But the view from the air can offer a more vivid picture,
exposing one checkerboard after another, with patches of natural
forest interspersed by tracts razed to the bare earth, and by
others whose uniform green was a telltale sign of the planting of a
single variety of tree.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent afternoon, in the rugged terrain of the Cumberland
plateau, not far from Chattanooga in southeastern Tennessee, the
extent of the leveling was particularly vivid and appeared to
support the findings of one federal research project whose
conclusions suggested that in particular cases, the broad-brush
estimates might not reflect the severity of timber loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that, more broadly, no one really yet knows
exactly what is going on,'' said Jonathan Evans, a biologist at the
University of the South who is director of the federal project,
which focused on impoverished, rural Grundy County and found that
the county lost 12 percent of its hardwood habitat from 1981 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among particular points of dispute is whether the chip mills are
part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Only 32 of the more than 150 chip mills existed before 1985, but
timber industry officials say the increase represents a step toward
efficiency, by making it possible to ship pulpwood to paper mills
as chips, instead of as logs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a demand out there that's going to be met,'' said
Slocum of the forestry association group. ``The demand is from
people for pulp and paper products, and the chip mills are going to
bring in the wood necessary to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As a corollary benefit, foresters like Buckley say, the mills
provide a market for scrap wood that otherwise would have little
commercial value, thus encouraging an overhaul they say is
necessary to make way for healthier forests.
</P>
<P>
   But environmental groups and their allies see the mills more as
instruments of an assault on Southern forests whose only guide is
the corporate bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The Dogwood Alliance, a group formed to the protect Southern
forests, has estimated that more than 1.2 million acres of forest a
year or about 1,500 square miles is needed to feed the chip mills
now in operation.
</P>
<P>
   In operations of that scale, the critics said, neither time nor
attention is given to selective logging measures aimed at promoting
natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I've always waited until the trees get big, and
only then do I saw them,'' said Rodney Robbins, 44, a
third-generation logger from Union Mills. ``But these timber
companies only see one way of doing things: They just want to go in
and mow everything down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
