<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUKE-CLEANUP-NYT &LR;      08-07 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-CLEANUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB SITES POSE HAZARDS FOR CENTURIES, NATIONAL ACADEMY REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., N.M., Wash.)   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most of the sites where the federal government
built nuclear bombs will never be cleaned up enough to allow public
access to the land, and the plan for guarding sites that are
permanently contaminated is inadequate, the National Academy of
Sciences said Monday in a report.
</P>
<P>
   ``At many sites, radiological and nonradiological hazardous
wastes will remain, posing risks to humans and the environment for
tens or even hundreds of thousands of years,'' the report said.
``Complete elimination of unacceptable risks to humans and the
environment will not be achieved, now or in the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the production of nuclear weapons has produced
``national sacrifice zones,'' land that the public can never use
again, is not new. The term became common in environmental circles
in the late 1980s, when the United States began recognizing the
environmental legacy of the Manhattan Project, the effort during
World War II to develop atomic weapons, and the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But the academy's report, which was commissioned by the
Department of Energy, goes a step further. It says that the
government can try to declare certain areas permanently off-limits,
but it does not have the technology, money and management
techniques to prevent the contamination from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some of the contaminants have already ``migrated''
outside plant boundaries and others will follow, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas M. Leschine, the chairman of the committee that wrote the
report, said site managers could use barbed wire and post guards at
the sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Leschine, an associate professor in the School of Marine
Affairs at the University of Washington, added: ``There's no
assurance that we can maintain any of that control. It's one thing
to put a fence up around something, but it's really something else
to maintain it in perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Controls on the use of some of the land are already breaking
down, the report said. For example, in the early 1990s, the
Department of Energy sold land near its Oak Ridge Reservation in
Tennessee for use as a golf course, stipulating that the
groundwater was contaminated and was not to be used. ``Within a few
years, however, DOE discovered that a well was being drilled to
irrigate the golf course,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Leschine said the committee had found another case in which the
Department of Energy had posted ``no fishing'' signs at a creek
near Oak Ridge because of radiation contamination in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signs all got stolen, because the local high school kids
thought they were nice things to have,'' he said. ``Then there were
months of protracted battles between the local authorities and the
Department of Energy, over whose responsibility it was to replace
the signs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Department of Energy, Gerald G. Boyd, the deputy
assistant secretary for science and technology, said his agency
established a long-term stewardship office a year ago to cope with
the problem, with about a dozen people working with engineers and
planners at the various sites. The office was established soon
after the department requested the study from the National Academy
of Sciences, Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   He compared his operation to a highway department that replaced
stop signs stolen from street corners, thefts that might cause
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to put plans in place so we have a way to make sure
that it doesn't happen, or if it does happen, we correct it,'' Boyd
said. ``That's the kind of planning we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The department has accelerated efforts to clean up the sites,
reduce the costs involved and minimize risks to surrounding
communities, but a perfect cleanup is not possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the breakdown of control, Leschine cited the
fire that endangered the Los Alamos National Laboratory, near
Albuquerque, N.M., in May. The fire set the stage for mudslides in
the coming rainy season that could contaminate the Rio Grande with
radioactive and chemical toxins from the weapons laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   But the cause of the blaze was not natural or malicious; the
fire was set by another government agency as part of its
land-management efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that no plan written now to minimize the spread
of uncontained wastes would suffice over the tens, hundreds or even
thousands of years that some of the contaminants would remain
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   It urged the department to assume that engineered barriers like
concrete and steel would eventually fail, and that most of what was
known about the behavior of contaminants in air, soil or water
might ``eventually be proven wrong.'' The department needs a
long-term program that ``actively seeks out and applies new
knowledge,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   It recommended that clean-up efforts be left to future
generations at sites with low risks, or where technology might be
developed in the future that would make the job more practical, and
that priority should be given to sites where a delay would allow
contamination to spread.
</P>
<P>
   But it also said that too little information was available about
most sites to be able to decide which category to put them in.
</P>
<P>
   The report identified 144 sites where the department and its
predecessors, notably the Atomic Energy Commission, processed
nuclear materials, and it said that 109 of them would not be
cleaned up enough for unrestricted release, because of insufficient
money, technical skill or political will to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VOICE-IN-YOUR-HEAD-NY     08-07 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-IN-YOUR-HEAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIST WHO TRAVELS WITH YOU (ON TAPE, THAT IS) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH BOXER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ I first heard the voice, an insinuating, whispering
voice in my head, in Switzerland. Inside the new Kunstmuseum in
Lucerne, in the middle of an exhibition called ``Mixing Memory and
Desire,'' somewhere between Joseph Reinhardt's late-18th-century
paintings of Swiss peasants and a maze of 21st-century installation
art, I heard it. I had climbed into a black-curtained booth, a
theater in miniature called ``Playhouse,'' and had sat down to
watch a singer projected on a tiny stage. I put on the headphones
that were waiting on the chair.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a woman whispered in my ear, ``Sorry I'm late.'' I
wheeled around to see who had invaded the booth. No one was there.
The voice was in the headphones. As the singer onstage sang, the
voice kept whispering next to me _ something about the singer, the
song, a box under my seat, a gun, a crime to be committed. Then she
left. I looked under my seat. Nothing was there. I left the booth
and put the voice out of my mind.
</P>
<P>
   But the voice followed me to London. I was wandering around the
Tate Modern and had almost finished seeing an exhibition of
installation art, ``Between Cinema and a Hard Place.'' People were
standing around watching a miniature movie in a puppet-size
theater. They were motioning to their friends, ``You've got to see
this.'' What was the big deal? I picked up some headphones. ``The
Muriel Lake Incident'' was playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any popcorn left?'' a familiar voice whispered in my
ear. Soon I could hear a woman next to me munching popcorn, quietly
but audibly. How rude! I looked over. No one was there. The whisper
started again: ``This isn't the film I thought it was. I thought it
was supposed to be directed by Orson Welles.'' The voice
disappeared, and shots rang out. The people next to me jumped, then
smiled sheepishly at their friends.
</P>
<P>
   The voice belonged to Janet Cardiff, an artist from Lethbridge,
Ontario, and it had me snared. When I learned that the voice could
be heard in Whitechapel, the East London neighborhood where Jack
the Ripper did his dirty work, I went. At the Whitechapel Library I
exchanged my credit card for ``The Missing Voice (Case Study B)'':
a pair of headphones, a Discman and a map of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The whispering voice ordered me to the back of the library. I
went. I heard the rustling of newspapers. Was it real or was it
Memorex? The voice pushed me into a corner and had me scanning the
third shelf for a book by Reginald Hill. It was there. I pulled it
down. The voice read a passage on page 88: ``She set off at a brisk
pace.'' Then the voice inside my head said calmly but firmly: ``I
want you to walk with me. There are things I want to show you.''
</P>
<P>
   We went up the stairs together, and she pointed out the peeling
ceiling. She confided in me: ``I started these recordings as a way
to remember, to make things more real.'' I understood. She led me
out of the library and onto the street and treated me as an old
friend. ``I sometimes follow men late at night,'' she told me. ``It
makes me feel safe.'' That was eerie. I used to do that, too _ find
``a secret guardian angel'' on the street. ``I have red hair,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She was my guardian angel in Whitechapel. When it was time to
cross the street, she reminded me to look both ways. This was
London, after all, and Americans never know which way cars are
going. As we gazed at the words ``Look left'' and then ``Look
right'' painted in the gutter, she said, ``I'm glad they write that
on the streets for people like me.'' But she was an odd guide. She
kept imagining strange men about to commit crimes. And she kept
pointing out banana peels on the sidewalk that just weren't there.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to hear her whisper. On the tape there was Caribbean
drumming. In the street jackhammers were pounding. And there she
was, oblivious, telling a story about a man who spent 20 years
looking for the woman he loved. He played the violin. She seemed to
give careful directions, but I couldn't keep pace with her
footsteps, tapping faintly right beside me on the sidewalk. I was
having trouble navigating.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani restaurants were closed. It was Saturday. Only the
workmen with their jackhammers were out. I walked blocks in the
wrong direction, stretching my imagination to make myself think
that I was actually seeing what she was pointing out. Finally, I
reoriented myself at the Jesus Christ Spitalfields Church.
</P>
<P>
   As I looked at the brick buildings with clay chimneys and white
lintels, she told me to to head toward a red-on-orange sign that
said, ``Eat Drink Restaurant.'' At last I found it. At the moment
of my navigational triumph, she told a spooky story from her
childhood. She had found a man's body hanging from the neck. It
turned out to be her father's suit, hanging out to dry. A real man
walked by us yakking into his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a row of men marching toward me,'' she whispered as
we made our way down a narrow alley. ``They have pointy hats and
striped beards.'' Striped beards? The sound of gentle kazoos filled
my ears. Waiters were tossing buckets of water in the gutters.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we sat down on a bench facing Bishopsgate Street. ``I
like looking at the chimneys,'' she said. People had obviously
begun to notice her. Or maybe they were looking at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wonder why I'm talking into this thing,'' she said in
her breathy voice. I could hear the click of her tape recorder
turning on, turning off. She wanted to move on. It was a sunny day.
The song ``Downtown'' was blaring inside my head, and it was hard
not to walk to the music of the gentle bossa nova. As my angel and
I strolled down the sidewalk together, I felt giddy.
</P>
<P>
   But she broke the mood. ``Woman's Body Found in Thames,'' she
read from a paper on the newsstand. Then she saw him: ``There's a
man in a suit coming towards me. His shirt collar is too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   She slipped into a nearby church. But for me, it was locked. She
told me to wait in the garden. ``It smells like incense in here,''
she told me, as if we were on walkie-talkies. Outside I smelled
flowers in the sun. She listened to the organ and reminisced about
her father's heavy breathing in church and the way the sun used to
move through the figures in the stained glass. I was locked
outside, listening to bird song and looking at trampled thistle.
Finally she came outside to join me and quickly noticed ``an older
man with a black jacket, tuning his radio.''
</P>
<P>
   She told me her dream of a polar bear and pointed out a woman
with red hair reading a book called ``Body Identified.'' Was she
pointing herself out to me? It didn't matter. No one was there.
</P>
<P>
   At last we reached a McDonald's at the Liverpool Street train
station. I had long since given up sorting out the layers of sound
and story in my head. There were literary voices reading
hard-boiled crime stories, loud birds in the plaza, skirmishes on
the street, working people having lunch, a man singing lieder,
another man saying, ``Her letter made no sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly she said: ``I have to leave now. I wanted to walk you
to the library, but there isn't enough time.'' She left. Walking
back quietly to the Whitechapel Library, I found my eyes wide open.
I saw a man on a cell phone, iron manhole covers in the cobblestone
streets, dog dung in the gutter, a fashion shoot on the sidewalk.
The voice inside my head had finally stopped. I was cured.
</P>
<P>
   WHITHER A VOICE
</P>
<P>
   In Lucerne, Switzerland, Janet Cardiff's audiovisual
installation ``Playhouse'' can be seen in the exhibition ``Mixing
Memory and Desire,'' at the new Kunstmuseum through Sept. 24.
Telephone: 011-41-41-226-7800.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Cardiff's audiovisual piece ``The Muriel Lake
Incident,'' made with her husband, George Bures-Miller, is included
in ``Between Cinema and a Hard Place,'' a temporary exhibition of
the work of 23 contemporary artists at the Tate Modern through Dec.
3. Telephone: 011-44-20-7887-8008.
</P>
<P>
   Also in London, her audio-walk ``The Missing Voice (Case Study
B)'' begins at Whitechapel Library and is available through the end
of the year. The Artangel information line: 011-44-20-7713-1402.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
