<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST-NYT &LR;      08-07 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS OUTRAGED OVER RABBI'S REMARK ON HOLOCAUST VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The 80-year-old spiritual leader of Israel's largest
strictly observant political party outraged many Israelis with a
sermon over the weekend in which he said that the 6 million Jews
who perished in the Holocaust died because they were reincarnations
of sinners, and he sought Monday to calm the storm.
</P>
<P>
   In a new sermon, the spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef,
offered no explicit apology for his remarks in a broadcast on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Baghdad-born rabbi, the pre-eminent figure in the Shas
party, which holds a key bloc of 17 seats in Israel's 120-seat
Parliament, appeared to backtrack from his earlier statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six million Jews, among them 1 million children, were killed
by the wicked Nazis,'' he said. `` All were holy and pure and
complete saints.''
</P>
<P>
   The new sermon, carried like the earlier one over a
party-controlled radio station and relayed by satellite overseas,
contained no hint of contrition for remarks about the peace efforts
that insulted Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi said on Saturday that Prime Minister Ehud Barak, by
``bringing snakes beside us'' with the compromises he had put
forward at the recent Camp David talks, had demonstrated that he
had ``no brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outcry from rabbis, politicians and Jewish leaders
around the world, many voices in Israel dismissed the earlier
remarks as the ramblings of a bellicose old man with a long record
of provocations. A commentary in Monday's editions of Yedioth
Ahronoth, the country's most widely circulated newspaper, described
him as ``an aging political hack who has lost control of his
tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Israelis were less ready to dismiss the remarks, and
not only because of the deep offense they caused. Yosef remains
important to the peace efforts, if only because his party of
strictly observant Jews may determine whether Barak succeeds in
rebuilding his shattered coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the controversy raged, officials in Barak's Labor Party
confirmed Monday that contacts were continuing to lure the rabbi's
Shas Party back into the governing coalition that began to
disintegrate last month, before peace talks at Camp David failed.
</P>
<P>
   Shas and two other right-wing parties quit in protest against
Barak's peace plans, prompting other defections that have left
Barak, by the estimate of many Israeli commentators, with the
assured support of barely a third of the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators said that Barak, in careful comments on
Yosef's Holocaust remarks on Sunday, had ``pandered'' to the rabbi
so as not to spoil the chances that Shas would rejoin the
government, or at least back efforts to revive peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said the remarks were unworthy of Yosef's status, and
added, ``His words could harm the memory of those who perished in
the Holocaust and could hurt the feelings of their families and the
feelings of the entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's restraint brought a chorus of criticism. ``Any pursuit
by Ehud Barak of the blasphemous rabbi, from this moment on, should
be considered as unconscionable kowtowing, as the abandonment of
any semblance of self-respect, and as groveling for the seats that
will give this government another few months,'' said Shalom
Yerushalmi, a columnist in Maariv, another major paper.
</P>
<P>
   Bannered in newspaper headlines and given top billing in radio
and television newscasts, the rabbi's remarks became the principal
talking point wherever Israelis gathered. Although Yosef has been
at the center of controversy before, commentators said they could
recall no occasion in the country's 52-year history when an Israeli
public figure had caused such an outcry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the harshest condemnations came from Yosef Lapid, a
68-year-old member of Parliament and Holocaust survivor whose
father died in the death camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear Rabbi Yosef's words, I feel that my father was
murdered a second time,'' said Lapid, who is leader of the
secularist Shinui party. ``If an important rabbi in Israel comes
and says that 6 million Jews who died in the Holocaust were sinning
souls, it's tantamount to his saying that Hitler was doing holy
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Others saw the remarks as a reflection of the divisions between
the European Ashkenazi Jews and Sephardic Jews, mainly from the
Middle East and north Africa, whose political power has grown. Shas
draws much of its support from working class Sephardis, a fact
alluded to by Lapid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that Rabbi Yosef wanted to say that Ashkenazis sinned
and that is why they died in the Holocaust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still others said they feared the remarks could encourage
anti-Semites who deny that the Holocaust occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics saw Yosef's remarks about Palestinians as an
attempt to complicate the peace efforts further. But if the rabbi
intended to impede the peace efforts by insulting Palestinians, the
signs Monday were that he had failed. Israel Radio and the Agence
France-Presse news agency reported that Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, had told reporters in the Gulf state of Abu
Dhabi that President Clinton could set up a new summit meeting
after the Democratic National Convention ends on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in Barak's office, quoted by Israel radio Monday,
said that it was ``premature'' to talk of a new summit meeting. An
American official with first-hand knowledge of the Camp David talks
said the United States would not be ready to call a new summit
without ``an indication that something has changed'' in the
negotiating stands of the two sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-RIGHT-NYT &LR;      08-07 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-RIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN VIEWED AS KINDRED SPIRIT BY MANY EVANGELICAL CHRISTIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See GORE-LIEBERMAN and related stories) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Al Gore has managed to choose as his
running mate an Orthodox Jew whom many Christians _ and especially
conservative evangelicals _ regard as an ally on many social and
moral issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been seen by some Christians as a kindred spirit
for his willingness to speak of the influence of religion in his
life. His talk of the Talmud inspiring both his values and his vote
has often been cited by those Christians who believe the Bible
ought to guide public policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of serious Christians in America, the fact that he's
an observant Jew would be viewed very positively,'' said the Rev.
Richard John Neuhaus, a Catholic priest who is the editor of
``First Things,'' a neoconservative religious journal. ``America is
incorrigibly and confusedly a religious nation, and the fact that a
person is viewed as religiously devout, someone who lives what he
believes, is clearly a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political scholars dismiss the idea that Christians, who
account for 85 percent of voters, would react negatively to a a Jew
on a national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   America has changed, they say. In 1937, only 46 percent of
voters surveyed in a Gallup poll said they would vote for a Jew if
the candidate was qualified. By 1999, 92 percent of voters said
they would. Other polls have found similar results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that those numbers are so high,'' said John C. Green
director of the Ray Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the
University of Akron, ``suggests that even if there is a hidden bias
that people are unwilling to admit to pollsters, it is not
substantial enough to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   There are anti-Semitic racist groups that call themselves
Christian ``churches,'' said Green, but they have few adherents and
are so alienated from politics that many do not even vote. Some
African-Americans harbor anti-Semitic attitudes borne of years of
conflict, said Green, but not enough to change the vote of a
constituency that usually votes solidly Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Lieberman has championed some of the issues dear
to Catholics, mainline Protestants, and conservative Christian
evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported school vouchers and pushed for the State
Department to punish countries for religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   His speech on the Senate floor in 1998 denouncing President
Clinton for sexual immorality won praise from Christian clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the vice president made an excellent choice,'' said
the Rev. Jerry Falwell, a founder of the Moral Majority, in an
interview. ``It is a public acknowledgment that his candidacy has
two great needs. One is credibility, which Mr. Lieberman brings to
anything he touches. The second is an everlasting divorce from Bill
Clinton, and this is that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is acknowledging that character, not the economy, is the
issue in November,'' said Falwell, who is actively supporting Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   R. Albert Mohler Jr., president of the Southern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Louisville, Ky., said, ``American
evangelicals respect persons of great moral substance and
conviction, and we certainly share with Senator Lieberman a great
moral heritage to which we are both committed, in terms of the Old
Testament, the Hebrew scriptures, and most essentially, the Ten
Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Mohler, Neuhaus and others noted, however, that having the Ten
Commandments in common is not enough. Many Catholics and
evanglicals who oppose abortion and homosexuality would not vote
for a Gore-Lieberman ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evangelicals are not going to be deceived in believing that
this represents a shift to the right on the Democratic ticket,''
Mohler said.
</P>
<P>
   But the evangelical vote is far from monolithic. There are
evangelicals who care more about poverty than abortion, more about
environmentalism than homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone who is pro-life uses that issue as a litmus test
for who they are going to vote for,'' said Rabbi Yechiel Eckstein,
an Orthodox Jew who founded the International Fellowship of
Christians and Jews, based in Chicago. Lieberman served as co-chair
of the group's Washington affiliate, the Center for Jewish and
Christian Values, along with Sen. Dan Coats, a conservative
evangelical Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are many, many Americans who may be committed to
the pro-life platform, but who give equal value to violence on TV,
to morality in the public square, and integrity in the White
House,'' said Eckstein, ``and I think they would look to somebody
like Joe Lieberman for leadership in those areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
