 PERSONALS: Observations From the Field 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How out of it is  &UR; Richard Rosen &LR; ? ``Say,'' he writes, ``I see
where this  &UR; George Bush  &LR; fella is running for president again. I
thought he learned his lesson in '92.'' But Sen.  &UR; John Breaux &LR; ,
D-La., is more fogbound:  &UR; Peter Rosenbaum  &LR; and  &UR; Paul Rauber &LR; , both
listening to NPR Monday, heard him say of the Democratic vice
presidential candidate that people wouldn't care ``what church he
goes to on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Music to play while you're on the way to the shrink: &UR; Gino &LR; 
 &UR; Robair &LR;  forwards a press release for a new Internet radio network
that contains channels ``specifically programmed for a specific
demographic or psychographic market segment.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Piano-man  &UR; Michael Slaughter &LR;  says that real pianists say
PYAN-ist, a two syllable pronunciation as compared with the
three-syllable ones provided by Personals' dictionary. In response
to a survey of professional (one's an opinion; two's a survey) the
San Francisco Symphony's  &UR; Robin Sutherland &LR;  prefers pee-YAN-ist _
because ``the instrument we attempt to play is the pee-YAN-o,'' and
furthermore, prefers FLOOTists to the ``extremely irritating
flautists.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Marsha Cohen &LR;  forwards a flyer tucked into the windshields
of cars parked in the Haight Ashbury, warning ``Don't Use Car
Rads.'' The hand-out says that RADS, remote activated devices that
lock and unlock car doors can cause a variety of health problems,
including premature aging.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Eleanor Coppola &LR; , costume designer, textile expert, artist,
documentarian and matriarch of the movie-making clan, sold six
drawings and a sculpture that were shown at the Paule Anglim
Gallery. All proceeds went to charities; buyers wrote their checks
to the nonprofits of their choice. The ACLU and a group that works
with homeless people in North Beach were among the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   -- BidBay.com is selling a trailer used in the filming of the
forthcoming ``Charlie's Angels'' movie, which the seller says is
``shot full of holes and blown up.'' Starting price was $400, which
is just where it sat Monday, with no one having bid.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Andrew Hartley-Snazelle &LR; , great-great nephew of &UR; Wallace
Hartley &LR; , who was the orchestra leader on the ``Titanic,'' attended
the musical in San Francisco last week.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Macaulay Culkin &LR; , 20, and &UR; Rachel Miner &LR; , 19, have separated
after two years of marriage. His publicist announced their decision
is ``very amicable and they remain the best of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; KENNETH TYNAN ON GORE'S CHOICE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The latest New Yorker includes installment 2 of the diaries of
 &UR; Kenneth Tynan &LR; , in which the British-born critic, author and
theatrical maven _ who died in 1980 _ recounted a dream relevant to
Monday's announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Tynan dreamed that he asked Lady  &UR; Antonia Fraser &LR;  (the historian
married to playwright  &UR; Harold Pinter &LR; ) whether it was true she had
converted to Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' answered Fraser in Tynan's dream. ``But as Dr.
 &UR; Jonathan Miller &LR;  once said, I'm not a Jew. I'm Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I've always had a killer bod. But it was a lot tougher
dealing &LR; 
 &UR; with guys chasing me when I was 16 than it is now. The advantage &LR; 
 &UR; and disadvantage of being a star is that most guys are terrified &LR; 
 &UR; of you.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- &LR;   &UR; Cameron Diaz &LR;  in the Sunday Mirror of London.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
