<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE CAPITAL STILL ROLLING IN DESPITE TECH STOCK RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the public stock markets cooled, the level of venture
capital investment nationwide changed little in the second quarter,
the National Venture Capital Association reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more companies received investments in the April-June
period than in either of the previous two quarters, though the
amount invested declined slightly for the second straight quarter
after growing at a blistering pace last year.
</P>
<P>
   And the survey found that e-commerce companies have fallen out
of favor, with Internet-related investments focused increasingly on
communications and infrastructure start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that the nation's 640 venture capital firms,
and the venture investment arms of corporations, poured $24.5
billion into 1,695 companies, compared with investments of $24.8
billion in 1,627 companies in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the increase from a year earlier was striking. In the
second quarter of 1999, $12.5 billion was invested in 1,168
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   But since April, when the value of many technology stocks
tumbled, some venture capitalists have said they were investing in
start-ups less aggressively than they did last year, wary that they
would not be able to take companies public so readily.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Metzger, director of marketing for the National Venture
Capital Association, an industry trade group, said the present rate
of investment showed that venture firms were still financing
entrepreneurs at a healthy rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The VC industry continues to grow at a strong pace,'' she
said, particularly ``when you take into account that this was a
period of substantial market volatility.'' She added that the fact
that the investment rate leveled off should not be cause for
concern because the growth in investing last year _ an increase of
150 percent over the total in 1998 _ was unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted in conjunction with Venture Economics, a
division of Thomson Financial Securities Data, found that
Internet-related investments grew to $19.9 billion in the second
quarter, from $19 billion in the previous period. Of such
investments, communications and infrastructure companies _ such as
those focused on wireless technology, telephony, or voice and data
transmission _ attracted 26.9 percent, compared with 20.1 percent
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce companies, in contrast, attracted 14.5 percent of
Internet-related investments, compared with 27.2 percent in during
first quarter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
