<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-BUSH-EDUC-GUINIE     08-07 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-BUSH-EDUC-GUINIER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT BUSH DOESN'T DESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, Aug. 8, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By LANI GUINIER and GERALD TORRES    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the Republican Convention last week, Colin Powell boldly
challenged his party to be inclusive and follow the leadership of
George W. Bush in Texas. As a model of inclusive reform, he touted
Texas' 10 percent plan, which grants automatic admission to the
flagship public colleges to all state students graduating in the
top 10 percent of their high school classes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush calls this plan, which has been remarkably successful, an
example of his compassionate conservatism. But this claim would be
more convincing if his oratory about the program today had been
matched by action when it was being debated. The Texas Legislature
adopted it in 1997, after a U.S. Court of Appeals ruling, the
Hopwood decision, had outlawed affirmative action at the University
of Texas. Black and Hispanic state legislators conceived and
advocated the plan. Bush's contribution? He didn't veto it.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate over the bill, Bush ``never publicly supported
the idea,'' says Irma Rangel, the Democratic chairwoman of the
higher education subcommittee in the Texas House and the plan's
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has about 1,500 high schools. But before the program's
inception, the University of Texas at Austin, the most selective
state-supported Texas college, filled 75 percent of its freshman
seats from about 150 economically privileged suburban and private
schools. Under the 10 percent plan, several poor white counties in
rural West Texas sent graduates to Austin for the first time.
Moreover, about 300 African-American freshmen were enrolled last
year, a 50 percent increase over the year immediately after the
Hopwood decision ended affirmative action. The number of Hispanic
students has also increased, to more than when affirmative action
was the official policy.
</P>
<P>
   (It is worth noting that the plan ensures integration at the
university level even if the high schools remain segregated. But as
some national Democrats point out, the plan is not a panacea for
educational reform, especially in states without the extraordinary
racial and economic segregation of Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the fears that they would be unqualified, the 10
percenters exceeded expectations; their collective grade point
average in their first year of college was higher than the freshman
average for all students before the Hopwood decision. Part of their
achievement comes from the university's efforts to make the school
itself smarter. The university created more small classes for
freshmen and allocated full scholarships to high schools with large
numbers of poor and working-class students.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these successes, and despite the high regard in which
Bush professes to hold the plan, there are rumblings among
Republicans about trying to change it in the next legislative
session. They want to restore a requirement that applicants take
the SAT, which rewards those who can afford coaching and test
preparation and does not predict the qualities of leadership and
achievement that the university values. And Bush is notably quiet
about these proposed overhauls. ``Hopwood required forward
thinking, and he's been passive,'' Michael Olivas, a professor at
the University of Houston who specializes in higher education law,
says of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 percent plan has worked in Texas to spread educational
opportunity to those who have had too little of it. It never would
have happened without leadership of people of color. Bush should be
bold enough to credit the black and brown leaders who gave him the
opportunity to crow about its success today. That would be
inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   (Lani Guinier and Gerald Torres, professors of law at Harvard
and the University of Texas, respectively, are authors of the
forthcoming ``The Miner's Canary.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
