<HEADER>
A5189 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-LIEBERMAN-FREEDM     08-07 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-LIEBERMAN-FREEDMAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SPEAK WITH ONE'S OWN VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, Aug. 8, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By SAMUEL G. FREEDMAN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the midst of World War II, when my Uncle Seymour was about to
have his bar mitzvah, my grandmother went to the rabbi of their
Bronx synagogue with a request. At the climax of the ceremony, when
Seymour would march through the sanctuary bearing the Torah
scrolls, the rabbi should follow, holding aloft a portrait of
Franklin Delano Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   That the rabbi eagerly complied with this motherly meddling
attests to more than the Jewish devotion to FDR. It served as a
vivid reminder that even in tolerant America, even at a time of
Nazi extermination abroad, most Jews depended on a righteous
gentile like Roosevelt to protect them and their interests. To
shout out on their own behalf, to draw attention to their tiny
share of the American populace, was to court anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-century later, Al Gore has shattered the
enduring concept of American Jewish insecurity by naming as his
running mate Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, the first Jew
ever on a major party's presidential ticket. And in ways he himself
may not even understand, Gore has sent a powerful message by
choosing a Jew who is Orthodox, and, more specifically, Modern
Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this century, the Jews who rose in government
service or partisan politics tended to be of Reform belief and
German ancestry. Herbert Lehman, Henry Morgenthau and Felix
Frankfurter arose from a subculture of Jews who had shed much
observance and ritual, who had embraced English liturgy as part of
becoming American. All these men, in their way, were domestic
equivalents of the shtadtlan of Eastern Europe's ghettos, the
communal diplomats who pleaded the Jewish community's concerns to
the crown.
</P>
<P>
   By now, so much has changed that a nation that is only 2 percent
Jewish has elected 34 Jews to both houses of Congress. Yet even
amid such company Lieberman stands out because of his public
observance. He is not Sandy Koufax or Hank Greenberg, making a show
of not playing ball on Yom Kippur while otherwise living a
relatively nonreligious life. Lieberman worships at Kesher Israel,
an Orthodox synagogue in Georgetown, and observes the 613
commandments, the mitzvot. If there is a vital session of Congress
on the Sabbath, he still attends and votes, but he walks rather
than drives.
</P>
<P>
   And recognizing that balance is essential to understanding
Lieberman's significance in the world of American Jewry. The Modern
Orthodox movement believes in the concept of Torah Umaddah _
literally ``Torah and worldly knowledge,'' but more broadly, the
value of engaging with the larger society.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this style of Orthodoxy that has been whipsawed
by two contradictory trends _ ever-increasing assimilation by less
observant Jews and withering criticism by ultra-Orthodox Jews who
view secular America as a spiritual pollutant that must be handled
only to the extent necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that Joseph Lieberman earned his place on Al Gore's
ticket during the Monica Lewinsky scandal, when he rose in the
Senate to despair over a president's conduct. From a purely
pragmatic standpoint, that speech may help Gore distance himself
from Clinton's personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Far more important, though, Lieberman's oration, suffused as it
was with a religious man's sense of propriety, offered proof that a
Jew in modern America need not diminish his faith as the price of
worldly achievement or consider such faith alone a replacement for
the crucible of public life.
</P>
<P>
   (Samuel G. Freedman, a professor of journalism at Columbia
University, is the author of ``Jew vs. Jew: The Struggle for the
Soul of American Jewry.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
