<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-BRAVES-SYSTEM     08-07 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-SYSTEM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The system is what keeps the Braves rolling along
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cincinnati - Their reputation was for professionalism, winning
and confidence, not to mention pitching. So in March 1999 when Mike
Remlinger followed Tom Glavine to the Braves clubhouse after a
spring training game in St. Petersburg, he was shocked to hear
these words: ``Man, I had no idea what I was doing out there,''
Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger, acquired from Cincinnati, also had struggled in his
first game with the Braves. It was only spring training, but
Remlinger, retelling the story 1 1/2 years later, recalls trying to
unload his pitches at 100 mph to prove to the Braves he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out for him on the mound, but it did later in the
Braves clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What? You have days like that too?' '' Remlinger
said. ``It was something that simple . . . that it was OK to have a
bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger is one of many players who have thrived in the
``relaxed'' atmosphere of the Braves organization. Andy Ashby and
B.J. Surhoff, the Braves most recent acquisitions, have noticed the
same thing. And they're not just talking about the quiet afternoons
in the clubhouse, where games of hearts and rummy are being played,
or the post-game locker room, where there's no music blaring to
dictate whether the team won or lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere around here is a part of who we are and what
makes us successful,'' said Glavine, who has helped set the tone
since the Braves run of success in 1991. ``A very businesslike
approach, a demeanor of confidence. . . . ``Sometimes we're
perceived as being cocky, but I think a lot of guys who come over
here from other organizations find out right away this is a good
situation. Our atmosphere is one that's easy to fit in and feel
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you not (like it)? You're playing for a manager who
treats you like a man, playing for an organization that's fair and
does what it can to win, and you're playing with good guys,''
Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger often struggled before finding this peace and
performance in Atlanta. Playing out the first year of his first
multi-year contract, Remlinger has become the most reliable
reliever and a poster boy for what works for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   He has talked to pitcher Stan Belinda, the newest addition,
every day since he arrived a week ago. Belinda was released by the
Rockies after compiling a 7.07 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Belinda, `This is the best place you'll ever play,'''
Remlinger said. ``I'll come back in a month and you'll tell me
that. You'll pitch better than you've ever pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger said it all adds up to success _ from the rules Bobby
Cox has for the clubhouse, to the way he and his coaches runs team
meetings, to the availability of the support staff .
</P>
<P>
   He has heard his teammate John Burkett say again and again,
``I've played baseball for 13 years, and I've finally gotten to the
big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams have people watching every move you make,''
said Burkett, who joined the Braves at the end of spring training
after being released by Tampa Bay. ``Here it's more of a relaxed
atmosphere. They expect you to get it done and be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox's rules are simple: If players want to listen to music in
the clubhouse they must wear headphones, eliminating arguments that
are common in other clubhouses. Players can't talk on cell phones
in the clubhouse. Players can't have family or friends in the
clubhouse after 3 p.m. The same rules apply for all players, stars
included.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby treats everybody the same,'' Keith Lockhart said. ``It
doesn't matter if you're a bench player or Greg Maddux, you'll get
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitchers can play golf, as long as it's not on the day
they pitch. Players can't wear earrings and have to dress the same
for batting practice, with no shorts or pullovers like other teams
might wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I've been my whole life,'' Cox said. ``I've
always tried to have my lockermates' best interest at heart. If a
guy has to get psyched up listening to music, he can do it with
headphones. . . . You can talk. You can't talk in other
clubhouses.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules are old school, but most players have come to
appreciate them because they're intended to foster respect among
teammates, and that's something Glavine thinks carries onto the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't like everybody; you won't go out to dinner with
everybody, but when you go on the field there's a respect factor,''
Glavine said. ``When it's time to go out and play, we have a common
goal, and it's, `I've got your back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger likes that pitchers take batting practice on the road,
something that didn't happen when he played for the Reds. He also
likes not having to stretch on the field before batting practice
like most every other major league team does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you need to stretch at 4 when your work doesn't start
until 10?'' Remlinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla enjoyed his first spring training in which players
weren't asked to stay late into the afternoons. Cox just asks that
they get their work in early and get on with their days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best spring training I've ever had,'' Bonilla said.
``I thought I was cheating myself. I'm seeing the benefits now.
Some people call these the dog days. They don't seem to be now. And
at 37, that's a beautiful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla's reputation was not the best when the Braves called.
But there have been no problems in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so delighted they gave me a call,'' Bonilla said. ``Even
after all the (problems), they totally disregarded all that. . . .
There's a certain professionalism in this clubhouse. There's a
relaxed atmosphere I don't think I've experienced with any team. A
clubhouse is a clubhouse, but when the bell rings, everybody is
focused and ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers appreciate the approach Braves coaches take during
scouting meetings, where they focus on positives. Instead of
saying, ``Mark McGwire is a great fastball hitter; don't throw him
a fastball,'' Leo Mazzone might point out that McGwire is hitting
.150 with two strikes against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give them five, six, seven ways to get hitters out,''
Mazzone said. ``Are you going to tell Tom Glavine he's got to jam
everybody he faces? You have to make sure to take advantage of what
pitchers do best or you'll underestimate yourself or overestimate
who's hitting. You'll put yourself in a position where you're
throwing without conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   And Braves players learn to follow Cox's lead of not getting
animated after losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the game, he's intense,'' Glavine said. ``When the game
is over, he has his 5 or 10 minutes of being ticked off and it's
over, get ready for the next game. . . . What that does is give
guys a sense of security, a sense of not panicking. If you're on a
club where everybody was throwing stuff and upset, as a player that
would tend to make you go out and play fearful of making mistakes.
What will it be like after we lose? You've got to shrug it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Belinda hasn't taken a month to make up his mind about playing
for the Braves. After his first bullpen session with Mazzone, he
told Remlinger he felt like he was 19 again.
</P>
<P>
   In just more than a week, he has become a believer with two
scoreless outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody else takes an interest in you, it boosts your
confidence,'' Belinda said. ``It gives you the feeling of these
guys really believe in me. You want to make sure you go about
things the right way and give it all you have. The confidence they
radiate rubs off on you. You start feeling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
