<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     08-07 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WEST ALWAYS A DEADEYE ON TALENT, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a round of golf in the summer of 1995, Jerry West and
Rick Pitino were discussing a kid who was going into his senior
year in high school in Pennsylvania. Pitino, then coach of
Kentucky, said he was determined to recruit the kid. West, the
executive vice president of the Los Angeles Lakers, said: ``Forget
about it, Rick. He's going pro right out of high school. And we're
going to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike today, star high school basketball players then were not
often considering the direct jump to the National Basketball
Association. ``C'mon, Jerry, he'll go to college for a year or two
at least, to get experience,'' Pitino said. West disagreed, saying,
``Not only will he go pro right away, but he's going to be one of
the greatest players in the history of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino recalled: ``I thought Kobe Bryant would probably be an
NBA player one day. And maybe even excel. But at that time, to
think he'd be one of the best of all time was quite a leap. But
West saw something that I didn't see, and that many others didn't
see. But that's Jerry West.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Jerry West have an eye for the basket, as one of
the greatest players in the history of the game, but he also had a
remarkable eye for talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to scout,'' said Jerry Krause, general manager of the
Chicago Bulls. ``I'd be there with him on the road, and it's late
at night and you're watching your fourth, your fifth, your sixth
game of the day. I've never known a great ex-player who was a great
general manager _ who would spend that kind of time at details _
other than Jerry West. He just had a passion for building a team,
and he was also a master of the salary cap. Remember, the trade he
made with Vancouver, two expensive players for two draft choices,
opened up the cap so he could afford Shaquille O'Neal.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jerry West, age 62 _ who, over two decades, was the
architect of numerous Laker championship teams, from Kareem and
Magic to O'Neal and that young first-team NBA player, Kobe Bryant _
has announced that he is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as he said Monday, it's just time for him to be
``unburdened of the pressures.'' Maybe he indeed was just burned
out; it had reached the point where he couldn't sit through Laker
home games but had to pace about in an exit ramp. In the Lakers'
final game last June which gave them the NBA title, he motored
along the freeways and had a friend telephone him with updates on
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as some have speculated, the new coach, Phil Jackson, has
gained more control of the team than makes West comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as others contend, West felt that that Jerry Buss, the
Lakers' owner, had never shown sufficient respect for his
achievements by offering him a piece of the team. At this last
championship celebration in Los Angeles, West, for whatever reason,
was conspicuous by his absence. (After 40 distinguished years in an
organization, one may cut him slack on a snit.)
</P>
<P>
   But for many, the image of West the executive fades to West the
player. The first time I saw him in person, in Chicago Stadium in
1958, he was an all-American with West Virginia. Despite a cast
covering a broken (nonshooting) left wrist, his sweet-as-marmalade
jumpers and knifelike drives staggered a superb Northwestern team.
</P>
<P>
   Krause recalled the 1965 playoff series between Baltimore _
Krause was then a Bullets executive _ and Los Angeles: ``The Lakers
were Elgin Baylor, West and three other average guys. Baylor got
hurt after five minutes of the first game and missed the rest of
the series. West took it upon himself to carry the team. He was
unbelievable.'' West, who averaged 31 points a game during the
regular season, averaged 46 in that series, scoring 49, 52, 44, 48,
43, and 42 points as the Lakers beat the Bullets in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, West was invariably candid and thoughtful, and,
it seemed, always wore the same size fedora regardless of his
accomplishments. Near the end of the 1974 season, West announced
his retirement as a player. ``I've enjoyed the camaraderie of
teammates, and I'll miss that a lot,'' he told me then. ``But right
now I feel like just going somewhere where there is no basketball
and there is no coach running my life. But I'll probably miss the
hell out of that, too, after about a week.''
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, though, West will still be around. The NBA logo
of the graceful dribbler silhouetted in red, white and blue was
taken from a long-ago photo of West. For those of us who have
enjoyed Jerry West in his various careers, we hope, as he reckoned
26 years ago, that he'll be back in basketball in a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
