<HEADLINE>
HERTZ RAISES RATES AND OTHERS FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Car rental rates jumped last month, with Hertz taking the first
step and the other national companies following immediately. Hertz,
usually the industry pacesetter, announced a $3 daily increase for
noncorporate renters, effective July 14. The weekly rate for cars
reserved 21 days in advance rose $10, and the weekly rate for
reservations made at shorter range generally went up $20. Lauren E.
Garvey, a spokeswoman, said that rises in vehicle prices, wages and
interest rates required the increases, although the company had
record earnings for the most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A week's rental of a midsize Ford in Orlando, Fla., Garvey said,
will cost $271.99 before taxes, up from $261.99, with a reservation
made 21 days ahead. The same rental at La Guardia Airport in New
York will be $489.99 before taxes instead of $469.99, regardless of
reservation time.
</P>
<P>
   Avis said it was matching the rates, as did Budget and Dollar.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WORK OF THREE WYETHS IN NEWPORT NEWS, VA.
</P>
<P>
   An art museum in Newport News, Va., has mounted a triple
exhibition of the works of the three Wyeths _ N.C., Andrew and
Jamie.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, the Peninsula Fine Arts Center, is showing 15 oil
paintings by N.C. Wyeth, one of the country's best known
illustrators in the early part of the century.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. Wyeth's son Andrew, now 83, is represented by 14 works _
watercolors, pencil and tempera _ including scenes from the area
that has been home to all the Wyeths, Chadds Ford, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest Wyeth painter, Jamie, 54, a son of Andrew's, has 19
pieces in the show, including an oil portrait of Andy Warhol.
</P>
<P>
   The Peninsula Arts Center is at 101 Museum Drive in the Mariners
Museum Park in Newport News. Telephone (757) 596-8175. Admission is
$4, $2 ages 4 to 15. The museum is open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday
through Saturday, 1 to 5 p.m. on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The show runs until Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   --IRVIN MOLOTSKY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEA CARNIVORES MOVE IN AT LAS VEGAS CASINO  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An aquarium featuring some of the most feared predators of the
sea _ venomous tropical fish, carnivorous water monitors and 10
species of shark _ recently opened at the Mandalay Bay Resort and
Casino in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Shark Reef at Mandalay Bay is constructed to resemble the
ruins of an ancient temple sinking into the sea. A path winds
through the temple's courtyard and gradually descends, to suggest
that the visitor is going underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen exhibits range from a touch tank of small stingrays and
horseshoe crabs to a display of moon jellyfish. A
1.3-million-gallon tank features the largest sharks, including
nurse sharks that reach 12 feet. Staff members in scuba gear have
an underwater communication system that lets them answer questions
from visitors as they work.
</P>
<P>
   The 105,000-square-foot aquarium was developed in conjunction
with the Vancouver Aquarium Marine Science Center in Vancouver,
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino is at 3950 Las Vegas
Boulevard South, Las Vegas, Nev., (877) 632-7400. The Shark Reef is
open daily 10 a.m. to 11 p.m. Admission is $12.95, $9.95 ages 12
and under; 5 and under are free.
</P>
<P>
   MORE OPTIONS FOR MILES WITHOUT FLYING
</P>
<P>
   Several new partnerships have been formed that allow travelers
to earn frequent flier miles without boarding an airplane. America
West has joined forces with MCI WorldCom, and Continental Airlines
has changed its long-distance alliance from MCI to AT&AMP;T. United
Airlines has formed a partnership with Abercrombie &AMP; Kent, a tour
operator specializing in adventure travel, and Best Western is
Northwest Airlines' newest hotel partner.
</P>
<P>
   America West Airlines' FlightFund members earn miles for their
MCI WorldCom phone use, with five miles for every dollar spent on
MCI WorldCom services, such as long distance, local toll service
and calling-card calls. New MCI customers are eligible for bonuses
of 1,000 miles a month for the next two months and an additional
1,000 miles for online enrollment. For information and to enroll,
call (877) 624-3863.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Continental Airlines' frequent flier program now
receive five OnePass miles for each dollar spent on residential
long distance calls made through AT&AMP;T. For information and
enrollment, call (800) 255-4600.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines program members who book Abercrombie &AMP; Kent
vacation packages from one of seven brochures through Dec. 31, and
complete the trip by the end of 2001, are eligible for 5,000
Mileage Plus miles. For reservations, call (800) 323-7308.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in Northwest Airlines' frequent flier plan receive
250 WorldPerks miles for each stay at a Best Western International
hotel in North, Central or South America. For reservations, call
(800) 937-8376.
</P>
<P>
   NEW WEB CHOICES FOR VISITORS TO JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   The Japan National Tourist Organization has redesigned its Web
site, www.jnto.go.jp, and launched a site specifically for North
Americans, www.japantravelinfo.com.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned site includes timetables for domestic Japanese
railways and air routes, a directory of restaurants, and listings
of cultural activities, self-guided walking tours and weather
forecasts. The new Web site includes visa requirements, a list of
national holidays and a directory of tour operators.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN DOORS TO HONOR JEWISH HERITAGE
</P>
<P>
   Jewish sites in 16 European countries will simultaneously open
their doors to the public on Sept. 3 for a European Day of Jewish
Culture, in recognition of Jewish heritage as an integral part of
European tradition.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The list includes about 300 sites, including synagogues,
cemeteries, ritual baths, museums and medieval ghettos in Austria,
Belgium, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech Republic,
France, Germany, Greece, Italy, Portugal, Romania, Slovakia, Spain,
Switzerland and Britain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Italy alone, sites in nearly 40 towns and cities will be
open, as will more than two dozen synagogues and Jewish cemeteries
in the Alsace-Lorraine region of France.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Concerts, lectures, performances, guided tours, exhibitions and
other events are also planned. These range from a Jewish book fair
in Bologna to concerts of Sephardic Jewish music and Jewish food
tastings in Girona and Toledo, Spain, to publication of a new
brochure on local Jewish history in Bratislava. In Florence, the
Italian Culture Minister Giovanna Melandri is to attend a ceremony
formally inaugurating restoration of the ornate synagogue and
Jewish museum at Via Farini, 4.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sites on display date back centuries. Some, like the
Old Jewish Cemetery in Prague, and the two medieval synagogues in
Toledo, are world famous. Others, like the 18th-century synagogue
in Pfaffenhoffen, France, are used as Jewish museums. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But most, including the baroque synagogues in Carmagnola and
other towns in Italy's Piedmont region, are generally closed to
public access, little known or out of use.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is coordinated by the European Council of Jewish
Communities (www.ecjc.org), the Strasbourg-based Agency for the
Development of Tourism of the Bas-Rhin
(www.sdv.fr/judaisme/journee/europ/3sept.htm), B'nai B'rith Europe
(www.bnaibrith-europe.org/program.html), and the Red de Juderias de
Espana (www.redjuderias.org), based in Girona. (Note that some of
these sites do not yet list the full program.)
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Europe has included it as part of its campaign
promoting ``Europe, a Common Heritage.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The event is an expansion of an Open Doors to Jewish Heritage
program initiated in Alsace in 1996, which has grown each year
since then. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --RUTH ELLEN GRUBER &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
