<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-JEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWS VOICE PRIDE IN SELECTION OF LIEBERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (See GORE-LIEBERMAN and related stories) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of political leanings or depth of spirituality,
American Jews expressed great pride on Monday that one of their
own, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, had been picked by Vice
President Al Gore to be his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   They were proud, they said, not only that a Jew had made it for
the first time into the highest echelons of U.S. politics. Their
pride was also in America itself, for having reached a point that
it could accept the possibility of a Jew _ and an Orthodox Jew at
that _ being a proverbial heartbeat from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects a coming of age and maturity, both for American
Jewry and our political system,'' said Gary Rosenblatt, editor of
The Jewish Week, a newspaper based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For some Jews, pride was tempered by concern that having a Jew
in a position of such prominence might trigger an anti-Semitic
backlash or, at the least, feelings of unease among other
Americans. Indeed, political chat rooms on the Internet focused on
the Lieberman designation all day on Monday, and many of the
comments were rawly anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 p.m., an America Online message board set up to discuss
Lieberman had received more than 14,000 postings, compared with
2,000 messages received on a similar board created after Dick
Cheney was named the Republican vice-presidential nominee. At times
on Monday, anti-Semitic slurs and other offensive language made up
half the conversations.
</P>
<P>
   But many Jews, including the leaders of major Jewish groups,
said that, while anti-Semitism remains an inescapable fact of life,
it is waning in this country and has been pushed far from the
political and social mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Ismar Schorsch, chancellor of the Jewish Theological
Seminary in Manhattan, called Gore's selection of Lieberman ``a
historic step forward in the complete integration of Jews in
American society.'' But Schorsch added that it was perhaps an
inevitable step, given the fact that Jews were already highly
visible in the upper reaches of American life, from corporate
boardrooms to the U.S. Senate and even the president's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this nomination just confirms the status of Jews in
American society,'' he said. ``It's not a breakthrough. It's a
confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is a development, he and others said, that will
ultimately benefit members of all minority groups whose presence on
the national tickets of the major political parties had been
virtually unthinkable until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very special day not only for the Jewish people,'' said
Elie Wiesel, winner of the 1986 Nobel Peace Prize and chronicler of
the Holocaust. ``Now the political system is open to all men and
women, of all ethnic origins.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, perhaps, there were expressions of uncertainty about
a Jew's rising so close to the top. This concern is often summed up
in a question that is, at once, self-mocking and sincere: is it
good for the Jews? After enduring centuries of hostility and
oppression, many Jews are not totally comforted by their latter-day
success and remain uneasy when co-religionists reach positions of
influence and power.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude was reflected in the comments Monday of Shlomo
Singer, 33, who lives in the Borough Park section of Brooklyn, a
neighborhood of New York City inhabited largely by Hasidic Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jews are too visible, it's bad news,'' Singer said. ``The
Jews have to remember that they're in a diaspora and that they have
no business running politics.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, attitudes like that are ``sort of hard-wired
into our system, for better or worse,'' said Rabbi Avi Shafran,
director of public affairs for Agudath Israel of America, an
Orthodox group based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, it is leavened with pride,'' he said,
and other agreed with him that feelings of apprehension are not
nearly as strong, or as widely held, as they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, some Jewish leaders saw Lieberman's ascension
as an opportunity to show Americans that Orthodox Judaism is a
diverse world and not solely the province of bearded men in black
caftans.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the campaign, I'd be very surprised if the
picture of the Orthodox Jew, active in his religion but also very
much part of this world, hasn't been elevated in the eyes of
Americans.'' said Dr. Mandell I. Ganchrow, president of the Union
of Orthodox Jewish Congregations of America, said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Jews were delighted by the Lieberman appointment. Among
them was Rabbi Michael Lerner, editor of Tikkun, a liberal magazine
on Jewish affairs. ``Rather than championing dramatic escalations
in spending for social purposes and to end poverty and oppression,
he will champion defense spending,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Jewish right, many disapprove of the senator's support of
abortion choice and gay rights, and are unhappy that he has not
supported calls for freeing Jonathan J. Pollard, the American Jew
serving a life prison sentence for spying for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the dominant feeling among Jews was that they
had arrived. ``For everything there is a time,'' said Abraham
Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League, ``and this
is the time for a Joe Lieberman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
