<HEADER>
A5210 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VP-GRAHAM08-FLA-COX     08-07 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-GRAHAM08-FLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Democrats: Lieberman is `outstanding' choice
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ South Florida's Jewish Democrats, who
already vote in large numbers, are likely to come out even stronger
because of the ``great excitement'' about having a Jewish running
mate for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut will join Gore in
Nashville today for the formal announcement of the new Democratic
presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Joe Lieberman is an outstanding selection,'' said
Florida Sen. Bob Graham, who is vacationing in Wyoming and was
among those being considered for the number two slot by Gore.
Supporters of Florida's senior senator said that while disappointed
that Graham's was not chosen, Gore's decision was ``a bold one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a fantastic choice,'' said Attorney General Bob
Butterworth who is Gore's state campaign chairman and Graham's top
cheerleader. ``Sen. Lieberman is going to be very strong in South
Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Monte Friedkin, a major contributor to Jewish causes and
chairman of the Palm Beach County Democratic Party said ``phones
are ringing off the hook. There is great excitement in the Jewish
community.''
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans have made gains with both groups, Jewish and
black voters are among the Democratic Party's most loyal
supporters. Florida Democrats had been counting on Graham to help
push Gore over the top here in November, but now they believe
Lieberman will be cause enough excitement to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help us not only with Gore but Lieberman will help
with congressional races and all the way down the ballot,'' said
Bob Poe, chairman of the Florida Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Poe believes that an increased Jewish voter turnout could be
especially helpful to Jewish state Rep. Elaine Bloom of Miami Beach
who is running an uphill congressional race against Republican
incumbent U.S. Rep. E. Clay Shaw of Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had anyone at this level of politics,'' said
Friedkin of the 58-year old Lieberman. ``I thought Gore wouldn't do
it. It's a gutsy move.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time a person's religion was an issue on the national
ticket was when Catholic John F. Kennedy ran for president in 1960.
He had to convince certain segments of suspicious voters that he
would not be beholden to the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 21st Century we ought to be talking about people's
records and not their religion,'' said Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   Said Friedkin, ``It will certainly wake-up the anti-Semite crowd
but they weren't going to vote for Democrats anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
