<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS TAKE THIRD STRAIGHT FROM YANKEES, 8-5 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Seattle manager, Lou Piniella, stepped from the
visitors' dugout before the National Anthem Monday, made eye
contact with his counterpart across the field and dramatically
doffed his cap and bent a knee in respectful tribute. Yankee
Manager Joe Torre and his staff responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Those might be the last acts of civility between teams possibly
heading for a playoff showdown. The Mariners whipped the Yankees,
8-5, in spite of four home runs by the Yankees on a hot and swampy
afternoon, and exchanged knockdown pitches before departing Yankee
Stadium with three straight victories in the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cranky day for the Yankees, all things considered:
After reliever Jeff Nelson was ejected for offering an opinion on
the work of home plate umpire Mark Carlson, Chuck Knoblauch, the
Yankees' lead-off hitter, was placed on the 15-day disabled list
with an elbow injury that may or may not improve this season. The
Yankees made a small deal for the backup infielder Luis Sojo,
trading the minor league pitcher Chris Spurling to the Pittsburgh
Pirates, and a larger acquisition in claiming the slugger Jose
Canseco on waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, on the disabled list for the first time in his
10-year career, initially hurt his right elbow making an awkward
throw against Baltimore July 24. Knoblauch's condition has not
improved, and he was given a dye test Monday, which club officials
said confirmed an earlier diagnosis of inflammation. Knoblauch
mentioned on Sunday that he has a tear.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the exact nature of the injury, it could have
serious consequences for the Yankees. Knoblauch has been a crucial
member of the team, in spite of his throwing jitters, because he is
such an effective leadoff hitter. The Yankees hope his condition
can improve to the point that he can throw and play second base
again. ``Hopefully, he can continue,'' said Brian Cashman, the
Yankees' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch can still hit, in spite of his elbow trouble, and if
he can't play second base, then Torre might consider using him as
the designated hitter. Until Knoblauch returns -- possibly the
first week of September -- then Jose Vizcaino will play second and
share the leadoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter led off Monday, and the Yankees took a 1-0 lead in
the second inning when David Justice hit his 28th homer; he added
another two innings later. But in the top of the sixth inning, with
Seattle leading, 3-2, the Mariners rallied against Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and runners at first and second, Neagle got ahead
of Rickey Henderson, no balls and two strikes. But Neagle
eventually walked Henderson - his critical mistake, Neagle would
say later. The bases were loaded, the count went to three balls and
two strikes on Carlos Guillen, and Neagle tried zipping a fastball
over the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed hitting Guillen poked the ball toward right
field. Neagle was sure it was an easy fly to right fielder Paul
O'Neill. But O'Neill ran toward the wall, hit the fence and watched
Guillen's drive ride a swirling wind into the stands, just over the
314-foot sign in the right field corner. Grand slam. Yankee Stadium
usually will be a friend to Neagle, a fly ball pitcher, but this
time it hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime anybody wraps something around the pole, there's
really not a whole lot you can do about it,'' said Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley relieved Neagle and nailed Edgar Martinez with a
fastball, and Piniella patrolled the Seattle dugout, talking aloud.
When Justice came to bat in the bottom of the sixth inning,
Mariners pitcher John Halama threw a fastball behind Justice, clear
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch got away from him,'' Piniella said later. ``Although
Edgar did get hit the previous inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Halama: ``Whatever Lou said stands for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice said later he understood what Halama was trying to do,
and had no problem with that. But Justice did turn and ask the
umpire, Carlson, if he was going to give a warning to Halama, and
became somewhat animated when Carlson said no. Before the next
pitch, Justice stepped far back in the box, in anticipation of
another brushback that never came.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Justice was called out on strikes twice on pitches
that appeared to be out of the strike zone. Justice never said
Carlson retaliated for Justice's arguments, but it was apparent he
felt that way. ``Y'all got TV,'' Justice said. ``Y'all saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenallen Hill and Jorge Posada also hit home runs - too little,
on a frustrating afternoon for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
