<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PROTESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAIL REDUCED FOR MAN ACCUSED OF LEADING PHILADELPHIA PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man accused of being the ringleader of the illegal street
protests during the Republican National Convention had his bail
reduced from $1 million to $100,000 on Monday, as defendants
contended that the Philadelphia police were guilty of jailhouse
brutality and city officials maintained there was a criminal
conspiracy to shut down the city.
</P>
<P>
   During an appeal hearing, the million-dollar bail on misdemeanor
charges was ruled excessive for John Sellers, the 33-year-old
leader of the Ruckus Society of Berkeley, Calif. He denies leading
a conspiracy and insists that he only trained demonstrators in the
techniques of nonviolent civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   At the same hearing, Common Pleas Judge Lisa A. Richette
rejected a request for bail reduction for about 150 defendants
still in jail who are protesting their arrests by refusing to give
their identities to city authorities. Most of the defendants are
charged with misdemeanors, with bail of $20,000 or less. They would
probably be released with no bail once they properly identified
themselves, said the district attorney, Lynne M. Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   As more defendants from a total of 391 arrested returned to
freedom with complaints about their detention conditions, the
American Civil Liberties Union of Pennsylvania cited ``credible
stories concerning serious injuries inflicted'' in jail, and urged
anyone who was injured to file complaints with the city Police
Advisory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Frankel, executive director of the ACLU, accused city
authorities of overreacting to the provocations and relatively
petty crimes of some demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that vandalizing property, turning over trash cans,
assaulting persons and shutting down the city by blocking traffic
are not activities protected by the First Amendment,'' Frankel
said, summarizing the main street incidents that occurred last
Tuesday. ``However, they are not the kind of crimes that justify
treating the defendants as if they were dangerous urban
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The main demonstration group, R2K Network, protests the
``corruption of democracy'' through the power of Wall Street and
the globalized economy. R2K leaders accuse the city of
``criminalizing dissent'' by pre-emptively arresting some
protesters and seeking high bail, amounting to preventive
detention. R2K members noted that some of the same demonstrators
arrested in April in Washington during a similar protest were
eventually fined $5 for jaywalking.
</P>
<P>
   A network organizer, Beka Economopoulos, said some defendants
had been brutalized, denied medication and ``hog tied''
ankle-to-wrist in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The police denied the accusations and said defendants were
creating their own problems by offering fanciful identities,
staging hunger strikes and, in some cases, stripping off their
clothes to hinder identification from videotaped street protests.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John F. Street has accused the protesters of ``a very
well-thought-out, well-planned conspiracy to shut down the city.''
And the police commissioner, John P. Timoney, maintained that
protest leaders had far more than nonviolent dissent in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them conspirators and criminals and cowards,'' he said
on Friday in detailing some charges, including what he said was the
stringing of piano wire across Market Street in an attempt to
injure police officers on horseback and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   The gravity of that charge was conceded in an interview by
Bradley Bridge, an assistant legal aid lawyer with the city's
Defender Association. But Bridge complained that 70 defendants were
being held for a far less suspicious incident _ being present in a
factory raided by the police where street puppets and other protest
materials were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there negotiating and saw the puppets,'' Bridge said.
``It's appalling those guys are still in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials contended that, with the police widely praised
for exercising restraint during the protests, the demonstrators
were deprived of bloody encounters and now sought to create an
issue with allegations of jailhouse brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders argued that the city was bent on detaining
defendants beyond the Democratic National Convention next week in
Los Angeles. But they vowed that demonstrations planned for that
convention would be stronger because of the arrests in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   With bail appeals continuing, the court did not reduce the
$500,000 bail set for Darby Landy, 20, who is accused of a felony
assault on the police in a street fracas with bicycling officers
led by Timoney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
