<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KRONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIE KRONE INDUCTED INTO RACING'S HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Julie Krone began in Michigan as a
barefoot 5-year-old bareback aboard Stony Baloney, whom she called
her Wonder Pony. As an 18-year-old, she hopped a fence at Tampa Bay
Downs to take out her first jockey license. She won riding titles
in New Jersey and Florida, and 119 stakes races in every important
hub of horse racing, and became the first and only female jockey to
win a Triple Crown event when she coaxed Colonial Affair home in
the 1993 Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   None of it came easily. Krone had to convince owners that a
woman possessed the physical strength to handle a 1,000-pound
thoroughbred and the mental ballast to recognize and take
opportunities at 35 miles an hour. There were scrapes with male
jocks and two bone-jarring spills that could have snuffed out her
career.
</P>
<P>
   Now 37 and retired, the 4-foot-11-inch Krone faced one more
obstacle before she became the first woman to be inducted into the
National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame. She overcame that, too,
by stepping up on a milk carton to reach the microphone on the
podium to deliver her acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could put everyone single one of you on the back of a
horse at the one-eighth pole,'' she said, ``so you could have the
feeling of communicating with an animal you love so much. I got to
do that every day of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She entered the Hall of Fame in impeccable company. The sport's
great past was invoked by the welcoming of the 1956 Kentucky Derby
winner, Needles. The museum's historic review committee also
announced that Tom Smith, the trainer who campaigned Seabiscuit in
the 1930s, was elected posthumously to the Hall of Fame and would
be inducted next August. Racing's current glory was reflected in
the inductions of the trainer Neil Drysdale and his horse A.P.
Indy, as well as of Winning Colors, who became only the third filly
to win the Kentucky Derby in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale was presented by Peggy Whittingham, the widow of the
Hall of Fame trainer Charlie Whittingham, whom he had apprenticed
under before going out on his own to train five champions,
including A.P. Indy, and guiding Fusaichi Pegasus to victory in
this year's Kentucky Derby. The 52-year-old Drysdale, a native of
Britain, conservative and concise, offered a brief but poignant
acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career would not be possible without a very forgiving
clientele tolerating me, and a very understanding and loyal
staff,'' he said. ``But most of all, these lovely four-legged
creatures that have given my life such passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Krone was the most galvanizing inductee in the class,
prompting much discussion in the racing community over whether she
had the statistical heft to deserve election. She amassed an
accomplished record, winning 3,545 races _ or 17 percent of her
mounts _ for earnings of $81.8 million, which are records for
female jockeys. But the rider she beat on the ballot, Earlie Fires,
for example, won more than 6,000 races, and current riders in the
Hall Of Fame like Jerry Bailey and Pat Day have won more than 4,600
and 7,600 races, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But the trainers who trusted Krone on horses have been the most
vocal about her worthiness. She won the Belmont aboard Colonial
Affair for Scotty Schulhofer, giving them both their first victory
in a Triple Crown race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little leery about her being a girl,'' Schulhofer
conceded. ``But when I saw her on a horse for me firsthand, I could
see she was a great little horsewoman. She's got great finesse,
beautiful hands on a horse, and good communication. You don't have
to bully a horse _ just talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   As her loud and warm ovation demonstrated, Krone is beloved
throughout racing for her effervescent personality and high-pitched
voice. In her heartfelt and often rambling speech, she told how the
Hall of Fame rider Angel Cordero Jr. used to tease her about how
she patiently waited on a horse until the stretch and one furious
run. Cordero would compare her to Day. From atop the milk crate,
she mimed the laid-back seat she would take on a horse and chirped,
``Angel used to say that if me and Pat Day had a baby, we'd go to
give it a bottle of milk and that baby would say, `No, no, you have
to wait an hour.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Krone was the nation's third-leading jockey with 368
victories and was in demand as a rider. If not for two serious
spills, she might still be piling up numbers today. In 1993, on the
last day of the Saratoga meet, she shattered her ankle after being
tossed to the turf by the filly Seattle Way. She returned nine
months later, but she was more fragile of body and mind. In 1995,
she had finger surgery after an accident at Gulfstream Park in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   This time her rehabilitation also encompassed counseling and
prescription medication after post-traumatic stress disorder was
diagnosed. Krone returned to racing in 1997 and rode well at
Monmouth Park, but she decided in 1999 that injuries had diminished
her skills and eroded her determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing better than getting a second chance and coming
back and doing it right,'' she acknowledged, thanking the trainers
like Jonathan Sheppard, who presented her here, who had stuck with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Krone shrugged off the second-guessing of her Hall of
Fame status. She pulled on the lapel of her blue blazer with the
Hall of Fame insignia. ``Go cast a net over 500 people in the
grandstand and see what they say,'' she said. ``From the personal
response I have received, I think most people believe I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   The trainer Neil Drysdale said the Kentucky Derby winner
Fusaichi Pegasus has been kept in racing shape with continual
gallops, while his owners try to negotiation a stallion deal. He
said Fusaichi Pegasus, the 3-year-old son of Prospector, would race
again, but didn't say which races he would run in the fall. ... The
New York-bred Turnofthecentury held off the late charge of Aldo to
capture the National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame Handicap on
Monday. The gray colt paid $9.80 for a $2 bet to win and earned a
$90,000 purse for the owners Barry K. Schwartz and Eugene Hauman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
