<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-PORT-WAR-0808-COX     08-07 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORT-WAR-0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rivalry growing between ports of Charleston and Savannah
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The Cooper River shimmers in the stifling
heat, a reflection of the rising rivalry between South Carolina's
major port here and its smaller competitor in Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Savannah nabbed from Charleston a portion of its
Asian container business from Maersk Sealand, the world's largest
shipping line.
</P>
<P>
   Maersk's container ships now call on Charleston nine times a
week, rather than 10. That 10th vessel instead goes to Savannah,
delivering merchandise from Asia to the distribution centers of
retailers including Wal-Mart Stores and Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Maersk officials say they are testing Savannah, with a far
greater stake to be decided over the next year. The shipping line
is evaluating whether to leave its South Atlantic hub in
Charleston, or move part or all of the multibillion-dollar business
to Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for Maersk's hub goes beyond Southern bragging
rights. It's a test of both ports' abilities to handle ever-larger
volumes of containers, crucial for the facilities' long-term
prosperity and the strength of their respective states' economies.
</P>
<P>
   Any significant gain of Maersk's business would be a coup for
the port of Savannah, which handles a little more than half the
container freight volume as Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists worry that Maersk is playing the two
ports against one another to pressure Charleston and Savannah to
deepen their navigational channels, which the shipping line has
said will be a key factor in its decision. Environmentalists say
that could harm wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international shipping lines are using their economic
leverage to try to force all of the ports to expand and to deepen
their channels, at taxpayers' expense,'' said Trip Van Noppen, a
lawyer with the Southern Environmental Law Center in Chapel Hill,
N.C. ``Maersk is the clearest example of this.''
</P>
<P>
   After spurring a bidding war two years ago from Norfolk, Va., to
Halifax, Nova Scotia, Maersk decided to keep its North Atlantic hub
at the New York and New Jersey ports. Those ports agreed to pay for
at least $1.6 billion in infrastructure projects over the next 27
years.
</P>
<P>
   Maersk says it is responding to a simple demand of the brutally
competitive global shipping business: It needs deeper channels in
Charleston and Savannah to accommodate its increasingly large
ships. In some cases, vessels must wait for high tide to call on
the two ports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ports do not have enough water, they are limiting our
ability to bring in the big ships already on the high seas,'' said
Nick Taro, vice president of Universal Maritime Services, the
Maersk arm that oversees the line's East Coast and Gulf Coast
business. ``We are not able to maximize our assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Charleston ranked as the nation's third-largest
container port, and Savannah ranked ninth. Buoyed by the strong
Southeastern economy, both recently completed record years in
shipments of 20-foot-long and 40-foot-long containers distributed
by trains and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In another victory last month for the Georgia Ports Authority,
Evergreen, the world's second-largest container shipper, selected
Savannah over Charleston for a new service to Asia, also involving
52 ships each year.
</P>
<P>
   Taro said Maersk, in the early stages of its evaluation, may
decide to divide its South Atlantic business between Charleston and
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   The ports authorities of South Carolina and Georgia are spending
heavily on equipment such as cranes and on expansions to speed the
transfer of containers from ships to trucks and rail cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the (shipping) lines come, they want a berth on demand, a
crane on demand,'' said Byron Hock, the Georgia Ports Authority's
director of trade development. ``They do not want to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more controversial is the deepening of the navigational
channels in Savannah and Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is in the midst of deepening
the Charleston Harbor channel from 40 feet to 45 feet. After that
project is completed in the next two to three years, South
Carolina's ports authority may start what promises to be the
complex, contentious process of deepening the channel to 50 feet or
more, said Chief Executive Bernard Groseclose.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the proposed deepening of the Savannah River's
navigational channel from 42 feet to 48 feet has received
congressional authorization, with the condition that the estimated
$230 million project win approval from federal agencies such as the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional funding for the Savannah River deepening would
come afterward, possibly two years or more from now. But it faces a
legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Southern Environmental Law Center filed a federal
suit on behalf of four conservation groups challenging the proposed
deepening. According to the suit, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
did not adequately evaulate the project's environmental impact
before issuing a favorable report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: For more information about the ports:
www.gaports.com and www.port-of-charleston.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
