<HEADER>
A5221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SHOPLIFTING-FASHION-N     08-07 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPLIFTING-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPLIFTING TO ORDER INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Va., Ill.)   By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tossed on a bed in a Brooklyn apartment were a $600
Vuitton Broadway satchel, two $600 burgundy quilted polyester nylon
skirts from Chanel, a $545 scarf with the block-lettered Chanel
logo worked into the weave and two pairs of blunt-toed $425 Prada
Nero shoes for men. None of the garments matched. But that did not
matter. The apartment was a way station on a convoluted
distribution route, and the clothes did not yet have owners.
Unless, you count the retailers they were stolen from.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are going right out to Manhattan,'' said Angie E., a
transgendered person who pilfers clothing for a living. The
apartment is hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use this fence in the diamond district,'' E said. ``There's
two brothers. They're the ones that sell it. I just mop the stuff
and get my little cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Mopping, or shoplifting, is no new development on the retail
scene. But large-scale shoplifting of luxury goods to order may be.
Although criminal law does not distinguish between shoplifting and
other kinds of larceny, law enforcement officials say that theft to
order of luxury brands appears to be a growth sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going for the upscale stores,'' said Joe Morrash, a
detective assigned to a stolen-property task force with the
Alexandria, Va., police. ``They're stealing in volume and selling
to fences and underground boutiques.'' At one drab single-family
home in Queens County, Morrash said, the New York police uncovered
over $500,000 in stolen clothes in 1998. ``The inside looked like
Macy's,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's isn't the only target of enterprising thieves. As label
culture signals social arrival, even crooks are getting into the
act. ``It's a society where everybody's got their Fendi and their
Chanel and their Vuitton,'' said Gerald Dupree, 39, a Brooklyn
maintenance worker who said he left a career as a semiprofessional
shoplifter when he broke a longtime heroin habit four years ago.
``You've got to keep pace.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a breathtaking pace. In a survey conducted by the
University of Florida, retail ``shrinkage'' _ as shoplifting is
euphemistically called in the business _ was shown to have caused
losses exceeding $8.9 billion in 1997, the last year for which
figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, police officials say, an increasing number of
semiorganized crime syndicates, many of them South American, have
been operating along the Eastern Seaboard, in urban centers and at
upscale suburban malls. ``It's not normal shoplifting anymore,
where they're stealing one or two items,'' said Andrew McColl, a
Washington-based agent for the Federal Bureau of Investigation, who
heads a task force on property crime. ``They're going for the
leather coats, the luxury items. The last arrest we made at Tysons
Corner mall here, they had $100,000 in goods.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to imagine running up a total like that when you
consider the tagged prices of goods the thieves are now after.
``You can order a Chanel suit in size 10, and there are people who
can mop it and fences who have the goods,'' Dupree said. Such suits
typically cost around $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Angie E. is a thief whose audacity has led her, by her own
account, to steal satchels from Louis Vuitton, baguettes bags from
Fendi, shoes from Prada and scarves from Hermes, goods that are
often kept in glass cases or under lock and key. She is, as Dupree
said, ``one of the ever-famous fierce girdle bandits of New York,''
a term referring to the practice of stuffing stolen goods into
underclothes. ``One thief I know put a whole mink in a girdle,''
Dupree asserted. Another, he said, would ``go into a jewelry
counter and, you know how they have chains hanging on display
racks?'' He paused. ``She could just lift the chains up all at once
and drop them down her sleeves.''
</P>
<P>
   At Saks Fifth Avenue last week a salesman said, ``If you don't
nail it down, they're going to take it.'' He was recounting an
episode in July, when a woman grabbed six $200 Coach bags from a
counter near the main Fifth Avenue exit and bolted. Although the
bags were equipped with acoustomagnetic sensors, designed to
trigger an alarm, that did not serve as a deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think they care about the sensors?'' asked the
salesman, who, like most of the retailers I interviewed, did not
want to be identified. ``They're in, they're out, it's fast. Who's
going to chase them for the bags? The bags are insured.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of shoplifting is an abiding taboo. Only one of a
dozen luxury store managers in Manhattan I spoke to would consent
to discuss shrinkage on the record. The response of Ellen
Hopfinger, manager of the Versace store on Fifth Avenue, was
typical. ``It's not something we would ever talk about,'' Hopfinger
said. ``I used to work at another luxury store, Armani, and no one
talks about it, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are various, explained Bruce Van Kleek, a member of
the Loss Prevention Advisory Council at the National Retail
Federation. ``It points to internal problems, high turnover, people
coming and going all the time,'' he said. Public admissions about
shoplifting problems can also, of course, give potential thieves a
heads up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sick that you have to write about these things,'' said
Stephanie Greenfield, a retailer who attributes a low level of
shrinkage at her two Scoop stores in Manhattan to security guards
posted at every entrance. Still, she said: ``It's going to happen.
Look at the economy. Everybody wants stuff. I don't think it's only
people who can't afford it. I think there's a prejudice that people
don't steal on all class levels, all income levels. There's a
mistake people make only looking at one type of crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Kleek added that shoplifters ``come in all shapes and sizes,
from the 10-year-old stealing a comic book to sophisticated
criminal gangs.''
</P>
<P>
   The innovation, Morrash said, is that inroads are being made on
the luxury goods trade by professional gangs with greater levels of
sophistication and taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South Americans are only doing upscale stores now,'' he
said. ``The Limited, Nordstrom, Lord &AMP; Taylor, Bloomingdale's.''
</P>
<P>
   Goods obtained by one Chilean syndicate, the Washington police
reported, were later used to stock a ``legitimate'' Los Angeles
boutique. ``We had six guys who'd stolen $150,000 in three days,''
Morrash said. ``They move around the major cities like L.A., New
York, Washington and Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   They rent hotel rooms and getaway cars. They use sophisticated
signaling methods to rake designer clothes into bags. One group
compiled a manual for ``contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never wander around with any of the pieces you are planning to
take,'' read a copy of these guidelines that I obtained, ``because
not only will the salespeople want to help you or hold them for you
or put them in a dressing room for you, all of which defeat your
purpose, but it gives security a chance to count how many you
have.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time an alarm sounds, most professional thieves are gone.
In Manhattan particularly, where shoppers are made uneasy by
excessive security and surveillance, shoplifters often have
preferred exits from their favorite stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Madison Avenue side of Barney's,'' E. said, citing an
example ``The Fifth Avenue entrance to Saks. I did a job at
Pink's,'' the London shirtmaker with a branch on Madison Avenue and
53rd Street. ``They had $165 Sea Island shirts and a side door with
nobody around,'' she said. ``I got six. Everybody's always
complaining that they can't find anyone to wait on them. I say:
`Thank you. Let's keep it that way.'''
</P>
<P>
   An assistant manager at Pink, who would not give his name,
responded, ``That's sad, but that's New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoplifters have been known to line shopping bags with foil or
duct tape to thwart sensors. But Van Kleek of the retail federation
said that the spate of successful theft owed less to cunning than
to new levels of brazenness.
</P>
<P>
   It is a view that Dupree, the former thief, confirmed. The
secret of success, he said, is a formula that rings of business
motivational seminars: ``You go in there thinking, `This is mine
and I'm taking it with me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
