<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-ANNOUNCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN ANNOUNCEMENT IS AIMED AT STEALING REPUBLICAN THUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See GORE-LIEBERMAN and related stories) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a select number of other journalists covering the Gore
campaign, Claire Shipman of NBC News received the official word on
Monday about Sen. Joseph Lieberman's selection as Vice President Al
Gore's the running mate before even Lieberman did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the calls at 4:30 a.m., and we put together a package at
5 a.m.,'' said Shipman, who added that she had been working the
phones for days. ``The deal was I was going to use it at 7 a.m. and
not before.''
</P>
<P>
   At a few minutes to 7, Katie Couric, the co-host of ``Today,''
offered a tease about the news that would be elucidated at the top
of the hour. The Associated Press put out an urgent bulletin, and
the Gore campaign was off on a fast break with its hottest news day
in months. By 7:01 or thereabouts, every major network and a
variety of news-oriented Web sites were buzzing over Gore's choice
of Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, was by no means an accident. In the wake of a
Republican convention as tightly choreographed as a modern ballet,
the Democrats were answering with a political announcement as
finely plotted as a three-act whodunit. The aim, Democratic
officials said, was to quell the post-convention Republican thunder
by a pre-emptory saturation of news pages, Web sites and airwaves
with the choice of Lieberman, a selection that allowed commentators
to use words like ``bold'' and ``historic.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all part of an effort to make a big splash going into the
Democratic convention next week, and to draw vivid contrasts
between the ways in which Gore and Gov. George W. Bush picked their
running mates _ as if to put forth the selection process as a
metaphor for the kinds of administrations they would preside over.
Aides to Gore were quick to point out that Bush's choice of Dick
Cheney leaked out so haphazardly that the Bush campaign was made to
look indecisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to throw out information in a very controlled,
businesslike fashion,'' said an official in the Gore campaign,
``while they lost control of the process very early on.''
</P>
<P>
   A commentator on MSNBC's ``Equal Time,'' Paul Begala, a former
speechwriter and adviser to President Clinton, said that in an age
when the press and the public try to deconstruct every television
image, ``process is often message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of Gore's message is that he is experienced and
intelligent,'' Begala added. ``Nothing could prove it better than
the way he handled this. He kept his own counsel, then he made his
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident, either, that the news was spread by the
campaign 32 hours in advance of the formal declaration by Gore at a
rally on Tuesday in downtown Nashville that was to include a
performance by the pop singer Jewel. The idea was to turn the news
conference into something like political infotainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting coverage all day today, all day tomorrow and
getting a lot of coverage probably on Wednesday and Thursday,'' the
Gore campaign official said. ``The pick is a historic pick, and you
want to leverage something like this as much as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, having served as defense secretary during the Persian
Gulf war, has a higher public profile than Lieberman, whom the
Democrats essentially will have to introduce to a large percentage
of American voters. Gore campaign aides said they needed to make
sure that they got the first shot at ``defining'' Lieberman for the
public.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, close advisers to Gore spent the wee hours on
Monday lining up prominent Democrats to speak for Lieberman on
morning and daytime news programs. Among those recruited were Sens.
John B. Breaux of Louisiana, Joseph R. Biden Jr. of Delaware, Frank
R. Lautenberg of New Jersey and one of the others who had been
mentioned for the vice presidential slot, John Edwards of North
Carolina. Former Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York, Eleanor Holmes
Norton, the nonvoting House delegate from the District of Columbia,
and Labor Secretary Alexis Herman also offered their opinions in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's a situation where once the decision is made by
the vice president, you have to be very aggressive to control the
news,'' said another Gore aide.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have refined their ideas about managing the news
in the years since 1984, when the last groundbreaking nominee,
Geraldine Ferraro, was picked to run with former Vice President
Walter Mondale. That year, said Martin Kaplan, who was Mondale's
chief speechwriter at the time, Ferraro was flown overnight to
Minnesota and appeared with Mondale the next morning, just as the
story broke. The event pretty much spoke for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most dramatic moments I've ever been at,''
Kaplan said. ``There were tears in the eyes of some of the Secret
Service people in the chamber.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
