(NYT16) JAKARTA, Indonesia -- Aug. 7, 2000 -- INDONESIA-WAHID --
Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid, left, dozes off as his
speech is read to the People's Consultative Assembly at the
Parliament building in Jakarta on Monday. Admired for his
integrity, democratic ideals and intellect, Mr. Wahid has drawn
constant criticism for his disorganized and impulsive leadership
style, particularly at a time when Indonesia struggles with
economic collapse, sectarian violence and political disarray. The
60-year-old president, who is virtually blind, has talked in the
past of delegating daily administration to a chief of staff.
(Anastasia T. Vrachnos/The New York Times) LITE
