(NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 7, 2000 -- CISNEROS-UNIVISION -- Former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros has resigned as president of the
Spanish-language network Univision to form a new company dedicated
to developing new housing. Cisneros, the former mayor of San
Antonio, also has resigned his position on Univision's board of
directors. Before joining Univision, Cisneros was involved in a
scandal involving false statements made to the FBI about money he
paid a former mistress. He pleaded guilty to a single misdemeanor
count of lying to the FBI in 1999 and was fined $10,000. Cisneros
talking to reporters after his arraignment at federal court in
1998. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
(NYT6) UNDATED -- Aug. 7, 2000 -- SCI-CULTURE-THOUGHT -- Recent
work by Dr. Richard Nisbett, a social psychologist at the
University of Michigan, and his colleagues, have found that people
who grow up in different cultures do not just think about different
things: they think differently. `We used to think that everybody
uses categories in the same way, that logic plays the same kind of
role for everyone in the understanding of everyday life, that
memory, perception, rule application and so on are the same,`
Nisbett said. `But we're now arguing that cognitive processes
themselves are just far more malleable than mainstream psychology
assumed.` Nisbett in an undated photo. (University of Michigan/The
New York Times)
(NYT5) STRATHAM, N.H. -- Aug. 7, 2000 -- SCI-NILE-VIRUS-2 -- West
Nile virus appears to be settling in for the long haul in the North
East region. More slowly than expected, but steadily, the
mosquito-transmitted virus is dispersing from last year's focal
point in northern Queens, leaving a trail of dead birds that so far
extends north to Boston, west to Syracuse, and south to Maryland.
Sarah MacGregor, head of the Dragon Mosquito Control, Inc., holds a
Salt Marsh mosquito. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
(NYT4) UNDATED -- Aug. 7, 2000 -- SCI-NILE-VIRUS-1-B&AMP;W -- West Nile
virus appears to be settling in for the long haul in the North East
region. More slowly than expected, but steadily, the
mosquito-transmitted virus is dispersing from last year's focal
point in northern Queens, leaving a trail of dead birds that so far
extends north to Boston, west to Syracuse, and south to Maryland.
West Nile Encephalitis as magnified by an electron microscope.
(Institut Pasteur/The New York Times)
(NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 7, 2000 -- GORE-LIEBERMAN-2 -- Sen. Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn., is Vice President Al Gore's pick as his running
