<HEADLINE>
WORLDFOR NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: LEADER'S WORLD TOUR
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Chavez has arrived in Saudi Arabia on the first
leg of a tour that includes stops in every member nation of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. He said the main
goal of his trip was to coordinate the details of an OPEC meeting
in Caracas next month, but King Fahd said his country and Venezuela
also wanted to continue limits on oil exports in order to maintain
prices at $30 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PRONOUNCEMENT ON KASHMIR
</P>
<P>
   Reassuring hard-liners, and perhaps straining the cease-fire
process, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee told Parliament that
while peace talks with one of Kashmir's militant groups were
without conditions, no decision would be outside the framework of
the constitution _ which precludes the possibility of permitting
Kashmir's secession from India.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: FLOOD VICTIMS
</P>
<P>
   Flooding in eastern India has claimed more than 120 lives and
left more than 2.5 million people homeless, authorities said. The
state of Assam has been hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: INTERNET POLICE
</P>
<P>
   New police units will monitor the Internet, the official New
China News Agency reported. Local governments in at least 20
Chinese provinces and cities have reportedly established groups to
maintain order on computer networks. China is embracing the
Internet for e-commerce but remains wary of its role in
disseminating politically sensitive information. Internet experts
say the country is fighting a losing battle trying to keep tabs on
the country's Internet users, now 17 million strong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
