<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL PROBING STOLEN PATIENT RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Dana-Farber Cancer Institute will begin notifying
12,000 patients this week that personal information, including
Social Security numbers, may have been stolen from its records and
used fraudulently.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital and law enforcement officials said a major
investigation is under &UR;  &LR; way to determine the extent of the theft
that could leave cancer patients fighting to clear their financial
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything in our power to make sure this does not
get in the way of medical care,'' said Dana-Farber chief operating
officer James Conway. ``There is no question.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman patient, who Conway refused to discuss because of
confidentiality laws, is so far the only person authorities say has
been victimized by the identity theft. The patient could not be
reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A temporary Dana-Farber employee, working as a patient intake
worker, allegedly used the patient's name and other data to obtain
$2,500 in long-distance and other telephone service, officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Boston Police department's Major Case Unit is
investigating the financial and credit histories of several
patients to determine whether the same scheme was used with them,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman charged in the alleged scheme had the personal data
for 23 other patients in her pocketbook, according to court
records. A co-worker allegedly found the information at the woman's
home and returned it to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dana-Farber officials said the records that were allegedly
accessed would typically include a patient's name, Social Security
number, date of birth, next of kin, and health insurance carrier.
Medical records are kept separately and are not involved, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely no inkling that clinical information was
involved here,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital and law enforcement officials would not say what
triggered the discovery of the theft. But Conway said the hospital
learned of the problem July 28 and contacted Boston police that
day.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the first suspect in the case, Marlene Honore, was
arraigned in on one count of larceny over $250 for stealing the
$2,500 in telephone service, and one count of identity theft for
allegedly giving a patient's personal data to the telephone company
when it installed a phone line.
</P>
<P>
   Honore pleaded not guilty and bail was set at $500. Her
court-appointed attorney, Gus Sanderson, said in court that Honore
has been assisting the investigation and has shared information
with Boston police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may very well not have the right person,'' Sanderson
said. Honore is a native of Haiti who is living in the United
States on a green card and lists a Woonsocket, R.I., apartment as
her home address in court records.
</P>
<P>
   Honore worked at the hospital from February until May of this
year, during which time 12,000 patients came to Dana-Farber for
treatment. In letters to patients, Conway said the hospital will
apologize and promise to help patients settle any problems linked
to identity theft.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital will urge patients to check their credit histories
and if they discover a problem they should contact the hospital,
which has hired a firm with expertise in resolving credit history
disputes to assist patients.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said the hospital in January began running criminal
background checks on full-time, non-medical personnel, and began
checking medical personnel in July. Next month the hospital planned
to begin checking the criminal backgrounds of temporary workers.
Honore has no prior criminal record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
