<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruling by Arbitrator Splits Arthur Andersen in Two
</P>
<P>
   An international arbitrator ruled that the world's largest
consulting firm could separate from the the world's largest
accounting firm. The ruling frees Andersen Consulting, with 65,000
employees, from its parent company, which now consists entirely of
Arthur Andersen, a tax and auditing firm with 77,000 employees. In
exchange, Andersen Consulting will have to give up its name and pay
Arthur Andersen $1 billion. Analysts called the decision, coming at
the end of a three-year battle, a major victory for the
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Settles a Lawsuit
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns, the sixth-biggest United States securities firm,
paid $30 million to settle a lawsuit over its role as an adviser on
an ill-fated takeover, said lawyers involved in the case. The case
sent tremors through Wall Street two years ago when a federal jury
in California found the firm was negligent in the way it advised
its client, Daisy Systems, on a 1989 purchase of Cadnetix, and
awarded $108 million in damages to shareholders. The judge later
reduced the award to $36 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two Millstone Reactors to Be Sold
</P>
<P>
   Dominion Resources said it was buying Northeast Utilities' two
nuclear reactors at Millstone Point, near New London, Conn., for
$1.3 billion, in what the buyers said was a record price for a
nuclear plant.
</P>
<P>
   ABC to Correct Organic Food Story
</P>
<P>
   ABC News said a report it showed twice, challenging the assumed
benefits of organic food, was based in part on research that did
not exist. ABC said it would issue a correction during ``20/20'' on
Friday night. In the report, the correspondent John Stossel said
that research commissioned by ABC showed that conventional produce
does not necessarily have more pesticide residue than organic
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Rise on Interest Rate Hopes
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose for a third day on optimism the economy is slowing
enough that the Federal Reserve will not raise interest rates again
in 2000. The Nasdaq composite index climbed 75.63 points, or 2
percent, to 3,862.99. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 16.39 points, or 1.1
percent, to 1,479.32. And the Dow Jones industrial average gained
99.26 points, or 0.9 percent, to 10,867.01.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Associates to Revamp
</P>
<P>
   Computer Associates International, seeking to bolster its
sagging stock, reassigned senior managers and said it intended to
use spinoffs or other strategies to tap the value of fast-growing
units now overshadowed by the company's main businesses. Charles B.
Wang is turning over the job of chief executive to Sanjay Kumar,
who had been president and chief operating officer. Wang will
continue as chairman. Computer Associates shares have fallen from
their 52-week high of $79.4375 to below $24 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros Is Leaving Univision
</P>
<P>
   Henry Cisneros, the former Housing Secretary in the Clinton
administration who became president and chief operating officer of
Univision Communications, the largest Spanish-language television
broadcaster in the United States, announced that he was leaving
after three and a half years ago to run a company that will build
affordable housing in downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings Fall at British Airways
</P>
<P>
   British Airways reported a 65 percent plunge in quarterly
earnings, attributing the poor performance to the effects of the
strong British pound and the rising price of jet fuel. The airline
is trying to break out of a prolonged slump, partly through a
proposed deal to acquire KLM Royal Dutch Airlines. But there were
signs that those negotiations have not advanced very far.
</P>
</TEXT>
