<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-ASSESS-2TAK     08-07 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: LIEBERMAN'S REPUTATION FOR PROBITY SEEN AS MAJOR FACTOR
IN SELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-LIEBERMAN) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After striving for more than a year to outrun
President Clinton's restless shadow, Vice President Al Gore on
Monday made his boldest bid yet for autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   By picking Sen. Joseph Lieberman, one of the earliest Democrats
to rebuke Clinton during the impeachment proceedings, Gore's
objective, his advisers and other leading Democrats say, is to seek
to replace his political partner of eight years with a fresh _ and
untainted _ face who is regarded as one of the most upstanding
politicians in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats close to Gore also said he was seeking a No. 2 who
could inject a note of excitement into the race and illuminate the
Democratic ticket, as polls show that Gov. George W. Bush is on the
ascendancy after his triumphant convention in Philadelphia last
week.
</P>
<P>
   At that convention, the Bush campaign left no doubt it will make
the moral lapses of Clinton a basic subtext of its strategy,
emphasizing the need to restore dignity and honor to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very clear after Philadelphia that these guys are going
to run a campaign of innuendo and guilt by association,'' said Al
From, the executive director of the Democratic Leadership Council,
a moderate group that Lieberman had chaired for five years. ``It's
going to be harder for Republicans to sustain that campaign. A
Gore-Lieberman ticket is not going to be associated with bad
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the very factors that make Lieberman an enticing choice also
make him a vulnerable one.
</P>
<P>
   In picking the first Jewish running mate _ and an Orthodox one
at that _ Gore hopes to underscore his willingness to break the
political rules and display a dash of daring that has largely been
absent from his campaign. But while the choice could energize
Jewish voters (though they are overwhelmingly Democratic anyway) it
could alienate others who might not be comfortable with a Jew in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hopes to protect himself from scandals of Clinton by
tethering himself to a politician who is above reproach, and who
has spoken out not only against the president but for campaign
finance reform. The downside is that Lieberman's public
denunciations of Clinton in 1998 could give the Republicans cover
to even more forcefully raise questions about the Clinton
administration's conduct, including Gore's own fund-raising
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In turning to a politician with a decidedly moderate voting
record who prides himself as not being particularly partisan, Gore
also may have an easier time challenging Bush for the loyalties of
independent voters that he desperately needs to win. But that could
also unsettle some faithful Democrats who cringe at Lieberman's
breaks with the Democratic Party _ and Gore _ on issues ranging
from school vouchers to capital gains taxes. Some of these voters
could even end up defecting to Ralph Nader, the Green Party
nominee, Democratic strategists fear.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Gore campaign had tried to tar Bush by invoking Dick
Cheney's conservative voting record, the Bush campaign on Monday
sought to use Lieberman to undermine Gore's positions. The campaign
said Gore picked a running mate whose ideology is closer to Bush
than to the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to figure out what the Gore people were
thinking,'' said Michael Nelson, a political scientist and
authority on the vice presidency at Rhodes College in Memphis.
``He's Jewish but it's not as if the Democrats don't already have
them energized. The only thing it brings is criticism of the
president _ and I don't see that as an advantage. Like it or not,
the vice president is yoked to the president whom he served.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans acknowledged it was difficult to directly condemn
Lieberman because of his reputation for moral rectitude. William
Bennett, the conservative morals maven who is close to Lieberman,
said he could not find fault with a politician who joined him in
repudiating the film industry in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's arguably the best Democrat in the Senate,'' Bennett said.
But asked whether Lieberman's ramrod reputation would inoculate
Gore against being linked with Clinton, he made a point echoed by
some Democrats, ``I don't know that Gore becomes a saint because of
Lieberman's virtues.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans made it clear that they are not about to abandon
their drive to fasten Clinton to Gore with the same zeal that
Democrats tied Bob Dole to Newt Gingrich four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers said they had no expectation that they will drop
this refrain that Cheney declared to cheers in Philadelphia last
week: ``As the man from Hope goes home to New York, Mr. Gore tries
to separate himself from his leader's shadow. But somehow, we will
never see one without thinking of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gillespie, an adviser to the Bush campaign, practically
validated Gore's choice by calling Lieberman ``a decent man and an
honorable person.'' But, he added, ``There are just a number of
significant issues that Gore has just bitterly attacked Governor
Bush on and now he turns around and picks a running mate who agrees
with Bush on those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an even bigger danger for Gore is that several political
consultants said they did not have to think hard to come up with an
attack commercial for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It would open with a clip of Lieberman shaking his finger like
an Old Testament prophet, denouncing Clinton for ``disgraceful''
and ``immoral'' behavior. The next frame would be a clip of Gore,
celebrating Clinton as ``one of our greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial could end with side-by-side photographs of a
scowling Clinton and Gore and the tagline, ``Even his running mate
disagrees with Al Gore over what is appropriate conduct for a
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   However Lieberman is received, this much is clear: It was not a
play-it-safe choice as was Bush's pick of Cheney. That reflects the
political reality that as his convention approaches next week in
Los Angeles, Gore advisers said they felt it was necessary to do
something daring _ yet not foolhardy _ to gain ground.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats on Monday said they have come around quickly to
Gore's thinking. In assessing the other possibilities on Gore's
short list of running mates, they said that Sen. John Edwards of
North Carolina was charismatic and youthful, but would be attacked
for serving only a year and a half in the Senate. And Sen. John
Kerry of Massachusetts, they said, had the experience and a
compelling war record, but could be dismissed as a Northeast
liberal as Gore is trying to broaden his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But in keeping with the mold cast by Clinton in selecting Gore
eight years ago, the vice president demonstrated that he was not
driven by crass electoral considerations, like picking a candidate
from a battleground state. Some Democrats said they expect, though,
to hear grousing from voters who complain that in picking a Jewish
running mate, Gore is pandering to one of the most important
segments of the Democratic electoral base and one of the party's
deepest sources of contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans, however, rejected the notion that
Lieberman's religion could damage him. They said that people who
would oppose the ticket because of Lieberman's religion would
probably support the third party candidacy of Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Lieberman, Gore also showed he was comfortable with
a No. 2 who is not known as especially scintillating on the
campaign trail. (It could be, of course, that after being Clinton's
understudy, Gore did not want someone who would outshine him.)
</P>
<P>
   And the vice president's choice seemed to reflect his genuine
concern about having a No. 2 with the experience and temperament to
help him govern. In addition, many people close to Gore have long
said that if personal chemistry were the more compelling factor,
Lieberman would shoot to the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   For all the calculations of how Lieberman would help or hurt,
the senator, in an interview several weeks ago, dismissed what he _
or anyone _ could bring to the ticket. ``I presume any factor can
make enough of a difference,'' he said, ``although not a large
difference to be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The relevance of a running mate choice, he said, was that it
``may tell the American people something more about the two major
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the choice may tell the public something more not
just about Gore, but about his relationship with his political
partner for the past eight years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
