<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH LIEBERMAN, NOT ONE TO TOE THE PARTY LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2, 3, 8, 10, 11 and 15 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 3, 1998, Joseph Lieberman stood up in the U.S. Senate
to speak about Bill Clinton. They had been friends and Democratic
allies for 30 years, but the cornered president had finally
admitted having an affair with Monica Lewinsky. Anger, resentment,
a sense of betrayal: the bitter emotions had racked the nation, and
were about to find a powerful voice in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such behavior is not just inappropriate _ it is immoral,''
Lieberman said, abandoning for a principle a man who had campaigned
for him in his first political race for the Connecticut state
Senate in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is harmful, for it sends a message of what is
acceptable behavior to the larger American family,'' he added. ``I
fear the president has undercut the efforts of millions of American
parents trying to instill in our children the values of honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   With those hard words, Lieberman, the first Orthodox Jew to
serve in the Senate, became the first Senate Democrat to denounce
the president's behavior. While he ultimately voted to acquit
Clinton in his impeachment trial, the episode strongly reinforced
his reputation as a maverick Democrat, often at odds with party
leaders, and as a moral compass in the wastelands of politics.
</P>
<P>
   It was apparently with those beguiling traits of pragmatic
independence and personal integrity in mind that Al Gore tapped the
58-year-old Lieberman as his vice-presidential running mate, a
choice widely seen as his boldest stroke yet to distance himself
from President Clinton and the scandal-tainted Clinton
administration, and one to spark his campaign before the start of
the Democratic convention in Los Angeles next week.
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman was expected to help Gore shed himself of
Clinton's baggage, his selection also carried a risk, for he would
be the first Jew named to a national ticket. The weeks to come may
show whether Lieberman's faith will raise questions in the same way
that John F. Kennedy's Catholicism became a focus in the 1960
presidential election: whether religion might affect his
performance as vice president, for example, or the policies of a
Gore administration _ or a Lieberman administration _ toward the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who describes himself as an observant Jew, strictly
observes the Sabbath, from sundown on Fridays to sundown on
Saturdays. While his religion ostensibly prohibits working, riding
in vehicles and other activities during the Sabbath, Talmudic
scholars say that exceptions are allowed for Jews to act to
preserve human life or on behalf of the needs of the community.
</P>
<P>
   In public life for more than three decades, Lieberman has always
shunned campaigning and purely political activities on the Sabbath,
but has considered it his duty to attend legislative sessions, to
vote and to sit in on important public meetings. In 1988, for
example, he refused to attend the Democratic convention that
nominated him for the Senate, but has often walked five miles to
the Senate from his home in Georgetown. He has cast 75 votes on
Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been a staunch Senate supporter of Israel, but has
also backed arms sales to Saudi Arabia. And he has often found
himself in the company of Senate Republicans. In 1991, for example,
he was one of 10 Democrats to support American involvement in the
Persian Gulf war, and he was one of a handful of Democrats who
favored the deployment of American troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do what I think is right on every issue, and not
feel obliged to vote a particular way because it's the party line
or because people expect me to,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In his 12 years in the Senate, Lieberman has acquired a
reputation for steady habits, family values and faithfulness to his
beliefs _ a moderate who carefully deliberates options, sometimes
agonizing over them publicly, and often seems to be striking a
balance between conservative and liberal instincts.
</P>
<P>
   On the liberal side, he has voted for abortion rights, gun
control, tax increases, welfare reforms, consumer protections and
civil rights legislation. On environmental issues, he helped draft
clean air laws, wrote the Pollution Prosecution Act of 1990,
exposed lax security measures in nuclear power plants and supported
minimum-wage increases and laws to protect whistle-blowers.
</P>
<P>
   On the conservative side, he has been far more enthusiastic than
most of his Democratic colleagues concerning military spending. As
a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee, he has had an eye
out for Connecticut's many military industries. Among other things,
he has supported the development of an anti-missile defense system
for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to toe a party line, Lieberman broke ranks with
Democrats in 1997 during the Senate hearings on campaign finance,
which investigated fund-raising abuses by the Clinton-Gore campaign
in 1996. Other Democrats lobbed softball questions at
administration witnesses, but Lieberman asked tough questions and
tried to position himself as objective and above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   He also has been conservative on so-called family values and
related issues. He supported tuition vouchers, for example, that
would allow parents to send their children to private schools at
taxpayer expense. And while some of his colleagues have dubbed him
the ``conscience of the Senate,'' he has also been criticized as
something of a moralizer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Lieberman and William Bennett, the former secretary of
education, began handing out ``Silver Sewer Awards'' to draw
attention to the producers of sexually explicit and violent films,
music, television programs and video games. Critics were quick to
note, in a recent financial disclosure form, that the Senator had
stock in Fox and CBS, two recipients of his awards.
</P>
<P>
   He also pushed for electronic devices that would permit the
blocking of television programs that parents find offensive, has
monitored a system of voluntary ratings to guide children's
television viewing and has denounced rap music with lyrics that
celebrate violence and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is not an electrifying orator. Associates say his
politics and personality are too moderate for him to play for an
emotional edge. His speeches tend to be heavy with facts and
figures. But having run for offices since he sought his ninth-grade
class presidency, he is poised in public and at times passionate
about the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman was born in Stamford, Conn., on Feb. 24, 1942,
the son of Henry Lieberman, a liquor store owner and real estate
agent, and Marcia Manger Lieberman. He attended public schools in
Stamford and Yale University in New Haven, where he graduated with
a bachelor of arts degree in 1964. Three years later, he received
his law degree at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   For two summers during his college years, he worked in
Washington as an intern, once for Sen. Abraham Ribicoff of
Connecticut and once for the Democratic National Committee. After
practicing law for several years, Lieberman, at the age of 28, ran
successfully for the state Senate in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   One of his campaign volunteers was Bill Clinton, then a
24-year-old Yale law student. (Lieberman returned the favor in
1992, becoming the first senator outside the South to endorse the
Arkansas governor for president.) After a decade in the state
Senate, the last six as majority leader, Lieberman gave up his seat
to run for Congress, but lost.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, however, he made a comeback, winning election as
Connecticut's attorney general by a wide margin. He gained wide
popularity as an advocate for consumers and environmental issues,
and was overwhelmingly re-elected in 1986. Halfway through his
second term, he ran an uphill but successful campaign to unseat
Sen. Lowell Weicker Jr., a popular three-term Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Lieberman's Senate career, a pattern became apparent.
Lieberman voted with Democrats on civil rights and environmental
issues, but joined Republicans on several high-profile issues, like
military spending and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he first voiced support for the confirmation of
Clarence Thomas as an associate justice of the Supreme Court, but
eventually voted against him. His varying stances, however, did not
appear to harm his standing with senators on either side of the
aisle, many of whom say they respect his independence, or with the
voters. He was re-elected in 1994 with 67 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has written five books, including ``The Power
Broker,'' a 1966 biography of the late Democratic party chairman,
John Bailey; ``The Scorpion and the Tarantula,'' a 1970 account of
early failures in controlling nuclear proliferation, and ``In
Praise of Public Life,'' a study of practical politics, written
with Michael D'Orso and published this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and his wife, the former Haddasah Freilich, have each
been married twice. His first marriage, to Elizabeth Hass, whom he
met in 1963 when they were interns in Ribicoff's office, ended in
divorce in 1981. They had two children, Matthew, now 32, and
Rebecca, 31. He and Haddasah married in 1983, and she brought a son
from her previous marriage, Ethan, 24. The couple also have a
daughter of their own, Hana, 12, and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The Liebermans, who have homes in New Haven and Georgetown, are
not lovers of the social scene in Washington, preferring quiet
dinners at home. He jogs to keep in shape, and reads voluminously,
including the Bible daily. He attends services in the capital at
Kesher Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi there, Barry Freundel, is a friend, and said of the
senator: ``He's not afraid to put life's most important things in
front of politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
