<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY UNDERGOES OPERATION FOR CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second time in two years, Darryl Strawberry,
the former Yankee slugger, underwent surgery Monday to remove a
cancerous tumor in his abdomen. The surgery marked the beginning of
another and much tougher round in his fight against colon cancer,
cancer experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was in stable condition at Columbia Presbyterian
Medical Center Monday night after a team of four surgeons found and
removed an ``isolated tumor mass'' near the left kidney, Myrna
Manners, a spokeswoman for the hospital, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physicians caring for Strawberry are optimistic for an
uneventful recovery'' from surgery, Manners said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's cancer was first discovered in early October 1998
as the Yankees were steamrolling toward the World Series. Surgeons
operated on him Oct. 3, removing a 16-inch section of his colon and
36 lymph nodes. One of those lymph nodes tested positive for
cancerous cells, suggesting the cancer had begun to spread through
the lymphatic system. Strawberry underwent intensive chemotherapy
for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Though Strawberry did play last season, he missed 113 days.
Major League Baseball suspended him after he was arrested in Tampa,
Fla., in April 1999 on charges of possessing cocaine and soliciting
a prostitute. He returned to the Yankees on Sept. 1 and, over the
last 24 games of the season, hit .327 with three home runs and six
runs batted in, helping the team to its third World Series in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, while Strawberry was serving a yearlong
suspension for failing a drug test, a CAT scan revealed what
appeared to be a cancerous growth in a lymph node near the site of
his original tumor. Last week, tests at the Palms of Pasadena
Hospital in Tampa, Fla., confirmed the player's worst fears: the
cancer had returned.
</P>
<P>
   In those tests, Jonathan D. LaPook, Strawberry's
gastroenterologist, determined the cancer had spread into tissue
next to the player's left kidney but appeared not to have recurred
inside the colon itself.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons _ Mitchell C. Benson, George J. Todd, Richard L.
Whelan and Peter B. Schiff _ said after the operation that they
believed they had removed all of the cancerous tissue, Manners
said. It remained unclear what further treatment Strawberry would
be given, but it is likely to include chemotherapy, oncologists
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You trust the people who are taking care of you,'' Yankees
Manager Joe Torre said. ``He has to be convinced he's in good
hands. It's nice to have faith, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the successful surgery, it will be an uphill battle for
the former slugger. Harmon Eyre, the chief medical officer of the
American Cancer Society, said studies have shown that people who
have a recurrence of colon cancer within two years have a 5 percent
to 15 percent chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a new baby,'' Torre said, ``and that's something that
scares you the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's odds may be slightly higher because he is
relatively young at 38 years old and extremely strong, Eyre said.
That means he can withstand stronger doses of chemotherapy and more
extensive surgery than an older patient could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of people who have a recurrence of colon
cancer die from it,'' Eyre said. ``It's not a good situation, but
it's not totally hopeless, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Strawberry has made millions as a ballplayer in the last
17 years, he has told reporters recently that he is in deep
financial trouble. Strawberry, an eight-time All-Star, has five
children from two marriages. He was put on baseball's ineligible
list because he tested positive for cocaine on Feb. 28. It was the
third time he had been suspended for cocaine use in his career. In
March, he checked into a rehabilitation clinic in Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, however, he left the clinic abruptly, telling
counselors he needed to earn money. In late July, he asked Major
League Baseball to reinstate him early. He also pursued a minor
league contract with the St. Paul Saints in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has a career batting average of .259. He has hit 335
home runs and driven in 1,000 runs in 1,583 major league games with
the Mets, the Los Angeles Dodgers, the San Francisco Giants and the
Yankees. He was the National League Rookie of the Year with the
Mets in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the promise he showed that year, Strawberry's career
has been held back by numerous personal problems: twin addictions
to alcohol and cocaine, injuries, charges of tax evasion, and
failure to pay child support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
