<HEADER>
A5260 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-RECORD-HNS &LR;      08-07 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-RECORD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In two terms in the U.S. Senate, Democratic vice-presidential
hopeful Joseph Lieberman has at times voted more like a potential
running mate for Gov. George W. Bush than Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, senator from Connecticut, sponsored legislation in
support of private school vouchers, has spoken in favor of
privatizing Social Security, and was a prominent critic of
President Clinton during the impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But while he differs from Gore on a variety of issues, political
observers said Monday that Lieberman's record in the Senate could
prove a political enhancement for the Democratic presidential
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieberman's voting record places him politically to the right
of Gore, which shows that the election is not about rousting the
core voters, but playing to the center,'' said Bob Stein, Rice
University political scientist and pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gore, Lieberman supports abortion rights, and he voted
against a ban on late-term abortions, known by opponents as
partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lieberman also has called for requiring
parental consent of minors seeking abortions in federally funded
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Lieberman, a critic of the entertainment industry's
penchant for sex and violence, co-sponsored V-chip legislation to
help parents monitor what kids watch on television.
</P>
<P>
   Varied on issues of interest to gays, Lieberman sponsored
anti-discrimination legislation protecting homosexuals in
employment matters.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1994, Lieberman spoke disparagingly of the ``homosexual
lifestyle'' in backing a bill to deny funding for schools that
present materials supportive of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Senate, Lieberman has supported experimental
voucher programs that would let parents use federal funds to send
children to the schools of their choice _ a plan favored by Bush
but opposed by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schechter, chair of the Harris County Democratic Party,
downplayed the significance of conflicting positions between the
running mates, saying it's up to Gore to set the tone for the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley supported vouchers and he certainly seemed to
have a strong following among Democrats,'' Schechter said. ``I am
not sure there are big enough differences there that anyone is
going to be too concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   On defense issues, Lieberman sided with Republicans in backing
early deployment of the national missile defense system, and he
supported the war in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gore, he now supports the death penalty, although he
opposed it earlier in his career.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported the Clinton administration's anti-crime
legislation, notably mandatory sentencing guidelines for crimes
involving guns.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lieberman has been directly critical of
Clinton and Gore on campaign finance and recent controversies over
the duo's fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, noting that past fund-raising scandals present a
lingering political problem for Gore, said Lieberman's moral
rectitude on that and other issues could actually prove useful for
the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is not credible to moderates and conservatives, and to
independent and swing voters, it looks like he's pandered to a wide
range of traditional Democratic constituencies,'' Stein said.
``What he says with Lieberman is that this is a guy out front for
vouchers who's been critical of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lieberman has criticized human rights infractions in
China, he shares Gore's interest in liberalized trade and
normalizing trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's record reflects support for expanding hate crimes
laws, and for environmental initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   He backed mandatory child safety locks on guns and a five-day
waiting period for handgun buyers and a ban on semi-automatic
assault weapons. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
