<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5264 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-VP-MAIN0808-COX     08-07 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-MAIN0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman accepts Gore's VP offer
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville, Tenn. _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut joins
Vice President Al Gore here today to make his debut as the
Democratic presidential candidate's running mate and the first Jew
on a major-party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to introduce Lieberman at a downtown rally at
1 p.m., 24 hours after he offered him the post.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the first prominent Democrat to publicly criticize
President Clinton over the Monica Lewinsky affair, took the call
from Gore on his car phone Monday as he was returning from a
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ask you if you would honor me by being my running
mate,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be honored,'' Lieberman replied. ``I'd be humbled.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men had a moment ``of shared prayer,'' the 58-year-old
senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, his wife, Hadassah, two of their four children and
his mother flew to Nashville on Monday evening to have a private
dinner with Gore and his wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and Gore will be in Atlanta on Thursday with Gov. Roy
Barnes and a contingent of Southern Democratic governors to promote
the successes of welfare reform. Georgia Democratic Party Chairman
David Worley said they will attend a rally at noon at Centennial
Olympic Park downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is perhaps best known outside his home state for the
hard line he took on the Lewinsky matter and on the fund-raising
practices of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's choice of Lieberman, who nevertheless voted to acquit
Clinton on impeachment charges, may be intended to blunt efforts to
tar Gore with the Clinton character issue, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows Al Gore's sense that he is very vulnerable to the
linkage to Bill Clinton and the whole character aspect,'' said
Republican pollster Whit Ayres of Atlanta. ``This is an effort to
separate him from President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Monday had nothing but praise for Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bold thinker, he's always full of new ideas, he's
supported the changes that we've made over the last eight years,''
Clinton said, speaking to reporters while vacationing at Martha's
Vineyard, Mass. ``I think he's just an extraordinary guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also won praise from some of the core constituencies
of the Democratic Party, including the environmental activist
Sierra Club and the Human Rights Campaign, a gay and lesbian rights
group. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney also applauded Lieberman,
even though the senator, like Gore, supports free trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But Loretta Kane, acting vice president for the National
Organization for Women, said her group was disappointed Gore didn't
pick a woman to run with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not our dream candidate, but he's not a nightmare
either,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who surprised the political establishment when he
upset Republican Sen. Lowell Weicker in 1988, cuts a different
profile from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Easygoing and accessible, Lieberman is generally not regarded as
a fierce partisan, and he has worked with Senate Republicans on a
number of high-profile issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Lieberman is not a party-line Democrat,'' said Sen. Max
Cleland of Georgia, a Democrat who serves with Lieberman on two
Senate committees.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was a co-sponsor of tax-free education savings
accounts for elementary and secondary school, legislation promoted
by the late Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell of Georgia and opposed
by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a harsh critic of Hollywood and the entertainment
industry's use of sex and violence in movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore and I have pretty much walked the same path, and where
we've had disagreements they've been good-faith disagreements,
never disagreements that touch our values,'' Lieberman said Monday,
speaking outside his home in New Haven, before he received the call
from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaignsought to minimize the policy differences,
saying the two men share the same core philosophy of improving the
lives of ordinary Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ticket is going to reflect (Gore's) agenda,'' said Gore
spokesman Chris Lehane. Gore will not change his opposition to
education savings accounts favored by Lieberman, Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gore-Lieberman ticket will represent the new guard,''
Lehane said. ``A central issue of this campaign is: Do we want to
turn the clock back, which is Bush-Cheney, or do we want to move
forward?''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman learned of his selection when news leaked out early
Monday morning from Gore's headquarters in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   He was clearly surprised, telling reporters outside his home
that ``miracles happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed of this,'' Lieberman said. ``And you know what
it says to me _ and everyone else _ that every day that we are
lucky enough to be alive by the grace of God is full of
possibilities, and miracles happen. And I consider this a miracle
for which I am grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore settled on Lieberman on Sunday night after meeting with
campaign chairman William Daley, campaign manager Donna Brazile,
wife Tipper and former secretary of state Warren Christopher, who
chaired Gore's search committee, Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the running at that point included Sens. Evan Bayh of
Indiana, John Edwards of North Carolina, John Kerry of
Massachusetts, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri
and New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   Gore phoned the other potential candidates Monday afternoon and
called two ``wild card'' candidates whom Lehane declined to
identify.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is not required to give up his Senate seat to campaign
for vice president, but he would resign if he and Gore win. His
resignation would allow Connecticut Gov. John Rowland, a
Republican, to name a successor, possibly complicating the
Democratic Party's hopes of gaining a majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
