r p BC-VPORTHODOX0808-COX     08-07 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VPORTHODOX0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman's religious faith deep and long-standing
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - If he is elected, this vice president
will pray for 45 minutes every morning before breakfast. He will
drape a prayer shawl over his shoulders and attach a small wooden
box filled with Hebrew prayers, written on parchment, on his
forehead and arm.
</P>
<P>
   If he is elected he will attach passages from Deuteronomy to
every door of his vice presidential mansion. He will ask that the
food at State dinners be cooked in a kosher kitchen. He will not
drive or write or work on the Sabbath unless it is absolutely
necessary, and he will study the writings of long-dead rabbis with
names like Maimonides and Rashi and Rashbam for wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most conspicuously, if Joseph Lieberman is elected
vice president of the United States, the two-term senator from
Connecticut will put to rest a question floated in synagogues and
Jewish community centers across the country for years: Is America
ready for a Jew in the White House?
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I surprised when I woke up this morning and I heard he'd
been nominated? You bet I was,'' said Rabbi Moshe Scheiner of the
Palm Beach Orthodox Synagogue, which Lieberman attends when he is
in the area. ``I didn't think this country was ready to have a Jew
one heartbeat away from being president, but obviously (Gore) reads
the climate better than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is not just a Jew, he is an Orthodox Jew _ one of only
three in Congress out of 23 Jewish representatives and 11 senators.
(U.S. Reps. Robert Wexler and Peter Deutsch are the other two).
</P>
<P>
   He walks the 3 miles from his house to Capitol Hill if he has to
vote on the Sabbath, when driving is forbidden. He observes the
Jewish dietary laws. He studies the ancient commentary of the
Torah. He is married to the daughter of a rabbi. His own daughter
was recently bat-mitzvahed in New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been serious about his religious beliefs as long as I've
known him,'' says Dr. Michael Gelfand, president of the Palm Beach
Orthodox Synagogue and a friend of Lieberman's since their freshman
year at Yale. They were two of only four students in the class of
'64 to observe the kosher dietary laws. ``He was (Sabbath
observant) in college. This is something that has been ingrained in
him since childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   How ingrained? Lieberman once told the congregation at Palm
Beach Orthodox Synagogue that during a 12-mile road race he ran at
Yale he sang ``U'faratztah'' under his breath the entire distance
to keep himself motivated. The peppy song is the unofficial tune of
the Chabad Lubavitch sect of orthodoxy and means literally ``And
you shall spread forth.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Modern Orthodox Jew Lieberman believes that every word in
the Torah was dictated by God to Moses, says Scheiner. But instead
of building a wall around themselves as some orthodox Jewish
communities do, modern orthodoxy asks believers to fuse ancient
Judaism with the modern world.
</P>
<P>
   The concept may sound a little foreign to non-Jews. But Gore is
hoping that taken together with Lieberman's reputation for honesty
and integrity it will come off as noble and admirable, said Andrew
Grossman, a Democratic pol suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, anti-Semitic campaigns may even be welcomed by the Gore
team, Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any attack on Lieberman (as a Jew) is the worst-case scenario
for Bush,'' Grossman said. ``All it takes is for one person to open
their mouths _ and you know they are going to _ and a whole lot of
moderates are going to flee the Republican Party. ``
</P>
<P>
   From where Ed Lefkowitz sits in his home on Singer Island, the
fact that this conversation is taking place at all is a bit of a
miracle. An 80-year-old Holocaust survivor, born in Poland,
Lefkowitz said even 20 years ago if someone had told him there
would be religious Jew on the presidential ticket, he would have
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has come forward a big, big amount,'' Lefkowitz
said. ``This is a big chance for us. Hopefully he'll make the Jews
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
