<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VERIZON-WIRELESS-ART-     08-07 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-WIRELESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: UNIONS LEAVE COMPANIES SPEECHLESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to watch public relations executives from the nation's
biggest communications companies get uncomfortable? Ask them about
their unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the current circumstances I think our executives would
rather stay out of this, so we're going to decline to get involved
in this story,'' Burke Stinson, an AT&AMP;T spokesman, said Monday, the
second full day of a strike by 87,000 union workers at Verizon
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Or ask Mark Bonavia, a spokesman for the Sprint Corp. ``We
decline to discuss the issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Or Joe Chandler, a spokesman for the BellSouth Corp., which has
52,000 union employees out of 99,000 total. ``The people who are
closest to this, it's going to be difficult for them to be out
front on this right now, so you're stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at Worldcom Inc., which has fewer than 500 union workers
among its 75,000 employees, the subject is officially out of
bounds. ``We just have a policy that we don't talk about these
issues,'' said Peter Lucht, a Worldcom spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For companies that spend millions of dollars lobbying
regulators, buying advertising and trying to influence members of
the media _ not to mention having communications as their core
business _ why the sudden laryngitis? Because the unspoken secret
is that the established communications carriers that still have
unions basically wish that they did not. And the younger companies
that do not have them will do just about anything to keep them
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``All else being equal, would it make our life easier if there
were no union? Of course,'' said an executive at a large
communications carrier, on condition of anonymity. ``But we do, so
we just have to deal with it, and it's very delicate.''
</P>
<P>
   It is delicate because of fear, in particular fear of the
Communications Workers of America. But the bald fact is that a
preponderance of the communications companies that have had the
best financial performance over the last decade (Worldcom, for
instance) have not had the significant union presence of many of
the industry's laggards (AT&AMP;T and the former Bell company Nynex,
which is now part of Verizon).
</P>
<P>
   To acknowledge this is not to say that unionization is prima
facie bad for a communications company. It may just be that the
communications carriers that have had the strongest and most
powerful unions have happened to be in the weakest strategic
position, or have had subpar management or have been plain unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be that, down the road, companies with loyal
unionized work forces will fare better than even nonunion companies
in hotly contested growth businesses like wireless communications
and high-speed Internet access _ markets where the ability to
provide a reliable network and professional customer service may
matter more to customers than providing the lowest-cost product.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a reason why Verizon, the local phone behemoth
formed by Bell Atlantic's acquisition of the GTE Corp., has been
willing to tolerate a strike by tens of thousands of its workers as
it negotiates a new contract with the CWA. There is a reason why
the company has been fighting to keep its fast-growing wireless and
Internet operations union free.
</P>
<P>
   That reason is that the company, rightly or wrongly, appears to
believe that unions put it at a some disadvantage. And at least
some investors and financial analysts agree.
</P>
<P>
   This is Business 101. Few companies of any kind welcome unions.
But what makes the issue more important for the big, old
communications companies is that they are battling well-financed
competitors in various niches of their business _ especially
wireless and data communications _ that have little or no union
presence at all. So as the growth in the communications business
continues to shift to those very niches, those big old companies,
each in turn, could find themselves fighting this same battle.
</P>
<P>
   On condition of anonymity, one Wall Street analyst said Monday
that if Verizon's wireless operation were completely unionized, it
could cost the unit $300 million in additional annual expense. That
money probably means a lot more to Verizon's workers than it does
to the company; some analysts are expecting that same wireless unit
to generate $5.5 billion or more of cash flow this year. So in the
overall financial scheme, unionization may not be that big a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other factors that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're unionized,'' said John M. Bensche, a wireless
communications analyst for Lehman Brothers, ``you have less
flexibility in terms of hiring and firing people. And when you're
growing this fast and want to shift resources around in a company,
that can matter. For example, you might see a company move an
entire collections department over to customer activation at
Christmas time because it's really busy. And you might have to ask
whether they could do that if they were unionized.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon and the other Bell companies in particular have become
very familiar with union work rules (and, some might say, the ways
around them). The issue they face is that the unions can use their
leverage over the companies' core business _ providing local
telephone service _ to try pry open new business units that had not
been unionized.
</P>
<P>
   But that leverage does not exist at, say, VoiceStream
Communications, an upstart wireless company that has agreed to be
acquired by Deutsche Telekom and that has has virtually no union
presence. Even at Sprint, only 10,500 of the company's 78,000
workers are unionized, almost all of them in Sprint's local phone
business _ not long-distance, not wireless and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   MCI, the long-distance carrier that spent years battling the
unions, was acquired in 1998 by Worldcom. And Bernard J. Ebbers,
Worldcom's chief executive, has been loath to deal with unions. The
fewer than 500 of the combined MCI-Worldcom's 75,000 employees who
are unionized are affiliated with the Teamsters, not the CWA.
(Perhaps not coincidentally, the unions were big opponents of
Worldcom's proposed acquisition of Sprint, a deal recently shelved
in the face of opposition by antitrust regulators.)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Bell companies, because of their legacy as part
of AT&AMP;T, have always had a significant union presence. AT&AMP;T itself
still has 36,000 union workers out of a total of 145,000 employees.
And the former Bell company Nynex, which covered New York and New
England before merging with Bell Atlantic a few years ago, was
always considered a union bastion with its New York-to-Maine
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of organized labor is a nontrivial reason why
Nynex had lower productivity than its peers,'' said Eric
Strumingher, a communications analyst at Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back and look at the CLECs,'' Strumingher added, using
telecommunications argot to refer to new local communications
companies like MFS, which was acquired by Worldcom, and Teleport,
which was acquired by AT&AMP;T. ``They had non-union labor, and they
were competing against companies that were unionized, and that was
a clear advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, there is only so much money to go around,
and everyone _ workers, management, investors _ wants as much as
possible. Labor negotiations may not quite be a zero-sum game, but
they can appear quite close.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I think everything will be fine,'' said Adrian G.
Davies, a communications analyst for Federated Investors, the
mutual fund company based in Pittsburgh. ``But unionization means
less money for shareholders, and of course we're not happy about
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
