<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HOPES LIEBERMAN TO HELP DISTANCE HIM FROM CLINTON SCANDALS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presidential hopeful Al Gore sought to inoculate himself from
lingering effects of the Monica Lewinsky scandal by choosing as a
running mate Sen. Joseph Lieberman, who once ripped President
Clinton over the Lewinsky affair, political experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, D-Conn., a longtime friend and political ally of
Clinton's, was among the first and most vocal of Democrats
castigating the president for his sexual relationship with the
youthful White House intern. Lieberman called the relationship
``disgraceful'' and ``immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words were surprising coming from a Democrat who was known
to be a Clinton confidant, but in character with Lieberman's
carefully cultivated reputation for rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks made Lieberman the symbol of those hating the sin
while loving the sinner, when it came to Clinton. And, some experts
said, they made him the perfect choice for Gore's effort to
distance himself from the president's scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the first one to step up to disapprove of Bill Clinton,
who was an old friend of his,'' said Stephen Hess, senior fellow at
the Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank. ``If that
doesn't give you a moral vaccination, nothing will.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as California political analyst Sherry Bebitch Jeffe said,
``Joe Lieberman is air freshener for those who were going to have
to hold their noses to vote for Gore because of the Clinton
association.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts reckoned that the selection of Lieberman could free Gore
from continuing his own litany of disapproving statements about
Clinton's behavior while also helping make the case that Gore was
stepping out of Clinton's shadow and becoming his own man.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gore has any overriding requirement heading to Los Angeles,
it is to establish himself as his own person,'' said Michael Franc,
an analyst at the Heritage Foundation. ``Surely the selection of
Lieberman, who was very critical of Clinton, goes a long way toward
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans tempted to use Lieberman's words blasting
Clinton against Gore, to do so carries the risk of being seen as
too willing to wallow in the mud of Clinton scandals people are
tired of hearing about, analysts warned.
</P>
<P>
   But others were dubious that Lieberman would prove a Teflon
coating shielding Gore from the residue of Clinton's ethical woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it neutralizes the scandal issue for Gore,''
said Stuart Rothenberg, editor of a political insider's report.
``There are people who just won't vote for Gore because of the
ethical problems of the Clinton administration, and this doesn't
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg noted that Gore has had his own brushes with campaign
finance scandal, independent of the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lieberman's sharp critique of Clinton's behavior during
the Lewinsky case that was the first major break in Democratic
ranks during the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Clinton admitted the affair with Lewinsky, and before
independent counsel Kenneth Starr filed his report describing
potential impeachable offenses against Clinton, Lieberman publicly
rebuked the president, saying the affair had ``compromised his
moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said in September 1998, that his initial anger at
Clinton's behavior had deepened to ``a larger, graver sense of loss
for our country, a reckoning of the damage that the president's
conduct has done to the proud legacy of his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Clinton's actions were ``disgraceful'' and,
``deserving of public rebuke and accountability,'' while adding,
``such behavior is not only inappropriate, it is immoral and
harmful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had no comment Monday on the Lieberman rebuke of Clinton, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, traveling in Massachusetts, said of Lieberman, ``He's
been a friend of mine for 30 years. I've worked with him for 15
years or more through the Democratic Leadership Council. He's a
bold thinker, he's always full of new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative groups were willing to raise the specter of
Lewinsky on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Traditional Values Coalition, a conservative religious
group, issued a statement by its head, the Rev. Louis Sheldon,
saying Gore was trying to ``send a message to the American people
that he disapproved of Clinton's sexual antics,'' in picking
Lieberman. ``This `moral move' is a little late. In fact, it is
nearly eight years too late,'' Sheldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's willingness to criticize Clinton must be seen in the
context of a long friendship between the two that has continued
post-impeachment, Washington political experts said.
</P>
<P>
   And Lieberman can note that while he was critical of the
president, he did vote against impeachment. He also worked with
Republicans to assure a quick Senate trial at which Clinton was
acquitted. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
