u a BC-UNDERGROUND-TANKS-750     08-07 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-TANKS-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES AND CITIES FLOUT LAW ON UNDERGROUND FUEL TANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn., N.J., Calif., Texas, Ohio, Va.)  By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ While private industry spends millions to meet
a 1998 federal deadline to upgrade leaking underground fuel tanks _
the nation's leading cause of ground water pollution _ state and
local government agencies continue to operate thousands of
antiquated tanks in danger of leaking chemicals into water
supplies, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Most private companies, from deep-pocketed oil conglomerates to
mom-and-pop gas retailers, upgraded their tanks before the December
1998 deadline to avoid stiff fines and negative publicity. But many
governments, from New York state to the town hall in Cheshire,
Conn., have taken advantage of lax enforcement standards to flout
the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough making people do something like this,
especially when the political will isn't there,'' said Hal White, a
technician with the Office of Underground Storage Tanks at the
Environmental Protection Agency. ``What they really need is a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Most outdated underground tanks are probably leaking fuel,
either into the soil, drinking-water wells or aquifers, said Tim
Fields Jr., a Washington administrator in the EPA's solid waste and
emergency response unit. Leaking fuel tanks have already tainted
hundreds of wells in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut,
including more than 400 in New Jersey alone, according to a 1998
study by the agency. But leaking tanks are a nationwide problem. A
1998 study by the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in
California found traces of a gasoline additive, MTBE, in more than
10,000 sites statewide. Environmental groups complain that many
other states, like Texas, have failed to adequately track leaks and
punish tank owners.
</P>
<P>
   The full impact on ground water supplies from these old steel
tanks, which become prone to leaks after about 10 years, will take
years to gauge, environmental experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly a long-term issue,'' said Lois Epstein, an
environmental engineer with the Environmental Defense Fund in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half the nation's population draws its drinking water,
billions of gallons of it per day, from below-ground sources like
public and private wells or aquifers. In 1984, recognizing the
potential threat that the old single-wall steel underground fuel
tanks posed to the water supply, Congress ordered the EPA to
establish a compliance program to remove or replace the tanks to
protect against corrosion, spills and leaks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the agency gave owners of the nation's 3 million or so
underground storage tanks _ which hold hazardous liquids, including
gasoline and industrial solvents _ 10 years either to remove or
upgrade them.
</P>
<P>
   The federal regulations covered underground tanks capable of
holding at least 1,100 gallons; home heating oil tanks, which are
generally smaller, were exempt from federal law, though some
states, including New York, regulate them.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 percent of the 750,000 storage tanks still in the
ground nationwide were in compliance as of March, according to the
EPA. Fields called the agency's tank-upgrade program ``a tremendous
success story'' that has significantly reduced the amount of fuel
trickling into the nation's soil and water.
</P>
<P>
   About 110,000 other tanks are being operated illegally,
according to state records. ``A large portion of those would be
leaking,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, only a slight percentage of underground tanks
are still operating illegally, according to the EPA. But in other
states, compliance rates are either far lower or unknown. In Ohio,
only 4,556 of the 29,177 active storage tanks were upgraded fully,
according to March data provided by the state to the EPA. Texas,
home to 62,600 storage tanks, more than New York and New Jersey
combined, failed to report any data for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Most industrial and private tank owners, particularly those in
the highly competitive retail gasoline business, upgraded their
tanks before the deadline because they knew they would be the first
to be fined by the EPA, said John Huber, vice president of the
Petroleum Marketers Association of America, a trade group based in
Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   But state and federal enforcement officials took a more lenient
approach with government-owned tanks, he said. ``If you're a state
EPA inspector, are you going to go around to the state police, or
are you going to check private citizens?'' Huber said. ``How smart
would you look to be the one to shut down an ambulance's tanks?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   State environmental officials said many government-owned tanks
listed as being in violation of the deadline might actually be in
compliance, but that there was no way to know until they were
inspected.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, several state agencies are operating a total of 350
tanks illegally, EPA officials said. A spokeswoman for the state,
Jennifer Post, disputed that number and said that only 74
state-owned tanks were out of compliance. New York City officials
are negotiating the penalty amount the city must pay for operating
614 underground fuel tanks past the deadline, said Nina
Habib-Spencer, an EPA spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, a state-managed database lists 440 tanks operated
by public agencies and governmental bodies that are being used
illegally.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the EPA estimated that 100 to 300 water wells
are tainted by gasoline additives. More than a quarter of the 2,027
underground fuel tanks listed as out of compliance by the State
Department of Environmental Protection are owned by a town or city
or the state itself, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, like many other states, has about a dozen
tank-related spills and leaks a year. In June, for instance, an
upgraded fiberglass tank under an ExxonMobil station in Madison,
Conn., leaked 6,000 gallons of gasoline over five days,
contaminating local ground water.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, officials discovered 26,000 gallons of diesel
fuel had leaked from a tank under a truck stop in Southington,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, it's not documented as to how much leaked,''
said Peter Zack, supervisor of Connecticut's underground storage
tank leak-detection program. ``A lot of times it will show up in a
river or stream.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond contributing to soil and ground water contamination, the
failures of city, county and state governments to upgrade
underground storage tanks, has cost taxpayers hundreds of thousands
of dollars, if not millions, in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   On July 9, 1999, for example, the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority agreed to pay a $32,000 fine for allowing tanks under a
South Bronx bus depot to leak 9,000 to 19,000 gallons of fuel,
Habib-Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, the EPA has sought to collect a $37,221 fine from
the State Department of Transportation for operating storage tanks
that do not meet federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, at least 19 cities and towns, including
Hartford, New Haven, Waterbury and Danbury, have been fined or
cited for fuel tank violations, including some that have
contaminated rivers and ground water, said Scott Deshefy, one of
four inspectors in charge of monitoring the 13,500 underground
storage tanks in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Underground fuel tanks in New Jersey, the most densely populated
state in the country, have tainted hundreds of private and public
water wells, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   All state-owned tanks in New Jersey have been upgraded, said
Kevin Kratina, chief of New Jersey's Bureau of Underground Storage
Tanks. But in July 1997, the EPA fined the New Jersey Transit
Authority $130,000 for failing to install leak protection equipment
on tanks it had at several sites around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners have also been caught grossly out of compliance
with the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the EPA fined Gaseteria, a chain of gasoline
stations, $360,000 for tank leaks. On Thursday, the agency
announced that it was seeking to fine Supervalue, a supermarket
chain based in Spring Valley, N.Y., $261,595 for tank violations at
four locations in northern New Jersey. On May 30, a federal judge
ordered a gas station owner, Oliver Hill, to pay $4.75 million _
the largest fine ever imposed for tank violations _ for ignoring a
1995 EPA order to clean up 10,000 gallons of gasoline that leaked
from tanks buried under a station on the Onondaga reservation in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing owners of underground fuel tanks to comply with
regulations has been difficult because there are too few
inspectors, EPA officials said, with enforcement left primarily to
individual states.
</P>
<P>
   But effectively enforcing laws protecting ground water also has
been complicated by politics, federal and state officials said. For
example, in New York, unlike most states, the Legislature never
passed a law giving the State Department of Environmental
Conservation the power to enforce the EPA's tank-upgrade law, said
John Kushwara, the chief of the EPA's regional unit on ground water
compliance in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington politics has also hindered enforcement of the
national storage tank law, state and federal environmental
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Congress has overseen a fund, collected from taxes
paid by petroleum companies, to help states clean up large fuel
spills caused by underground storage tanks. Though the fund, called
the Leaking Underground Storage Tank Trust Fund, currently has $1.3
billion in it, federal law permits the EPA to draw only about $70
million a year, roughly the amount the fund earns in interest each
year. That money can be used only to clean up spills, not to find
and close leaking tanks or enforce the current tank-upgrade
regulations, EPA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials in Washington and petroleum industry executives
said the law should be changed to free up more money and to allow
it to be used to detect fuel-tank problems before they erupt into
disastrous spills.
</P>
<P>
   But federal and state environmental officials, as well as
several petroleum industry executives, said congressional leaders
had refused to touch the fund's $1.3 billion principal as part of
the effort to reduce the federal deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the law to allocate money for more enforcement action
would go a long way toward better preventing ground water
contamination, environmentalists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really know a lot more about how to prevent this,'' said
Epstein, the engineer with the Environmental Defense Fund. ``It's
just a matter of money, and it's a matter of will on the part of
the owner-operators, and the agencies in charge of enforcement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
