<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEAR-STEARNS-NYT &LR;      08-07 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-STEARNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAR STEARNS CLOSES BOOK ON AN ILL-FATED TAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bear Stearns Cos. has closed the books on one of the darker
chapters in its history as an investment bank by writing a check
for $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns, the sixth-biggest U.S. securities firm, paid that
amount to settle a lawsuit over its role as an adviser on an
ill-fated takeover, lawyers involved in the case said Monday. The
case sent tremors through Wall Street two years ago when a federal
jury in California found the firm was negligent in the way it
advised its client, the Daisy Systems Corp., on a 1989 purchase of
Cadnetix Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded $108 million in damages to the shareholders of
the two companies, both of which are now defunct. That was easily
the biggest award against an investment bank for giving bad advice
in a merger or acquisition, and it held up other bankers' opinions
to the scrutiny of jurors, securities-law experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the creditors of Daisy Systems, a software company,
had argued that Bear Stearns contributed to the failure of the
companies by telling them that it was ``highly confident'' that it
could line up financing for the highly leveraged transaction, said
John Coffee, a law professor at Columbia University, who testified
as an expert witness in the original trial. When the firm failed to
arrange bank loans, Daisy Systems had to borrow at interest rates
higher than it could afford, Coffee said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge later reduced the award to $36 million, but Bear
Stearns and the bankruptcy trustee for Daisy Systems appealed that
decision. Then, as those appeals headed for a mid-summer hearing,
Bear Stearns agreed to settle the case for even less. It paid $30
million and withdrew a bankruptcy-court claim for $2.5 million in
investment banking fees, said J. Thomas Hannan, a lawyer in San
Francisco for the trustee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot better than paying out $108 million _ and they had
use of the money for two years,'' said Jimmy Lynn, a lawyer in
Oklahoma City who defended Bear Stearns. ``Bear Stearns wanted to
be rid of the case, and the plaintiffs wanted to be rid of the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn also defended Bear Stearns in a case in which a wealthy,
Canadian currency trader won a $167 million award against the firm
in May. A hearing for an appeal of that judgment, for which the
firm took a $96 million charge against its earnings last quarter,
is scheduled for Sept. 28 in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, Lynn
said.
</P>
<P>
   By settling, Bear Stearns averted the possibility of having to
pay much more, even having the original $108 million award
restored, Coffee said. But, he added, the firm also ruled out the
chance of having an appellate panel completely throw out the
original decision by finding there was not sufficient evidence to
hold Bear Stearns liable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the investment banking industry who weren't facing
this liability were hoping that it would be reversed,'' Coffee
said.
</P>
<P>
   They fear increased liability for what they say in the
``fairness opinions'' that they render on all mergers and
acquisitions, he said. Corporate directors insist on having
investment bankers sign off on proposed transactions to shield them
from liability if shareholders sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment bankers make very high fees for giving these
opinions,'' in part, because ``the law places great weight on
obtaining these opinions,'' Coffee said. ``As a matter of public
policy, we want some risk of liability to attach to these opinions
or else they're likely to be fabricated.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannan, the lawyer for the trustee, said the case was notable
because ``two companies died but the creditors will recover'' some
of their losses and because it laid down guidelines for the
responsibilities of investment bankers in mergers and acquisitions.
Coffee said the jury had found that investment bankers, like
doctors in medical matters, play a pivotal role in mergers and can
be liable for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is unlikely to have much of an effect on Bear
Stearns' earnings because the firm had already set aside money to
cover the larger, original damage award and will be able to use
what is left of that reserve to cover other legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be some reversal'' of the legal reserve in the
next quarter, said Joan Solotar, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, ``but I would not imagine that it would be a total
reversal. They could either fully release the reserve or find some
other use for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
