 &UR; BOFA:  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ Get ready for a corporate makeover at Bank
of America as it prepares to enter the post-Hugh McColl era.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview yesterday at San Francisco's Hyatt Regency
Hotel, Kenneth Lewis, the odds-on favorite to be the bank's next
chief executive, said giant corporate takeovers, cronyism and
Southern regional chauvinism will be out under his leadership. In
will be efficiency, profitability and an open corporate style. &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; SAM ZUCKERMAN &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PUC:  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ Gail DeLong says she was offered a
long-distance deal too good to refuse: less than 8 cents a minute
during business hours.
</P>
<P>
   But the great rates evaporated after two months. Starting with
the third bill, the phone company suddenly started billing her in a
mysterious unit called ``TCUs'' (total call units) instead of
minutes. &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PUCSIDE: &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Two years ago, John McDonald was stunned
to find a $35 charge on his phone bill from a company he'd never
heard of _ a billing firm called USP&AMP;C. &UR; BY TODD &LR; 
