<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN </SLUG>
  
 CHILD CARE PROGRAMS BRING TAX BILLS DOWN TO SIZE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMN BY ARTHUR LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q:My wife and I both work, and we plan to place our son in day
care. We will pay about $360 per month. How much of a tax break
would we get? I've heard about the dependent care tax credit but
don't understand it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Granted, it is somewhat complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The child and dependent care credit allows you to deduct from
your tax bill a certain percentage of the amount you pay for your
son's day care. However, it applies to no more than $2,400 per year
in day care expenses. (If you had two or more children in day care,
the cutoff would be $4,800.)
</P>
<P>
   Credits are different from _ and better than _ deductions.
Deductions reduce the amount of your taxable income. Credits
directly reduce the tax itself.
</P>
<P>
   If your income is no greater than $10,000, then you can reduce
your tax bill by 30 percent of $2,400 _ that is, $720. The
percentage is scaled down to 20 percent for families with incomes
of $28,000 or more. If you are making that much, your maximum
credit would be $480.
</P>
<P>
   You should check whether your employer or your wife's employer
offer a superior alternative. I'm referring to an IRS-approved
dependent-care assistance program that allows you to set aside up
to $5,000 of your income tax-free to pay day care expenses.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in the 28 percent tax bracket _ and if you are
fortunate enough to have an employer who sponsors such a program _
you can do better than you would with the child care credit.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, the $360 monthly day care expenses would amount to
$4,320 annually. If you don't have to pay taxes on that amount, you
will save $1,209.60 _ several hundred dollars more than you would
save with the child care credit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How Total Is Total? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Early last year, I bought 2,145 shares of a stock called
Shaman Pharmaceuticals for about $5,000. It was a bad investment,
and the stock fell so steeply that by midyear, the company declared
a 1-for-20 reverse split, leaving me with 107 shares. This year
there was another reverse split _ this time, 1-for-50 _ leaving me
with a mere 2 shares. Those shares recently were selling for about
11 cents apiece, so my investment has been just about wiped out.
Can I claim a total loss on my income tax?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the company's stock became permanently and totally
worthless, you could write it off as a total loss in the year it
happened, notes Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaman Pharmaceuticals, a South San Francisco company that
produces dietary supplements derived from tropical plants, still
has an active market for its stock. It had revenues last year of
about $1 million (and a $16 million loss), and the current market
value of all its outstanding shares is more than $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   You can, however, sell your stock _ all 22 cents' worth _ and
claim a capital loss on the transaction. Bear in mind that you
can't claim the full $5,000 loss in one year unless you offset it
against at least $2,000 in capital gains. If you end the year with
more than $3,000 in net capital losses, you have to carry the extra
amount over to the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, your broker probably will charge a commission far greater
than the value of your shares _ but that's not altogether bad.
Weller says you can count the commission as part of your capital
loss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Treasury Bonds a Good Bet &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: My parents are retired and of modest means. Each month they
receive a personal check of $400 from a family member to whom they
made a loan. I recommended that they put away that money as savings
in a low-risk investment such as Treasuries. But Treasury bonds
apparently require a $10,000 minimum investment. Is there some way
they can participate, perhaps through a mutual fund?
</P>
<P>
   A: Treasuries aren't just for the big boys anymore. It's true
that they used to be priced out of reach for many small investors,
but now you can buy them for $1,000 each. That's the case with all
kinds of Treasuries: bonds, which expire in 30 years, notes (two to
10 years) and bills (13 to 52 weeks).
</P>
<P>
   They are easy enough to buy.
</P>
<P>
   If your parents have access to the Internet, tell them to go to
the U.S. Treasury Department Web site at  &LR; www.treasurydirect.gov &LR; .
They will find all the how-to information they need to open an
account and buy Treasuries commission-free. The purchases can be
made over the Internet or by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't have access to the Internet, tell them to apply to
one of the regional Federal Reserve banks for the necessary forms
and information. In San Francisco, the number to call is (415)
974-2330.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
