<HEADLINE>
BATTLE FOR CONTROL OF REFORM PARTY COMES TO SHOWDOWN 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LETITIA STEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A long-simmering battle for control of the Reform
Party will come to a showdown over the next several days as party
members gathering in Long Beach, Calif., to nominate a candidate
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the painstakingly scripted Republican and Democratic
conventions, a week of political infighting is expected to set the
stage for the formal selection of a Reform Party presidential
candidate at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't so much that our party is in disarray,'' said Judy
Duffy, co-chair of the national convention committee. ``All parties
are in disarray. It's just usually done behind closed doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the stakes are high in the Reform Party contest: The
convention winner will land $12.6 million in federal money for the
fall campaign, as well as ideological control over the fractious
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will determine the future of the Reform Party,'' said
Michael Farris, chair of the presidential nominations committee.
``Will it keep faithful to our initial promise of a broad, third
party for independent voters, or will we become a narrow, extremist
conservative party?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the convention does not officially kick off until
Thursday, many delegates are gathering today for a meeting of the
party's national committee. The meeting pits Reform Party
traditionalists against the growing ``Buchananite'' wing,
supporters of conservative commentator Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   When he fell short last year in his third try for the Republican
Party presidential nomination, Buchanan abandoned the &UR;  &LR; GOP and
began organizing a social conservative movement within the Reform
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan foes hope to block a conservative takeover by backing
challenger John Hagelin, a physicist who has twice run for
president on the Natural Law Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan predicted that if he is denied the nomination, the
Reform Party will wither and die.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get this nomination, it is pretty much the end of
the Reform Party,'' the conservative commentator said Sunday in a
pre-convention interview on CBS' Face the Nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party was organized by Dallas billionaire Ross Perot
after his third-place finish in the 1992 presidential election.
Perot, running as the Reform Party nominee in 1996, received about
9 percent of the vote, enough to qualify the party for federal
funding this year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Perot is staying quiet and away from the party's
nominating convention. He has declined entreaties from his
supporters to block Buchanan by running this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's warring factions are at odds over whether a
party founded principally for government reform should get involved
in the politics of social issues. The party has avoided taking an
official position on the most controversial social matters. But
Buchanan has angered some party loyalists with his conservative
views on abortion, homosexual rights and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's turning the party into a right wing, conservative
fund-raising organization,'' said party secretary Jim Mangia. ``It
was supposed to be socially neutral, bringing together people from
different viewpoints and ideologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next week, the heated interparty feud could prove more
than ugly _ it could become dangerous. Mangia recently reported
receiving death threats from pro-Buchanan callers. Security forces
are being deployed to keep the peace during the convention or the
first political face-off at the national committee meeting this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The committee could decide to overturn an earlier executive
committee motion to disqualify the Buchanan candidacy for alleged
voter fraud. More significantly, the committee will name the chair
to the powerful credentials committee, which decides which
delegates will be seated at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the anti-Buchanan forces have accused the candidate
of trying to stack this committee to gain the two-thirds majority
needed to overturn the primary results and take control of the
party platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it will be contentious,'' said Russell Verney, a
former party chairman and Buchanan opponent. ``I think you'll see
very outspoken, passionate people fighting for the future of the
party.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Verney plans to challenge the Texas delegation,
which he claims was appointed in violation of party rules. At the
state convention in June, Buchanan supporters refused to seat
anti-Buchanan delegates from Dallas and Bexar counties on
parliamentary technicalities. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
