<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PUCBILL-PUC &LR;      08-07 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUCBILL-PUC </SLUG>
  
 PAC BELL CRACKS DOWN ON FIRMS TIED TO QUESTIONABLE BILLING
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two years ago, John McDonald was stunned to find
a $35 charge on his phone bill from a company he'd never heard of _
a billing firm called USP&AMP;C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely fictitious charge for voice mail,'' fumed
McDonald, a manufacturing engineer from Van Nuys (Los Angeles
County).
</P>
<P>
   In industry parlance, McDonald had just been ``crammed.'' Like
thousands of other customers in California, McDonald discovered
that a billing agent had shoved an unauthorized charge onto his
local phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although they don't actually handle any calls themselves,
billing companies ``aggregate'' charges from scores of tiny
telecommunications firms and hand them off to the local phone
companies that print your bill. Since late 1997, billing
aggregators have racked up thousands of complaints in California
for passing along phony charges from shady operators.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators and local phone companies are striking back,
effectively putting some billing agents such as USP&AMP;C out of
business in at least some states and forcing others to fix the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell, the dominant local phone company in Northern
California, stopped pass along charges from USP&AMP;C last fall, after
state regulators began a formal investigation into the complaints.
Ohio, meanwhile, expelled the Kansas City, Mo., firm from its
borders altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Other billing firms are under fire. Ohio sued Telephone Billing
Services (TBS) of Las Vegas and HBS Billing Services of San Antonio
for cramming. And the Federal Trade Commission forced HBS to cough
up a $125,000 settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Billing companies insist they are simply caught in the middle.
Executives say they have no way to know the charges are phony until
consumers receive their bills and call to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the crackdown appears to be working.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Complaints Drop &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Complaints against billing firms dropped by more than two-thirds
during the past year in California. State regulators logged 884
complaints in 1999, down from more than 3,000 in 1998, according to
a Chronicle analysis of complaints filed with the state Public
Utilities Commission. Even fewer complaints are coming in so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two of the worst offenders appear to have shut down
altogether: International Telemedia Associates of Atlanta and TBS
in Las Vegas, also known as Long Distance Billing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Other billing agents have been forced to shed troublesome
clients, such as psychic hotlines and X-rated 900 numbers, to keep
regulators at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The whole industry has become more scrutinized over the past 18
to 24 months,'' said Michael Hynes, spokesman for Billing Concepts,
another billing service. ``Finally, it got to the point where we
had to do something. We had to fire a lot of customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Billing Concepts has reduced complaints by
two-thirds in California, and some rivals have had even more
success. Integretel, which drew 536 PUC complaints in 1998,
received just 40 last year. Both HBS and the Operator Assistance
Network in Northridge (Los Angeles County) also reduced complaints
by more than 90 percent in California during the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt the crackdown has helped,'' said Pac Bell
spokesman John Britton. Whenever Pac Bell receives too many
complaints about a billing company in a quarter, it now puts the
firms on probation, warning that it will begin refusing to pass
along the company's charges unless complaints go down.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, complaints haven't dried up altogether.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Most Complaints &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Billing Concepts, which bills customers under the names U.S.
Billing, Zero Plus Dialing and ESBI, still drew 239 complaints in
1999, more than any other firm.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  But Billing Concepts says it controls 65 percent of the
market, so it should be expected to generate more complaints. And
executives insist charges are usually legitimate, even when
customers squeal.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget McQueen, a spokeswoman for San Jose billing firm
Integretel, insists that billing agents often won't find out about
a scam until customers receive their bills and complaints flood in.
</P>
<P>
   Billing Concept's Zero Plus Dialing division, for instance,
frequently draws fire because it passes along hefty charges for
calls placed at no-name pay phones. Since most states do not cap
the rates for calls from independent pay phones, consumers are
often stunned when the bill arrives.
</P>
<P>
   One customer complained on an Internet message board that he was
billed $381.47 for four collect calls from Mexico totaling less
than an hour. And two parents were floored when they were billed
$35.11 for two short collect calls from their daughter, who was
returning from a church camp in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the customers blamed Zero Plus Dialing, instead
of the phone company that handled the call _ possibly because the
billing company's name is usually the only one to appear on the
local phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacquelene Mitchell, a Billing Concepts vice president,
insists customers could have avoided a nasty surprise had they
bothered to ask about the rates up front before placing a collect
call or agreeing to accept the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even when charges are incorrect, billing agents claim they
are just caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Difficult Clients &LR;
</P>
<P>
   USP&AMP;C lawyer Sheldon Krantz, for instance, blamed the company's
539 complaints in 1998 on a few troublesome clients, which he said
USP&AMP;C no longer works with. But in a complaint filed in October,
state regulators accused the company of violating state rules by
not clearly describing the charges and refusing to provide
information to the PUC. The probe has not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency to automatically believe any allegation,''
Krantz said, ``but this is a very good company trying to do a very
good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Billing Concepts has suffered, too. Sales for the latest quarter
fell 19 percent to $29 million. And Profits, excluding its Internet
operations and special charges, shrank by $6.5 million to $700,000
during the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms fared worse and are going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   TBS, also known as Long Distance Billing Co., logged 141
complaints in California last year, more than any other company
except for Billing Concepts of San Antonio. The company did not
return phone calls. And Dean Kajioka, the lawyer listed on the
company's corporate charter filed with the state of Nevada, refused
to say whether the company is still operating. ``I don't know if I
can say that,'' Kajioka said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ITA, which sparked 276 gripes in 1998 alone, hasn't
generated a single complaint in more than a year. Two industry
executives said that's because the firm shut down. The Chronicle
could not find any telephone listing or Web site for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of when a company bills for (troublesome)
clients, it can end up being their demise,'' said Sandy McGreevy,
Pac Bell's general manager of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevy said local phone companies such as Pac Bell are
increasingly willing to automatically remove charges from billing
companies whenever customers complain _ cutting off their main
source of revenue. Pac Bell, for instance, has set up a call center
with 200 people in Redding (Shasta County) to field complaints
about charges from other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now some billing agents complain that phone companies and
regulators could go too far _ refusing to accept charges for
anything other than phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
