<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-NEWCEO </SLUG>
  
 BOFA EXEC PLANS FOR PROMOTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Get ready for a corporate makeover at Bank of
America as it prepares to enter the post-Hugh McColl era.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday at San Francisco's Hyatt Regency Hotel,
Kenneth Lewis, the odds-on favorite to be the bank's next chief
executive, said giant corporate takeovers, cronyism and Southern
regional chauvinism will be out under his leadership. In will be
efficiency, profitability and an open corporate style.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 53, the bank's president and No. 2 executive, sounded
very much like a man who has passed his career in the shadow of a
domineering leader and is struggling to find his own voice.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, of course, is the corporate titan who built his little
North Carolina bank into the nation's largest through an audacious
series of takeovers. Two years ago, McColl capped his career when
NationsBank bought San Francisco's BofA, took its name and elbowed
aside the California bank's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 65-year-old McColl is easing his way toward retirement,
something bank watchers believe could happen at the end of this
year or early next year. While Lewis' appointment is not official,
few doubt he will get the job.
</P>
<P>
   As McColl fades and Lewis emerges, the bank is going through a
seismic shift in strategy. Lewis is swearing off the kind of
megamergers McColl used to build BofA in favor of the more mundane
task of making the bank more efficient and profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year we have been adding a bank,`` Lewis noted. Now, he
said, the bank needs ``a new model that is customer-centric as
opposed to acquisition-centric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating a different kind of company than we have ever
been before,`` Lewis stressed.
</P>
<P>
   The change Lewis is pushing is sorely needed, Wall Street
analysts said. McColl's focus on growth made BofA a force to be
reckoned with, but it produced lackluster profits and weak stock
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been on an acquisition tear for many years, but
they've come to the end of the road,'' said Sutro &AMP; Co. analyst
Campbell Chaney. ``Now they have got to look internally to find
earnings growth.``
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only strategy Lewis said he will remake. It's also
the bank's insular culture.
</P>
<P>
   McColl packed BofA's board and top executive ranks with an
unswervingly loyal group of buddies, all from the South. The
Mississippi-born Lewis, handpicked by McColl as his successor, said
he will end that practice, though he was careful not to criticize
his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he will select executives regardless of whether they
are NationsBank veterans or from other banks. And as current
directors retire, the bank will be ``very focused on broadening
board representation geographically,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's claim of a new day at BofA isn't made any easier by
recent events, all of which took place under his supervision.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the bank's corporate and global banking unit
has demoted most top managers from the old BofA. San Francisco's
Northern California retail banking regional headquarters has been
shut and its functions combined with a similar office in Los
Angeles. And a cutback of up to 10,000 management jobs swept away
former California Treasurer Kathleen Brown, one of the old BofA's
most visible female executives.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said job cuts are needed to meet the bank's profit targets
as it moves away from big acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   And he stressed the bank's commitment to the Bay Area market.
``It's the market in which we do best. The growth rate is higher
than anywhere else in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's president didn't comment specifically on what kind of
organization the bank will keep in San Francisco, but he said the
bank plans to keep its Concord computer center open for the
foreseeable future. ``Concord is a very important center for us and
will continue to be so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' style is bland, and he doesn't seem the sort to feed the
kind of cult of personality that built up around McColl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build the best brand in financial service,'' Lewis
said. ``I want the brand to overwhelm any individual.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
