<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, AUGUST 8 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-ARAFAT-ARABS-NYT (moved Friday, August 4)
</P>
<P>
   Because of editing errors, an article on Saturday about an
effort by Arab leaders to find a consensus on outstanding
differences between the Palestinians and the Israelis misstated the
Arab position on the issue of refugees. The Arab nations have long
contended that Palestinian refugees are the responsibility of
Israel, not of the rest of the world. The article also misstated
the number of peace agreements signed by Israel with Arab
countries. It is two _ not just with Egypt but also with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GOP-BUSH-FAMILY-NYT (moved Thursday, August 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August 3
about Bush family members who attended the Republican National
Convention misstated the occupation of Marvin Bush, the former
president's son, and the location of his business. He is a
co-founder of an investment firm in McLean, Va., not a management
consultant in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT (moved Monday, July 31)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 31
about a speech on AIDS at the Republican National Convention
misstated the source of the fortune made by Max Fisher, a
Republican donor whose daughter Mary Fisher spoke about AIDS at the
1992 and 1996 conventions. He made his fortune in the oil business
and as an investor, not in the auto body business.
</P>
<P>
   BC-KODAK-DIGITAL-NYT (moved Thursday, August 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August 3
about the Eastman Kodak Co.'s push into digital products misspelled
the name of its new untearable photographic paper. It is DuraLife,
not Duralite.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NEW-PLANETS-NYT (moved Sunday, August 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 6
about the discoveries of planets outside Earth's solar system
misstated the number found. It was 9, not 10; one planet was
observed independently by two teams of astronomers.
</P>
</TEXT>
