<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-ISRAEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS HAIL SELECTION OF LIEBERMAN 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israelis on Monday hailed the selection of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman as Al Gore's running mate, while Palestinians
worried that the Connecticut legislator's tough pro-Israel stance
could be an impediment to peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, D-Conn., an Orthodox Jew, has consistently stood
behind Israel during peace negotiations with the Palestinians and
Syrians, often joining ranks with other pro-Israel senators to bash
the administration's Middle East policy.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, in 1997, Lieberman wrote a letter to President Clinton
in which the senator called Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat a
``villain'' and slammed the administration's policy of
``even-handedness'' in Mideast peacemaking, which Lieberman said
had not been earned by the Palestinians. Four Republican senators
also signed the letter.
</P>
<P>
   That record of strong support for Israel would make Lieberman's
candidacy for vice president an attractive choice for many people
here, said Leslie Susser, an Israeli commentator and diplomatic
correspondent for the English-language Jerusalem Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a dream ticket for Israel,'' said Susser.
``Lieberman, who is a Zionist, who knows Israel very well, would
probably be very sympathetic to Israel's needs, a continuation to
the very favorable terms of the Clinton presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials here declined comment on Gore's choice of
Lieberman. One official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
only that ``as a member of the Senate, (Lieberman) has shown a deep
interest in the Middle East peace process and is a regular visitor
to the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman last visited Israel in June.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, those same pro-Israel qualities may not sit too
well with a portion of the Israeli public, Susser said. Some
Israelis might worry that Lieberman could be an impediment to
progress in negotiations with Palestinians _ a fear shared by many
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Israelis feel that perhaps a Gore-Lieberman ticket would
be too pro-Israeli and that could lead to Israeli intransigence and
a slowdown in the peace process,'' Susser said. ``It could lead to
the relationship between Israel and the Arabs being more difficult
than it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Palestinians said they already were worried that Gore's
strong pro-Israel stand during his years as a Tennessee senator and
then as vice president would leave them at a disadvantage in
peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Lieberman, they said, would increase Arab
skepticism about America's ability to maintain its role as a
neutral facilitator of the peace talks that have been reduced to a
low level since Israelis and Palestinians failed to reach an
agreement during 15 days of intensive negotiations at Camp David
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad news for the Palestinians, but it's in no way a
surprise,'' said Ghassan Khatib, a Palestinian political analyst
who directs the Jerusalem Media and Communication Center. ``We've
got enough bias statements from the vice president, so it's bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an impression of him being so biased and supportive to
Israel,`` Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli politicians here said they did not expect Lieberman's
Jewish background to affect American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that the United States is behind Israel, behind
the peace process, and also for a fair settlement ... which will
give Palestinians freedom and security, and I am sure that is
independent of being a Jew or a non-Jew,'' said Michael Melchior,
an ultra-Orthodox Jew and Israel's minister of diaspora affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Melchior said, Lieberman's nomination was evidence that
the American people had come of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud that American society has matured to this
point that a Jew, that is a conscious Jew, a religious Jew, can be
a candidate of this high position,'' Melchior said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
