<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE SESSION LAST WEEK PAYS OFF FOR SIDOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Anne-Gaelle Sidot and Ai Sugiyama
played a practice set together last week in Carlsbad, oblivous to
the possibility they would meet for real Monday in the first round
of the estyle.com Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her it had been a long time since we played each
other,'' Sidot said. ``Then I saw the draw and I saw Sugiyama and I
was surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The friendly rivalry didn't make for much drama. Sidot went up a
break early in each set, cruised to a 6-3, 6-4 victory at the
Manhattan Country Club, and set up a second-round matchup with
second-seeded Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Sidot, a native of France, is trying to match her breakout 1999
season, when she finished a career-best 27th in the world and
reached the semifinals at Manhattan Beach and three other
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Sidot has reached the quarterfinals of just three tournaments
this year but seemed enthused with a victory over an opponent whose
game she respects a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sugiyama) has improved a lot,'' Sidot said. ``Last year she
was not as early on the ball, but now she's more aggressive. If
you're not ready with your legs, it's too late. The ball is going
to come fast.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Survivors:!end! The singles main draw was completed Monday
afternoon when four players advanced out of the 32-player
qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In the final qualifying matches, Marlene Weingartner of Germany
beat American Meghann Shaughnessy 6-4, 7-5; Tamarine Tanasugarn
beat American Kristina Brandi 0-6, 6-3, 6-4; Daja Bedanova of the
Czech Republic beat Maureen Drake of Canada 7-5, 6-3, and Tatiana
Panova of Russia beat Cara Black of Zimbabwe 3-6, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   The best match of the day was the first on center court. Brandi
blitzed Tanasugarn in the first set with a strong serve and
consistently accurate ground strokes and broke serve to open the
second set. But she couldn't maintain the same high level of play.
Both players' games were plagued by frequent unforced errors in the
third set, but Tanasugarn's serve was strong enough to hold off
Brandi.
</P>
<P>
   Tanasugarn's first-round opponent will be Spain's Magui Serna,
who avoided the qualifying tournament and joined the main draw on
Friday, when Anke Huber withdrew because of an elbow injury. The
players met two years ago in the first round at Manhattan Beach,
and Serna won in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   __ Can't beat the heat: Warm and humid weather increased the
sale of bottled water and led to a few overheated players.
</P>
<P>
   Nathalie Dechy of France dropped the first set and the first
game of the second set to Russia's Elena Dementieva. Then WTA
officials examined her for possible heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-minute rest, Dechy came back to win the next three
games and eventually tie the match with a second-set victory, but
Dementieva went up a service break early in the third set and won
6-4, 4-6, 6-4, to advance and face third-seeded Monica Seles in the
second round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV- &LR;      08-07 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS HAVE A BIZARRE GRIP ON REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've got it, we'll televise a beauty pageant and let the
contestants pick their own winner, Darwin style.
</P>
<P>
   One contestant from each state. They're all locked in a
dormitory, see, and they do talent shows, and swimsuit
competitions, and world peace platitude contests, and are tempted
with chocolates, and form nasty alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, five of them get booted out. The eventual winner
gets a million dollars, a crown, a sash, a ton of endorsement deals
and probably more attention than Miss America.
</P>
<P>
   Unsavory? Maybe, but it's practically ``Masterpiece Theatre''
compared with ``Chains of Love,'' the reality show NBC is pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by the makers of ``Big Brother,'' ``Chains of Love''
involves four men shackled to one woman, who turns them loose one
at a time until she holds the key to one stud's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seems there's no idea too crazy these days,'' says
Mike Darnell, executive vice president for specials and alternative
programming at the Fox network, and a man who knows crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell took heat for ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multi-Millionaire?'' But the fiasco that followed the onstage
marriage of Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger obscured something
noticed by programmers at every other network _ that February
special on Fox was a smash hit, and perversely riveting.
</P>
<P>
   It also proved that people will do (set ital)anything(end ital)
to be on TV, for the right price or the right exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``Survivor,'' this summer's top-rated program, and
``Big Brother.'' The race was on. Hollywood was suddenly
chockablock in wild ideas for TV reality shows.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the concepts that have been pitched to the networks:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Temptation,'' described as ``Change of Heart'' meets ``Blind
Date'' meets ``Survivor.'' Four couples in long-term relationships,
but not married, are sent to a Club Med-type resort where three
``dream dates'' are arranged for everyone to test their romantic
resolve.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Love Test,'' a similar idea except that men and women are
sent to separate resorts, where tempters and temptresses try to
seduce them. Andrea Wong, ABC vice president for alternative
programming, says the amazing thing is that ``the men know they're
being filmed but they do it anyway.'' Of course they do; they're
guys.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Glass House,'' a sort of ``Big Brother'' cousin, in which
contestants live in a glass house situated in a public park. In
other words, they're on display much like animals in a zoo. The
house keeps shrinking because every time a participant is banished,
a room is demolished.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Boot Camp,'' in which masochistic volunteers are subjected
to tests of physical stamina and plenty of verbal abuse from
military-style drill instructors. Fox has picked it up for future
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Mole,'' in which contestants try to perform appointed
tasks while a saboteur in their midst tries to undermine their
efforts. Contestants have to try to identify the ``mole.'' It's
under development for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Popstars,'' based on a popular Australian series and
revolving around a Spice Girls-type band, from the band's inception
to the release of its first CD. Even though ``Making the Band''
didn't post big numbers on ABC, the WB network has picked up
``Popstars'' for midseason.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Reality Check'' is a concept similar to ``Popstars,'' but
this one chronicles the lives of would-be journalists as they
prepare stories for their own TV program. It's under development
for the WB, where programming chief Susanne Daniels regards it as a
blend of ``Primetime Live'' and ``The Real World.'' Daniels wants
to change the title.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Runner,'' in which contestants must make their way
across the United States without being recognized and captured by
alert viewers. Matt Damon and Ben Affleck are developing it for
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Endurance,'' an American version of the Japanese game show
in which contestants willingly endure all kinds of physical torment
and personal indignities. Apparently no takers yet.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hotel Getaway,'' where unknowing ``contestants'' are awarded
free hotel vacations by friends who are in on the scam. The
destination turns out to be a Hotel Hell, where things go horribly
awry. Last dope to check out is the winner.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wagon Train 2000'' is a variation on the recent British and
PBS hit ``1900 House,'' except that this show would involve
modern-day Americans making their way across the West in a covered
wagon, living as settlers did more than 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Big Diet,'' a ``Big Brother''-type endurance test for
contestants who need to lose weight. The houseguests' aggregate
weight loss would be converted into gold.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these, maybe most, will fall by the wayside before
they ever reach the airwaves. But right now, the network appetite
is keen.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that ``it's a whole new world out there'' and that
reality programming ``is not just a fad, it's a trend,'' NBC West
Coast President Scott Sassa hurriedly assembled a team of
programmers last month to seek out offbeat shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa was under the gun; he reportedly was upbraided by his
General Electric superiors for failing to anticipate the
``Survivor'' phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa's mandate might be based on more than a fad. Reality shows
can be done on the cheap, they're a tonic for the summer
programming doldrums and they lend themselves to the coming age of
TV and computer fusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' for example, is an Internet show as well as a
TV show on CBS, and ``The Runner'' supposedly will have an
interactive computer component for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the frenzied pursuit of imitative hits is an old,
cyclical story in the television business. If all trends had
lasting legs, we'd still be watching adult Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
