<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNIVISION-RESIGN-NYT     08-07 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVISION-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS LEAVING UNIVISISON TO RUN HOUSING COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Cisneros, the former housing secretary in the Clinton
administration who became president and chief operating officer of
the largest Spanish-language television broadcaster in the United
States, announced Monday that he was leaving the company, Univision
Communications Inc., to run a company that will build affordable
housing in downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is returning to his hometown of San Antonio, where he
served as mayor from 1981 to 1989, to become a partner with one of
the nation's largest homebuilders, Kaufman and Broad Home Corp.,
for his new venture. Cisneros said in a telephone interview that
his company, American CityVista, will identify areas that have been
overlooked by major homebuilders but are centrally located in order
to build residential communities, or ``villages within cities,'' at
affordable market prices.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was welcomed by Texas Democrats, who have
fallen on such hard times they currently hold no statewide office.
The possibility that Cisneros would run for office again, perhaps
governor, is tantalizing in the eyes of those who say Cisneros'
star power remains strong in Texas despite the scandal involving
payments to his former mistress that drove him out of national
politics. Last September, Cisneros pleaded guilty to one
misdemeanor count of lying to the FBI about the payments and was
fined $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisneros has denied any desire to run for public office
again. At 53, he said, he had been looking instead for ``an
entrepreneurial opportunity'' that would satisfy both his public
service and business inclinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a melding of mission and business,'' he said.
``Providing housing for people is as close as public service as you
can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, political experts said, Cisneros can considerably help
lift his party by using his charisma and fund-raising abilities to
help elect Democrats in 2002, when the statewide offices will be on
the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   As Univision's president and chief operating officer since 1997,
Cisneros focused on selling the broadcaster to leading advertisers.
The company, which has experienced tremendous growth in both
advertising and revenue as the rapidly growing Latino population
expands viewership, reaches more than 90 percent of the Hispanic
television audience in the United States through 33 broadcast and
1,093 cable affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the publicly-traded company said Cisneros
played a critical role in penetrating multinational advertisers.
But they said that Univision has a good management team and that
Cisneros' departure should not affect the company's operations or
growth in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   After the resignation announcement, Univision stock was down
$4.31, or 3.54 percent, to $117.56 while that of Kaufman &AMP; Broad
Home Corp. rose $2.62, or 13.04 percent, to $22.75.
</P>
<P>
   Univision is headed by Chairman and Chief Executive Officer A.
Jerrold Perenchio, a Hollywood dealmaker and major Republican Party
donor who led the group of investors that bought the network from
Hallmark Cards Inc. in 1992. Perenchio, who has assumed Cisneros'
responsibilities, said in a written statement that Cisneros'
``efforts on behalf of Univision were instrumental in our
development and he will certainly be missed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5297 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-GUINNESS-APPRECIATION     08-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINNESS-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUINNESS' ACTING DID THE TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alec Guinness hid inside his roles. A recluse, he also hid in
life. He lived in the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In one of life's little tricks, the shy actor, who died Saturday
in England at the age of 86, became famous throughout the world and
across the generations for a role he came to dislike, Obi-Wan
Kenobi in ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   The public's strong identification of him with the role surely
played a big part in his aversion to it. He also had no truck with
the pop mysticism that slopped over from Obi-Wan Kenobi onto
himself.
</P>
<P>
   There were consolations. Director George Lucas shared the ``Star
Wars'' bonanza, and Guinness reportedly got 2.25 percent of the
profits from the 1977 blockbuster. The actor went on to appear in
the sequels, ``The Empire Strikes Back'' (1980) and ``Return of the
Jedi'' (1983).
</P>
<P>
   Guinness was an unprepossessing figure, a drawback for a leading
man but no disadvantage at all for a character actor. From the
beginning of his film career, he was a master of disguise.
</P>
<P>
   He was more in the English theatrical tradition of John Gielgud,
his mentor, who died in May, rather than that of their great
contemporary, Laurence Olivier. The primary tool of Guinness'
craft, apart from disguise, was the compelling voice, in contrast
to the presence and force of personality, the charisma of an
Olivier.
</P>
<P>
   Guinness was anti-charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Obi-Wan Kenobi, he was known for his films since the
end of World War II, eccentric little English comedies and enormous
David Lean spectacles as well as an extraordinary range of leading
character roles, including that of the bunkered Fuhrer in ``Hitler:
The Last Ten Days'' (1973).
</P>
<P>
   He won an Academy Award for best actor as the monomaniacal Col.
Nicholson in Lean's ``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' (1957).
Guinness fans have their own favorite characterizations. Among them
are the anarchistic painter Gulley Jimson in ``The Horse's Mouth''
(1958), for which Guinness also wrote the screenplay, and the
Scottish military man, Lt. Col. Jock Sinclair, who is being
squeezed out of command in ``Tunes of Glory'' (1960).
</P>
<P>
   The portrayal of the tightly wound Scot might have been as close
as Guinness ever got to revealing anything personal onscreen. The
illegitimate son of a 60ish Scottish father he saw only a few times
and was taught to call Uncle, the young Guinness was reared by his
mother and spent much of his childhood by himself. The seeds of his
imaginative life were planted there.
</P>
<P>
   The Lean connection was a long one. It began with two Charles
Dickens adaptations, ``Great Expectations'' (1946) and ``Oliver
Twist'' (1948), and continued through the grand, literary-based
spectacles after ``Kwai.'' He was the Arab revolutionary leader
Prince Feisal in ``Lawrence of Arabia'' (1962), the storyteller
Yevgraf in Boris Pasternak's ``Doctor Zhivago'' (1965) and,
finally, the canny old Brahmin, Godbole, in E.M. Forster's ``A
Passage to India'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   The creation of Fagin in ``Oliver Twist'' in 1948 was followed
the next year by his most famous feat of disguise, all eight
members of an aristocratic family who are being knocked off one by
one by a serial killer in ``Kind Hearts and Coronets.''
</P>
<P>
   It made Guinness an international star. In 1952 he received the
first of his Academy Award nominations, as best actor for ``The
Lavender Hill Mob.'' He was nominated for supporting actor for
``Star Wars'' in 1978
</P>
<P>
   and for ``Little Dorrit'' in 1989. For ``The Horse's Mouth'' in
1958,
</P>
<P>
   he was nominated for best screenplay adaptation, based on the
novel by Joyce Cary.
</P>
<P>
   Guinness lived quietly in the country near London with his wife,
Merula, and their three dogs. His wife and their son, Matthew,
survive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Guinness was honored by the San Francisco International
Film Festival with a retrospective of his work. He did not like the
trappings of stardom or being fawned upon. He told a Chronicle
interviewer that it was easy for him to avoid attracting attention:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make myself anonymous when I want to, not by wearing a
disguise but by the way I carry myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
