<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5298 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS0808-COX     08-07 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS0808-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stocks, mutuals excite some sports superstars
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The image of sports superstars as spoiled kids
squandering money by the ton is not a complete picture, says Money
(September), the personal finance magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every clown blowing a signing bonus on a puce Bentley and
a dozen gold Rolexes, there is at least one eager student of
finance who brings a laptop to practice and talks asset allocation
in the locker room,'' the magazine says in a profile of sports
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's Shaquille O'Neal favors tech stocks such as Lucent and
AOL; basketball great Michael Jordan is mostly in large-cap mutual
funds at the moment; and NASCAR winner Dale Earnhardt likes _ what
else? _ GM and Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   Five hefty quarters
</P>
<P>
   Economists predicted that corporate profits would be good to
strong in the second quarter, and they were right, Business Week
(Aug. 14) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings increased 17 percent for the 900 companies the magazine
monitors, making it the fifth straight quarter of double-digit
earnings growth. Not surprisingly, one of the biggest gains came in
the energy sector, where coal, oil and gas companies posted a 187
percent year-over-year gain.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest growth was in the ``new economy'' semiconductors
industry, up 271 percent. The biggest casualty was the ``old
economy'' steel industry, which lost money. Health care, banks and
publishing industries also suffered big declines.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-free and rewarding
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody say ``munis''? Once regarded as the investment
choice of widows and orphans, municipal bonds are winning fans in
the most unlikely of places, Barron's (Aug. 7) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Dot.com millionaires have been buying tax-exempt bonds as a
hedge against the volatility of tech stocks. That's because the
tax-free yield on munis of, say 5.85 percent, is equivalent to a
9.69 percent taxable yield to an investor in the top bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking without film
</P>
<P>
   Digital imaging has been seen by some analysts as the death
knell for old-fashioned photography, and with it companies such as
Kodak, the world's best-known photo company.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says Forbes (Aug. 21), which notes that Kodak Chief
Executive Dan Carp sees digital images as ``an explosive
opportunity'' for the film company, not the kiss of death.
</P>
<P>
   If he's right, says Forbes, Kodak is an undervalued company. But
if he's wrong, it's lights out in Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Fast Company (September) devotes 100 of its 400 pages to the
tech magazine's second annual analysis of the ``new economy,''
including the comments of 17 people ``on the cutting edge of the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro sports is big business in metro Atlanta, with an estimated
$4.5 billion economic impact during the past five years, Georgia
Trend (August) reports. One reason is the breadth of the sports
menu, from baseball to football to basketball to motor sports, and
then some.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
