u p BC-LIEBERMAN-MAIN-HNS &LR;      08-07 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SURPRISE GORE VP CHOICE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ In a historic move that could give a lift to
his campaign, presidential contender Al Gore Monday selected as his
running mate Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a centrist Democrat and
Orthodox Jew who will be the first of his faith to join a major
party presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials compared the breakthrough to John F.
Kennedy's bid to be the first Roman Catholic president four decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significantly, the choice of the two-term senator
from Connecticut underscores Gore's resolve to distance himself
from the scandals of President Clinton, which political experts
have opined may be contributing to Gore's difficulty in closing the
double-digit gap in polls with Republican rival George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, 58, gained national prominence when he stood on the
Senate floor and denounced Clinton's affair with White House intern
Monica Lewinsky as ``inappropriate'' and ``immoral.'' But he voted
against removing Clinton from office after he was impeached.
</P>
<P>
   While the senator could give Gore some moral cover, he could
cause the candidate some headaches with liberal Democrats who may
be unhappy with some of his more conservative stands, such as his
support for private school vouchers. The Bush campaign was quick to
say that Gore's running mate had more in common with the Texas
governor than the Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman and the Gore camp played down differences between
the two men, noting that over the years they have shared similar
values. Both have been active in the Democratic Leadership Council,
a group that has worked to steer the party to the middle of the
ideological spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore and I have pretty much walked the same path. And where
we've had disagreements they have been good faith disagreements,
not disagreements that press our values,'' said Lieberman, who was
in Hartford shortly before noon Monday, when Gore called to offer
the running mate position.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman called the decision a ``a miracle,'' saying that he
assumed that when he went to sleep Sunday night, he had been
crossed off Gore's short list that included three other Senate
colleagues, John Kerry of Massachusetts, John Edwards of North
Carolina and Evan Bayh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, after spending Sunday in Tennessee consulting with
a group of close advisers and his wife, Tipper, Gore settled on
Lieberman just after midnight, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, his wife, Hadassah, and two of his four children flew
late Monday afternoon to Nashville, where they were scheduled to
join the Gores for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will officially introduce Lieberman as his
vice-presidential pick today at the War Memorial in downtown
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the two men will participate in a town hall
meeting in Carthage, where the Gore family owns a farm, before
flying to Lieberman's home state of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore did not publicly confirm his choice, his aides were
eager to discuss the pick they believed would give the campaign a
boost before the Democratic National Convention next week in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane called Lieberman ``a man of
character and a man of integrity.'' He said that the Democratic
ticket will provide a vivid contrast with Bush and his running
mate, Dick Cheney, the former Wyoming congressman and defense
secretary whom Democrats have lambasted as too conservative and too
close to Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a ticket that will represent the new guard vs.
the old guard,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said that advisers were not concerned that because
Lieberman is an observant Jew he will not campaign on the Jewish
Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we are going to be very respectful of his
religion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Stamford, Conn., Lieberman is a graduate of Yale
University and its law school. He served as state senator and
Connecticut attorney general before first being elected to the U.S.
Senate in 1988. He was re-elected in 1994, with 67 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials found few faults with Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore has, in fact, selected Joe Lieberman, he has chosen
a man whom Secretary Cheney and Governor Bush respect,'' said Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Gore will have difficulty attacking the Texas
governor for his positions on several issues, such as support of
school vouchers and Social Security privatization, which are
similar to Lieberman's stands.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane dismissed the criticism, saying the Bush camp was ``a
little bit flummoxed'' by the choice of Lieberman. He also said
that Gore's positions will prevail on issues where the two men
differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Al Gore is running at the top of the ticket. The
ticket will reflect his agenda,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm called Lieberman
``a bold choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore has demonstrated his strength of character
and independence by choosing someone who does not agree with him on
every issue,'' Malcolm said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lieberman decision got high marks from political analysts,
including conservative Heritage Foundation scholar Marshall
Wittmann, who called the choice ``a brilliant stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Wittmann &UR; , &LR;  who advised former Republican candidate John McCain,
said the selection allows Gore to counter two negative images that
voters hold about him: that he is too cautious and too close to the
morally flawed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Wittmann said that Lieberman's ``strong Orthodox faith will
deflect Bush's claim that only he can restore dignity to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ralph Reed, the former head of the Christian Coalition and
Bush adviser, praised Lieberman as a ``strong man who has taken
some courageous stands.'' However, Reed said that unless Gore
changes his positions on some key issues the Democrats will have a
hard time winning the White House.
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman may create a sensation as the first Jewish
person on the presidential ticket, he may not attract additional
voters since Jews historically have voted for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Florida pollster Jim Kane said that Jews are already among the
most active and reliably Democratic voters in that key swing state.
</P>
<P>
   Kane said some voters may remain reluctant to vote for a Jewish
candidate. Polls showing that more than 90 percent of voters would
be willing to accept a Jew on the presidential ticket may be
deceiving because people will not reveal their prejudices to
outsiders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lieberman works with Republicans regularly and often
takes similar stands on issues, it may be difficult for him to
fulfill the vice-presidential candidate's traditional role of
attack dog.
</P>
<P>
   However, Connecticut political observers noted that Lieberman
ran an aggressive campaign in 1988, when he ousted Republican
incumbent Lowell Weiker.
</P>
<P>
   At the Elliston Place Soda Shop on Monday, around the corner
from the hotel where Gore made his choice, many customers,
including those who were backing Bush, had admiration for
Lieberman, particularly his willingness to scold Clinton for his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieberman is a stand-up sort of guy,'' said Steve Ladd, 45,
who added he was amazed that Gore made the choice because he is
``so wishy-washy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
