r f BC-PUC-LYNCH-PUCCHIEF &LR;      08-07 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-LYNCH-PUCCHIEF </SLUG>
  
 PUC CHIEF DEMOTES CONSUMER AFFAIRS MANAGERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In her boldest move so far, the newly appointed
head of the California Public Utilities Commission has demoted two
key managers in the division that handles consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Lynch, who became president in March, said she couldn't
discuss either move because they haven't been announced.
</P>
<P>
   But the former trial lawyer pointed out that last year the state
legislature gave the PUC president broad powers to make staff
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lynch said she felt the legislature gave the agency head
``a clear directive to become more active in the management of the
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   William Schulte, who has been director of the consumer services
division for 11 years, confirmed yesterday that he has been asked
to step down. Schulte said his last day will be Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One source identified the second demoted official as Larry
McNeely, one of Schulte's key deputies and the head of the consumer
enforcement division, who retired a few weeks ago. (Separately,
Kent Kauss, director of governmental affairs, left last week, but
that move was unrelated, Lynch said.)
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said she is still looking for their replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Carl Wood, a fellow Democrat and key ally of Lynch,
also cited other reasons. He said Lynch didn't think Schulte was
doing enough to protect consumers' rights and was concerned about a
state auditor report that chastised the division for sloppy
accounting managing contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a matter of President Lynch having a senior management
team that she has full confidence in,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   But the move immediately sparked complaints by some consumer
watchdogs, including those who have been critical of the consumer
division but thought Schulte did the best job he could within the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am kind of shocked,'' said Nettie Hoge, executive director
of The Utility Reform Network in San Francisco. ``I have only seen
him do good work.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shames, executive director of the Utility Consumers'
Action Network in San Diego, said he was also concerned,
particularly because no replacement has been named.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Schulte was a very experienced internal advocate at the
CPUC,'' Shames said. ``I don't know of any one at the CPUC who can
bring his wealth of knowledge about utility tricks or enforcement
strategies to that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Witteman of the Greenlining Institute in San Francisco was
more neutral, saying he thought Schulte was ``a good guy'' but
thought Lynch should be given the latitude to pick managers she
likes.
</P>
<P>
   Schulte, who spent 28 years with the agency, said he wasn't
bitter about the move. ``She has the right to put in who she wants
and who she puts faith in.''
</P>
<P>
   He could still decide to stay on with the commission in a lesser
role or take another job.
</P>
<P>
   What's less clear is how the three Republican commissioners
react. Because Wood and Lynch only control two votes, they often
need help to approve key policies. So far, they have often been on
the losing side of 3-to-2 votes in controversial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Josiah Neeper said he was unaware of the changes
and couldn't comment. The other commissioners couldn't be reached.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
