u a BC-INDIANS-FISH-ART-1STL     08-07 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANS-FISH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN TRIBES IN MICHIGAN SIGN FISHING ACCORD WITH GOVERNMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (Eds: SUBS 15th graf, Unlike the ..., to correct to four other
Northern Michigan tribes, sted four total in Upper Peninsula.) 
 (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PESHAWBESTOWN, Mich. _ The federal government, the state of
Michigan and five American Indian tribes in northern Michigan
signed an agreement Monday aimed at rebuilding fish populations in
the upper Great Lakes and improving strained relations between
whites and Indians in upstate Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The pact settles 27 years of litigation over whether the state
can restrict Indian fishing, people involved in the negotiations
said.
</P>
<P>
   A vibrant national economy has created a boom in vacation homes
and tourism here in the northern third of Michigan's Lower
Peninsula. The accompanying surge in pleasure boating and
recreational fishing has increased tensions between whites and
Indians, as pleasure boats become dangerously entangled in Indian
nets and charter boat operators blame the Indian fishermen for
depleting trout and salmon populations.
</P>
<P>
   Some Indian nets have been sabotaged, state officials say.
Indian leaders have denied that they are responsible for declining
fish stocks and have angrily denounced what they have described as
efforts to take away some of the few ancestral rights they retain.
</P>
<P>
   The pact calls for the tribes to reduce drastically their use of
large-mesh gill nets, which kill fish of various sizes and species
and can entangle boats. The Indians are to replace gill nets with
trap nets, which allow fishermen to catch fish more discriminately
and are less likely to entangle other boats. The state government
will pay $17 million to buy boats equipped with trap nets and
fishing permits from white-owned companies and give them to Indian
fishermen to replace boats with gill nets.
</P>
<P>
   The trap-net fishing permits are mainly for remote areas of
northwestern Lake Michigan and northern Lake Huron, pulling Indian
fishermen far from Michigan's main recreational boating and fishing
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government will pay an additional $8.3 million to
the five tribal governments. The tribes are expected to use some or
all of the money to compensate small-scale Indian fishing
operations, which will not receive the trap-net boats but will face
restrictions on gill-net fishing for the next 20 years. Use of
large-mesh gill nets by non-Indians has been heavily restricted
since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has been particularly acrimonious here in this
Indian community and eight miles west in the mainly white town of
Leland. Both towns are on the northwest shore of Michigan's Lower
Peninsula, 220 miles northwest of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   For whites like John Lindenau, who stood on the dock in Leland
on Monday morning next to his 30-foot charter fishing boat, the
Infinity, the dispute has been about imposing the same rules on
Indians that white fishermen must meet. ``We won the Indian wars
and gave it all away,'' Lindenau said.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Peshawbestown, on the tiny reservation of the Grand
Traverse Band of Ottawa and Chippewa Indians, the agreement is the
cause of considerable bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grand Traverse Band hesitantly, really hesitantly agreed
to sign off on the deal,'' said Ardith Chambers, one of seven
members of the tribal council, as she sat glumly in her office
Monday afternoon. ``All the state wants to do is take apart treaty
rights, and so does the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   The five tribes ceded the upper third of Michigan's Lower
Peninsula and the eastern half of Michigan's Upper Peninsula to the
federal government in the Treaty of Washington, concluded in 1836.
That treaty allowed the Indians to continue fishing in the region,
but allowed non-Indian fishing, too. The Indians have used the
treaty to oppose efforts by the state to limit Indian fishing,
because the treaty was signed a year before Michigan became a
state.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Traverse Band has only a dozen fishermen left. Most
will lose their livelihoods because they do not catch enough fish
to qualify for trap-net boats from the state, and they will face
new restrictions on the use of gill nets, Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Traverse Band agreed to the pact because it was
engaged in a separate dispute with the state over its main
livelihood, the Turtle Creek Casino, a few miles east of Traverse
City. The tribe is so dependent on the casino that it felt
compelled to accept the fishing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other four northern Michigan tribes, the Grand
Traverse Band is far from the trap-net fishing grounds being
established. The pact was signed Monday night in Brimley.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers along the coastal highway here in northern Michigan find
that Peshawbestown, with its battered trailers and small wood
houses, is a sharp contrast to other communities. The coastline
elsewhere has many million-dollar mansions, often built in the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Leland has older houses and has been a fishing center since the
late 1800s; the old wood fishing shanties and smokehouses of its
Fishtown neighborhood are popular with tourists. Leland fishermen
say that the trout population has plunged in recent years, and
blame two large, Indian gill-net boats moored Monday morning at the
Leland dock.
</P>
<P>
   But Indian officials attribute the fish shortage to
environmental factors, like unusually warm lake water in recent
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MURDER-NYT &LR;      08-07 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S MURDER RATE, AFTER UPTURN, STARTS TO SLIDE DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-POLICE-SAFIR) 
 By ELISSA GOOTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City's murder rate, after a surge that
alarmed the Police Department and brought about an expensive and
aggressive street enforcement campaign, has begun to slide back
down.
</P>
<P>
   The upturn in homicides, which by the end of last year was 6
percent above the count from 1998, had put the department on the
defensive and loomed as a potential political liability for Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who had made crime reduction his most important
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But recent department statistics show that the homicide rate has
flattened, with this year's murder count, which was 413 as of
Monday, an even match with the corresponding period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers looked even better just last week, with homicides
down 1 percent for the first seven months of this year, compared
with the same period last year, but the rate edged up slightly this
weekend, when the city had one of its most violent nights of the
year: Six people were fatally shot or stabbed throughout the city
late Saturday night into early Sunday. By the end of July, there
had been 392 murders, compared with 396 by the end of July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of a flat murder rate belies a more marked
decline, given that at the beginning of the year, the police were
still facing a rise in homicides. By the end of March, the city had
13 percent more murders than in the first three months of last
year. That the weekend's onslaught of slayings did not push this
year's homicide count over the total from last year at this time
illustrates that, blips and spurts aside, the situation is
stabilizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crime rate,'' Giuliani said Monday, ``is down all over the
city, even with the violence over the weekend, which occasionally,
unfortunately, you deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of relief that we've turned the trend
around,'' said Garry F. McCarthy, the deputy police commissioner of
operations. ``Although it's not the bellwether crime _ the
bellwether crime is robbery _ it's obviously the most important.''
</P>
<P>
   The police credit the drop to Operation Condor, an antinarcotics
program begun in late January. The program has come under intense
criticism for its high cost, for saturating neighborhoods with
narcotics teams and for increasing the number of arrests for petty
offenses. The police say they have since broadened the program to
take aim at crimes against drivers of taxicabs and livery cabs and
to add uniformed street patrols focusing on quality-of-life
offenses like jumping subway turnstiles and peddling without a
license.
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least $41 million has been spent on the program;
police officers working under its banner have made 53,933 arrests
in the course of about 100,000 overtime shifts. In its latest,
broadest incarnation, the police say, Operation Condor is not so
much a new strategy as a redoubling of the department's regular
enforcement efforts in the neighborhoods that need it most.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are reluctant to credit the program for the decline in
homicides, saying the numbers are small, the downward curve is new,
and the murder rate could simply be fluctuating based on forces
that have little to do with law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Police Department has done a lot to reduce crime,
but I'm not sure that they can take all the credit,'' said Karim
Ismaili, an assistant professor of criminal justice at St. John's
University in Queens. ``If the economy goes on a slide and if some
other drug market or underground economy flourishes, we're going to
see an increase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
