<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYPD COMMISSIONER LEAVING FOR CORPORATE JOB, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir, whose department
won accolades for routing crime and scorn for its unraveling
relationship with many of the black and Latino citizens it served,
is expected to announce Tuesday that he is leaving the job by the
end of this month, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials said Safir, 58, who is being treated for
prostate cancer, will announce that he is taking a job as an
executive with Choice Point, a corporate security firm in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of Safir, a loyal, taciturn administrator who
spent four years in the job, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will have to
select his third and most likely last commissioner to lead the
agency whose work has done the most to form the public perception
of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Safir, the 39th man to hold the post of
commissioner and the first Jewish one, refused to discuss his
plans. His health was not thought to be an issue in his departure,
several officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As the chief executive overseeing the 40,000-member police
force, Safir shared in the credit for New York City's plummeting
crime rate, which mirrored a national trend.
</P>
<P>
   Although murder rose slightly last year, overall crime remains
lower than it has been in more than three decades, and the safer
streets have been a large factor in New York's resurgence as a
tourist and business capital.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing crime reduction has confounded skeptics who
questioned whether Safir, a quiet and aloof man, would be able to
fill the shoes of his more affable predecessor, William J. Bratton,
an innovator and motivator who was widely seen as one of the
architects of the city's more aggressive approach to public safety.
But Safir ended up even improving the record in reducing crime and
undercut the perception that he was merely a caretaker in the post.
</P>
<P>
   During the latter part of his tenure, however, those gains have
been largely overshadowed by a series of incidents, like the
shooting of Amadou Diallo and stationhouse torture of Abner Louima,
that have raised concerns about whether the police, in their zeal
to cut crime, have trampled the civil rights of citizens,
particularly blacks and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators have found the city lax in its handling of
brutal officers, and the U.S. Civil Rights Commission concluded in
April that police anticrime units appeared to engage in racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Safir contends that high-profile cases like that of Diallo have
blurred a less-sensational reality: that the number of police
shootings, civilian complaints and brutality lawsuits have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   But some black and Hispanic New Yorkers said that Safir had
often hurt his own cause by adopting a defensive style.
</P>
<P>
   Public Advocate Mark Green, who has called several times for
Safir's resignation, called him a ``failed commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He unnecessarily allowed a racial polarization to grow because
he would not move fast enough or far enough in reforming
recruitment, training and discipline,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he has resolutely defended his officers, Safir has never
been particularly popular with them. The Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association cast a vote of no-confidence in his leadership last
year, and many officers dismissed Safir early on as the mayor's
marionette.
</P>
<P>
   Allies and mayoral aides have said these officers missed how
artfully Safir advocated for his agency, securing additions in
staff and expansions in overtime that have fueled various anticrime
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought he had a very dignified air about him that
the department benefited from,'' said Richard J. Condon, a former
police commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Before being appointed police commissioner in 1996, Safir had
spent two years as fire commissioner. He had also served several
years as a federal drug agent, often working undercover, and in
several posts at the U.S. Marshals Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
