<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-PALMEIRO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO SURPASSING FORMER RANGERS STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
CLEVELAND _ There was a time when it was ludicrous to think you
could have traded Rafael Palmeiro for Jose Canseco. Ten years ago,
you probably couldn't have traded three Palmeiros to get one
Canseco.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But times have changed, as yesterday showed. The Tampa Bay Devil
Rays, eager to dump Canseco's salary and tired of his many
injuries, gave him to the New York Yankees for the $20,000 waiver
price, also ridding themselves of the almost $1 million it costs to
pay him the rest of the year. The Yankees are Canseco's sixth team
in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered the best player in baseball, he has become a
wandering slugger: have bat, will travel. By contrast, Palmeiro,
two months younger, remains an immensely productive player,
entering yesterday's game hitting .275 with 29 home runs and 86
runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the rabbit; I was the turtle,'' Palmeiro said,
observing how he has become more productive than his old friend.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it has been with many of Palmeiro's
contemporaries, who were once considered better players. Ruben
Sierra is in the minors, Will Clark is filling in for Mark McGwire
in St. Louis, and Juan Gonzalez is struggling in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but steadily, Palmeiro is separating himself from those
once more glamorous former Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as me being lucky, me being consistent and me
being fortunate,'' Palmeiro said. ``Hard work, too. All those
things come into play. Also having the drive, seeing the light at
the end of the tunnel, where I've been and where I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro is blunt about what happened with some of his former
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it, I think, has been carelessness,'' Palmeiro said.
``The main reason is they have been hurt. They've had major
setbacks and can't go out there. But some of it is being content,
not really putting the right amount of time and effort to stay at
the top, not wanting to attain higher goals and achieve more.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not been the case with Palmeiro, who wants to finish his
career with 500 home runs and 3,000 hits, a mark only three other
players have achieved: Hank Aaron, Willie Mays and Eddie Murray. He
has 390 home runs and 2,264 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm still at the top of my game,'' Palmeiro said. ``My
experience is carrying me, but I still think the physical ability
is still here. No way do I think I'm on my way down. I feel I'm as
good as ever on defense and as good as ever on offense. I may have
lost a step of speed, but I was never fast anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Canseco, Palmeiro has also had his physical problems. Last
year, he underwent two knee operations, but instead of letting that
drag him down, Palmeiro went out and had his best year ever. Being
used mostly at designated hitter, Palmeiro hit .324 with 47 home
runs and 148 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates likes to point out Palmeiro played in more
games in the 1990s than Orioles ironman Cal Ripken and said, ``You
don't do that without a little fortitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said: ``I could have sat out the first two months of
the season \Rlast year\S based on how my knee felt. There were days
I got out of bed, and my knee would give in. But I found a way to
play and help the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Cal Ripken also taught me that. I saw him go
through some bad times; there were days when he would practically
crawl into the clubhouse looking like he couldn't play. But not
only would he pick himself up and get into the lineup, he'd find a
way to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro is driven. He admitted he would like to finish with big
career numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me what I've done so far would be it, I'd be very
disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he would also, more than anything, would like to win a World
Series. In that respect, this season has been hard. He knows the
Rangers are finished, and he wonders what will happen to the team
in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ultimate deal,'' said Palmeiro, who played in two
American League Championship Series with the Baltimore Orioles.
``I've been so close, and it hurts so bad, especially feeling you
had the best team. I know how it hurts, so I can only imagine how
it feels \Rto win\S. I don't know if I'll get that feeling, but
I've got to make sure I stay at the top my game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around this clubhouse, guys like Ruben Mateo and Gabe
Kapler, they're going to be good. These guys are going to be the
next stars in three or four years, and I want to be at the top of
my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro has three more years on his five-year, $45 million
contract. Despite his knee problems, he has given the Rangers no
reason to worry about receiving full value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raffy today is the best unknown major-league baseball
player,'' Oates said. ``He quietly stays in the background and puts
up big numbers. He's going to get 500 home runs. Three thousand
hits might be a little tougher, but if he plays five more years, he
could get it. That would be a pretty good career.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a Hall of Fame career. It doesn't appear as if
Canseco can say the same thing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
