<HEADER>
A5427 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-PLANE-KAN &LR;      08-07 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-PLANE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING 1932 WACO AIRCRAFT A 10-YEAR EXCERCISE IN LOVING CARE AND
FRUSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The dirt path worn in the grass around John
Swander's biplane all but told the story of his adventures at the
recent AirVenture airshow in Oshkosh, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Admirers, trying to get a good gander at the restored 1932 UEC
Waco Cabin, flocked to the black plane with silver wings.
</P>
<P>
   Swander, of De Soto, Kan., felt pride, and then a little
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying how beautiful a plane it is,'' said Swander,
who restored the Waco. ``But I know better. I know all of the
imperfections and the flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Swander's reservations aside, the plane is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see it among other Wacos and antiques of its type, as good
as many of them were, you could see it stand out,'' said Henry
Frautschy, executive director of the Vintage Aircraft Association
and editor of Vintage Airplane Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Swander won the Grand Champion Antique award at the AirVenture
Oshkosh 2000 airshow, sponsored by the Experimental Aircraft
Association. The Waco competed against 100 other antique airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The annual airshow, held at Wittman Regional Airport in Oshkosh,
is one of the world's largest recreational aviation events. More
than 765,000 people attended this year's event, from July 26 to
Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what it boils down to is that John has done an
extremely original restoration of the aircraft,'' said Frautschy,
whose association is a division of the Experimental Aircraft
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks just the way it looked as it came off the factory
floor in Troy, Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Swander said the Waco Aircraft Co. of Troy built just 45
aircraft of the model he restored. Today, only eight still exist,
and just two, including Swander's, are capable of flying.
</P>
<P>
   Swander's plane was far from its current state when he and his
wife, Jodi, bought it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   John Swander had just sold a plane _ a 1937 Stinson Reliant SR93
_ and was looking for another to restore.
</P>
<P>
   He ran into his friend, Ron Huckins of Wichita, who mentioned he
had a Waco Cabin for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Swander drove to Wichita, disassembled the plane and took it
back to his workshop in the basement of his house. He started
restoring the plane in the fall of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's wing structure is constructed of wood, while the
fuselage is constructed of steel tubes with wood components. Fabric
covers the fuselage and the wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I removed the fabric, I knew I had my work cut out for
me,'' Swander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally I thought it would take only five years and I would
get it knocked out,'' Swander said. ``I had to take another five
years after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Swander estimated that he had put more than 4,000 hours and
$80,000 into the plane. Had he known it would take so long, he
might not have started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly have no desire to do it again,'' Swander said.
</P>
<P>
   Swander said more than 60 persons helped him restore the plane.
He has a list that credits them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody does a project of this enormity all by themselves,''
Swander said.
</P>
<P>
   The one he credits the most is John Krekovich of Overland Park,
Kan., who helped with all of the woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the hint that he wanted my help before he bought the
plane,'' Krekovich said. ``I knew that if he bought the plane, I
would jump right on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Krekovich said the restoration project came just as he was
recovering from a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The project became a good rehab,'' Krekovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Jodi Swander said that although the project stretched on, it
didn't bother her too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing how important it was to him made it easy for me,'' she
said. ``When he would get frustrated, I would convince him to put
it aside for a month or two. Sometimes I would provide a shoulder
to cry on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a perfectionist too,'' she said. ``Somebody else would
have put on something that John rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   A prime example: When applying the fabric to the fuselage, he
decided it didn't look right. He cut it all off and started over,
trashing about a year's worth of work and expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision at the time,'' John Swander said.
``But I decided that the first time was good practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when he got specially made coverings for the wheels,
called wheel pants, Swander just set them next to the plane and
didn't install them.
</P>
<P>
   That puzzled Krekovich, who after three weeks ask Swander why he
didn't put them on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me and said, `I'm afraid to drill the first
hole,' &UR; '' Krekovich said.
</P>
<P>
   But Swander's precision and attention to detail paid off.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane sat on the grass near its hangar at Gardner, Kan.,
Municipal Airport on Saturday, people still gathered for a closer
look.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dolan of Gardner was among them. He was driving by the
airport when he just had to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me being an airport bum, I just had to get out and walk around
the plane,'' Dolan said. ``It is not just any day when you get to
see such a gorgeous plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
