<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME IS RUNNING OUT ON STEELERS' STEWART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Since Kordell Stewart can't throw a football
with any consistency, he should throw in his Terrible Towel.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stewart is a football player. He is not a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He is a player for all positions. He is a quarterback/running
back/receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Did you happen to catch him the other night in the Pittsburgh
Steelers' exhibition game against the Miami Dolphins? Of course you
didn't. Then again, neither did his receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was 0-for-6 with an interception. On one of his
misfires, Stewart had receiver Bobby Shaw wide open in the corner
of the end zone, but he failed to step up in the pocket, and
Dolphins defensive end Jason Taylor hit Stewart's arm.
</P>
<P>
   In Stewart's defense, he had no time. He was chased all 12 times
he dropped back to pass, and the two times he ran for his life, he
gained 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Stewart is most dangerous _ outside the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two seasons, Stewart drove defensive coordinators
crazy. He earned his ``Slash'' nickname by completing 16 of 37
passes for 160 yards and one touchdown, catching 31 passes for 528
yards and four touchdowns and rushing for 257 yards and six
touchdowns on 54 carries. Remember the Monday night game against
Cleveland in 1995 when Stewart's first career pass went for a
2-yard touchdown to Ernie Mills? Or how about the next week against
Cincinnati when he scored on a 71-yard pass from Neil O'Donnell?
Stewart was more exciting than Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Stewart and the Steelers decided he was a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, it proved to be a good move.
</P>
<P>
   With Jerome Bettis running for a career-best 1,665 yards in
1997, Stewart passed for 3,020 yards with 21 touchdowns and 17
interceptions in his first year as a full-time starter, and the
Steelers made it to the AFC Championship Game before losing to the
Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's performance got offensive coordinator Chan Gailey the
Cowboys' head coaching job, and prompted the Steelers to reward
Stewart with a $27 million contract extension that included an $8.1
million signing bonus. Both teams put too much stock in Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   There was the infamous ``Crying Game'' in 1998 in Tampa when
television cameras caught Stewart bawling on the sideline after he
was benched. There was last season when he threw six touchdown
passes, had an AFC-worst 64.9 passer rating and was moved to
receiver for the final five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I was to a point where I was down and out, but
you know, when you don't have too much success, it kind of causes
you to start searching to try to find some things to happen for
you,'' Stewart said. ``When it doesn't happen, it can cause you to
mope. But I've always been one to work off faith, and with that,
anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I don't ever want to go back out there and play
receiver. That's something that's been done in the past. It's
behind me. My future is to be a quarterback, and hopefully, I'll be
a great one. I'm the player formerly known as Slash. Hopefully we
can move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had three offensive coordinators in his first three
seasons as a full-time starter. He also had a receiving corps that
couldn't catch a cold. He now has the same coordinator _ Kevin
Gilbride _ for the second consecutive season, and he has big-play
receivers in Troy Edwards and Plaxico Burress. He is out of excuses
and time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cowher's job is tied to Stewart's future. Stewart's future
is tied to Bill Cowher's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell,'' Cowher said, when asked about Stewart's
future as a quarterback. ``That's just something that's going to
take time. There are going to be some tough games he's going to
have come back from, so I think everyone's kind of waiting for him
to have a bad game and see how he reacts to it. But you know what?
He's just got to stay focused and be ready to deal with everything
that comes. I think he's been hardened to a lot of things that have
taken place, and I think consequently, it's going to allow him to
deal with the tough times that are inevitable for every
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   By next year, Cowher and Stewart both could be somewhere else.
Cowher could have a new zip code, and Stewart could have a new
position.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
