<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SEND DOWN CORDERO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
CLEVELAND _ The Rangers sent struggling reliever Francisco Cordero
to Triple-A Oklahoma yesterday and called up right-hander Darwin
Cubillan. Cordero had allowed 32 hits and 16 runs in 16 innings in
his past 14 appearances.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He needs to work on some things,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said. ``One of them is locating the ball better. I can't get
him into enough ballgames here, and you can try some things in the
minor leagues and work on some things. You can't experiment in the
major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordero will likely be back in September, although Oates said he
can't promise anything. Oates said the Rangers are planning an
organizational conference call today to discuss Cordero and Darren
Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Cubillan was acquired from the Toronto Blue Jays on July 19
along with minor-league infielder Mike Young for pitcher Esteban
Loaiza. Cubillan made six appearances with Oklahoma and did not
allow a run in 13 innings. He allowed 14 runs in 15 2/3 innings in
seven games while with the Blue Jays from May 19 to June 24.
Free-agent broadcasters Besides players, the Rangers have four
other potential free agents: television broadcasters Bill Jones and
Tom Grieve and radio broadcasters Eric Nadel and Vince Cotroneo.
All four of their contracts expire after this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have yet to address that situation, but club
president Jim Lites said he wants to do so this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody needs to be nervous or worried,'' Lites
said yesterday. ``We just need to sit down and evaluate the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox bought the Rangers' television rights for the next 10 years,
and Lites said the team will have input on the television team. The
Rangers control who does the radio broadcasts, and Lites said
several people will have input, starting with owner Tom Hicks.
Lites, Southwest Sports Group chairman Michael Cramer, club vice
presidents John Blake (public relations), Jeff Cogen (marketing)
and John McMichael (finance) and general manager Doug Melvin also
be involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are close to a new agreement with KRLD for the radio
rights, and it's unlikely the Rangers would make a change with
Nadel, who has been with them for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Eric, and I like his style,'' Lites said. ``But he
still has to be evaluated. Everybody does. The job is more than
just broadcasting the game; there's also presenting our product to
the public and selling and representing the advertisers. That
doesn't mean there are any problems, but we still have to look at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites said he doesn't want to wait until the end of the season,
saying, ``That wouldn't be fair to anyone.''
Oliver sent to Oklahoma Darren Oliver, on the disabled list with
weakness and fatigue in his left shoulder, has been assigned to
Triple-A Oklahoma on medical-rehabilitation assignment and is
scheduled to Saturday against the Nashville Sounds. The Rangers
want Oliver to make at least four starts for Oklahoma so he can
build up the arm strength and durability that has been missing this
year.
Port Charlotte meeting The Rangers are planning to meet with
officials from Charlotte County this month and will likely work out
a one-year extension to stay at the training facility in Port
Charlotte, Fla. The Rangers aren't ready to commit to a longer
extension until they're sure the county will make the proper
improvements in the facility.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have been looking into Las Vegas, but club vice
president John McMichael said the chances of getting something done
there are diminishing. The Los Angeles Dodgers seem committed to
staying in Vero Beach, Fla., and the Toronto Blue Jays are close to
extending their lease in Dunedin, Fla., for another 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping Las Vegas open as an option, but it's getting
less likely that will happen,'' McMichael said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
