<DOCNO> NYT20000807.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5432 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-LIEBERMAN-1STLD-     08-07 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LIEBERMAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PICKS LIEBERMAN, A CRITIC OF CLINTON AND FIRST JEW ON A
NATIONAL TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: ADDS 4 grafs bgng, Christopher said ..., before first
optional trim to add pollster's comment about independent voters.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT2,3,8,10,11,15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore picked Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman of Connecticut to be his running mate Monday, putting a
Jew on a national ticket of a major party for the first time and
choosing the first prominent Democrat to openly chastise President
Clinton for his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is to formally announce his decision at a rally here at
noon on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was one of five candidates to be thoroughly vetted by
a corps of lawyers over the last two months and emerged as Gore's
choice early Monday morning, after the vice president huddled for
hours with top aides and family members at a hotel suite here.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides said Lieberman brought a sense of moral rectitude to
the ticket as well as a seriousness of purpose, qualities that Gore
was intent on seeking after Gov. George W. Bush, his Republican
rival, chose Dick Cheney, the former secretary of defense, as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Christopher, the former secretary of state, who led
Gore's selection process, said in an interview Monday that Bush's
choice had influenced Gore. ``Cheney meant that the vice
president's choice would be measured by a standard of seriousness
reflected by his record,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   But the comments of the Gore camp, laced with words like
integrity and rectitude, also seemed to reflect their desire to use
Lieberman to move their candidate away from the scandals of the
Clinton administration, which provided one of the themes of last
week's Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at both men, Al Gore and Joe Lieberman, they're
both people who throughout their lives made the right choices,''
said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``Both led very responsible
lives and are people who, when faced with tough choices, have time
and time again made the right choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has also been a vigorous advocate of campaign finance
reform, and he recently supported legislation that would ban
unregulated donations to political parties. His record on the issue
could clearly benefit Gore, whose aggressive fund-raising efforts
in 1996 are expected to be the subject of Republican attacks in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   But in choosing Lieberman, Gore has also picked a running mate
whose record on a number of issues, from school vouchers to capital
gains taxes, are more conservative than the vice president's.
</P>
<P>
   Although reporters were informed of Gore's chose around dawn
Monday morning, Gore did not formally offer the spot to Lieberman
until the afternoon, catching the senator on his cell phone as he
drove into his driveway in New Haven, Conn., after giving a speech
to the Connecticut AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the call,'' Lieberman told reporters waiting at his
house. ``It was directly from Al Gore.'' He said the two had said a
short prayer together.
</P>
<P>
   Gore chose Lieberman over several other senators, including John
Edwards of North Carolina, whose only governmental experience was
two years in the Senate, and John Kerry of Massachusetts, whose
liberal voting record would surely have become an inviting target
for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Also vetted were Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana and Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a 58-year-old Orthodox Jew, is known on the national
stage chiefly as the first Democrat to condemn Clinton during the
Lewinsky scandal, when he took to the Senate floor and branded
Clinton's behavior ``immoral.'' Gore, who did not criticize the
president throughout the impeachment process, has had a difficult
time in his campaign distancing himself from Clinton's personal
behavior, in part because he has also sought to associate himself
with the president's positive job performance and the booming
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Lieberman, Gore advisers said, recognizes that the
Republicans will try to make the president's character a campaign
issue, and they hope the move will shield Gore from such attacks
and undermine Bush's claim that he will restore honor and integrity
to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers said the decision, and its timing, a week before
the opening of the Democratic convention in Los Angeles, also was
grounded in Gore's recognition that he needed to do something to
shake up the race. The latest polls show Gore trailing Bush by as
much as 17 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign portrayed the selection of Lieberman as a bold
choice because of its historic nature in naming the first Jew to a
national ticket, but questions were raised early on and again
Monday night about whether Lieberman's religion would work against
him.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore aides said they believed that the
decision would demonstrate something the campaign had been trying
to convey for months: that Gore is a ``principled fighter'' who
will stand up for those who have been discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher said that the question of Lieberman's religion had
been raised but that Gore ``shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hart, a Democratic pollster, said Gore was aiming his
selection at independent voters and the 15 percent of the
electorate that liked Clinton professionally but not personally.
Hart also said Lieberman, with his ``moral absolutism,'' could
appeal to supporters of Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is saying, `I have to find a way of talking to the middle
and getting to the middle,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist message that Lieberman sends was an important
consideration for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore began interviewing potential running mates at the end of
July and had completed them by July 25. He interviewed Lieberman in
Washington at the vice president's residence, where four of the
five candidates sneaked passed television cameras. He interviewed
the fifth candidate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman, who have known each other since serving in
the Senate together, spoke for about an hour in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   One of the overriding factors for Gore was that he pick someone
who could become president on a moment's notice. This became more
imperative, advisers said, after Bush picked Cheney. Although Gore
advisers saw immediate weaknesses in Cheney's voting record, they
also saw that Bush had picked someone whose ability to step into
the Oval Office would not be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Christopher said that Gore chose
Lieberman for several reasons. He said the vice president valued
the senator's independence, and the two were personally compatible.
And, Christopher said, Gore regarded Lieberman as ``a symbol of
rectitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore could visualize his being a very wise counselor in the
White House,'' Christopher said. ``People in the Senate have a very
high regard for the values he brings to decisions,'' he said,
adding: ``He conveys a very serious purpose.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The final selection process spanned several hours on Sunday.
Gore met at his hotel suite here at 3:30 p.m. Sunday with
Christopher, William Daley, his campaign chairman, and Frank
Hunger, his brother-in-law. They met until 6 p.m., then recessed.
</P>
<P>
   At 9, after dinner, they reconvened, this time with Jim
Hamilton, the senior vetter, and two aides, Tom Nides and Ron
Klain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's wife, Tipper, and one of their daughters, Sarah, arrived
about 11 p.m., their commercial flight from Washington delayed by
bad weather. The circle then expanded to include other top
advisers, including Donna Brazile, the campaign manager, Tad
Devine, Carter Eskew and Bob Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his decision after midnight. Some in the room asked
him if he wanted to sleep on his decision. He said no.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he awoke to news reports that he had been chosen.
Monica Dixon, a Gore adviser, told Lieberman's staff that the
reports were based on statements by Democratic officials, but
Lehane, the Gore spokesman, said that Dixon had not told them
whether the accounts were true.
</P>
<P>
   When the cameras caught up with him mid-morning, Lieberman said
he was still awaiting the call. But he was confident enough to be
overjoyed, saying, ``Miracles happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
