</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLODGET-MARKETPLACE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: AN INTERNET BULL EXPRESSES DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change 26 companies to 29 in lede, and changes `covers' to
`recommends.' Also changes 26 to 29 in 5th and 14th grafs; nine to
11 in 5th graf, and 17 picks to 18 in 8th graf. Adjusts other
figures in 5th, 8th and 10th grafs.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Henry Blodget's words used to add rocket fuel to the
new economy. On Monday, Merrill Lynch's star Internet analyst
re-entered the atmosphere, downgrading 10 of the 29 companies he
recommends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are resetting the investment ratings for our Internet
universe,'' Blodget wrote in a report. Four months after the start
of the April bloodbath that halted the Internet's unfettered
charge, one of the most reliable of Internet bulls is finally
showing signs of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Blodget, 34, is considered one of the Internet sector's two
premier analysts, along with Mary Meeker of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. Last month, Meeker showed a speck of caution when she
raised her loss-per-share estimates for Amazon.com, but she stopped
short of a downgrade. Blodget has countered with a raft of
downgrades, but on Monday they barely registered across the sector.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com Internet index gained 4.07 percent, and even
several of the names Blodget downgraded surged forward. Why? Maybe
because of how far they have already fallen. The analyst, who once
led the market up, now appears to be following it down.
</P>
<P>
   This has not been a banner year for Blodget, even by the recent
anemic standards of Internet investors. Of the 29 stocks he covers,
11 of the companies are new to the group this year. The other 18
stocks, which he has covered all year, are down an average of 54.2
percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this has been an abysmal year for investing in
Internet stocks. TheStreet.com Internet index is down 33.8 percent.
Since April, Internet mutual funds have had a choke hold on the
bottom of the barrel, entrenched as the worst-performing funds
among all domestic mutual fund categories this year.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing an analyst's picks to a mutual fund has its flaws, but
it can be useful for a rough picture. Blodget's average return
ranks behind even the worst-performing domestic mutual fund, Jacob
Internet, which is down 51.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of his 18 picks, Inktomi, has gained this year. Six
have lost more than 70 percent of their value. EToys has lost 84.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is no longer giving some companies the benefit of
the doubt,'' said Blodget in an interview. ``We're acknowledging
that. The sector is so volatile that it's made some of the ratings
meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring heavily into the ``resetting'' of Blodget's downgraded
names were e-commerce stocks. Perhaps the fact that TheStreet.com
E-Commerce index had already fallen 65.5 percent for the year when
the day began meant that there was not much more room for the group
to tumble. Some did fall. Buy.com dropped by 16.1 percent. Others
soared. Doubleclick, the Internet advertising firm, gained 9.8
percent following Blodget's downgrade. IVillage, the beleaguered
portal aimed at women that Blodget downgraded to accumulate from
accumulate/buy, gained 4.8 percent. And Barnesandnoble.com soared
38.4 percent after it struck a deal with Microsoft to create an
online store for digital books.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor could be that Blodget's report was far from a
stark reappraisal of the sector's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the reset is not to make a new `call' on the
direction of the group,'' the report said, ``but to provide a more
precise differentiation of our current opinions (by using a wider
range of ratings.)''
</P>
<P>
   A wider range of negative ratings, that is. For those who
actually followed his recommendations, it might come as cold
comfort that Blodget has decided to add a new word to his lexicon
of ratings. Before Monday, his ratings have all been combinations
of one of two words, either ``buy'' or ``accumulate,'' which is
more tepid than a buy recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Now Blodget has added the word ``neutral'' to his repertoire.
Previously, none of the 29 Internet stocks Blodget covered merited
a neutral rating. Neutral, according to Merrill Lynch, means that
it is not clear when a company will be profitable and that
``significant uncertanties or reservations remain.'' In plain
English _ though analysts rarely admit as much _it is roughly
analogous to a ``thumbs down'' from Roger Ebert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's trying to say, `Look, there are a handful of
companies that are going to be stellar. Those are the Yahoos and
AOLs and maybe Inktomi,'' said James Houlton, manager of the Strong
Internet fund. ``As the market has put the Internet in its place,
it has put him in his place, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with just about everybody else, as Houlton added.
</P>
<P>
   So which companies picked up the dread word neutral? Monday,
eToys, the online toy seller, was downgraded from an accumulate/buy
rating to neutral. Barnesandnoble.com fared slightly better,
downgraded from an accumulate/buy rating to neutral/buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is focused on now is profitability,'' said Blodget. ``I
think we have been very vocal about the stage of the industry's
development. We suggested as far back as last July that this was
going to be a rough time.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, when the Internet was still something of a
novelty item, Blodget predicted that Amazon.com would climb to $400
a share. His prediction made him the butt of jokes in some
quarters, until Amazon hit $400 a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Blodget left his job at CIBC/Oppenheimer for a blue
chip post at Merrill Lynch. His picks became a roadmap for some
investors. This year, the road has become less traveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an emerging sector like this,'' he said, ``you are going to
make mistakes picking stocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
