<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIRWAYS REPORTS 65 PERCENT DROP IN ITS EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Airways reported a 65 percent plunge in
quarterly earnings on Monday, attributing the poor performance to
the effects of the strong British pound and the rising price of jet
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The results for the March-June quarter were reported as the
airline is trying to break out of a prolonged slump, partly through
a proposed deal to acquire KLM Royal Dutch Airlines N.V. But there
were more signs on Monday that those negotiations, which began in
early June, have not advanced very far.
</P>
<P>
   While both airlines are still in exclusive talks, concerns over
regulatory approval from both the European Union and the United
States have cast doubt over the deal. Executives close to the talks
have said that the two sides are not yet close to an agreement on a
price for KLM. British Airways chief executive, Rod Eddington, said
on Monday it remained unclear whether the talks would result in an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory obstacles are high for a deal with KLM to receive
approval. British Airways encountered regulatory problems when it
tried to form an alliance with American Airlines. A deal with KLM
was expected to face tougher antitrust scrutiny in Europe because
the combined routes of both airlines would cover a large share of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said pretax profit before one-time items dropped to
(PS)8 million, or $12 million, from (PS)23 million a year earlier.
Sales rose 4 percent to (PS)2.3 billion. Nonetheless, British
Airways posted a loss of (PS)50 million after the charges were
accounted for, compared with a profit of (PS)200 million a year
earlier. The airline said the rising price of jet fuel and the
strong pound were largely responsible for the financial results.
Fuel is one of the largest expenses for airlines, and a strong
currency translates into fewer profits when overseas earnings are
repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain cautiously optimistic,'' Andrew Light, an analyst at
Solomon Smith Barney, wrote in a note to investors about the
airline. But, he said, the uncertainty of the KLM deal remains a
big risk for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of British Airways dropped 3 pence to 388 pence, or about
$5.82. KLM stock rose 5.9 percent to 30.39 euros, or $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
