<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
 
McMICHAEL FOLLOWS HEART, NOT RANGERS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Chuck McMichael always looks like a man with his
passport in his back pocket.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He always looks like he is ready to ``go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not next week.
</P>
<P>
   Not tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Right now.
</P>
<P>
   He looks like a man who is about to catch a plane.
</P>
<P>
   To Puerto Rico. To the Dominican Republic. To Venezuela. To
Taiwan. Someplace, anyplace, with an exotic name and a baseball
diamond carved out of the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   With his dark tan and his casual, easy use of Spanish, he is as
at home talking about baseball in La Romana, or Maracaibo, or Nuevo
Laredo, as he is in his own backyard in Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   He is exactly what he looks like _ a baseball scout.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, he plied that trade for the Texas Rangers. Not
anymore, and that's what this story is about.
</P>
<P>
   Through no real fault of their own, the Rangers have lost a good
baseball man, and that's never a good thing. McMichael resigned
after four years as the Rangers' director of domestic and
international scouting.
</P>
<P>
   You could call it a case of burnout, but that wouldn't be quite
right. You could say it was a difference of philosophies between
McMichael and general manager Doug Melvin, but that wouldn't be
accurate either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gets down to one guy's decision to be true to himself,
to say, `You know, follow your heart a little bit here,' ''
McMichael said yesterday. ``Baseball people tend to migrate toward
their heart, and my heart is in scouting. I was getting farther and
farther away from doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, McMichael found his administrative duties as the
Rangers' scouting director were keeping him away from his first
love, and that was in the field, not in the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dirt and the grass and the sunshine and the smell of the
park are definitely in my blood,'' he said. ``I love Latin America.
I love spending time with newer scouts. I learn from them like they
learn from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a particular thrill to walking into a country when you
know no one in your organization has ever been there and then begin
pulling players out of there, whether it's Korea or Taiwan or
Nicaragua or Honduras or wherever.''
</P>
<P>
   The career blueprint the 42-year-old McMichael once thought he
would follow would have had him well on his way to becoming a
major-league general manager by 45. At one time, that seemed
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, maybe 55 would be OK,'' he said. ``Maybe I'll get back to
it then.''
</P>
<P>
   He's simply not ready to give up the grassroots part of the
game, and that's what his job with the Rangers was basically
forcing him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an adjustment to be a scouting director,'' conceded
Melvin, who has been one himself. ``It's a demanding job and a
transition to go from the field to the office. We all get faced
with that sometime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had an opportunity to work in here and do that. Part of
it is not only evaluating talent; it's directing and supervising
and managing people _ putting staffs together. There's a lot more
to it than just going out and seeing ballplayers. People just have
to decide what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, McMichael has supervised the move of the
Rangers' baseball academy in the Dominican Republic from San
Cristobal to La Romana; opened a new academy in Venezuela;
increased the franchise's presence in Panama; and worked to
establish ties with teams in Mexico. At the same time, he has
overseen the club's scouting, drafting and signing of amateur free
agents in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You create this monster,'' McMichael said, ``and then you have
to have a zoo keeper to feed the monster.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35 to 55 voice messages each day, the 30 e-mails each day,
the three to five hours on the cellphone every day, the constant
interruptions at home _ those are all normal days for a scouting
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``To feed the monster requires a huge amount of time and
sacrifices that in the end, you think you're best at,'' McMichael
said, ``and that's evaluation and creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, McMichael would make a terrific special-assignments
scout. Send him to New York, or Chicago or Toronto to evaluate the
players in a possible trade. Have him cross-check the abilities of
a hard-throwing high school pitcher in Cedar Rapids, Iowa. Send him
to the Dominican Republic or Venezuela to give a second opinion on
the talent there. That's what McMichael is good at.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers already have a fine special-assignments scout in
Rudy Terrasas. They have an experienced, veteran major-league scout
in former Astros general manager Bill Wood. Melvin thought about,
but ultimately rejected, creating a position to try and keep
McMichael, because he couldn't make it financially feasible for
either the organization or McMichael.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you lose someone who can evaluate talent, it hurts,
but it will give somebody else in the organization an opportunity
to grow,'' said Melvin, who has already talked to all three
cross-checkers (Jeff Taylor, Dave Klipstein and Tim Hallgren)
within the system to get a feel for their level of interest in
becoming the team's next scouting director.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael, meanwhile, has already had calls from Cleveland,
Colorado, Atlanta and Kansas City, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered by the number of people who have called, almost
embarrassed,'' McMichael said. ``I'll find something that's the
right fit, something that will involve some major-league scouting
with international scouting mixed in.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 42, McMichael has taken the unusual and courageous
step of throwing out the career blueprint to follow his heart.
</P>
<P>
   He's got places to go, people to see.
</P>
<P>
   Have passport, will travel.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
