<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WASTE HELLING'S EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
CLEVELAND _ Gabe Kapler's hitting streak reached 21 consecutive
games last night, but Rick Helling's six-game winning streak is no
more.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Helling didn't deserve for his streak to end, but he was
pitching on a night when Kapler's streak and Rusty Greer's 1,000th
career hit were about the only good things to happen to the Rangers
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   And Helling ran into an unusual opponent, as five Indians
pitchers, including starter Steve Woodard, held the Rangers
scoreless on five hits for a 2-0 victory at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Helling held the Indians to four hits through seven innings but
got his first loss since June 23 because of one controversial play
at the plate in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched awesome,'' said catcher Bill Haselman, shaking his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Haselman wasn't happy the Rangers lost when Helling pitched so
well. He was also fuming about the play at the plate in the seventh
inning that gave the Indians their first run.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring 12 consecutive batters, Helling walked Jim Thome
to start the seventh. After David Segui flied out, Wil Cordero
singled to right on a hit-and-run, moving Thome to third.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fryman followed with a medium fly to right fielder Chad
Curtis and Thome tagged up. Curtis' throw beat Thome and Haselman
seemed to get the tag on Thome, who tried to slide around it. But
umpire Brian Runge ruled Thome got his hand on the plate before the
tag, a dubious point Haselman and manager Johnny Oates argued long
and loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question in my mind he was out,'' Haselman said. ``I
wouldn't have argued if I didn't think so. All I know is I tagged
him hard, but he \RRunge\S said he stuck his hand in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians added a run in the eighth against reliever Mike
Venafro on three consecutive two-out singles by Omar Vizquel,
Roberto Alomar and Thome. That was more than enough against the
Rangers, who wasted Helling's performance by getting shut out for
the third time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great pitching performance by Rick,'' Greer said. ``I
don't think anybody in the clubhouse expects Rick or anybody on the
pitching staff to do that every night. It's up to the offense to
help him out, and we didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' best chance came in the fifth when Rafael Palmeiro
and Kapler led off with singles. Ricky Ledee was supposed to bunt,
but missed the sign. Instead he hit a high drive to deep left and
Cordero got back to the wall to make a great leaping catch, taking
away an extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward then struck out Haselman, walked Mike Lamb and struck
out Royce Clayton to end the inning. The Rangers also loaded the
bases with two out in the sixth, but reliever Tom Martin got
Curtis, pinch hitting for Ledee, to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I pitched well,'' Helling said. ``Their pitchers
made the big pitches when they had to. I have all the faith in the
world in our offense. It was just a night when we didn't score any
runs.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
