<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MCNEIL-TEX </SLUG>
 
A Q&AMP;A WITH COWBOYS CORNERBACK RYAN McNEIL 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Deion. Deion. Deion.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ryan McNeil has heard that name enough to last two lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   The man, however, whom the Cowboys signed to replace their
former all-everything cornerback, knows the constant comparisons
have just begun. The regular season and two much-anticipated
meetings with Deion Sanders and the Redskins are still weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with Star-Telegram staff writer Clarence E.
Hill Jr., McNeil, who sports a brash, cool flavor compared with
Sanders' flashy and bold flair, said he just wants to be accepted
for being himself.
</P>
<P>
   Besides he says he didn't come here to replace Deion. He came
here to win a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ST: Are you comfortable here yet? I'm sure knowing head coach
Dave Campo and some of the other coaches from your days at Miami
helped.
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``It's been a smooth transition. One of my biggest assets
has been adaptability. This is my fourth team in seven years. I
have the ability to mesh well, mesh quickly. But here it was a lot
less effort doing so than previous teams.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: You've played with one-year deals the past four years, yet
you signed with the Cowboys for five years. You also could have
gotten more on a one-year deal in Cleveland. Are you looking for
stability?
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``This is the longest I've signed in my whole career. That
says a lot. I plan on being here five years or longer. Cleveland
was a great one-year deal situation. But there's going to be some
time before they have a lot of success. I've been a winner all my
life and the last four years in Detroit \R1996\S, St. Louis \R1997
and 1998\S and Cleveland \R1999\S have been miserable team-wise.
The Cowboys have been there and done that. Management is hungry for
another Super Bowl. The players are hungry for another Super Bowl.
I'm starving for a Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Does it bother you that you weren't the Cowboys first
choice? They turned to you after they got shunned by little-known
Deron Jenkins, who chose San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``It doesn't bother me who played here before me or after me
or who else they wanted. That doesn't concern me. I know what I can
do. I've always been able to narrow my focus so much that it's like
a rifle shot as opposed to a gun shot. I know what I'm here to do,
and I'm going to do it well.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: OK, let's cut to the chase. Can you replace Deion?
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``I don't look at it as replacing Deion. What he brought to
the table as far as talent, nobody can replace him, not one person.
He is that special. He was a wide receiver, a kick returner and a
cornerback. My corner of the pie is the cornerback position. I've
done that most of my life. I've played cornerback. So I'm not
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Do the constant Deion questions frustrate you, and how are
you dealing with them?
</P>
<P>
   RM: No, I knew the deal coming in. It takes a special person to
sign under those circumstances. But I had a long talk with Mr.
\RJerry\S Jones, coach \RDave\S Campo and coach \RMike\S Zimmer. I
understand where they are coming from. And I wanted it crystal
clear where I was coming from. I just told them what you see is
what you get. I'm not trying to be anything I'm not. I'm not trying
replace anybody. I'm a businessman. That's the way I approach the
game. I try to have fun. But for the most part I am serious. That's
the way I am. I want people to accept me for who I am. And for me,
the simplest approach is the easiest approach. Once training camp
starts, everything outside of football is extra. I cut that out as
much as possible. To me, the Deion stuff is extra. That has no
bearing on how I play. The game of football is 100 yards. You get
six points for a touchdown, and my job is to stop the opposing
receiver from catching the ball. It's been that way since peewee.
The rules haven't changed. I'm able to deal with that and thrive on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: You were criticized in minicamp for being rusty. Now the
coaches are seemingly comfortable with what you can do. What was
the deal?
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``One thing I like about the coaches is that they were
patient with me. Yes, I was rusty. My technique wasn't up to par.
But I'm critical on myself. I will put more pressure on me than any
coach, media or owner. I've worked out the kinks, and I'm playing
pretty well. I'm not where I want. I will get better. But they have
some sense of security in me now.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: But is it funny that your early struggles caused such a
ruckus?
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``It all tickles me. Why bring me here if you didn't think I
could play? But I could feel everybody holding their breath. As a
veteran, you can sense it, people holding their breath, crossing
their fingers, hoping I can play. But it's cool. It just goes back
to me dealing with me. I just need to focus and keep things in
perspective the way I've been doing. I'll be fine. The key thing is
that I control it. I control how I play and what I do. That's all
that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Do you understand why your success is so important? With so
much uncertainty at cornerback, the Cowboys need to know they can
count on you, and the scrutiny is going to continue.
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``I'm not worried about that. I've always been able to count
on myself. I've always bet on myself. That's why I have all these
one-year deals. I've sacrificed some money because of it. That's no
big deal to me. I just want to be in a place that I'm respected,
welcomed, and loved. That's why I came to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: You are from Florida like Deion. You went to the University
of Miami like Michael Irvin. Yet, you don't wear flashy clothes,
and you don't talk trash. Aren't those rites of passage down there?
</P>
<P>
   RM: ``I'm down to earth, conservative. That's always one of the
biggest surprises when I tell people where I'm from and where I
went to school. But I'm not like that. I'm a businessman. That's
how I carry myself.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
