<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SIGN TIGHT END, CORNERBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Cowboys filled needs at two
injury-plagued positions yesterday by signing tight end Rickey
Brady and cornerback Hurley Tarver, free agents who were NFL Europe
teammates with the Scottish Claymores this summer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brady, who turns 30 in November, is a 6-foot-4, 246-pound tight
end who had a training-camp tryout with the Cowboys in 1996. He
will try to replace Mike Lucky (major knee surgery/out for the
season) as David LaFleur's backup at blocking tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Tarver, 24, was a track and football star at Western Hills High
School, where he was all-district in the triple jump. The 6-foot,
186-pounder is needed because of the day-to-day injury situations
with cornerbacks Dwayne Goodrich (strained left hamstring) and
Duane Hawthorne (sprained left shoulder). Both were hurt in
Saturday's 20-9 loss to Atlanta in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Tarver, who played at Central Oklahoma University, was cut each
of the past two preseasons, at San Francisco and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Brady was drafted in 1994 in the sixth round by the then-Los
Angeles Rams but has spent his career bouncing around the league _
mostly on practice squads _ with the Rams, Saints, Eagles, Jets,
Cowboys, Redskins, Saints again, Buccaneers, Titans, Dolphins and
Cowboys for a second time.
Briefly Defensive ends Peppi Zellner (dislocated finger) and Aaron
Fields (head contusion) are expected to practice today. X-rays on
Zellner's left hand were negative. The Cowboys, with the
maximum-allowed 88 players, no longer are keeping a spot open for
Pro Bowl offensive tackle Erik Williams, a three-week holdout who
who has indicated through his agent that he might retire. If
Williams reports, the Cowboys likely would get a one-week roster
exemption from the league office. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
